<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT ON BEHALF OF BANK ROBBER TO GO FORWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ A federal judge refused to dismiss a civil
rights lawsuit Tuesday that accuses Los Angeles police of allowing
one of the North Hollywood bank robbers to bleed to death after a
ferocious gun battle Feb. 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Opening statements and testimony could begin today in a case
that questions whether police acted with vengeance or believed it
was unsafe for paramedics to treat Emil Matasareanu.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing for the dismissal, an attorney for one of the accused
officers claimed the attorney who brought the lawsuit on behalf of
Matasareanu's two children has no evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``By his own admission, he said he had no facts. It would be
manifestly unfair to let him proceed with the trial,'' said Bradley
Gage, who is representing former Officer John Futrell.
</P>
<P>
   Matasareanu's attorney, Stephen Yagman, told the judge the
deadline for the dismissal had expired, and that he has evidence to
support his claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an absurd, baseless motion,'' Yagman said after the
hearing. ``And I don't even know why it was made.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Christina A. Snyder said she might reconsider the motion
to dismiss, but only after hearing some of Yagman's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to see what evidence comes forward,'' Snyder
said.
</P>
<P>
   Matasareanu died after he and accomplice Larry Phillips Jr.
wounded 17 people while trying to rob a Bank of America. Phillips
died after shooting himself and being hit by police bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accuses former Officers James Vojtecky and Futrell
of allowing the hulking bank robber to bleed to death and thereby
violating his civil rights. Also named in the lawsuit is the city
of Los Angeles and former Police Chief Daryl F. Gates, who Yagman
contends encouraged misconduct in the department.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder also declined Tuesday to allow the gag order Yagman had
requested, saying the attorneys were free to speak publicly during
the trial, which is expected to take three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yagman said he plans to call 13 witnesses, including Futrell and
Vojtecky. It remained unresolved Tuesday whether Yagman's first
scheduled witness, Los Angeles Times photographer Carolyn Cole,
would testify. In taking pictures, she got near Matasareanu as he
lay bleeding and saw how police treated him, Yagman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I know of what she saw, she is absolutely the best
witness to set forth all the facts of what happened, Yagman said.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder is expected to announce today the extent to which Cole
can be compelled to testify. Gage said he wants jurors to see
Cole's photograph, which seems to show Futrell standing over
Matasareanu.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a man of compassion,'' Gage said. ``He wanted to make
sure he comforts the guy and lets him know an ambulance is on the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
