<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE THROWS AREN'T
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's nothing the struggling UCLA Bruins do
worse than shoot free throws. They're embarrassingly bad _ and
getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   A 9-of-21 performance Sunday at Syracuse dropped their season
percentage to 58.2. That's 11 percent below the Pac-10 average and
an astounding eight percent below the ninth-ranked team, Oregon
State. Put another way: The Bruins could make 100 in a row and
they'd still trail OSU.
</P>
<P>
   The only player shooting better than 70 percent from the line is
out for the season (JaRon Rush). The starters are shooting 59.4
percent, the reserves 53.5. Even sharpshooter Jason Kapono is
guilty; he's missed seven of his last 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Steve Lavin has no explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With some guys it's technique, with some it's confidence, with
some it's touch, and with some it's concentration,'' said Lavin,
whose team shot 59.6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we shoot between drills. Sometimes we run and shoot.
There are a million philosophies. Dean Smith said don't talk about
(free throws). Some coaches like to (teach players to) visualize.
Some like to bring in shot doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, the crime has cost the Bruins dearly. Three
losses are directly attributable to poor foul shooting:
</P>
<P>
   __ They were 9 of 19 from the line in a one-point loss at
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   __ They were 18 of 27 from the line in a three-point loss to
Cal.
</P>
<P>
   __ They shot 42.9 percent from the line in Sunday's four-point
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shot 200 (per player) before we got on the plane Friday and
we're going to shoot 200 more every day in practice,'' Lavin said.
``We have to keep trying to bring our percentage up. . . . If we're
three or four percentage points better, that could be the
difference in a one- or two-point game.''
</P>
<P>
   Because free throws are tougher on the road and because the
Bruins must win at least one road game to secure an NCAA Tournament
berth, their season depends on accurate free-throw shooting
Thursday at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a comforting thought for a team shooting 51 percent
in conference road games.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rush update: After consulting with Rush's lawyers, UCLA
submitted its appeal of his 29-game suspension last week and hopes
to hear any day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were anticipating a response Friday or Monday and got
none,'' UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis said. ``We left a
message with the person (who oversees the NCAA sub-committee on
appeals) and still didn't get a response.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Up and down: Reserves Ray Young and Matt Barnes can't seem to
play well at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Young, a guard, emerged from a slump to contribute against USC
and Syracuse. Barnes, a forward who played well a few weeks ago,
has struggled lately. He scored 12 points in 26 minutes against
Stanford. In the three games since, he has made one basket and
played 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't done anything wrong,'' Lavin said. ``But because
we're keeping Dan (Gadzuric) and Jerome (Moiso) out of foul
trouble, there are less minutes to go around. As a result, Matt
isn't getting as much playing time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
