<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM MILD BANTERING TO FLORID BULLYING, WITH KEYES IN THE MIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With REPUBS-DEBATE) 
(sw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ For the first 15 minutes, Gov. George W. Bush
and Sen. John McCain exuded all the aggression of a pair of
dowagers at a late-afternoon tea party.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 15 minutes, they made like professional wrestlers,
and were it not for the fortunate positioning of Alan Keyes between
them, they might well have started body-slamming.
</P>
<P>
   It happened in an instant, this transition of the Republican
presidential debate here on Tuesday night from mild bantering to
florid bullying, from cool discourse to contact sport. And it
traced, in miniature, the arc of the Republican presidential race,
once so sedately respectful, now anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Did Bush and McCain ever really get along? If so, it was
difficult to remember as they traded an encyclopedia of facial
expressions, from carefully muted glares to undisguised sneers, and
a bevy of wounded and wounding words.
</P>
<P>
   ``He questioned my trustworthiness,'' the Texas governor said of
the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be ashamed,'' the Arizona senator said to the Texas
governor. ``You should be ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   That was about the tenor of things, and it was left to Keyes,
usually the iconoclast, to articulate what was undoubtedly on the
minds of most observers: Was the nastiness really necessary?
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, referring to the worldwide television audience for the
event, said, ``I really am sitting here wondering, because I said
we were going out to 202 countries, and is this kind of pointless
squabbling really what we want them to see?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about electing the president of the United
States,'' Keyes admonished and reminded his two rivals.
</P>
<P>
   It was perhaps because those rivals, unlike Keyes, actually have
a chance of winning that office that they came to the debate with
such full bags of tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Each claimed a similar dramatic moment by burrowing into his
pocket and pulling out . . . a sheet of paper!
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's case, the document was a flier meant to show that
McCain had not lived up to a recent renunciation of negative
campaigning. In McCain's case, it was a copy of the abortion plank
of the platform from the Republican Party's 1992 convention, and it
was intended to expose bits of fuzziness or internal
inconsistencies in Bush's position.
</P>
<P>
   But the details mattered less than the gesture, which carried
its own message: I am about to reveal what a sham my opponent
really is, and here is the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   What was remarkable, in the course of it, was how alike the two
men came to seem: a bit petty, a bit self-pitying, more than a bit
smug. They brought out the worst in each other, including a shared
distaste for being interrupted or cut short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me just finish up, O.K.?'' McCain complained at one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me just say, let me just say,'' Bush stuttered moments
later.
</P>
<P>
   Like teen-agers, they ridiculed each other's friends as uncool.
McCain noted that Bush had hung out on the campaign with a Vietnam
veteran with a record of mean statements about Bush's own father.
Bush noted that McCain was tight with former Sen. Warren Rudman,
who Bush said had once called members of the Christian Coalition
bigots.
</P>
<P>
   Getting in on the action, the moderator, Larry King, chimed in:
``You're not popular in the Senate.'' The comment was directed at
McCain, and it rendered the ``Clueless'' atmosphere complete.
</P>
<P>
   There were seemingly clueless moments as well. Bush seemed to
forget that the Republican nominee gets formally selected in
August. ``I intend to try to win the nomination in the fall as
well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Metaphors were ripe for the taking: A group of Bush's aides were
in a room at the fairgrounds, just across the street, to watch the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, an interactive research group called SpeakOut.com
had assembled 46 South Carolina voters and given them little dials
with which to register their positive or negative feelings about
the candidates as the debate progressed.
</P>
<P>
   News flash: the dial jockeys liked Keyes the best, seemingly
endorsing his midstream review of the event and all the negativity
between Bush and McCain that preceded and surrounded it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people need to start thinking about whether this is
the kind of spectacle that actually characterizes a serious
political process,'' Keyes said, ``because I don't think it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
