<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES, KOBE FINALLY TO MEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In the half-dozen years they've known each other, Kobe
Bryant and Eddie Jones have gone head to head hundreds of times.
Just not in a game that counted in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   That changes tonight, when the Lakers play in Charlotte and
former teammates Bryant and Jones will be guarding each other every
step of the way. It's the second matchup of the year between the
Lakers and Hornets, but Jones was injured for the last one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun, man. It's going to be interesting to
watch,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a challenge playing against E.J.,'' Bryant
said. ``It's a challenge I look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair have known each other since Jones was at Temple and
Bryant at nearby Lower Merion High in Philadelphia, and they became
close friends when Bryant joined Jones on the Lakers in 1996. Then
the friendly battles began, everyday at practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won all of them,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Responded Bryant: ``Y'all know Eddie likes to lie a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   So who won the majority of the time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I did,'' Bryant said. ``I used to pound Eddie. The way Eddie
would beat me is his mental game was so much tougher than mine.
He's a very smart defender, he's very heady. He can fool you into
doing things that you really don't want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers traded Jones and Elden Campbell to Charlotte last
March for Glen Rice, and Bryant and Jones have played each other
just once since _ in Sunday's All-Star Game. But that was hardly a
serious affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just fun,'' Bryant said. ``I told him I forgot how much
he likes to reach. Every time he goes by me, he's reaching for the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones looks forward to seeing Bryant but said he won't have any
emotions facing his old team for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``None whatsoever,'' he said. ``It's just another game, just
like I was playing Cleveland or whoever. Of course I want to win. I
may put a lot more into that game, but it's just going to be
another game for me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Slowdown: Coach Phil Jackson continues to keep an eye on Ron
Harper's 36-year-old legs, and he hopes to keep his minutes down in
the second half of the season to preserve him for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to see how Ron plays,'' Jackson said. ``If he
plays well, he's got to play, because the nights that he moves
right, he's a great player for us. And if his legs are bothering
him or he's not altogether there, then I start to make
substitutions. But he's held us together for a lot of games and
I've got to watch him a little bit down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Bull played just 22 minutes Tuesday night in his
first return to Chicago and got six rebounds and five assists but
struggled with his shot, going 1 for 7 for three points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
