A8239 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS &LR;      02-16 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
BUSH, McCAIN EXCHANGE JABS ON NEGATIVE TACTICS 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ George W. Bush and John McCain, sniping their
way through a crucial debate Tuesday night, hammered each other's
negative campaign tactics in a heated assault.
</P>
<P>
   Both leading candidates for the Republican presidential
nomination objected to being likened to President Clinton by the
other's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't equate my integrity and trustworthiness to Bill
Clinton's.'' Bush told McCain early in the 90-minute exchange.
``That's about as low a blow as you can give in the Republican
primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was referring to a McCain television ad, which the Arizona
senator dropped as the negative tit-for-tat boiled over last week.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he was ``beat up very badly'' by Bush surrogates,
``called Clinton, called Clinton-Lite ..., called a hypocrite.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the almost evangelical style he has adopted over the
last week, Bush was more assertive in stating positions and holding
his own than he had been in previous debates. Except when the issue
was negative campaigning, McCain seemed as if he were trying to
appear more placid and mature _ once using ``grown up'' to contrast
one of his positions to that of the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   The nationally televised debate came four days before the
critical South Carolina Republican primary in which Bush needs a
victory to redeem himself after the trouncing McCain gave him in
New Hampshire. McCain needs to win to show that his 19-point
victory in the Granite State was not a fluke. The debate was the
only major joint appearance for the two candidates between the New
Hampshire vote and the first Southern test of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won the opening caucuses in Iowa and Delaware's primary
Feb. 8, contests in which McCain did not actively campaign. After
South Carolina's vote, the race moves quickly to other regions,
with primaries Tuesday in Michigan and Arizona, states where Bush
had led earlier in the campaign but where polls now show McCain
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent polls of likely voters in South Carolina gave Bush a
narrow lead. In a Los Angeles Time poll published Monday, Bush and
McCain were in a statistical tie.
</P>
<P>
   Former Reagan administration official Alan Keyes also
participated in the debate, although polls indicate he is not a
major factor in the Republican race at this point. Keyes' principal
role was as a Greek chorus, tsk-tsking against McCain's and Bush's
``kind of pointless squabbling.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes criticized Bush for kicking off his South Carolina
campaign by appearing at Bob Jones University in Greenville and not
condemning the school's policy against interracial dating. Bush
denounced the policy only when asked about it later by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, a black man married to a woman from India, noted that he
used his speech at the school to denounce its ``demons of racial
bigotry and religious bigotry.'' He said confronting the issue on
an ``if asked'' basis was insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he had not been invited to speak at Bob Jones, but
contended that if he had spoken there, he would have vocally
opposed the ban and was prepared to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, what you're doing in this ban on interracial dating is
stupid, it's idiotic and it is incredibly cruel to many people,''
said McCain, pointing out he has an adopted daughter from
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   The debate covered a range of issues. Bush described _ and
McCain faulted _ the governor's plan on campaign-finance reform
unveiled earlier Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When the debate first turned to negative campaigning, Bush
blamed himself for not answering McCain quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of smiled my way through the early primaries, and I got
defined,'' Bush said. ``I'm not going to get defined.''
</P>
<P>
   As the exchange continued, McCain grew more agitated, saying
that ``what really went over the line'' was Bush sponsoring a
campaign event at which a member of ``a fringe veterans' group''
said McCain had abandoned veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I don't know if you can understand this, George, but that
really hurts,'' said McCain, who was a POW for almost six years in
Hanoi. ``You should be ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain repeated his objections to political phone calls being
made in South Carolina for which he would not directly blame Bush.
When McCain said he had withdrawn negative ads, Bush brandished a
flier that he said was from McCain's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an attack piece,'' Bush said of the ad, which says:
``When it comes to keeping Social Security, George Bush's figures
simply do not add up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not by my campaign,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says paid for by John McCain,'' Bush replied tartly,
provoking laughter from the audience. The sponsorship line on a
copy of the flier given to reporters by the Bush campaign read:
``Paid for by McCain 2000, Inc.''
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, McCain conceded the fliers were printed by his
campaign but contended they had not been distributed in several
weeks. Bush said it was found on windshields of cars at a rally of
his Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The face-off was the first since the New Hampshire vote Feb. 1
and the subsequent withdrawals from the race by publisher Steve
Forbes and Reagan administration official Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute debate was sponsored by CNN, whose talk-show host
Larry King was the moderator, and the South Carolina Business and
Industry Political Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Before the debate, Bush, who by bringing in $69 million in
contributions has raised more money than any presidential primary
candidate in U.S. history, sought to undercut McCain on the
campaign finance issue by proposing several reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the list was a ban on contributions from lobbyists to
members of the House and Senate while Congress is in session. The
proposal is based on a provision in the Texas Constitution that
bans anyone from contributing to statewide officeholders or
legislators from 30 days before until the conclusion of a regular
legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
