r a BC-SECEDE-HOLLYWOOD-LADN     02-16 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECEDE-HOLLYWOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD STARTS CITYHOOD DRIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  Hollywood, Calif. _ Adding some razzle-dazzle to the cityhood
movement, Hollywood secessionists launched their petition effort
Tuesday, and honorary mayor Johnny Grant was the first resident to
sign.
</P>
<P>
   The man who welcomes new stars to the Hollywood Walk of Fame and
hosts the annual Christmas parade lent a little star power to the
effort to include the movie capital in a study on the viability of
breaking up Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a historic day,'' Grant said after the petition
drive kickoff at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel. ``It's been talked
about for years _ that Hollywood should be its own city. Most
people think it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has been part of Los Angeles for nearly a century.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Hollywood Voters Organized Toward Empowerment want to
slice a 19.5-square-mile area from Los Angeles and form a separate
city with about 200,000 residents. They contend the area's
revitalization has come despite the city's involvement, and they
want more control over issues affecting their community.
</P>
<P>
   To break away, Hollywood VOTE first must gain enough signatures
of registered voters to qualify for a study assessing the financial
viability of both the new city and the remainder of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The San Fernando Valley and San Pedro-Wilmington already are in
the study. With consultants expected to begin the work in March,
Hollywood VOTE leaders don't want to miss the opportunity to have
their territory be included.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock ticks as of today. We don't have a lot of time, but
we will do it,'' said Fares Wehbe, the group's president.
</P>
<P>
   The drive was delayed several weeks while a final map, required
on petition forms, was drawn.
</P>
<P>
   There is some overlapping of the proposed Valley city, whose
southern boundary is Mulholland Drive. But leaders of both efforts
said no conflict is brewing, and the Local Agency Formation
Commission will decide where to draw the lines.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood VOTE has six months to collect signatures from about
15,000 registered voters, 25 percent of those registered in the
area proposed as Hollywood. The group aims to collect more than
20,000 signatures in three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner the better to tie everything in together. But if
they do it within six months, they should be able to be folded in
without any problem,'' said Larry Calemine, executive officer for
the Local Agency Formation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The study has been tentatively budgeted at $2.65 million, and
LAFCO would need an additional $300,000 if the Hollywood proposal
is added to the assignment, Calemine said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said he expects data produced in the study to be
instructive not only for areas whose residents want to break away
from Los Angeles, but also for the rest of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure you'll find the feasibility report to be as
intriguing as a Hitchcock movie and as revealing as a Frederick's
of Hollywood lingerie catalog,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A cityhood vote could be held in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said support already is evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens remember the difficult times in past years, and,
along with a new sense of pride, they have a proprietary feeling
and a desire to control their community and their government on a
more local level,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE leaders said they are optimistic that Hollywood VOTE
will get enough signatures to qualify its plan for inclusion in the
study. ``It further legitimizes the concerns that were first raised
by the Valley residents. It shows there are widespread problems
that need to be addressed,'' said Richard Close, Valley VOTE
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will also help us get a majority of the entire city's
approval once it gets on the ballot in two years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 0024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
