<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-DOG-SHOW-NYT &LR;      02-16 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-SHOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLISH SPRINGER SPANIEL WINS BEST IN SHOW AT WESTMINSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 10:30 Tuesday night, the call went out for the
seven finalists to take the stage at the 124th annual Westminster
Kennel Club Dog Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poodle!'' shouted Peter R. Van Brunt, a vice president of the
club. ``Dobie! English springer. Bedlington. Shih Tzu. The Basset.
Corgi. Poodle, in front of the line!''
</P>
<P>
   As one trotted after the other onto the green carpet of Madison
Square Garden, primed for their chance to be top dog of 2000, the
Bedlington terrier, Ch. Willow Wind Tenure, paused to do some
business. ``Cleanup!'' a steward shouted.
</P>
<P>
   The best-in-show competition was the culmination of the most
prestigious show for dogs, as a crew of judges winnowed 2,500 dogs
in 156 breeds down to seven winners of the hound, sporting,
nonsporting, terrier, herding, toy and working groups.
</P>
<P>
   The judge of the top dog, Chester Collier, president of
Westminster, eyed the seven closely, sending them on their paces.
The crowd adored the sad-faced basset hound, Ch. Moonbeam's
Astronomer, cheering Astro's every waddle as if he were Leonardo
DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   But Collier was not swayed by the audience's momentary
infatuation. Instead, he carried the champion's silver trophy to a
cheerful English springer spaniel, Ch. Salilyn 'N Erin's Shameless,
a 5-year-old bitch whose sire, Ch. Salilyn's Condor, won best in
show in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's perfection for the standard,'' Collier said of the
winner, also known as Samantha. ``She lives up to what the standard
says. You saw her line and her energy. That was it. She just kept
moving. She wanted. And she got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Samantha's triumph was not a shock, she beat the
presumed favorite, Ch. Lakecove That's My Boy, a white standard
poodle known as Treson. The poodle was the top-ranked dog of 1999
and has won 169 best in shows in her 2-year career. Treson's
grandfather had won the 1991 best in show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed,'' said Dennis McCoy, Treson's handler.
``I loved the springer. It's a great feeling to win. I've been
there.''
</P>
<P>
   During Samantha's photo-op in the middle of the show ring, on a
lavender rug, she hopped momentarily into the silver champion's
bowl. At 42 pounds, she didn't fit as easily as last year's best in
show, a 6-pound Papillon, and quickly hopped out.
</P>
<P>
   As Samantha kibbitzed with the media surrounding her, licking
camera operators as if they were old friends, her handler, Kellie
FitzGerald, said: ``I just depended on her to give me a good show.
She showed great. I can't describe the feeling of being on the
other end of the lead. She represents so much and represents her
father so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Samantha, who is part of a breeding line that goes back 63
years, has earned 49 best-in-breed titles and 200 best in groups in
her show career. She won her breed in each of her three appearances
at Westminster and will now retire to breed.
</P>
<P>
   In retirement, she will not have to work out twice a day on her
canine treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just working, never out of control, perfect, happy and
looking at the crowd,'' FitzGerald said. ``She has heart to
spare.''
</P>
<P>
   Samantha's victory in the sporting group avenged her loss last
year to a legendary Gordon setter.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Billings, the judge of the group, said, ``As I scanned
the group, I knew the judges had really done their work. They sent
me the cream of the sporting group. It was a photo finish with the
black cocker spaniel. They were both in prime condition. But the
springer spaniel, for her breed, had a slightly better head, and
when you say that, you've said it all.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it seemed that the selection of Astro to win the
hound group might portend a truly stunning best-in-show upset,
something to really yip home about. If the dour-looking basset
could win, well, anything was possible.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-year-old native New Yorker has lived in Buenos Aires,
Argentina, for four years and exercises for a half-hour daily on a
treadmill. But mostly, Astro likes to eat, sleep and eat some more.
Astro hadn't even shown for a year, but beat the favored Saluki
bitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy!'' exclaimed Maria Elisa Martinez, who owns 12
bassets, including Astro, cherishing them for their dour visage,
their deliberate gait and their Hush Puppies shoe heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The short-legged Astro couldn't have presented a starker
contrast with the off-white, elegant Saluki, Ch. Sundown Alabaster
Treasure JC, who loped easily, his floppy ears bouncing, as his
handler, Andy Luque, showed him on Madison Square Garden's green
carpet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basset doesn't move as fast as the others, but he moves in
the right way,'' Luque said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the English springer spaniel, 2000's king of
dogs, moved the best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 0027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
