<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8248 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-TIGER-LADN-(SLANG     02-16 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR OF THE TIGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No streak? No difference. Not for Tiger Woods,
whose PGA winning streak reached six _ second best in tour history
_ before Phil Mickelson ended it in a stirring duel last week at
Torrey Pines.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson's victory in the Buick Invitational stopped Woods five
wins shy of Byron Nelson's seemingly untouchable record of 11 in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   With the streak over, Woods can now concentrate on winning the
Nissan Open at Riviera Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is what really drives me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That won't change whether this week's Nissan is for one in a row
or eight in a row. The latter looked as if it might happen when
Woods erased Mickelson's seven-shot lead to tie for the Buick lead
with five holes to play.
</P>
<P>
   After Mickelson had won, Tiger wasn't disappointed in having the
tour's longest streak since 1952 stopped, only in finishing second.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm out there playing or getting ready for a
tournament,'' he said the day before the streak ended, ``the only
time I think about the streak is when you guys bring it up. That's
the only time. I'm out there trying to win a tournament _ that's
all. And what I did last week doesn't really matter this week.''
</P>
<P>
   That immediate focus helped stretch Woods' run as much as his
will to win and his shotmaking accuracy that can border on the
unreal. On the final regulation hole of the Mercedes Championship
last month in Hawaii, Woods needed an eagle to get into a playoff
with Ernie Els for a fifth consecutive tour victory. He hit a
three-wood nearly 300 yards to within eight feet of the flagstick
and got his eagle. And he got the playoff win.
</P>
<P>
   At Pebble Beach two weeks ago, down seven strokes with seven
holes to play, Woods nearly had back-to-back eagles from the
fairway, holing his first attempt from 106 yards and leaving his
next within inches of the cup from 115 yards.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of shotmaking, in Woods' view, was the best part of
his streak. It also might be the best reason to think a future
streak is not that unlikely for the 24-year-old. In just his fourth
full season, Woods has 17 tour victories, including two majors, and
ranks first on the all-time money list.
</P>
<P>
   ``His desire has always been to be the best player who ever
lived,'' Paul Azinger said after Woods' comeback at Pebble Beach.
``I don't think anything's going to slow him down.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Els: ``He's not afraid to make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best I've played against in my 20 years on tour,''
said 1999 Player of the Year Mark O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   Woods remains focused:
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about the streak rather than the shots I'm hitting
or the putts I made here and there,'' Woods said last week. ``And I
think that's more important than the streak because that's what
keeps it alive.''
</P>
<P>
   When it ended on Sunday, it was as much because he had lost his
accuracy rather than Mickelson's tenacity down the stretch. Woods
was able to overcame the lapse with a wondrous short game, but he
was so off his game, he was laughing about it with his caddie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Would you just hit a fairway?' I said, `I'm trying!'
And I missed the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' ability to enjoy himself while struggling is a change
from his early days on tour, when he often responded to misfortune
with irritation. He says it's a matter of feeling more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life changed pretty dramatically from 1996 (when he turned
pro after winning a record third consecutive U.S. Amateur title)
into '97,'' Woods said of his transition from college student to
worldwide celebrity in a span of six months.
</P>
<P>
   He attracted the spotlight by winning twice in his first eight
tour events. When he followed that with a dramatic win in the '97
tour-opening Mercedes Championship _ nearly hitting a hole-in-one
on the first playoff hole _ then won his first professional Masters
by a record 12 strokes, Woods found himself, at age 21, the most
well-known golfer in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can ever prepare you for that,'' he said. ``And I
guess, you know, I didn't handle it well at times. And at other
times I was just kind of learning as I was going.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no class for that, nothing anyone can ever say can
help you along. You have to go through it yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Woods is obviously more accustomed to celebrity and
appears comfortable with his status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a little more experienced than I was in '97 to
handle all this,'' he said to another packed media throng at the
Buick Invitational, where credential requests tripled.
</P>
<P>
   Although the streak is now history, there will likely be no
shortage of media or fans this week at Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   His opposition will likely go with the game plan endorsed by
Woods' former Stanford teammate, Notah Begay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road to any tournament,'' Begay said, ``goes through Tiger
Woods' driveway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
