<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FIREFIGHT IN SOUTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for rewriting throughout) 
 (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Feb. 17:
</P>
<P>
   As their debate in South Carolina demonstrated on Tuesday night,
Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain are in more than a
scorched-earth battle for the Republican presidential nomination.
They are also offering different approaches to conducting and
financing campaigns. Bush sought to re-establish his presidential
stature, accused McCain of starting the mudslinging, and proclaimed
himself again a ``reformer with results.'' McCain tried to be
even-tempered while blaming the governor for shameful negative
attacks and being a come-lately to campaign finance reform. He cast
himself as the one Republican who could rebuild the Reagan
coalition by pulling Democrats and independents into the Republican
fold, while Bush insisted he was the only Republican who could
``end the Clinton era.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the 90-minute debate was Bush's attempt to grab
the label of reformer away from McCain. Before the debate, he even
announced his own version of the campaign finance cleanup advocated
by the Arizona senator. The Texas governor's insistence that his
approach constituted reform had a hollow ring on Tuesday night,
however. His proposal was designed to gain attention without really
removing special-interest money from politics.
</P>
<P>
   Like McCain, Bush would ban unlimited ``soft money'' donations
to political parties by unions and corporations. But unlike McCain,
he would let wealthy individuals make contributions as big as they
want, on the specious ground that curbs on the size of individual
donations are an unconstitutional infringement of free speech. Far
from reforming the system, Bush's proposal is an attempt to confuse
voters and enhance the power of wealthy interests. McCain correctly
condemned the Bush plan as leaving ``a billion-dollar loophole.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate, in Charleston, was often muddled, in part because of
the tirades of Alan Keyes, the third candidate, and weak management
by Larry King. Much of it bogged down as McCain and Bush accused
each other of starting what has become a junkyard campaign of
smears and attacks in the Lee Atwater tradition.
</P>
<P>
   McCain appeared dignified and determined, but he did not get the
knockout he surely desired as a follow-up to his New Hampshire
landslide. He adopted a wounded tone in discussing the negative
telephone calls, mailings and campaign ads that may be causing his
own standing in the polls to slip. He again called on Bush to
follow his lead in abandoning negative ads.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gave an energetic rebuttal to the senator's appeal, warning
McCain not to question his trustworthiness and not to compare him
to Bill Clinton _ ``about as low a blow as you can give.'' The
governor's more combative style and his vow not to be ``defined''
by his adversaries could win sympathy in a state more accustomed
than most to tough politicking and one that is also essential to
the survival of his candidacy. Bush's flooding of the state with
negative attack ads could hurt him down the road by draining his
campaign machine of money, but he is clearly betting that the low
road will work in the low country.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also tried to take the high road on foreign policy. Like
Bush, he assailed the Clinton administration for coddling China and
said that the United States had too readily deployed troops around
the world. But he said that moral factors would weigh more heavily
with him in deciding whether to intervene in certain trouble spots,
indicating that genocide in Rwanda might well be such a case. Bush
disagreed, saying he would not send troops to Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was at his best in defending his record on education in
Texas, and McCain on reconstituting the Republican Party and
curbing its addiction to special-interest money. If McCain can win
without mud or push polls, he could elevate the entire process for
the rest of the year. He has also redefined the nature of
campaigning by subjecting himself to more questioning from regular
voters and from reporters on his campaign bus than any leading
presidential candidate in decades. But this debate, with its dogged
performance from a more confident Bush, showed that the next four
days in South Carolina will see a free-swinging battle whose
outcome cannot yet be predicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
