<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FIGHTING THE WIMP FACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for changes throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIKEN, S.C. _ George Bush fighting the wimp factor? That rings a
bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it, but I think Bush's problem is that he's
wimpy, he seems to dilly-dally,'' confided Barbara Looney, a
retired gift-wrapper at Macy's who lives in North Augusta, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend Lois Marable, a fellow retiree, agreed: ``I do not
like the way he looks on television. He looks like a wimp.''
</P>
<P>
   The two John McCain fans had come to the University of South
Carolina here to see their man. After he spoke, he called on Mrs.
Marable during the question period. She had only one question: Was
he nuts?
</P>
<P>
   While the Arizona senator must persuade South Carolinians that
he's not too coiled, Bush must persuade them that he's coiled
enough.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Saluda on Monday, Bush acknowledged,
after his flaccid performance in New Hampshire, that South
Carolinians had been pressing him about whether he was tough enough
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, people do that all the time,'' he said. Asked why, he
replied: ``I guess because they think I'm such a nice fellow, you
know? I don't know. 'Cause they want to win in November, they want
to figure out who can go toe-to-toe.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is why he has been talking louder and faster in
speeches here, and came out swinging, determined to dominate, with
an aggressive and well-coached debate performance on Tuesday night,
even as McCain tried to appear calm and avuncular.
</P>
<P>
   So now it was W. who was coiled, and McCain who was too detached
as he overplayed the adult card. ``It's not the Washington
mentality,'' the senator said of his plan to stress debt reduction
over tax cuts. ``It's the grown-up mentality. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   It must have been a nightmarish, Groundhog Day experience for W.
to be forced, as his father once was, to defend his toughness, when
he expected to simply swagger in and avenge the family name.
</P>
<P>
   W.'s campaign has imitated his dad's playbook, which may be
sorely out of date: pandering to the religious right, splashing mud
on foes while promising to inspire Americans' ``better angels.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was one way the son was never supposed to be like the
father. His supporters never thought W. would get tagged with the
``W'' word. He would never be called wimp. He was, they whispered,
more like Ronald Reagan. He had that cock-of-the-walk way about
him. He seemed more peppery Texan than flighty preppy.
</P>
<P>
   The 1987 Newsweek cover with the headline ``Fighting the Wimp
Factor'' was a searing experience for Vice President Bush, a war
hero, and his hyper-loyal son. The story said many Republicans were
worried that George Bush might not be ``strong enough or tough
enough for the challenges of the Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
   W., still a hothead in those days, called the magazine's White
House correspondent to inform him: ``Newsweek's been cut off.
You're out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   In September 1988, the vice president was still so peeved that
Katharine Graham, the publisher of Newsweek, had to meet with him
to appease him. He had even counted the number of times the word
``wimp'' had been used in the story.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, W. still sometimes needles Newsweek reporters about
the wimp war.
</P>
<P>
   So he must loathe the position he now finds himself in, locked
in an unexpectedly scorching battle with a gritty war hero who
treats him as a callow squirt.
</P>
<P>
   Why was that ``W'' word popping up with this W.?
</P>
<P>
   Was it the bad luck of drawing this particular opponent, someone
who can speak knowingly about self-sacrifice to spoiled boomers,
while W. can only embrace such notions as distant ideals? Was it
the consequence of Bush's own diffidence about the race, which has
clearly been more grueling than he expected? Or did his attempt to
mimic everything McCain does _ including his risible,
loophole-laden campaign finance ``reform'' package _ leave him
looking like an insecure adolescent?
</P>
<P>
   Louise Hendley, 77, who swooned over McCain at a campaign event
at the Beth Shalom Synagogue in Columbia on Tuesday, said she
really liked Bush. ``But he just doesn't give me the feeling that
he could be in charge in an emergency,'' she said. ``He's just a
cute little boy to me, a cute little puppy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the sort of praise that would make a candidate's blood
run cold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
