<HEADLINE>
INVECTIVE FLIES IN S.C. DEBATE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Palmetto State's primary election just three days away,
Arizona Sen. John McCain and Texas Gov. George W. Bush had one
last, raucous scrap on national televi sion, with each accusing the
other of negative campaigning even as they sparred on issues like
tax policy and campaign reform.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute debate, carried live on CNN, was characterized by
a series of testy exchanges about the increasingly nasty tone the
Republican race has taken.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's GOP primary in South Carolina is viewed as an
important milestone, with the winner expected to grab the coveted
momentum as the cam paigns head into the Super Tues day primary
sweepstakes March 7.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has closed on Bush here in recent weeks, hopes to
keep the race tight by defusing a series of negative Bush ads that
have been saturating the air waves all week. Pundits say Mc Cain
might have a chance to beat Bush here if turnout is high in
Saturday's contest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's ads blast McCain on a series of issues from campaign
finance to personal integrity, and it was Bush who accused McCain
during the debate of triggering the barrage with an ad that
compared Bush to President Clin ton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not question my trustwor thiness, and do not compare me to
Bill Clinton,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   During a heated finger-point ing session, McCain retorted that
he had pulled the ad last week. He chided the Texas governor for
continuing the attacks and em bracing campaign surrogates who, he
said, are bent on sullying McCain's reputation, particularly with
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the nastiest campaign people have seen in a
long time,'' McCain said to Bush. ``You should be ashamed of your
self.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, McCain told report ers that South Carolina voters
were tiring of the hostilities. He predicted Bush will suffer the
consequences at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's already beginning to be a backlash against it,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, made it clear what voters can expect through the
end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand by my ads,'' Bush said. ``I stand by what I'm trying
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although arguments over the conduct of the campaign often
dominated the debate, the candi dates also tried to contrast posi
tions on sensitive issues like taxes and campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   Wedged between McCain and Bush, and often trying to steer the
debate back to issues, was Republican Alan Keyes, running a distant
third in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot more impor tant things,'' Keyes said. ``And
all I'm doing is listening to these guys go on about their ads?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush tried to stake out new turf on campaign finance reform, a
subject McCain has pushed hard for months and appears to be
resonating with voters, partic ularly independents and Demo crats
who could cross over to vote in Saturday's open primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed limits on soft-money contributions to political
parties by corporations and unions as well as limits on cam paign
contributions from lobby ists while Congress is in session. Bush
used stump speeches this week to tout his plan.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, however, called the reform plan fatally flawed. Be cause
it allows unlimited soft-money donations by individuals, McCain
said, it's ``a billion-dollar loophole.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain tried to distinguish himself on fiscal policy, saying he
would seek to balance tax cuts for middle-income Americans with
spending to shore up the Social Security trust fund and reduce the
national debt. Bush stood by his proposal for deep tax cuts that
would target wealthy taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet I'll cut taxes at the top; that'll encourage entrepre
neurship,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Moderator Larry King led the candidates onto some unfamiliar
ground as well, asking at one point whether they would sup port a
moratorium on the death penality in light of advances in DNA
testing that have exoner ated some death row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Bush answered bluntly, defending Texas' record of exe
cutions.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that the develop ments ``would provoke a review,
clearly, of cases that are ques tionable,'' but that he would not
ban the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death penalty is an ap propriate penalty for certain
crimes,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
