<HEADER>
A8253 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DNA-CONVICTIONS-SFCHR     02-16 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-CONVICTIONS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DNA EVIDENCE STUDY SHOWS HOW 62 INNOCENT MEN WERE FOUND GUILTY  &HT;     By ERIN HALLISSY 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A newly released study of 62 inmates exonerated by DNA evidence
shows that mistaken eyewitness identification played a role in 84
percent of the wrongful convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Whites were more likely to misidentify blacks as their
attackers, according to DNA experts and authors Barry Scheck and
Peter Neufeld.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, who gained nationwide fame working on O. J.
Simpson's defense during his murder trial, run the Innocence
Project at a New York City law school. Their study, presented in a
book written with New York Daily News writer Jim Dwyer, ``Actual
Innocence: Five Days to Execution and Other Dispatches from the
Wrongfully Convicted,'' was released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck and Neufeld have scheduled a meeting at the Boalt Hall
School of Law at the University of California at Berkeley to
discuss setting up a similar Innocence Project there.
</P>
<P>
   Several universities nationwide are part of what Scheck calls
the Innocence Network, doing investigative and legal work for
inmates claiming that DNA evidence could prove that they were
wrongfully convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of network is what really makes a difference in
improving the system,'' Scheck said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck, a Boalt Hall graduate, said he would love to have
students at UC-Berkeley working with the network.
</P>
<P>
   Boalt Hall Professor Charles Weissenberg,cq &LR;  who is meeting with
Scheck next Tuesday, said he's intrigued by the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want to hear more of how this project would work,''
he said. ``I think whether or not we do it is going to depend upon
interest, the possibility of attracting outside funding and a
decision about whether the cases we could do are really good
teaching and training classes for our students.''
</P>
<P>
   DNA evidence has been used to exonerate 63 male inmates in the
United States, including Kevin Green, an Orange County man who was
freed in 1996 after 16 years locked up for a crime he didn't
commit. It is also expected to free a Riverside man who was
sentenced to 45 years for rape and robbery in 1998. Recently
completed tests done by a Richmond lab reportedly have shown that
he could not have committed the crime.
</P>
<P>
   DNA technology has become a growing issued in California, with
California Attorney General Bill Lockyer saying his top priority
this year is to improve the state's DNA databank in Berkeley. As
reported by The Chronicle last October, the databank of convicted
murderers, sex offenders and spouse abusers has a backlog of more
than 100,000 untested samples.
</P>
<P>
   The man who actually committed the murder that Green was
imprisoned for was identified through the database for that crime,
along with a series of others.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer has pushed for more than $5.4 million in additional
funding for the lab this year, on top of $10 million already
allocated between 1999 and 2001 for hiring additional staff members
and processing more samples. The databank, which now has about
45,000 profiles of convicted offenders, should have more than
200,000 by June 2001, Lockyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck is a supporter of DNA databanks, saying the genetic tests
are the most important forensic tool to convict the guilty and free
the innocent. The study that he, Neufeld and Dwyer released Tuesday
shows that a number of factors were behind the wrongful convictions
of the freed inmates, including fraudulent science and police and
prosecutorial misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Their book examines 62 of the 63 cases in which there were
exonerations. The authors said they were most disturbed by racial
misidentification in the conviction of black men, especially in
cases that involved white victims.
</P>
<P>
   According to the authors, whites misidentified African Americans
35 percent of the time, compared to African Americans
misidentifying African Americans 24 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known for some time that cross-racial identification is
a troubling problem,'' Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   The book notes that Illinois and New York, the only two states
with laws authorizing postconviction DNA testing, led the country
in the number of inmates exonerated through the technology.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. John Burton, D-San Francisco, introduced legislation
last month to allow postconviction DNA testing if the evidence or
technology for testing that evidence was not available to the
defendant at the time of trial.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck said most Americans believe that DNA testing should be
available to defendants who say it could exonerate them, and
therefore states should not impose limitations on postconviction
testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The testing doesn't cost that much money, much less that it
costs to keep someone in jail,'' said Scheck. He said the tests
cost about $3,000 to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a simple matter of justice,'' Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Charlie Goodyear contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 0056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8254 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-SEQUOIAS-PROTECTION-S     02-16 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEQUOIAS-PROTECTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CONSIDERS PROTECTING CALIFORNIA SEQUOIAS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By JONATHAN CURIEL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton asked for a review Tuesday that could lead to
permanent protection of more than 400,000 acres of California's
giant sequoia trees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton directed Agriculture Secretary Daniel Glickman to
consult with members of Congress, California officials and others
to see if it is ``appropriate'' to designate the sequoias as a
national monument.
</P>
<P>
   About 33 groves of giant sequoia trees are in Sequoia National
Forest, bordering Sequoia National Park and Kings Canyon National
Park, not far from Fresno. The groves are already on federal land
but are still subject to periodic, limited logging.
</P>
<P>
   Besides these groves, Clinton is considering whether to add
protections to two groves in Sierra National Forest and one grove
in Tahoe National Forest. Clinton has already asked for federal
money to purchase another grove of giant sequoias on private land
adjacent to Sequoia National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Glickman, Clinton said he is considering using
the Antiquities Act of 1906 to redesignate the groves. The
president has used the Antiquities Act several times, most recently
last month to give permanent protection to land adjacent to the
Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to ensure that these majestic cathedral groves, which
John Muir called `Nature's masterpiece,' are protected for future
generations to study and enjoy,'' Clinton wrote the agriculture
secretary, whose department includes the U.S. Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he wants a recommendation from Glickman within 60
days. It is possible Clinton could create a sequoia national
monument within days of receiving Glickman's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups have campaigned to protect the sequoia
groves for many years. About 70 giant sequoia groves are located in
Central California, close to the Sierra. Approximately 25 of those
groves are in Yosemite and other national parks and are protected
from logging and other encroachments. The remaining groves are in
Sequoia National Forest and surrounding areas and are not
permanently protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people would be surprised that more than half of these
trees are managed according to a forest plan that talks about
sustainable harvest of the sequoias,'' said George Frampton,
chairman of the president's Council on Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   Frampton said Clinton is considering protecting between 330,000
and 440,000 acres of land, or about a third of the Sequoia National
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental organizations, including the Sierra Club, praised
Clinton's letter, but the California Forestry Association, a timber
industry lobbying group, complained that the sequoia groves don't
need more protection.
</P>
<P>
   Another lobbying group said that Clinton's directive was partly
political.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he uses (the Antiquities Act) excessively, partly to
score political points for Al Gore,'' said Michael Klein, spokesman
for the American Forest &AMP; Paper Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 0059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
