<SLUG> BC-SMALL-CASINOS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER LOSES BID TO SUE FOUR AREA CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Kansas City lawyer who said he lost more
than $95,000 gambling at ``illegal'' area riverboats since 1994 has
lost an appeal to save his proposed class-action federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen B. Small filed the claim in 1997, based on a Missouri
Supreme Court decision that said some off-river casinos were
operating illegally. Small appealed a federal district judge's
dismissal of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Small alleged that defendants Harrah's North Kansas City Casino
&AMP; Hotel, Argosy Riverside Casino, Station Casino Kansas City and
the Flamingo Hilton Casino had ``reaped hundreds of millions of
dollars in receipts from the conduct of land-based or
non-Missouri-River-based gambling games ... (which the Supreme
Court has declared) unconstitutional gambling activities in the
state of Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Tuesday upheld the
dismissal, ruling that the casinos hold valid state gambling
licenses and that Missouri voters in November 1998 retroactively
legalized games of chance aboard casinos moored off-river.
</P>
<P>
   Small had sought to have himself appointed administrator of a
fund that would have been established by the court with casino
revenue to pay back ``persons who conveyed money ... in unlawful
gambling games of chance'' at the four casinos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
