<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8269 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-DRUNK-KAN &LR;      02-16 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS MAN PLEADS GUILTY TO CHARGES FROM WRECK THAT SERIOUSLY
INJURED WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- KC-DRUNK-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ From the moment his pickup veered into
oncoming traffic and collided with a woman's car, severely injuring
her, Larry R. Watson II has taken responsibility for what happened.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday he made it official, pleading guilty in Johnson
County, Kan., District Court to aggravated battery and driving
under the influence of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Olathe, Kan., man faces 34 months in prison if
the judge follows plea negotiations. Sentencing is April 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all my fault. I shouldn't have been drinking,'' Watson
told one of the first witnesses to reach the wreck Sept. 29, said
Lannie Ornburn, an assistant district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's attorney, William Grimshaw, said Watson would not
request probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been Mr. Watson's position that he is responsible
and should pay the penalty,'' Grimshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Kelleher, 30, was in a coma for several days after the
collision near 153rd Street and Lindenwood Drive in Olathe, Kan.,
Ornburn said.
</P>
<P>
   She was in the hospital until Oct. 12 and spent two more months
in a rehabilitation center. She still requires twice-weekly
rehabilitation sessions, and doctors say she may never fully regain
her motor skills, Ornburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's blood-alcohol level was measured after the wreck at
0.14 percent, Ornburn said, almost twice the legal limit of 0.08.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also estimated that his truck was going 58 mph
when he began braking and 45 mph at impact. The speed limit is 30
mph on that part of Lindenwood, Ornburn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
