<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8271 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-PISTONS-H     02-16 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-PISTONS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Detroit's Grant Hill and Jerry Stackhouse, the NBA's
second-highest-scoring twosome, spent the weekend dunking and
2balling and showing off in the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Shandon Anderson and Cuttino Mobley were relatively hard to find
when the league shined its spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   If you looked closely enough, you could spot Mobley either
playing in the rookie game or tossing a pass to Steve Francis in
the dunk contest. Anderson had a comfy seat in front of a big
screen in Atlanta. NBC declined to feature either in a commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Then the real games started up again Tuesday night, and the
Rockets twosome threw themselves into the teeth of the Pistons and
carried Houston to a 107-102 win.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Rockets (21-30) a home record better than
.500 for the first time this season. They are 14-13 at Compaq
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Mobley combined for 46 points to give the Rockets
all they would need and were more than the Pistons, the league's
highest-scoring team, could handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was really important that they just didn't have a
one-sided game,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``I thought
we pushed it at them pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson led the Rockets with 25 points, adding six rebounds and
four assists. It marked the sixth time this season he has led the
Rockets in scoring, and the Rockets have won all six.
</P>
<P>
   It was also one of many games in which Anderson took on a high
scorer _ Allen Iverson, Ron Mercer, Penny Hardaway and now Hill _
and had one of his best offensive nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to score against anybody,'' Anderson said with a laugh.
``I always want to go at somebody, but especially against those
guys. They're the core of their team. They both got more than 20
shots up tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it was just Anderson's fifth game with at least 20
points, Tomjanovich described it as typical of Anderson's style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shandon was great,'' Tomjanovich said. ``He's all over the
place. It was one of those Shandon games where he's finding a way
to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we'll see more and more of that. He's the kind of
guy who finds holes in the defense. When you've got a guy who plays
so hard and the effort is always there, good things are going to
happen. He's going to have games like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley added 21 points, including 14 in the second quarter, when
he drove the Rockets to an 18-point lead. But unlike Anderson, who
said he purposely sought to step up his offensive game to make Hill
and Stackhouse work defensively, Mobley said he was simply in his
usual role as a scorer off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just go out and play, and it doesn't matter if it's against
them or anybody else,'' Mobley said. ``I've played against guys
like that since I was 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Stackhouse and Hill had their usual high-scoring games and then
some. But neither could maintain any control of the game.
Stackhouse led all scorers with 29 points, but he made just 10 of
26 shots, including four of 12 in the second half and one of five
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Hill had 23 points, 11 rebounds and six assists. But he also had
a season-high eight turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wears you down chasing us around instead of going down
there relaxing,'' Anderson said. ``If we make those guys run
around, when they come back down they're breathing hard, and it's
hard to get your legs under your shots. Sometimes your best defense
is your offense.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Pistons picked themselves up nicely, knocking all but
two points off that 18-point second-quarter deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Rockets lost their composure with their lead fading
so rapidly, they found themselves almost as soon as the fourth
quarter started.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even talk about it,'' Mobley said. ``We just kept
playing. We stayed aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   It took two minutes to push what was a five-point lead going
into the quarter to 10. Later, with one more strong two-minute
push, they built it back to 14.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon scored on a drive, and when Pistons coach Alvin
Gentry, the NBA leader in technical fouls, complained about that
drive, he drew a technical foul. Mobley made the free throw for a
92-79 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After a Hill drive, the Rockets had another three-point
possession. Steve Francis hit a free throw, then grabbed the
rebound of his miss.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon scored on a turnaround jumper to push the lead to 95-81
with seven minutes left. The Rockets were still up by 12 with two
minutes left when Gentry cleared his bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense is nonexistent,'' Stackhouse said. ``Houston got
too many easy opportunities, and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hill: ``It's amazing we have above a .500 record (25-24)
considering where our defense is.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the Rockets' offensive sources _ six players scored
in double figures _ they cited their defensive effort for slowing
the prolific Pistons offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against a really athletic team, I thought we did a good job
defensively, especially in the first half,'' Tomjanovich said. ``In
the second half, they really got it going. They're tough to guard.
They really are.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, so were a Rockets twosome, even if they might not
yet star in NBA productions or soft-drink commercials.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
