<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-JACKSON-COLUMN-LA     02-16 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JACKSON-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO REMINDED OF WHAT IT'S MISSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In a town where every Bulls game used to be Super Bowl
Sunday, Tuesday night was as good as it gets these days.
</P>
<P>
   The United Center was packed, not just for the return of coach
Phil Jackson, but for Shaq and Kobe and the only Bulls game that
has mattered since Michael Jordan retired two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls tried to play down Jackson's return, but their gritty
88-76 loss to the Los Angeles Lakers suggested otherwise. This is a
team with only 10 victories and looking at a whole lot of bad
before it gets good.
</P>
<P>
   There was a pregame ovation for Jackson in remembrance of the
six NBA titles he helped bring to this city. When the game started,
the Lakers played like a victory was only a matter of time. The
Bulls played as if every trip down the court was their last.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone now,'' said Bulls forward Elton Brand, the No.e pick
in last year's draft. ``We didn't play well because of him. We have
to plot our own course.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a slow process, but with 7:08 left Monday and the
score tied at 67, a playoff game broke out, probably the only one
this building will host for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal moved into the paint and was taken down by Will
Perdue, a center on three of Jackson's championships in Chicago.
There was a brief scuffle and Perdue was given a flagrant foul.
</P>
<P>
   But the real damage for the Bulls came when O'Neal sank both
free throws, then came back and hit a six-foot hook shot.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the buzz of a sellout crowd, the game ended right
there. It was the Lakers' first victory in Chicago since March 11,
1995. But the theater was far from over.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal called Perdue a bum. Perdue mentioned his four
championship rings, including one last year with the Spurs, and
asked how many Shaq was carrying In a flash, the attention moved
off Jackson and onto O'Neal, who sank 11 of 12 free throws despite
a sore shoulder. Shaq entered the game shooting 48 percent from the
line this season and 54 percent for his career.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, he hit his first nine. Perdue said if that
continues, the NBA season could be over for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers fans should be ecstatic about the possibilities. Perdue
said he was proud of his young teammates, who said they were not
overwhelmed by all the Jackson hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great story, Phil's first visit back,'' Perdue
said. ``There were a lot of people who came out tonight who haven't
been here all year and I want to thank him for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson arrived in town Monday but got the town buzzing at last
weekend's All-Star Game with not-so-subtle jabs at his former
bosses Jerry Reinsdorf and Jerry Krause. During his final years in
Chicago, Jackson and Krause often battled over decision-making with
the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson did not see Krause and Reinsdorf but caught up with many
old friends.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after he left the Bulls and sat out the season, the
Bulls honored Jackson in a ceremony that included hoisting a banner
to remember his 545 victories with the club.
</P>
<P>
   At the morning shootaround, Lakers guard Kobe Bryant kidded
Jackson about seeing the coach's name in the rafters with Jordan
and former Bulls greats Bob Love and Jerry Sloan, now the coach in
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the number of wins?'' Bryant asked. ``And what did
Jerry Sloan do for this organization?''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson admitted there was plenty of emotion when he received a
loud ovation from the sellout crowd of 23,208. There were a few
empty seats, a sign that all is not forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for all the photographers,'' he said. ``I couldn't
see any of the people and there were a lot of them out there. It
was a warm welcome, a very friendly welcome. I thanked the Bulls
for not doing anything extraordinary. I might have broke down and
cried.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other bench, Bulls rookie Ron Artest didn't know what to
make of the applause. He knows the history. It hangs high above the
floor and resides in the hearts of every Bulls fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard a lot of cheering here but never that loud for
someone on the other team,'' he said. ``We want to keep those for
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
