<HEADER>
A8273 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHR     02-16 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH HAS SOME CALIFORNIANS FEELING LEFT BEHIND
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
With just three weeks to go before the California primary, GOP
front-runner George W. Bush has riled some California Republicans
by suggesting he may not attend the only debate scheduled in the
state before voters go to the polls on March 7.
<P>
   Some GOP insiders say they're now worried that the Texas
governor may be taking the state for granted, and that not debating
in California could hurt his campaign for the Republican
presidential nomination _ as well as the GOP cause in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something counterintuitive about not showing up to
campaign in the biggest state in the nation,'' said Don Casper,
chairman of the San Francisco Republican Party and a pledged
delegate for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all realize that a candidate can't be everywhere he wants
to be. But given California's importance and its peculiar open
primary, it would seem prudent of Gov. Bush to make a series of
appearances _ or at least one major appearance _ before the
election.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate between Republican presidential candidates, sponsored
by CNN and the Los Angeles Times, is scheduled for March 2 in Los
Angeles, and organizers insisted this week that Bush had informally
committed to appearing.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's top state campaign officials this week said the GOP
presidential hopeful never agreed to the event and may not be
there. They said the governor's schedule was fluid after South
Carolina's primary on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign's debate announcement raised concerns from
some state GOP activists, who noted that the governor has skipped
the past three state conventions _ the most recent this month _ and
hasn't visited the state since November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush keeps sending out mixed messages. He keeps saying he's
going to compete vigorously in California, but he needs to back
that up with some action,'' said GOP consultant Matt Cunningham,
the former state spokesman for the Forbes campaign. ``It would send
a discouraging message to Republicans to skip the Los Angeles
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   The suggestions that Bush could be a no-show at the California
debate also drew a bemused response from the campaign of GOP rival
John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``For California Republicans, this is the ghost of presidential
campaigns past,'' said Dan Schnur, communications director for the
McCain campaign. ``George Bush Sr. blew off the state entirely, Bob
Dole didn't campaign here until it was too late, and now Gov. Bush
is telling the people that this isn't a priority for him either.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain believes it's important for the people of
California to see and hear the candidates talk about the issues,''
said Schnur. ``Thirty-three million Californians are worth that
attention ... and we'll be there, either way.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign had another reason to be happy about its
prospects. The Associated Press reported last night that California
Secretary of State Bill Jones, the state's highest-ranking
Republican, will endorse McCain at a news conference Wednesday in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   CNN and the Los Angeles Times scheduled the California debate
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has told us informally that he is planning on
attending,'' Maryanne McNellis, president of the Times' National
Edition told Chronicle columnist Debra J. Saunders. McNellis said
Bush has assured Times staffers on the campaign trail that he'd be
there, and added, ``We are expecting him. ... We'd hate to see his
campaign represented by an empty chair.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, there have been reports that GOP candidates
could appear at another California debate _ one planned by the
Technology Network, a Silicon Valley advocacy group _ possibly
using the Internet as a venue.
</P>
<P>
   But Ellen Stroud, spokeswoman for the group, ruled that out day,
saying negotiations had been under way, but ``we decided not to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That left state Republicans debating the fallout Tuesday should
Bush pass up the the only scheduled debate in California.
</P>
<P>
   Bush holds a three-point lead over McCain in California in the
latest Public Policy Institute of California poll.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign said the governor will be no stranger to his
supporters in California before voters go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush is going to campaign vigorously throughout the
state of California leading up to the primary in the coming
weeks,'' Alixe Mattingly of Bush's California campaign said
yesterday. ``He has devoted much time to California. He has an
unprecedented grassroots organization throughout the state which is
enthusiastically working on his behalf now and in the coming
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one leading Republican state consultant noted that with
Bush holding the lead in crucial primaries in South Carolina and
Michigan, McCain has little to lose by making an issue of the
California debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course John McCain will come out here and do every free
appearance he can. He needs the earned media,'' the consultant
said.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, the strategist said, may have more to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he decides to take a pass on it because there are other
ways to get the message out, that's a strategic decision,'' said
the consultant. ``We've got to take a serious look, as any campaign
would, on where (the) soft spots are. You have to be very shrewd in
your targeting. The open primary dynamic has changed the
fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   State GOP officials declined to take sides in the dustup, saying
that whatever happens, March 7 will be good for Republicans here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about the debate that's occurring between the
Republican presidential candidates _ it has excited Republicans
from Del Norte to San Diego,'' said Stuart DeVeaux, spokesman for
the state GOP. ``If anything, we're waiting for Bradley to start
beating up on Gore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
