r a BC-EXAMINER-SALE-SFCHRON     02-16 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HEARST CORP. REPORTS THAT EXAMINER HAS SEVERAL POTENTIAL BUYERS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Political consultant and onetime mayoral
candidate Clint Reilly, who filed a lawsuit to block the Hearst
Corp. from purchasing The San Francisco Chronicle, emerged Tuesday
as one of several potential buyers of the rival San Francisco
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst had set a deadline of Tuesday afternoon for offers to be
submitted by potential buyers. Reilly's lawyer, Joseph M. Alioto,
told the Associated Press that his client had been invited by
Hearst to submit a proposal for the 112-year-old paper and
subsequently did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did make a proposal,'' Alioto was quoted as saying. ``He's
an unusual guy, and he's willing to do this and put up his money to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, a millionaire political consultant, spent more than $3.5
million trying to unseat San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Reilly attended a meeting at the Examiner and ended up
with a broken ankle following a dust-up with Executive Editor Phil
Bronstein. He subsequently filed an assault-and-battery suit, which
was settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly is currently overseas on business and could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst said Tuesday only that it had received several
``indications of interest'' from potential buyers of the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are presently engaged in the process of reviewing and
evaluating the proposals,'' said Debra Shriver, a Hearst
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   She also said no time limit exists for the company to make a
final decision on which suitor, if any, will be chosen to purchase
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner has been for sale since August, when Hearst said it
intended to purchase the Chronicle for $660 million. If no buyer
for the Examiner emerges, Hearst has said it would close the paper
and merge its staff with that of The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect that Hearst is now gnashing its teeth in
disappointment,'' said Stephen Barnett, a law professor at the
University of California at Berkeley and newspaper antitrust
expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the last thing they wanted to happen,'' he
said. ``A sale would mean competition for the Chronicle. The last
thing Hearst wants is competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Justice is investigating Hearst's purchase of
The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto also told the Chronicle Tuesday that Hearst asked Reilly
late last week to postpone a March 9 hearing on his lawsuit until
March 23.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said he filed Tuesday for the delay ``based upon written
assurances that they would not consummate any deal until that
date'' or would give 10 days' notice before a sale is made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not expect them to be doing anything before the
hearing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, which had originally placed a ``for sale'' sign only on
the Examiner's name and subscription list, sweetened the deal last
month by including a printing plant, the Examiner office building,
trucks and other assets.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department and city officials had complained that Hearst
was not making a sincere effort to find a buyer for the paper.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, even the new-and-improved sale terms do not include
the joint operating agreement under which the Examiner and
Chronicle have shared resources _ and revenue _ for 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Without a continuation of the agreement, which expires in any
case in 2005, critics have charged that Hearst is not serious about
finding a new owner for the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   UC Berkeley's Barnett said any sale would probably have to
include at least a temporary extension of the joint operating
agreement to make the change in ownership a smooth one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether the Justice Department will look over
Hearst's shoulder to make sure they make a reasonable deal,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst offered no clues Tuesday as to who might be interested in
purchasing the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Fang, publisher of San Francisco's Independent newspaper,
has been frequently mentioned as a potential buyer. He could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential buyer is the Knight Ridder chain, based in San
Jose. Chief executive Tony Ridder has said in the past that he
would not be interested in purchasing the Examiner unless it
includes the joint operating agreement with the Chronicle. He
declined to comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Singleton, whose Alameda Newspaper Group publishes the
Oakland Tribune and other newspapers, said in a statement last
month that he has ``no interest in purchasing the San Francisco
Examiner under any circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim White, publisher of the Examiner, said staff members had not
been expecting earth-shattering news Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's sort of a presumption that today, tomorrow and the
next day aren't going to be very climactic,'' he said. ``It feels
as though things are going to be dragging on for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   He had no comment on the report that Reilly had submitted a
proposal for the paper.
</P>
<P>
   One Examiner reporter said the mood was fairly low-key in the
newsroom and that ``people are just wandering around telling
jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bronstein, the Examiner's executive editor,
``People here have done remarkably well given the possibility of
distraction. They've been very professional.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
