<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-UNIVERSITIES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 UC, STANFORD CLAIM PART OF OLD RENO  &HT;     By CARL NOLTE and BILL WORKMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the strangest land title cases in the history of the
West, the University of California and Stanford University are
laying claim to streets in the heart of Reno's downtown gambling
district.
</P>
<P>
   The issue came up when the city of Reno started going through
some dusty 131-year-old deeds and records. The city was trying to
collect money from several big casinos that had built skyways over
the downtown streets so gamblers could walk from casino to casino.
</P>
<P>
   The casinos disputed the city's claim that it owned the streets,
but when the city dug around, it found that UC and Stanford might
have title, based on deeds that went back to 1868.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is kind of strange,'' said Mike Chapman, an attorney who
represents Reno. ``No case in the country has been like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The city thought it would contact the two universities, who
inherited claims owned by the 19th century railroad moguls known as
the Big Four. The city had filed an action to quiet title to the
streets; instead, it stirred a dusty old hornets' nest.
</P>
<P>
   The universities, said Chapman, ``are taking kind of a hard line
on it.'' Indeed, they are. Both Stanford and UC say they have
rights in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made arguments in favor of our interests in the
property, and we intend to pursue this,'' said UC counsel Lloyd
Lee. ``We can't just give away assets that have substantial
value.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an obligation to the trust (that established
Stanford), and we need first to qualify if there are any assets and
find their value,'' said Stanford acting general counsel Debra
Zumwalt. ``Even with something as strange as this, we have got to
look into it first.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Flanagan, a Reno lawyer UC and Stanford have retained to
represent them in Nevada, says he thinks the two universities have
a good case; he believes that Charles Crocker, one of the Big Four
and the owner of the Reno town site, never ceded the streets to the
city. Flanagan says he has some old deeds to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   The city says it has some old deeds to prove the opposite.
``Stanford and UC do not own anything,'' Chapman said.
</P>
<P>
   All of this arises out of those swashbuckling days of
yesteryear, when the West was open for the taking. A man named
Myron Lake founded a town on the banks of the Truckee River and
named it Reno, for a Civil War general.
</P>
<P>
   Silver was found in huge quantities nearby, making Reno
important. And in 1868, the Central Pacific railroad came through,
linking the little town to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Crocker ran the construction crews that built the railroad and
bought up Lake's land. He had railroad surveyors lay out streets
and a town, and sold lots. Crocker signed all the deeds himself.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Crocker land in this part of Nevada came under
the control of a firm called the Pacific Improvement Co., which, in
turn, was controlled by all of the Big Four _ Crocker, Collis P.
Huntington, Mark Hopkins and Leland Stanford. The four men were the
richest in the West.
</P>
<P>
   When they died, Hopkins and Huntington left their interests to
UC. Stanford and his wife, Jane, founded a university, which
inherited the Stanford interests.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth party, the Crocker interests, belonged to the Crocker
Estate Co., said Charles Crocker, the great-great-grandson of the
original Charles Crocker. He said that portion was sold to Foremost
McKesson Corp. in 1968. It was unclear whether McKessonHBOC, as the
company is now known, would have a claim against Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting historical footnote,'' Crocker said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the facts are shrouded in history,'' said Flanagan.
</P>
<P>
   The city thinks the universities are out to get money from the
city. How much, Chapman does not know. He says he does not even
know how much the casinos were paying the city for air rights over
the disputed streets. ``Under a million a year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that the rights to the streets of Reno are worth
many millions.
</P>
<P>
   The city's defense is that so much time has elapsed that the
universities have no further interest in something that occurred
more than 130 years ago. ``It is the doctrine of acquiescence,''
said Chapman, who alleges, in effect, that a claim that has been
quiet for 130 years should remain quiet. ``We have a very strong
case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have deeds signed by Crocker.''
</P>
<P>
   The universities also have deeds signed by Crocker and, Flanagan
says, they show he never intended to deed the streets of Reno to
the city of Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be decided by Judge Steven Kosach in Washoe County
District Court. He has received briefs and is considering the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Tanya Schevitz contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
