<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SIDEWALK SUPERINTENDENTS EXTINCT  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Where have all the knotholes gone? In the old
days, when lives and minds were simpler, there were holes in the
plywood walls around construction sites, and people would stop and
watch the modern world being built.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are no holes. WillieWorld is alive with digging and
building, but it's all behind high walls with plugged knotholes.
What are they doing back there that they don't want us to see?
</P>
<P>
   -- Local celeb ``outed'' by supe tab! The supermarket tabloid
stalked the celeb all over town with a snoop cam, caught him buying
adult gay videos. This is news ... somewhere. Stop the
pressesz-z-z.
</P>
<P>
   -- Willie Brown says take rent-control protection away from
wealthy renters. Critics say that would only benefit greedy
landlords. Possible solution: For every new dollar a landlord
collects from a rich tenant, make landlord give the city 50 cents,
and earmark the money for developing low-income housing stock.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lotta Dotz dropped by the Old Pro sports bar in Palo Alto,
saw a T-shirt inscribed: ``The face is familiar, but I can't seem
to remember my name.''
</P>
<P>
   -- At the NBA All-Star Game, the few tattoo-free players looked
unfinished, like blank billboards. Overheard in stands: ``Read any
good players lately?''
</P>
<P>
   -- R.I.P., the Museum of the City of San Francisco. It's outta
business after eight years at the Cannery. Just another sad
renter's tale. Surely there's a place where curator/historian
Gladys Hansen could set up shop again.
</P>
<P>
   -- Who wants to be a Reform Party presidential candidate? The
Party Party is still reeling from the defections of visionaries
Trump and Ventura. Say, what are Cheech and Chong doing?
</P>
<P>
   -- Party of six eats at Spenger's Seafood Grotto in Berkeley.
Has way-less-than-satisfactory dining experience. Kevin Lewis
writes detailed letter to Spenger's GM. Gets form-letter thank-you
for the ``feedback'' and five $10 coupons.
</P>
<P>
   Letter is received on a Thursday, certificates stamped for
expiration the next day. Lewis: ``I wonder if they pay the same
attention to the expiration dates of their fish?''
</P>
<P>
   -- Poor Oakland. It lands the NBA All-Star Game, but the
All-Star team is Warrior-free. Most of the All-Stars and limo'd
VIPs stay at S.F. hotels. Warriors owner Chris Cohan is booed by
the capacity crowd. Mock-up of Bay Bridge at the Arena is referred
to in a Chronicle photo as the Golden Gate Bridge. Official game
program lists the site of ``NBA All-Star 2000'' as ``Bay Area,
California.''
</P>
<P>
   -- By day it's the Hotel Pickwick, corner of Fifth and Mission.
At night, thanks to balky neon, it becomes HOT PICK. Hope they
don't lose their T.
</P>
<P>
   -- Another way we guys get cheated: The S.F. Maritime Museum
fought hard to obtain a four-foot model of the President Coolidge,
a liner that sank in WWII when the captain ran her into our own
minefield in the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dandy model, but there is no room for it in the Steamship
Room, so the museum people have the Coolidge on display in the
ladies head (nautical for rest room). Hey, women get the couches,
and now they get the good ship models, too?
</P>
<P>
   -- The kids at Kent Middle School in Marin had a great time at
their recent watch-the-lunar-eclipse party. But one parent asked
the principal: ``Why did you schedule it on a school night?''
</P>
<P>
   -- Driving Presidio Heights weekdays is tough enough, says Susan
MacTavish Best, what with the gardeners and contractors. ``Now I
have to dodge all the WebVan delivery trucks and their perky
deliverymen.''
</P>
<P>
   Perky?
</P>
<P>
   -- On Powell St. (where else?), Patrick Flynn was approached by
a young woman panhandler with a sign around her neck: ``Please
support the homely.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Muni salute: On the historic Market Street F Line trolley,
operator Ken Johnson not only calls out the stops (bonus point) but
gives brief descriptions of local attractions (bonus point), and
Monday he wished each passenger a happy Valentine's Day (five bonus
points).
</P>
<P>
   -- Job applicant at big downtown restaurant, under ``previous
experience,'' wrote: ``I worked on a mortuary ground crew.'' OK,
but what about salad experience?
</P>
<P>
   -- Paul Fingerote drove down to Los Angeles for the recent
Pavarotti concert, noticed that Luciano was dressed in formal
finery, of course, and ... black sneakers. That's right: Tenor
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hey Giants: Lisa Kluber says your new ballpark should have an
external message board, giving at least the score, ``So the hoi
polloi who can't score tickets won't feel so left out.''
</P>
<P>
   Also the poor saps who spend the first four innings stuck in
traffic, looking for parking.
</P>
<P>
   -- If George W. Bush ever debates, and gets a tough question,
Bob Lacey figures W will say, ``Read my father's lips.''
</P>
<P>
   I think he'll say, ``Moderator, I'm going to use a lifeline. I'd
like to ask the audience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
