<HEADER>
A8291 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DEBATE-GOP-SFCHRON &LR;      02-16 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-GOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AT SOUTH CAROLINA DEBATE, CHARGES OF DIRTY POLITICS FLY  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Reflecting an increasingly hostile battle for
the Republican presidential nomination, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
and Arizona Sen. John McCain each accused the other of engaging in
dirty politics Tuesday night during their final showdown before
this state's critical Saturday primary.
</P>
<P>
   The escalating fight over campaign tactics has begun to dominate
the final days of the South Carolina contest, which polls suggest
is still up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Consistent with statements made in campaign rallies throughout
this conservative state, the 90-minute forum included broad
agreement on policy matters ranging from support for the death
penalty, a national missile defense, banning abortions and moving
the Israeli capital to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But the nationally televised debate was marked by indignant
clashes over tactics as Bush, McCain and former State Department
official Alan Keyes tried to portray the other a perpetrator of
old-style politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can understand this, George, but that
really hurts,'' McCain said at the onset of the debate, alluding to
Bush's appearance beside an army colonel who had questioned
McCain's commitment to veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be ashamed,'' McCain said, citing his 17-year
record in Congress on veterans affairs. ``You should be ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Bush shot back with his own barb aimed at a
McCain commercial that suggested Bush twists words, like President
Clinton. McCain pulled the ads off the air last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, you can disagree with me on issues, John, but do not
question _ do not question _ my trustworthiness. And do not compare
me to Bill Clinton. That's about as low a blow as you can give in a
Republican primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, the only other Republican in the race, frequently
interrupted their sparring from his seat between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This debate is being broadcast in 202 countries,'' Keyes said
at one point. ``Is this really pointless squabbling what we want
them to see?''
</P>
<P>
   Without fundamental disagreements over issues, the closely
contested GOP campaign has turned into a bitter tit-for-tat over
who is the purveyor of politics as usual _ and who is the reform
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina residents can hardly turn on their radios without
hearing a Bush ad calling McCain ``just another Washington
insider,'' while McCain branded Bush last night as the candidate of
the Republican establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by CNN's Larry King, the debate took on added
significance coming just four days before South Carolina votes in a
contest that has become critical to each candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush held a enormous lead here for many months. But McCain's 18
percentage point victory in New Hampshire turned the race on its
head as the two candidates have twice traded places atop the polls.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Tuesday by CNN /USA Today/Gallup showed Bush
with a seven-point lead. The survey of 552 likely voters has a
margin of error of five points.
</P>
<P>
   Since his defeat in New Hampshire, Bush has adopted a more
aggressive style, playing off McCain's role as a political maverick
by calling himself a ``reformer with results.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of smiled my way through the early primaries and I got
defined,'' Bush said. ``I am not going to let that happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's assertiveness was on display in the debate as he
forcefully answered questions on foreign policy, saying that China
should be treated as a competitor, not a partner, and insisting
that the United States should use force only ``when it is in our
national strategic interest.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain took issue with the last point, telling Bush: ``It's not
that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when our principles and values are so
offended, we must take action,'' McCain said, citing the recent
genocide in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Most of their policy disagreements involved nuances. McCain said
he supports a permanent ban on Internet taxes; Bush supports a ban
until the issue is studied more. McCain supports changing the
Republican Party's platform to reflect his belief that abortions
ought to be legal in the case of rape, incest or when the mother's
life is at stake. Bush supports the exceptions to an abortion ban,
but does not feel the platform should be changed.
</P>
<P>
   The pair also fought over who best deserves the mantle of
political outsider _ McCain, a 17-year veteran of Congress, or
Bush, the son of the former president.
</P>
<P>
   ``My zip code is Austin, Texas,'' boasted Bush. ``Both John and
Alan have Washington zip codes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a point McCain refused to yield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fair to say that once again I have not won Miss
Congeniality in the U.S. Senate. The Republican Party has lost its
way,'' McCain said, referring to Bush's early status as the
front-runner. ``They have selected an establishment candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, who was excluded from a similar debate four years ago in
South Carolina _ and was led away in handcuffs while protesting his
exclusion the following week _ made an appeal to conservative South
Carolina voters to follow their heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here, because I articulate _ perhaps better than anyone
else in the country _ what's on the heart of Republicans and real
conservatives around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes did not shy away from making his own attacks, at one point
accusing McCain's campaign of boosting its crowd at a late-night
rally by providing beer to underage residents.
</P>
<P>
   In a curious exchange about race, King asked Bush to defend his
position to speak at South Carolina's Bob Jones University, which
bans interracial dating. When Bush said it displayed leadership to
talk to such groups even when he does not agree with all of their
beliefs, King asked why Bush would not meet with gay Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush responded that the Log Cabin Republican Club _ the group he
refused to meet _ had already endorsed McCain, something that was
not true when he refused their invitation for a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCain said that if he had been invited to speak at
Bob Jones University, he would have criticized their dating policy
as ``stupid, idiotic and incredibly cruel.''
</P>
<P>
   When King began to question Bush about how he would handle
abortion issue if one of his 17-year-old daughters got pregnant,
Bush quickly cut him off, telling him that while he was
anti-abortion, ``I'm not going to drag my daughter into this
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes took a similar tact with McCain, scolding him for saying
several weeks ago that if his daughter got pregnant, it would be a
family decision whether she got an abortion. The reference prompted
an indignant response from McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen enough killing in my lifetime _ a lot more than you
have,'' said McCain, who spent five and a half years in a North
Vietnamese Prisoner of War camp. ``I will not listen to your
lectures about how I should treat this. ... Do not, please, bring
my daughter into this.''
</P>
<P>
   Between barbs, McCain and Bush each praised the other as being a
``good man.''
</P>
<P>
   And all three candidates found common ground in their criticism
of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do is to nominate someone to end the
Clinton era,'' Bush said at the conclusion of the debate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
