u a BC-NY-NUKE-SHUTDOWN-1STL     02-16 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NUKE-SHUTDOWN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIATION LEAK PROMPTS SHUTDOWN OF N.Y. NUCLEAR REACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite portions of 3rd, 4th and 9th grafs for
precision.)  
(mk) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN with MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A leak in a steam generator at the Indian Point 2 nuclear
reactor in Westchester County, N.Y., released a small amount of
radiation from the plant Tuesday night, forcing officials to shut
it down and declare an alert.
</P>
<P>
   The plant's owner, Consolidated Edison, stressed that the leak
was what it called ``momentary'' and that there was no danger to
residents of the surrounding area or to employees of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   But the declaration of the alert _ the second level of four
categories of nuclear emergency _ was the first issued by Con
Edison since the Indian Point 2 plant opened in 1974. Con Ed
officials said Tuesday night that they did not know what caused the
leak.
</P>
<P>
   The leak in the 1,000-megawatt plant, in Buchanan, about 35
miles north of New York City, occurred at about 7:30 p.m., said
Michael Spall, a Con Ed spokesman. It allowed hot, radioactive
water, which is supposed to be kept isolated, to mix with clean
water that is boiled into steam. The steam then flows out of the
reactor's containment dome into a turbine that spins to generate
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The leak of radioactive gas into the air occurred because the
plant has a system for ejecting air from the steam loop in order to
limit corrosion, Spall said. He added, however, that ``several
seconds later'' the system diverted the air back to the containment
dome, limiting the amount of radioactive gas released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any releases would have posed no threat to the safety of plant
personnel or the general public,'' he added. ``While this is a
serious event, it is not one that threatens public health and
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   There are four categories of nuclear event: a notification, an
alert, a site area emergency, and a general emergency, which is
what occurred at Three Mile Island in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Con Ed quickly sent monitoring teams to the plant's
perimeter, but they found radiation to be normal, Spall said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the plant produces about one-seventh of the power used
by Con Ed's 3 million customers, officials said there was no power
shortage, nor would there be one because other plants in the region
would supply the power.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Michalski, a spokesman for the New York State Emergency
Management Office, said that Con Edison followed all the proper
safety procedures, and alerted the state agency's office in 15
minutes. He added that the leak ``occurred within the generating
structure, but they shut off the valve so none of that steam left
the facility.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission received a report from Con
Edison at 8:07 p.m., within the one-hour reporting time limit.
Spall said the leak was in a steam generator, which is a heat
exchanger inside the containment dome. The leak opened a path for
mildly radioactive water to flow out of containment and into the
turbine hall, from which ``a small amount'' was released to the
environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Point's steam generators, four of them for each reactor,
are towering metal vessels, filled with thin-walled metal tubes, in
the shape of an upside-down U. The tubes are filled with water that
flows through the nuclear core to the steam generators and then
back to the core, carrying heat away from the reactor so it can be
used to make electricity. This water gradually picks up radioactive
contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the tubes there is clean, nonradioactive water, which is
pumped in and boils. The steam flows out through giant pipes,
through the heavy concrete and steel wall of the containment dome
to the turbine hall, which is used to spin a turbine and make
electricity. This nonradioactive steam is then run through a big
metal cooling box called a condenser, where it is turned back into
water. The condenser is kept cool with water from the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   The alert was the first in the plant's operating history, said
Spall. Indian Point 2 opened in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight, Spall said that operators had shut off the flow of
steam from the steam generator, and shut off the flow of water that
is boiled into steam. And they had reduced pressure in the reactor
to 1,000 pounds per square inch, he said. Normal operating pressure
is above 2,000 pounds per square inch. But bringing the reactor to
cold shutdown _ when it is cool enough to open up without the
cooling water boiling away _ was still several hours away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other reactors of similar design, called pressurized water
reactors, have had steam generator problems.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Point 3, which is owned by the New York Power Authority,
had corrosion and cracking problems with its steam generators, and
replaced them. But Con Edison said it did not need to, perhaps
because it paid closer attention to water chemistry, to limit
corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   Rochester Gas &AMP; Electric's Robert E. Ginna reactor suffered a
steam generator tube rupture in January 1982. Many plants have been
closed for months by steam generator tube problems.
</P>
<P>
   With the economic value of nuclear plants much diminished by
changes in technology and in utility rules, it was not clear
whether it would pay to replace the steam generators, if that were
to become necessary. Like an old car that needed a new
transmission, a severe steam generator problem could lead to
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison said earlier this month that it would offer the
reactor for sale this year.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Point 2 has had a spotty history in recent years. In
1994, the plant broke the world record for longest continuous
operation _ 19 months _ of a light-water reactor, the kind used in
the United States and most of the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But in December 1996, a minor chemical spill forced the plant to
shut down. In 1998, the plant was closed again, this time for
several months, because of safety concerns. And last September, the
plant was temporarily shut down after a series of electrical
problems that caused the system to misread temperature and pressure
readings and throw the plant into shutdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
