<SLUG> BC-GLF-BOGIE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGEY'S TREE COULD CAUSE PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Bogey's Tree,'' a stately old sycamore that
predates Riviera Country Country Club, is the sentinel of the 12th
green. According to legend, the tree is named after Humphrey
Bogart, who hung out in the shade of its canopy sipping from a
Thermos filled with Jim Beam during Los Angeles Opens past.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, it's been a benign moniker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bogey's Tree'' has turned few away as the surgeons of the PGA
Tour routinely carved the 12th hole to pieces, wielding a 3-wood
like a scalpel and short iron to suture things up.
</P>
<P>
   Noted architect George C. Thomas, who designed Riviera, would
not be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tree may finally live up to its nickname during the 2000
edition of the Nissan Open, which will be played this week.
</P>
<P>
   Riviera is fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   Come Sunday, a few competitors may be thinking about attacking
number 12 with a chain saw.
</P>
<P>
   As part of some not-so-subtle tweaking of Riviera, a new tee box
was built, extending the par-4 hole to 479 yards from the tips.
This week the pros will play it at 460 yards, 50 more than they did
last year.
</P>
<P>
   And now, ``Bogey's Tree'' is back in play.
</P>
<P>
   With approach shots from farther back in the fairway, the small
green will look even smaller and the deep bunker in front more
daunting. And the longer walk will give players more time to ogle
Mel Brooks' stunning white estate along the left side of the
fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Yoshitake, Riviera's head professional, said that playing
the hole to its full length might have been too much to thrust on
the PGA this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, most of the pros hit a 3-wood and a 9-iron. Now most
will hit driver and have something like a 6-iron or 7-iron, maybe
even a 5-iron,'' he said. ``It's now a tough target to hit. It's
changed the hole completely.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, will the scores. Yoshitake thinks they will be going
up.
</P>
<P>
   Driving accuracy will be rewarded, since Riviera's notorious
gnarly rough is going to be up a bit this year. Drives into the
long grass most often will arrive at the green sans spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem now is hitting the fairway on that hole,'' said
Yoshitake.
</P>
<P>
   This is just one of several not-so-subtle changes at the
venerable old course.
</P>
<P>
   Number nine, a beautiful hole with a green framed by the
majestic clubhouse sitting high on the hill, will also play
tougher.
</P>
<P>
   It has been lengthened by 38 yards, to 458 yards, which does not
sound like much in this age of titanium.
</P>
<P>
   But the added distance brings a yawning fairway bunker back into
play.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshitake says a drive must stay airborne 290 yards to carry the
bunker and leave a short iron into the green. In tournaments past,
the players gave this bunker little respect since it could be
carried with a drive of 255 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the (hole) will now play as it was meant to play. The
pros can attempt to carry it, but it will take a good poke,''
Yoshitake said. ``Basically the pros are faced with the same hazard
that the members have to play every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Laying up short of the bunker will leave a shot of about 200
yards to the green.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes, under the direction of the Tom Fazio Group, are
also planned.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation is being done out of respect for Thomas, not out
of spite for the skills of today's athletes. ``Basically, the
intent is to return the course back to the original George Thomas
design and the provide the shot values that he wanted for the pros.
It's a classic. There is nothing fancy about it. It's a real simple
design, it's easy to walk and it changes every day with the wind
patterns,'' Yoshitake said.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Ernie Els is not put off by Riviera's new
look. And he acknowledges that yes, technology has rendered some
classic golf courses obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riviera is one of the classic golf courses around the globe.
Ben Hogan made it famous. It's highly regarded by both the pros and
the public. It's a great course,'' Els said. ``The (classic)
courses do play a little easier. In the old days, they used
persimmon drivers, which went as far as we hit 3-woods today.''
</P>
<P>
   So this week there just might be trouble lurking in the shade of
``Bogey's Tree.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 0206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
