<HEADER>
A8296 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CPT-E-SPORTS-TEX     02-16 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-E-SPORTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS FAN RETALIATES OVER SABRES' CRIES OF FOUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every action creates a reaction, especially in the bitter Dallas
Stars-Buffalo Sabres rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   While it has taken nearly eight months, a Stars fan finally has
fired a shot in defense against a bitter Sabres fan who created
Nogoal.com to openly complain about Dallas' game-winning goal in
Game 6 of the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   It's called Starsrule.com.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Key of Lone Oak, Texas, recently launched Starsrule.com as
a counterstrike to Nogoal.com, a site created by Sabres fan Jeff
Spring two days after the Stars' controversial triple-overtime
victory in June.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than be repulsed by Nogoal.com's shots at the Stars and
the NHL, Key said he was inspired. But Key didn't want
Starsrule.com to be obsessed with the controversial goal like
Nogoal.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to change gears and not focus on the poor
sportsmanship of the Buffalo fans, but to focus on extolling the
greatness of the Dallas Stars,'' Key said.
</P>
<P>
   Starsrule.com isn't as comprehensive as Nogoal.com _ in fact,
other Stars fans sites offer a better tribute to the team _ but
it's much more visual with an animated introduction that requires a
browser plug-in. And in honor of the Stanley Cup's reported dip
into a pool at the hands of the Stars' Guy Carbonneau, Key also has
a Javascript application that shows what the trophy looks like
underwater.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Starsrule.com is more flash than substance. But by
summer, Key plans a player database, a message forum and updates on
the new American Airlines Center.
</P>
<P>
   Spring, who works at a Buffalo, N.Y., bookstore selling Sabres
merchandise, has pulled together an impressive site with bitterness
spewing from nearly every feature.
</P>
<P>
   On his site, Spring has rounded up NHL rule points, articles
about the controversy, Nogoal.com merchandise and message boards.
His merchandise even drew a threatening letter from the NHL about
copyright infringement for use of the image of the Stanley Cup and
team logos of the finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Spring said the NHL figured that the threat would make him pull
his site.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you're committed to something like this, you don't
quit until you get what you want,'' Spring told the ``Boston
Globe.'' ``And what we want is an apology'' from the league.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTONA COVERAGE: NASCAR Online (www.nascar.com) is letting
Daytona 500 fans keep an eye on the pit area with its Garage Cam
this week. A popup window provides constantly updated images on the
site. NASCAR's official site also will include updates and image
galleries throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Online also has scheduled chat sessions with drivers
through the week. Geoffrey Bodine is scheduled to chat at 3:30 p.m.
Tuesday and Randy LaJoie an hour later. Dale Jarrett chats at 5
p.m. Wednesday and Bobby Labonte chats at 3:30 p.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona fans can also access the Daytona International
Speedway's official site (www.daytonaintlspeedway.com) for
merchandise and souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   GOODWILL CHAT: The inaugural Winter Goodwill Games in Lake
Placid, N.Y., features a week full of online chat sessions on
CNNSI.com. Scheduled participants include world champion skier
Jimmy Shea at 3 p.m. Thursday and Goodwill Games president Mike
Plant at 3 p.m. Monday. The games, featuring Olympic and world
champions in 11 winter sports, are scheduled to run today through
Sunday.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
