<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYTON SCORES CAREER-HIGH 41 AS SONICS ROUT WIZARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ About the only time Gary Payton seemed to show any
emotion Tuesday night was when a 3-pointer rolled around the rim
and out in the third quarter. It was a rare moment when one of
Payton's shots did not fall.
</P>
<P>
   So he stopped, then glared at the basket as if it had violated
him.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence was a minor blip on a night the Sonics point guard
exhibited the most explosive scoring performance of his career. He
scored a career-high 41 points in the Sonics' 114-85 rout of the
Washington Wizards at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   But mention to Payton that he is unquestionably playing his best
basketball in 10 NBA seasons, and he seems numb to the fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just playing basketball. It's just something that
happened,'' Payton said, re-emphasizing what has become a patented
line despite scoring, rebounding and assist averages that are
personal bests.
</P>
<P>
   This is clearly a much different, more dominating Payton.
</P>
<P>
   It took just 30 minutes for Payton to make 14 of his 21 shots.
It didn't even take that long for the Sonics to dispatch the
hapless Wizards. The Sonics took an 8-0 lead, and Payton scored 11
of the team's first 19 points just five minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics led by 17 at that point, and demoralized the Wizards
with strong defense and 3-point shooting. Washington shot 36.6
percent from the field and turned the ball over 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who made 7 of 12 3-pointers, did not play in the fourth
quarter. That's because the Sonics built a 27-point first-half
advantage and later led by 34 points behind Payton's unmatched
energy.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4 guard scored 29 points by halftime and played at
warp speed, making the Wizards look lost in slow motion.
</P>
<P>
   So laughable was the rout that Brent Barry took a sip of a
woman's drink after chasing a ball out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   So dangerous was Payton that he probably could have made baskets
from the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just in a rhythm,'' Payton said, showing no sign of
being tired from participating in All-Star weekend. ``You just keep
shooting the ball and if it keeps going in, it goes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton had scored 30 or more points eight times this season. His
previous career-high was 38 points, March 24, 1996, at Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after tying his previous career high, Payton tossed in a
3-pointer over Washington's Chris Whitney to set the new scoring
mark with 1:42 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think a guy that's been as good as he's been for so
long would have had a game or two along the way,'' Sonics coach
Paul Westphal said of Payton eclipsing 40 points. ``I think he'll
have more.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton could have scored more than 50 points had he remained in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's disrespectful to the other team,'' Payton said. ``Why
should I be in the game when we're up 30 points? I didn't want to
go through all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   After shooting 1-for-8 for the Western Conference in the
All-Star Game last weekend, Payton intended to get his team off to
a good start after the break.
</P>
<P>
   Once Payton made his first five shots, four of which were
3-pointers, his teammates picked up the groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't say it but he felt he had a little something to prove
by not starting in the All-Star Game,'' center Horace Grant said.
``He's playing with that attitude and I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   An impressive start to the second half of the regular season
came at the expense of a wayward Wizards team. Washington suffered
its fourth consecutive loss and 12th in a row on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal was afforded the rare opportunity to give his starters
extended rest.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who suffered from the flu, benefited the most, playing
just 15 minutes. Greg Foster started the second half in place of
Grant and the Sonics didn't miss a beat.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Payton was still on the court.
</P>
<P>
   TIP-INS: Grant's twin brother Harvey was in attendance. Harvey
has yet to be picked up by an NBA team after being cut by the
Orlando Magic. ... Barry, who injured his left knee in the Feb. 9
game against Dallas, played 28 minutes with it heavily bandaged.
... Because the Sonics scored at least 110 points, fans were
eligible to receive free Taco Bell chalupas.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
