<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8298 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKC-CRAWFORD-SPI &LR;      02-16 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CRAWFORD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY OWNED BY CRAWFORD'S BENEFACTOR HAS A SPORTS ARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS and TED MILLER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle business executive Barry Henthorn is listed as
operating ``a sports management service'' as part of his
telecommunications business, according to recent documents filed
with Dun &AMP; Bradstreet, a Wall Street information service company.
</P>
<P>
   But Henthorn said Tuesday the sports management component of his
business refers only to the company's work with hydroplane racing
and is not an attempt to establish a sports agency to promote
University of Michigan basketball player Jamal Crawford or any
other athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn, 33, is being investigated by the NCAA and the
university for his relationship with Crawford, a former Rainier
Beach High School star. Henthorn contends his only venture into
sports was a hydroplane boat sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Henthorn said, his company managed a boat and its
driver, ``Freeway'' Jimmy Ablott.
</P>
<P>
   ``It no longer falls under our corporate umbrella,'' Henthorn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Innovative Technologies' Internet site claims its director
of operations ``implemented ICT's 1999 national marketing/sales
tour integrating Innovative Cellular's National Hydroplane Race
Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   The P-I could not confirm any tour sponsorship, but Henthorn's
name does show up on Ablott's boat as a sponsor. The boat raced in
about 12 events last year. Ablott could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Dun &AMP; Bradstreet listing for Henthorn's Innovative
Communications Technologies Inc. is dated Feb. 10, 2000. It also
lists his company as operating an unproduced TV game show called
``Name that Lick.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Henthorn's family members, NFL player Eric
Metcalf is listed among ICT investors. Metcalf, who grew up in
Seattle and played for the Carolina Panthers last season, is listed
as owning 12.5 percent of the capital stock in the company, but
Metcalf's agent said his client is only an investor and does not
want to comment about the association with Henthorn.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures about Henthorn's business connections could be
vital to the ongoing investigation of Crawford if they show
Henthorn was acting as more than a quasi-guardian for the player.
Crawford was suspended for six games _ five by the NCAA, one by
Michigan _ and ordered by the NCAA to repay approximately $15,000
to Henthorn after the university raised questions about a 1988
Mercedes Crawford tried to register on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Peterson, spokeswoman for Michigan, would not comment
directly about the information in the Dun &AMP; Bradstreet documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reviewed many new pieces of information over the past
few days, and we are investigating them all,'' Peterson said.
``We're just not commenting on each new piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's NCAA suspension expires Feb. 24. The university
originally planned to appeal the penalty until the
Post-Intelligencer last week revealed that Henthorn provided
additional money, jewelry and another car to Crawford, who was
still in high school at the time. The disclosures came after the
P-I reported on a lawsuit filed by Henthorn's former administrative
assistant, who claimed she was coerced into co-signing on three
loans totaling $10,097 for Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn also set up a non-profit foundation, known as the
Academic Assistance Foundation, apparently to provide additional
benefits to Crawford. Neither Henthorn's foundation nor the
existence of the other loans were part of the initial university or
NCAA investigation of Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Henthorn denied he had anything to do with a
letter Crawford belatedly sent to the NBA to make himself available
for last summer's NBA draft. The letter was received too late and
discarded, and Crawford reversed his decision and stuck with his
commitment to attend Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was aware of that, but I didn't encourage it,'' Henthorn
said of the letter. ``I didn't think it was a good idea then, and I
don't think it's a good idea this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford earlier this week was quoted in the Ann Arbor (Mich.)
News as denying a broadcast report that he was turning pro after
his freshman season at Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be back next year. It's not even a question,'' Crawford
told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn said Tuesday he has talked with the NCAA as part of the
expanded investigation. Although he wouldn't comment on his
interview with the agency, he did say he was pleased with how it
went.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely positive I will be vindicated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dun &AMP; Bradstreet report states that Innovative
Communications Technologies, which started in 1994, had sales of
$1.2 million and a worth of $2.37 million as of December 1997. It
employs 35 people, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   While the description of ICT's operation had been updated as of
last week, the financial data has not been updated since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn said he was unsure why that hasn't happened, noting it
doesn't fall under his range of duties. A spokeswoman for Dun &AMP;
Bradstreet said that because the company is privately held, it is
not obligated to provide financial information.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ted Miller can be reached at 206-448-8017
</P>
<P>
   or tedmiller &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Angelo Bruscas can be reached at 206-448-8010
</P>
<P>
   or angelobruscas &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
