<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: Truth about nuggets hard to swallow
</P>
<P>
   By John Kelsoc. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Is anybody really surprised that chicken nuggets
are disgusting? If chicken nuggets weren't disgusting, they'd name
them after the part of the chicken that they come from, instead of
labeling them ``nuggets.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal food inspectors at two Alabama chicken processing plants
say that schoolchildren in 31 states have been fed chicken nuggets
made out of chickens with sores and such.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know why the chicken crossed the road? So he could
develop sores and become a chicken nugget.
</P>
<P>
   This is why to find chicken nuggets it helps to dine at a
restaurant that has the word ``Eats'' displayed on the side of the
building. I'm sure you've noticed that chicken nuggets generally
aren't mentioned on the chalkboard at establishments such as, say,
Jean-Pierre's Upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that these federal inspectors say that even
though some of the chickens being turned into nuggets are diseased,
the chicken nuggets won't hurt you, because people don't pick up
chicken diseases. So much for the heartbreak of pluckitis.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the real reason these chicken nuggets won't hurt you
is that they are generally breaded and cooked in hot fat.
</P>
<P>
   If you bread a possum and cook it long enough in hot fat, it
won't hurt you, either. And if you don't believe me, ask somebody
from Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, it wouldn't take a federal investigation to figure
out that a chicken nugget is a horrid little food item because,
when you look at a chicken, you can't find a nugget anywhere on it.
</P>
<P>
   If you find a nugget on a chicken, my suggestion would be to eat
around the nugget and enjoy the rest of the chicken. Save the
nugget and mail it to Ripley's Believe It -- r Not.
</P>
<P>
   The chicken nugget, like the steak finger, is one of those menu
choices that makes you suspicious because the name doesn't say what
part of the animal it comes from. Steak fingers. How is this
possible? Find me a cow with knuckles, and I'll start believing in
steak fingers.
</P>
<P>
   But the real question is this: Are these standard chicken
nuggets our schoolchildren have been served, or are they free-range
chicken nuggets?
</P>
<P>
   The other thing that gets me about this investigation is that it
has led me to learn about a new food group I was blissfully unaware
of _ binder.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. One of the federal food inspectors interviewed
about the tainted chicken nuggets said the skin of the chicken that
has sores on it is mixed with the rest of the meat, where it serves
as ``binder.''
</P>
<P>
   So that means that the three basic food groups are now fat,
breading and binder?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not paying attention to a food pyramid that mentions
``binder.''
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't eat in a restaurant that has ``binder'' on the menu.
``My name is Jason, and I will be your waiter this evening. Would
you like a little binder on your salad?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``You kids aren't leaving this table until you've finished
your binder.''
</P>
<P>
   What is binder? What is the recommended federal daily
requirement of binder? If you don't eat enough binder, does it mean
that your bellybutton comes unscrewed and your stomach falls off?
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8450 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN17-COX     02-16 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Polly, not a celebrity, but loved by all
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Lamantia means family. Polly Lamantia's life was
measured in small moments, small traditions: Sunday afternoon
socials with her close-knit brood of seven children. Annual get
togethers in Chicago with her six sisters. Card games with the
grandkids.
</P>
<P>
   Her life and death were hardly dramatic, hardly the stuff of
headlines. She appeared in the Dayton Daily News only once in
recent years, when I wrote about the family's celebration of the
25th ``birthday'' of their Five Oaks home in 1996. What sold her on
the home, she told me then, was that it would be ``an ideal place
to hide Easter baskets.'' Polly understood the symbolism of such
rituals, the way they reinforce family.
</P>
<P>
   Polly, who died last month at 69, was a not very newsworthy
citizen but her funeral packed 'em like dignitaries. ``It was the
love of family carried over into the love of neighbors, of
community, of church,'' explains her daughter, Debbie Smith of
Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years, Dick Lamantia says, his wife, Polly, ``operated on
half a heart.'' You wouldn't have known it, though, if you visited
her rambling, Swiss-chalet style home in Five Oaks. Polly was the
mother in the neighborhood all the other kids called ``Mom.'' She
was the central nervous system of one of those large Catholic
broods where the kids never quite seem to leave home, even when
they have their own children and mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Even in her last year, ``she would make it to the Sunday social
if she had to crawl there,'' Debbie recalls. If she couldn't
preside over a family get-together, Polly orchestrated them. She
informed her son, Mark Lamantia of Kettering, that he would be
hosting the family Super Bowl party. Polly died of heart disease
Jan. 27, three days before the game, but Mark knew his mother
wouldn't have considered that any kind of excuse to call off the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a woman who has her priorities straight. A
meticulous housekeeper, Polly retired from housekeeping and cooking
during her last year, except, of course, when the parish priest at
Corpus Christi Church came over for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if she were saving her heartbeats for the things
that are really important, and cooking and cleaning weren't that
important to her any more,'' Debbie says.
</P>
<P>
   Family was important, and she reflected on the meaning of family
in a series of beautifully written essays. In October, only a few
months before her death , Polly wrote about getting together every
year with her sisters, also known as ``the Walsh girls'' or the
Seven Sisters Sorority: ``Where would we have gone instead? Who
would have enriched us more? Where could six married sisters and a
seventh sister, a Franciscan nun, have an opportunity to spend five
days away from home, children, husbands and phones?''
</P>
<P>
   Polly has nurtured that same spirit in her own children, just as
her mother instilled in her. ``Her mother raised those kids to the
highest standard in spite of being poverty-ridden and having a
husband who was a recovering alcoholic,'' says Dick Lamantia. ``And
Polly? She never had an alcoholic father. She never grew up in the
Depression. She had an enchanted childhood. And I bet you a dollar
to a doughnut if you went back to the great-grandmother, she would
be the same kind of woman. It's a legacy that's in their bones.''
</P>
<P>
   And now it's in the bones of her children and grandchildren, who
will continue the traditions with which she so seamlessly bound
them together . ``I told Mom I don't know how many times that our
Sunday socials will continue long into this millennium,'' Debbie
says.
</P>
<P>
   She was saving her heartbeats for the things that are really
important, Debbie said. And hers is a legacy that will be measured
not in headlines or biographies, but in the lifeblood of family, in
the heartbeats of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
