<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8451 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN17-COX     02-16 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Possible candidate would bring new meaning to
'White' House
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The Reform Party is about to go from weird to
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Gov. Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura and Donald ``The Ego''
Trump have bailed out of Ross Perot's Reform Party, the door now is
open for Pat ``The Foreigners Are Coming'' Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan is to America what Joerg Haider is to Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Austrians have a right to vote for for an
immigrant-bashing politician who praised Adolph Hitler's ``sound
employment policy,'' Americans have a right to vote for an
immigrant-bashing politician who supported Nazis and belittled
Holocaust reports.
</P>
<P>
   After Haider's Freedom Party won second place in Austria's
October parliamentary elections based on anti-immigrant and ethnic
purity appeals, Haider was included in a new government.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and European nations quite properly let the
Austrian government know that they will not again sit idly by while
a demagogue rallies support for an ethnic contagion that threatens
the stability of nations.
</P>
<P>
   While most Austrians do not support Haider's message, not enough
spoke up in time to prevent the son of a Nazi official from
assuming power.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps due to his father's influence, Haider once praised
Waffen SS officers as ``decent people with character who stuck to
their belief through the strongest headwinds.''
</P>
<P>
   Haider is a well-spoken, charismatic man who has apologized for
any of his statements that may have been misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian's don't like being threatened with diplomatic sanctions
because 27 percent of their voters supported Haider's Freedom
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the democratic process at work,'' Austrians say. They ask
how Americans would like it if the world threatened them with
sanctions because U.S. voters supported a politician with a history
of attacking the ethnic impurity of some of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   That's a question Americans need to consider if Buchanan is
chosen to run for president by the shattered remnants of Perot's
Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   If Buchanan isn't a racist, fascist, anti-Semitic, pro-Nazi,
nativist, isolationist bigot, then he sure appeals to people who
possess those traits.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan says his father, William Baldwin Buchanan, was a great
influence on him. The elder Buchanan was a dedicated supporter of
the America First Committee, a deplorable organization that
attempted to convert Americans to its anti-Semitic, pro-Nazi,
nativist and isolationist views.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan the son has called his previous political campaigns
America First, as has former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke, whose
political campaigns share many of Buchanan's positions.
</P>
<P>
   Like Haider, Buchanan says his statements have been
misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   Also like Haider, Buchanan has praised Hitler. He once described
Hitler as ``an individual of great courage ... extraordinary
gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has expressed admiration for Spain's fascist dictator
Francisco Franco, who happened to be a favorite of the elder
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The man who wants to be America's president admired the white
supremacist ``Boer Republic'' so much that he once applied to be
ambassador to South Africa's racist government.
</P>
<P>
   Even Austria's Haider has never gone so far as to call for
putting armed troops along its borders to guard against illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan wants a bayonet curtain along America's southern border
but has invited white Canadians, who share his European heritage,
to join the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Good Austrians failed to speak out against Hitler and Haider
before they gained power. Americans should not make the same
mistake with Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
