<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8452 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-COMFORTFOOD-BOOKS17-C     02-16 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMFORTFOOD-BOOKS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Comfort foods warm the body and soul
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It takes only a slight dip in the
temperature to send us searching for comfort foods: hot casseroles,
pot pies and roasts with vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Three new cookbooks address this style of cooking and can help
you produce something warm and steamy from the oven.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Book of Casseroles'' by Maryana Vollstedt (Chronicle
Books, $19.95), provides 250 recipes, from the ultimate tuna-noodle
casserole to contemporary enchilada mixtures. There are a fair
number of casseroles influenced by Mexican and Latin flavors, and
old favorites such as lasagna (usually not considered a traditional
casserole, but think about it) and macaroni and cheese. Also
included are stews, chili and the mom-inspired chicken with rice
and vegetables. Any good cook could mix and match with Vollstedt's
recipes and come up with her own combinations to suit available
ingredients and the family's tastes.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Clay Pot Cooking'' by Elsa Petersen-Schepelern (Time-Life
Books, $15.95), a basic chapter on using clay pots as cookware
defines the many clay pot types used around the world: tians,
tandoors, tagines, etc. The recipes for them also follow an
international route: yellow pea soup from Sweden; poule au pot, a
French classic; Mediterranean garlic lamb shanks with rosemary and
lentils; and Chinese red-cooked pork. The recipes are filled with
flavors, and they can be adapted to stainless steel or iron
cookware. ``Pot Pies'' by Diane Phillips (Doubleday, $24.95) is
divided into four main chapters_ turkey and chicken, meat, seafood
and vegetables. The diversity of flavor and ingredients is wide,
though a slight Mediterranean influence comes through. Two recipes
for stock will be helpful, but the pies don't require them every
time. The crust recipes are nontraditional and give life to old
favorites. They include cheese, pastry crust, noodles, pancakes,
focaccia and a unique topping called a rouille (red pepper pesto,
of sorts). Again, this book lends itself to variation and
substitutions at will and to taste, so while the price for a
single-subject cookbook seems high, the inspiration it provides
makes up for it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
