<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-SECURITY     02-16 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON SEEKS WAYS TO PROTECT THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;     By MARK HELM and ERIC ROSENBERG   
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Searching for ways to combat Internet attacks,
President Clinton turned Tuesday to America's high-tech leaders,
law enforcement officials and a hacker named Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   Although he called last week's successful assaults on several
popular Web sites ``a wake-up call'' to the country, Clinton
downplayed the damage done to Internet commerce and security.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not an electronic Pearl Harbor,'' he said at a
meeting in the White House Cabinet Room with 29 industry
representatives as well as national security experts and Attorney
General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should leave here with this vast sense of
insecurity,'' Clinton said. ``We ought to leave here with a sense
of confidence that this is a challenge that was entirely
predictable. It's part of the price of the success of the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial idea of the session was to address the problem of
terrorists using cyberspace. But Clinton said a blizzard of
assaults last week that disabled some of the nation's most popular
Web sites _ among them CNN.com, eBay, Yahoo!, Amazon.com and ETrade
_ convinced him that the government needs to focus on protecting
the Internet itself.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, he promised to provide $9 million in
``start-up money'' for a high-tech security institute to study ways
to improve Internet security. But the president stressed that
security on the Internet should be improved without jeopardizing
the entrepreneurial potential of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have to keep cyberspace open and free,'' Clinton
said. ``At the same time, computer networks (must be) more secure
and resilient and we have to do more to protect privacy and civil
liberties.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators think the cyber attacks against the Web
sites were perpetrated by one or more assailants who hacked into
computer systems including those at Stanford University and on at
least two campuses in the University of California system. The
assailants then directed those large, powerful systems to flood the
Web sites with data, causing them to fail for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Companies represented in Tuesday's meeting included America
Online, Yahoo!, 3Com, Cisco Systems, Sun Microsystems, MCI
Worldcom, IBM, AT&AMP;T, Hewlett Packard, Intel and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Another participant was Mudge, nickname for a member of a
``think tank'' of hackers who are security consultants operating
under the name Stake. Mudge refused to give his name, but the White
House released a list of participants that included an Stake
representative named Peiter Zatko of Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here because I know how the people who broke into the
those Web sites think,'' said the long-haired Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   The president emphasized that private industry should lead the
way in solving the Internet security problem with the government
playing only a ``minimal role,'' such as coordinating industry
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The industry security representatives agreed, saying they did
not want a large government presence on the Internet. Instead, they
pledged to share information ``regarding cyber attacks,
vulnerabilities, counter-measures and security practices'' on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has a lot to do, certainly by example and
education, but the private sector has to drive the security of the
Internet,'' said Charles Wang, chief executive of Computer
Associates International, a business software firm in Islandia,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge said, ``Every business on the Internet gets hurt when a
Web site is broken into because it makes people afraid of using the
Internet so it's in the interest of businesses to help each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most participants said the attacks were not
catastrophic, Thomas Noonan, CEO of the Atlanta-based Internet
Security Systems, said they signaled that ``an arms race'' was
under way, pitting the government and computer industry against
cyber-hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Noonan said he told Clinton in the closed-door meeting that it
is next to impossible to stop a cyber terrorist from launching an
attack. ``But what we can do is make sure our systems are not
vulnerable, and we can make sure that our networks are capable of
detecting and responding to any attacks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such security capability, which would ensure that U.S.
e-commerce can run smoothly and fend off attacks, will cost up to
$50 billion, Noonan said. ``We have built our new economy on a
vulnerable infrastructure. You'd never build a skyscraper on a
foundation full of holes. But that's just what we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Noonan said the group advised the president, ``For God's sake,
lead by example. The government's computers are some of the most
vulnerable out there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a computer believed to have been used in last week's
attacks was seized by federal agents, according to Hillsboro, Ore.,
Police Sgt. Allen Zaugg, head of a group of officers trained for
high-tech cases. The FBI is now analyzing that computer, which was
seized within the last two days from a home business in the
Portland, Ore., area, a federal official in Washington said,
requesting anonymity. The computer's owner apparently was not aware
the computer was used as part of the attacks, the official said.
The FBI also was seeking to interview several hackers known by
their Internet screen names, including one who calls himself
``mafiaboy'' and another who calls himself ``coolio,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm and Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or
at the e-mail addresses markhearstdc.com and erichearstdc.com,
respectively.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-15-00 1911EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
