 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Take it from an old hacker: Recent fears are overblown
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the beginning of the computer age, there were
hackers. The word had a slightly different meaning back then. A
hacker was a computer hobbyist who didn't love computers because
they were useful, instead he loved them because they were
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of being a hacker was not, in those days, breaking
into computers and computer networks _ but don't let anyone kid
you, there was plenty of that going on.
</P>
<P>
   I know because I was a hacker. I wasn't a genius hacker; there
was no danger of my getting rich because of my computer knowledge.
I wasn't smart enough. Nor was there much danger that I'd someday
be the anti-hero of a movie because of my skill at breaking into
computer networks. When it came to skill and to breaking into
networks, I was no more than fair-to-middling.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe that's enough to make it easier to talk to you about
what's going on these days. It's difficult to pick up a newspaper
without finding a banner headline talking about hackers bringing
some Web site to its knees.
</P>
<P>
   When I talk to my friends, I keep hearing dark fears that
there's some sort of sophisticated international conspiracy
designed to bring the Internet down. In fact, a lot of what I hear
reminds me of the hysteria Y2K stirred. It was going to be the end
of the world as we know it, and it turned out to be less potent
than an old-fashioned ice storm.
</P>
<P>
   First, you need to know that in some ways _ despite the growth
of sophistication of security on the Net and the World Wide Web _
that hacking is easier than ever. Nowadays, a beginning hacker
doesn't have to write the computer code for a hacking program.
Instead, you can download these programs from the Web _ a nice
piece of irony in itself, since Web sites have been the primary
target. So while there are sophisticated hackers out there, the
majority are cookbook hackers, following directions found on Web
sites, using tools downloaded from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Second, keep in mind that the recent attacks on Yahoo, eBay and
CNN.com (by the time you read this there may be more _ I'll explain
why before I'm done) were denial-of-service attacks. In no case did
the hacker get secret information or break in and steal passwords
or personal data.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they jammed up the system by trying to connect to it
from a variety of servers (computers connected to the Net). It's
really no different from a prankster tying up your phone line by
redialing it over and over. I'm not saying that hackers are
incapable of breaking into networks and performing some of the
feats that movies are written about. But that kind of hacking is
more difficult and requires entirely different skills.
</P>
<P>
   Third, despite what the experts say, I'm not sure that there is
a big and well-organized conspiracy here. Instead, that one hacking
exploit, say, bringing Yahoo to its knees, brings out the ``me,
too'' hackers who want to prove that they can do it, too.
</P>
<P>
   While there are big hacker organizations _ you can find many on
the Web by doing a search _ historically the best hackers, and the
best criminals in general, have worked alone and are as shy as a
15-year-old on a first date. These vandals want publicity; the
people you should fear most do not. But since this ``me, too''
mentality is a fact of life, you probably will see more incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, the smartest computer security experts I know are
getting rich because they are smart. They end up getting jobs with
computer networks and making a lot of money. A lot of them start
out as hackers. The good news is that the best and the brightest
generally go to work trying to stop the worst and the dullest.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not telling you that there is nothing to worry about when it
comes to hacking. But I am saying that _ when it comes to worrying
about criminal acts _ to worry about getting a good deadbolt lock
for the front door of your home and to make sure not to leave the
keys in your cars. The real world is still a more dangerous place
than cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
