<HEADER>
A8482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH-ISMELL15-COX     02-16 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-ISMELL15-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Web team gets whiff of future
 &HT;    By Brian D. Crecente
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It won't be long before your computer is
stinking up the joint.
</P>
<P>
   The iSmell _ no kidding, that's its name _ is a boxy gizmo that
looks like a pencil sharpener and attaches to your computer like a
printer. Inside is a tray of scent materials, called a scent
palate, that can produce thousands of smells on command.
</P>
<P>
   That means you'll soon be able to tool the information
superhighway and stop and smell the roses, say Joel Bellenson and
Dexster Smith, founders of Oakland, Fla.-based DigiScents and
makers of the iSmell.
</P>
<P>
   Bellenson and Smith predict an entire e-world teeming with
scents: Smelly Web sites and e-mail, stinky movies, music and
advertising, and some really rank games. According to Scentworld,
DigiScents online guide to the world of smells, playing a
shoot-em-up might soon include an experience like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel helpless, and then it hits you ... a slight stream of
warm air, saturated with the stench of death and decay, drifts into
your nostrils.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellenson said racing games could use the smells of the terrain
and the vehicles to help pull users into the experience; adventure
games could use smell cues to tip a player off that a creature has
entered the room, and Web sites and e-mail could include just about
any smells you care _ or fear _ to imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Movies could use smell the way they currently use soundtracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding scent to movies will be like adding color to movies,''
Bellenson said, and despite the failure of the cruder attempts of
Smell-O-Vision, Bellenson is sure DigiScents will succeed. ``The
first movie with sound was `Jazz Singer' and it was basically a
piece of crap that people hated, but that didn't doom sound in
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 Bellenson and Smith founded Pangea Systems, Inc., a
tremendously successful biotech company that is working to unravel
the mysteries of DNA. They left early retirement to found
DigiScents in February 1999. When they discovered a way to digitize
and transmit the ``language of smell'' through a computer, the
iSmell was born. The company plans to start testing it by early
spring and have it on store shelves by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Bellenson said the company is also developing software that will
allow scentographers to create smell-laden art and invent their own
scents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope our tools will give rise to a large body of people who
will try to be creative,'' he said. ``I'm sure there will be
legions of young people trying to create their own scent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the whole world might soon smell like teen spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
