<HEADER>
A8485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-PAY-700&AMP;     02-16 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-PAY-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETRADE FILINGS WITH SEC OMITTED DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ETrade Group, the most visited investment site on the Internet,
has spent millions of advertising dollars to build its reputation
as a company that empowers individual investors. Along the way,
however, it has been slow to provide investors with some crucial
information about itself.
</P>
<P>
   On two occasions in recent months, ETrade has excluded
information about its executives' pay packages from Securities and
Exchange Commission filings. The omissions are an apparent
violation of SEC rules, compensation experts and lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Di Chiro, an ETrade spokesman, said the company had a
strong record of disclosing information and had done nothing wrong.
One instance was ``an oversight,'' Di Chiro said, and the company
did not think it had erred in the second.
</P>
<P>
   An SEC spokeswoman declined to comment on ETrade's filings,
saying the commission did not publicly discuss specific matters.
</P>
<P>
   On the first occasion, ETrade belatedly released information on
the repricing of stock options granted to top managers. On the
second, it delayed for six months releasing the terms of a new
contract for its chief executive, Christos M. Cotsakos.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, pay experts said, investors would have an unusually
hard time figuring out whether the executive pay packages would add
significantly to ETrade's losses or whether Cotsakos' contract
included a golden parachute big enough to make a future sale of the
company more likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this,'' said Graef S. Crystal, an executive-pay expert
who first noticed the missing information, ``suggests these guys
are not putting the shareholders' interests before their own.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, Cotsakos agreed to a new contract. But the company
did not include details of it in its next quarterly SEC filing in
August, as the SEC requires. The company also failed to report the
contract's details in its next quarterly filing and in its annual
proxy. ``That's definitely a no-no,'' said Judith Fischer, the
publisher of Executive Compensation Reports, a newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   The proxy did mention that Cotsakos would receive a ``a special
enterprise value enhancement bonus'' if new management were to take
control of the company. But since the company did not attach a copy
of the contract to the proxy or to the earlier filings, investors
had no way to determine how big it could be.
</P>
<P>
   Di Chiro said that listing Cotsakos' salary and acknowledging
the existence of the special bonus, even without discussing its
size, was sufficient for the proxy. ``The feeling here is that we
did disclose the major terms of that agreement,'' Di Chiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation lawyers, however, noted that in 601(b)(10) of
regulation S-K, the SEC specifically requires companies to attach a
copy of a new contract for top executives to the quarterly filing
after it is signed.
</P>
<P>
   ETrade has included a copy in its most recent filing, which it
sent to the SEC on Monday, and which will be available to the
public later this week, Di Chiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Cotsakos, one of the highest-paid executives in the online
investment industry, made almost $10 million in the 12 months that
ended Sept. 30, including his salary, bonus and gains for exercised
stock options. He received option grants potentially worth tens of
millions of dollars more.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Cronrath Bamberger, an SEC spokeswoman, said that if the
commission determined that a company regularly left out required
information, it would consider taking action that could range from
a letter expressing concern to a fine. ``We take these filings very
seriously,'' Bamberger said. In the last two years, the SEC has
stepped up its enforcement against late filers, she added.
</P>
<P>
   The recent instances involving ETrade are particularly troubling
because of the kind of company it is, pay experts said. ETrade
deals with highly detailed SEC rules every day, and the company,
with $250 million in revenue in its last quarter, is one of the
more established Internet firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not the kind of company you'd expect to be missing
pertinent disclosures,'' said Patrick S. McGurn, a vice president
at Informational Shareholder Services, which advises institutional
investors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the first of the two instances, ETrade failed to include a
chart that listed the occasions in which it repriced its
executives' stock options over the last decade, as required by SEC
rules.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1998, ETrade repriced more than 14 million options,
many with a strike price of $6 to $7, at $4.25. At the time, the
stock was hovering around $4, having lost more than half its value
in just four months. It has grown to $21.50 since then.
</P>
<P>
   Repricing is controversial because it allows executives to
profit from options even after they have failed to reach earlier
goals. But nobody debates whether the SEC requires a company to
publish the details of its repricings from the last decade, and
ETrade's November 29 proxy did not include a repricing table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a black-letter rule,'' McGurn said. ``When you reprice,
you do the 10-year look-back table. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after publishing its proxy, the company released the
table as an addendum, correcting what Di Chiro called an oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many investors are likely to miss the information when
they research the company. Investors who rely on the actual proxy _
printing it from the SEC's online database without noticing the
addendum, for example _ will not have the table.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate-governance experts say they are concerned that
ETrade's slow disclosures are part of a general attitude among
dot-com executives that many widely accepted management practices
are not crucial. Technology companies, for example, are among the
most generous to their executives, even when they miss financial
targets. And many, including ETrade, have relatively small boards
with a high proportion of directors who have ties to management,
McGurn said.
</P>
<P>
   Di Chiro said that ETrade had an effective board and that the
company adhered to all SEC rules. ``It's very serious business
around here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-14-00 2315EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
