<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRIGGER-HAPPY COPS OR JUST SCARED? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN LYNCH  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It was seven or eight years ago. I was one of
three newspaper executives in a car on the way to inspect a new
office in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   We were two middle-aged guys in suits and ties and a woman in
stylish business attire. The car was upscale. I was riding shotgun
in the passenger seat as we pulled off a superhighway _ and as the
driver took us through a stop sign.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, a lot of people blew by that stop sign. A couple of
New York State Police cruisers were parked just beyond it. The
troopers motioned us over. One of them, a woman, stuck her head
inside the driver's side window.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just went through a stop sign,'' she told the driver.
``Let's see your license and registration.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver reached over and opened the glove compartment. The
door to the thing fell down and smacked me in the knees. I told the
driver, ``Let me get out of your way here.'' I opened the passenger
door, and stood up.
</P>
<P>
   And almost got shot.
</P>
<P>
   The trooper immediately slapped her hand on the butt of her gun.
``Get back in the car!'' she shouted shrilly.
</P>
<P>
   Startled, I glanced at this woman over the car roof. What I saw
on her face was an expression of sheer panic. She was a smallish,
dark-haired woman in her late 20s. And, if she was frightened of
me, which she clearly was, I can assure you that I was a hell of a
lot more frightened of her. She was the one with the gun, after
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, ma'am,'' I said, and slid ver-r-r-ry slowly back into
that passenger seat.
</P>
<P>
   I made it a point to get her name from her tag. Afterward, I
spoke to a friend in the State Police about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, car stops can be dangerous,'' he explained. ``I know
her. She's young, and she got skittish. With a crew of well-dressed
people in a nice car in broad daylight, she should have kept cool,
but she's new on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   I've never forgotten that incident. I hadn't realized until then
just how jumpy cops can be. The other day, as I watched Officer
Sean Carroll testify on Court TV defending himself against a murder
charge in a case where he and three other New York City cops blew
away an unarmed man, that incident with the young trooper was
dancing in my brain.
</P>
<P>
   Quite clearly, Amadou Diallo shouldn't have reached for his
wallet when the cops told him not to move. Quite clearly, I
shouldn't have gotten out of that car that day. But if I'd taken a
bullet beside that road for doing that, I suspect I would have been
seriously annoyed. If I'd taken 19 bullets, as Diallo did, I would
expect the legal system to be seriously annoyed on my behalf.
</P>
<P>
   I've been watching this testimony, day after day, and I still
don't know what to make of it. Were those cops jumpy when they
approached Diallo, a young West African immigrant living in the
Bronx? Well, 30 New York City police officers have been gunned down
since 1990. The cops had ample reason to be jumpy _ especially at
night in a high-crime neighborhood and with a guy who wasn't
showing them his hands as they say they ordered him to do. And when
he reached into his pocket for what turned out to be a wallet, and
when one of the cops thought it was a gun Diallo had in his hand,
then whammo!
</P>
<P>
   Whatever comes out of this trial, though, we'd all better hope
it includes an intensely sharper awareness on the part of police
officers that theirs are not the only lives on the line in
situations like this.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us also should realize that any contact with a
police officer on the street or the highway can end up as more than
a mere annoyance. Just assume that the cop is scared spitless.
</P>
<P>
   And you'd better be scared, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
