<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8503 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BOWL-EMPIRE-STATE-HNS     02-16 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOWL-EMPIRE-STATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MISSOURI BOWLER CLOSES IN ON HALL-OF-FAME FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Mo., Ohio, Calif., Ga., N.Y.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETE DOUGHERTY  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATHAM, N.Y. _ For career goals, Pete Weber looks no further
than his family. The son of a Professional Bowlers Association Hall
of Famer wants to win as many titles as his dad.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Weber drew one step closer.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of the third-seeded position, Weber won two matches
Saturday to capture his 25th PBA title, the Parker Bohn III Empire
State Open at the Bowlers Club in Latham. One more and he will
equal the total of his father, Dick, who is tied for fourth on the
all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't have Dad having more than me,'' said Weber, who is
from St. Ann, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   One of Dick Weber's 26 titles came 40 years ago at the Empire
State Open. That was before Pete or Bohn _ whose name was attached
to the tournament this year _ were born.
</P>
<P>
   The first-place check in 1960 was $2,500, out of a $16,500
purse. Weber, 37, received a $15,000 winner's share from a total
prize fund of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just nice to win,'' Weber said. ``I won the Showboat 33
years after Dad won it, and made 10 times what he made for
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber defeated tournament leader Brian Himmler of Cincinnati
209-198 in the title match. Weber needed to convert a 3-6-10 spare
in the 10th frame to clinch to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the spare to be shooting for a title,'' said Weber,
who missed the same leave in the third frame against Himmler. ``A
double (two consecutive strikes) is easier to throw than a 3-6-10
spare.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber threw hard and straight at the spare _ he tried to hook
the ball on his earlier conversion attempt _ to get the necessary
pins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never doubt that I can win,'' Weber said after earning his
first victory since Feb. 21, 1998. ``If you doubt that you're going
to win, then it's time to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Himmler, on the strength of two doubles, had the lead through
eight frames. He could have closed out Weber with strikes in the
9th and 10th frames, but he left a 2-10 split, which he missed. Had
he struck out in the 10th, Himmler would have forced Weber to
strike.
</P>
<P>
   A pesky 10-pin followed by a 6-count on his fill ball made
Weber's task easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the match right in my hands until I gave it to him in
the 9th and 10th,'' said Himmler, who won $8,000. ``I have no
excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber advanced to the title game with a 236 in the semifinals to
eliminate Ryan Shafer (212) and Jason Hurd (209), who won the first
two matches.
</P>
<P>
   Weber needed a 9-count on his first ball in the 10th to close
out Shafer, but he nearly blew it. Weber's shot crossed the pocket,
but he left only the 7-pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking nine,'' Weber said. ``Even a ringing 10(-pin)
would look good. I didn't quite get it out far enough. It hooked
enough to get Brooklyn and get nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Shafer, the tour's leading money winner, failed to strike in his
first five frames, but a triple gave him a chance heading into the
ninth, where he left a 10-pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave it a run,'' said Shafer, who took third place, ``but I
started too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurd, a 6-foot, 250-pound right-hander from Visalia, Calif., was
the story of the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening match, Hurd (232) used a late five-bagger to
dispose of Jeff Lizzi of Sandusky, Ohio (202), and Steve Wilson of
Lake Worth, Fla. (198).
</P>
<P>
   Lizzi, who doubled in the 10th frame Friday night, could have
advanced with two strikes, but he left a pocket 7-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got up and told myself to throw a good shot, that I've got a
chance to win the match,'' Lizzi said. ``I threw it good, got a bad
break. I'm a little disappointed, but I'm happy about the way I
threw it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second match, Hurd (256) threw 10 of 12 strikes to get
past Brian Voss (234) of Atlanta and Rick Steelsmith (188) of
Wichita, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd had a chance to catch Weber in the semifinals, but a 3-6
leave in the ninth frame sealed his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ninth frame was the only bad ball I threw, and I knew it
as soon as I threw it,'' Hurd said. ``With the two guys (to bowl
against), there really isn't an area to make a bad shot. It's so
hard to beat two other guys out here, especially when you've been
bowling good all week to make the show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
