<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8562 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      02-16 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
 THIS STORY ALSO MOVING IN THE ``L'' CATEGORY 
 RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MIGHT HAVE MISSED IT. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``COLORS OF THE MOUNTAIN'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Da Chen (Random House, $25)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is that rarity in these times, a truly marvelous book. Da
Chen was born in 1962, in a tiny town in southern China, and his
memoir begins with his childhood stories of life during the
Cultural Revolution. Chen's grandfather had been a wealthy
landlord, reason enough to incur relentless mistreatment for him
and his family (he lived with Chen's parents and their five
children), as well as the loss of their house, land and most
possessions. Food was scarce, humiliation was waiting around every
corner, and the future seemed without promise. And yet, the view
through young Chen's eyes is remarkably cheerful, made so by his
curiosity and pugnacity and by his parents' enduring dignity in the
face of their dreadfully altered lives. This big-hearted and
sometimes even humorous story is written in simple, evocative
prose, and it ends as Chen leaves for college in Beijing. It's a
moving moment, but not the book's first _ we were misty before we
got past the dedication. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``THE BRETHREN'' &QL; 
 &UR; By John Grisham (Doubleday, $27.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to mock a rich man, but we must give Grisham credit:
He doesn't take the advance and run. His new novel is inventive and
unpredictable, and very different from any of his previous books.
It focuses on three judges who are incarcerated in a
minimum-security prison for sins ranging from tax evasion to
driving drunkenly over two hikers in Yellowstone. In jail, they
preside over a ``court'' in which inmates file grievances against
each other (witnesses are expected to lie, and verdicts are quick
and without appeal). The judges also run a mail scheme in which
they pose as young, nubile inmates, bait wealthy men on the
outside, then blackmail them for the gay sex talk in their letters.
Trouble brews when they target Aaron Lake, U.S. congressman from
Arizona and the presidential candidate backed by the powerful
director of the CIA. Everyone's sleazy here, and the efforts at
damage control are complex and entertaining. When this one lands on
the bestseller lists, the honor will be deserved.  &QL; 
 &UR; ``MATCH WITS WITH MENSA'' &QL; 
 &UR; (Perseus, $19.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We have found our omnipotence, and it is in vocabulary _ we will
stomp all challengers into the ground. It was the only subject in
this book at which we showed any prowess, but thank God there was
something. The editors say they have assembled more than 800
puzzles. We were struck by the inordinate amount of yakking that
precedes them. You must wade through much discussion of a category
_ trivia, analogies, logic etc. _ and a sometimes lengthy list of
acknowledgments before you get to the tests themselves, which makes
us think that Mensa members need rest between bouts of mental
exertion. We were also struck by how much Mensa members _ to be
one, you must score in the top two percent of the population on any
standard intelligence test _ like to look at themselves in the
mental mirror. But we digress. Here is what the editors consider to
be a ``warm-up'' trivia question: ``Domenikos Theotocopoulus is
better known as who?'' The answer is El Greco, the painter. We
looked it up.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``THE WHITE DEATH'' &QL; 
 &UR; By McKay Jenkins (Random House, $23.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins calls John McPhee his mentor, and you can see McPhee's
influence in the way Jenkins comes at his subject _ avalanches _
from all sides. His main path is the story of five young climbers
who died in an avalanche on Mount Cleveland in Montana's Glacier
National Park in 1969. He mixes the personal stories of those young
men with fascinating information about snow, mountains, rescues and
survival. He shows us how terrifying it is to be caught under snow,
not knowing which way is up (the only way to tell, he says, is to
spit _ whichever way it falls, you should dig, if you can move, in
the opposite direction), how you increase your chances for survival
if you remember to shut your mouth (many victims are found with
their mouths full of snow), how your chances plummet if you are not
rescued within minutes. Dogs have found people alive in 15 feet of
snow, sniffing them out by their individual scents. Each living
person smells different, Jenkins says. All corpses smell the same.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1307EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8563 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-Y2K-WOES-ABOUND-RESEN     02-16 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-WOES-ABOUND-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDESPREAD Y2K PROBLEMS ARE NOW SURFACING  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from Feb. 14)   (This 650-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By CHARLES ARTHUR  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The millennium bug was not a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 ``significant'' failures were caused by the
rollover from 1999 to 2000 in January alone, says the consultancy
KPMG.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the faults were trivial, a number were
potentially serious, including reported failures in nuclear power
plants and blackouts on military spy satellite processing systems.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Y2K faults are still emerging, and could reach a
peak over the next few months with the occurrence of the leap year
and the end of the financial year.
</P>
<P>
   Banks warn that Feb. 29 is likely to trigger more problems than
the New Year's Eve rollover, because some calendar software failed
to notice that _ unusually for a ``00'' year _ this is a leap year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.K., a survey by the Office of National Statistics
found that 5 percent of companies reported some sort of adverse
impact on computer systems arising from the year change,'' said
Malcolm Marshall, KPMG's information risk management partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in the U.S., a survey of IT professionals found a quarter
had experienced some sort of Y2K problem since the New Year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even computer manufacturers were not immune to the problem,
which prompted many organizations to invest millions of pounds to
protect their computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Apple, in a Stock Exchange announcement, said that in January it
had ``experienced a limited number of minor malfunctions in its
information technology (IT) systems as the result of the date
change,'' despite spending $10 million preparing against such
problems. Those mostly affected its manufacturing operations.
</P>
<P>
   David Walton, of the British Y2K Community Action Network _ some
of whose members forecast that the millennium bug would spell
disaster for civilization _ said: ``I would say that I was
pleasantly surprised by how little disruption there was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did see a lot of low-impact bugs, which was interesting _
it suggests that the high-impact ones were identified and dealt
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Walton works as an IT consultant and was so worried about
the potential for collapse that on New Year's Eve he had a
generator ready to kick in if the electricity supply failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was all so safe, why did the (British) Government have a
Millennium Center with 200 staff? You have to ask yourself what
they knew about what might happen that they didn't tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   The analysis by KPMG noted that ``the experience so far seems to
be that problems are being rapidly dealt with once they become
apparent.'' Of the recorded incidents, 67 were in the first week of
the year and 23 came later.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, companies are still discovering problems with their
systems caused by the shift to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Organizations needs to remain vigilant around the key dates of
the leap year and the end of months,'' said Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Among the incidents recorded by KPMG were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Seven U.S. nuclear plants had ``minor problems.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Two Japanese nuclear plants had ``failures.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pentagon was unable to process spy satellite data for a
number of hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ France's military satellites ``lost'' data.
</P>
<P>
   _ A kidney machine in Scotland failed during routine running.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cash and credit cards issued by American banks would not
validate.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the U.S., Medicare payments were disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hundreds of Web sites displayed the date as ``January 1,
1900'' due to misprogramming; almost as many displayed it as
``January 1, 19100.''
</P>
<P>
   _ U.K. Register Office reported dates of birth as 20200.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Kremlin Press Agency was unable to send out e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   _ Traffic lights in Jamaica failed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Port traffic software in Uganda displayed wrong dates.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 50 minor problems at six major Japanese electronics
firms.
</P>
<P>
   _ Customer records at a foreign bank in Japan deleted.
</P>
<P>
   _ A customer returning a rented videotape was charged $91,000
for being 100 years late. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 650-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
