<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDOWS-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MICROSOFT CHIEF PITCHES NEW WINDOWS SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The president of the Microsoft Corp. is playing
a boisterous pitchman for Windows 2000, the new business operating
system that goes on sale Thursday amid less than rave reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Windows 2000 is the PC at its very best,'' Steven A. Ballmer,
the president and chief executive of Microsoft, told the
Commonwealth Club of California on Tuesday. He said the software,
the latest version of Windows NT, enables corporate and small
business users to take advantage of electronic commerce and
Internet opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 2000 cost the Redmond, Wash., software giant more than
$1 billion to develop and release _ a year after its target date.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most impressive thing is the way it opens up computers to
the next realm,'' Ballmer, 43, who took the helm of the company
last month from his Harvard University friend, Bill Gates. Gates,
who remains the company's chairman, stepped down to become chief
software architect.
</P>
<P>
   Flashier events to launch Windows 2000 include a concert with
musician Carlos Santana and actor Cheech Marin on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Much is at stake with Windows 2000, which is a vital element in
Microsoft's strategy to remain relevant in the post-PC, Internet
age, industry watchers said. Yet Microsoft's shares tumbled almost
6 percent Friday, to $99.94, on analyst reports of potential
Windows 2000 software compatibility problems in computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has to hitch its wagon to the big star _ the
Internet,'' said Mark Specker, a managing director at Wit
SoundView, a San Francisco technology investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   The embattled software developer is engaged in a bitter legal
fight with the Department of Justice and 19 state attorneys
general. In a finding of fact last November, a federal judge stated
that Microsoft abused its power to create a monopoly, but it still
is yet to be determined whether those actions were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   At the Commonwealth Club, Ballmer declined to discuss the
potential court-ordered breakup of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any discussion of this is beyond irresponsible and
premature,'' Ballmer said. ``We'd like to settle the lawsuit, and
get this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer also said that despite the attacks that temporarily
crippled several major Internet sites last week, the government
should not increase its regulatory role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Private industry will come up with the solutions,'' Ballmer
said. ``Technology will provide the defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
