<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8573 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-`STEPFORD'-HILLARY-RE     02-16 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`STEPFORD'-HILLARY-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY, HILLARY, WHATEVER HAS HAPPENED TO YOU?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...RESENDING from Feb. 14)   (This pithy 950-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``p'' political news, ``a'' domestic news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The lady may not bake cookies, but she tosses a
``mean'' salad and can even fry a ``great'' omelette _ just so
long, of course, as no eggs get broken.
</P>
<P>
   Such, it seems, are the minimum qualifications for a woman
seeking public office in equal-opportunity America at the start of
the 21st century. Ask Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   When Hillary Clinton _ sorry, Hillary Rodham Clinton _ was first
approached to run for the Senate, it looked a mad and ill-advised
idea, but you could understand the temptation and had to admire her
chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   She may have been flattered into running and she was taking a
risk, but America likes a risk-taker _ and we women wished her God
Speed.
</P>
<P>
   Never having had a Margaret Thatcher, U.S. lawmakers could do
with a Hillary Clinton to shake their all too complacent
congressional chamber out of its torpor.
</P>
<P>
   If past performance is the measure, there is no doubt that in
Senator Clinton, the people of New York would have a tough, feisty
and intelligent woman standing up for their interests.
</P>
<P>
   A passionate political speaker in her student days, she can
still command a hall. A lawyer respected by her fellow
professionals in her mid-years, she has lost none of her sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   Now one of the most popular first ladies on record, she has
travelled the world and overcome the most personal and political of
travails (Monica, impeachment and the Whitewater non-scandal) to
emerge forthright and strong.
</P>
<P>
   Who could forget her televised tour de force of loyalty and
political savvy when she defended her husband against the
``right-wing conspiracy'' in the early days of the Monica
allegations?
</P>
<P>
   It mattered not that she was, as it turned out, misguided in her
loyalty, and probably wrong in her charge of conspiracy. She was
dignified and magnificent. She had saved her husband's career
before, and her own, and would do so again.
</P>
<P>
   Half a year later, she was privately humiliated, but publicly
stoical, and hailed as a heroine across the land for doing exactly
what she had pledged not to do: stand by her man like some Tammy
Wynette.
</P>
<P>
   Small rebellions had attended her advance: that ``Rodham'' she
kept in her name, even in conservative Arkansas; those pantsuits
she settled on as her business attire; her solo travels abroad, and
now that move from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Most memorable, perhaps, was her retort, eight years ago, as the
then-presidential candidate's wife, that she had better things to
do as a professional woman than bake cookies.
</P>
<P>
   What a smashing of taboos was there; what a shock to cloistered
suburbia. She was Senate material even then.
</P>
<P>
   That Hillary, though, must have slipped out of the back door of
her new home in Chappaqua, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who stood in her three-quarter raincoat and sensible
shoes by the front gate on moving day was but a caricature.
</P>
<P>
   House-proud and pert, with conversation all of belongings and
shopping, this woman was no Senator-in-waiting. She had to be an
impostor.
</P>
<P>
   The substitution, to be sure, was gradual and stealthy. When the
tabloids told us that she had visited a renowned plastic surgeon
last summer, we did not want to believe it. Hillary Clinton would
not be so vain as to be diverted from her serious work by a few
facial wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   With or without the knife _ the best surgeons keep you guessing
_ she has changed: a new face, new makeup, new hair _ and a new
rack of pantsuits.
</P>
<P>
   It all shouts ``young,'' but ``young,'' alas, as all others look
young: a standardized, Stepford candidate.
</P>
<P>
   When the woman who called herself Hillary _ no more Rodham, no
more Clinton _ finally made her Senate run official this month, the
substitution was complete.
</P>
<P>
   Who would elect a senator called Hillary? She wore oversized
pearls too crude even for her remade features. She spoke in the
singsong tones and false emphases of today's political
voice-trainers, and she pointed and jabbed with her hands, just as
the male politicians are taught to do.
</P>
<P>
   And if her style has been clipped, so have her causes. Where is
the woman who told Americans to their face that their lack of a
national health system was a disgrace to a civilized nation and she
wanted to do something about it?
</P>
<P>
   Where is the woman who embarrassed the Administration by
speaking out for a Palestinian state, because she believed it
inevitable, and right?
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's all schools and women and children: all very laudable
and all very safe.
</P>
<P>
   The old Hillary was a lifelong left-winger with a streak of
idealism; the new one calls herself a ``new Democrat,'' just like
her husband, and steers none too deftly the middle course between
government as the problem and as the solution.
</P>
<P>
   She has turned tough on crime and supports the death penalty.
And she is learning how to say nothing of consequence. She will not
even commit herself to sending that small Cuban boy back to his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, Hillary, you don't need the Florida vote, your husband
can't run for another term; you are not the vice president's
keeper. Just imagine that child was Chelsea and tell us what you
would do.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary, Hillary _ have you really let the consultants remake
you? Do you really believe that New Yorkers will prefer a
well-meaning suburban housewife to the independent woman you were?
</P>
<P>
   And if they did _ which would only confirm the lamentable
conformism of America's women _ is that the sort of senator you
would want to be? &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this pithy 950-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
