u s BC-RAC-DAYTONA-BIRMINGHA     02-16 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DAYTONA-BIRMINGHAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-LAWYER UNDERGOES A TRIAL BY FIRE IN RACING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ He grew up in Boston, a hockey and
baseball fan who played both sports at St. Sebastian's, where he
now serves on the board of directors. After a stint in the Army, he
studied business at Georgetown, then law at Boston College before
joining the Boston firm of Mintz Levin Cohn Ferris Glovsky and
Popeo, becoming a partner in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped practicing law about 20 years ago,'' said Jack
Birmingham as he and his wife, Karen, relaxed in the luxurious
motor coach of their NASCAR Winston Cup team at the paddock area of
Daytona International Speedway. ``I practiced trial law in Boston
and bought a business and realized that I couldn't do both. I went
into business and wound up owning Steinway and Sons. I sold it and
sat on the beach, looking for something to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he decided to do something that appealed to his
competitive nature.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to go racing. In the ultra-competitive Winston Cup
series, no less. But he learned, as many wealthy car owners do,
that the best way to make a small fortune is to take a large
fortune and go racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple of false starts before, but it was just
something we wanted to do and we decided to go after it,'' said
Birmingham, 58, whose interest in motorsports was piqued when he
began watching races on television. ``It took us more than a year
and half to get to the point where Chuck Rider was willing to sell
his team to us.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rider agreed to sell Bahari Racing to Birmingham last July
for an estimated $5 million-$6 million, it marked the birth of the
Eel River Racing team, named after the Cape Cod waterway that
flowed near the Birminghams' summer home in Osterville.
</P>
<P>
   The Eel River outfit shifted into high gear when Birmingham
enlisted veteran crew chief Barry Dodson as a minority owner.
Dodson, in turn, hired Jeff Fuller, a former Modified champ from
Auburn, Mass., to campaign their No. 27 Pontiac Grand Prix as the
replacement for former Bahari driver Derrike Cope.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually a pretty weird situation,'' said Fuller, who got
an early start in racing at age 15 driving late models and
modifieds at Westborough Speedway. ``I didn't really know Jack
Birmingham, the owner, when this deal was put together. When they
called for me to come over and meet with him, knowing that he was
from Massachusetts, I mean, that was just a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the news last December that Eel River Racing had
landed a primary sponsor: Viagra, the wonder drug produced by the
pharmaceutical firm Pfizer used primarily to treat erectile
dysfunction. At the press conference announcing the sponsorship,
members of the media snickered.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first heard about it, everybody had the same response
about this and that,'' said Fuller. ``But the serious side of the
situation is that men don't get checked. They're going to be
providing a trailer at every Winston Cup event for the fans, so the
guys can actually come down and get checked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early detection is a key factor. If the trailer is able to
screen 30,000-40,000 people this year, then they'll feel they've
done a good job, so it's a win-win situation for both NASCAR and
Pfizer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I decided that I wanted to get involved and it would be
possible to do it, I spent a lot of time talking with a bunch of
different guys to see if it was doable,'' Birmingham said. ``There
was certainly some risk in it, but it was doable. But when you're
not a celebrity, you can only attract a sponsor by putting together
a good team and that's what we've tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   With Dodson their steward, Birmingham and Fuller will be intent
on earning their stripes as rookie owner and driver when they
jockey with NASCAR's elite for a starting spot in Sunday's Daytona
500.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got in racing, my goal was modifieds,'' said
Fuller, 42, who won the 1992 NASCAR Featherlite Modified Series
championship. ``I've had a lot of races up there (in New England)
and made a lot of friends and I miss the modifieds, but ultimately
when you make it to the modifieds, you look at making another step.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started in '95 and did the Busch Series, I was hoping
that after two or three years that this (NASCAR ride) would be the
next step I'd take. It did take five years, but I'm not
disappointed with that. I think it might even be a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've obviously got a super opportunity with Barry Dodson. He
won a championship with Rusty Wallace and he knows these race cars,
so hopefully he can speed up my learning curve a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they struggled during pole qualifications Saturday, the
Eel River team got some encouragement Monday when Fuller made
significant gains in a practice session with a hot lap of 191.526
miles per hour. But before anyone could celebrate, the team was a
severe blow when their primary car was totaled in a crash caused by
Greg Sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller, who had just returned to the track for another drafting
session, was sent hurtling toward the wall and his car burst into
flames, but Fuller escaped with nothing more than a sore neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's heartbreaking,'' said Dodson, who is scrambling to
prepare Fuller's backup car for Thursday's Twin 125-mile
qualifiers. ``We put 90 percent of our effort into this one car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get the backup car out there and go through the same
motions. It's kind of a Russian roulette until that last practice
is over before Thursday, but we're just going to calm down and try
to do everything right on this car, and then race our way in.''
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham seemed prepared for a bump or two like this when he
came aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's very democratic about it is that you go out
on the starting line, put your foot on the gas, and if you come in
first, everyone will be cheering for you,'' he said. ``It's a
competitive struggle, and so we're off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
