<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRIS WILL TAKE A RUN AT IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Since it happened for the St. Louis Rams
with Kurt Warner, NFL teams are now wondering whether players can
virtually drop to them from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? It makes for a great story. And it's cheap.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will bring in a few second-tier running backs in
the next week or two and hope one or two pans out.
</P>
<P>
   You never know, right? Just ask the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   One player they've already locked in to a two-year
minimum-salary deal is Raymont Harris, the former Chicago Bear and
Green Bay Packer who has one 1,000-yard season on his resume. The
Patriots are hoping he can be the surprise of their team after
missing the entire 1999 season while recuperating from a fractured
right leg.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 29, was never a great back but is certainly a tough,
rugged, tackle-to-tackle runner. Two years ago, he fractured his
left fibula and tore ligaments in his leg. When he tried out for
the Patriots before last season, he wasn't quite ready. Nobody
called him after that.
</P>
<P>
   Harris spent the year working with Ohio State strength and
conditioning coach Dave Kennedy and Seattle holdout wide receiver
Joey Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's in top condition again, and it didn't hurt that
Harris has the same agent as Patriots coach Bill Belichick (Neil
Cornrich). It also didn't hurt that Harris was familiar with
Patriots receivers coach Ivan Fears, who was receivers coach in
Chicago when Harris was there and played a part in devising the
running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's starting over in the Patriots organization,'' said
Harris. ``It's just like me. I'll be starting over, so it'll be an
ideal situation for me. I'm getting a chance to be a lead running
back for a team that's very solid. That's all I could ask from
anybody, to get the opportunity to be a starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris was a fourth-round pick of the Bears in 1994. He rushed
for 1,033 yards in 1997, scoring 10 touchdowns. Besides missing
last season, he also missed 1995 with a broken collarbone sustained
in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he's out to show people ``that I'm not brittle or
soft. I've just had some tough breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have come back and I could have played well wherever I
went and helped somebody's club. I think if I would have come back
last year, I would have played, but I wouldn't have been 100
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he will leave Kennedy and join the Patriots'
conditioning program in late March. The Patriots tried to hire
Kennedy, but so far he's turned them down. Harris has seen Andy
Katzenmoyer and Terry Glenn working out at Ohio State this winter.
</P>
<P>
   At 228 pounds, Harris said he's right at his playing weight. He
has a lot of pent-up energy he hopes to let out on the gridiron
soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Having lost Shawn Jefferson, and with Troy Brown unsigned, the
Patriots have expressed interest in Bears free agent receiver Bobby
Engram. They're also looking at defensive linemen, such as
Pittsburgh's Nolan Harrison, former Dolphin Shane Burton, and
former Jet Anthony Pleasant . . . Steve Israel will visit the
Bengals next Wednesday. Former Patriot cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock
also is due in Cincinnati soon . . . The Patriots may part ways
with middle linebacker Marty Moore, who is an unrestricted free
agent.
</P>
</TEXT>
