<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8593 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ECOM-STORES-ART-BOS &LR;      02-16 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-STORES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 BRICK-AND-MORTAR STORES LURE CUSTOMERS IN CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea came to Jeremiah T. Doyle while shopping for groceries.
Many e-commerce Web sites take business away from brick-and-mortar
retailers, but why wasn't there a way for small, local merchants to
use the Internet to fight back?
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Doyle recently launched Eversave.com in Woburn,
Mass., one of many commercial Web sites seeking to put a new
Internet twist on some old marketing ideas and loyalty programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to link the Internet to Main Street,'' said Doyle, 34,
a direct-marketer by trade. ``We want to use the Web to drive foot
traffic to brick-and-mortar stores.''
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, Eversave.com aims to be a free service about
online coupons, comparison shopping, and saving time. First,
consumers would check prices and bargains at the Web site. Then
they would head out to Main Street to make their purchases.
</P>
<P>
   In an ideal scenario, Eversave.com hopes to create a shopping
experience that combines the best of the online and off-line
worlds. Its Web site would supply valuable information, and
brick-and-mortar retailers would provide service, product, and a
chance for consumers to see and touch what they're buying.
</P>
<P>
   To small merchants, Eversave.com positions itself both as an
Internet strategy to compete with retail Web sites and as a
marketing tool, a sort of online Yellow Pages where they buy ads.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers often consult the Yellow Pages before making a
purchase; the hope is that many consumers will regard Eversave.com
in the same way, as a go-to shopping resource.
</P>
<P>
   If Eversave.com borrows some ideas from the Yellow Pages, it
also may be reminiscent of the old-fashioned, loyalty-card programs
used by everyone from Star Market to public TV stations. Even The
Boston Globe once tried a loyalty card.
</P>
<P>
   Just as with those programs, consumers who choose to apply for
an Eversave.com card qualify for discounts at participating
merchants, though Web site visitors can skip the card and simply
print out online coupons. What's in it for the merchants? They get
to learn more and more about a consumer's shopping habits.
</P>
<P>
   Eversave.com is hardly the only Internet company using coupons
to lure eyeballs to its Web site. There are CoolSavings.com and
MySavings.com, just to name two.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of players out there, but they're not all
playing the same way,'' said Melissa Shore, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications, an Internet research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because they both see the small Main Street merchants as
their best customers, Eversave.com caught the eye of TransWestern
Publishing, a regional Yellow Pages company whose biggest investor
is Thomas H. Lee Partners, the Boston buyout firm. Last month, the
two announced a strategic partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership with TransWestern may help Eversave.com meet one
of its biggest challenges. In getting started, this kind of Web
site faces a chicken-or-egg dilemma. The big question: Which comes
first? The merchants or the consumers?
</P>
<P>
   To persuade consumers to join the network, the Web site must
offer them discounts from many merchants. But merchants won't agree
to offer the discounts _ or pay to advertise on the network's Web
site _ unless they're convinced many consumers will be visiting the
site on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Such sites are ``dependent on getting a critical mass, both of
consumers and merchants,'' said Jill Frankle, director of
e-commerce retail research at Gomez Advisors of Lincoln, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   So far, about 650 merchants have agreed to place ads on
Eversave.com, though many were enticed by a free trial offer.
</P>
<P>
   With only 25 employees, Eversave.com needed more personnel to
recruit more merchants to use its marketing services. Now
TransWestern's sales force will help with that task as it
approaches merchants with package deals on buying ad space both in
regional Yellow Pages and on Eversave.com's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   As Doyle sees it, Eversave.com solves a problem for
TransWestern; one drawback to buying space in a Yellow Pages is
that a merchant is stuck with one ad for a whole year.
</P>
<P>
   For merchants, the beauty of advertising on the Web is that ads
can be regularly updated, Doyle said. Merchants can offer seasonal
specials or discounts on slow-moving merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   What's made the Yellow Pages successful is that it exposes a
small merchant's products to consumers ``at the precise moment when
consumers are ready to buy,'' said TransWestern chairman Larry
Bloch; now Eversave.com can extend this strategy online.
</P>
<P>
   TransWestern isn't the only one Eversave.com has turned to as it
looks to build an online network that connects merchants and
customers. Eversave.com has formed a strategic alliance with Pan
Pacific Retail Properties Inc., a West Coast mall operator, and it
has entered a partnership agreement with the Magma Group, a Boston
firm that specializes in marketing to college students.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Eversave.com said it has persuaded 85,000 consumers to
join its online discount program. To date, it says it has attracted
nearly $5 million in venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   Why should a consumer choose Eversave.com over rival coupon
sites? Doyle offers several reasons. For openers, Eversave.com can
link consumers to local services such as chimney sweeps or roof
repairs, as well as products.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``Product &AMP; Price Finder.'' Using this feature,
consumers can e-mail Eversave.com with such requests as: ``I need
to find a private dining room for my husband's 50th birthday party.
Who can do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Using the consumer's zip code to narrow the search, Eversave.com
forwards those requests by e-mail to nearby restaurants, but
without the consumer's e-mail address to protect the consumer's
privacy, Doyle said. Over the next few days, merchants e-mail
responses to Eversave.com, which relays them to the consumer. The
consumer then decides which merchants, if any, to contact.
</P>
<P>
   Though consumers need disclose only an e-mail address and zip
code to qualify for discounts, they're invited to fill out a
``personal profile'' and apply for a membership card.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Eversave.com hopes to learn more and more about an
individual's shopping habits. Eversave.com can then use this
information to help merchants target their online ads.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a consumer who has bought golf clubs with an
Eversave.com coupon or card may see different banner ads when he
visits Eversave.com's Web site than a consumer who bought flowers
will see.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers also have the option to allow Eversave.com to e-mail
them special alerts on merchant promotions. A golfer, for example,
might opt to be alerted about sales on putters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
