<HEADER>
A8597 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-ORLEAN-ART-BOS     02-16 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-ORLEAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SUSAN ORLEAN DIGS IN THE SOMETIMES THIEVING ORCHID TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It starts accidentally enough. New Yorker magazine staff writer
Susan Orlean picks up a newspaper left behind on an airplane and
finds a story about a white man and three Seminole Indians who have
been arrested with rare plants stolen from a Florida swamp for
cloning and sale.
</P>
<P>
   Always on the lookout for odd juxtapostions (like swamp,
orchids, Seminoles, and cloning) Orlean grabs her pen and heads for
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The result of that brief encounter with discarded newsprint is a
funny, richly descriptive book called ``The Orchid Thief'' about a
subculture of obsessed collectors. It becomes a surprise
best-seller, is optioned by movie director Jonathan Demme _ and
embroils Orlean in an orchid war with those who feel she has goofed
on their sacred calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a certain number of people who flogged me
mercilessly for errors,'' says Orlean. ``These are people who
pedigree their houseplants, so it didn't come as a surprise to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   One of these people is Ned Nash of the American Orchid Society,
who is thanked in the acknowledgments for fact checking the book
but has demanded that his name be removed.
</P>
<P>
   It's still there. ``I'm leaving him in just to irritate him,''
says Orlean, a former columnist for the Boston Globe Magazine and
the Boston Phoenix, interviewed at the Harvard Museum of Natural
History, where she spoke earlier this month in connection with an
exhibition on orchids.
</P>
<P>
   She also has no patience with orchidists who complain that the
flower on the book's cover is upside down: ``I tell people it's a
bird's-eye view.''
</P>
<P>
   Iconoclastic John Laroche, the orchid thief of the title, is
unperturbed, however. He despises the AOS establishment that shuns
him. ``Susan didn't start out critical of the orchid
establishment,'' he says. ``I told her they were lunatics. She
said, no, they're just plant collectors. But after her interviews
with them she said I was right.''
</P>
<P>
   His opinion of Orlean's work? ``I didn't care if the book was
any good,'' he says. ``I don't care if the movie's any good.''
</P>
<P>
   What Laroche does care about is that he just sold the story
rights to his life to Tri-Star, which is planning to make the
movie. He says he's getting $200,000, and more if the movie's a
hit. ``They told me, `You can never sell your life again.' I think
that's a good catch phrase: You can only sell your life once!''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is going to have to invent a plot because nothing much
happens in the book. The actual trial ends quickly and
undramatically with a few hundred dollars in fines. Laroche is
barred from reentering the swamp, which confines his outings with
Orlean to orchid nurseries and shows until the last chapter. When
he finally takes her into the Fakahatchee swamp anyway in search of
rare ghost orchids like those he stole, they fail to find one in
bloom. They get lost. They find their way back to their car. The
book ends.
</P>
<P>
   Orlean pads this slender narrative into 284 pages that include
lively chapters on the history of orchid hunting, fraudulent
Florida land deals, and the Seminole Indians, emphasizing bizarre
details such as the disposition of 19th-century chief Osceola's
severed head.
</P>
<P>
   She also hangs out with members of the American Orchid Society
and orchid nurserymen, frequently making droll fun of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Orchid Thief'' is ``a color piece in the grand old
tradition of people from New York coming to points south and
finding a bunch of gargoylish characters that they can portray in
an amusing light,'' says orchid grower Martin Motes by telephone
from his nursery, Motes Orchids, in Homestead, Fla. He describes
himself as ``one of the minor gargoyles on the cathedral.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many members of the American Orchid Society, which moved
its headquarters from Cambridge, Mass. to West Palm Beach, Fla.
about 15 years ago, hate the book, Motes, like most readers, thinks
it's a hoot. But he also says Orlean rearranges chronology and
colors details to make him sound like a ``hick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan was not wanton with the truth, but accuracy was not
necessarily what she was looking for. She's in love with being able
to conjure a scene,'' says Motes, who disputes seven items in the
eight-page section that describes his nursery.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, his greenhouses are state-of-the-art, not
``slightly seedy,'' he says, and his doberman-rottweiller and
yellow lab are not ``mud-colored.'' When one of them bites Orlean,
it is on her ``fourth or fifth visit,'' he says, but the incident
is written to sound like it occurs during their first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are there are ``sixty thousand orchid species,'' as Orlean
writes. ``Nobody knows, and so there are all kinds of wild
estimates, but 30,000 is the top end figure,'' says Motes.
</P>
<P>
   The peculiar thing is that this numerical error has been widely
pointed out and Orlean says ``we changed it in the hard cover.''
But it's still there in the new paperback edition from Ballantine
Books.
</P>
<P>
   Motes calls the upside down orchid on the book cover ``classic
bad taste, whether it matters out there in the world of books. It's
not a very good flower, either, horror of horrors!'' He laughs
again, his voice warm with southern charm. ``A very common
phalaenopsis, your basic Kmart orchid.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from New York, the book's editor
Jonathan Karp at Random House, explains the inverted orchid on the
cover matter-of-factly: ``It looked better that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Karp calls Orlean ``the heir to John McFee'' and ``a cross
between Lucille Ball, Brenda Starr and Dorothy Parker.'' He says,
``She'll spend hours on a paragraph until it sounds just right.
</P>
<P>
   She'll even tromp through a swamp.
</P>
<P>
   Laroche recalls their foray. ``Susan was petrified,'' he says.
``She's naturally pale, but she had no color at all. She's a short
girl. Water up to my hips is water up to her chest. And there's
things swimming in there.'' Like alligators and poisonous water
snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Orlean says she assumed such expeditions would utilize ``a swamp
buggy or something.'' When the awful truth ``slowly dawned'' on
her, she almost wept.
</P>
<P>
   However, Orlean jokes, a wade through the Fakahatchee looks easy
compared to giving shape to her mass of notes. ``It was more of a
swamp than the swamp,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But all the slogging through word and water is paying off more
handsomely than stealing orchids ever could.
</P>
<P>
   Orlean has read one script for the movie and says it is
``wild.'' When it comes to films, no one even bothers to think
about accuracy, though Laroche's contract promises not to depict
him as a drug addict and a few other things. Other than that, the
sky (or the swamp) is the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Though Orlean describes their relationship as ``grudgingly
affectionate'' and absolutely not romantic, their constant sparring
provides much of the humour of the book. Yet if the movie does get
made, some are already speculating that Orlean's and Laroche's
characters (a diminuative, redheaded and feisty Holly Hunter? An
exasperating, roguish George Clooney?) will probably be swept by
mutual passions beyond orchids.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll end up in each other's arms in the primordial swamp,''
Motes laughs. ``The New York girl loses her patina of
sophistication.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he see this as the triumph of the Southern gargoyles?
``Yes! Absolutely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8601 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM-THORPE-BOS &LR;      02-16 1618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-THORPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIAN SWIM STAR IAN THORPE HAS HIS OWN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Take an articulate 6-foot-4-inch 17-year-old
with size 17 feet and a gracious manner, and ratchet up the
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Pin on him the hopes and expectations of his entire country,
which is the host for this year's Olympic games. Give him special
handlers who ensure his food and drink can't be tampered with by
enemies who might try to taint him with illegal substances, and
insulate him from an ever-growing, ever-insistant crush of the
media. A boy in a bubble.
</P>
<P>
   What you get is Ian Thorpe, a young man trying to balance life
as a ``typical'' Australian teenager with his status as a national
treasure. The ``Golden Goose,'' as he is called.
</P>
<P>
   The way Aussies see it, when the Summer Games come to Sydney in
September, Thorpe is not just their hope to win multiple medals,
not just the point man to reclaim Australia's past swimming
glories; he may well be the biggest Australian story of the Games,
and the comparisons with Mark Spitz are already coming thick and
fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a chance to be another Michael Johnson,'' says John
Devitt, 1956 Olympic gold medal swimmer and now vice president of
the Australian Olympic Committee, referring to Johnson's role as
the dominant athlete for the host team at the Games 1996 Games in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It could all make for a happy story, except for the cloud of
controversy, suspicion, accusation, national jealousies, and
paranoia hanging over this sandyblond, 190-pound heir-apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Just back from two weeks of World Cup swimming in Germany,
Thorpe appeared Monday at a packed press conference in Sydney, one
of the last he will face before his managers take him into a kind
of splendid isolation (``so he can concentrate on what he has to
do,'' says Devitt) in the five months leading to the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his chances, it would seem he won't have to do much
more than he has been doing. Thorpe has dominated the last two
years of international swimming. He holds four world records _ 200-
and 400-meter freestyle, the 4X200-meter freestyle (long course),
and the 200-meter freestyle (short course) _ and has twice been
named World Swimmer of the Year by US Swimming World Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the German experience two weeks ago was an indication of the
bitter pressures that come with being a world champion, whether or
not one is ready for them.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 5, Thorpe's World Cup performance in Berlin was
questioned by German coach Manfred Theismann, who said other
swimmers were skeptical of the record-breaking time he posted.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe was one of five Australian swimmers given a random drug
test after the races, but Australian coach Don Talbot threatened to
withdraw his team at that point, complaining that Thorpe and others
had not been provided with tamperproof containers for the urine
test.
</P>
<P>
   The US, whose backstroker, Lenny Krayzelburg, also set a world
mark, joined with the Australians in complaining that the urine
samples could easily be popped open and manipulated. Talbot
threatened to pull his team from Sunday's World Cup races, and in
the face of the boycott, Berlin police finally agreed to seal the
samples.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot had said he would in no way leave urine samples in Berlin
that could be manipulated, especially since the controversy had
been sparked by allegations from a German coach.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe feels he rose to the test and overcame the negative. He
was so angry he considered withdrawing from Sunday's race; then he
felt ``sad'' about people passing rumors of his cheating; and
finally, he decided ``it was pretty humorous.'' He went out Sunday
and sped across Berlin's Europasportpark to shatter his own his own
200-meter freestyle record by more than a second.
</P>
<P>
   The hearty applause from some 2,000 fans gave his spirits a
lift. ``I've never gotten so much applause after a competition,''
said Thorpe. ``That moved me deeply. It shows me that people are
behind me and believe in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the faulty drug-testing procedures used in Berlin,
Thorpe's record may fail to be ratified, but without sounding
chippy, the teen sensation says it would not bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't concern me if I lose that particular time,'' Thorpe
said at Monday's press briefing. ``Everyone knows I performed that
time and I did it without assistance. I should be able to perform
it again.'' Devitt added that he saw no reason why the new record
would go forward with FINA, the sport's governing body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed Europe,'' said Thorpe. ``But I learned a lot on this
trip that you're not always able to compete the way you'd like to,
that you sometimes have to compete under some pretty extreme
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I learned a lot about myself and about Australian swimming
and the support I have from the nation. That really did startle me
at the time, because I could pretty much feel the whole nation get
behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thorpe and the Australia swim team have their eyes on much
bigger prizes than a European World Cup. To the end that nothing
goes wrong that could damage his career between now and the Games,
Thorpe will be under the constant watchful eye of manager David
Flaskas who has assigned three assistants to give virtually
full-time security to Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe says he will no longer eat out at restaurants or accept
any food or drink whose origins he is not aware of. While he calls
the precautions ``paranoia,'' many swimmers and other top athletes
have talked about the possible spiking of food and water bottles
with banned substances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big concern is when he goes out to dinner and to movies
with the guys from the pool,'' says Ian's sister, Christiana. Ian
asks to open all the cans and bottles he drinks himself, and will
send them back if they've been opened. At the pool, he has to be
sure to pick up his own water bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear is about the many banned substances that could show up
in drug testing. When he left a Berlin hotel last week feeling
sick, Thorpe says he was afraid to buy from a pharmacy what looked
like a familiar medicine because, packaged in another country, it
may have contained banned substances.
</P>
<P>
   Paranoid? Perhaps. But understandable after the German issue,
which he believes may have been concocted to throw him off his
swimming pace. Thorpe has come to believe that an athlete at his
level, with so much to lose, can never be too careful.
</P>
<P>
   English team officials, he points out, warned their athletes to
lock up their food supplements after tests revealed the presence of
the steroid nandrolone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me very paranoid about everything,'' said Thorpe. ``I
can go to restaurants, but who is to say someone won't spike
something.''
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, Thorpe eats ``99 percent of my meals at home.''
Margaret, his mother, makes sure all the food is fresh and
well-washed, that packaged food is well-sealed.
</P>
<P>
   According to Flaskas and other swimmers on the team, there have
been several recent cases in which athletes have blamed positive
drug test results in tampering of water bottles, food supplements,
and even tooth paste. Says Australian sprinter Matt Shirvington,
Thorpe's experience in Germany has increased his own fears of being
victimized. ``It's so easy for someone to do it,'' he says, ``but
so hard for us to explain.''
</P>
<P>
   Former gold medalist Duncan Armstrong said Thorpe was now in
good hands with his managers and coaches but probably has ``been
targeted since he was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australian swimming is just so professional these days they
will not let anything happen to him,'' says Armstrong. ``Ian Thorpe
is our golden goose. He could win three or four golds.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as manager David Flaskas says: ``Ian is a 17-year-old kid,
and he has to have a little life. He is only a young man. There's a
very fine line between giving him enough space and keeping an eye
on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorp, who says that he goes out with his friends just as he
chooses, ``like any normal teenager,'' is far from reckless. He
thinks about everything he eats _ almost all of his snacks being
fresh fruit and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   As for the issue of drug testing, Thorpe says, ``I don't think
the drug issue has been resolved at all. And until blood testing
comes in and a strict procedure in place, these things will
continue to happen, either to me or to some other swimmer. We
really need to enforce the testing procedure in order to protect
all those innocent swimmers out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday is yesterday,'' he adds, ``but Lenny Krayzelburg and
I are still not happy with the doping control procedures. We
believe a manipulation of the samples can't be ruled out, and
that's important to innocent athletes. Blood testing combined with
the urine testing we're already doing is the only way we'll put a
strong foot forward in the stand against drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of a strong foot forward, Thorpe is used to jokes about
his feet, which give him nearly twice the surface area of more
normal sizes. The size 17s beat through the water like flippers,
giving him what teammate Kieren Perkins describes as ``a huge kick,
with great power, and an incredible change of speed. These are all
the things that you need to be competitive in sprint events.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe says he can brush aside the unpleasantness of the Berlin
World Cup incident and resume a ``more than happy'' lifestyle
training for a goals his nation has for him. It's not pressure, he
says, only if you let it be pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any expectations anyone else has of me for the Olympics are
nowhere near the expectations I have for myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
