<HEADLINE>
HELPING WITH THE FINANCIAL TURMOIL OF DIVORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year, 1.4 million divorces are granted in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising, then, that the severing of marriage bonds
has spawned a market niche for consultants and a culture of divorce
that includes everything from counseling groups and social
organizations to publications. Now there's even a new breed of
professionals: certified divorce planners, or CPDs, who help people
seeking divorce manage their finances.
</P>
<P>
   For men, often overlooked in the divorce process, the financial
pressures and emotional toll can be devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say men often lack the social supports needed to help
them through such an emotionally wrenching period. Many hide their
feelings, fearing loss of a job or loss of respect. Not
surprisingly, new organizations and associations have sprung up in
support of divorced and single fathers with children.
</P>
<P>
   Divorce planner Margorie Engel of Boston says her goal is to
help both men and women ``understand that divorce is a transition,
and that the financial decisions they make will have a far-reaching
impact on their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Engel sorts out clients' finances and determines how possessions
should be divvied up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times, women will want to keep the home,'' she said.
``Many will fight for it, but that can have a negative financial
impact later on. The courts are not required to consider the tax
ramifications associated with keeping a house. That means if the
couple bought a house together and it appreciated in value, but she
decides to sell, she will bear the sole burden of any capital gains
realized from the sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Ann Wilson, author of ``The Financial Advisor's Guide to
Divorce Settlement'' (Times Mirror, 1996), maintains that few
courts recognize the assets of a career as property and few women
realize that in a divorce property is divided only once, but assets
stemming from a husband's career continue to multiply and produce
income for years to come. These assets may include stock options,
pensions, health insurance, life insurance, disability insurance,
vacation pay, sick pay, and money spent on education and training.
</P>
<P>
   Engel agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women tend to fight for the wrong things,'' she said. ``So I
talk to them about their longer-range financial goals, and what it
will take to get there. The whole business of women being the
primary custodial parent and head of the household is still new.''
</P>
<P>
   For Adam Kornfeld, a Massachusetts salesman and divorced father
of a 4-year-old son, Jordan, a local organization for divorced
fathers helped him cope with his 1998 divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a devastating experience,'' said Kornfeld, who is in
his 30s. ``I was barely sleeping. I found it very, very hard to
concentrate. Sometimes I just wanted to retreat from the world, but
I could not. I couldn't as a parent, or as an employee.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornfeld credits a sound co-parenting arrangement with his
ex-wife, a job that permits him to telecommute full time, and a
group called Fathers and Families with helping him make the
transition. Now remarried, he sees his son on the days his former
wife works.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ned Holstein, a Brookline, Mass. medical doctor and founder
of Father and Families (617-357-4832), a nonprofit organization
with 1,400 dues-paying members, contends men are often the
unwitting victims of a court system that, more often than not,
considers them tangential to their children's lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers' lives after divorce are not cakewalks. But there
needs to be a new attitude that says that dad is also important to
the kids,'' he said. ``There should be more flexibility. Even the
terminology used in the courts is offensive. Dads, for example, are
considered visitors and are given visitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Holstein, who is also divorced, founded the organization two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court system considered me superfluous to my children's
well being,'' he said. ``A judge gave me and my ex-wife joint
physical custody and it has worked out. But this is done only 5
percent of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Next month, members will gather at the First Unitarian Society
to discuss the impact divorce has had on their personal and
professional lives. At past meetings, the men have talked about
depression so great they could barely do their jobs, about finding
ways to balance the demands of work with child custody
arrangements, about making support payments after a layoff,
demotion, or move to a lower-paying job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Divorced dads have many, many problems relative to the
workplace,'' said Holstein. ``Child support payments, for example,
may take up to 60 to 70 percent of what they earn. If anything goes
wrong and they are laid off or fired or a bonus doesn't come
through, they could wind up on the state registry for deadbeat
dads. Nobody tells them that they can go to court and modify their
child support order.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the chance to air their concerns at periodic
meetings, Fathers and Families members say their primary goal is to
change the way the court system views divorcing fathers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Additional resources
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --``Divorced Dads: Shattering the Myths,'' by Sanford L. Braver
($24.95, Tarcher-Putnam Books, New York).
</P>
<P>
   --``Divorce Help Sourcebook,'' by Margorie L. Engel ($17.95,
Visible Ink Press, Detroit).
</P>
<P>
   --The Fatherhood Project at the Families &AMP; Work Institute in New
York, headed by James Levine (212-465-8637). The institute conducts
research on parenting, state and federal funding for day care,
parental leave, and the concerns of divorced fathers, single
mothers, and dual earner couples.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Questions, comments, story ideas? Contact Diane E. Lewis at
work(at)globe.com, or 617-929-2069.)
</P>
</TEXT>
