<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8609 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-BOS &LR;      02-16 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONOMICAL SUMS FLOW TO START-UPS FRAUGHT WITH RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A billion dollars used to be a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   That was before this era of venture capital nirvana and
rocket-fueled technology stocks. Before it became a national
obsession to get in on a hot initial public offering. Before
investors forgot about that old wallflower, risk.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the amount of venture capital flowing to start-ups has
reached previously unthinkable levels. Venture capitalists are
raising billion-dollar funds in a few brisk months, sometimes
weeks. That helped make 1999 a year for the history books. Private
investors plowed $35.6 billion into 4,006 companies last year,
according to the latest Boston Globe/PricewaterhouseCoopers venture
capital report.
</P>
<P>
   Eager investors are happy to sign up. Perhaps too happy,
experienced venture investors concede.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are rumblings of worry bubbling to the surface of this
frothy market. Pension managers who invest in venture funds mutter
about 1929 and wonder aloud whether some venture portfolios, flush
with cash, are dropping their standards as they hunt for hot
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   These giant new funds are handing $15 million a pop to young
companies they would only have invested $5 million in a few years
ago. And they're giving the nod on those deals quicker than ever,
in days instead of months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is accelerated,'' said Kenneth Mabbs, director of
merchant banking for First Albany Corp. in Boston. ``There are
definitely going to be lots of blowups. I think you're already
seeing it on the `b-to-c' side.''
</P>
<P>
   The business-to-consumer Web firms that were all the rage last
year are ice cold today. Business-to-business is where the action
is, most venture players insist. And in this trend-conscious
market, betting on yesterday's story is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Take a glimpse at the performance of recent IPOs that tried to
defy the market's changed direction. There's Fogdog Inc., the
online sporting-goods retailer, whose shares have been flat since
their Dec. 8 debut. Health sites, from MotherNature.com and
Healthcentral.com to Plastic Surgery Co., have seen their shares
dive by double digits in two months, putting them among the worst
IPOs of December. New education sites have stumbled too.
</P>
<P>
   Venture professionals are warning that hawking vitamins, light
bulbs, or tennis rackets online might be short-term games. Broader
companies are more likely to thrive. And copycat businesses could
be big losers.
</P>
<P>
   Even as investors worry about the future, venture capitalists
are
</P>
<P>
   back on the street, raising brand-new, billion-dollar
portfolios. Polaris Venture Partners in Waltham recently raised
$800 million. CMGI Inc. in January launched two funds worth $1
billion each and is luring investors for a third. Highland Capital
just raised $500 million. And Thomas H. Lee Co., which invests in
more mature companies, is raising a fund that could reach $6
billion in just two months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UFBITE MUST DELETE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --New England entrepreneurs garnered nearly $1.6 billion in
venture capital investments in the 4th quarter. C15
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists say they're flooded with ideas from
entrepreneurs. Oliver Curme, a partner at Battery Ventures in
Wellesley, said the firm invests in one out of 300 deals that it
reviews. When it finds one that it wants, it has to move quickly.
But even deals he turns away are finding money elsewhere.
``Everything is getting funded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the whirlwind the fact that companies are going from seed
finance to venture funding to IPO faster than ever. The whole
process can zoom by in 18 months, instead of the four to five years
it took in the mid-1990s. It's easy to make costly mistakes when
things are moving so fast, investors say.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Flint, a partner with Polaris, recalls venture
investors piling into disk-drive makers in the 1980s. Only a couple
of manufacturers were winners, he said. A couple dozen others were
money losers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet once again, Flint said, ``You find less-experienced VCs
doing me-too companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the bad deals are getting done,'' he added. ``There's so
much angel money and uninformed corporate money.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, what makes a good deal is debatable. There are no
hard and fast rules. Most venture pros say they're looking for a
company with good managers and a promising market niche. But every
deal requires a leap of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Benjamin, the first West Coast partner with Boston's
Highland Capital Partners, scurried to get a deal done during his
first week on the job, last fall. Though he claims to be focused on
business-to-business and calls the consumer space ``more crowded,''
he jumped for a site that exudes consumer kitsch: TheMan.com.
</P>
<P>
   Highland ponied up $15 million to back the San Francisco-based
company, whose Web site offers men Valentine's Day shopping ideas
and advice on golf, Scotch, and cigars. There are sympathy stories
on baldness, a list of what makes for ``seduction dates,'' and
pithy tips on getting out of the doghouse _ like sending her to the
spa for a beauty day.
</P>
<P>
   TheMan.com is the antithesis to the guy sites that carry sports
scores and porn, Benjamin said. It's all about helping men solve
problems, book vacations, and purchase anything from lingerie to
jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that none of the women's sites is making money,
Benjamin said. This is the only site of its kind, explains
Benjamin, who sits on TheMan.com's board. He calls it a ``viral''
business that could spread fast by word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Benjamin boasts, TheMan.com got seed financing from
Lycos Inc. chief Bob Davis. It's run by another Lycos veteran,
Calvin Lui, and ex-Ernst &AMP; Young consultant Steven Lombardi. And if
there was any question about their devotion to their enterprise,
they've got fresh tattoos to prove it. They had TheMan.com's logo
etched on their ankles last week, as they vowed they would if their
engineers beat programming deadlines for the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   When might TheMan make money? ``I have no idea,'' Benjamin said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, turning profits is overrated in the Internet zone. As
long as investors will snap up money-losing companies in IPOs,
entrepreneurs face little pressure to produce black ink.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, profits do matter. Wall Street punishes
unprofitable companies. Venture capitalists, by law, have to wait
at least six months to sell their stakes in companies that go
public. But they can't just dump their shares after that because
that would prompt the stock price to fall. Since their exit isn't a
quick flip, they need their companies' stocks to have some staying
power.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin is about to make his fourth deal after reviewing more
than 100 prospects. In this market, it takes just one big success
to make up for several failures. Said Benjamin: ``It's by no means
over in terms of attractive opportunities. The hard part is having
the discipline to be picky.''
</P>
<P>
   Discipline is indeed the key. But with a billion-dollar fund
being born every other week, will all that money find wise deals?
</P>
<P>
   Pension funds, endowments, and wealthy individuals want entry to
the top venture funds while the going is good. No one wants to pass
up a chance to ride the next Amazon, eBay, or Akamai _ high-tech
companies that have rewarded early venture backers with
unfathomable riches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question they're taking on more
risk,'' said Patrick Gray, a partner in PricewaterhouseCoopers's
global technology group in Boston. ``But the opportunities for
rewards are also much bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Those tantalizing rewards are driving the astounding growth of
venture capital and private equity investments from Boston to
Silicon Valley. And it's making some forget the inherent risks of
investing in young, private companies.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the uninitiated are joining what was once the preserve
of elite investors. A professor makes a venture bet, risking a
significant sum in hopes of boosting a lackluster nest egg.
Inexperienced investors are becoming ``angels,'' making seed
investments in start-ups. A 22-year-old analyst lucks out and turns
a $15,000 bonus into more than $1 million in one deal.
</P>
<P>
   Observed First Albany's Mabbs: ``Everybody's a venture
capitalist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
