<HEADLINE>
VENTURE FUNDING SOARS TO $14.59B IN FOURTH QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Venture capital investments soared in the fourth quarter of 1999
as 1,271 companies nationwide landed $14.69 billion in funding _ a
fourfold gain over the last quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Software and Internet services for businesses led the way.
</P>
<P>
   New England entrepreneurs garnered nearly $1.6 billion, or 10.8
percent of the total, according to the latest Boston
Globe/PricewaterhouseCoopers Money Tree Survey. A record 169
companies received financing, making the region second only to
Silicon Valley, where 358 companies landed $5.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a sound business idea and you live in the New
England area, you can get money,'' said Patrick Gray, a partner at
PricewaterhouseCoopers in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For the full year, venture financings nationally broke every
record, jumping 150 percent to $35.6 billion. A total of 4,006
companies linked with investors, up from 2,849 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected 1999 to be big, but this figure surpassed even our
most aggressive estimates,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   New England ended the year with $4.1 billion worth of deals,
compared with Silicon Valley's $13.4 billion. The New York City
metropolitan area was third, with $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While New England's 104 percent gain in venture-capital deal
volume for the full year was significant, the region grew slower
than many others.
</P>
<P>
   New York raced ahead with 250 percent growth, the Northwest
gained 220 percent, the Los Angeles area surged 200 percent, and
Silicon Valley increased 195 percent. Even Colorado, the Southeast,
and the Washington, D.C., area grew faster than New England did.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, New England's share of the nation's venture money
came under pressure, slumping to 10.8 percent in last year's final
quarter, compared with 15.3 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Gray suggested that New England companies tend not to be part of
the biggest venture deals, which could affect the rankings. The
largest New England deal in the fourth quarter was HarvardNet Inc.,
which got $70 million for its networking and equipment operation.
Companies like CarsDirect.com and Colomotion Inc., both in
California, landed more than $200 million each.
</P>
<P>
   The second-biggest New England deal of the quarter was
InfoLibria Inc., a software maker that won $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Across all regions, early-stage companies attracted the biggest
share of the funding in 1999, seizing $15 billion, or 42 percent.
Each company received an average of $7.5 million, up from $4.2
million in 1998, as the size of the deals grew. Young Web firms
reaped bigger-than-average financing packages, averaging nearly $9
million each.
</P>
<P>
   Business services, new media and retail/distribution were the
fastest-growing sectors for the year; software and
telecommunications grabbed most of the cash.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in five years, investments in nontechnology
companies declined. Internet-related investments have surged,
however. In New England, such deals represented 63.2 percent of
dollars invested in the latest quarter, up from 3.7 percent in
early 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet-related companies,'' Gray said, ``offer so much
potential so quickly that they now attract the lion's share of the
investing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8621 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ORGANOGENESIS-GROWTH-     02-16 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGANOGENESIS-GROWTH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PROFIT ELUDES ORGANOGENESIS, BUT CEO HAS BIG PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Mass. _ Philip Laughlin remembers the reaction when he
told his 9-year-old son his new job is leading a company that makes
human skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me and said, `You mean like `The Blob' _ it's
alive!' '' recalled Laughlin.
</P>
<P>
   But explaining to a child how laboratory-grown skin can help
heal certain wounds is easy, compared to convincing Wall Street the
product can be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Laughlin, 53, is the new president and chief executive of
Organogenesis Inc., a 15-year-old company that in 1998 beat the
naysayers and gained US Food and Drug Administration approval to
market the first lab-grown human skin equivalent. The pieces of
skin are cultivated from cells donated from infant males'
circumcisions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its rivals, which are developing products with cells from
pigs and cows, Organogenesis is the only company with FDA approval
for a full-thickness human skin substitute. The ability to
cultivate a skin replacement opens a new chapter in the emerging
field of tissue engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Organogenesis's product, called Apligraf, is used for treating
venous ulcers, which are leg wounds caused by ruptured blood
vessels. About 800,000 people, many of them elderly, suffer from
the open wounds.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly 22 months after FDA approval, Organogenesis has not
met many of its own ambitious expectations. After years of ups and
downs, the company has attracted a top-name pharmaceutical company,
Novartis, to market its product and is starting to show signs of
real growth. But Wall Street expects profits are still two years
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a new pill, a drug maker gets into the marketplace
quickly. But the learning curve to educate doctors about a new
medical device, like skin (replacements) _ something they have not
seen before _ takes time. And that took longer than Organogenesis
expected,'' said Michael D. Becker, an analyst at Wayne Hummer
Investments in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there are no signs of profitability, and 1999 revenues
was far below initial expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Organogenesis stock, which once commanded $35 a share, has
recovered somewhat from a low of 6 3/4 in October. It closed
Tuesday at 10 7/8, up 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Laughlin comes in. In October, he became the
company's third president in just nine years. He added the chief
executive post in December. Since Laughlin has 23 years of
marketing and sales experience in the medical device industry _
four years at Medtronic Inc., a developer of medical stents, and 19
years at Baxter International, a health care products giant _
investors are looking to him to finally bring stability and
leadership experience to a company with a turbulent history.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, the company was run by Herbert M. Stein, 72,
the mercurial chairman who co-founded it in 1985 with Eugene Bell,
a professor of biology at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, who several years earlier grew a living skin equivalent
in his laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The skin was originally called Graftskin and subsequently
renamed Apligraf. Starting with cells from a single foreskin,
Organogenesis can grow more than 100,000 three-inch round pieces of
skin in large petri-like dishes containing nutrients. Each
stretchable piece of skin costs $975. (Foreskins are donated to
Organogenesis by families with circumcised baby boys; the company
never pays for foreskins because federal law prohibits the sale of
body parts.)
</P>
<P>
   The production process requires separating different types of
cells from the foreskin and growing them over 20 days to create a
full thickness skin. Since Apligraf is a living product, the
company says, it can heal itself when cut and over time its color
adjusts to the pigment of the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Under Stein, Organogenesis scrambled for money, raising $7.2
million in its initial public offering in 1986 followed by a series
of warrant exercises, private placements and public secondary stock
offerings that brought in over $103 million. Over the years, the
company has had a 2-for-1 stock split and four 5-for-4 stock
splits.
</P>
<P>
   Stein shunned investment bankers and few Wall Street analysts
followed the company. He rarely talked to the press and Wall Street
analysts, and his management style led to a revolving door in the
executive suite, according to former executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stein kept Organogenesis going during the lean years, but he
also was difficult to get along with and never felt comfortable
speaking to groups of people,'' said one former executive. ``I
moved on because I was not entirely comfortable with his approach
to things.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last year Stein, with an eye toward retirement, hired
Laughlin as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Without Stein, Laughlin has more lattitude to make changes,
which he says boil down to solving four fundamental problems:
convincing Medicare to reimburse patients for the $975 cost of
Apligraf; expanding Apligraf usage into new markets, such as
diabetic foot ulcers; creating a pipeline of skin and non-skin
products; and reducing manufacturing costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't view Organogenesis as broken,'' said Laughlin who ran
the cardiac surgery business unit at Medtronic, where he was a
senior vice president. ``It is just going through a maturation and
transformation stage, from research and development to a
multi-functional commercial company.''
</P>
<P>
   The steps Laughlin makes may also boost the company's stock
price and reduce the company's unusually high number of shares tied
to short sellers _ investors who borrow shares and sell them,
hoping to replace the shares at a lower price. Heavy short selling
in a stock can be an indication that investors think it is
overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Organogenesis has in recent years been a heavily shorted stock.
Even now, short sellers still control 5.62 million shares _ about
18 percent of the company's 30.5 million outstanding shares.
</P>
<P>
   Some early investors in Organogensis were burned when the
company, under Stein, made provocative statements about how quickly
it would get FDA approval and become a leader in the $10 billion-a
year-market for wound healing devices. The overly optimistic
predictions led to accusations from some investors in the mid-1990s
that company may have manipulated the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Sturza, who edits an influential medical investment
newsletter and remains one of Organogenesis's most ardent critics,
said this week that the company's clinical trial was flawed. He had
predicted in 1997 that the FDA would not approve Organogenesis's
product.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months after his prediction, the FDA approved Apligraf for
use in treating venous ulcers and early last year Business Week
magazine cited Apligraf as one of the 10 best new products for
1998, proclaiming ``a new era in regenerative medicine has
arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Sturza earlier this week said he was surprised that
Organogenesis received FDA approval, but warned that the company
will have a tough time making a profit with it under its marketing
agreement with Novartis. The pact, he said, favors the big drug
maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Herb Stein gone, that is a real positive and the new guy
(Laughlin) is very credible,'' said Sturza. ``But Organogenesis's
sales, after all these years, is still laughable and we don't see
any profits any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some Wall Street firms had expectations in 1997 that the
company would report 1999 revenues of $10 million to $33.5 million.
The reality is that Organogenesis lost $20 million, or 66 cents a
share, on revenues of $2.6, for the first nine months of last year.
Of that, $1.8 million was from Apligraf.
</P>
<P>
   Laughlin maintains there is an upside. He acknowledged that
Novartis, after nearly a year, is just beginning to seriously
market the product with a 50-person sales force. The huge
pharmaceutical company is also is working on gaining Medicare
coverage for Apligraf. Currently, some physicans simply won't use
Apligraf because some venous ulcer patients lack the insurance
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   He also expects to gain a second FDA approval this year for use
of Apligraf on diabetic foot ulcers _ a potential market of 600,000
potential customers who could theoretically avoid foot amputations.
Organogenesis is also developing a replacement vein for patients
undergoing cardiac surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has made the dream-to-reality transition,'' noted
Michael Ehrenreich, a health care and biotechnology analyst at
Techvest LLC, a New York investment firm. ``It's time to take a
second look at Organogenesis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
