<HEADLINE>
CAN I AFFORD TO RETIRE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am divorced and hope to retire very soon, but I question
whether I can afford to. I keep hesitating _ all of my aunts have
lived into their mid-90s and one is 103 years old now. I can retire
now with a $2,500 monthly pension, for which a cost-of-living
adjustment is not guaranteed, but which has recently been increased
at a rate of about 3 percent a year. The values of my holdings in
this list are as of the end of 1999. Social Security will kick in
at age 62 or later. Is it better to take it early? I own my own
home outright but will probably move to a condo, which will cost
about $50,000 more than the value of my home. I think I should also
have long-term health insurance. Can I afford to retire?
</P>
<P>
   G.M., Signal Mountain, Tenn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The big question here is how much money you think you will
need in retirement. If you can get by on about $45,000 a year for
the next five to eight years, you should be in pretty good shape.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the way I view it. Your total savings of $538,900
consists of about 72.7 percent fixed-income holdings; although you
have a lot of funds and they are fairly nicely diversified, the
portfolio is overwhelmed by the three largest holdings _ the CDs,
the money market account, and the fixed-income annuity. Given your
happy expectation that your retirement might last 40 years or so, I
think that position is too conservative.
</P>
<P>
   The most spectacular loafer in your portfolio is that $100,000
in a bank money market account, which is probably paying you only a
little more than about 2 percent; the national average for these
accounts was 2.10 percent entering this week. Many mutual fund
money market funds now pay in excess of 5 percent, and they offer
check-writing privileges that give you nearly the same liquidity as
banks offer.
</P>
<P>
   I would move half of this money _ the funds that might
eventually be used for your condo purchase _ to such a fund. I
suggest you then move the rest of the money into a solid balanced
fund _ perhaps adding to your position in Fidelity Puritan, or
perhaps going to Vanguard Balanced Index fund. (I am making this
suggestion based on the very conservative nature of your
investments; if it were my portfolio I would make the swap to
Magellan or Index 500. But I am loath to push people with very
conservative holdings to a risk level that may be uncomfortable for
them.)
</P>
<P>
   Those moves would leave you with $50,000 for your real estate
purchase, and the $270,000 in CDs and the annuity should be able to
supply you with an income stream of about $15,000 to augment your
pension income. If you feel you can live on that, retirement should
be no problem. I would have the returns from all of your other
holdings reinvested.
</P>
<P>
   The question of when to take Social Security remains. Certainly
with the prospect of living to a very old age, you probably would
profit by waiting until age 65 or later to begin collecting
benefits. Once you do begin to collect Social Security, you should
have to rely only to a small degree upon your fixed-income
investments. At that stage, you might need to use only about a
third of the fixed-income yield for living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   So, I suggest the remainder of the yield from the fixed-income
side of the portfolio be diverted to additional purchases on the
stock side _ enhancing the growth prospects of the part of the
portfolio which you will rely on to protect you against the
long-term effects of inflation. You don't need to make a final
decision on Social Security now _ you can review your overall
situation once you reach age 62, and if you decide to wait until
age 65, you can then review how things are going and decide then
whether to wait still further.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We have the savings described in the enclosed statement in
the bank. What bothers us are the following statements on the form:
Not FDIC Insured; May Lose Value; No Bank Guarantee. With all these
banks changing names one doesn't know which end is up. Could you
let us know what you think?
</P>
<P>
   C.M., Chula Vista, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. What you have is an investment in a mutual fund that invests
in long-term California municipal bonds _ issues that provide you
with an income that is free of both federal and state taxes. This
is very different from bank savings, for all of the reasons you
noted. Your money has been pooled with that of other investors to
buy these government-issued bonds, and the value of your principal
rises or falls as the long-term bond market rises or falls.
Recently its mostly been the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Note on your statement that for the period in question, your
investment brought you interest income of $65.31, but despite this
the total value of your account fell by nearly $123. That was
because of interest rate increases, and fears of more to come.
Morningstar Mutual Funds, a company that tracks the performance of
most mutual funds, grades your fund average overall. Last year the
fund lost 3.7 percent, which was a better performance than most
funds which have similar investments, but is still doubtless
frustrating to its owners. As this is written, the fund has gained
.43 percent in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   I feel a rant coming on. Clearly you did not understand where
you were putting your money and the fact that it was invested in
securities that could bring you losses as well as the potential for
gains. In my experience, it is most common that people who are
almost totally in the dark about where they have invested their
money are people who have bought mutual funds through a bank. As
you apparently did, many assume that since the bank was offering
the investment, it has the same kind of security that most people
associate with bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what to tell you about what to do at this point.
The fund has a 4.75 percent up-front sales charge, meaning that if
you began with $16,000, $760 of the money immediately disappeared
through the sales charge. If you were to close the account, that
money would have gone for nothing. People who have substantial
levels of income are often attracted to municipal bond funds
because of the tax-exempt nature of the yield, and such funds tend
to work nicely for people who take a very long-range view of the
investment. But if you have a fairly modest income level, you
probably would be better off with taxable _ and insured _
investments, such as CDs.
</P>
<P>
   If you are uncomfortable with the risk element inherent in this
holding, I suggest you get out. First I would make an effort, which
will probably be unsuccessful, to get the bank to acknowledge its
failure to assure that you understood what you were buying, and to
reverse the transaction. Most likely, though, you signed a document
saying that you did understand the nature of the investment, and
the bank will be covered legally, although from my point of view,
not morally. So if you want to get out of the investment, you
probably will have to chalk the misadventure up to experience. And
you can remember the experience by recalling what I consider the
number-one rule of investing: Never buy anything that you don't
fully understand. And this applies as much if you are buying it
from a banker as a snake-oil salesman. End of rant.
</P>
<P>
   One final point: If you look carefully at the statement, you'll
see that although $328.95 of the income you received from the fund
last year was tax-free, the fund also produced a long-term capital
gain of $46.70 for you. This came from profitable sales of holdings
within the portfolio, and you must report this amount as taxable
income on your state and federal tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money Musings: Can a fund family get hot? Especially in a fairly
frigid climate? While I was scanning the Sunday paper, I noted that
of the nation's most popular mutual funds, only three of them were
in the black _ and all were offerings from the Janus fund family.
Checking the entire list of Janus 30 funds, only two of them _ the
Janus Aspen Flexible Income and Janus Flexible Income _ showed
year-to-date losses, and those were small, 0.1 percent and 0.2
percent, respectively. Janus Twenty showed no gain and no loss. The
rest of the Janus funds were all in the black. The national average
for domestic general stock fund performance this year is a 2.4
percent loss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
