<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8623 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-16 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFSIDE RACES INTO DERBY PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kentucky Derby picture is slowly coming into focus, and, at
this early stage, a filly has assumed the leading role. While a
number of prominent 3-year-old colts are struggling to get their
acts together, Surfside is already taking bows. On Saturday, the
superbly bred daughter of Triple Crown winner Seattle Slew and
2-year-old champion Flanders, captured the $200,000 Las Virgenes at
Santa Anita, marking her third straight victory, and second of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Surfside is a homebred of Overbook Farm, and she is a serious
racehorse. Trainer D. Wayne Lukas, who saddled last year's Derby
winner, Charismatic, and also trained Winning Colors, the last
filly to win the Run for the Roses (1988), has said from the
beginning of the year that he is pointing Surfside toward the May 6
Derby. Usually, trainers with top fillies wait to assess the
strength of the male contingent before choosing between the Derby
or the Oaks, which is exclusively for fillies, on the previous day.
However, with Surfside, Lukas has never considered the Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   The attractive bay now sports a mark of 8-6-1-1 and earnings of
$860,230. The two times she was defeated (second in the Spinaway at
Saratoga last August and third in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile
Fillies at Gulfstream in November), she was trapped wide. Her
record is so strong that only three foes could be found for Las
Virgenes. Bob Baffert, who trains 2-year-old filly champion
Chilukki, was so impressed with Surfside that he shipped Chilukki
to California to make her sophomore debut Saturday in the $125,000
Davona Dale at Fair Grounds in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Surfside won the Frizette at Belmont in October over a sloppy
track, but Las Virgenes, raced at one mile, provided her with her
first challenge from a track officially labeled as ``muddy.''
Spain, a nice filly who had earned a check in three straight
stakes, gave Surfside a good go, but the Lukas charge proved too
tough, winning by three-querters of a length. Rings A Chime was
another half-length back in third. Off at 1-5, ($2.40 to win),
Surfside covered the mile in 1:37.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got to the turn, she started fighting the racetrack,
and just wasn't comfortable,'' said Pat Day, who has ridden
Surfside in all of her races, and will ride her in the Derby if she
stays healthy. ``Then they came at her from both sides, and, when
she was in close proximity, she was very game. I think she was just
hesitant to really put her all into it because of the footing.''
</P>
<P>
   While the trainers of several of the talented colts are either
trying to get their horses healthy, or find the right spot for a
major Derby prep, Lukas has his schedule all laid out. ``It helps
that she got looked in the eye,'' said Lukas. ``You know, she's
gotten a little complacent. I was not concerned that anyone would
get by her in the stretch. Now, we've got another month until the
next one, the Santa Anita Oaks March 12, and then we'll get another
month before the Santa Anita Derby April 8. I would imagine we'll
have to reach down a bit more these next two races, and we'll wake
her up for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a man with a plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's mutuel
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The odds for the first Kentucky Derby Future Wager, which begins
Thursday and runs through Sunday, have been posted, with Churchill
Downs linemaker Mike Battaglia installing the mutuel field as the
favorite at 5-1. Charismatic came out of the field last year.
Surfside, the only female on the list, which includes 23
individuals plus a field composed of all others, and War Chant,
impressive winner of two races at Santa Anita, are next at 8-1.
Captain Steve and The Deputy are at 10-1, while Anees, Chief
Seattle, Dixie Union, Greenwood Lake, High Yield, and More Than
Ready are all at 15-1. Fusaichi Pegasus and Red Bullet are the
longest shots on the list at 50-1. The individuals listed are
chosen by Daily Racing From handicappers Mike Watchmaker and Brad
Free, and John Asher, vice president of racing communications at
Churchill Downs. ``It's the same situation as last year, when I
made the mutuel field the favorite for pool No. 1,'' said
Battaglia. ``This year, I made the field 5-1, but it will probably
close at shorter odds than that. I really mulled it over because
this is such a wide open group of horses, but 5-1 seemed fair.''
The Future Wager calls for win betting only, and the key thing to
remember about an advance bet is that there are no refunds. You
lose if your horse does not make the race for whatever reason.
Because of the racing statutes in Massachusetts, Suffolk Downs can
not offer the bet. It is, however, available at Rockingham Park in
New Hampshire. The bet will go through two more cycles, with
changing odds and horses: Round 2 from March 9-12 and Round 3 from
April 13-16 . . . Anees, the 2-year-old champion and winner of the
Breeders' Cup Juvenile, has yet to start. The son of Unbridled has
been battling a foot bruise, and he had his first workout of the
season Sunday at Santa Anita, going a half in :50 over the muddy
surface. Anees may nake his 3-year-old bow in the San Felipe March
19 . . . Greenwood Lake, who won the Champagne at Belmont and
Remsen at Aqueduct last year, worked five furlongs in :59 3/5 last
Saturday at Hialeah as he prepares for this Saturday's $200,000
Fountain of Youth at Gulfstream. The Fountain of Youth, run at a
mile and 1-16th, is the first Grade I event of the season for
3-year-olds in the East. Greenwood Lake, who is a deep closer,
caught a speed-favoring track in the Holy Bull at Gulfstream Jan.
15, and could do no better than sixth. ``I couldn't ask for
anything better,'' said trainer Nick Zito of the work. ``All I can
hope for now is a good trip Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lambana resting
</P>
<P>
   Lambana, who was named New England Horse of the Year for 1999 by
the local turf writers, was recently named Claimer of the Year by
the National Horsemen's Benevolent and Protective Association.
Lambana was claimed at Tampa Bay Downs in January for $6,250 by
trainer Marshall Novak, and won nine of 11 starts, including three
stakes on the turf at Rockingham, with earnings of $132,017. After
being switched to the grass, Lambana, then age 5, ended her season
with six straight tallies. At the New England Turf Writers' Dinner
in November, Novak, who owns the mare along with his wife, Suzanne,
and partner Gary Jackson, said he may not bring Lambana, who is
wintering on Novak's farm in Tampa, back to the races until Rock
reopens in June. ``She loves that course,'' he said. ``I think,
maybe, I'll just wait.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks, the
Thoroughbred Times, and the Daily Racing Form was used to prepare
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
