<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8626 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-16 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKWELL'S AND SCHULZ'S GIFTS TO CIVIL RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Schulz did not really have to insert the character
Franklin into Peanuts in 1968 to ensure his legacy, any more than
Norman Rockwell was obliged to publish ``The Problem We All Live
With'' in 1963. Schulz would still be remembered as a cartoonist of
everyday insecurities and Rockwell a painter of everyday interludes
and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   What is striking about Schulz, who died last weekend, and the
late Rockwell, whose magazine art is on a national tour, is that
they were white shapers of American culture who grew to see a
nation beyond blond and red hair, blue eyes, ruddy cheeks, and
all-white scenes at diners, ballfields, and neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   This is a live issue in the year 2000, given last fall's nearly
all-white lineup of new television sitcoms. It is a live issue
since most of these shows on the foibles and fantasies of white
people are situated in cities that have a majority of people of
color. Seeing how hard it remains for today's white shapers of
culture to acknowledge the very existence of black people, it is
arguable that Schulz and Rockwell are unfortunately still ahead of
their time, even though they are dead.
</P>
<P>
   It did not matter that Schulz's art was the attempt to capture
character in simple forms of caricature. It did not matter that
Franklin was not a major figure in the Peanuts universe and, of
course, a token. What mattered was existence.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin came into the comic strip long after I grew out of it,
but I still noticed that he was dignified, smart, with a sense of
history passed on to him by his grandfather. In earlier times,
Franklin would have been a Pigpen, the dirtiest figure in the
strip. That Franklin was not Pigpen, given the ``Buckwheatization''
of black children, this was a victory.
</P>
<P>
   When he was alive, Rockwell suffered from barbs that his
attempts to capture America's character were too much like
caricature, so much so that he is absent from most ``serious''
books on American art. In the passing of time, one can much more
appreciate Rockwell's character. Few living artists can go from
Gary Cooper to Rosie the Riveter or from white boys being caught at
an illegal swimming hole to the portrait of many of the world's
ethnicities in the ``Golden Rule.''
</P>
<P>
   This might not seem a great leap if one knows that Rockwell was
interested in civil rights and lent his voice to efforts to
integrate a sorority in the 1940s at the University of Vermont. But
through the 1950s he was given clear rules for his magazine covers.
Rockwell said the editor of the Saturday Evening Post told him to
``never to show colored people except as servants.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1960s gave Rockwell the freedom to break the rules and put
``Golden Rule'' in the Post in 1961. He was then moved by the
attempt in 1960 by African-American first grader Ruby Bridges to
integrate a New Orleans elementary school. His painting of a little
black girl, being escorted by four white federal marshals past
thrown tomatoes and ``nigger'' graffiti, was the centerfold of an
edition of Look in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   This was ``The Problem We All Live With.'' When Ruby Bridges was
asked back then by Harvard University's Robert Coles about the
painting, Bridges said, ``I sure wish I could draw the way he does!
He's got it down, what's happening.'' Rockwell's painting was one
of the few media images of that time where the focus was truly on
her as a person and not the angry mobs heckling her. Bridges told
Coles, ``That picture is about me, I guess _ and what you see in
the news is about the trouble on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles, then an Air Force psychiatrist, also interviewed one of
the white parents who protested integration. After seeing
Rockwell's painting, the white father, whose daughter would have
been in Ruby's class, said, ``That magazine tells you to `look,'
and I sure did; I thought `There she is, the nigra kid.' You look
at her and you begin to feel sorry for her _ a lot of people will,
I'm sure. It's not her we were against, you know. It's the
interference in our life by those folks up North, that's what it
was, that's what we were saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles said this was a dramatic shift for someone who routinely
called Ruby a ``nigger.'' Coles wrote in ``Norman Rockwell,
Pictures for the American People,'' that the white parent ``was now
(as never before the case) letting Ruby herself off the hook,
directing his considerable ire at his nation's political life, at a
region rather than a person. I couldn't help but feel that a
magazine's picture had somehow touched his heart, had given him
some psychological if not moral pause.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why a pause is deserved for Schulz and Rockwell. They
were gifted white men who could have very easily contained their
art in whiter, more serene worlds and still achieve fame (Rockwell
would go on to depict the murder of civil rights workers). Their
cracking of the cocoon is a lesson for today's shapers of American
culture, particularly those on network television. Today's
television moguls do not yet understand what Schulz and Rockwell
realized a long time ago. We all have problems, foibles, and
fantasies that we all live with.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
