<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ELECTIONS-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 PART I: IRAN'S NEW REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;    Editors: When Iranians go to the polls Feb. 18, the fate of
President Khatami's efforts at reform will be put to the test. Will
the country embrace political and social change or will Islamic
hard-liners prevail?
 &HT;    To bolster your coverage of the election _ as well as the 21st
anniversary of the Iranian revolution _ we recommend this excellent
two-part series, which has moved over the wire in the ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news category codes: By ROBIN WRIGHT  
 c.2000 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Iran, one might say that the government of God has plummeted
back to earth _ with a thud. The country's increasingly savvy
population is taking stands on social issues, making demands and
defying the theocrats. Even clerics who have held high office and
intellectuals who were proteges of the Ayatollah Khomeini are now
challenging the religion's basic precepts as well as the specifics
of strict Islamic rule. Gradually, the government of God is being
forced to cede to secular statecraft _ and to empower Iranians.
(slugged: BC-IRAN-PEOPLE-POWER-NYTSF) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PART II: FROM UNDER THE CHADOR &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; By ROBIN WRIGHT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c.2000 Foreign Affairs Magazine &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Iranian women are by far the most politically active in the
Persian Gulf and are among the most empowered in the Islamic world.
In defiance of the theocracy, Iranian women are proving
irrepressible. Beginning in the mid-1990s, pressure from women
changed laws on employment, divorce and maternity leave. Women have
challenged other male bastions as well. Thousands of women broke a
long-time ban on attending male sporting events when they poured
into Tehran's stadium to greet the Iranian soccer team after it
qualified for the 1998 World Cup. (slugged:
BC-IRAN-WOMEN-REVOLUTION-NYTSF) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ..................................................
</P>
