<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8630 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WELCOMING-KISS-BOS &LR;      02-16 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELCOMING-KISS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO DO WHEN A HANDSHAKE ISN'T ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The handshake is losing its grip as the all-purpose American
greeting. And in its place, there's a lot more kissing and hugging
going on.
</P>
<P>
   Someone might kiss your right cheek, or maybe just the air
around it. He or she could offer one kiss, or maybe even three, on
alternating cheeks. (If you don't turn your face, you may
accidentally wind up with a big wet kiss on the lips.) And if you
don't offer your hand quickly, someone might lean over and give you
a hearty embrace.
</P>
<P>
   While fear of sexual harassment complaints have made people more
restrained in the workplace, Americans are actually far more
relaxed in their greetings with friends, colleagues _ and even
strangers _ than ever before, say sociologists and historians who
track American customs.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly exposed to the more familiar greeting styles of
those in other countries _ either from traveling abroad or
observing immigrants here _ once-uptight Americans are loosening
up.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was shocked to see Steve Case, chairman of America
Online, and Gerald Levin, chairman of Time Warner, locked in a full
embrace last month when announcing their momentous merger. And
people have long become accustomed to President Clinton hugging on
all occasions, momentous or not. (At the other extreme, developer
Donald Trump hates hand-shaking, calling it a ``barbaric'' practice
that spreads germs.) Without a monolithic manners book, it's a
confusing world out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I put my hand out to shake a client's hand, and they
say, `Are you kidding?!' and they give me a hug. But it's a very
light hug,'' said Alicia Calascibetta, 26, a sales representative
on her way to a meeting in Boston last week.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, nobody wants to come off as staid, even in New
England. But does a hug require full-frontal contact? And how much
eye contact should there be? In the absence of
one-gesture-fits-all, people are trying out different salutations.
</P>
<P>
   James Bratton, 33, managing director of the Boston office of
Dominion Ventures, a venture capital firm, said he often adds a
strong pat on the shoulder along with a handshake to signal special
warmth to a client or colleague he likes. In social settings, he
practices what appears to be a new standard: A man gives a woman he
knows a light kiss during hellos and goodbyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A simple handshake sometimes seems aloof or distant,'' said
Bratton. ``If it's someone I've worked with for awhile, our
relationship seems like it deserves more than a simple handshake. I
want to communicate that I like the person.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some young adults, influenced by the gestures of
popular American black athletes, favor ``the pound'' (giving each
other two or three knocks with closed fists) and even chest-bumping
hugs.
</P>
<P>
   The best part about this, say etiquette watchers, is that
Americans are more aware of the pluralistic world in which they
live, and are less likely to take offense at those who want to
reach out and touch them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Etiquette standards have not dropped, they've adapted,'' said
Terri Morrison, co-author of the book, ``Kiss, Bow, or Shake
Hands,'' which explains social customs across the world. ``We're
much more open to different styles.''
</P>
<P>
   Some sociologists say they are also pleased that Americans are
better able to differentiate between affectionate and sexual
touching. It's something some other cultures, such as those in
Latin America, have been able to do for some time, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have a Puritanical heritage,'' noted David Karp, a
professor of sociology at Boston College. ``In the American mind,
you couldn't separate touching from sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the easing of some restrictions, hugging and kissing
between men is still much more rare than between men and women, or
women and women.
</P>
<P>
   If you care to follow the rules of etiquette consultants, which
are a traditional lot by nature, they say it's important to
consider a number of factors. In general, men should defer to
women, younger people to older people, work subordinates to
superiors, and foreigners to native citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say err on the side of formality,'' said Rosanne Thomas,
who works for Protocol Advisers in Boston, an etiquette consulting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   When dealing with people who are devoutly religious, say
experts, one should respect their customs, particularly when
touching someone of the opposite sex. Muslim men, for example, are
generally not comfortable touching a woman in a greeting.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the handshake originated as a way for our
primitive ancestors to reassure one another that nobody was armed.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists and historians trace the decline of the handshake
and America's relaxation with physical touching to the 1960s, when
the youth culture promoted informality and intimacy. It gained
momentum, they say, during the 1970s and 1980s, when things foreign
gained cachet.
</P>
<P>
   America's changing styles are evident in the classes at the
International Institute of Boston. At this nonprofit organization
that helps the city's new immigrants adjust to life in this
country, instructors taught only the handshake as the generic
greeting 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although they still emphasize the handshake in business
settings, instructors now demonstrate other greetings, mostly for
social situations, such as the light kiss or a brief hug, said
Marcia Chaffee, coordinator of adult education.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell them what is allowable here,'' Chaffee said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's always important to read body language cues.
</P>
<P>
   ``With some folks, you still shake hands,'' said Gil Van Geyte,
50, New England manager for Haworth Inc., an office furniture
manufacturer. ``With others, a hug is appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone likes this trend. Some etiquette experts see
tactile friendliness as pretentious Euro-philia or phony intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People assume too much,'' said Ann Nicol, who runs an
etiquette consulting business in Glen Ridge, N.J. ``Just because we
had dinner and a good conversation, that doesn't mean you have the
right to give me a kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph Boskin, professor of American history at Boston
University, said he likes the growing trend toward more physical
touching in greetings. A self-described hugger, he said it meets a
basic human and animalistic desire for closeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more natural for people to touch each other than not
to,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
