<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8631 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-IRAN-PEOPLE-POWER-NYT     02-16 1731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-PEOPLE-POWER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S NEW REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This is Part I of a two-part series on contemporary Iran by
Robin Wright, a veteran Middle East correspondent. Part II is
slugged: BC-IRAN-WOMEN-REVOLUTION. For rates, please contact one of
these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By ROBIN WRIGHT  
 c.2000 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   A generation after it seized power, Iran's revolutionary regime
is deeply troubled.
</P>
<P>
   It is fractured by intense political divisions, endangered by
economic disorder, discredited by rampant corruption and smothered
in social restrictions no longer acceptable to large sectors of the
changing population.
</P>
<P>
   To the outside world, the Islamic Republic of Iran often appears
to be at a precipice, its unique theocratic government on the verge
of imploding from internal tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year its domestic drama has played out visibly,
and sometimes violently, in killings by a rogue death squad,
newspaper closures, student unrest, political trials and, as
always, uneasy relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Iran, often in spite of the theocrats, has begun to achieve
one of the revolution's original goals: empowering the people. For
new social and political movements are blossoming defiantly,
ranging from religious reform and cultural expression to women's
rights.
</P>
<P>
   True, the theocratic regime that seized power in 1979 is
unlikely to survive in its current, austere form because of
profound internal problems. Yet the driving force behind the
revolution has proven adaptable enough to allow Iranians to get for
themselves what the theocracy has failed to provide. Iran's
increasingly savvy population is taking stands on social issues,
making demands and even defying the theocrats.
</P>
<P>
   _ The First Republic (1979-1989). Iran's revolution was about
more than getting rid of an unpopular leader. After the shah's
ouster, the coterie around Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini gradually
crafted a theocracy instead of a democracy. Human rights were
virtually ignored during the decade-long ``First Republic,'' which
lasted from 1979 until Khomeini's death in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The regime's zealots became obsessed with deconstructing the
past and winning converts to their cause, both at home and in the
region. The new state survived only by crushing dissent, spending
its foreign exchange reserves and tapping into fierce, age-old
Persian nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, seeds of public empowerment were planted and grew.
The ``construction jihad'' _ carried out by teams of development
experts and builders _ brought progress in the form of new schools,
social services, clinics, electricity, television and roads to the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   The revolution particularly excelled in education, in quantity
if not always in quality.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, only half of Iran's youth between the ages of
six and 24 were literate. Two decades later, the number had grown
to 93 percent _ even though the population had doubled. And
students remained in school longer: The number of university
graduates soared from 430,000 in the late 1970s to more than 4
million in the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   This success spurred people's expectations of a greater role in
the system and access to new instruments of progress.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Second Republic (1989-1997). During President Hashemi
Rafsanjani's tenure, Iran graduated to realistically dealing with
the present. One might say that the government of God plummeted
back to earth _ with a thud.
</P>
<P>
   The new leadership initially promoted physical reconstruction of
the nation, economic reform and a diplomatic thaw. But without the
Ayatollah's authority, longstanding political divisions deepened
and paralysis set in.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a brief try at privatization, including reviving the
monarchy's stock market, the promise of change remained largely
unfulfilled. In the end, the regime's blatantly manipulative
tactics kept it from achieving its goals, instead spawning
corruption, deepening debt and social turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, the very policies that Rafsanjani introduced to
win back the support of a war-weary public inadvertently
jump-started the process of the people's empowerment. The regime
sporadically tolerated cultural freedoms and relaxed some of its
social restrictions. It also facilitated a consumer spending spree
on imports by making credit available.
</P>
<P>
   The outside world soon flooded back in, through satellite
dishes, videos, computers and textbooks full of ideas. From that
point on, the tide of information could no longer be controlled,
regardless how hard Iranian conservatives and clerics tried.
</P>
<P>
   The Second Republic also overlapped with the end of the Cold
War, which Iranians felt deeply because of their shared border with
the Soviet Union. The collapse of Soviet rule _ in a country with
superpower resources _ sent a powerful warning about the
vulnerability of revolutionary regimes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Iran's upheaval was part of global change, including the
demise of communism in Europe, white rule in Africa and military
dictatorships in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's theocracy came to recognize that it was endangering its
own agenda by ignoring the state's real problems _ for example, its
``population policy.'' In the 1980s, millions of women had obeyed
the theocrats' dictate to breed a new Islamic generation that would
defend the revolution. In seven years Iran's population jumped from
34 million to more than 50 million; it is now 70 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the clerics soon realized that soaring population numbers
were more likely to undo the revolution than to save it. So they
introduced one of the world's most extensive family-planning
programs. Every form of birth control, from condoms and pills to
sterilization, became free.
</P>
<P>
   Today all couples have to undergo and pass a family-planning
course before obtaining a marriage license. Thousands of women
mobilized by the Health Ministry have gone door-to-door to explain
the necessity of birth control. Clerics, preaching the benefits of
small family size, have issued decrees approving everything from
intrauterine devices to vasectomies.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Third Republic (1997 to present). In the 1997 presidential
election, which had the highest turnout since the Iranian people
endorsed revolution, 70 percent of Iran's voters spurned the
theocrats' candidate of choice. Instead they elected a dark-horse
cleric named Mohammad Khatami, a former minister of culture and
Islamic guide who was purged in 1992 for ``liberalism'' and
''negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   The election marked the burgeoning of what is by now a very
public fight for empowerment. The outcome of the Iranian elections
will at least partly reflect the degree of Khatami's success in
restoring the rule of law, fostering a civil society (two of his
campaign pledges), and wresting power from the religious
superstructure _ the theocratic part of Iran's system _ that limits
the government's powers.
</P>
<P>
   But more likely, Iran's future will be decided by the newly
energized popular forces that made Khatami's election possible in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Even clerics who have held high office and intellectuals who
were proteges of the Ayatollah Khomeini are now challenging the
religion's basic precepts as well as the specifics of theocratic
rule.
</P>
<P>
   For example, all of Tehran was engrossed last autumn in the
trial of Abdollah Nouri, a cleric and editor of the newspaper
Khordad, who served during the Third Republic as vice president,
interior minister and Tehran city councilor. The Special Court for
the Clergy charged him with multiple counts of ``insulting'' Islam,
the prophet Muhammad and the Ayatollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri, a close supporter of President Khatami, had run articles
in Khordad that questioned everything from the Islamic concept of
eye-for-eye justice to the clergy's automatic right to hold power.
At his trial, he astonished Iranians by denying the court's right
to judge him: ``I totally reject the court, its membership, and its
competence to conduct this trial, and any verdict you reach will
have no legitimacy.''
</P>
<P>
   In late November, Nouri was sentenced to five years in prison.
His newspaper was banned, although his staff defiantly pledged to
launch another publication _ the new way of getting around forced
closures.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nouri, Mohsen Kadivar, a popular young cleric and professor
put on trial for ``disseminating lies and disturbing public
opinion'' by advocating the separation of political and religious
institutions, rejected the clergy's right to judge.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being convicted and receiving an 18-month sentence,
Kadivar gained celebrity status. Posters of him were plastered all
over Tehran. Students held a candlelight vigil in the hills near
Evin prison, where he was being held without bail. Chanting
``freedom of thought, forever, forever,'' they released doves as a
symbol of liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Like the world around it, Iran is still undergoing a profound
transformation. More internal turmoil lies ahead, as the
revolution's early passions are replaced by hard-earned pragmatism,
and as arrogance gives way to realism among many sectors of Iranian
society.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the government of God is being forced to cede to
secular statecraft _ and to empower Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEXT: Part II: ``From Under the Chador'' -- The status of
Iranian women is fast changing, as an energetic ``liberation''
movement is shattering the starkest stereotype of the Islamic
republic: the chador-clad female. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Robin Wright, a former Middle East correspondent for The
Sunday Times of London, currently covers global affairs for the Los
Angeles Times. She is the author of ``The Last Great Revolution:
Turmoil and Transformation in Iran.'' This article is adapted from
a longer version in Foreign Affairs.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8632 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-IRAN-PEOPLE-POWER-NYT     02-16 1730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-PEOPLE-POWER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S NEW REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This is Part I of a two-part series on contemporary Iran by
Robin Wright, a veteran Middle East correspondent. Part II is
slugged: BC-IRAN-WOMEN-REVOLUTION. For rates, please contact one of
these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By ROBIN WRIGHT  
 c.2000 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
