<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-IRAN-WOMEN-REVOLUTION     02-16 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-WOMEN-REVOLUTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM UNDER THE CHADOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This is Part II of a two-part series on contemporary Iran by
Robin Wright, a veteran Middle East correspondent. Part I is
slugged: BC-IRAN-PEOPLE-POWER. For rates, please contact one of
these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By ROBIN WRIGHT  
 c.2000 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Iranian women are by far the most politically active in the
Persian Gulf and are among the most empowered in the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 200 women ran for the 270-seat parliament and 14 won.
In 1997, four women registered to run for the presidency. Although
all were disqualified by the Council of Guardians that vets
candidates, the decision was not based on gender.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad Khatami's stunning upset victory in the 1997
presidential election, in which 70 percent of the voters said no to
the hard-line conservative candidate, would not have happened
without the female vote. And as president, Khatami appointed a
female vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, 5,000 women ran in local elections, and 300 won. Today,
more than 40 percent of university students are female, as are
one-third of faculty members. Thousands of women educated after the
revolution work as engineers, doctors, scientists, lawyers and even
clerics. More than 340 directors-general in government ministries
are female.
</P>
<P>
   Iran has 140 female publishers, enough to hold an exhibition of
books and magazines published by women only. Women have become
painters, authors, designers, photographers, movie producers,
directors, stars and sculptors crafting ``anatomically correct''
female figures (otherwise known as nudes).
</P>
<P>
   A fierce women's movement was not what the theocrats had
intended to see as characteristic of Iran's Islamic revolution.
Their original goal was more akin to gender apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   After the revolution, the regime, in one way or another,
dismissed almost all women who earlier had risen to positions of
importance. A former female education minister was executed for
promoting ``prostitution'' among girls.
</P>
<P>
   The revolution's severe intentions were reflected in the new
Islamic dress code and the lowering _ to age 9 _ of the minimum age
at which women could be married. The new constitution also removed
critical women's rights in divorce and child-custody battles.
</P>
<P>
   A generation later, many of the country's restrictions on women
still border on the bizarre:
</P>
<P>
   _ A woman may have an equal vote in parliament or equal powers
among the vice presidents, but her testimony in court carries only
half the weight of a man's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women can head universities and publish newspapers but cannot
leave the country without their husbands' written permission.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women can act in plays and movies alongside men, but they
cannot sing in public or ride in the same section of a public bus.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Iranian women have proven irrepressible. In
defiance of the theocracy, they are putting their imprints on
diverse aspects of Iranian life.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the mid-1990s, pressure from women changed laws on
employment, divorce and maternity leave. Women packed a courtroom
to protest child-custody laws after the brutal death of an
eight-year-old girl. She had weighed only 35 pounds and suffered a
fractured skull, two broken arms and burn marks over her body at
the hands of her father, a drug addict with a criminal record and a
documented history of child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic tradition allows a mother to keep a daughter until the
age of seven and a son until the age of two; full custody then
switches to the father. In 1998 Parliament revised the law to
stipulate that a child could no longer be awarded to an unfit
father, defining the custody qualifications in a way that could
often disqualify men.
</P>
<P>
   Women have challenged other male bastions as well. Thousands of
women broke a long-time barrier preventing females from attending
male sporting events when they poured into Tehran's stadium to
greet the Iranian soccer team after it qualified for the 1998 World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Women are also playing sports. Tehran alone has 85 women's
basketball teams in five leagues. Only 10,000 women engaged in
intramural sports on the eve of the revolution. Today, 2 million
participate in soccer, basketball, swimming, tennis, handball,
skiing, aerobics, fencing, judo, shooting, volleyball, rowing,
horseback riding, gymnastics, golf, table tennis, karate, tae kwon
do and even water-skiing. This, despite the slightly absurd
waterproof coats and scarves women must wear to demonstrate
``modesty.''
</P>
<P>
   And women have forced the theocrats to acknowledge their
official participation. At the 1996 Olympics, for the first time, a
female athlete led the Iranian team onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   The new activists are as distinct as their political
environment. The most outspoken women are no longer necessarily
Westernized or upper-class elites, but have emerged from within the
revolution. Many are from traditional families, clerical circles
and rural areas _ none of which had previously produced female
activists.
</P>
<P>
   Women's publications have been brazen on reform issues. ``Zan''
(Woman) _ which the theocrats banned in 1999 _ was a newspaper
published by Faezeh Hashemi, the daughter of former President
Rafsanjani, and a member of parliament. It editorialized against
child-custody laws, the use of stoning as a punishment, and
``temporary marriage'' _ the practice of contracting a short-term
wife. It ran an expose on the return of prostitution and reported
on a New Year's message sent to the country by the former empress
of Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Another publication, ``Farzaneh,'' is trying to reconcile more
robust women's rights with the Islamic faith. Its articles have
included ``Human Rights of Women in Islam,'' ``A History of Silence
and Debates Today,'' ``How to Proceed'' and ``The Long Way Ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Iranian cinema, which often focuses on women, has led a major
countercultural revolution since the early 1990s. We find female
movie characters who are challenging the status quo, plots that
focus on the shortcomings of the Islamic system and dialogue that
extends the boundaries of public discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Dariush Mehrjui, the father of modern Iranian cinema, wrote a
quartet of films _ ``Banoo'' (1992), ``Sara'' (1993), ``Pari''
(1995) and ``Leila'' (1997) _ about the professional and personal
plight of women in Islamic society. Each ended with the lead female
character defying convention or leaving her husband to head out on
her own _ a radical move in a society where women must get written
permission to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   Mohsen Makhmalbaf, who spent five years in the shah's jails, was
known in the 1980s for ardently religious and pro-revolution films.
But his seventh film, ``A Time to Love,'' was a controversial tale
_ with three endings based on three perspectives _ about a married
woman who pursues a younger man.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Makhmalbaf's teen-age daughter Samira made her film
debut with ``The Apple,'' the true story of an illiterate man who
had locked his 12-year-old twin daughters at home since infancy,
for fear that the girls' purity would be spoiled by strange men's
gazes.
</P>
<P>
   The movie revolved around the gradual exposure of the girls _
almost mute, unschooled and both physically and mentally disabled _
to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the film to make this point: All it takes to imprison
many, many women is one man,'' Samira told reporters when the film
opened in New York in 1999. ``What I noticed about those two girls
is that the more they came into contact with society, the more
complete they became as human beings. For me, that became a
metaphor for all women. Women in Iran are like springs. If they
want to be free, and if they try, they burst out with a lot of
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Robin Wright, a former Middle East correspondent for The
Sunday Times of London, currently covers global affairs for the Los
Angeles Times. She is the author of ``The Last Great Revolution:
Turmoil and Transformation in Iran.'' This article is adapted from
a longer version in Foreign Affairs.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1400EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
