<P>
   .....................
 &UR; THE PRESIDENT and ME &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By `BUDDY,' as told to CHARLES SIEBERT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   These may be lonely and wistful times in the White House, but
the First Dog has never had it so good. In this article, Buddy, the
Labrador retriever, muses on his expanded role now that Bill
Clinton has headed into the eighth and final year of his
presidency, with Chelsea, his only child, away at college; Hillary,
his wife, in New York running for the Senate; and Al Gore, the vice
president, on the road seeking to beat George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Charles Siebert is the author of ``Wickerby: An Urban
Pastoral'' and, most recently, ``Angus,'' a memoir of his late dog,
to be published by Crown this spring. slugged:
BC-BUDDY-DOG-CLINTON, priority code r, category code a,k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HA JIN'S CULTURAL REVOLUTION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DWIGHT GARNER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ha Jin's first novel, ``Waiting,'' the story of a Chinese doctor
who wants to end his arranged marriage so he can marry a more
modern woman, recently won a National Book Award. It was a mere 11
years after Jin began writing seriously in English. In the 50-year
history of the awards, only two other writers who weren't native
English speakers have taken home the fiction prize: Isaac Bashevis
Singer and Jerzy Kosinski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Dwight Garner is an editor for The New York Times Book Review.
slugged: BC-HA-JIN-NOVEL, priority code r, category code a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `JOHNNY MAC, DON'T EVER CHANGE' &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JULIAN RUBINSTEIN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe, at age 40, has lost little of the intensity that
made him one of the best _ and most controversial _ athletes of our
time. Seven years after leaving the pro tennis circuit McEnroe is
still at it _ and not just on the court in seniors matches. He has
taken his swagger to the broadcasting booth, where he has drawn a
lot of attention, most of it good; last year, he was nominated for
an Emmy. And in February he becomes captain of the Davis Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Julian Rubinstein is a writer whose work has appeared in Men's
Journal, Sports Illustrated and The Washington Post. slugged:
BC-McENROE-TENNIS-PROFILE, priority code r, category code a)
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------- &QC;
</P>
