<HEADER>
A8668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     02-16 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS WARM TO MILLER'S NEW MILLENNIUM FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you ran a company, would you have one of your star employees
work only two days week? If you owned a baseball team, would you
use one of your top players only three innings per game?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is obvious. Of course you wouldn't. So why, if you
are Fidelity Investments, do you have Neal Miller manage only $3.6
billion worth of mutual fund assets, peanuts by today's standards?
</P>
<P>
   Miller is one of Fidelity's stars, a Peter Lynch style manager
who finds lots of different ways to make money. Since he started
the New Millennium Fund in December 1992, he has had an average
annual return of 34.2 percent, far above the 20.7 percent return of
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index. According to Lipper Inc., Miller
ranked first among his 46 peers in the mid-cap growth category over
that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, New Millennium was up a stunning 108 percent.
Unfortunately, relatively few investors got a piece of that action.
New Millennium has been closed to new investors since May 1996.
Only existing customers can put money in the fund.
</P>
<P>
   A little history is in order here. When New Millennium was
created in 1992, Fidelity promised it would never get bigger than
$500 million. The decision was not hard to understand. The greater
the cash flow into a fund, the harder a manager has to work to
invest the money. In a big fund, a manager also may be forced to
move up the capitalization ladder and buy larger stocks than he
would like.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity didn't honor its initial pledge. When New Millennium
reached $500 million, in 1995, the fund stayed open. But the next
year, with assets still well under $1 billion, Fidelity shut the
door. In an interview last year, Miller said the fund's small size
was a plus. Last week, a Fidelity spokesman said there were no
plans to reopen New Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   We don't buy that. In fact, we think Fidelity ought to give
serious consideration to opening the door and letting some new
investors inside.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, quite a few other mutual fund companies manage to
run successful small and mid-cap funds with far more than the $3
billion that Miller runs. Putnam's Vista fund has more than $9
billion in assets; T. Rowe Price's New Horizon fund has close to $7
billion under management.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Miller does not stick all that closely to the strict
definitions of market cap. A mid-cap stock is supposed to be one
with a value of less than $10 billion. Yet at the end of 1999,
Miller's holdings included Qualcomm (market cap: $95 billion),
Veritas Software ($43 billion), CMGI ($30 billion), and Micron
Technology ($20 billion).
</P>
<P>
   The truth is $10 billion doesn't go as far as it used to _ not
when brand-new companies do IPOs and have market values of $15
billion at the end of the first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we are not part of the camp that believes size matters
all that much. Robert Stansky has done a nice job managing the $100
billion Magellan Fund. Is there any reason to think Neal Miller is
any less skillful?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fidelity managers are smart enough to put cash to work,'' said
Jim Lowell, editor of Fidelity Investor, a newsletter. ``I don't
like to see managers having their hands tied behind their backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially Miller's. The guy is an original. He claims to get
his ideas by reading up to 300 periodicals, everything from
``American Funeral Director'' to ``Bandwidth.'' In an interview
with one of Fidelity's in-house publications last year, he
explained his investment style this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on a bank overlooking a calm sailboat race and what I see
is what all other investors see. But what I am looking for is
happening outside that efficient picture. I am looking at the cloud
formation on the horizon, which is what generates the wind which
will ultimately decide how the race evolves and who will win. I'm
looking for a change dynamic.''
</P>
<P>
   Burt Greenwald, a Philadelphia mutual fund consultant, puts it
simply. ``No question Miller is a star,'' he said. Greenwald thinks
Fidelity could create a ``son of Millennium'' to leverage Miller's
talents.
</P>
<P>
   Giving investors a shot at Miller also would be good for
Fidelity. The mutual fund giant has seen money flow out of its
conservative funds and into its aggressive ones. Funds like
Aggressive Growth and Growth Company have ballooned in the past
year. Erin Sullivan, the manager of Aggressive Growth, resigned
Monday to run her own hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Fidelity is it doesn't have enough hot funds to
offer investors. David O'Leary, president of Alpha Equity Research,
thinks the lack of exciting funds explains why Fidelity took in $2
billion in new money in January, compared to $8 billion for red-hot
Janus, a Denver-based mutual fund complex.
</P>
<P>
   Why not a ``new'' New Millennium fund for the new millennium? It
would be good for Fidelity and good for investors.
</P>
<P>
   So how about it, Neal? We think you could handle the extra dough
and still turn in some stellar results. How about opening that door
a little and letting the rest of us in?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
