<HEADER>
A8663 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TIM-ROBBINS-INTERVIEW     02-16 2149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIM-ROBBINS-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKIN' ROBBINS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE showing Tom Robbins on the set of ``Cradle Will
Rock'' is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this article.
The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARK GANEM  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Here's what Tim Robbins says when you call him one of
Hollywood's most political actors: ``I don't like politicians. I
think they lie all the time. I don't hang around with politicians;
I don't support candidates. I resent having to vote for the lesser
of two evils. Political is a negative term in my life, and that's
why I resent being called that. I don't have anything to do with
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, don't expect Robbins to join Warren Beatty, Alec
Baldwin or Cybill Shepherd on a celebrity presidential ticket any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   His reasoning might smack of semantic hairsplitting, but it's
sound enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political people are people who do things for their own
benefit,'' he explains. ``When you make a political decision,
you're not making an emotional or humanist decision. You are making
a decision that is calculated and cold.''
</P>
<P>
   So you try again: Is he a humanist? A socially responsible
artist?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very suspicious of labels people use.'' he shoots back.
``Why do they call them ethnic Albanians? They're Albanians. I
think sometimes if a word is thrown out, people use it without
thinking about it, and it becomes a way to label someone.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why Tim Robbins has a reputation as a prickly
interview subject, one who's been said to dismiss questions he
doesn't like (say, anything that reduces him to the status of Mr.
Susan Sarandon) and even _ although he says this is untrue _ to
walk out abruptly in the middle of an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But that picture is far from complete. It would be more accurate
to say that Robbins, who is an enthusiastic and brutally
competitive amateur athlete, loves to debate. And he seems to love
being right even more.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it can be disconcerting to see his malleable face
transform itself: One minute, he looks like an amiable goofball _
recognizable from his roles in ``Bull Durham'' and ``The Hudsucker
Proxy'' _ and the next he exudes the sly intelligence of Griffin
Mill, the ruthless movie executive he played in ``The Player.''
</P>
<P>
   He can train his eyes on a interlocutor like a predator fixing
lunch in its gaze. When he hears a question intended to direct him
toward well-trodden territory _ his protesting of the Gulf War, for
instance _ a faint smile of bemused professorial condescension
plays across his face.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in an untucked navy-blue flannel shirt open over a
thermal T-shirt and jeans, his lanky 6-foot-5-inch frame unraveled
on a chair in his New York office, Robbins gives the impression of
a superannuated college kid _ he'd be that smart, earnest guy who
took a semester off to organize factory workers in some benighted
part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The office, located among the Internet startups of Silicon Alley
in the Flatiron district, is headquarters for his Havoc Productions
and does resemble a grown-up version of a college dorm _ a perfect
place for late-night bull sessions. There are well-worn Mission and
veneered '30s antiques, movie posters on the walls, a treadmill and
Stairmaster sitting unplugged in one corner and a comfortable,
understuffed green velvet sofa in another.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins is munching on a cheeseburger and picking at an enormous
pile of french fries as he discusses his latest directorial
project, ``Cradle Will Rock,'' a sweeping drama about the final
days of the WPA's Federal Theater Project.
</P>
<P>
   The film takes its title from a real-life 1937 labor-movement
musical by the composer Marc Blitzstein and follows its production
at New York's Federal Theater, directed by a young Orson Welles and
produced by John Houseman.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress cancels the Project's funding, the production is
shut down on the eve of its opening, sparking a renegade
performance at a nearby theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cradle'' is populated by a slew of historical and fictional
characters played by an ensemble that includes Sarandon, John
Turturro, Emily Watson, John and Joan Cusak, Bill Murray, Hank
Azaria, Cherry Jones and Vanessa Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Robbins interweaves disparate stories from the closure of
Welles' production to Theater Project head Hallie Flanagan's
efforts to defend the program before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The genesis of the film was a proposed script on the subject
pitched to Robbins by a pair of producers in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I don't want to read this script, but I want to do
this film,''' the actor recalls, adding that he began researching
Welles' production with an eye to writing a script of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I read, the more the movie expanded into different
stories,'' he says. ``I did about 40 versions (of the script). Lots
of cutting and pasting.''
</P>
<P>
   What he wound up with could almost be an homage to the
kaleidoscopic style of director Robert Altman.
</P>
<P>
   The similarity is not lost on Robbins, who has starred in three
of Altman films: ``The Player'' (which launched the actor into
stardom), ``Short Cuts'' and ``Ready to Wear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never hidden my love for his films, especially
`Nashville,' being a seminal experience for me,'' Robbins says.
``It was one of the first times I remember sitting in a movie
theater and understanding how wonderful film can be. I was 17. What
impressed me most was the scope of it, the idea that at the end of
the movie, after watching all these characters and story lines, you
walk out with an emotion or feeling about culture _ America _ and
how people are to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   The acting bug bit Robbins while he was still a child, growing
up in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   The son of folk singer Gil Robbins (Tim's brother David is a
composer who scored ``Dead Man Walking'' and ``Cradle'' and
co-wrote, with him, the spite-laden political folk songs for Bob
Roberts), Robbins joined the Theater for the New City, a street
troupe, at the age of 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember doing these street vaudevilles critical of the
administration,'' he says. ``There was no one there to beat us
after the show _ the government was actually giving us money to do
it. They had the confidence in the strength of this democracy to
fund this act. That's amazing; I grew up with a great faith in
democracy because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   After Roman Catholic grade school and Stuyvesant High School, he
attended UCLA and soon after founded the Los Angeles theater group
The Actors Gang.
</P>
<P>
   His first big film break was 1988's ``Bull Durham,'' which also
provided an introduction to Sarandon, 12 years his senior. The
couple now has two children, and they divide their time between
homes in the Village and rural Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins followed ``Bull Durham'' with Adrian Lyne's underrated
``Jacob's Ladder''; ``The Player,'' which earned him a Golden Globe
and best actor at Cannes; ``The Shawshank Redemption,'' the Coen
brothers' ``The Hudsucker Proxy'' as well as less memorable films
like ``I.Q.,'' with Meg Ryan and this past summer's ``Arlington
Road,'' which he also produced.
</P>
<P>
   In between, he launched his writer/director career with the
caustic political ``mocumentary'' ``Bob Roberts'' in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I like directing my own stuff,'' Robbins says. ``It
takes an enormous emotional commitment to direct a film. It takes a
lot of time from your family. Acting is a breeze compared to
directing, for me. You become obsessed, you're staying late,
editing, working weekends. It's just an all-consuming kind of
occupation, so I don't know if I want to deal with someone else's
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim's got an incredible eye for detail,'' says Cherry Jones,
who plays Flanagan. ``I remember watching him for an hour as he
placed the background players for one scene, choosing the colors of
the costumes to paint the picture in his eye ... It's thrilling to
keep up with Tim's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins' most successful directorial effort to date was ``Dead
Man Walking,'' for which he received an Academy Award nomination.
Sarandon earned an Oscar as Sister Helen Prejean, who develops a
complex relationship with a death-row inmate played by Sean Penn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each film I've ever done is a different animal; each one has
its own life,'' Robbins says. ```Dead Man Walking' is a very
personal, very intimate love story; `Cradle' is an epic. It is a
wider canvas, and it's about more things than `Dead Man Walking.'''
</P>
<P>
   While Robbins and Sarandon are loath to discuss their
relationship, ``Dead Man's'' intense shoot gave rise to rumors of
tension between the couple, which Robbins downplays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with Susan, there were some difficult days,'' he says
now, ``and we talked about them (to the press) in the context of
doing a movie together. People seized on this idea that we didn't
get along for the entire shoot. We had a couple difficult days; you
have a couple difficult days with anybody. Some days you're in love
with everybody, other days things don't come so easily.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple tries to arrange work schedules so that one can be at
home with their children while the other is on the set. But that
doesn't mean there's no shop talk at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll show her stuff I write,'' Robbins says. ``I don't know if
I'd want to be her when I do that, because I'm so insecure. I don't
take criticism well. Sometimes I just want to hear that it's really
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins and Sarandon garnered more attention than they bargained
for with one particular collaboration in 1993, when they presented
together at the Oscars and made a public plea on behalf of 260
HIV-positive Haitian refugees being detained by the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
   The incident got the couple banned from the following year's
ceremonies and opened them to criticism as celebrity grandstanders,
an accusation Robbins vehemently denies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not grandstanding, I'm sorry, that's not
grandstanding,'' he says. ``Grandstanding is getting up and
bragging about yourself. If there was someone reporting about (the
detainment incident), if it was in the news, we would not have done
it. That would have been grandstanding.'' (Their protest, he adds,
led a federal judge to order the refugees' release days after their
Oscar speech.)
</P>
<P>
   Robbins is particularly irked when he's not taken seriously. Or
worse, when he's ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's an example,'' he says. ``When I was publicizing
`Arlington Road,' we started talking about Columbine and about
violence in America, and about what Clinton had just said the week
before _ about how taking more responsibility for violence in
films. And I said that I'm willing to take responsibility for that
if he takes responsibility for violence in real life. There's a
real violence happening now in Kosovo because of our lack of
communication. Why do we think as a nation that that doesn't affect
us? And he's talking about fictional violence? That's insane. This
didn't get picked up anywhere. When I said something negative about
`Forrest Gump,' it got all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins does participate, grudgingly, in the political process.
He votes _ for Bill Clinton in the last presidential elections
(``he's the first Republican I've ever voted for,'' he jokes) and
would for Warren Beatty, although he notes, ``I vote only because
of the Supreme Court, to get people in.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Hillary Clinton's senate run from New York, he says only,
``If Giuliani were running against a fire hydrant, I'd vote for the
fire hydrant.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, his next film, Brian DePalma's ``Mission to
Mars,'' is due out in March. Robbins is scheduled to begin work
soon on Terrence Malick's adaptation of Walker Percy's ``The
Moviegoer'' with Julia Roberts _ and he's still not keeping his
mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't shut up because people are going to disagree with
you or criticize you,'' he says. ``It's a free country we're living
in. You should be able to go up and say whatever the hell you
want.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mark Ganem is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
