<HEADER>
A8669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-SEASON-BOS &LR;      02-16 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SEASON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOODS THAT RECAST WINTER AND ITS DISCONTENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If we really ate with the seasons, we'd starve. No one is
growing vegetables anywhere near us, and what's in the markets
carries a high price tag. So it's official: It looks pretty dreary
out there.
</P>
<P>
   So why is this winter different from all other winters? Because
this is the year you should change your attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Decide that the glass is half full.
</P>
<P>
   Then walk briskly past cucumbers that lack summer's snap, and
don't bother with those expensive tricolored bell peppers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; You're looking for bulbs of beautiful fresh fennel, their
fernlike leaves spilling onto the other greens. Or pick up some
fresh baby spinach leaves, loose or packaged. And don't be a snob
about the frozen case. Peer deeply into it for tiny peas and frozen
haricots verts, the slender French green beans. They're not as
crisp and firm as the fresh ones, but don't overcook them and
they'll be bright green and just right beside slices of roast
chicken bathed in their pan juices.
</P>
<P>
   Darkest February begs for a little pantry cheer. It might be
something as simple as varying your pasta shape or tossing
beautiful olives into the tomato sauce. Here's a short list of
items to boost your spirits until crocus time.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh fennel (about $2 each) is the winter salad-lover's savior.
Bulb shaped, with firm, overlapping white leaves and fern-like
ends, fennel has the mildest licorice taste and a beautiful crunch.
It is perfectly wonderful roasted with a little olive oil. Or use
it raw in a salad. Slice it as thinly as possible and cut the
slices into matchsticks. Arrange peeled, sliced navel oranges on a
platter, scatter the fennel matchsticks on top, add a handful of
whole Italian parsley sprigs, and sprinkle lightly with oil,
vinegar, salt, pepper, and crumbled goat cheese. Just add warm,
crusty bread.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen haricots verts ($1.59), the slender French green beans,
come in 1-pound bags at Trader Joe's (781-433-0234) and take
seconds to cook. Imported from France, the beans are individually
quick frozen, which means that you can pour tonight's portion out
of the bag, then reseal it. Drop them into boiling water; when the
water returns to a boil, let them cook for half a minute. Drain
them and rinse with a teacup of cold water to set the color. Serve
haricots verts beside any juicy meat or fish, so they can mingle
with the juices. Or chill them and scatter them onto a winter
salad.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny cherry tomatoes shaped like grapes, called grape
tomatoes (around $3 for a pint box), are one of the best new
products to come along in years. These little gems are sweeter than
all the other cherries shipped north in midwinter, and best of all,
their skins aren't thick. If you see them on sale, buy lots and
make a quick tomato saute to ladle over pasta or accompany lamb
chops: Heat just enough oil in a skillet to film the bottom, add
the tomatoes, salt, and pepper, and cook over medium heat for 10
minutes, stirring often, until the tomatoes release their liquid.
Add a handful of fresh herbs (parsley, thyme, oregano, or basil).
</P>
<P>
   Also relatively new to the markets is fresh baby spinach, which
comes loose or bagged. The bags are less than half a pound (about
$2 each), found in the produce department with the lettuces that
are already cut and bagged. Look carefully to make sure the spinach
hasn't deteriorated inside. At home, remove the stems and add a
heaping handful of spinach to vegetable soup. Cook it only until it
wilts. Or saute the spinach in a little butter with a pinch of
nutmeg, salt, and pepper. This is the spinach you should use to
make a raw spinach salad, or add some to a bowl of mesclun, fennel,
and watercress.
</P>
<P>
   Once called Yuppie Lettuce because of its high price, mesclun
salad (about $7 per pound) is now everywhere. This mixture usually
combines at least half a dozen greens, including curly endive, beet
leaves, arugula, mizuna, mache, radicchio, and baby lettuces. The
drawback is that it's highly perishable. If one of the greens
wilts, it can give an off taste to the whole mix. Look closely at
the bin to make sure that any green lettuces have not already
turned yellow. At home, pack them in a large plastic container that
is lined on the bottom with a damp paper towel. Cover the lettuces
with another damp paper towel and seal with the lid. Toss mesclun
with other lettuces, baby spinach, and fennel.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed olives ($7 to $9 per pound) used to be hard to come by
outside of specialty markets, but now stores that sell good olives
generally offer them. Most manufacturers make their own mix and
include all sizes of green and black olives grown in France, Italy,
and Greece. Toss a handful of olives in any chicken dish with a
tomato-based sauce, or add some to a garlicky tomato sauce along
with chopped anchovies, a generous pinch of crushed red pepper, and
capers. This will produce the classic puttanesca, a spicy sauce
named for Italy's streetwalkers.
</P>
<P>
   With the sauce, of course, you want pasta, not the same
spaghetti you make year in and year out, but rather a great new
pasta shape. Strozzapreti (literally ``strangle the priest'') is a
pasta shaped like a teardrop with a twist at the end, or, more
precisely, a noose. Made by Benedetto Cavallieri, a 1-pound bag
($4.95) will feed four. It's more expensive than other brands, but
you'll taste the difference. When top-quality pasta is cooked to
the point when it is tender but still has some bite, it brings new
definition to the words ``al dente.''
</P>
<P>
   And just in case you thought that pasta was one of the few
mandatory items in the pantry, here's another: Trader Joe's canned
whole kernel corn (69 cents), 15 ounces of sweet crunch, and a big
surprise for anyone who looks down her nose at canned vegetables.
Picked and processed in Idaho without sugar or preservatives, the
corn is very yellow and very cheerful. Microwave it for one minute
just to remove the chill. Add a little summertime to your plate.
</P>
<P>
   Winter's coldest months do bring a sweet treat from the sea.
Tiny, tasty, fresh Maine shrimp ($5 to $7 per pound) are fished off
the coast of Maine from mid-January for exactly 60 days. That gives
you until the middle of March to get to a good fish market and find
these little treats. And they are little. About four shrimp will
fit into a soup spoon. Cook them in boiling water just until the
water returns to a boil. Drain and rinse with cold water until they
are no longer hot. Peel (if they're not peeled already) and toss
with mayonnaise, a squeeze of lemon juice, and a dash of liquid hot
sauce. Pile them onto crusty toasted French bread and thank the
weather gods for winter.
</P>
<P>
   You might also want to thank them for the warm days we had
earlier this winter, if you're a fan of shad roe. Thanks to the
weather, it's here early this year _ about two or three weeks ahead
of schedule. But that means the season will end early, too, so
while you're shopping for shrimp, you might as well ask for shad
roe, too. Saute it gently in butter over very low heat, add a
squeeze of lemon, and supper's ready.
</P>
<P>
   In the grain department, there are more tiny finds, French du
Puy lentils. Smaller, darker, and more flavorful than ordinary
lentils, du Puys (around $5 per pound) are less likely to fall
apart in the pot, which makes them wonderful in salads. Moisten
them with vinaigrette and add lots of spring onion, red onion, and
parsley. In soups, use them in place of ordinary lentils. They beg
for something smoky in the pot _ bacon, pancetta, Canadian bacon,
or serrano ham.
</P>
<P>
   Intensely dark, moist, and ultra-thin, German rye, wheat, and
multigrain breads (about $2.50 per pound) will stay fresh in the
fridge for weeks. One of the best is made by Mestemacher and is
available at food specialty stores. Spread slices of bread lightly
with butter and then add smoked salmon in a very thin layer.
Garnish with a sprig of fresh dill. Cut the bread into triangles
and arrange them on a platter. Cover them with a damp paper towel,
then a clean kitchen towel, and let them sit in a cool place for as
long as several hours. To serve: Light a fire, pull some
comfortable chairs close to the fireplace, uncork the wine, and dig
in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1409EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8671 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-PURCHASERS-H     02-16 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-PURCHASERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POSSIBLE EXAMINER BUYERS MAY INCLUDE EX-MAYORAL CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Clint Reilly, the failed candidate for mayor who
went to court last month seeking to block the merger of the city's
two daily newspapers, has emerged as a potential buyer of the
135-year-old San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Hearst Corporation, which owns the Examiner and
is buying the rival San Francisco Chronicle, announced Tuesday that
they had receive more than one proposal. Tuesday was the deadline
the company set for selling the Examiner, which was purchased by
they Hearst family in 1887.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst officials said they would not say who had made offers.
But Reilly's lawyer, Joseph M. Alioto, announced that his client
made a bid after he was ``invited'' to do so by Hearst lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement marks the latest development in efforts by
Hearst to find a buyer for the Examiner as part of a plan announced
last Aug. 6 for Hearst to purchase the Chronicle for an estimated
$660 million and sell the Examiner. If no qualified buyer appeared,
Hearst indicated it would merge the two newspapers and close the
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst officials promised staff members they would not lose
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Justice and the California attorney
general are reviewing the proposed merger to determine if it
complies with anti-trust laws. The San Francisco Board of
Supervisors, which has said it wants to preserve both newspapers,
also is examining the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst on Jan. 25 expanded its effort to find a buyer, throwing
delivery trucks, a printing plant and the Examiner office building
into the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said Reilly wasn't interested in buying the newspaper
until after Jan. 11, when he filed an antitrust lawsuit to stop the
Hearst Corporation from merging the two newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Alioto said, Hearst lawyers suggested that Reilly
buy the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client was invited to do this,'' Alioto said. ``If I find
out later they were not serious, I will take the appropriate
response.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the New York-based Hearst could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, who was in Hong Kong on Tuesday and unavailable for
comment, once sued the newspaper and Examiner Executive Editor Phil
Bronstein over a conference-room altercation. He was criticized in
Examiner editorials during his campaign against Mayor Willie Brown,
in which he spent nearly $4 million of his own money for a
fourth-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said the bid for the newspaper has nothing to do with
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Others who have express interest in the newspapers, which has an
afternoon circulation of 107,000, did not return telephone calls.
The morning Chronicle's circulation is 457,000.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said last month that he hoped to save the Examiner and
would try to bring together some investors to buy the newspaper. He
also talked about creating a ``Save the Examiner'' task force. The
mayor's press secretary declined to comment on potential bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Cuthbertson, executive officer of the Northern California
Media Workers Guild, said he was surprised that there were several
offers, one of them coming from Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be highly interested in seeing what kind of plan they
have to survive, whether they have pockets deep enough to go head
to head in the morning with the Chronicle,'' Cuthbertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuthbertson said the delays that could result because of the
offers would only prolong feelings of uneasiness at both
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in both newsrooms has been frustrated for years to
one degree or another, not knowing what their futures would be,''
Cuthbertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bronstein said he has not been involved in discussions of the
sale. ``I'm not in that loop,'' he said. ``My job is to run the
newsroom.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a century, the Examiner and the Chronicle were
morning rivals. But in 1965, the newspapers entered into a joint
operating agreement (JOA) under which the Examiner switched to
afternoon publication. The newspapers maintain separate news staffs
and compete for stories, but the companies share printing and
business operations and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Such arrangements were later authorized by the Newspaper
Preservation Act of 1970, a federal law aimed at preserving
newspapers that would be forced to close without relief from the
expense of head-to-head competition.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco JOA expires in 2005, but last year the owners
of the Chronicle Publishing Co. decided to sell all the company's
assets.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department must approve the sale of the Chronicle to
Hearst. A decision is pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
