<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8672 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-16 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVICE PROBLEMS STIR DINERS' PASSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I recently asked you to talk back about service in today's
restaurants. Talk back you did, flooding my e-mail, the fax
machine, and the US mail with replies. Not only did you answer the
eight questions, but you gave specifics on calculating tips
according to the level of service, told horror stories and
heartening tales, and over and over gave a clarion call that
restaurateurs ignore only at their peril. As one reader commented
after answering the questionnaire: ``Boy, I had no idea I felt so
strongly about this subject!''
</P>
<P>
   When the Zagat survey asked in New York City whether men are
treated better in restaurants than women, the question got an
overwhelming number of affirmatives: Four out of five said men were
given preference. In this poll, the spread was narrower, but still
many more women _ and men _ think that women get short shrift when
eating out. Seating was the biggest complaint, with women saying
they always were seated at the worst tables in the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Groups of women, the readers said, are particularly
discriminated against, and both men and women took some time to
list what might be the reasons. But, as a male reader said, ``I am
a man who worked for many years in a field dominated by women, so I
spent a lot of time eating in restaurants with women. Women are
treated worse in restaurants than men both by waiters and by
waitresses. Some places it is really embarrassing. Partly it is
clearly sexism and partly it is that women at least appear to take
longer to order, fuss more over their orders and their food, and
are reputed to tip less well than men. And I have also eaten in
restaurants with women who divide a check down to the penny (``I
had, you had, so my share of the tip is $4.19''), and I imagine
this drives waitstaff crazy. But the sexism is still inexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
   Inexcusable indeed. I was most amazed by women who apologized,
seemingly agreeing that the waitstaff was justified in ignoring
them or placing them at inferior tables. Because the
most-often-cited reason for discrimination against women in
restaurants _ that they don't tip as well _ certainly is not borne
out by the answers to this survey. Many more women than men replied
that they tipped 20 percent of the total bill or even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to challenge the stereotype,'' one woman wrote, ``by
tipping 20 percent consistently; 25 percent if service is
excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the most generous respondents pointed out that at some
point in their lives they had been on the other side, as waitstaff.
Others were more exacting about the terms of tipping. One man
wrote: ``When I walk into a restaurant, the tip is 15 percent. It
goes up or down from there, depending on the quality of the total
experience (in my opinion, the total experience being broken down
to 50 percent service, 50 percent food quality).''
</P>
<P>
   Although most respondents did say they adjusted a tip according
to service, many adding that they never went below 15 percent, one
reader thought differently. ``I dine out frequently and my
experience is that too many people give tips even when the service
is poor or inept. . . . The problem is that some diners feel
uncomfortable or are afraid to leave small tips or no tips at
all.'' This, he says, only exacerbates the problem, and waiters and
waitresses ``have become spoiled and expect a large tip just for
delivering the food.'' Small tips or no tips would encourage
waitstaff to do better or to find work elsewhere, this reader
argued, ``which will benefit everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said they make sure to praise good service to the
management as well as tipping above 25 percent. One reader told of
giving a waitress a small tip because of service but ``personally
handing money to the busboy because he had been very attentive to
us and was working very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Some respondents said they never complain about service, adding,
``it is too time consuming and inept'' or ``rude servers are
impossible to correct or complain to.'' But many more said they do
voice their opinions, while making clear they understand that some
service problems, such as food that's slow to arrive, are not
always the waitstaff's problem. One reader, who does complain to
management, added: ``I also make sure to mention if I feel the
problem is due to a lack of staff or the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reader told of a particularly grim restaurant visit
involving a 45-minute wait for salads, disappearing staff, and warm
wine, and then recounted the reaction of the manager, who solicited
her party's reasons for being disgruntled. ``He said: `it only took
25 (minutes), besides, we have only been open 6 weeks and you seem
hostile.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone thought restaurants should compensate for errors and
should reduce the cost of the meal and pay for cleaning in case of
spilled drinks or food. A woman who owns a retail business pointed
out: ``Always better to err on the side of generosity _ and
customers remember and appreciate it.'' But that doesn't always
happen. One reader wrote: ``I had hot coffee sprayed on me over a
railing. A manager came by to ask, `was the food compromised?' When
I said no, he walked away without saying another word. I had to
have my pants dry-cleaned.''
</P>
<P>
   And what kind of service is your ideal? ``Friendly but not too
friendly'' was the consensus of the respondents. But efficiency is
very important, no matter what the style of the restaurant. The
server should know the menu, be attentive, and be open to answering
questions. And smile _``If you smile and do your job correctly,
then I will tip you VERY well,'' one woman said.
</P>
<P>
   Noise matters a lot to some people and not much at all to
others. Most said they would complain to the server.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other pet peeves _ some that are mine, too.
Lighting is often too dim or poorly placed to let you read the
menu. A woman replying to the question about gender treatment said
she can't stand restaurant personnel who insist on calling her and
her friends ``dearie.'' Many others commented on other annoying
phrases such as ``are you still working on that?'' Or ``will you be
needing change?'' Or the server saying, ``What will you guys be
having?'' Others complain of ``servers who want to pounce on the
plate of someone who has finished eating,'' leaving that person
feeling silly while others finish dinner. Many complained about
silverware not being changed between courses.
</P>
<P>
   And the complaint that I agree with since I see it constantly:
servers who almost have to be sought out and run to the ground
before they'll bring the check. Don't they want to get paid? I
always wonder. But many readers wrote that management is
responsible for service in the end, that owners and managers should
be aware how the dining room is running, and that staff members
should be trained. ``There was a time,'' one reader wrote, ``when
management trained service personnel, from headwaiter or greeter to
waitstaff, on how guests should be greeted and served, thus
providing guests with a pleasant dining experience.''
Unfortunately, the reader said, that seems often not to be the
case.
</P>
<P>
   As another woman wrote: ``I like to be treated the way I would
treat a guest in my home.''
</P>
<P>
   By far, the crucial question for restaurateurs is the last: ``Do
you complain about service or do you just not return to that
establishment?'' A majority of the respondents said they vote with
their feet. No matter how unpleasant it might be to deal with
complaints, it's better than lack of business.
</P>
<P>
   But over and over readers were loud and clear on the reason:
``There are too many restaurants to put up with poor service or
poor anything,'' one reader wrote. And he added: ``Word of mouth is
very powerful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
