<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-PPV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WCW still failing to generate excitement for TV shows
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This past Monday held a lot of promise for the floundering World
Championship Wrestling's ``Nitro'' television program. For the
first time in 2000 (it will happen again when the U.S. Open comes
back to New York in September), the TNT show ran unopposed from the
USA network juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   The night promised to be a big one with legends Hulk Hogan and
Ric Flair meeting in the ring, along with a handful of story lines
going for the final push before Sunday's ``SuperBrawl''
pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   But before the lights went up on the 8 p.m. show from Long
Island's Nassau Coliseum, trouble had already arrived. After a
weekend wrestling with WCW in Germany, Scott Hall, who has been
thrust into the main-event spotlight since Kevin Nash's injury, was
not allowed on his flight out of Germany because he was
intoxicated, according to a 1wrestling.com report. Without Hall,
who would've been in the main event, the ``Nitro'' show had to be
rewritten and it resulted in a match that was orginally going to be
the main event for the pay-per-view. Luckily it won't be because
the match was average at best.
</P>
<P>
   It followed a good match between Hogan and Flair. The two
veterans (combined age: nearly 100), pulled out all their old moves
for the millionth time in the match that went as any average fan
could've scripted from home.
</P>
<P>
   The show was a loss when Ernest Miller was given a promo right
after the Hogan-Flair battle. And that's what the writers at WCW
seem to be missing. The show should grow to something. Set up the
night's event early, then don't waste time with some bit with a
mid-carder.
</P>
<P>
   There is no fan excitement around ``SuperBrawl'' because the
fans don't care or are split in different directions on the Scott
Hall-Sid Vicious-Jeff Jarrett match. They don't care because the
story line is weak and the combatants are miscast. The giant
wrestler (Vicious) is playing the role of the underdog. In order to
make a 6-foot-10, 340-pound man seem like an underdog, they have to
put him in situations where there are two or three wrestlers
against him. But then the pay-per-view has him going against two
guys who no longer can work together, so who cares? That's bad and
will translate to more poor buy-rate figures this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Things only seem to be getting worse for WCW. Shane Douglas and
Chris Kanyon are the newest departees. Douglas is suing WCW for
releasing him, in part because he has nowhere else to go. The WCW
is also in the middle of a lawsuit for racial discrimination from
three former performers. This suit is not expected to be settled
like the Douglas one. And WCW has not been able to pry Sabu and
Chris Candido away from their ECW contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
