<HEADER>
A8684 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-GAME-ZOBMONDO-LADN &LR;      02-16 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAME-ZOBMONDO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KID-LEVEL PLAYGROUND HUMOR COMES TO ADULT BOARD GAME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By PHIL DAVIS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would you rather bite the curb and get kicked in the back of the
head or get a papercut on your eyeball? Would you rather be hairy
like Bigfoot or have body odor that can be detected across the
yard?
</P>
<P>
   The questions take you back to the playground _ a time when it
was still possible to ponder the price of eating a booger. Santa
Monica entrepreneur Randy Horn wants to take you back to that
elementary school mindset with his twisted board game Zobmondo.
</P>
<P>
   At first, adult minds want to resist. The only logical answer to
the questions above _ plucked from the Zobmondo box _ is none of
the above.
</P>
<P>
   But 32-year-old Horn knows the lure of the playground is strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying to get you to have a logical, reasonable
conversation that you can't even believe you're having,'' said
Horn, who created Zobmondo three years ago while pursuing a
master's degree in business at the University of California, Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're sitting there choosing to eat a handful of worms as
your preference,'' Horn continued. ``You look at that person and
say, `Do you realize what you're saying? You're vehemently arguing
to eat a handful of worms.' That's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Zobmondo (kid-speak translation: really bad) works like this: A
player must try to predict which of the two terrible options the
rest of the players will choose. The other players have three
minutes to reach a consensus. If the prediction is correct, the
player rolls again. The first player to the end _ the ``quagmire''
_ must devise his or her own Zobmondo question, creating a dilemma
so prickly that the other players cannot reach a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Horn is not the only one cashing in on bizarre dilemmas these
days.
</P>
<P>
   Authors Justin Heimberg and David Gomberg were among the first
to cash in on this childhood game with the 1997 book ``Would You
Rather ...?'' (Plume; $8.95).
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the concept has been, er, refined. Perhaps fermented
is a better word.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Doe, two Hollywood entertainment execs whose crude,
in-your-face books are so annoying they must hide behind aliases
and disguises, rolled out ``The Book of Horrible Questions'' (St.
Martins Griffin; $9.99). This disgusting book could one day give
aliens an excellent argument for the extermination of the human
race.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the questions are too crude to print in a family
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned that basically everybody has a price,'' said Smith,
who refuses to reveal his true identity. ``No matter how
disgusting, humiliating or embarrassing the act is, everybody has a
price. So we wrote a book that took that concept to the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we're prophets, don't you think, Doe?'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' the more honest Doe replied, ``we're for profits.''
</P>
<P>
   These ``would you rather?'' entrepreneurs have struck a chord in
society. It's contagious.
</P>
<P>
   Horn decided to create Zobmondo after ``would you rather?''
questions saved a particularly dreadful evening with a dull date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all started having a great time immediately,'' Horn said.
``The bartender was in on it, the food servers were coming out
telling me they've asked the cook _ everybody in the restaurant is
talking about these questions. I'm sitting there thinking it's
unbelievable. As we were walking out, I thought this is what's
supposed to happen when you sit down to play a social board game.
If what we're trying to do is create fun, this does it.''
</P>
<P>
   He took the idea back to his business class. Horn hired comedy
writers to write the 1,500 dilemmas in the game and honed the rules
with focus groups. A year later, after recruiting friends and
family to invest in the concept, his game was the sleeper hit at
the 1998 Toy Fair.
</P>
<P>
   He still hasn't had the breakthrough success of Pictionary or
Trivial Pursuit, but the $35 game has spread from 300 to 1,000
specialty stores, such as the Store of Knowledge in Woodland Hills.
It's also for sale on the Web at www.zobmondo.com, amazon.com and
etoys.com.
</P>
<P>
   If this kind of stuff is not your thing _ tough. Get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Horn and Smith and Doe are working on TV deals to take
their warped humor to the airwaves. Horn is hoping to catch
Hollywood's current game-show fever.
</P>
<P>
   And while Smith and Doe finish a book that they claim will
expose everyone's secret sexual desires, Horn is pitching Zobmondo
to calendar companies, toy manufacturers, CD-ROM distributors and
anyone else who will listen.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, somehow, somewhere, these crude questions are going
to find you. So just relax and start calculating your price to eat
a live, kicking 2-inch cockroach. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1419EST &QL; 
