<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM TO EXPAND IN EUROPE AS SALES SURGE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Editors)   (This 475-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``f'' financial news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By BILL MCINTOSH  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amazon.com, the high-profile online retailer, stepped up its
expansion into Europe this week, detailing plans for a new customer
service center in The Hague, while revealing that sales via its
U.K. Web site during the Christmas quarter jumped more than
fivefold to (pounds sterling)26 million (over $40 million).
</P>
<P>
   The company indicated it would add further Web sites in Europe
beyond its existing British and German operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands facility, which will serve customers across the
continent who shop at the British and German sites, will employ 125
people when it opens later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon, which is currently accessible over PCs only, is also
exploring links with mobile phone and interactive television
operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a clear commitment to make Amazon's shopping platform
available through PCs, mobile phone and television,'' said Steve
Fraser, managing director of Amazon.co.uk, while declining to
provide details.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're committed to doing is building a great platform for
e-commerce and we're great believers in open access to different
systems,'' he said. ``Our goal is universal access: anything,
anywhere, anytime on whatever platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon said that 1 million Britons visited its site during the
quarter and that it has 17 million users worldwide. In November and
December, Amazon's U.K. operation shipped 1.5 million items in some
900,000 packages.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's interactive retailers, including Open, controlled by
BSkyB and British Telecom, and WHSmith, have declined to release
sales figures.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding competition from Open, Fraser said: ``I'm not sure
they're even close to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon is the world's biggest online retailer and has extended
its retail offering beyond its bookseller origins to CDs and
consumer electronics goods.
</P>
<P>
   But despite rapid growth in quarterly sales, the company still
refuses to say when it will reach profitability. Earlier this
month, it reported a 1999 pro forma net loss of $390 million
compared with a pro forma net loss in 1998 of $74 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among new initiatives, Amazon.com opened five new retail stores
around the world during the Christmas quarter, along with its
sothebys.amazon.com service. It also agreed to ventures with
NextCard, Greenlight.com, drugstore.com, Audible, and living.com.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's presentation in London closely follows Amazon raising
$600 million from the euro-denominated sale of junk bonds to
European investors.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon, however, paid a price to get the debt issue subscribed,
including a hefty 6 7/8 percent to 7 3/8 percent coupon.
</P>
<P>
   It also offered a debt to equity conversion premium of 35
percent to 40 percent, meaning that the bonds are convertible into
Amazon stock at a price that is 35-40 percent above the current
market price.
</P>
<P>
   Convertible bonds are hybrid instruments that act like stocks
but offer investors a bond-like return. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 475-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
