<HEADER>
A8700 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ECONOMY-$ADV20-COX     02-16 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RECORD ECONOMIC BOOM HASN'T DONE MUCH FOR THE LESS WELL-OFF
 &HT;    1260&AMP;add. With ECONOMY-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, Feb. 20.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Next month, the U.S. economy will complete nine
consecutive years of growth, extending the longest and largest
economic boom the country has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   Since the expansion began in March 1991, the economy has grown a
staggering 64 percent to become the mightiest engine of commerce in
the history of the world, on track to kick out more than $9.5
trillion worth of goods and services this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   At its current growth rate, a sizzling 5.8 percent a year, the
economy is generating $1.5 billion worth of new wealth each day.
That's enough to create 62 new millionaires every hour, with enough
left over for a new minivan.
</P>
<P>
   The prosperity, however, hasn't been evenly shared. The great
American wealth machine is making the richest Americans richer
while its poorest workers fall farther behind.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, only the highest-earning Americans have
seen their net worth grow after inflation, and these same fortunate
few have collected an ever-growing share of the nation's income.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton touts the achievements of the economy's
winning streak, aides concede that leveling the economic playing
field, a central goal of his administration, continues to elude
policy makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're completely satisfied,'' Martin Baily,
chairman of the White House Council of Economic Advisers, told
reporters this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly progress that needs to be made,'' said
Baily, ``to make sure that everyone shares in that prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration claims that it has begun to make headway.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1993 and 1998, Baily pointed out, income for the poorest
fifth of the nation's workers grew at about 2.7 percent a year, on
average, compared with 2.4 percent growth for the highest paid 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But those gains, driven almost entirely by a $1-per-hour hike in
the minimum wage, have been swamped by longer-term trends in income
and wealth distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear who's getting what here,'' said New York
University economist Edward Wolff. ``We've seen a continuation of
rising inequality, though at a moderating rate.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are varied, and not all are confined to traditional
economics.
</P>
<P>
   _ The economy is evolving in ways beyond the average working
family's control.
</P>
<P>
   Workers must adapt to the revolution in computer and
communications technologies, the growing importance of services
over goods, and the sharp increase in global trade or face
declining fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   _ The stock market boom, by its very nature, heavily favors
those with the most money to invest.
</P>
<P>
   _ Social factors, ranging from drug use to demographic shifts
away from traditional family structures, continue to hold many
people back.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the causes, some analysts warn that if the trends are
not reversed, fundamental questions of economic fairness will arise
that challenge the ideals of opportunity and egalitarianism at the
nation's political core.
</P>
<P>
   ``It matters, because it goes to the heart of what we believe
about our society,'' said John Weicher, a specialist in income
inequality at the Hudson Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point,'' said Cornell University economist Robert
Frank, ``we have to ask whether the economy is sustainable if all
the growth continues to go to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy's long and potent expansion has showered broad
benefits, to be sure, on workers at all levels.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment is a razor-thin 4 percent, its lowest level in a
generation. Average wages for workers who punch the clock have
climbed to $13.50 per hour, up 35 percent since the boom began. And
the poverty rate, at 12.7 percent, is the lowest since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, behind each heartening statistic lies a more complex
and troubling tale.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the wage gains for low-income workers have come since
1997, after Congress raised the minimum wage to $5.15 an hour. Even
so, the minimum wage remains 20 percent below 1970s levels after
adjusting for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment remains high for those who lack the education or
skills to compete in the new economy. Nearly 6.5 percent of high
school dropouts can't find work, and the figure is higher for
minority groups such as African Americans, for whom the jobless
rate is near 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While poverty has declined, the reductions have occurred almost
exclusively in the South, which has enjoyed something of a boom
within a boom. Elsewhere across the country, good times haven't
made a dent in the poverty that continues to afflict more than one
in every three children of black or Hispanic descent.
</P>
<P>
   For millions of Americans, in fact, work is no ticket out of
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the last year for which figures are available, the
number of full-time, year-round workers living in poverty jumped
459,000 _ the largest such increase in history _ to 2.8 million,
according to the U.S. Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you know,'' Wolff said at a recent briefing hosted by
the American Enterprise Institute, ``the worse it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Things aren't getting better over time.
</P>
<P>
   Between World War II and the mid-1970s, the nation's surging
prosperity was broadly spread. ``Everybody saw their income grow at
about 2.8 to 2.9 percent a year,'' said Frank, ``rich and poor
alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past quarter-century, though, the gaps between rich and
poor have widened, both in terms of annual income and accumulated
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-year period from 1978 to 1980, the wealthiest
20 percent of the nation's families earned 7.4 times as much, on
average, as the poorest fifth of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1996 and 1998, the richest fifth was making 10.6 times
as much as the bottom 20 percent, according to a January study by
the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The widening income gap has increased the portion of the
national earnings pie gobbled up by the wealthiest families.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the richest fifth of the nation took in 46.6 percent of
the country's total earnings. By 1998, that figure had grown to
49.2 percent, even as the income meted out to the poorest fifth
fell from 3.9 percent to 3.6 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   In dollar terms, the disparity is no less jarring.
</P>
<P>
   As of 1998, the lowest-paid 20 percent of workers earned, on
average, $9,223 a year. That was just $250 above 1990 levels, after
adjusting for inflation, representing a miserly 2.8 percent gain
over the entire period.
</P>
<P>
   The top fifth, however, got a whopping 17.4 percent raise over
the same period, increasing their annual paycheck by $18,858, on
average, to $127,529.
</P>
<P>
   As income inequality has widened, so too has the difference
between wealth in poor households and rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distribution of wealth is even more skewed'' than lopsided
earnings, said Elizabeth McNichol, an expert on the subject at the
Center of Budget and Policy Priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have money,'' she said, ``you can make money.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, the ledger looks increasingly grim.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1990 and 1998, families earning less than $10,000 a year
actually lost ground. Their net worth slumped from an
inflation-adjusted $6,200, on average, to $5,600, a decline of 9.7
percent, according to a January report by the Federal Reserve
Board.
</P>
<P>
   Families taking in more than $100,000 per year, however, saw
their wealth jump from $195,500, on average, to $239,500, a gain of
22.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The wealthier a family, the more it stands to gain from good
economic times.
</P>
<P>
   For the richest 1 percent of Americans, said the Hudson
Institute's Weicher, fully half of all wealth comes from ownership
of businesses or investment real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Those assets are at risk, of course, if the economy sours. As it
soars, though, so do the fortunes of asset owners.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the greatest stock market gains, and risks, accrue to
those with the largest stake there.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the country's workers own stocks or mutual funds,
directly or through retirement savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Again, though, the real money is concentrated at the top.
</P>
<P>
   As of 1997, the richest 1 percent of households held half the
stocks and bonds in the country, said Wolff.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 percent accounted for 90 percent of share and bond
holdings and have garnered the greatest benefits from the more than
tripling of the Dow Jones Industrial Average since the current
economic run-up began.
</P>
<P>
   Portfolio values further underscore the divide. Only the richest
one-fourth of American families held $10,000 or more worth of stock
in 1997, said Wolff.
</P>
<P>
   The figure has risen, no doubt, with the market gains of the
past three years. The vast majority of American workers, however,
are not getting rich on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Not all analysts accept the suggestion that the economy has
become more ruthless than ever at anointing winners and dispatching
losers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distribution of wealth isn't changing in any significant
way,'' said Weicher. ``We're getting richer, the rich and the poor,
at more or less the same rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all economic debates, this one will be settled, if at all,
only with the aid of several years of hindsight.
</P>
<P>
   By then, if the growing body of data is any guide, the rich will
be far richer still, and the poor will be struggling against
ever-lengthening odds.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
