<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Is Mr. Clean coming out of the closet? 
 &HT;     By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By David Grimes
</P>
<P>
   NYT Regional Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   How would you like it if you'd been unable to speak since birth
and now you're 42 years old and suddenly, miraculously, you find
yourself able to talk and the first question you are asked is ...
Are you gay?
</P>
<P>
   That is the dreary prospect facing Mr. Clean, the bald hunk with
the earring who's been pitching cleaning products since 1958.
</P>
<P>
   In a new version of his Web site set to open later this month,
Mr. Clean will speak in full sentences for the first time.
Possibly, someone will ask him how to get stubborn dog stains out
the carpet or suggest a trick for restoring the luster to whitewall
tires, but this being America and this being the Web and this being
America's brain on the Web, you've got to think a good number of
questions will have to do with Mr. Clean's sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   For all his cleaning prowess, Mr. Clean apparently has no effect
on dirty minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been receiving questions like that for at least the past
10 years,'' Mr. Clean spokesman Damon Jones told Salon's Amy
Reiter. ``We're not sure where it started _ it could have to do
with his earring or his attire _ but we like to think Mr. Clean was
just a man before his time.''
</P>
<P>
   The don't-ask-don't-tell policy may be good enough for the
military, but it's not good enough for Mr. Clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll definitely have an answer to that question,'' Jones
said. ``Whether it will be the answer people want to hear or not,
that's a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear, to me at least, what answer people do want to
hear. What good, after all, is a cleaning product if it never comes
out of the closet? If you keep two Mr. Cleans side-by-side under
your sink, will you be breaking the law in Hawaii? How about Texas?
Why haven't we heard the Rev. Jerry Falwell weighing in on this?
Has he suddenly gone soft on switch-hitting mopping solutions?
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, this flap over Mr. Clean's image comes at a time
when the average American home is dirtier than it's ever been.
</P>
<P>
   According to USA Today, the average time that married couples
spend doing housework has dropped from 36 hours a week in 1965 to
29 hours a week now. The newspaper did not say whether those lost 7
hours are now spent pondering the sexual orientation of fictional
cartoon icons, but I think the implication is clear.
</P>
<P>
   (Guys will be happy, or unhappy, to know that we're doing more
housework now than in 1965, 9 1/2 hours a week compared to 4 1/2
hours. It's women who have slacked off, dropping from 27 hours a
week to 15 1/2 hours. No wonder the house is such a mess.)
</P>
<P>
   I think I speak for a lot of Americans when I say that Mr. Clean
can dress up in high-heels and a low-cut dress if he agrees to come
in and clean bathrooms. The earring thing is not a problem either,
as long as he can get that green mossy stuff out of my shower.
</P>
<P>
   For his 40th birthday two years ago, Procter and Gamble
described the image of Mr. Clean as someone who approaches home
life as a ``partnership'' by ``helping to clean, organize, repair,
shop, assist with homework, provide emotional and other support
(and) makes life better and easier for their mate and everyone in
the home.''
</P>
<P>
   If a person like that volunteered to go to work in my house, I
would be overjoyed and much too grateful to ask what side of the
plate he bats from or any other questions that are none of my
business.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
