<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV18-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 
 &HT;     (For release Friday, Feb. 18)  
 A romantic getaway easy to rationalize  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A short getaway, perhaps to take advantage of the kids going to
your brother's or maybe just a compelling need to be where e-mail
doesn't go, is something that even workaholics can rationalize.
</P>
<P>
   The getaway is not like a real vacation. The umbilical cord to
everyday life is only briefly cut. You don't even have to drive
into a different area code. The goal is to simply play hooky for a
weekend, although it's even more mischievous if you do it in the
middle of the week.
</P>
<P>
   I think that's why B&AMP;B's thrive, because they invite you do the
things that you might do at home if you could indulge yourself free
time without guilt. To stare outside at the rain, read all day by
the fire, eat chocolate in bed. Were you to do this on a Saturday
in your own house someone would certainly wonder if you were sick
or sulking.
</P>
<P>
   We need our getaways, even more so now that so many people's
home is also their office and it's so easy to wreck a Saturday just
by checking your messages.
</P>
<P>
   My pal Rachel, who has an inn in Mendocino, says couples often
come to celebrate birthdays, anniversaries, the last time alone
before the baby comes, even the successful completion of a work
project, but more and more the typical couple ``arrives just
exhausted from their normal frenetic pace. What they're looking for
is an excuse to simply do nothing.'' Think of it. Two days being
unaccountable plus baby soaps and free shampoo -- what a great
escape.
</P>
<P>
   In this economy people have more money than time, says Rachel.
``It's very hard to find time to just squander.'' We live in an
overbooked world, when overtime is the norm and multitasking is an
epidemic. You even have to play productively. You plan an extended
vacation and you better come back with adventures, an award-winning
travel video and a list of little known museum shows. There are
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to report what happens on a quick getaway,
because people are going to think all you did anyhow was stay in
bed and read the funny papers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with some couples there may be one who loves the idea
of getting away and one who wonders why a person would choose to
sleep in a strange bed when their mattress knows them so well.
They'll go out to eat, but sleeping over is pushing it.
</P>
<P>
   In long-ago sexist times, we would have assumed that it is more
a womanly thing to crave a night away and that more women than men
appreciate the novelty of leaving wet towels on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   But, Cathy, who runs a B&AMP;B in California's Wine Country says
just as many men as women call looking for a room and a place to
chill the champagne. This week she talked to a man who explained
his wife was between jobs and for the first time in a long time
they were both free to get away. Last week Cathy hosted a couple
whose seven kids were stashed elsewhere so they could spend the
whole day in her living room just reading and writing.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a promotion for B&AMP;Bs, but a seasonal reminder that
staying over in some clean, cozy spot which has a claw-foot tub and
a deck to sit with your coffee when the sun breaks through can get
a person as many points as booking a trip to France. You don't even
need to take a change of clothes and it doesn't cost that much
considering the huge breakfasts that are part of the deal. Red
roses and poetry are nice but a person can feel very pampered being
led to a tub full of bubbles and told they needn't worry about the
strain on the well and that a clean terry robe is waiting when they
get out.
</P>
<P>
   Simple pampering is what the workaholic couple craves. Sarah
runs an inn in New England and tells people not to come if they
want chandeliers and velvet drapes but do come if they like dogs
and cats, sleeping in a big bed and well-stocked book shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Reading makes me think of chairs which can be an issue. There's
this person who will agree to go away but first he needs
reassurance about the chairs. He gets a little itchy if he walks
into a room that's over-fluffed and the bed is piled high with
heart-shaped pillows. But he can put up with an excess of lace if
at least the chair is right.
</P>
<P>
   We all have our getaway needs and his is a chair that is
comfortable enough to read and doze in. He believes that's
impossible in anything made out of rattan or wicker.
</P>
<P>
   All I want is a room with a view and a fireplace, wood stacked
and ready to light, no TV, no phone, a window that opens and
someone else up early to make the coffee.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
