<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, Feb. 17,
2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GOP-SCMAIN _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ After a testy debate with Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, Arizona Sen. John McCain won the endorsement
of a former rival for the GOP nomination, Gary Bauer, and launched
an upbeat TV ad today assuring voters he ``can win'' the
presidency. Bauer, a conservative activist and former aide to
President Reagan, planned to endorse McCain at a rally today at
Furman University. McCain also was picking up an endorsement today
from Bill Jones, the California secretary of state who had endorsed
Bush last year but has decided to switch to McCain. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution/Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MONEY _ HILTON HEAD, S.C. _ Unexpectedly finding himself in
a battle with John McCain for the GOP presidential nomination,
George W. Bush has spent nearly $50 million of his $68 million war
chest. The campaign took steps Wednesday to downplay the
significance of this figure, but some insiders are clearly worried.
(Herman, Austin American-Statesman). 20-25.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ISSUES _ They don't walk alike. They don't talk alike. But a
close look at the issues shows that for all their style
differenceS, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain
think pretty much alike. A look behind style at the substance.
(Heath, Austin American-Statesman). 25.
</P>
<P>
   ISSUES-GLANCE _ Where Bush and McCain stand on some key issues.
(Heath, Austin American-Statesman). 6.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-GORE _ Southwest Georgia continues to recover from this
week's tornadoes. Vice President Al Gore visits, and holds news
conference with Gov. Roy Barnes. (Quinn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-JUDGE _ ATLANTA _ Superior Court Judge Alice Bonner has
been assigned to the Ray Lewis case. No court appearances are
scheduled yet for Oakley and Sweeting. Their attorneys are expected
to ask that bond hearings be scheduled. Meanwhile, one of Lewis'
attorneys says he'll remain in Atlanta for a couple more days.
Police here and in Baltimore are expected to say more today about
how they'll make sure the Baltimore Ravens All-Pro linebacker is
adhering to the terms of his bond agreement. (Longa/Bixler/Fish,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE _ WASHINGTON _ The American Association the Advancement
of Science, the largest scientific society on Earth, opens its
annual meeting here this week with several thousand scientist ready
to describe research on a variety of topics, ranging from social
science to stem cells. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ Developments from a news conference
President Clinton is holding. (Deans, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   NAVARRO-CANCER _ WASHINGTON _ Chairman Dan Burton, R-Ind., of
the House Government Reform Committee and Republican presidential
candidate Alan Keyes participate in a news conference on a bill
that would grant 4-year-old Thomas Navarro access to an unproven
brain cancer treatment that the Food and Drug Administration
refuses to approve. (Livingston, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-EARNINGS _ WASHINGTON _ The House Social Security
subcommittee meets to mark up a bill that would let Social Security
recipients earn an unlimited amount of money without reducing their
benefits. President Clinton approves the idea. (Lipman, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WATCHDOG _ WASHINGTON _ He's not a household name, but David M.
Walker has a huge assignment: ferreting out the waste and
mismanagement in the $1.5 trillion plus federal government. In an
interview Monday, the new comptroller general of the United States,
a former Atlantan, says Congress needs to spend more time on
oversight and worries that some of the steam may be going out of
the war on waste in the era of surpluses. (Malone, Cox News
Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-FARMERS _ WASHINGTON _ Attorneys representing more than
4,000 farmers announce a lawsuit Wednesday against the U.S.
Department of Agriculture saying its dealaings with major tobacco
companies is causing them economic harm. (Livingston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-AFRICA _ WASHINGTON _ More than 150,000 jobs in the United
States depend on relations with countries in Africa. But many
Americans _ particularly blacks _ are far behind Europeans is
awareness of the business opportunities in Africa. The National
Summit on Africa opening Wednesday addresses that knowledge gap.
Seeking the views of Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell, a vocal proponent
of stronger African-American ties.(Turay, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving spot in (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: With chart information attached at end of the story.
</P>
<P>
   IVORY-COAST _ Alassane Ouattara, the former prime minister of
the Ivory Coast, places enormous faith in democracy. It can, he
says, spur economic growth, calm ethnic strife, reduce corruption
and even slow the spread of AIDS. Yet, despite all that, Ouattara
is glad that a coup in December forced his country's president out
of office. Why? Because he thinks the coup will help, rather than
hinder, democracy. Ouattara plans to run for president in elections
he hopes the Carter Center will monitor. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   KOREA _ Members of the Korean Community Presbyterian Church were
surprised a few year ago when one of their deacons got into a
drunken scuffle and went to prison. The truly shocking news,
however, came when the church learned a few months ago that the
federal government plans to deport the deacon because of a 1996
immigration law roundly criticized as unduly harsh. Worry about the
deacon's predicament became the flash point for the first
well-organized political effort among the roughly 50,000 Korean
immigrants in Georgia. (Bixler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
