<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANK (New York) _ A former Bank of New York executive and
her husband pleaded guilty today to money laundering charges,
admitting they accepted $1.8 million to arrange a tax-evasion
scheme involving the illegal transfer of as much as $10 billion
from Russia. (Summary from wires) By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NATO (Moscow) _ Russia and NATO declared today that they
were restoring their ties after a period in which relations were
practically frozen over the alliance's bombardments of Yugoslavia
and Russia's war in Chechnya. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KOHL (Berlin) _ Wolfgang Schauble effectively resigns as
head of the scandal-plagued Christian Democrats, saying he won't
seek the job at party congress in April. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (London) _ Developments as the principals meet at
10 Downing Street on Northern Ireland. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-HEALTH (Paris) _ Two Spanish newspapers say that the
medical report on Augusto Pinochet, the former Chilean dictator
being held in Britain, finds that he has a worsening brain
condition and ``is not currently fit'' to stand trial. By Marlise
Simons.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-TIME (Jerusalem) _ With Interior Ministry now in hands of
Natan Sharansky rather than the religious-based Shas Party,
Sharansky has decided to unilaterally change when Israel goes off
daylight savings time. The move will bring Israel into synch with
rest of region, but will offend Orthodox whose prayer/fast
scheduled was eased by previous system. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-POLITICS (Beijing) _ The presidential campaign in Taiwan
_ the election is March 18 _ gets ugly as the governing party files
a criminal lawsuit on embezzlement changes against a former top
party official who bolted and is now a leading independent
candidate for president. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S. (Tokyo) _ Strobe Talbott, U.S. deputy secretary of
state, and Japanese officials discuss Japan's desire to reduce its
payments to the U.S. for military support and theater missile
defense. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Boston) _ With heating oils prices rising to $2 a
gallon and politicians from Northeastern states demanding Federal
action, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson hosts heating oil summit.
By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-IMMIG (New Orleans) _ In a sharp change in policy, the
AFL-CIO calls for amnesty for illegal aliens and for an end to
sanctions against employers that hire illegals. This new policy,
which seeks to improve labor's ties with the immigrant community,
is based on the notion that current immigration policy has failed
and has allowed employers to exploit undocumented workers. By
Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-CHINA (New Orleans) _ The AFL-CIO details its plans for
pressuring Congress to bar China from the World Trade Organization.
The labor federation also releases a poll on the subject and lays
out its post-Seattle plans for dealing with globalization. By
Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCHES-POVERTY (Undated) _ An unusually broad ecumenical
group, bridging the usual divisions among Christians, has adopted a
statement calling for a new national effort to fight poverty. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-POLL (Undated) _ Results of the latest N.Y. Times poll
on the national presidential campaign. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   SC-POLITICAL-PROFILE (Dateline to kum) _ A look at the changing
nature of the economy and political power in South Carolina. By Jim
Yardley and David Firestone. (1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN (Dateline to kum, S.C.) _ Day story on John McCain; he's
endorsed by Gary Bauer, who recently quit the GOP race. By Alison
Mitchell. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS () _ News and notes from the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GREEK-BONES (Undated) _ Archeologists say they have found
bones of Athenian soldiers from the Peloponnesian War between
Athens and Sparta. The bones are at Adelphi University on Long
Island. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TOYS-FAIR (New York) _ At the annual Toy Fair in New York, the
seminal event for the nation's toy manufacturers, it is abundantly
clear that technology has become an essential component in toys for
the nation's children practically from the moment of their birth _
replacing the kinds of inanimate objects once considered
playthings, and supplanting adult involvement in activities like
learning the ABC's and singing a baby to sleep. The trend appears
to be breathing new life into toys whose sales might otherwise have
trailed off. But experts worry that many of the newer electronic
toys have effectively eliminated the need to interact with another
person, either adult or child, and may be short-circuiting a
child's social and intellectual development. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-ATTACK (Washington) _ FBI Director Freeh and
Attorney-General Reno testify before Congress about Internet
security. Other developments. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   HP-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Hewlett Packard is to report
first-quarter earnings after the stock market closes. Forecast is
for 78 cents a share. H-P's spinoff, Agilent Technologies, also
posts its first quarterly results. (22 cents). By Lawrence M.
Fisher
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were down in mid-afternoon. At 2:20
p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was off 99 points, the S&AMP;P
500 down 8 points and the Nasdaq composite index was up 50 points.
The long bond was priced to yield 6.27 percent. European markets
were higher, with London up 1.77 percent and Frankfurt up 0.81
percent. In Asia, the Nikkei closed up 1.19 percent and the Hang
Seng ended up 2.13 percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GOLD-PRICE (Undated) _ Looking at gold prices after troubled the
Ashanti Goldfields of Ghana is rescued from collapse. Gold falls
below $300 an ounce in London trading but is higher in early New
York trading. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-DRUGS (Tokyo) _ In an unusual gain by a foreign company,
Boehringer Ingelheim, a German drug maker, has increased its stake
in SS Pharmaceuticals of Japan to nearly 36 percent through an
unsolicited tender offer. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-EARNINGS (London) _ Glaxo Wellcome and Smithkline Beecham,
which will combine to form the world's biggest drug company,
announce results for the year. Glaxo's are lackluster, while
Smithkline's are strong. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
