<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8721 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE17-COX     02-16 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old-fashioned fare has soothing, therapeutic effect
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It gets late early out there.'' _ Yogi Berra
</P>
<P>
   'Tis the season for comfort foods. Unlike those little
medallions of something or other arranged on an oversize plate,
with _ if you're lucky _ a couple of baby carrots and three or four
green beans for color, then drizzled with swirls of some kind of
sauce like a Jackson Pollock painting and topped with a sprig of
brittle herb, comfort food makes no claim at being trendy or arty
or nouveau anything. The claim of comfort food is simply that it
hits the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort food is difficult to categorize. But like art, it
depends on the eye _ or the taste _ of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is life in a nutshell _ you're born, someone slaps you,
you cry, someone gives you milk, you stop crying'' is the
straightforward way comfort foods are described in a cookbook of
the same name by Rita M. Harris.
</P>
<P>
   A bit tonier description comes from ``Simple Abundance: A
Daybook of Comfort and Joy'' by Sarah Ban Breathnach. ``When the
miseries strike and you're down in the dumps, food transformed by
love and memory becomes therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   What all comfort foods do have in common is their ties to our
past and memories of life as a fairly uncomplicated proposition _
before we started obsessing about good and bad cholesterol, fat
ratios and ketosis.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has their own favorite comfort food. If I could but
taste again a stuffed artichoke like my mother, Josephine, used to
make, I know I would weep with the joy of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort food can range from meatloaf and mashed potatoes all the
way to scones. Tomato soup, banana sandwiches, macaroni and cheese,
rice pudding, strawberry shortcake, fried chicken and biscuits, lox
and bagels and veal Parmesan all rate high in the comfort food
category.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort for winter days and nights
</P>
<P>
   If you want to experiment with what comforts others, check out
these sites for some new recipes and new twists that might put some
ease into those chilly, dreary winter days and nights.
</P>
<P>
   Most comfort foods prepared the old-fashioned way don't have
today's higher nutritional standards. If you are serious about good
nutrition, there's no need to give up your favorite comfort foods
of old. Dietitian Michele Peters offers recipes for some
slimmed-down versions of old favorites like macaroni and cheese,
pot roast and meatloaf at
www.homearts.com/mrfood/articles/49comf16.htm.
</P>
<P>
   For other low-fat comfort food recipes, including a beauty for
pineapple upside-down cake, see
www.californiaheartland.org/archive/hl314/comfort.htm.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in Vegetarian Journal, Rachel Himmelheber says
that when she craves comfort food, she goes to the same old-timey
diner and orders a vegetable plate. On one visit, though, she
couldn't keep her eyes off her neighbor's plate, which was heaped
with a hot open-faced hamburger sandwich, with mounds of mashed
potatoes and gravy. ``My fresh corn on the cob was wonderful, but I
</P>
<P>
   envied how rich and comforting their dinner looked.''
</P>
<P>
   She set out to develop vegetarian recipes with the comfort-food
component, including a chicken soup with no chicken that looks like
it may do the trick. See www.vrg.org/journal/vj98jan
</P>
<P>
   /981vegan.htm.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the dietary spectrum comes ``Radiance, the
magazine for large women,'' which put out a call on the Internet to
people in the fat-acceptance and big-folks news groups for stories
about their favorite comfort foods. To check out the great
responses, stories, some humdinger recipes and to see what these
gals can do with peanut butter, eggs, rotini pasta, Monterey Jack
cheese and fudge, see www.radiancemagazine.com
</P>
<P>
   /comfort.html.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort food is not the prerogative of Americans. Asian cultures
have comfort foods, too. For comfort food with an Asian flair, see
www.minorities-jb
</P>
<P>
   .com/asian/AP/1029lifcookingpart2.html.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a comfort food classicist and feel that if it's not
meat and potatoes, it just doesn't count, see ``Comfort Foods Made
Easy With Beef'' at www.gov.mb.ca/agriculture/food/greattastes
</P>
<P>
   /cgt08s01.html.
</P>
<P>
   When you're under the weather, comfort foods take on increased
importance. For ideas on what to put on the dinner tray of a person
in bed with the flu, see www.canoe.ca/CNEWSLifeArchive
</P>
<P>
   /dec1comfort.html.
</P>
<P>
   There are even instructions on making those tiny triangle
sandwiches with the crusts cut off that you got only when you were
home sick in bed.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Meatloaf
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 pound 90 percent to 95 percent lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound ground turkey breast
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   (from 2 to 3 slices bread)
</P>
<P>
   1 (10-ounce) box frozen chopped spinach, thawed, well-drained
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Lightly coat a 5-by-9-inch loaf pan
with nonstick cooking spray. Heat a medium saucepan over medium
heat until hot. Remove from heat and lightly coat with nonstick
cooking spray. Return to heat and add onion. Cover and cook 3 to 4
minutes, or until softened. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, lightly beat egg. Stir in onion, Worcestershire
sauce, ground beef, ground turkey and salt. Mix to break up meat.
Stir in bread crumbs and spinach. Spoon into pan and spread to
smooth. Bake 45 to 50 minutes, or until meatloaf is cooked through
and browned on top. Unmold onto a platter and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 275 calories, 27 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 9 grams carbohydrates, 121
milligrams cholesterol, 400 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1450EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8722 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-POTROAST-COX     02-16 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-POTROAST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's nothing like a pot roast, slow-cooked for Sunday-dinner
like Mom used to make
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My mother's brisket was a company dish, served with buttered
noodles on the Wedgwood platter from the top shelf of the china
closet. My mother's pot roast was a family dinner, a haphazard
thing forgotten in the oven and then served in its battered
roasting pan. We peeled back the aluminum foil cover and pulled off
shreds of meat and pried loose the carrots and potatoes as sweet
and brown and sticky as caramel candy.
</P>
<P>
   Like every good hausfrau of her generation, my mom combined two
of the most common but tasty convenience products _ Lipton onion
soup mix and Heinz chili sauce _ and let the alchemy of the slow
braise take it from there. Time was a readily available seasoning
in her pantry, one she could always add at will to transform cheap
ingredients into the flavors and smells of home.
</P>
<P>
   My home smells like that only on weekends, when I find the time
to even consider the four-hour proposition of a pot roast. But I'm
glad when I do.
</P>
<P>
   Like my mom, I always begin with a chuck blade roast _ the big,
thick, flat, fat-marbled slab that has that beefy flavor deep in
its fiber. A chuck roast is such an easy thing to cook because it
needs only time. It forgives variations in the recipe _ the amount
of braising liquid, the temperature, the cooking vessel _ as it
transforms inexorably from a chewy mass into shred-apart fibers.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, of course, is to catch the roast during the window
when it is succulent and sliceable but before it separates into
visible strings.
</P>
<P>
   I tested chuck roasts for this article, cooking one in a covered
Dutch oven on top of the stove, another in a foil-covered roasting
pan in the oven. I even burnt one beyond all recognition, which is
something my mother never did, I suppose because she always put it
in the oven after ``All My Children'' and took it out when my dad
came home at precisely 6:10.
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, to my taste the best pot roast was cooked in the oven at
275 degrees for slightly more than three hours. After four hours it
begins to dissolve into shreds.
</P>
<P>
   If I wanted to use the braising liquid as a gravy, I found it
necessary to decant it to drain off the copious fat.
</P>
<P>
   We tested some gourmet-seeming recipes that called for white
wine and brandy. We played around and cooked one pot roast with
smoky Mexican chipotle peppers. We looked deep into an empty pantry
and still managed to fashion a great braising liquid from beer,
balsamic vinegar and an oddly perfect secret ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   And then we went back to onion soup mix and chili sauce and
agreed that was the best of all. Even for company.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Note
</P>
<P>
   Chefs and other food professionals often sear meats, then braise
them slowly at low temperatures, but the USDA Meat &AMP; Poultry
Hotline advises home cooks to set their controls higher. Our best
pot roast recipes inside can be made either way.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1450EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8723 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-POTROAST-RECIPES     02-16 2514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-POTROAST-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spiced up or homey, roast will win raves
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The term pot roast is kind of a misnomer if you consider that
the meat is braised rather than roasted and that most people use a
high-sided pan or skillet rather than a pot. But ``braised chuck''
just doesn't have that homey ring, does it?
</P>
<P>
   You can get a chuck blade roast with or without bones, and in
our tests we noticed no difference in how the roasts behaved or
tasted, so it's solely a matter of preference.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some recipes that Mom would approve of. And a few that
she wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chipotle Pot Roast
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 3 1/2-4 hours
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is particularly delicious when you shred the beef
and toss it with the defatted sauce. Then it becomes a delicious
base for tacos and burritos. Otherwise, serve with polenta or
mashed potatoes to soak up the spicy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 top blade roast or top chuck roast (about 3-4 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground Mexican oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon New Mexican red chile powder
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 canned chipotle peppers, mashed
</P>
<P>
   2 cups tomato juice
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 275 degrees (see Safety Note). Heat the oil in a
large skillet over a medium-high flame. Salt and pepper roast and
sear in pan until very brown on both sides. Remove. Add onion and
garlic and saute until translucent, about 3-4 minutes. Add spices
and mashed chipotle and stir until the chile tickles your nose,
about 30-45 seconds. Add tomato juice and stir well, loosening
brown bits in the bottom of the skillet. If skillet is oven-safe,
add roast to pan, cover with foil and place in the oven. If not,
place roast in a high-sided baking dish, pour contents of skillet
into dish and cover with foil. Braise in oven for 3-4 hours, until
very tender. Before serving, decant juices from pan into a large
measuring cup and let fat separate to the top. Remove fat.
</P>
<P>
   If desired, wait until meat is cool enough to handle and shred
it with your fingers. Toss with the reserved pan juices. Serve with
warmed corn or flour tortillas, shredded lettuce, sour cream,
sliced avocado and lime juice.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 390 calories, 32 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 61), 4 grams carbohydrates, 118
milligrams cholesterol, 296 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic-Ale Pot Roast
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 3 1/2-4 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Chinese oyster sauce gives a sweet, earthy depth charge to long
braises as well as stir-fries. And, as odd as the combination
sounds, it combines well with balsamic vinegar. This easy recipe
has more flavor than the short ingredient list would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 top blade roast or top chuck roast (3-4 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium white onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle of good ale (we used Pete's Wicked Ale)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Chinese oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 275 degrees (see Safety Note). Heat the oil in a
large skillet over a medium-high flame. Season roast with salt and
pepper and sear in pan until very brown on both sides. Remove. Add
sliced onions to pan and stir until they begin to wilt and turn
fragrant. Add remaining ingredients and stir well, loosening brown
bits in the bottom of the skillet. If skillet is oven-safe, add
roast to pan, cover with foil and place in the oven. If not, place
roast in a high-sided baking dish, pour contents of skillet into
dish and cover with foil.
</P>
<P>
   Braise in oven for 3-4 hours, until very tender. Before serving,
decant juices from pan into a large measuring cup and let fat
separate to the top. Remove fat.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 388 calories, 32 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 61), 3 grams carbohydrates, 118
milligrams cholesterol, 370 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pot Roast (Braised Roast)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 3 1/2 to 4 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   The coffee and brandy give this pot roast a subtle perfume. The
author, a ``Cook's Illustrated'' editor, tested pot roasts cooked
at different temperatures and found that the relatively low 200
degrees produces the most succulent roast. The USDA recommends 325
degrees for safety. See Safety Note.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 pot roast (top blade roast or top chuck roast), about 3 pounds
</P>
<P>
   2 slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon instant coffee powder mixed with 1 tablespoon hot
water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup low-salt beef or chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brandy
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cornstarch mixed with 1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 200 degrees (see Safety Note). Mix together the
thyme, cloves, allspice, pepper and salt and rub over meat.
</P>
<P>
   Cook bacon in a heavy pot just large enough to hold the pot
roast. Remove bacon (reserve for another recipe) and all but 1
tablespoon of fat. Add olive oil and brown pot roast on all sides
over medium-high heat. Remove meat to a platter or bowl; add onion
and carrot to pot and saute for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add wine, coffee, broth, brandy and bay leaf and scrape bottom
of pot with a wooden spoon. Boil rapidly for 3 minutes, stirring
constantly. Add pot roast, along with juices that have accumulated
in the bowl, and cook over medium heat until liquid starts to
simmer. Ladle liquid over roast and cover roast loosely with
aluminum foil. Cover pot tightly with aluminum foil, then cover
with lid. Immediately place in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Cook about 3-4 hours. Remove meat from pot and cover with
aluminum foil, then pour braising liquid into the bowl of a food
processor. Process for 7 seconds. Return puree to the pot, place
over medium heat and bring to a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Add the cornstarch mixture and whisk until thickened. Serve with
sliced pot roast.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure cooker variation: This is the best method for cooking a
pot roast, but you will need a 5-quart pressure cooker to hold the
meat.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the directions above, browning the meat in the pressure
cooker, and when the pot roast is added back to the pot after
browning, place the roast in the pressure cooker on top of the
trivet (most models have round metal trays that allow the roast to
sit above the liquid; if yours does not have one, simply place the
roast on the bottom of the cooker), secure the top of the cooker
and bring it up to high pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Cook under high pressure for 60 minutes. Remove from heat, allow
pot to cool on stovetop, and when pressure subsides, remove cover
and proceed. _ From ``The Cook's Bible'' by Christopher Kimball
(Little, Brown)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 412 calories, 32 grams protein, 29 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 63), 3 grams carbohydrates, 119
milligrams cholesterol, 288 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pam's Mom's Brisket
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 1/2 to 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Is it simply the nostalgia that makes this taste so good? That
unmistakable odor of onion soup mix meeting chili sauce and onions
that so many people remember from childhood? Who knows. But if
there's a better pot roast on the planet, we'd like to find out.
</P>
<P>
   Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 package dried onion soup mix
</P>
<P>
   3 medium onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 celery ribs, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bottled chili sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle lager beer
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 (4- to 6-pound) piece of beef brisket or chuck or 6 pounds
short ribs, trimmed of most external fat
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Water or beef stock if necessary
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Combine sauce ingredients (soup mix
through water) in a large Dutch oven with a cover or in a covered
casserole. Put the meat in and spoon some of the sauce over the
top. Cover the pot and bake for 2 1/2 to 4 hours. Check the meat
after 2 1/2 hours to see if it's fork tender. If not, cook until
done. Ideally, you should refrigerate the meat and sauce overnight,
remove the congealed fat, then slice and reheat the meat in the
sauce. Or you can degrease the sauce, taste for salt and pepper,
slice the meat and serve it in the sauce immediately. If the sauce
seems too thick, dilute it with a little water or stock. _ From
``The Complete Meat Cookbook'' by Bruce Aidells and Denis Kelly
(Houghton Mifflin)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 360 calories, 42 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 44), 6 grams carbohydrates, 127
milligrams cholesterol, 363 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chefs and food professionals, including Atlanta food scientist
Shirley Corriher, widely tout cooking roasts at 200 degrees for
maximum flavor and tenderness and maintain the practice is safe, so
long as the meat is seared first, to kill any surface bacteria, and
cooks no longer than 4 hours in an accurate oven. Be sure to test
the temperature of your oven with an oven thermometer. Cooking it
longer at a low temperature could create an environment where
harmful toxins can develop, Corriher says.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA, however, recommends not taking any chances and advises
cooking meats at a temperature no lower than 325 degrees. The meat
will not be as tender, Corriher says, but it should be acceptable.
(Incidentally, the pot roast method in ``Joy of Cooking'' (1980
edition) calls for cooking a 3- to 4-pound roast at 300 to 325
degrees for 3 to 4 hours.)
</P>
<P>
   If you do go the higher-temperature route, Corriher suggests
cooking the meat several hours longer than the cooking time called
for, adding more liquid if necessary to keep it from drying out.
For tough cuts of meat, longer cooking times produce more tender
</P>
<P>
   results, ``so it will eventually reach a fall-apart stage,
although it still won't be as tender and juicy as one cooked at a
lower temperature.''
</P>
<P>
   Any pot roast recipe, she adds, also may be adapted for a
crockpot. After searing the meat, place it in the crockpot first on
high for 30 minutes, then on low for 7 or 8 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Choose the cooking method you feel most comfortable with. If you
are serving the roast to anyone who is very young, very old or has
a compromised immune system, it's wisest to go with the USDA
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Moroccan Pot Roast
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Food stylist Mary Ann Clayton, who devised this recipe,
recommends serving it with soft polenta _ a better match for the
robust sauce than couscous. It would also be good with rice.
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground black pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1 3-pound beef roast, chuck or brisket
</P>
<P>
   2 preserved lemons, rinsed (found in jars in Asian and Indian
groceries and some gourmet foods shops), and cut in thin strips
</P>
<P>
   1 cup brined black olives (Greek or Kalamata), pitted
</P>
<P>
   5 small onions, quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   2 cups hot water
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl combine the paprika, coriander, cinnamon, black
pepper and turmeric. Pat this mixture on the beef roast and place
in a roasting pan. Add the lemons, olives and onions to the pan.
Dissolve the honey in the water and pour over the roast. Pour in
additional water to a depth of 1 inch. Cover tightly and bake for 3
1/2 to 4 hours. Check periodically after a couple of hours to make
sure roast does not dry out. Add a little more water if necessary
to ensure about 2 cups of sauce. When roast is falling-apart
tender, remove from oven and let it rest about 20 minutes before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 424 calories, 35 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 57), 10 grams carbohydrates, 119
milligrams cholesterol, 249 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pot Roast Pasta
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here, leftover pot roast can be used like Italian gravy meat and
be the basis for a ragu with the wide-ribbon pasta called
pappardelle.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 large carrot, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 28-ounce can tomatoes, with juice
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pasta, preferably pappardelle or pantacce
</P>
<P>
   2 cups leftover pot roast, coarsely shredded
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in pot large enough to hold sauce and pasta. Add onion
and saute for 2 minutes; add garlic and continue to cook until
onion is transparent. Add carrots, tomatoes with their juice and
the bay leaf; bring to a boil, reduce heat and simmer until carrots
are tender, about 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, cook the pasta according to directions, just
until al dente. Drain the pasta and add it to the sauce, along with
the shredded pot roast. Toss and cook for about 2 minutes. Transfer
to serving bowls and sprinkle with parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 538 calories, 27 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 29), 68 grams carbohydrates, 53
milligrams cholesterol, 266 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia ``Roast Beef'' Sandwich (Braised Beef and Red
Pepper Hoagie)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 generous serving
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a great use for leftover pot roast.
</P>
<P>
   1 (8- to 10-inch) soft Italian or French roll or piece of French
baguette
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 ounces thickly sliced cooked pot roast made from chuck,
brisket, rump or round plus 1/4 cup of the braising liquid
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup thinly sliced onion from pot roast (or sauteed until
soft in 1 tablespoon olive oil)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced red bell pepper, sauteed until soft in 1
tablespoon olive oil, or 1/2 cup bottled, roasted red peppers in
oil, cut into rough strips
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   For garnish:
</P>
<P>
   Sliced bottled sweet or yellow peppers
</P>
<P>
   Chopped chard, sauteed with olive oil and garlic
</P>
<P>
   Split roll, keeping two halves attached. Set aside. Reheat the
pot roast slices in the braising liquid for 5 minutes in a covered
pot or in the microwave for 1 minute in a covered container. Spread
the meat over the roll. Spoon all the gravy over the meat and layer
on the onion and red peppers. Lightly salt and pepper the sandwich
and eat it right away with garnishes. _ From ``The Complete Meat
Cookbook'' by Bruce Aidells and Denis Kelly (Houghton Mifflin)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 900 calories, 50 grams protein, 45 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), 71 grams carbohydrates, 135
milligrams cholesterol, 802 milligrams sodium, 6 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
