<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fudge formula classic treat made for sweet tooth
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fudge formula sent in by Anna Judd of Lawrenceville, Ga.,
should satisfy Phyllis Flory's sweet tooth. Someone Flory used to
know made a fudge with light brown sugar that tasted much like the
See's brand, and she hoped to duplicate it.
</P>
<P>
   Judd, who recently moved South from southern Indiana, found the
</P>
<P>
   recipe in a small book called ``Candy Cookbook,'' published in
1966 by Favorite Recipes Press in Nashville. ``It's one of those
oldies full of classics,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She has made this fudge many times and says her daughter really
likes it.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Brown Sugar Fudge
</P>
<P>
   Makes 36 pieces
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10-12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup firmly packed
</P>
<P>
   light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugars and milk in a saucepan; cook over low heat until
sugars dissolve, then increase heat to medium and boil until soft
ball stage (234-240 degrees), stirring occasionally. Remove from
heat; stir in butter and vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Place pan in sink of cool water to stop cooking. (The mixture
may look curdled but will smooth out when beaten.) Beat until very
thick. Add nuts; pour into greased 8-inch square pan. Let stand
about 30 minutes. Cut into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 65 calories, 1 gram protein, 2 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 23), 12 grams carbohydrates, 2 milligrams
cholesterol, 11 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Request
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Schleicher of Atlanta asks for a flan recipe that was
in a paperback cookbook of recipes from Spain. The flan had a layer
of caramelized prune paste instead of caramelized sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
