<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, Feb. 17:
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN-LEGACY (New York) _ In London, Washington and, most
recently New York, attendance at the traveling exhibition on
Charles and Ray Eames, the post-war design mavericks, broke museum
records. But most people filing by to marvel at their plywood
molding experiments _ the prototypes that didn't quite cut it and,
eureka!, the ones that did _ were unaware that nearly every major
American institution had passed on the opportunity to buy the
Eameses legacy of furniture invention. The Museum of Modern Art and
the Metropolitan Museum of Art were among those that turned it
down, leaving the Eames family faced with huge inheritance taxes,
the threat of eviction and the prospects of selling off the
products, piecemeal, to resale stores. The preservation movement
that routinely takes up arms to protect buildings with an
established cultural significance has yet to take an active role in
saving America's modern design legacy. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   METAL-INTERIORS (New York) _ Americans consumed 130 million tons
of steel last year. Some were extremely fussy about it. The
minimalist vogue has elected crude metal the interior material of
the moment. From the TSE boutique to Gianni Versace to the Giorgio
Armani offices and showroom, enough steel, aluminum and bronze has
gone in recently to make New York City the newest Rust Belt. And
Thomas Hand, a metalworker and ex-sculptor with a studio on Leonard
Street in TriBeCa, is the cold-rolled-steel set's current ``It''
Boy. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   DIANNA-ROSE (Undated) _ When Elton John sang ``Goodbye England's
Rose'' at Westminster Abbey in 1997, who knew it would lead to
``Hello Garden Sales''? Bonnie Masterson, who runs a little company
called Collectible Commemorative Gardens out of Tulsa, Okla., calls
it ``one of life's little miracles.'' Lt. Col. Kenneth Grapes, the
director general of the Royal National Rose Society in England,
thinks it is ``the most extraordinary coincidence you ever heard
of.'' The players, with their collision of rolling Southern accents
and clipped British voices, are all counting on profits to flow in
from a new rose dedicated to Diana, Princess of Wales. By Anne
Raver.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitizki.
</P>
<P>
   DOG-PICTURES (New York) _ When the John Emms painting of dogs
called ``A Jack and Two Knaves'' sold on Tuesday for $125,000, more
than three times the low estimate, the audience let out a
collective whoop _ and the auctioneers breathed a sigh of relief.
Only two lots before, another Emms painting ``Sailor and Bramble''
didn't sell at all. Tuesday was Dog Day at the William Doyle
Galleries. With the Westminster Kennel Club show packing dog lovers
in to the point of claustrophobia at Madison Square Garden, the
auctioneers hoped this would be an ideal time to auction off
hundreds of canine pictures, many of debatable value. By Tracie
Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
