<HEADER>
A8753 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-GOURMET-RAFTING-2000(     02-16 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOURMET-RAFTING-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-GOURMET-TRIPS) 
FAR FLUNG'S GRANDE GASTRONOMIC ADVENTURES NOT SO FAR-FETCHED
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanied by BC-GOURMET-RECIPES, BC-GOURMET-LIST,(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TERLINGUA, Texas _ Just how gourmet, we wondered, could a Rio
Grande rafting trip be? We were camping on the Mexican border, more
than 100 miles from even so much as a cappuccino stand.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we of little faith. How gravely we underestimated our
Swiss-born chef, who has more than a dozen years' experience at
river catering: 14 pounds of salmon, 7 pounds of duck breast, 7
pounds of lamb and 60 bottles of wine later, we had embraced
gastronomic nirvana, Chihuahua Desert-style.
</P>
<P>
   Like all groups that take one of the eight trips offered by
outfitter Far Flung Adventures and catered by San Antonio chef
Francois Maeder, the 17 travelers on a three-day float on the Rio
Grande last fall quickly became passionate rafting-cuisine
converts. We swooned as do newly infatuated lovers over the
culinary surprises wrought by a skilled and cheerful staff that
wooed us well with truffles, cream and cognac.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a shared adoration for exquisite food _ mind you,
we're the kind of people who habitually speak with fervor about
what's for dinner while we're savoring every morsel of lunch _ we
shared an appetite for the irresistible measures of mysterious
beauty and isolation that the Big Bend region of southwesternmost
Texas holds.
</P>
<P>
   Our journey began roughly a half-hour's drive west of Big Bend
National Park. After a quick safety chat from one of the guides,
who emphasized the importance of drinking gallons of water in this
desert environment, we were afloat.
</P>
<P>
   The delightful surprise in my raft was better than most
desserts: Our oarsman, the guy who would do all the work for our
minigroup of four, was singer/songwriter Butch Hancock, a Terlingua
resident who's currently touring with his Lubbock pals as the
Flatlanders. Nearly every gourmet trip Far Flung sponsors comes
with entertainment by Hancock or acclaimed Texas music man Steven
Fromholz.
</P>
<P>
   There was just enough water in the Rio Grande to keep the raft
moving, but Butch had to row if we wanted to get anywhere. We
spotted bright-red birds called vermilion flycatchers, myriad
ducks, hundreds of turtles along the way. We talked about food.
</P>
<P>
   Our days of floating were interludes so lazy that some
passengers actually napped on the rounded sides of their rafts. As
Hancock rowed, he pointed out geological oddities in low rises on
either side of the river and shared the homespun philosophies that
come easily to songwriters.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly two hours had passed before our first lunch stop, but it
was long enough that some floaters were sunburned and a few beer
drinkers were talking amusing trash. Our accomplished guides put
down their oars and picked up knives to artfully slice tomatoes and
oranges, which they spread on platters with lovely cheeses. We had
impressive platters of cold cuts and spreads such as pesto and
sun-dried tomato with cracked-pepper crackers; none of that Cheese
Nips tackiness, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The first dinner and sleep-over took place at the wax camp, a
campsite on the Mexican side of the river so named for the
proliferation of candeleria plants that are harvested for wax. The
desolate, sandy clearing a few yards from the river quickly became
a small village where river guides tossed up tents in moments,
while the kitchen was erected and put in business by Francois and
two assistants who traveled with him from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   In 13 years of catering such gourmet rafting gigs several times
each spring and fall, Francois' operation has become seamless. With
Francois' own employees and the experienced hands of the three or
four oarsmen, the elaborate meal unfolded with the precision of a
well-practiced prep line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think menus like this would be hard to prepare at home for
this many people, much less when camping out,'' said Carol
Giddings, a traveler and novice camper from Corpus Christi, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Those who don't get the chow jobs have the tasks of pitching
tents, setting up dining tables and establishing the latrines.
Clearly, KP is the desired duty.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's social hour was spent munching Francois' truffle
pate and the cream cheese-stuffed salmon rolls prepared by one of
the oarsmen and sampling various chardonnay and pinot noir
selections. As rafting patrons mingled, we established that our
group was perfectly safe; our numbers, it turned out, included two
physicians and four nurses.
</P>
<P>
   As more wine was poured, we discovered that the retired
commercial airline pilot among us was a devoted bird-watcher. At
the end of the wine guzzling, we found that the two older women in
our outfit would be the most dedicated snorers.
</P>
<P>
   While we quaffed and visited, a dining room sprang up: From the
supply rafts came a spread of folding tables, draped in
snow-white-and-azure linens, as well as folding chairs, glass wine
goblets, china and stainless steel cutlery.
</P>
<P>
   We discovered that the Orvieto classico was an ideal companion
for our first course, angel-hair pasta tossed with olive oil, pine
nuts, sun-dried tomato shreds, freshly chopped garlic and freshly
shredded Parmesan. This was followed by the exquisite main course,
lamb chops cloaked and soaked in a Dijon sauce, then grilled over
an open fire _ for which a nice accompaniment was a Napa cabernet.
</P>
<P>
   Ardent ooohs and aaahhs were heard. Repeatedly. Who said eating
isn't a sensual experience?
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
