<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GRAND JURY PROBE FOCUSES ON BROWN SUPPORTER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LANCE WILLIAMS and CHUCK FINNIE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal grand jury is scrutinizing financial
deals involving Mayor Willie Brown's office and his friend Charlie
Walker, federal subpoenas show.
</P>
<P>
   In four subpoenas issued from June through January, the grand
jury told the mayor's staff to turn over records involving
businesses through which Walker, a political supporter and former
law client of Brown, has sought city funds since Brown became mayor
of San Francisco in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Among the businesses of interest to the grand jury: a candy
company for which Walker unsuccessfully sought a
multimillion-dollar city loan and a nonprofit organization, the
Third Street Economic Development Corp., that obtained a $100,000
federal loan from Brown's Office of Community Development.
</P>
<P>
   The loan to the nonprofit organization is already under scrutiny
by the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development, which told
the city in a letter that the Third Street operation improperly
used the money to buy a building later used as a mosque by the
Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoenas were served at Brown's office, at the Mayor's
Office of Community Development and at an entity known as the
Mayor's Youth Fund. Taken together, they show that the grand jury's
probe has expanded beyond its original scope.
</P>
<P>
   When it began a year ago, FBI agents were investigating possible
criminal wrongdoing involving suspected contracting abuses at the
San Francisco International Airport, which is undergoing a $2.4
billion expansion.
</P>
<P>
   According to people who were interviewed, agents asked about
Walker, who was imprisoned in the 1980s for abusing the city's
minority contracting program, but who in recent years has won about
$800,000 in subcontracts at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The new subpoenas show the FBI and grand jury also are looking
into grants and loans administered by the mayor's office, as well
as real estate projects on city property.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 25 subpoena, for instance, the panel sought records of
meetings between Brown and developers seeking to build an
industrial park at Piers 90 and 92 and housing at the Hunters Point
Naval Shipyard. Both properties are controlled by commissions
appointed by the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been charged with wrongdoing, but the grand jury also
has subpoenaed more than a dozen people, including airport Director
John Martin, to testify.
</P>
<P>
   In July, FBI agents searching for evidence even shut the offices
of the city's Human Rights Commission for a weekend, while they
searched for documents.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has referred questions about the federal probe to the city
attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy City Attorney Joanne Hoeper said Tuesday the mayor has
urged city officials to do ``everything in their power to
cooperate'' with the investigators. She said the subpoenaed records
had been delivered to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has declined to answer questions about the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the subpoenas, the grand jury sought records regarding the
Third Street Economic Development Corp., the organization Walker
founded.
</P>
<P>
   The company is best known for hosting an annual gala honoring
the mayor, but is in a wrangle with HUD over alleged misuse of the
$100,000 grant administered by the mayor's office.
</P>
<P>
   In its grant application, the Third Street company claimed it
had been granted charitable tax-exempt status. But according to the
Internal Revenue Service, it has never received the tax-exempt
status it needed to obtain the grant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, public records show that, without telling the city,
Third Street last May sold a building to the Nation of Islam, which
used it as a mosque. Last month, a local HUD official told the city
it should repay the $100,000 because it was improper to spend
federal funds on religious activities.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office has been trying to get Walker to account for
the transaction, but has not been successful, city records show.
</P>
</TEXT>
