<HEADER>
A8769 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUSTRIA-INTELLECTUALS     02-16 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-INTELLECTUALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR RIGHT'S ASCENT DIVIDES AUSTRIAN INTELLECTUALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA _ Maybe it was just coincidence, but a few days after the
far right Freedom Party took power in Austria, Walter Famler, the
editor of a left-leaning literary magazine, got a letter from the
federal government informing him that it was canceling its
subscription.
</P>
<P>
   Famler doesn't think the order came from Joerg Haider, the
charismatic leader of the Freedom Party who has a habit of speaking
sympathetically about Nazis while demeaning liberals and
immigrants. Instead, he sees a more worrisome possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some civil servant decided it would not look good to have our
magazine in government offices,'' said Famler, editor and publisher
of Wespennest, which publishes essays by many of Austria's leading
intellectuals. ``Self-censorship is worse and harder to confront
than official censorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Freedom Party and the mainstream conservative
People's Party formed a coalition government three weeks ago,
intellectuals and artists have engaged in a heated debate whether
the rise of the far fight imperils intellectual and artistic
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   While the government has not published its cultural agenda, the
new culture minister, Frank Morak, has suggested there will be
budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   While a few artists have likened the arrival of the Freedom
Party to that of the National Socialists in 1938, when the Nazis
annexed a willing Austria, many others, like Famler, consider that
a gross exaggeration and see the rise of the right here as
something that should inspire caution, not panic.
</P>
<P>
   Like the reaction to Haider's party taking power in general, the
outrage among artists and intellectuals seems to have been stronger
outside the country. Lou Reed, the ageless American rocker,
canceled an upcoming concert in Vienna. Elie Wiesel, the
Romanian-born Nobel Peace Prize laureate and Boston University
professor, canceled a lecture in May. French actress Catherine
Deneuve canceled her appearance at the Opera Ball, Vienna's premier
social event. (The Vienna State Opera is of particular interest in
Boston because that will be the new home of outgoing Boston
Symphony Orchestra music director Seiji Ozawa in 2003.)
</P>
<P>
   Sylvain Cambreling, conductor of Germany's Sudwestrundfunk
Orchestra, said that while he is committed to play in this year's
Salzburg Festival, he would no longer perform in Austria because,
``I cannot work with people I consider to be fascists.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Mortier, the Belgian-born artistic director of the
Salzburg Festival who has complained about government interference
in the past, pushed up his departure by a year because of the
Freedom Party's rise.
</P>
<P>
   Artists also have said the rise of the Freedom Party is a threat
to civility and, by extension, artistic integrity. Elfriede
Jelinek, one of Austria's leading dramatists, has forbidden any of
her plays from being performed as long as the Freedom Party is in
power.
</P>
<P>
   While Jelinek also threatened to leave, Ioan Holender, director
of the Vienna State Opera, said artists and intellectuals have a
duty to stay and express their dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not happy with the situation,'' he said. ``But in times
like this we should not close the doors but open our mouths louder.
If we close the doors now, we do exactly what happened with the
Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   With that last sentiment, Holender hit on what has transformed
this debate from one that could be dismissed as just a bunch of
pampered elitists complaining about threats to their subsidies to
one that has extraordinary resonance in a city that could tolerate
the racist diatribes of a young Adolf Hitler and could find no way
to save Sigmund Freud from forced exile.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reaction here, and especially outside Austria, can
be explained by history, especially that of the Holocaust, said
Peter Gerlich, a professor of political science at the University
of Vienna. ``It is an exaggeration to call Haider a fascist,'' said
Gerlich. ``But it doesn't matter if he's a Nazi, because so many
people outside Austria think he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Famler said he is in constant contact with intellectuals across
Europe and is disturbed by what they are telling him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had a conversation with a German intellectual, and he
said intellectuals outside of Austria are developing a picture in
which we are the new Serbs. This is very dangerous. Intellectually
and artistically, we could be seen as the new pariah state, whether
that reputation is deserved or not.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, when the Nazis rolled into this gracious city, many
artists and intellectuals rolled out. Some fled because they knew
their artistic integrity would be compromised. Others, like Freud,
the father of psychoanalysis, were Jews and fled for their lives as
well as for their intellectual freedom. Freud got out, but his four
sisters were not as lucky. They were sent to concentration camps
and, like all but 2,000 of the 60,000 Viennese Jews sent to the
camps, were killed. There were 185,000 Jews in Vienna before 1938;
today there are 12,000.
</P>
<P>
   It is often said, only half in jest, that Austria's greatest
accomplishment was that it convinced the world that Hitler was
German and Beethoven was Austrian. In the city where Hitler was
allowed to hone his Aryan theories by arguing them in Vienna's
cafes while Freud had to die in exile in London, the question about
the relationship between the intellectual and the government
remains volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian artists and intellectuals depend heavily on government
subsidies. Famler's magazine, for example, gets a quarter of its
budget from the government. Now that the government has canceled
its subscription, he wonders if the magazine's grant is next. He
said the 12-year-old magazine would fold without its subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, sitting in his office in the capital of Carinthia, the
southern province where he is governor, laughed out loud when told
that artists and intellectuals are worried that the government will
cut back heavily on culture, and seek to censor art and writings
that are critical of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the opposite will happen,'' said Haider, whose office
walls are adorned with the usual ``grip-and-grin'' snapshots of
politicians and with several postmodern paintings. ``I'm
responsible for culture here in Carinthia, and we have spent more,
not less than the last government here. We started a program to
enlarge subsidies. Just ask the actors and artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced. The relatives of the late Ingeborg
Bachmann, a great Austrian poet and author, said Bachmann's name
could not be used on the annual literature prize given in her
memory until Haider guarantees freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing hard on a thin cigar, Gerlich, the bearded, bespectacled
professor, said he does not think Haider will clamp down on the
freedom of expression any harder than the Republicans in Congress
who went after the National Endowment for the Arts for funding
controversial pieces
</P>
<P>
   ``Culturally, I have no fear,'' Gerlich said, exhaling a long
stream of smoke into the air. ``It's simply not true to say that
Austrian civic society is not aware of the past and has not learned
from it. We are and we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Famler, the editor who puts a high-brow magazine out on a
shoestring, is more concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international image is so damaged it will take at least a
decade to get over this,'' he said. ``Intellectuals are leaving.
International performers will not perform here. International
orchestras are cancelling.''
</P>
<P>
   But while he believes calling Haider a Nazi is an exaggeration,
Famler defends the outrage of some artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an overreaction,'' he said. ``Artists send signals.
It is right and proper that they express their concern.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1531EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
