<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8781 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-GOURMET-RAFTING-2ndTa     02-16 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOURMET-RAFTING-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
TERLINGUA, Texas: sensual experience? 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost superfluous were the steamed broccoli and a fluffy green
salad, but the latter was drizzled with Francois' signature creamy
tarragon dressing, subtle and wonderful. Along with dessert _ a
sublime trifle of sponge cake, whipped cream, Baileys, almonds and
white chocolate _ were offerings of port, cognac and cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Francois joined the diners and talked about his work as
chef/owner of Crumpets, a San Antonio restaurant. ``Where does he
get his inspiration?'' the diners asked. ``Where does this artistry
come from?''
</P>
<P>
   It's just a job he enjoys, he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chefs who act like food is art just tick me off,'' said
Francois, who came to San Antonio from Geneva by way of Canada in
1978. ``It's not art. It might be a craft, maybe. But it's really
just a trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The cognac flowed still longer as Butch played his guitar and
sang his songs. Later, those who were sober enough peered at the
crowded blanket of stars through a thoughtfully supplied telescope.
Most everyone was asleep before midnight, but many woke when the
moon made a dramatic rise like a spotlight at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's breakfast was gobbled by a group that was half
bleary-eyed and searching for aspirin and half bright-eyed but
sand-coated from an overnight windstorm. Plenty of strong cowboy
coffee, fresh orange wedges, eggs Benedict on fresh croissants and
fruit pastries kept spirits aloft.
</P>
<P>
   When someone wondered aloud how much wine had been consumed the
night before, Francois announced the tally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-eight bottles,'' he said. ``You're a bunch of
lightweights.''
</P>
<P>
   Our Saturday float took in a setting moon in the deeply blue
Mexican sky, a skunk darting in and out of the riverside brush, a
gorgeous red horse grazing along the bank. The sighting of a dead
beaver drew a ``There's lunch!'' quip from Francois. Nary a snake,
nary a gar _ not that you can see anything in the muddy Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   The rafting staff whipped up a stellar lunch salad of shredded
chicken breasts, which had been chargrilled the night before, mixed
with apples, nuts and seasonings. This was accompanied by more
pesto and sun-dried tomato spreads, olives, smoked oysters and
myriad pickles.
</P>
<P>
   We hiked up rocky hillsides to look down into the mouth of Santa
Elena Canyon, which we drifted deep within after lunch. Guides
described the geological history detailed in layers of ancient,
soaring cliff walls and pointed out cactus we should _ but didn't
always manage to _ avoid.
</P>
<P>
   An afternoon of floating, enveloped by the craggy, towering
walls of Santa Elena Canyon, put us at sunset in our second
campsite _ and into a second stunning riverside nighttime feast.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the sea of tables swept with fresh linens came a
bountiful spread of platters of brie and crackers and chilled
marinated shrimp. During this ``cocktail hour,'' we were serenaded
by Houston oarsman Mike Casper, whose alias _ for good reason _ is
Dr. Fun and who sings a mean Cat Stevens song while playing the
guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Francois crafted a sensational saute of shallots, red wine and
cocoa for the juicy duck breasts he served as appetizers. This he
followed with a main course of gorgeous Alaskan silver salmon
fillets, simply seasoned with dill and black pepper, then
chargrilled and served with crisp, steamed asparagus and a fresh
green salad.
</P>
<P>
   Much merriment, augmented by plenty of port and cognac, followed
our dessert of fresh berry trifle. Butch Hancock and Dr. Fun led
hours of singing beside a roaring campfire before jolly rafters
stumbled over soft, sandy hills to tents and sleep.
</P>
<P>
   As we feasted on chubby breakfast burritos Sunday morning, we
watched a pair of peregrine falcons work the canyon wall, one
acting as a decoy while the second swooped down and nabbed a
white-throated swift for a meal. Breakfast as drama in the Santa
Elena.
</P>
<P>
   Our final float took us out of the canyon and to a hiking
excursion within a lush fern gully on the Mexican side of the
river. An easy climb inside a boulder-strewn limestone cranny
involved one quick stretch through an icy, spring-fed waterfall,
undertaken by all except the rafter who had injured her foot
stepping between rocks, and the one fearful of heights. Even the
party guy who bemoaned the growing distance between himself and his
beer cooler was a good sport.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal finale for our gourmet group was a floating Sunday
afternoon lunch. Tying our rafts together, we drifted for an hour,
drinking champagne and eating a lovely tortellini salad tossed with
vinaigrette and sun-dried tomatoes. Dr. Fun offered a farewell
serenade with softened versions of ``L.A. Woman'' and ``Mustang
Sally.''
</P>
<P>
   Vans awaited us, driving us through the national park, past
landmarks such as Mule Ear Peaks. Too soon, these sights were
replaced by the bleaker (for us, anyway) monuments of reality _ the
golden arches.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
7 nn
</P>
</TEXT>
