r d BC-BUNDY-RECIPES-TEX     02-16 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUNDY-RECIPES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READERS, START YOUR STOVES; HERE ARE SOME REQUESTED RECIPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're all about your requests this week; readers have been busy
searching for lost recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Dillard of Mineral Wells, Texas, sent the requested
recipe for pecan brittle.
</P>
<P>
   EASY PECAN BRITTLE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 pound
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup pecans, broken
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup white Karo syrup
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, pecans, water and syrup in a large saucepan. Cook
over moderate heat until it turns color, about 8 minutes. Remove
from heat and add soda. Beat with spoon until thoroughly mixed.
Pour quickly onto a buttered cookie sheet and spread thin. When
completely cooled, break into small pieces.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER 1-OUNCE SERVING: 122 calories, 5 grams
fat, 21 grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 38
milligrams sodium, 34 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BUCKEYES WITHOUT PARAFFIN: Many, many readers sent in the recipe
for chocolate-covered peanut butter balls. Called Buckeyes, after
the symbol of Ohio, most of the recipes included melted paraffin to
be mixed with the chocolate coating to make it solidify quicker.
Paraffin won't hurt you, but the idea of eating wax is a bit
distasteful. So, here are two recipes that omit the paraffin.
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT BUTTER BALLS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 30
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 tablespoons butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup sifted powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   _ 8 ounces chocolate-flavored candy coating
</P>
<P>
   In mixing bowl, combine peanut butter and butter. Gradually add
powdered sugar, stirring until combined. Shape into 1-inch balls;
place on wax paper. Let stand until dry _ about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Chop candy coating. Place in heavy saucepan, cook and stir over
low heat until melted and smooth. Cool slightly. Dip balls, one at
a time, into coating. Let excess coating drip off peanut butter
balls. Place on wax paper; let stand until coating is firm. Store
tightly covered in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER BALL: 90 calories, 6 grams fat, 9 grams
carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 3 milligrams cholesterol, 13
milligrams sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT BUTTER SQUARES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 117 (cq) pieces
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 sticks margarine, melted
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup creamy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup graham cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 pound powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   _ 12 ounces chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except chocolate and press into
9-by-13-inch glass pan. Melt chocolate and spread on top. Let stand
for 2 hours and cut into 1-inch squares. Don't put in refrigerator
before cutting because chocolate will crack when you cut it.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRIBUTOR'S NOTES: The peanut butter mixture can be rolled
into balls and dropped into the chocolate. When I have the time, I
use a plastic candy mold shaped like Reese's cups and, after
coating the mold with melted chocolate, I press a small amount of
the peanut mixture and then cover completely with chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SQUARE: 90 calories, 6 grams fat, 9
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 3 milligrams cholesterol, 13
milligrams sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   REQUEST:
</P>
<P>
   _ Avis Kennedy would like a recipe for white chocolate yeast
bread.
</P>
<P>
   _ Evelyn Shields of Fort Worth, Texas, is looking for a recipe
for pinto bean cake.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to her in care of the Star-Telegram at
Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column.) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
