A8787 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-THENIGHT-COX     02-16 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THENIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Morphine explores dark corners of `The Night'
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On July 3, 1999, Morphine's 46-year-old bassist/vocalist Mark
Sandman suffered a fatal heart attack on a stage near Rome. ``The
Night'' was delivered to the record company before the trio hit the
road in Europe. Unlike so many posthumous releases, this one has
been released just as Sandman intended. It finds the Boston-based
band growing and stretching, while maintaining its distinctive
sound. It's a shame that it stops here.
</P>
<P>
   Morphine sounds sexy. The music is steamy and sensual, not
salacious, but with a hint of danger in the guttural saxophones and
Sandman's sinewy bass lines. The saxophone is such a misused and
abused instrument in a rock context that its appearance is often
the listener's cue to take a powder. Without it, there could be no
Morphine, though. Dana Colley's shaded, sultry and utterly integral
baritone sax playing, as much as Sandman's raspy voice and
two-string slide bass, makes the band sound like nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Dark and occasionally forbidding, this is a perfectly titled
album. When it doesn't bring to mind the pleasures of the flesh, it
conjures the monsters that lurk beneath the bed or behind a
creaking closet door. Sometimes, as on the title track or the
twisted swirl of ``A Good Woman Is Hard to Find,'' the two
co-exist. This, sadly, is the last shot of Morphine we'll get, but
it's potent stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Night''
</P>
<P>
   Morphine. DreamWorks. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
