<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8789 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MINIS17-COX     02-16 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``In Too Deep'' (R) _ A decent undercover-cop thriller
highlighted by some smart performances. Omar Epps is quite good as
the detective, but LL Cool J is a revelation as the ruthless drug
kingpin, a monster made all the scarier by his seemingly benevolent
charm. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Story of Us'' (R) _ Director Rob Reiner's breezy,
laugh-a-lot, cry-a-lot big hankie of a movie with Bruce Willis and
Michelle Pfeiffer as a couple wondering if they'll survive 15 years
of marriage. It's a steady stream of sex jokes, butt jokes and guy
and gal pals dispensing weak-willed truisms. It may not be deep,
but it is entertaining. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Brokedown Palace'' (PG-13) _ A by-the-numbers prison drama.
Claire Danes and Kate Beckinsale sweat it out in a Thai
maximum-security pit after being duped into dope smuggling.
Unbearably high-minded, the movie doesn't even have the B-movie
juice of an old babes-behind-bars melodrama. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Joe the King'' (R) _ With this ``400 Blows'' wannabe,
actor-turned-filmmaker Frank Whaley has fashioned a starkly
hopeless memoir about growing up in the '70s with an abusive,
alcoholic father (Val Kilmer). Noah Fleiss is good in the role of a
neglected adolescent. But the movie strikes one note _ a blend of
blighted poignancy and stark injustice _ and stays there. Instead
of being moved, you're numbed. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Lovers on the Bridge'' (Rating) _ In this cult item from
France, Juliette Binoche plays an artist going blind who sets up a
makeshift shelter on the Pont Neuf bridge, already ``home'' to an
alcoholic, mentally unstable street performer (Denis Lavant). The
two cautiously develop a relationship. In one amazing scene, they
steal a speedboat and Binoche skis down the Seine while fireworks
explode. But much of the rest of the movie is mundane and
under-conceived. You sense director Leos Carax's talent and
audacity; you also sense his self-infatuation. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray and Bob Longino write for
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
