<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just beachy: Island locales provide paradise _ or not
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life's a beach. Especially if you're Leonardo DiCaprio. So
perhaps it's all too fitting that his first movie after that one
with the big boat is titled ``The Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on a novel by Alex Garland, it's about a myth-enshrouded
island off Thailand where a hippielike commune strives to create
its own private paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Islands, heavenly or otherwise, have long been a favorite theme
in movies. Maybe that's because not everyone out there can afford a
place at Malibu. Anyway, here are a few ideas for your own Beach
Blanket Bingo film fest. Minus, alas, Annette and Frankie. We'll
have their festival later.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Black Stallion'': A boy (Kelly Reno) and a horse are
stranded on an island paradise. A mystical bond develops between
the two. Gorgeously photographed by Caleb Deschanel.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? Absolutely. Especially if you're
more into animals than people.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Blue Lagoon'': A boy (Christopher Atkins) and a girl
(Brooke Shields) are stranded on an island paradise. A
not-so-mystical bond develops between them. The nubile leads
provide the gorgeousness.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? Probably, especially if you're
more into buff, inarticulate teens than people.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Swiss Family Robinson'': A family is shipwrecked, and they
build the coolest treehouse this side of Johnny Weissmuller and
Maureen O'Sullivan in the Tarzan movies.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? A functional family who can fight
off pirates and still get along? Sounds like paradise to me.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mysterious Island'': Some Union soldiers escape a
Confederate prison camp in a hot-air balloon and crash-land on an
island where the animals are Kong-sized. Effects by the master, Ray
Harryhausen; the score is by Bernard Herrmann.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? Depends on how you feel about
fending off giant crabs and overgrown chickens on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Papillon'': Steve McQueen and Dustin Hoffman star as
criminals incarcerated on France's infamous Devil's Island.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? They didn't. The whole movie is
about their various escape attempts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Crusoe'': Aiden Quinn plays literature's most famous
castaway, Robinson Crusoe. Ade Sapara is a very unservantlike Man
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? A tossup. The company's fine, but
do you want to camp out for the rest of your life?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Father Goose'': Island recluse Cary Grant shelters Leslie
Caron and some schoolgirls during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? Wouldn't you want to stay anywhere
with Cary Grant?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Six Days, Seven Nights'': A storm forces pilot Harrison Ford
and passenger Anne Heche to land on an isolated island, where they
try to survive drug-dealing pirates and each other.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? Sort of the Cary Grant principal,
depending on whether you're attracted to Ford or Heche or both.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``No Man Is an Island'': During World War II, GI Jeffrey
Hunter manages to hide from the Japanese for three years on Guam,
thanks to the help of some loyal and courageous natives.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? Sure, if the Japanese would just
go home.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Lord of the Flies'': Some British schoolboys are left on
their own on an uncharted island. Slowly but surely, they descend
from attempted civilization to utter savagery. Make sure to get the
Peter Brook 1963 version, not the remake.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? Only if you had an automatic
weapon and a waiting helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Island of Lost Souls'': Charles Laughton is a mad doctor
performing unspeakable experiments in the name of progress. Later
remade with Burt Lancaster in 1977 and Marlon Brando in 1996 as
``The Island of Dr. Moreau.'' The 1933 Laughton version is by far
the best; it still gives you chills almost 70 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Bela Lugosi as one of the so-called ``manimals.''
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? Not even with an automatic weapon
and a waiting helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Exit From Eden'': You, too, can go to an S&AMP;M fantasy camp
with Rosie O'Donnell and Dan Aykroyd.
</P>
<P>
   Would you want to stay there? Are you kidding?
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
