<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8792 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-THEMUSE-COX     02-16 0297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-THEMUSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inspiration in Hollywood can be a funny business
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Muse'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   In his perversely amusing comedy, writer-director-star Albert
Brooks plays Steven Phillips, a longtime screenwriter who, as
everyone keeps telling him, has suddenly ``lost his edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Steven's old friend and fellow scribe, Jack (Jeff
Bridges exuding Hollywood insider self-confidence), has a tip. He
introduces Steven to Sarah (Sharon Stone), a genuine
honest-to-the-gods Muse. As in, one of the nine daughters of Zeus.
Before you can say Mighty Aphrodite, Sarah has taken over Steven's
life and his bank account.
</P>
<P>
   As she explains to him, her job is to inspire. And in Hollywood,
inspiration doesn't come cheap. (There's a constant stream of
trinkets in little Tiffany's boxes, proffered by such grateful
clients as Rob Reiner, Martin Scorsese, Wolfgang Puck and James
Cameron.)
</P>
<P>
   As is so often true with Brooks' films, his framework is funnier
than his follow-through. Once Steven meets his Muse, the movie
loses a little of its edge. It becomes a broader satire, of
everything from marriage to writer's block. But there's a cheerful,
kind-spirited lunacy throughout the movie. And sometimes it's
downright hilarious. Especially when Brooks is satirizing his home
turf. When Steven's little daughter asks if she can star in one of
Daddy's movies, he replies, ``Of course, honey. As soon as you're
an older man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Muse'' is a lot like Brooks' sense of humor _subtle,
self-deprecating, off-the-wall clever.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta Journal-
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
