r d BC-AGGIE-CARROTS-TEX     02-16 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGGIE-CARROTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAROON CARROT IS NO AGGIE JOKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Texas A&AMP;M fans, it's the Aggie carrot. To the produce
marketing world, it's the Beta-Sweet. Either name will work _ as
will maroon carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Developed at Texas A&AMP;M University by Leonard Pike (the father of
Texas' 1015 onion), the Beta-Sweet carrot is a cross between a
nonedible purple carrot from Brazil and our standard orange carrot.
(Back in the mists of vegetable time, carrots were purple or white;
they were bred to today's hue by the Dutch.)
</P>
<P>
   So excited were the Aggies by their beloved maroon in vegetable
form, the publicity created demand that exceeded supply when the
carrots were introduced two years ago. Now there are two operations
in Texas' Rio Grande Valley licensed to grow the carrots, and
another grower is operating in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the carrots are widely available in grocery stores,
it's time to get acquainted with their eating qualities. They're
quite sweet, these purple guys, and good for eating out of hand.
They're also nice marinated and grilled or roasted. Don't saute
them, because they turn an unpleasant brown. As for those Longhorns
who might hesitate to support their rivals, they should keep in
mind that these carrots are far higher than ordinary carrots in
alpha and beta carotene, important preventatives for cancer, heart
disease and eye degeneration.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PICKLED MAROON CARROTS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 quart
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 tablespoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon mustard seed
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon whole black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon ginger, minced
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 1/2 habanero chiles, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 bunch (4 large) maroon carrots
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except chiles and carrots in saucepan.
Heat on medium flame until boiling. Remove from heat and chill.
Meanwhile, wash carrots well, but don't peel them. Cut either in
julienne or into coins.
</P>
<P>
   When brine is chilled, add chiles and carrots. Allow to marinate
at least 4 hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 59 calories, trace fat, 14
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 612 milligrams
sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Central Market chef Richard Wheatley nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1542EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
