<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CHIP-PLANT-HNS &LR;      02-16 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIP-PLANT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK CONTRIBUTES TO EXPANSION OF COMPUTER CHIP FACILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAMES M. ODATO  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York is taking another step toward offering
the world's most advanced computer research and development labs,
officials said in announcing a $15 million grant for a cutting-edge
plant here to make prototypes of the next generation of computer
chips.
</P>
<P>
   The laboratories will be part of a new wing of the Center for
Environmental Sciences and Technology Management building in Albany
that technology companies and the state helped build. New York
previously donated $10 million toward the facility's construction
and is providing $1 million annually in operating funds.
</P>
<P>
   The new wing would provide highly expensive ``clean room''
fabricating space, a business incubator and facilities for work
force training.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of the center would open many more opportunities
for partnerships with businesses in an industry expecting to need
40 new fabrication plants and thousands of workers to build the
next phase of computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   The center is already one of just a handful of labs worldwide
focused on semiconductor chip research, officials said, and it is
attracting bright students, research dollars and private
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope it will be the key to marketing this part of
upstate New York as a serious player in the emerging field of
computer chip development and manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, planners say, the facility would help drive the
region's economy in this century, perhaps luring one of the new, $4
billion chip-fabricating plants envisioned to employ a few thousand
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the only research and development facility
of its kind in the world, no hyperbole, no exaggeration,'' Alain
Kaloyeros, the director of the center, said Tuesday. ``That's going
to send a statement to the entire universe that New York is
investing in state of the art infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, Senate Majority Leader Joseph L. Bruno and
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver appeared together at the center
Tuesday to pledge $15 million in aid from a state economic
development account that the three leaders control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will make New York a leader in semiconductor chip R&AMP;D,''
said Pataki, a Republican, adding that he envisions spinoffs that
would allow this region to become another Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The new state money will be used to attract private investment
for the construction of a large manufacturing wing to make 300mm
wafers _ prototypes of the next generation of computer chips. They
would replace the 200mm wafers now used to carry the microchips
that make computers work.
</P>
<P>
   A goal of the investment is to lure computer-chip manufacturers
and associated industries to the region. Industry representatives
attending the announcement of the grant said the state is heading
in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited about having advanced R&AMP;D right here in the
Capital District, particularly close to our IBM locations is a big
plus,'' said John Kelly of IBM in Fishkill. ``This is a big
positive for our industry as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed wing will cost $55 million, Kaloyeros said. Another
$250 million in tools and systems will be needed to outfit the
facility, which is part of the Center for Advanced Technology at
the State University of New York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that this facility is going to be a magnet,''
said Kaloyeros, adding that it will attract private dollars and
allow the center to become a $1 billion, one-stop shop for chip
research. He said SUNY-Albany and Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute
will be applying for funding for a microelectronics venture under
the new state program to develop high-tech capabilities, called
Jobs 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturing space would be used by companies such as IBM,
Motorola and Intel, offering them testing and trouble-shooting
equipment. The business incubation space would be used for smaller
high-tech companies that do not require daily use of clean-room
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The work force training center would consist of a 100-seat
classroom linked electronically to schools such as community
colleges. The program will provide short-course training on
advanced semiconductor manufacturing practices, followed by
hands-on, on-site training.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
