<HEADER>
A8807 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-BEER-NUT-TEX     02-16 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-NUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOAST TO EAST GERMAN, COLORADO DARK ALES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quick _ name some ebony-colored ales that are neither porter,
dunkel or stout, yet refresh like exceptional lagers.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, I might've been stumped, too. But in my constant
quest to find new beverages to review so I may earn my monthly
stipend, I've come across two relatively new brews that fit the
bill: Colorado-made 1554 Brussels Style Black Ale and Germany's
Kostritzer Schwartzbier.
</P>
<P>
   The 1554 comes from our friends at New Belgium Brewery in Fort
Collins as part of their ``Special Release Beer Program.'' This
delightful, innovative brewery is responsible for the delicious Fat
Tire Ale and Abbey Ale, both previously (and positively) reviewed
in these pages. The idea behind ``Special Release'' is a kind of
test-marketing exercise, in which they fix up a limited batch of
something fun and see how it sells. Their Blue Paddle Pilsener was
just such a beer, and now it's part of their permanent product line
... as 1554 should be. Toasty, malty, full-bodied and easy on the
finish, 1554 is one of the more imaginative beers I've sampled in
ages.
</P>
<P>
   New Belgium claims to have discovered references to historical
Brussels black beers while attending a Belgian brewing conference.
Noting that the oldest mention of such mysterious brews was 1554,
their marketing wizards hit upon the next special-release name. As
their Web site says, ``In the profile of 1554 Brussels Style Black
Ale, our staff hoped to create an ale that it would be easy to
imagine as a beer served 445 years ago, but also a beer that
doesn't ignore 445 years of brewing advancements.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's coincidental, but the recent marketing push of
Kostritzer Schwartzbier (black beer) emphasizes the brewery's
equally ancient (1543) founding in Thuringen, Germany. After being
stuck behind the Iron Curtain these past few decades, Kostritzer is
making up for lost time with an aggressive sales effort that
deserves to be richly rewarded, because it's a wonderful brew:
toasty, malty and beautiful, with an elegant finish.
</P>
<P>
   The brewery's Web site calls Kostritzer ``Das Haus der Magischen
Biere,'' which, if my high school German still works, means ``The
House of Magical Beer.'' The rest of the site is in German, full of
scary words such as ``erfolges'' and ``farbebilden'' and
``andrang,'' none of which I understand, all of which I'm too lazy
to look up and don't think I want to know, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   My lack of intellectual questing aside, I comparison-tasted both
brews and came up even. Too close to call. Both beers have notable
merits and little downside. Add to it that they're readily
available at all finer booze stores, and I'd call that a win-win
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1555EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
