<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SILICON-FUNDS17-1STLD     02-16 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILICON-FUNDS17-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH-TECH GORE IS A FUND-RAISING FLOP IN SILICON VALLEY
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects Bush figures in grafs 3 and 4.
 &HT;    380&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SOFIA BASSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His supporters say he would be ``the E-president,''
but in the latest lap of the race for Silicon Valley's campaign
contributions, Al Gore ran dead last.
</P>
<P>
   A computer analysis of Federal Election Commission records shows
that in the last quarter of 1999, Bill Bradley led his Democratic
opponent in that high-tech battleground, and the Republican
presidential candidates as well.
</P>
<P>
   The former New Jersey senator raised $108,225 from the Silicon
Valley's 25 cities, while Gov. George W. Bush of Texas collected
$47,280 and Sen. John McCain of Arizona raised $42,906. Gore, who
brags about his role in developing the Internet, trailed with
$35,415.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1999, Bradley also came in first. He raised $617,475,
compared to $573,548 for Bush and $302,095 for Gore. McCain's
records for the first quarter were not available by computer, but
he had raised only $84,696 since April.
</P>
<P>
   At Gore's national headquarters in Nashville, his staff denied
that the gap may reflect a problem in Gore's message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects Bradley's emphasis on raising money and spending
on TV advertisements,'' said Doug Hattaway, Gore's spokesman.
``We've obviously been raising money,'' but Gore has concentrated
on meeting voters and pressing the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley has always been a big campaign fund raiser and a big
spender,'' added Hattaway. ``So it's not surprising that he has
raised so much money in this campaign and in Silicon Valley. He
outspent us in New Hampshire by quite a bit and we presume he'll
continue doing the same in the primaries to come, including
California.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is a sitting vice president,'' responded Judie Wong,
Bradley's California press secretary, ``and he's been doing his
share of fund raising as well. I think that Bill Bradley is very
appealing to people in the Silicon Valley because they believe he
is the strongest candidate on the issues that are of concern to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   She said what Silicon Valley people like most about Bradley's is
his ``understanding of the interactions between the private sector
and public sector in growing our economy'' and his ``blueprint for
education.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The analysis of Silicon Valley contributions shows that the
fund-raising gap between the two Democrats contenders has widened
over time. During the first three months of 1999, Gore was ahead.
He fell behind during the second quarter, but by year's end Bradley
was raising three times as much money.
</P>
<P>
   That resembles the picture nationwide, where Gore leapt to an
early lead, only to see Bradley close the gap by raising twice as
much money in the last quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The occupations of last fall's donors suggest that Bradley, who
taught at Stanford University between 1997 and 1998, is more
attractive to high-tech donors. Half of Gore's Silicon Valley
donors who declared their occupation were retirees or homemakers,
and only 3 percent were CEOs or company presidents. For Bradley, 9
percent of donors were CEOs and only 29 percent were not in the
labor force.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one contributor suggested that people in the
Silicon Valley look beyond bits and bytes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All candidates have been very careful to express policy that
are desired by people here in the valley,'' said Thomas Heller, a
professor at the Stanford University Institute for International
Studies who contributed $500 to Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``My choice has more to do with his expertise in foreign policy
and my sense that he would make an excellent president because of
his ability to manage complex staff,'' Heller said of Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Sofia Basso's e-mail address is sofiab(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
