<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8821 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX     02-16 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Movie, ad put two long-dead musicians in the spotlight 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say that everything old is new again _ and what's new/old
right now (besides, of course, Madonna's cover of ``American Pie)''
is a little-known English folk singer and the first European jazz
star, dead 26 and 46 years, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Nick Drake and Django Reinhardt, two men who have
little in common despite fierce loyalty from die-hard fans and a
sudden, unexpected status as at least strong blips on the
pop-culture radar.
</P>
<P>
   Drake's sweet ``Pink Moon'' is featured in a current Volkswagen
commercial; you know, the one where the carload of friends pulls up
to the party, they look at one another, and then the car goes
riding over a night-shrouded road. ``Pink pink pink pink _ pink
moon,'' his soft voice sings over an easy guitar strum.
</P>
<P>
   And Reinhardt (his music and the story of his life) is the
linchpin for Woody Allen's latest film, ``Sweet and Lowdown,'' the
story of fictional '30s jazz guitarist/scoundrel Emmett Ray (Sean
Penn), who both plays like and is obsessed with the Belgian
musician.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhardt is invoked constantly _ and is briefly ``seen'' _ in
the film, and his music and style of guitar playing are featured
prominently on the excellent soundtrack. Penn's Ray is so awed by
Reinhardt that, tricked into believing that Reinhardt is in the
front row of a show Ray is about to play, he simply skips out on
the gig, too scared to perform in front of his idol.
</P>
<P>
   Drake and Reinhardt could not be more different in musical style
or popularity: The former cut only three brief albums of lovely,
haunting folk music before falling into a severe, debilitating
depression. He played few shows (none in the United States), and
died of an overdose of anti-depressants in November 1974. His death
was ruled a suicide, although friends and family believe it was an
accidental overdose.
</P>
<P>
   None of Drake's three LPs sold well, but since then, he has been
elevated to icon status, his name invoked by R.E.M., Tom Verlaine,
Kate Bush and Lucinda Williams _ all noting how affected they were
by his fragile, sweetly sad songs.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhardt, on the other hand, is often cited as one of the
greatest jazz guitarists of all time. A Gypsy, he grew up playing
banjo, but his fretting hand was permanently disfigured in a fire
when he was 18, leaving him without the use of two fingers. He
switched to guitar and developed his own playing technique.
</P>
<P>
   A stunning soloist with amazing speed and taste, he is best
known for his work with violinist Stephane Grappelli; the two led
the Hot Club of France, the first important European jazz band. The
group cut dozens of records and became European superstars;
Reinhardt recorded with American jazz stars such as Coleman
Hawkins, played in France during the German occupation, toured the
United States with Duke Ellington in 1946, and died of a stroke in
France in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Several of his songs, such as ``Love's Melody'' and
``Djangology,'' have been frequently covered. Reinhardt was a huge
influence on numerous guitarists, from jazzers to the Allman
Brothers' Dickey Betts.
</P>
<P>
   And both men evoke a time gone by. Drake's downcast, evocative
folk was part and parcel of the post-Dylan folk boom that included
bands such as Fairport Convention and solo artists such as John
Martyn. The melancholia and sense of isolation in his music speak
to the end of the '60s and the beginning of the '70s, when the
dreams of Woodstock faded into harsher realities, harder drugs and
harder choices.
</P>
<P>
   Drake chose to simply withdraw into himself; when he died, he
was living with his parents in the tiny town of Tanworth-in-Arden.
In that context, his songs _ especially his final LP, 1972's ``Pink
Moon'' _ sound like a life slowly turning autumnal and blowing away
like leaves on a quiet country lane.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhardt's music is the polar opposite: Whether playing
original tunes or standards such as ``St. Louis Blues'' and Duke
Ellington's ``Solitude,'' he swings like mad, his solos ringing
with fire and intelligence. His music still evokes scenes of
well-dressed men and women dancing the night away in swank
nightclubs in a better time and place.
</P>
<P>
   But at least both share this: Their legacies have been
well-preserved _ Drake's years ago, and Reinhardt's just recently
on a monumental boxed set.
</P>
<P>
   The 1986 ``Fruit Tree'' box (reissued on CD by Rykodisc) is
literally everything Drake recorded: All three of his studio albums
and ``Time of No Reply,'' a 14-cut CD that ends with four songs
from his final recording session in February 1974. Much of the
material from that last session is as beautiful as anything he
released in his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhardt's music has been released and re-released on numerous
LPs and CDs. But in November, Mosaic Records dropped the mother
lode: ``The Complete Django Reinhardt and Quintet of the Hot Club
of France Swing/HMV Sessions 1936-1948.''
</P>
<P>
   The six-CD set collects all of Reinhardt's important recordings;
literally everything you need to know is here, from his landmark
1930s sessions with his band to duets with Grappelli to songs cut
with a big band and strings, to songs in which he backs vocalist
Josette Dayde. ``Nuages, Swing Guitars, Stockholm, Limehouse
Blues'' _ it's all here, beautifully packaged and with, most often,
excellent sound.
</P>
<P>
   A must-have for any jazz fan, the box is available by mail order
or by phone, and you'll need to act fast: Only 7,500 copies will be
printed.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1604EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
