<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-U.S.-NYT &LR;      02-16 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ASKS JAPAN TO CONSIDER MAINTAINING SUPPORT FOR U.S. MILITARY
OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CALVIN SIMS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In high-level security talks that concluded here
Wednesday, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott called on the
Japanese government to reconsider a proposal to reduce its
financial support for American troops stationed in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day talks follow a move by Japanese officials last month
to cut support payments to the United States to cover the costs
incurred by American military forces in Japan, including labor,
utilities, facilities, maintenance and training.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese financial support for American military operations
began in 1978, when the U.S. economy was foundering and Japan's
cost of living had skyrocketed. The Japanese government, which paid
about $2.5 billion to support the American military last year, is
now seeking to reduce those payments because it has fallen upon
hard economic times.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott, who led an American delegation including Defense
Undersecretary Walter Slocombe, asked Japan's foreign minister,
Yohei Kono, to generate public support for continuing the host
nation assistance for the U.S. military, said Japanese foreign
affairs officials familiar with the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I discussed with foreign Minister Kono, Japan and the
United States bring different contributions to our security
alliance,'' Talbott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bases and host nation support that Japan provides are a
critical contribution to the alliance,'' he said. ``Host nation
support is not just another line item in the budget, it is a
critical aspect of our alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese foreign officials said that there was no immediate
response from Kono but that the government's position was that the
military support payments, while important to Japan's security, are
a heavy burden, especially during this time of fiscal difficulty.
The agreement under which Japan provides support to the U.S.
military is scheduled to expire in March 2001 and is currently
being renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Germany and South Korea also make support payments to the United
States to cover the costs of American military operations in those
countries, but those payments are small compared with Japan's.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 45,000 U.S. military personnel in Japan,
including 19,000 marines in Okinawa and 13,700 air force staff.
American military officials have said that the importance of the
military bases in Japan has increased in the last decade with the
closing of bases in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the bases in Japan were especially vital for
responding to security threats from China, North Korea, or Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Slocombe, who is defense undersecretary for policy, Wednesday
called on Japan and the United States to continue cooperating on a
planned theater missile defense system to guard against the threat
posed by North Korea's missile program.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with the Japanese Defense Agency chief, Tsutomu
Kawara, Slocombe said that the United States and Japan needed to
consider ``a military approach'' in dealing with North Korea,
Japanese officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, North Korea fired a short-range ballistic missile over
the Japanese mainland and into the Pacific Ocean, raising concerns
across Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, North Korea threatened to test launch a more advanced
missile with a longer range and greater accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to those threats, the United States and Japan signed
an agreement to conduct joint research on a missile defense system,
which is estimated to cost as much as $521 million in the initial
phase that would be split equally by both countries.
</P>
<P>
   The theater missile defense system is intended to protect the
United States and its allies from incoming ballistic missiles
flying within about 1,800 miles' radius by detecting them with
satellites and shooting them down with missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a recent agreement by North Korea to suspend its missile
development program in exchange for the United States' lifting
economic sanctions, Slocombe expressed concern that the Stalinist
country still poses a security risk to the region, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a related issue, Talbott told Japanese officials Wednesday
that the United States wanted the government to shut down an
industrial-waste incinerator that is polluting an American naval
air base in Atsugi, just west of Tokyo, U.S. embassy officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   A survey conducted by the U.S. and Japanese governments found
high levels of dioxin in the air at the navy base, which is located
350 meters from the incinerating complex, which is operated by a
private company.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese foreign ministry officials said the government has
spent $12 million to reduce the plant's emissions and is currently
pressuring the incinerator's operator to install filtering
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Embassy officials here said the American delegation also
discussed issues related to Russia, Southeast Asia, Indonesia,
Japan's global role, and preparations for the economic summit
meeting of major industrialized nations that is scheduled to take
place in Okinawa in July.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation left for Beijing Wednesday evening where it is
expected to discuss the anti-missile shield, which China and Russia
have opposed because they cannot afford to a develop program and
they fear the system will give the United States and its allies a
strategic advantage if it works.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
