<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-INTERNET17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOUTHEAST'S SCHOOLS LEAD IN LINKING TO INTERNET
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Southeast leads the nation in connecting public
schools to the Internet, the U.S. Department of Education reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the West leads in success in installing high-speed
connections and the Central states lead in the race to bring
Internet service into every classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the percentage of schools connected to the Internet
stepped up each year, from 35 percent in 1994 to 95 percent in the
fall of 1999, according to the report on annual surveys of about
1,000 public schools by the National Center for Education
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The regional leader in the latest survey is the Southeast, with
98 percent of its schools connected. Five years previously, with
only 29 percent connected, the Southeast (defined broadly by the
survey-takers as states stretching from Texas to Maryland) had been
in last place.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 survey, connections had reached 95 percent of
schools in the West, 94 percent in the Northeast and 93 percent in
the Central region.
</P>
<P>
   As late as 1996, three-fourths of the schools linked to the
Internet had telephone dial-up connections like those used by most
computers in homes. By 1999, only 14 percent still used dial-up
modems. The rest had direct lines, ISDN, wireless, cable or other
faster systems that accommodate more students.
</P>
<P>
   Regionally, the slower dial-up connections still accounted for
16 percent of the school connections in the Southeast and the
Northeast, followed by the Central (14) and West (9) regions.
</P>
<P>
   Classroom connections are the next frontier. Only 3 percent of
public-school classrooms had Internet access in 1994. That has
reached 63 percent nationally. The leading area is the Central
region, with 70 percent of its classrooms wired, followed by the
West (68), Southeast (60) and Northeast (56).
</P>
<P>
   Because so many schools have Internet access, urban and suburban
high schools with few poor children are no longer more likely than
other schools to be connected to the Web. But they still have the
edge in obtaining high-speed connections and in wiring all their
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of the full report, ``Internet Access in U.S. Public
Schools and Classrooms: 1994-99,'' go to
http://nces.ed.gov/whatsnew/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
