<TEXT>
<P>
   Find what you looking for
</P>
<P>
   By Marylin Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been looking for White Wizard, a nontoxic cream that
cleans everything. It comes in a 10-ounce container and really
works. Does anyone sell it in Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   _ Miriam Karp, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Magically, we found two resources on the Internet for your
White Wizard cleaner. One is www.realgoods.com (1-800-762-7325). A
10-ounce tub is $7.95; when buying two or more, $6.95 each. Another
source is www.hica.com (1-888-466-9699). Two 10-ounce tubs are $14.
According to the packaging, White Wizard is odorless, nontoxic and
nonabrasive, and supposedly will take out such stubborn stains as
grease, oil, shoe polish, blood, chocolate, lipstick, tomato sauce
and wine. However, it will not remove permanent dyes and inks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to find a fragrance by Cartier called So Pretty.
My sister gave it to me for Christmas and I can't find it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yvonne Turnquest,
</P>
<P>
   Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Like the song says, ``I feel pretty, oh so pretty.'' You will
too, when you dab on So Pretty De Cartier, which debuted in the
jewelry-and-leather goods store in 1995. This fruity floral is a
combination of mandarin, neroli and dewberry with middle notes of
iris, rose and orchid, and bottom notes of sandalwood and musk. A
3.3-ounce eau de toilette spray is $85; a 1.6-ounce parfum is $70
at Cartier in Lenox Square, 3393 Peachtree Road N.E.
(404-841-0847).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in finding Paul Newman's Italian dressing. It
used to be everywhere. But now I can't find it anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sheryl Holland, Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your salads will soon have that Newman touch again. The
actor's Newman's Own Family Recipe Italian dressing can be found at
Harris Teeter, 3954 Peachtree Road N.E. (404-814-5990). A 16-ounce
bottle is $3.19. A drawing of the actor, who is depicted wearing a
striped T-shirt and straw sailor hat with red ribbon, adorns the
bottle. Incidentally, Newman, after taxes, donates all his profits
from the sale of the dressing for educational and charitable
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Tofutti. It's an ice cream product made
without milk but with tofu. I have children who are lactose
intolerant, and I would like to find this product for them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shannon Mandley, Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Everyone should be able to enjoy ice cream. We found Tofutti,
a nondairy Premium Frozen Dessert (1 pint, $2.99) at Kroger in
Brookhaven, 3871 Peachtree Road S.E. (404-240-0808). It's available
in a variety of flavors including vanilla and vanilla fudge,
chocolate and ``better'' pecan.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We own a two-story wooden cabin in North Georgia. I would
like to have a rope ladder that could be used from a second-story
window in an emergency. I have asked in hardware and mega-type
stores, so far without success. Thank you in advance for your help.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cindy Runyon, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a good idea for all two-story households. Although
it's not rope, we did find a First Alert Steel Fire Escape Ladder
(15 foot model is $39.97) at Lowe's, 4855 U.S. 78, Lilburn
(770-978-9724). The fully assembled, ready-to-use ladder has
slip-resistant rungs, six pairs of steel rung stabilizers and large
hooks that secure easily to windowsills for maximum stability. The
manufacturer, BRK Brands, warns that its fire escape ladder is
intended to be used only as an alternate escape means in a fire
emergency. It is not intended to be the main exit for escape in an
emergency. Look on the company's Web site, www.firstalert.com
</P>
<P>
   /index.html, for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
