<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MONEY (Columbia, S.C.) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who had
the biggest campaign fund of any presidential hopeful in history,
has spent all but $20 million of it, having to wage battles he
didn't expect and to remain competitive in several major media
markets simultaneously. The Republican has raised some $69 million
so far. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-BAUER (Greenville, S.C.) _ John McCain touts his
endorsement by former rival Gary Bauer in an effort to counter
doubts raised by George W. Bush about McCain's anti-abortion
credentials. Bauer praises McCain as ``the best shot we have to end
the era of Bill and Hillary and Al Gore.'' Bush, meanwhile, shrugs
off McCain's endorsement by Bauer and by California Secretary of
State Bill Jones and says he's still going to win Saturday's
Republican primary in South Carolina. By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-GORE (Raleigh, N.C.) _ Vice President Al Gore says he
opposes President Clinton's nomination of Bradley Smith to the
Federal Election Commission because of Smith's disdain for
campaign-finance regulations. Gore's rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination, former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, came
out against Smith a week ago. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton releases $125 million
in federal aid to help poor families in the Northeast pay for the
rising cost of home heating oil. Clinton makes the announcement
during his first official news conference of the year. The
president also touches on issues ranging from abortion to
overhauling the nation's campaign finance laws. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-FUNDING (Washington) _ NASA administrator Daniel Goldin,
seeking the first funding increase for his agency in seven years,
appears before a congressional panel to defend the space agency's
reliance on Russia to help it complete the International Space
Station. Panel members criticize NASA for working with the Russian
government instead of private Russian companies, but Goldin says at
least one of those companies had gouged NASA on prices for
hardware. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPINDLETOP-GUSHER (Beaumont, Texas) _ The dogged search by a
couple of surveyors has yielded the actual site of the first
Spindletop oil well, the Lucas gusher. The spot is under water now,
but Beaumont will mark it in preparation for the 100th anniversary
of the big discovery that made East Texas, for a time, the world's
oil capital. By JAMES KIMBERLY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHIP-PLANT (Albany, N.Y.) _ Gov. George Pataki and other state
officials announce a $15 million grant for construction of a
cutting-edge plant to make prototypes of the next generation of
computer chips. Officials hope it will be the key to marketing this
part of upstate New York as a serious player in the emerging field
of computer chip development and manufacturing. By JAMES M. ODATO.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-CINCY (Houston) _ North Carolina, Kentucky and UCLA may be
the first schools that come to mind when its comes to college
basketball tradition, but Cincinnati isn't too far behind. The
school that produced the likes of Oscar Robertson and Jerry Lucas
is now back at the forefront of college basketball with the
nation's No. 1 team. On Thursday, the University of Houston Cougars
will play the nation's top-ranked team. By JERRY WIZIG.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-AL-EAST (Undated) _ We take a look at Major League
Baseball's spring training in the American League East. By JOSEPH
DUARTE.
</P>
