u l BC-MARTIN-LUTHER-KING-HN     02-16 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTIN-LUTHER-KING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HIP-HOP PROFESSOR TAKES A NEW LOOK AT MARTIN LUTHER KING JR. 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VENISE WAGNER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Caution: The following contains material that
may offend readers partial to the sacrosanct portrayals of the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr. Reader discretion is advised.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Eric Dyson, social critic, self-described hip-hop
scholar and DePaul University professor, doesn't apologize either.
This 41-year-old Baptist minister is not one to censor himself at
the expense of revealing truths.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest and most controversial book, ``I May Not Get There
With You'' (The Free Press, $25), Dyson crushes the rose-colored
lenses through which the civil-rights martyr has been viewed since
his assassination three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   His aim is not to besmirch King, he says, but rather to make the
civil rights leader relevant to a new generation that views the
'60s protests, ``I Have a Dream'' declarations and refrains of ``We
Shall Overcome'' as relics of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired of people saying, `If Martin Luther King was here,
he'd be sick of hip-hop culture,''' says Dyson, a Detroit native
who sprang from poverty to become a Princeton Ph.D. graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson has experienced the same urban realities and resistance
that resonate in the rap music of the late Tupac Shakur and the
Notorious B.I.G., aka Biggie Smalls.
</P>
<P>
   The King that the hip-hop generation knows, Dyson says, has been
frozen in time, sanitized and beatified to assuage white
integrationists who fear the calls of black nationalism, the social
conservatives who learned to appropriate King's words for their own
purposes, and the older black establishment that wants to protect
its slain leader's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In the tradition of jazz saxophonists John Coltrane and Charlie
Parker, Dyson riffs with speed, eloquence, bawdy humor and
startling truths. He visited the San Francisco Bay area earlier
this week to promote his message and book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't no getting around it _ he ain't got to be perfect in
order to be great,'' Dyson said of the civil rights icon. ``My
point wasn't to bring King down, it was to lift them (those in the
hip-hop generation) up. My point is get real, be honest.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Dyson breaks it down: Martin Luther King Jr. womanized,
plagiarized and prophesied.
</P>
<P>
   He got it right when he predicted the rebellious rage of blacks
who tired of inequality, Dyson said. But he added that King got it
wrong when he thwarted the rise of women to leadership in his
circle. His own sexism squelched his wife Coretta's ambition to
participate in the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. was a radical, Dyson said, recalling that
he opposed the Vietnam War, embraced democratic socialism, gave
most of his earnings to the civil rights cause and called for a
form of reparations for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson recalled that King also told lewd jokes, talked trash,
pursued sex recklessly and suffered depression.
</P>
<P>
   He sometimes lost faith but always inspired hope, Dyson said.
King concluded that many whites were unconscious racists. Yet he
never stopped trying to illuminate their biases and help them
transcend.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., said Dyson, was not unlike
Shakur.
</P>
<P>
   In the minds of some, this is the equivalent of comparing Jesus
with Gabriel, the risen with the fallen.
</P>
<P>
   But Dyson explained, ``I wanted to suggest to
(hip-hop-generation members) that they have much more in common
with King than they realize, that Martin Luther King Jr. was much
more relevant, much more funky, much more insightful and much more
gritty than the smoothed-out iconic textures that have been
delivered to us by most media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both (Shakur and King) were obsessed with their own deaths.
Both used older rhetorical sources (Shakur sampled music, King
borrowed prose) and gave them fresh meaning. Both had distressingly
similar viewpoints about women. Both struggled against forms of
evil, like police brutality, racial inequality and economic
inequality.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyson's critics cringe at these comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights veteran Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., told the Washington
Post: ``I think a lot of what Dyson is doing is just a fad. I think
he does this to get attention. I think it's a disgrace. It's
shameful for him to put Dr. King on that level.``
</P>
<P>
   But others say Dyson is employing the rappers' trade of sampling
material, taking old stories and giving them a fresh sound, a new
look.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
