<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-TIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL ISRAELI DECREE EXTENDS DAYLIGHT SAVINGS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Daring to single-handedly alter a calendar that is
as politically sensitive as everything else here, Natan Sharansky,
the interior minister, decreed Wednesday that Israel's ``summer
time'' will be longer this year by 34 days.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where even the issue of daylight savings time is
contentious, it was a provocative decision, playing into a
long-running battle between secular Israelis and some religious
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Daylight savings time _ what Israelis refer to as summer time _
will start earlier in the spring and extend almost a month further
into the fall, Sharansky said. This rescinds a tradition of
accommodating the prayer schedules of some religious Jews leading
up to the High Holidays in September _ a tradition that secular
Israelis have long resented as subordinating the routines of the
majority to the special rituals of a minority.
</P>
<P>
   But religious politicians did not immediately react. They were
too busy confronting Sharansky, a Russian immigrant leader, on
another decision.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Sharansky said the Interior Ministry would
begin recognizing and registering civil marriages performed at
foreign consulates in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Such marriages _ which only some consulates perform _ make it
possible for immigrants here who are not recognized as Jewish to
marry Israelis. Under Israeli law, only religious weddings are
permitted, and what the rabbis see as inter-marriages are
forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky took over the Interior Ministry from Shas, an
ultra-Orthodox Sephardic party, after years of friction between the
Russian immigrants he represents and the Shas bureaucrats who had
the power to grant and deny them citizenship and marriage licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Wresting the Interior Ministry from Shas was part of Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's election platform, and taking control of it
was Sharansky's main plank.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sharansky's dealing with Shas have been strained, his
relations with other religious political groups have been based on
mutual respect. Sharansky is an observant Jew, and many of the
religious politicians believed that he respected them. His
recommendation about the consular marriage took them by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   In defending his decision on changing the daylight-savings
calendar, Sharansky said that ``preservation of life was the
guiding principle'' that pushed him to make the change, even if it
upset religious Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, daylight savings time ended on Sept. 3, and Israel
then moved into ``winter time.'' This meant that during the dog
days of early September, the sun was rising long before the workday
started and setting during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Technion Institute proved to him, Sharansky said,
that an additional hour of late-afternoon light would lower traffic
accidents by 9 percent, and fatal ones by 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For secular Israelis, the old system generated much grumbling.
But ultra-Orthodox Sephardic Jews, who traditionally recite
penitential prayers at the midpoint between sunset and sunrise,
were able to get more sleep _ starting their prayers at midnight,
say, instead of 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sephardic public, for the most part, works hard and has to
get up early for work,'' said Itzik Suderi, a spokesman for Shas.
``So if the penitential prayers are late, they can end at 3:30 a.m.
and then the people have to get up at 5:30 a.m. What we are asking
for is consideration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
