<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RELEASES $125 MILLION MORE FOR HOME-HEATING OIL
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: New England)   (nk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton ordered the release of another
$125 million in government aid Wednesday to help needy families in
the Northeast pay the soaring costs of heating their homes this
winter.
</P>
<P>
   The release, announced by Clinton at the start of an afternoon
news conference, comes only six days after the government made $130
million in home-heating aid available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have always pulled together in time of need,'' the
president said, referring to the government's recent help for flood
and tornado victims. ``Now, the families of the Northeast need our
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also suggested that states make assistance for
home-heating available to more middle-income people rather than
only to those loosely defined as poor.
</P>
<P>
   While a breakdown of aid amounts for individual states was not
immediately available, there was no doubt whatever that much of the
assistance would go to the Northeast and New England because a
large proportion of homes in those regions have oil heat. Crude-oil
prices have skyrocketed in recent weeks because of production
cutbacks by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people with home-heating oil are the most vulnerable
people in America by a good long ways'' to international economic
trends and upheavals beyond their control, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In the hardest-hit regions, the price of home heating oil has
passed $2 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that, in addition to telling the Department of
Health and Human Services to release the $125 million, he would
urge members of Congress and governors from the affected states to
adjust their guidelines to make more people eligible.
</P>
<P>
   State guidelines vary, but typically a family's income must be
no more than 150 percent of the official poverty level in that
state. For instance, if the official poverty level for a family of
a certain size is an income below $12,000 a year, aid is typically
available to families that make no more than $18,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In the release announced last week, New York state got the most
aid, just over $34.3 million. New Jersey got $7.5 million and
Connecticut just over $3 million. The allocations are based on
formulas that consider the cost of fuel in a given area, the
day-by-day weather in that area and poverty statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
