<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATCHDOG17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATION'S TOP WASTE-WATCHER CONFRONTS EUPHORIA OF SURPLUSES
 &HT;    570&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ David M. Walker picked up a small wooden cudgel
studded with sharp spikes that he prominently displays in his
office. He has promised not to use it, he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   But as comptroller of the United States, he needs all the potent
symbols he can find.
</P>
<P>
   The former partner and global manager in Atlanta for the
accounting firm Arthur Andersen, Walker is just 15 months into a
huge and increasingly thankless mission.
</P>
<P>
   He heads the 3,275-person General Accounting Office, the
investigating arm of Congress and chief watchdog for exposing waste
and mismanagement throughout the federal government, which Walker
calls ``the largest, most complex, most diverse entity on the face
of the Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Although finding waste in government may seem as easy as finding
sand at the beach, Walker has arrived in the capital just as
exposing waste has fallen out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   A deluge of budget surpluses has undercut the urgency for
heeding the approximately 1,500 audits, investigations and
testimonies that GAO churns out each year on everything from how
much the Pentagon pays for screws to the solvency of the Social
Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Walker is scheduled to appear Thursday before the House Budget
Committee amid an attempt by the panel's chairman, Rep. John
Kasich, R-Ohio, and the Republican leadership to revive some of the
lost zeal of the government reform movement.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Walker has prepared a list of what he calls
``immediate targets of opportunity'' in programs that are at
highest risk for waste, fraud and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is far from certain that the comptroller's
suggestions will be enthusiastically embraced by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   When Walker presented a list of 61 potential reforms and program
eliminations to the Senate Budget Committee a few weeks back, the
senators didn't wait to hear him speak before they pounced on the
list and defended their pet projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hearing illustrated the difficulty of making some
changes,'' Walker said philosophically in an interview this week.
</P>
<P>
   An impeccably attired 48-year-old whose wire-rimmed glasses and
orderly office fit the image of the nation's top auditor, he has
the job of digging out the facts and presenting recommendations.
But he pointed out that the lawmakers don't have to accept them.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, we work for 540 politicians, and they must be
accountable to the American people,'' he said during an interview
this week. ``Reasonable people can and do differ.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if his message is finding only a lukewarm reception, Walker
continues to admonish Congress to use the good economic times to
begin ``weeding out programs that have proven to be outdated,'' pay
down the national debt and prepare for the costs as the baby boom
generation begins to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're rolling in dough today, and we are in pretty
good shape from a budgetary standpoint,'' he said this week. ``But
we know we're going to face re-emerging deficits.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he politely suggested that Congress has fallen down on
the job of monitoring how money is spent. ``There is a recognition
on the Hill that there's a need for more oversight,'' he said,
noting the reason why. ``It's not headline-grabbing work,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And even with budget surpluses, he said, ``We still have a
responsibility to make sure that the taxpayer is getting a good
return on their investment.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Congress, the executive agencies and even the public may not be
listening very closely now. But the role of the comptroller general
is to deliver the bad news anyway, said Paul C. Light, director of
governmental studies at the Brookings Institution, a Washington
research center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he's going to feel like a skunk at a picnic and
sometimes he's going to feel more popular, but that's his job,''
Light said. ``And he's got to keep hacking on it and hacking on it
and hacking on it.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Light gives high marks to Walker's efforts, especially
for his dialog with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Only the seventh comptroller in the GAO's 77-year history,
Walker has met with most of the lawmakers. Meticulously
non-partisan, Walker has been a conservative Democrat, then a
moderate Republican and now has registered as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   He was the choice of congressional Democrats and Republicans as
well as the White House for the post, which carries a 15-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Government Reform Committee Chairman Fred Thompson,
R-Tenn., said that Walker ``has taken a fresh look at GAO and is
positioning the organization to be able to address the problems
that will affect the way government operates in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of that effort, Walker announced in early February that
modernization would start with the $378 million operations of GAO
itself. He is shutting down five of 16 field offices and shuffling
much of the staff, which is 40 percent below its peak in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He gave the agency a motto for their core values,
``accountability, integrity and reliability,'' a theme that has
earned him the nickname ``AIR Walker'' at his agency. He even had
the motto woven into a rug in front of his desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paid for it,'' he added quickly, as he gave a tour around
his spacious digs atop the GAO's building a few blocks from the
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   He makes no apologies for the large office. ``I spend 60 hours a
week here,'' said the comptroller, who generally begins firing out
e-mail to his staff soon after 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is that public service is a high calling,'' said
Walker, who has worked for the federal government in various roles
on three previous occasions. And regardless of who's listening, he
said the GAO would continue to dispense reports and assessments
that are ``objective, fact-based, non-partisan, non-ideological,
fair and balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
