<HEADLINE>
DELEGATING THE DIRTY WORK OF CLEANING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there a secret grapevine for cleaning companies that spreads
the word about which houses to avoid? Is it possible that the last
cleaning crew who came to my house could have taken photographs and
showed them to the competition?
</P>
<P>
   No, they seemed far too busy _ scraping glitter-flecked glue off
the kitchen table, removing a melted straw from the dishwasher and
using tongs to transport the baby's hidden supply of half-eaten
bologna to the garbage _ to have time to document the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   So why did I find myself unable to get my house cleaned last
month? Was it a coincidence that two companies didn't return my
calls, or that another cleaner quoted $300 for the job, a price
that did not include cleaning supplies or fresh tongs?
</P>
<P>
   Not to sound paranoid, but the lack of response reminded me that
the tree company never sprayed the hemlocks last fall. And the
gutter specialist never came by to measure for new eaves troughs,
situations that in the past might have prompted me to such acts as
_ this only happened once, I swear _ dropping in at a friend's
house with a plate of homemade cookies at a time I suspected his
carpenter would be there.
</P>
<P>
   Since that desperate juncture in my life, I have learned there
is an easier way to hunt down, I mean, hire, local service
providers: over the Internet. You go online to sites like
www.handshake.com or www.imandi.com that match your address with
merchants in their nationwide databases.
</P>
<P>
   (If you live in the Dallas-Fort Worth area, you can also try
www.fundu.com, which operates only in that area and plans to change
its name to ServiceLane.com next month.) These companies began
operating in the past year, and a fourth, www.efrenzy.com, is
scheduled to start Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Then you just sit there _ no need to leave whiny, pleading phone
messages about how you hate to be leaving yet another message, but
really, you need that stain on the rug, which might or might not be
food coloring, cleaned before your mother, who gave you the rug,
arrives in town on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site acts as contractor for all kinds of services, and
pretty soon the world comes to you. Bottled water delivery
services. Pet sitters. Airport shuttles. Movers.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded, frankly, too good to be true. To test it, I searched
for housecleaners a few weeks ago on imandi.com, which connects
customers to 180,000 merchants who provide services and products in
300 categories.
</P>
<P>
   After I clicked on ``house cleaning,'' I filled out a form to
describe the job, entering information about things like how much I
wanted to spend, the size of my house, the number of bedrooms and
bathrooms and the number of pets. There also was a box to type
additional comments; I thought it best to gloss over the baby's
bologna habit.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the registration, I entered personal information,
including my name, address and phone number. Then a list appeared
of a dozen or so cleaning services that operated in the New York
metropolitan area. I could click on the ones that interested me and
that operated in my geographic area.
</P>
<P>
   Imandi.com assured me that my request would go out to all of
them; they would be encouraged to respond directly to me by e-mail
or phone.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I received an e-mail message from one. Joe Brown,
who owns Klean and Brite Cleaning Service on Long Island, wrote
that he would be happy to schedule a time to send a crew of two men
with equipment and supplies ($35 an hour) to my house. As
references, he also provided the names and phone numbers of two
other customers. I phoned one, a longtime customer, who recommended
the service highly.
</P>
<P>
   Then I sent e-mail back to Brown, requesting a crew the
following Friday and including directions to my house. At the
appointed time, the crew arrived, cleaned everything really well,
collected payment and left me a receipt.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the cost of the Web site is being borne by the
investors who are betting on the concept's eventual success.
Although there is no fee for either for service providers or the
customers, the idea is that the sites will eventually charge
merchants for customer referrals.
</P>
<P>
   I know, this all sounds too good to be true. And actually, even
though the process worked fine for me, I identified a few potential
problems. For one thing, this concept is so new that when I also
tried to search for housecleaners at Handshake.com, I learned that
no housecleaners in my area had signed up for the company's new
Express Service feature, which promises immediate bids on
housecleaning requests.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, Klean and Brite was the only merchant to respond to
my request at imandi.com. The reason might be that many of the
merchants are not online themselves, said Raghav P. Kher, the
company's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving toward building closer and closer relationships
and convincing merchants who are offline to get online,'' Kher
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, imandi.com offers customers a list of ``star
merchants,'' service providers who are online, who promise to
respond within 72 hours and who provide references. For those
service providers not online, imandi.com faxes a customer's request
and phone number to merchants, who get in touch with customers
directly.
</P>
<P>
   You can see how this could become cumbersome at best, like an
unwieldy version of that old game Telephone, where you whisper
``Siamese cat'' into someone's ear and the phrase gets garbled as
it travels around the room, finally returning to you as ``Hyenas
fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem is that neither imandi.com nor
Handshake independently evaluates the merchants in their networks.
Instead, they encourage customers to post merchant reviews online.
(Fundu.com screens merchants in its network, a company spokesman
said, and eFrenzy will as well.) For now, the only evaluations I
found on imandi.com were ones that said a merchant ``never
responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Those caveats aside, I'd happily try imandi.com again. In fact,
I already have. Last week, I submitted a request for landscape
design to six local companies. So far, one designer has responded;
she's coming over to look at the job on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not neglecting my family's health anymore. I called
Klean and Brite back this week. As I type, I can hear in the
distance the sweetest sound on earth: the sound of men vacuuming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
