<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF A SIMPLE MACHINE THAT IS DEDICATED TO THE BASICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We are retired and only want to do word processing and use
the Internet. Is there a simple machine out there that will let us
just use word processing programs and go out on the Internet? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Any new computer will be capable of getting the user on the
Web, and most of them will handle word processing and other kinds
of software. But there are options available that may be especially
attractive to new users.
</P>
<P>
   The all-in-one computers, like Apple Computer's iMac (which runs
the Mac operating system) or Gateway's Astro PC (which runs
Windows), can simplify the hardware and software set-up process and
cost much less than a more complicated system. These types of
devices come with a monitor, a keyboard, a mouse, a sound card, a
modem and plenty of RAM to get you on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   These ``all in one'' systems provide not only basic
word-processing features and Internet capability but the potential
for many other uses (like games, home accounting or genealogy
software, for example) that you may find yourself wanting to try
once you get comfortable with the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Prices can range from about $800 to $1,600, and technical
support is often included. Some retailers offer rebates on the
total price if you sign up with a particular online service, but
read the fine print carefully before you buy.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wish only to explore the World Wide Web and send
e-mail might want to look at the Internet appliances that are
starting to hit the market. These devices, which cost about $300 to
$500, lack the features of a fully outfitted system but are often
simpler to use and fulfill their basic function: getting the user
online. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I finally understand how MP3 music files work, but what are
``skins''? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Skins are purely decorative interfaces for MP3 player
software. Instead of having a rather straightforward electronic
rendering of the CD-player controls and equalizer to play and mix
your digital music files, you can dress up your player.
</P>
<P>
   WinAmp, for example, a Windows MP3 player, has thousands of
skins available (www.winamp-skins.com), everything from futuristic
space-shiplike buttons to one that turns the equalizer into an
``Ecowlizer'' with little Holsteins to adjust the music levels.
</P>
<P>
   SoundJam MP, an MP3 player and encoder for the Macintosh, comes
with several alternate skins. A Web search should help you find
skins for your particular player.
</P>
<P>
   Mac users may want to see what is available in the downloads
section of www.soundjam.com or on the Macast site (home of another
Mac MP3 player) at www.macamp.net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have read much about DSL service for fast Internet
connections, but what is VDSL? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Most of the digital subscriber line services written about
these days refer to ADSL, or asymmetric digital subscriber lines.
</P>
<P>
   ADSL (the term is usually shortened to DSL when the service is
advertised by companies selling it) offers downloading speeds that
far surpass the capacity of the current 56K modems available. But
while DSL speeds can reach about 8 megabits per second, VDSL (very
high bit-rate digital subscriber line) downloading speeds can
approach 52 megabits per second.
</P>
<P>
   VDSL is still very much in development. The service, which uses
existing copper wire and fiber-optic networks, is not expected to
hit the general market until around 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If all the promises of the technology are fulfilled, however,
VDSL will add a new dimension to home networking.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ultrafast speeds, transmission of high-quality
video images over the phone line will be possible, which could
allow digital television channels to compete with cable television
companies for viewers. Video teleconferencing will also be much
smoother, Web browsing faster and downloading quicker.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, there is the VDSL Coalition page on the
Web at www.vdsl.org. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
