<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TALKS-355&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNING STREET TALKS FAIL TO PATCH UP NORTHERN IRELAND RIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Demands by the Sinn Fein president, Gerry Adams, that
Britain restore the suspended Northern Ireland government were met
in a crisis session at 10 Downing St. on Wednesday with counter
demands from other participants that the Irish Republican Army
first return to disarmament talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no room at all to do anything in this situation,''
said the beleaguered Sinn Fein leader, whose party is the political
wing of the IRA. ``The only breakthrough which can start to make
politics work is a return to the institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Under fire for the IRA's refusal to make any move to disarm,
Adams complained that his party was being unfairly scapegoated. ``I
don't think we can play a useful role on the arms issue when all we
are met with is rejections and rebuttals.''
</P>
<P>
   He also ruled out participating in a formal review of the
stalled peace negotiations, saying the British had acted illegally
in shutting down the Belfast administration last Friday. ``There
cannot be a review based on unilateral suspension,'' he told
reporters outside the British prime minister's official residence.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair's insistence that the time had come
for the IRA to start disarming gained valuable support from his
Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, who came to London to join in the
emergency talks.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that continued participation by republicans in the
Northern Ireland government with ``armed backing'' was
unacceptable, Ahern said, ``Whether people like it or not, it is
not compatible, beyond a short transitional period, to have that
democratic mandate with armed backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot agree to it,'' he told members of the Irish
parliament in Dublin before flying to London.
</P>
<P>
   His words may go some way toward closing a rift that had
developed between Britain and Ireland, the two sponsors of the
Ulster peace talks, over the British action suspending the
government in Belfast. Britain took the action, it said, because
the IRA had failed to begin disarming even after members of Sinn
Fein had been admitted to their ministerial positions in the
Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While speaking to the Irish parliament on Tuesday evening, Ahern
was surprised by an IRA announcement that it was ending its contact
with weapons mediators and withdrawing fresh proposals it had made
to consider disarming for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy leader of the moderate Catholic Social Democratic and
Labor Party, Seamus Mallon, who like Ahern had been opposed to the
suspension, joined in the criticism of the IRA on Tuesday for
pulling out of the consultations with the disarmament commission.
He said he found it incredible that the clandestine organization
had made its announcement at a time when Ahern was before his own
legislators in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only have they made a studied insult to Bertie Ahern, but
to the entire political process in Ireland as a whole and to the
Irish people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA action was a dismaying development for supporters of the
peace plan who had been holding meetings throughout recent days
hoping that the new IRA arms initiative would be a basis for
restoring the home rule government. The IRA had offered late Friday
to consider putting its arms ``beyond use'' and suggested that it
could live with a timetable that would see full disarmament by the
May date set down in the April 1998 peace accord. Then Tuesday the
group took back those words.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's meeting was scheduled to find a way to keep the
staggering peace effort on its feet, and the consensus that emerged
was that the vexing issue of guerrilla disarmament had to be
confronted before any progress could be made on restarting the
mothballed Northern Ireland government.
</P>
<P>
   Adams presented an opposite scenario in which the government
would have to be restored before the issue of disarmament could be
taken up, but he had no takers outside his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at Downing Street, his chief rival, David Trimble, the
Ulster Unionist leader, said, ``The onus is fairly and squarely on
the republican movement to put forward proposals as to how this is
going to work. The ball is still firmly in their court. We are not
interested in cobbling together a formula that enables this to
stagger on for a week or two. We want this sorted out once and for
all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
