<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING ZULU HISTORY ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For roughly 60 years during the 19th century, the Zulu kingdom
that had been forged by the warrior leader Shaka was one of the
mightiest black states in Africa. It took a full military campaign
by Britain to pull it down.
</P>
<P>
   Before succumbing, the Zulus inflicted on Britain in 1879 the
most crushing defeat ever by a modern army at the hands of an
aboriginal force.
</P>
<P>
   The Zulus, like others in South Africa, are still recovering
from mistreatment and brutality under apartheid, and their pastoral
traditions have been disrupted by poverty and urbanization. Until
recently, they were largely invisible on the Internet, too.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, the province of KwaZulu-Natal, which was formed from
Natal and the apartheid-era homeland of KwaZulu, has established an
economic development and tourism Web site
(www.kzn-deat.gov.za/tourism/kzntour.htm) that focuses on the Zulu
as a vibrant, living people, not a relic of history.
</P>
<P>
   Under Zulu Culture and Traditions, the site discusses ancestor
worship; the inyangas, or tribal doctors; food and drink (sour milk
and beer, which is brewed by the women); various dances; and
musical instruments, baskets and beadwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love letters date from the introduction of glass beads about
1830, which were quickly given meanings dependent upon their
color,'' the site says. There is more on love beads at the Zulu
Bead Art Page at www.compustyle.co.za/kwazulu/zulu/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cattle mean status, wealth, power and the ability to buy
wives,'' the site notes. ``Frequently, Zulu chiefs would be buried
in their cattle kraals.'' Shaka's kraal was estimated to be more
than 3 miles around and able to hold 12,000 warriors.
</P>
<P>
   The Zulus cannot be studied apart from the rest of South Africa,
in which they are the largest ethnic group (7 million of the
nation's 40 million people) and the most nationalistic.
</P>
<P>
   The founder and first president of the African National Congress
(www.anc.org.za) were both Zulus. So was Albert Luthuli, who became
South Africa's first Nobel laureate in 1960 when as president of
the Congress, he led passive resistance against racist laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site of the Inkatha Freedom Party, based in
KwaZulu-Natal and frequently at odds with the congress, is
www.ifp.org.za.
</P>
<P>
   Several Web sites on the Anglo-Zulu War of 1879, a war that the
Zulus did not want and were goaded into fighting by Britain, offer
sharply different perspectives on history. The British lost about
850 men and a roughly equal number of native allies at Isandhlwana
(pronounced is-sandal-WAH-na) on Jan. 22, 1879, after Lord
Chelmsford, their commander, misguessed the Zulus' strength and
location and split his force.
</P>
<P>
   The encampment was wiped out by 20,000 Zulu foot soldiers using
their assegais, or stabbing spears, and their classic ``chest and
horns'' flanking attack, which Shaka had perfected 60 years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A bitter 1979 essay on the centenary of Isandhlwana, from
Sechaba, a publication in exile by the African National Congress
(www.anc.org.za/ancdocs/history/misc/isandhlwana.html) emphasizes
the fight against colonialism. The defense of Rorke's Drift, a tiny
mission station, one day later, in which about 125 British soldiers
held off about 4,000 Zulus in 10 hours of hand-to-hand combat, is
detailed at www.battlefields.co.za/history/index.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Knight, an authority on Zulu warfare, has a detailed account
of Isandhlwana on the same site. He said the victory transformed a
little-known African kingdom into a stereotype of alien savagery
that colored whites' understanding of Zulu history and culture even
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most historical calamities, the British defeat came about
not through any single great error of judgment, but rather through
a combination of misunderstanding, miscalculation and sheer bad
luck,'' he wrote. ``The Zulu victory, on the other hand, was won by
sound tactical judgment, by aggressive spirit and by raw courage
and endurance in the face of an awesome and destructive enemy
weapon technology.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1627EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8842 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COUPLES-MAIL-NYT &LR;      02-16 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COUPLES-MAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE, HONOR, CHERISH. BUT REVEAL MY PASSWORD? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.H.)   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By JOYCE COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susan Fliess had been looking forward to receiving pictures of a
friend's baby through e-mail. She never got the chance. The
pictures arrived at fliess1(at)netscape.net, the e-mail address she
shared with her husband, Kevin, but then: ``Kevin was, like:
`What's this big, huge file? You know what their baby looks
like,''' Fliess said. ``The next thing I knew, he'd deleted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fliess doesn't mind an overflowing In box; her husband does. The
Silicon Valley couple, married nearly three years, decided to deal
with their different attitudes toward clutter by getting separate
e-mail accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The ascendancy of e-mail has opened a new arena to the delicate
diplomacy of relationships. Couples can share many things _ living
space, secrets, friends and finances. Should they share e-mail
accounts, as well?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things need to be negotiated, and e-mail is one of
them,'' said JoAnn Magdoff, a psychotherapist in Manhattan who has
written about the psychology of the Internet. ``But e-mail has its
own twists. It adds a layer of instant intimacy.'' A shared account
``raises issues of how far you really want to go in terms of
disclosure,'' Magdoff said.
</P>
<P>
   People may want an individual e-mail address at home, but feel
snubbed when their partners do, too. Or they may like the freedom
to gripe to their friends without being fearful or self-conscious
about what their partners might read.
</P>
<P>
   One stay-at-home mother, who did not want her name used, said
she resented that her husband had a private office address while
she used their shared AOL address at home. ``He can look at my
mail,'' she said, ``but I can't look at his.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he reads the mail and deletes it, so she doesn't see
it at all. At other times, he uses AOL's ``keep as new'' function
so she can't tell he has read the mail. And even when she has
deleted her outgoing messages, her friends have occasionally
incorporated them into their replies.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband was furious after finding out via an e-mail message
sent to her that she had told a friend something she had kept from
him.
</P>
<P>
   A common mistake couples make is assuming that e-mail is like
other, older forms of communication, Magdoff said. ``People dash
off e-mail where they wouldn't pick up the phone and certainly
wouldn't pick up a pen,'' she said. Home e-mail also affords much
less privacy than, say, a home telephone. On the phone, callers
assume that a couple share both a number and an answering machine;
talkers almost always know if there is a chance they may be
overheard.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for couples to create a merged e-mail name,
like romeoandjuliet(at)aol.com, or to announce their closeness with
an address like wevegoteachother(at)aol.com. The inclusiveness of a
merged name can be an appealing part of a relationship, said Lynn
Harris, who dispenses relationship advice on the Breakup Girl Web
site (www.breakupgirl.com). She refers to joint e-mail addresses as
``we-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people should share everything,'' Harris said.
``Some things are your own stuff. With so much free Web-based
e-mail, there's no need to share.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple's use of joint e-mail can reflect the way they function
in the real world. For Rabbi Michael Beals, the leader of B'nai
Tikvah Congregation in Los Angeles, and his wife, Elissa Green, a
veterinarian, that means he handles the household correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got married five years ago,'' Beals said, ``all the
`ugh' part of life Elissa delegated to me, like paying the bills
and taking out the kitty litter. You should play to your strengths.
My strength is communication, so I'm the one sending most of these
messages out. We're a team. It's fine for me to speak in both of
our names.''
</P>
<P>
   Their e-mail address, rabbivet(at)lafn.org, has caused some
confusion, though, with people assuming the rabbi is a war veteran.
Their signoff _ ``Michael, Elissa, Yofi and Shovas'' _ includes the
dog and the cat. It expresses what is important to them, Beals
said, although some of their correspondents think both the address
and the signoff are a little too cute.
</P>
<P>
   Even people with their own accounts face a question: Should they
reveal their passwords to their partners?
</P>
<P>
   Harris believes that whatever conclusion a couple reach,
password-sharing should not become another intimacy test in a
relationship. ``Some people are weird about sharing anything,''
Harris said. ``They wouldn't give their mom food off their fork.
You have to be careful about drawing relationship conclusions from
other interpersonal weirdness. It might not be a matter of intimacy
at all, but of what boundaries are comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The real red flag, Harris said, is online snooping. Like
medicine cabinets, credit-card bills and diaries, e-mail tempts the
distrustful. Judging from Breakup Girl's advice seekers _ and these
are people in troubled partnerships, not harmonious ones _ ``the
problem is there's enough suspicion to cause the snooping,'' Harris
said.
</P>
<P>
   And if that troubled partnership should dissolve, a shared
e-mail address means yet another headache.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when Dina Robertson and her husband, Scott
Robertson, got a home computer, ``it didn't occur to me not to do
something together,'' said Robertson, of Greenland, N.H. So they
combined everyone's initials, choosing SDDRobt(at)aol.com. (The
second D is for their son, Douglass.)
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when her husband moved out, there was no dispute
that Robertson, the coordinator for a children's advocacy group,
would keep the address. She changed the password.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is gradually reclaiming her maiden name, Dudarevitch.
But she can't get rid of her husband's name on her e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am thoroughly involved with that address,'' she said. ``If I
changed it, it would affect hundreds of people. I feel locked into
it. It really bothers me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
