<SLUG> BC-NASA17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. WILL PUSH AHEAD WITH SPACE STATION, CONGRESS TOLD
 &HT;    By ANGEL WILSON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NASA plans to continue construction of the
International Space Station regardless of whether Russia's
participates on schedule, a congressional panel was told Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   NASA Administrator Daniel S. Goldin told the House subcommittee
on space and aeronautics that the United States is prepared to
launch the interim control module and other space station
components without waiting for Russia to launch a service module
that was scheduled to be put in orbit first.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said Russia cannot be given full blame for the space
station delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians were not alone in experiencing launch failures,
as the Japanese, Europeans, and the U.S. struggled as well to
achieve safe and reliable access to space,'' he said. ``Russia was
having financial problems and the United States was having
technical problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The space station was the main topic during the hearing which
focused on NASA's budget proposal for 2001. President Clinton
requested $14 billion for NASA, an increase of 3.2 percent over the
budget for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The station involves 15 countries, including the United States,
Japan, and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Subcommittee members criticized Russia's inability to launch its
service module. The delay of the service module has caused a
six-year delay in the launching of NASA's interim control module,
costing the U.S. taxpayers millions of dollars since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members also expressed concern over the Mars Surveyor
program and the space shuttle program. The Mars Surveyor program
suffered a serious blow last year with the loss of the Mars Climate
Orbiter, the Mars Polar Lander and the Deep Space-2 probes.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said he was aware of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of the Mars failures, I appointed a Mars Program
Independent Assessment Team in December of 1999 led by A. Thomas
Young. That team has been charged to review and assess the entire
Mars program architecture, management, content, and recent
failures. Its report is due out in mid-March,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a particularly slow space shuttle year with only two
successful missions in 1999, NASA plans to complete six missions in
2000. The manifest for 2001 already has nine missions listed; seven
of those missions involve assembly of the space station.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 shuttle budget of $3.2 billion will enable the system
to successfully meet its goals of safer flying, customer diversity,
system improvement, and supportability improvement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must continue to ensure the space shuttle's viability as a
safe, effective transportation system and scientific platform,''
Goldin said.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Wilson's e-mail address is angelw(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
