<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8844 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-US-AFRICA-0217-COX     02-16 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-AFRICA-0217-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUMMIT SEEKS TO BOOST TRADE BETWEEN U.S., AFRICA
 &HT;    (800&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With chart information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The organizers of a national confab on Africa want
American companies and investors to realize what their European
counterparts have known for centuries: that Africa represents a
multi-billion dollar opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Africa's perceived political instability aside, such opportunity
was not lost on President Clinton two years ago when he paid the
longest visit to the continent by a modern-day American president.
At the time, more than 150,000 American jobs _ many in the
Southeastern U.S. _ were dependent upon trade with African nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those jobs are tied to (Africa's) oil, petroleum, and mining
industries,'' said Leonard H. Robinson Jr., president of the
National Summit on Africa _ which is hosting a five-day conference
that began here Wednesday in hopes of boosting commercial ties
between Africa and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Priority one in turning that hope into reality is making
American companies aware of the burgeoning business opportunities
in Africa to improve U.S.-Africa trade, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster that message, both President Clinton and Vice
President and Democratic presidential front-runner Al Gore will
each address the group Thursday and Friday, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more than 20,000 expected to attend, many _ such
Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell _ are already working to develop
increased ties with African nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, we took more than 60 people and 25 businesses
to South Africa for 10 days,'' said Campbell, who sees Atlanta as a
gateway to Africa. ``Now, with projects in place such as Delta Air
Lines' direct flight to South Africa, we are beginning to see the
results of our efforts through increased travel, trade
opportunities and growing tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, few American corporations _ such as Delta, Goodyear,
and H.J. Heinz _ have done business with African nations over the
years. That number pales in comparison to Europe, behind which U.S.
trade with the continent continues to lag.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Department of Commerce, U.S. trade with
Africa in fiscal year 1999 was $22 billion. Europe, by comparison,
did $63 billion worth of trade with Africa in 1998, the last year
for which complete figures are available.
</P>
<P>
   A primary reason for the trade gap falls upon American
companies' fear of political instability, military coups and
investments being expropriated by governments, said Mark Mallach
Brown, administrator of the United Nations Development Programme
(UNDP).
</P>
<P>
   Incidents from Ethiopia to Congo to Nigeria, and even the
relatively stable Ivory Coast, have done little to allay those
fears over the last decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Robinson argues, Africa is making economic progress and
it is time for American companies to take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was quick to explain, however, ``I'm not talking about
Americans staking out Africa for economic exploitation . . . (but)
Americans engaging in trade, investments, business with Africa on
an equal plane.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, efforts by Clinton and some in the U.S. Congress
have led the way in promoting trade with Africa. The Africa Growth
and Opportunity Act, the first major trade bill in five years, if
passed, would reward American sale and investment in Africa and cut
tariffs on imported African clothing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Export-Import Bank, which provides U.S.
exporters with financing, distributed $600 million in loans last
year. And bank chairman James Harmon last month promised another $1
billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, the the Ex-Im Bank has done 44 transactions in
Sub-Saharan Africa, totaling $77 million, said Gloria Cabe,
counselor to the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that excites us (about the 44 transactions) is that
we've had a lot of small transactions, which means that we are
supporting small American businesses as well as the large ones,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, others say increasing trade with Africa is the last thing
the continent, which is ``a basket case,'' needs. Walter Williams,
an economics professor at George Mason University said Africa is
more in need of a stable political system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want to invest in an area where there were no rule
of law and no respect for contracts,'' he said. ``You need
institutional infrastructure to promote investment.''
</P>
<P>
   George Ayittey, a professor of economics at American University
here agrees. He said although he is not opposed to helping African
people, their leaders haven't shown a strong commitment to reform.
And by investing in the continent, American companies are
supporting the gangs and thugs who run the governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can pass all the bills you want, but it won't make a
difference unless African leaders are willing to change,'' said
Ayittey, a native of Ghana.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a former World Bank vice president, agreed that Africa
has to regain American investors' confidence by building a
portfolio of success stories. But, he added that political
instability should not be a reason not to trade and invest in the
continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every country's long-term salvation depends on trade and
investment, not just aid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -----------------------------------------------------------------
</P>
