<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8847 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-KIRK-DOUGLAS-HNS     02-16 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KIRK-DOUGLAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIRK DOUGLAS STARTS `NEW CAREER' IN `DIAMONDS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Kirk Douglas is still game. After a
morning of interviews, the gray-haired actor _ he is now 83 _
should be exhausted. But courtesy comes first, and he quickly gets
to his feet to welcome his next interrogator.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas is clearly on an enthusiasm high. His handshake is
strong, and the light in his dark hazel eyes burns bright.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder. After years off the screen, the actor who was
always famous for his physical and emotional vigor is back,
starring in a motion picture, by his own count his 82nd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamonds,'' opening Friday, is Douglas' first film since the
stroke that hit him in January 1996 and a back operation that same
month.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Diamonds,'' Douglas plays Harry, a former boxer who has had
a stroke. Like Douglas, Harry has trouble pronouncing words but has
worked hard at speech therapy and can now be understood maybe 95
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Like Harry, Douglas has a lot to say. Publicists for
``Diamonds'' have to almost literally pull him away from the
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy who can't talk, I talk a lot,'' Douglas jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody minds. Douglas is a legend of cinema, a box-office star
from the late 1940s through 1970s, still playing leads into the
1980s. Make that into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Among his films: ``Champion'' (his first Oscar nomination,
1949), ``Young Man With a Horn'' and ``The Glass Menagerie'' (both
1950), ``The Bad and the Beautiful'' (Oscar nomination, 1953),
``20,000 Leagues Under the Sea'' (1954), ``Lust for Life'' (Oscar
nomination, 1956), ``The Gunfight at the O.K. Corral'' (1957),
``Paths of Glory'' (1958), ``Spartacus'' (1960), ``Lonely Are the
Brave'' (1962), ``Seven Days in May'' (1964), ``The Man From Snowy
River'' (1982) and ``Tough Guys'' (the last of seven films with pal
Burt Lancaster, 1986).
</P>
<P>
   Though he has never received an Academy Award for acting, he was
nominated three times and accepted a special Oscar in 1996. He
received an American Film Institute Life Achievement Award in 1991,
he was selected one of AFI's top 25 male stars of all time in 1999,
and was named one of the top 100 stars of all time by Entertainment
Weekly in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Jewish Russian immigrants (he was born Issur
Danielovitch on Dec. 9, 1916), he began acting in college and was
on Broadway by 1941. After World War II service, he got the male
lead opposite Barbara Stanwyck in his first movie, ``The Strange
Love of Martha Ivers'' in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   But his breakthrough came playing a tough boxer in ``Champion.''
How fitting it is, therefore, that scenes of Douglas in
``Champion'' are used for flashbacks in ``Diamonds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to go out and cast a guy who looked like young
Kirk Douglas,'' said ``Diamonds'' director John Mallory Asher.
``Kirk said, `Why don't we use `Champion' for this?'''
</P>
<P>
   The old boxing film means more to Douglas than just his first
Academy Award nomination. It broke him out of the ``intellectual''
characters he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When `Champion' came along, my agent was mad at me because
they had me assigned to a big picture with Gregory Peck and Ava
Gardner called `The Great Sinner.' I said `No, I want to do this
little picture, `Champion.' `Champion' made me a star.''
</P>
<P>
   As we sit in a large guest room in the exclusive L'Ermitage
hotel in Beverly Hills, the effects of age, a half-decade of pain
after a 1991 helicopter crash and the stroke are clearly evident on
that famous, broken-nosed, granite face. But the profile, seen
against the bright sunlight through a side window, is still strong
and distinct, and his trademark cleft chin is unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas is dressed in a black turtleneck, khaki slacks, white
socks and dark deck shoes. His hair is combed straight back.
</P>
<P>
   He struggles with his speech. The words are thick and come
slowly. But you'd better believe he is in command of them.
</P>
<P>
   In the original script for ``Diamonds,'' the character Harry had
Alzheimer's disease. It was changed to fit Douglas, who helped
rewrite many scenes to add what he had experienced. Even the
therapy tapes Harry watches are Douglas' own tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kirk and I did a lot of rewrites as we were shooting,'' Asher
said. ``He'd call me in the middle of the night and say `What about
Scene 54?' About 2 a.m. I'd hang up the phone and two hours later
I'd get up and go to the set. This was very important to him. I
can't commend him enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Diamonds,'' Harry has a melancholy scene with the madam of
a house of ill repute _ played by Douglas' lifelong friend Lauren
Bacall (they knew each other before they were in movies) _ and
tells her how difficult fighting back from the stroke has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see a lot of the screenplay I wrote myself,'' Douglas
says. ``(Like) when I told Bacall, `You just want to cry and give
up on everything.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was how Douglas felt in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terrible thing about a stroke is the depression,'' he
says. ``At the beginning of my stroke, I babbled like a baby. What
is an actor if he can't talk, you know? When I first had my stroke,
after my helicopter crash almost breaking my back, I thought, `I
will never do another movie again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you have to motivate yourself. Or have, like in my
case, your wife (of 45 years, Anne Douglas) say, `Come on, get your
(behind) out of bed and start working.'''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to act, Douglas turned back to writing. His 1988
autobiography, ``The Ragman's Son,'' had been a best seller, and he
had written three novels: ``The Gift,'' ``Dance With the Devil''
and ``Last Tango in Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 came a new memoir, ``Climbing the Mountain: My Search
for Meaning.'' The children's book ``Young Heroes of the Bible''
came out last October.
</P>
<P>
   But his real love and work is acting. He admits he missed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like coming back home,'' he says about working on
``Diamonds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was an important picture because, with a lot of
humor and some poignant scenes, we were making a statement, that
having a stroke is not the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamonds'' is a generational drama with comedy about the
bonding between Douglas' character, Harry's long-estranged adult
son Lance, played by Dan Aykroyd, and Lance's son (Corbin Allred).
</P>
<P>
   Forced into a road trip together, they discover the
relationships they had all been missing.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas has four sons, all of whom went into show business,
something he did not want to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want my kids to be actors,'' he says. ``The chances
for success are remote.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael, of course, became almost as famous as his dad. The two
have never made a film together, but father and son still hope to
act together in a movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the stroke, Michael and I were working on a script.
When I had the stroke, Michael said, `Well, Dad, keep working with
your speech therapist and we'll do the movie.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Look, why don't you work with my speech therapist.
And when you talk like I talk, then we'll make the movie.' He
thought that was very funny.''
</P>
<P>
   At least they soon will be onscreen in some of the same
theaters. Michael's new film, ``Wonder Boys,'' opens Feb. 25, a
week after ``Diamonds.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, who recently had his second bar mitzvah _ 70 years
after his first _ is looking forward to more acting work. He is set
to shoot a segment of ``Touched By An Angel'' this month and has
film plans in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have many things to be grateful for,'' he says. ``Making
`Diamonds' was like starting my life over again as an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   So the legend goes on. But don't tell Kirk Douglas he's a
legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not complimented because I think a legend involves the
past,'' he says thoughtfully. ``And I like to think that with my
stroke, I am now embarking on a new career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finished? I just started.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
