<SLUG> BC-CIR-SCHOOL-EMAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS HESITANT TO SEND TEACHERS E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (With CUR-SCHOOL-WEBSITES)  
(lh) 
 By BONNIE ROTHMAN MORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In September, Tricia Zarro, a first-grade teacher at Springhurst
Elementary School in Dobbs Ferry, N.Y., furnished her e-mail
address to the parents of her 19 pupils in the hope of making
herself more accessible. Since then, only four parents have sent
her e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   Zarro's experience is not atypical. Though many teachers have
been quick to supply their e-mail addresses to students and
parents, parents have not been using them.
</P>
<P>
   Even David Leahy, a fifth-grade teacher at Greenaway Elementary
School in Beaverton, Ore., whose Web-based activities are well
publicized in his school, said that on average, he receives only
one e-mail message every other week from parents of his students.
</P>
<P>
   Some teachers, though, may be secretly relieved by the parental
silence. ``A teacher's worst nightmare is that they get 30 e-mails
from all the parents they never had to respond to before,'' said
Jonathan Carson, chairman of the Family Education Network, a group
of online sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of educators still have some doubts as to how closely
they want to be communicating with parents,'' said Peter Grunwald,
president of Grunwald Associates, a consulting firm in San Mateo,
Calif. They seem to be concerned that they may have to give up some
of their autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Leahy said, an e-mail note from a parent to quickly
explain that a child is having a hard time at home, which may
affect his behavior at school, could be helpful. He said he looked
forward to a time when a parent did not hesitate to send him e-mail
with news. ``It isn't happening yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason may be that parents who did not do well in school may
feel intimidated, said Barbara Stein, a senior policy analyst at
the National Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   Or they just might fear getting back e-mail that has been graded
and checked for spelling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
