<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8854 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-IMAGE-SEARCH-2TAK     02-16 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-IMAGE-SEARCH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH SOFTWARE THAT COMPARES APPLES AND ORANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (Circuits) 
(af) 
By LISA GUERNSEY  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, experts in digital imagery have been puzzled by a
major technical challenge: Can technology be developed that enables
people to search for images by visual characteristics alone? Will
searchers someday be able to find photographs of, say, a basketball
game by searching for an image of a basketball, instead of relying
on keywords tagged to that photograph?
</P>
<P>
   Many high-tech engineers are now willing to admit that the
challenge is much more difficult than originally envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you can search for a basketball, explained Carlos
Montalvo, vice president for marketing at Virage, a company that
has developed image-searching tools and applied them to video.
``But you are just as likely to get an image with an orange or a
sunset,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of striving for perfection, several companies and
research laboratories are taking a different tack. Driven by the
proliferation of online images and digital cameras, engineers have
started to think about how even low-level technology can meet the
needs of a typical consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have concluded, for example, that people might be
satisfied with the ability to search through their digital
photographs by looking for relatively simple characteristics, like
colors or patterns, instead of specific images.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a new generation of image-searching technologies
that are ready for the consumer market, or nearly so. The majority
of them use low-level image searching, then incorporate keywords,
speech-recognition systems and other data, like the time a
photograph was taken, to refine the searches.
</P>
<P>
   One is called Shoebox, a project at AT&AMP;T Labs. It starts with
the concept at the crux of digital-image searching: matching visual
features (which are in essence bits of data) with mathematical
representations.
</P>
<P>
   A specific color, for example, is assigned a specific
mathematical code. An image containing several colors in a pattern
is represented by a combination of codes.
</P>
<P>
   When Shoebox's software is applied to a batch of digital
photographs, the program is able to index those photographs
according to the codes that signify their features. ``We do an
analysis of the color, texture and shape of that image,'' said Ken
Wood, a research scientist who manages the Shoebox project
(www.uk.research.att.com/dart/shoebox).
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, for example, the software analyzes a picture of a polar
bear. First it segments the picture by tracing regions that are
differentiated by color. Then it labels those segments and prepares
to find similar ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can say, This is a white fuzzy region with the following
shape and texture properties,'' Wood said. ``Then we can look at
the database and find other images that have white fuzzy regions
with similar shapes and sizes.''
</P>
<P>
   Corresponding pictures are shown with thumbnail images; some of
them, like a photograph of a woman in a white fur coat, may be
false matches. That is where the science of image searching ends
and the human brain comes in. A person looking at those thumbnails,
Wood said, could simply discard the fur coat picture. ``As long as
you can see immediately what you want, you can continue to narrow
your search,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wood also expects that people using the software might at least
tag photographs they have taken, either with the time stamps that
are automatically applied by digital cameras or by annotating the
images with keywords or recorded audio snippets. When the
technology is licensed by a manufacturer and ready to be sold,
which Wood said might happen within a year, it will probably
include a combination of those features.
</P>
<P>
   International Business Machines has incorporated some of the
same principles in its work on a technology it calls Query By Image
Content, or QBIC. QBIC, which was developed more than five years
ago, analyzes how colors and patterns are arrayed in an image.
</P>
<P>
   Now office-software makers like Lotus are starting to embed some
elements of the technology in their products so people can search
for things like presentation slides by typing in information about
a slide's layout and background colors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The technology is not as precise as some researchers would like,
said Dragutin Petkovic, the IBM scientist who started the QBIC
project. But he said that it would still have some significant
commercial applications, especially for e-commerce sites that sell
clothing or interior design products.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future,'' Petkovic said, ``you could take a piece of
fabric from your neighbor and then find all the Web sites that sell
similar fabric.''
</P>
<P>
   A demonstration on QBIC's Web site (wwwqbic.almaden.ibm.com)
shows how the technology works when applied to a database of stamp
images. If you are looking at a stamp with a green tint, for
example, you can request a color search and find a sample of stamps
with that tint.
</P>
<P>
   Petkovic is now applying the principles he learned in QBIC to a
more complex project called Cue-Video that combines image searching
with speech- and voice-recognition software.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, video searching is considered by many engineers to be
the next major application to use image analysis. One company that
has already decided to focus on video searching is Virage, which
has impressed television executives in the past year by
demonstrating how video clips of broadcast news can be archived and
searched.
</P>
<P>
   To index a video, Virage's technology watches for changes in the
color and patterns of each frame. A drastic change _ like a switch
from an anchorwoman sitting at a desk to a shot of a traffic jam _
is detected by the software, enabling it to tag those frames as a
new segment or idea.
</P>
<P>
   Those segments are then displayed on a computer screen as
sequential thumbnail images that offer a storyboard of the video.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Virage's technology integrates other elements of the
broadcast, like audio transcripts and the text that might go with a
graphic, into the index of the video clip. The company's next
endeavor, sales representatives say, is to add face recognition. By
analyzing famous people's photographs for features like the
distance between their eyes and the color of their hair, the
software finds matching images in live or stored video.
</P>
<P>
   Virage's primary clients are corporations and television
networks that can afford such advanced technology. But the company
is also offering a free program called MyLogger (it can be
downloaded at Virage's Web site, www.virage.com) that incorporates
some of Virage's basic tools for searching images and transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some people have a more basic request: they simply
want to search the Web for images instead of text. Some search
sites, like AltaVista, have offered help over the years by letting
people search for keywords that might show up in image file names
(like basketball.jpg). Now a handful of sites are trying to add
image analysis to the process.
</P>
<P>
   One is WholeWeb.net, a search-engine company that is creating a
program that its founders say will be able to match scanned
photographs to an index of images found on the Web. Another site,
Ditto.com, is already using some low-level image analysis, in
combination with keyword searching, to sort online images
discovered by its Web crawlers. Recently, the site has been
attracting as many as 10 million visitors each month, said John
Treacy, vice president for product management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly,'' Treacy said, ``the Internet has moved way, way
beyond enabling people to search for text.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1655EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
