<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-DOG-PICTURES-ART-NYT &LR;      02-16 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-PICTURES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MARKET FOR DOG PAINTINGS REFUSES TO PLAY DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Britain, Ireland, Greece, Texas, Conn.) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the John Emms painting of dogs called ``A Jack
and Two Knaves'' sold on Tuesday for $140,000, more than three
times the low estimate, the audience let out a collective whoop _
and the auctioneers breathed a sigh of relief. Only two lots
before, another Emms painting ``Sailor and Bramble'' did not sell
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was Dog Day at the William Doyle Galleries. With the
Westminster Kennel Club show packing dog lovers in at Madison
Square Garden, the auctioneers hoped this would be an ideal time to
auction hundreds of dog pictures, many of debatable value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these things that would only go for $100 or $200 in
one of our regular sales are bringing $400 or $500,'' said Alan
Fausel, the senior vice president in charge of European and
American painting at Doyle. ``In a regular sale, they would be lost
in the shuffle.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first such sale last year, Charles O'Brien, Fausel's
counterpart at Bonhams auction house in London, was ``stunned by
the prices Americans pay for the paintings,'' Fausel said. For his
part, O'Brien was a bit more circumspect. ``Americans,'' he said,
``really love the dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   So Doyle, joined by Bonhams, saved up dog paintings (and a few
cats), collected some dog sculptures and memorabilia, published a
color catalog and ``threw the net wide,'' said Kathleen M. Doyle,
the company's chairwoman. ``We got bidders from the Shetland
Islands, from London, from Texas, Ireland, Greece and New York,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Doyle said the sale had netted $743,000; a
mere doggy tidbit at an Old Master's sale, but a cause for delight
for a group of paintings that included a lot of brown hounds, some
dachshunds ripping apart an accordion, and a small portrait of
``Lady Yule's Favorite Poodle, Fifi,'' which sold for $3,250.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the usual crowd of decorators _ Mario Buatta paid $7,187
for a small painting of ``three sissy-looking dogs'' _ the
auctioneers sought dog breeders in town for the kennel club show,
hunters and anglers and dog painting collectors.
</P>
<P>
   While the hunters and anglers were not immediately apparent, the
collectors were, especially the younger ones.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Flannery, 27, and her husband, Will Flannery 3rd, 26,
who run a software consulting business in Houston. They came up for
the auction, with their 3-month-old son, Will IV.
</P>
<P>
   Flannery, who wore a silk shirt patterned with brown English
setters, said she and her husband knew they wanted to collect art.
``Then we went to Paris a year ago and bought our first dog
painting, and now we're hooked,'' she said. ``So we're having fun
collecting. My husband's a big hunter. He loves to quail hunt,
pheasant hunt, deer hunt.'' They bought Lot No. 8, ``By the Day's
Bag,'' of an English pointer and a Labrador retriever, for $2,530
and No. 97, ``English Setter Working a Wood,'' for $2,300.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd much rather collect dog memorabilia than spend money on
food,'' Flannery said with a laugh. ``We've been having fun buying
$5 dinners in diners and delis, and eating hot dogs on the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Steve Faigen, an aspiring collector who lives in New York, was
taken by the picture of the dachshunds going wild with the
accordion. ``I especially love pictures of dogs behaving badly,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although they were clearly enjoying themselves, some of the
newer collectors may not have been making the best investments,
auctioneers and dealers alike say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's straight dog portraits, and not paintings by Stubbs or
one of the great 18th-century painters, as far as their intrinsic
worth goes, I don't think they're any great shakes,'' said John
Rosselli, an art and curio dealer. ``They're decorative art.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosselli has begun reproducing some of the more appealing
decorative dog paintings in oils and acrylics, which he sells for
$1,000 to $1,500. ``People buy five or six and hang them together
on a wall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   J.J. Smith, a dealer in New Haven, Conn., said the market for
dog paintings is specialized but growing. ``Until 10 years ago,
your run-of-the-mill dog pictures were a plague on the market, seen
as not very serious, a sort of hee-hee,'' he said. ``Then all of a
sudden, they were like teddy bears: people started collecting
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Victorians particularly liked anthropomorphic images,'' he
continued. ``They seem a little gooey for modern tastes, but dog
lovers are used to looking at their animals, speaking to them,
misconstruing their looks _ although now they're finding that dogs
do smile.''
</P>
<P>
   While a lot of dog paintings may not be worth much as an
investment, Smith predicted that ``serious prices will be paid for
some of the top names.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's sale, it was clear he was right.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Emms painting ``Jack and Two Knaves'' which brought
$140,000, another large oil of four beagles by Wright Barker sold
for $60,000, the high estimate. A Victorian picture of puppies
playing with a British naval officer's jacket and sword, called
``Defense of the Realm'' brought $24,150. ``Study of the Head of a
Hound'' by Heywood Hardy, small and damaged but well painted, went
for $11,500 after spirited bidding.
</P>
<P>
   An almost surrealistic ``Group of 10 Black Labrador Retrievers
on a Beach,'' by Reuben Ward Binks (described in the catalog as the
Sargent of the dog world), brought $9,775. The auction house had
estimated that the work would sell for $1,800 to $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 66 out of 220 works sold for under $1,000. So far, there
has not been a dog picture that has surpassed ``Portrait of a
Newfoundland Dog,'' painted by George Stubbs for the Duke of York
in 1803, an oil that Sotheby's sold in November for $3.695 million.
Now that was a serious price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
