<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPLACING HANDLES ON TOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many craftsmen have a favorite hammer or other hand tool that
was purchased many years ago or one that was inherited from a
relative.
</P>
<P>
   Older tools are apt to have traditional wooden handles fashioned
from hickory. The main problem with wooden handles is that with
rough use, they can crack, split or break. It is unsafe to use a
hammer _ or any tool _ with a damaged handle. The only way to
salvage the tool is by replacing the handle.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing a hammer handle is not a difficult task, but first you
must remove the old handle. Begin by sawing off the damaged handle
just below the base of the hammerhead. Use a punch to drive the
remaining portion out of the ''eye.'' If this piece is firmly
wedged in and proves difficult to punch out, use a power drill to
bore out as much wood as possible, then punch out the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Some do-it-yourselfers try to burn the wood out of the head with
a torch. This is not a good practice because it will destroy the
temper of the steel.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to buy a replacement handle. These are
available in hardware stores, lumberyards and home centers. Even
though most stores stock one or two common handle sizes, it's still
a good idea to take along your hammerhead to check the fit.
</P>
<P>
   When you buy a new handle, you should also get two metal wedges
as part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the new handle by clamping it in a vise between blocks
of scrap wood and cutting two slots across the top with a back saw.
The slots should be about two-thirds of the hammerhead's depth.
Drive the head onto the handle. If the handle is too large to
accommodate the head, use a file to remove some wood, but don't
overdo it; the handle must fit tightly.
</P>
<P>
   After tapping the head onto the handle as far as it will go, cut
off any projecting wood so that the shaft is flush with the top of
the head.
</P>
<P>
   Next place the hammer in a 150-degree oven for an hour. This
will dry and season the wood thoroughly and assure a tight-fitting
handle.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, drive the two metal wedges into the slots that you
previously cut into the shaft. Tap each wedge alternately to spread
the wood evenly in the eye. File the handle flush with the top of
the head. Finish by sanding lightly then brushing on a coat of
linseed oil to protect the exposed wood.
</P>
<P>
   The same technique can be used to replace an ax or hatchet
handle. One difference in replacing an ax handle is that there is
only one metal wedge; the other is wood. Cut the slots to receive
these wedges at right angles to each other. The wooden wedge, which
is the larger of the two, is driven first into the slot cut across
the long axis of the handle top. Drive the metal wedge into the
other, smaller slot.
</P>
<P>
   Finish the job by filing the top of the handle flush with the ax
head, then sand and coat it with linseed oil.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing a broken shovel handle is a little more difficult
because the old handle is usually riveted in place. In addition,
the new handle usually must be cut to length and the end shaped to
fit the shovel socket. Part of the old handle will be riveted into
the shovel socket, so you will have to remove the rivet before you
can pull that piece out. Use a small grindstone chucked into an
electric drill to grind off the rivet head. Then drive the rivet
out with a hammer and punch.
</P>
<P>
   If the handle stub is broken off near the rim of the socket,
there may not be enough wood projecting to grip the stub and pull
it out. Try driving a three-inch wood screw into the handle stub.
Clamp the head of the screw in a vise and hit the shovel shoulder
with a mallet. This should drive the shovel away and leave the
handle stub and screw in the vise.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a new shovel handle at a home or garden center. Use the
assembled pieces of the old handle to determine the length of the
new one. The end of the new handle must be filed to a taper so it
can fit into the shovel socket.
</P>
<P>
   Again, use the old handle stub as guide to see how much material
you will have to shave off.
</P>
<P>
   When the taper is correct, fit the handle into place, then tap
it on the end to drive it home. Locate the rivet hole in the shovel
socket and drill a pilot hole into the handle. Drive a round-head
wood screw to secure the handle in the shovel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
