<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8879 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     02-16 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV05-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., MAR. 5, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I want to hang some vinyl wallcovering on my kitchen walls.
</P>
<P>
   In some of the homes I've seen, the electric outlet plates are
covered with the same decorative wallcovering so that they are
hardly noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   Is this something an amateur like me can do, and if so, are
there any suggestions or tips you can offer?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although simple to do, it does require some care and patience
if you want the pattern on the outlet plate to match the pattern
around it.
</P>
<P>
   Start by cutting out a piece of the wallcovering a few inches
bigger than the size of the outlet plate, but cut this piece out of
a section where the pattern approximately matches the section where
the electric plate is located.
</P>
<P>
   Hold this piece of material against the wall and hold the outlet
plate against it, moving the pattern around until the small piece
of material matches the pattern around it.
</P>
<P>
   Mark the corners of the plate on the piece of wallcovering by
using a pin or ice pick, then lay the piece of wallcovering face
down and cover the back of it and the front of the wall plate with
adhesive.
</P>
<P>
   Paste the wallcovering over the plate, making sure the pin
perforations in the corner exactly match the corners of the outlet
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Then cut off the four corners of the wallcovering at a diagonal
and use a razor blade to cut two diagonal lines across the material
covering each opening in the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Fold the flaps created into the holes so the material sticks to
the back of the plate, then wrap the excess around all four sides
of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Each time I flush my toilet there is an inch or two of water
left in the bowl. As a result the paper and solid waste does not
always get flushed away with just the one flush.
</P>
<P>
   The tank fills up OK, but a plumber I called said he had no
solution. Can you suggest what the problem might be?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sounds as though there is not enough water coming into the
bowl with each flush.
</P>
<P>
   This usually means that the water level inside the tank is not
high enough when the tank is full.
</P>
<P>
   All toilet tank ballcocks (inlet valves) can be adjusted to
regulate the height of the water in the filled tank, so try
adjusting this valve to make the tank fill up to a higher level
than you have now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The summer cottage I recently bought has ceilings covered
with untreated cedar sheets and there are water stains on these
ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   I would like to leave the ceilings untreated if possible, but
can you tell me how to remove the water stains?
</P>
<P>
   A: When you refer to ``cedar sheets'' I assume you mean cedar
plywood _ or wood of some kind. If so, removing the stains would be
almost impossible unless you use a wood bleach.
</P>
<P>
   But this means bleaching all the wood, not just the stained
areas. Otherwise you would end up with a blotchy appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you do bleach the entire ceiling, chances are that the
overall color would not be uniform unless you applied a stain or
sealer of some kind.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The varnished woodwork in my old house had an overall blond
color that showed the wood grain.
</P>
<P>
   I used a remover to take off all the varnish, but now it still
shows the white stain in some places but not in others.
</P>
<P>
   I like the original blond effect and want to restore this with a
white stain, but am not sure what to do about the uneven appearance
of the present woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   I tried applying a white stain, but it hid the grain in some
places and not in others.
</P>
<P>
   How can I duplicate the original blond or white stain effect?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is likely that when you used the remover you did not get
all of the old varnish off, so that some sections are still at
least partially sealed. In these places the stain cannot soak in.
</P>
<P>
   I think you need to go over these sections with another heavy
coat of varnish remover, using a semi-paste heavy duty type that
will work longer and do a better job of stripping down to the bare
wood.
</P>
<P>
   Then you should be able to get the effect you want by using a
white stain and wiping only part of it off to show the grain.
</P>
<P>
   Allow this to dry, then apply your varnish.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``CONCEALING OUTLET PLATE WITH
WALLPAPER'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: When covering outlet plates use section of wallcovering
that will match pattern on wall, then cut out piece and fold edges
over after pasting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
