</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BLACK-HISTORY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN-AMERICAN SITES LOOK BACK AND FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIC V. COPAGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sepia-colored words are evenly spaced and have a
schoolmarm's pedantic forward tilt. Looking at the letter quickly,
you might think it a recounting of a debutante's ball, not the
correspondent's matter-of-fact telling of being sold five times in
as many years, and the hope that her current owner will buy her
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was written by Vilet Lester in August 1857 and can be
found in an online archive of 19th-century letters from
African-American women. Brought face to face with it on your
computer screen, you are suddenly confronted with the smells,
sounds and mossy humidity of history.
</P>
<P>
   It's paradoxical that at a time when there is so much talk of a
digital divide, there are an unprecedented number of resources for
black history online.
</P>
<P>
   ``My 9-year-old daughter needed `Up From Slavery,' by Booker T.
Washington, and we just downloaded it,'' said Bianca Floyd, a
writer who has done research for The Chronicle of Higher Education.
</P>
<P>
   F. Leon Wilson, who is writing a book called ``Black Pioneers of
the Internet,'' said: ``Web sites are collecting information that
is not available through formal textbooks because they are not up
to date. The Web is allowing students to tap into this new
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens and enlightens a whole new discussion, not just for
African-Americans, but for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   There are online resources available for the scholar and the
schoolchild. They include photographs and documents, like the
slave's letter, that at one time were confined to musty libraries,
perhaps many miles from the inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the resources were previously available only to those
affiliated with a college or university.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd lauded the exponential growth in black historic Web sites
and credited academics for making information available. ``The
scholarly community should be commended,'' Floyd said. ``Many don't
get paid to put the information online. They just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some important caveats regarding the use of the
Internet to search for information on black history, Floyd added.
``For instance, you can't just use a search engine and type in
`black women,''' she warned. ``You are likely to get all these
links to pornographic sites and links to racist Web sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd said that when she was helping her young daughter, she
started with institutions like Duke University, the University of
Pennsylvania, the University of California at Los Angeles and
Harvard, which link to one another and other reliable sources.
``That way, you avoid the crackpots,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee D. Baker, an associate professor of anthropology and
African-American studies at Columbia University, cautioned against
certain sites that were ``on the edge in terms of legitimacy,''
like those put online by amateur history buffs. He also recommended
starting with academic sites as a way of finding reliable
information.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. CAPSULE REVIEWS OF WEB SITES FOLLOW)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The following Web sites were chosen largely from the many
suggestions submitted by Wilson, Floyd, Baker and Raymond A.
Winbush, a professor at FiskUniversity.
</P>
<P>
   THE ENCYCLOPAEDIA BRITANNICA GUIDE TO BLACK HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   blackhistory.eb.com/index2.html
</P>
<P>
   This collection from the Encyclopaedia Britannica includes audio
clips of Gwendolyn Brooks reading one of her poems and Malcolm X
talking about civil rights, and links to 15 other sites, including
the Amistad Research Center and the W.E.B. Du Bois Institute for
Afro-American Research at Harvard. ``The Encyclopaedia Britannica
got this one right,'' Winbush said. ``I particularly like the
timeline they include.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AFRICAN AMERICAN MOSAIC
</P>
<P>
   lcweb.loc.gov/exhibits/african/intro.html
</P>
<P>
   This is one of several resources on black history at the Library
of Congress. (Another is the African American Odyssey, at
lcweb2.loc.gov/ammem/aaohtml.)
</P>
<P>
   Highlights in Mosaic include photographs and historic documents
that help tell of events like the colonialization of Liberia by
free blacks in the early 1800s and the founding of places like
Nicodemus, Kan., one of the towns established by blacks after the
Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICANA.COM
</P>
<P>
   www.africana.com
</P>
<P>
   This Web site's producers include the editors of Microsoft's
Encarta Africana, the Harvard professors Henry Louis Gates Jr. and
Kwame Anthony Appiah. It is a full-fledged Web site _ with chat
rooms, news and the like _ and includes content from the
encyclopedia; it is not sponsored by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Africana.com may be perceived as a commercial site,'' Floyd
said, ``but it is backed by a team of scholars of African and
African-American history. It has a great directory of links, and
the breadth of their coverage is really great. You can browse by
subject and find anything from the history of the WPA to voodoo to
Charlie Parker to great sports figures.''
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN-AMERICAN WOMEN: ONLINE ARCHIVAL COLLECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   scriptorium.lib.duke.edu/collections/african-american-women.html
</P>
<P>
   Entering this site is like pulling back the cover on an old
family album: sepia-tone photographs appear on a screen that looks
like faded parchment. ``What I like about this site is that it is
technically wonderful,'' Baker said. ``You can access scanned
images of original letters from black women in the 19th century.
Moreover, you appreciate the nuances and complicated language that
was used _ even by black people _ in the 19th century.''
</P>
<P>
   MATHEMATICIANS OF THE AFRICAN DIASPORA
</P>
<P>
   www.math.buffalo.edu/mad/mad0.html)
</P>
<P>
   Created by Scott W. Williams, a mathematics professor at the
University of Buffalo, this site includes profiles of notable
contemporary black mathematicians, as well as a historical look at
mathematics in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   THE INTERNET AFRICAN AMERICAN HISTORY CHALLENGE
</P>
<P>
   www.brightmoments.com/blackhistory
</P>
<P>
   This site, one of my favorites, comprises 11 profiles of
prominent 19th-century black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   You can take three levels of multiple-choice quizzes. The site
doesn't simply tell you which answers you got wrong and give you
the correct answer; it tells you where on the site you can read to
discover the correct answer.
</P>
<P>
   GALE GROUP: BLACK HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   www.gale.com/schools/resrcs/blkhstry/bios.htm
</P>
<P>
   This selection of about 80 short biographies for children is on
the Web site of the Gale Group reference publishing company. The
subjects include contemporary celebrities, like Veronica Webb and
Lauryn Hill, as well as the usual historic subjects, like Frederick
Douglass; offbeat figures, like the science fiction writer Samuel
R. Delaney; and people in the news, like Louis Farrakhan.
</P>
<P>
   The site also has a link to a timeline of black history, a quiz
and links to 12 other black history and culture sites.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN SLAVE NARRATIVES
</P>
<P>
   xroads.virginia.edu/(tilde)hyper/wpa/wpahome.html)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In the mid-1930s, thousands of former slaves were interviewed
under the auspices of the Works Progress Administration. This Web
site includes text and audio clips from 13 of them.
</P>
<P>
   AFRO-AMERICAN HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   www.aawc.com/aah.html
</P>
<P>
   While this site may not be as lacquered as some of the others,
it highlights interesting links. Click on Black History Month and
you will be led to early black communities in Nova Scotia, for
example, and books by black Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you are interested in the 54th Massachusetts Volunteer
Infantry or a historical resource on the Gullah culture, this site
can guide you there,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   GATEWAY TO AFRICAN-AMERICAN HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   www.usia.gov/usa/blackhis
</P>
<P>
   Created by the State Department's International Information
Programs, this has links to bibliographies, archival and research
sites, presidential speeches and full-text versions of government
reports, and articles on topics like the Amistad revolt, the civil
rights movement and President Clinton's ``National Conversation on
Race.''
</P>
<P>
   A link is also provided to the Association for the Study of
Afro-American Life and History.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
