<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-EARNINGS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL TO END SOCIAL SECURITY EARNINGS TEST MOVING IN THE HOUSE
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a rare display of unity, a congressional panel
Wednesday unanimously agreed to eliminate the Social Security
earnings test that reduces benefits for workers aged 65 to 69.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be remembered as one of our best days,'' said Rep.
E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., moments before his Social Security
subcommittee approved the bill. ``We're doing the right thing and
doing it in a bipartisan way.''
</P>
<P>
   A House vote could come March 2, after which action would shift
to the Senate, where a similar bill has been sponsored by Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, workers between 65 and 69 are penalized $1 in
benefits for every $3 in earnings above $17,000. The bill would
eliminate that penalty for anyone over the full retirement age,
which will gradually increase to 67 by 2027. About 630,000 workers
would be affected this year.
</P>
<P>
   A provision in the law that penalizes workers who file for early
Social Security benefits between age 62 and 65 by $1 for every $2
earned above $10,080 would remain in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he expected quick passage in the House, but worried
that the bill could become a vehicle for other Social Security
reforms in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been stymied on any reforms to Social Security for
the past two years as it has struggled with various proposals to
completely overhaul the program, which supports 44 million elderly
Americans and survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Repeal of the earnings test is the first change to Social
Security that shows any sign of becoming law.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who called for repeal of the earnings test
two years ago in his State of the Union message, said Monday he
would sign the repeal if Congress sent him a ``clean bill'' without
other provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's panel held a hearing on the bill Tuesday and Wednesday's
action took about 10 minutes, including opening statements and a
staff explanation of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eliminating the earnings penalty is the right thing for
seniors who have spent a lifetime working for their Social Security
benefits,'' Shaw said. ``They should get the benefits they earned
and paid for, regardless of whether they keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would be effective retroactively to Jan. 1,
would cost the Social Security trust fund about $22.7 billion over
10 years, but its long-term impact would be minimal, according to
estimates by the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
