<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8891 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-EVERGLADES-$AD     02-16 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EVERGLADES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARKS FACE PRESSURE TO BAN OFF-ROAD VEHICLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Feb. 20) 
(jt) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big Cypress National Preserve in Florida, 729,000 acres of
wetlands and sodden stands of cypress in the Everglades, may not
seem to be a likely place for driving through roadless back
country. But it has one of the most active off-road-vehicle
programs in the nation, issuing about 2,000 permits a year to
drivers of sport utility vehicles, airboats, all-terrain cycles and
behemoths known locally as swamp buggies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Swamp buggies, which ride on immense tractor-style tires and can
weigh tons, are especially destructive to the soft soils and
sensitive vegetation in the swamp, ecologists say. As a result, the
National Park Service, which has already closed four areas of the
preserve to vehicles, is drafting a new control plan for the park.
</P>
<P>
   But local environmentalists say the Big Cypress plan does not go
far enough, and at the same time, a national coalition of
environmental groups is pressing the park service to ban off-road
vehicles altogether in the nation's parks to prevent noise,
physical damage, and harm to endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   The damage to Big Cypress is especially severe, making it a case
study for what the environmentalists want to prevent elsewhere. An
aerial study by the University of Georgia found that there are
about 30,000 miles of vehicle tracks in the preserve, which is
nearly as big as Rhode Island, many of them still visible years
after they were created. The study found that as much as 148,000
acres _ more than 10 times the area of Manhattan _ in the preserve,
which is home for endangered panthers, manatees and other species,
have been affected. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The park service's proposal for managing off-road vehicles in
the preserve has been criticized as not being tough enough. It
includes stricter limits on how vehicles are used, how big they can
be, the size of their tires, the noise they can produce and where
they may enter and leave the park. Fees would be raised, and
enforcement of rules would be tougher. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say that the park service should have issued
stricter limits on tire and vehicle size, and should have included
newly acquired land to the zones where off-road use would be
limited. They especially want to protect habitat of the endangered
Florida panther. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say that Big Cypress is not the only park
being damaged by off-road vehicles. In December, 68 organizations
filed a petition with the National Park Service calling for a ban
on off-road vehicles in all the parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off-road vehicles are killing wildlife, destroying peace and
quiet, polluting air and water, and endangering visitor safety,''
said Russell Long, the executive director of the Bluewater Network,
a project of the Earth Island Institute that is leading the
petition drive. ``Our public lands shouldn't become sacrifice zones
for motorized cowboys to get their kicks.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ed Waldheim, the president of the California Off-Road
Vehicle Association, said the idea of a total ban was overreaching
by ``environmental extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are conservationists,'' he said of his group, which he said
maintains trails and educates its members on responsible behavior.
``We want to preserve anything in as natural a way as possible, but
we want to enjoy it, too. And we want to share it with equestrians,
hikers and everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The environmental coalition said that off-road vehicles are used
in 56 of the 108 large national parks it surveyed. Twenty-three
parks permit their use in back-country roads, the survey found. But
rangers in 40 parks reported significant illegal use of the
vehicles, and 38 parks reported serious damage to park resources as
a result.
</P>
<P>
   Many parks are cracking down on the use of off-road vehicles, at
least in very sensitive areas. In November, the park service
proposed a permanent snowmobile ban in the core of Denali National
Park in Alaska. The ban would affect two million acres, but would
not affect most use of snowmobiles in four million acres that were
added to the park 20 years ago, including the popular riding areas
close to roads. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The park service said that snowmobiles hurt air and water
quality with their two-stroke engines, which give off lots of
exhaust that leaches into the water. They also damage soils and
vegetation, disturb animals and interfere with cross-country skiing
and dog-sledding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The environmental groups contend that the law controlling the
mission of the park service calls on it to leave its resources
``unimpaired for the enjoyment of future generations,'' and that
the damage to terrain and wildlife from off-road vehicles does not
meet that test. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Its petition seeks an immediate ban on the use of all-terrain
vehicles, dune buggies, sand buggies and four-wheel-drive vehicles
on all off-road areas in the national park system, including
beaches, primitive trails and back-country roads. The exceptions
would be subsistence use by indigenous people in Alaska,
traditional uses like transportation and hunting, law enforcement,
search and rescue and park administration, and access to private
land within the parks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
