<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER17-COX     02-16 2263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Political Ticker: Some Christian conservative weight to
McCain
 &HT;    EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conservative activist and recent presidential candidate Gary
Bauer endorsed John McCain Wednesday. Speaking at a rally in
Greenville, S.C., Bauer called McCain the GOP's ``best shot'' at
winning the White House in November. Bauer also said McCain wants a
political system that is ``not a money bags democracy, but a system
built on civility and decency and honor.'' In a twofer, McCain also
gained the endorsement Wednesday of California Secretary of State
Bill Jones, who defected from George W. Bush's camp. McCain is
hoping the Bauer endorsement will help with Christian conservatives
in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH'S BANKROLL GOING FAST
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's campaign is spending close to $3 million a
week, a rate that alarms his top fund-raisers and has forced Bush
finance officials to schedule a number of unplanned money-raising
events in the coming weeks. The campaign raised an unprecedented
$70 million, but a spending spree in the early primaries,
intensified with an ad blitz in South Carolina this week, has left
roughly $20 million in Bush's campaign treasury. Bush aides
confirmed Wednesday that he spent a record-setting $50 million so
far. Aides to John McCain said their man has spent about $26
million and had $10 million left in the bank on Jan. 31
</P>
<P>
   TIGHT RACE
</P>
<P>
   A Zogby/Reuters tracking poll of likely Republican voters in
South Carolina, conducted Monday and Tuesday and released
Wednesday, shows George W. Bush slightly ahead but the race still a
statistical dead heat. The poll, with a 4 percentage point margin
of error, gave Bush 43 percent, John McCain 40 percent and Alan
Keyes 4 percent, with 13 percent still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER DEBATE COME AND GONE
</P>
<P>
   Debating familiar differences in sharpened tones, George W. Bush
and John McCain each tried to prove the other guilty of negative
campaigning, without offering Republican primary voters any new
evidence on which to judge their rival bids for the White House.
Again, as in debates before, there were no breakthroughs and no
blunders, nothing apt to change the close, testy campaign for the
primary. Alan Keyes was there, too, denouncing the two
front-running leaders. The ninth installment in the Republican
debate series was Tuesday night in Columbia, S.C., broadcast
nationally by CNN as a ``Larry King Live'' special.
</P>
<P>
   NO ENDORSEMENT FOR PHOTO EDITOR
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes received endorsements today from the Congress of
Racial Equality and Jews for Morality. CNN reported that CORE
Chairman Roy Innis blasted the New York Times and the Daily News
for choosing South Carolina debate photos for today's editions
where Keyes is not visible. Keyes is the only African-American
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   THE POLITICS OF HEATING ASSISTANCE
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley's campaign released a document alleging New Yorkers
were ``left out in the cold'' when the Clinton administration
released federal emergency heating assistance through the Low
Income Home Energy Assistance Program. The document shows New
Hampshire residents got an infusion of assistance Jan. 26, a week
before the state's primary, while New York, which holds its primary
March 7, got its largest chunk of money Feb. 10. ``The timing is
interesting,'' Bradley said. ``I realize I'm running against
entrenched power,'' and part of entrenched power is helping a
favored candidate.
</P>
<P>
   POINTING THE CANNONS AT BOTH TARGETS
</P>
<P>
   John McCain's surge has unsettled some prominent Democrats, who
worry that his compelling biography would overshadow his
conservative record and find broad appeal among Democrats and
independents in a general election. As a sign of that concern, Al
Gore has moved from castigating only George W. Bush and begun
concentrating on McCain. According to the New York Times, some
Democrats close to the White House, who for months had been bracing
for a contest against Bush, have begun in recent days quietly
putting out negative information about McCain's record.
</P>
<P>
   MORE THAN JUST ABORTION
</P>
<P>
   John McCain tried to bolster his anti-abortion credentials in
the face of criticism from abortion foes that he isn't zealous
enough. At a question-and-answer session with several hundred
voters in South Carolina, McCain touted his ``17-year pro-life
voting record'' in Congress. But he also sought to change the
discussion by urging all Republicans, Democrats and independents to
go beyond single-issue voting to weigh his ``vision for the future
of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK ADS WITHOUT THE ATTACKS
</P>
<P>
   Now that John McCain has sworn off negative advertising, he's
making sure voters know it. ``John McCain has elevated the race for
the presidency back to where it should be,'' says a man in a radio
ad in South Carolina. The ad doesn't mention that less than a week
ago McCain was tossing as much mud as his opponent _ and George W.
Bush wants voters to remember that. Bush is continuing to air ads
that go after McCain, including one that says: ``Politics is tough,
but when John McCain compared me to Bill Clinton and said I was
untrustworthy, that's over the line.''
</P>
<P>
   `E-PRESIDENT' LESS THAN E-LECTRIFYING
</P>
<P>
   His supporters have said he would be ``the e-president,'' but in
the latest lap of the race for Silicon Valley's campaign
contributions, Al Gore ran dead last. A Cox Newspapers computer
analysis of Federal Election Commission records shows that in the
last quarter of 1999, Bill Bradley led all candidates in that
high-tech battleground of Silicon Valley's 25 cities, as follows:
Bradley, $108,225; George W. Bush, $48,208; and John McCain,
$42,906. Gore, who has bragged about his role in developing the
Internet, trailed with $35,415. For all of 1999, Bradley also came
in first, raising $617,475, compared to $574,476 for Bush, $302,095
for Gore and $84,696 for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   CROSSOVER PROTEST IN MICHIGAN
</P>
<P>
   Some black leaders in Detroit are urging the city's largely
Democratic residents to vote for John McCain in the Michigan
primary Tuesday to embarrass Gov. John Engler, a staunch supporter
of George W. Bush. The Rev. Wendell Anthony, president of the
Detroit chapter of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, and state Rep. LaMar Lemmons III said Engler had
not supported moves to help Detroit retain its tax base. Michigan
Democratic caucuses are in March.
</P>
<P>
   BUT WHAT IF MCCAIN'S SUPPORTERS ARE DIE-HARDS, TOO
</P>
<P>
   The George W. Bush campaign is a little worried about
fair-weather friends of John McCain; namely, the independents and
crossover Democrats who might come out in large numbers in the
Saturday primary to vote for McCain, especially if the weather's
nice. Bush's people are hoping the predicted rain Saturday will
come to pass, keeping many McCain supporters home while die-hard
Republicans flock to vote for Bush in conditions fair or foul.
``We've been conjuring up some rain dances,'' said Heath Thompson,
Bush's state director.
</P>
<P>
   TROOPER WAS A REAL TROUPER
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina state trooper who pulled over John McCain's
campaign bus last week just so he could meet him was worried he
would lose his job because of it. Trooper Michael O'Donnell stopped
the McCain bus on its way to Charleston, but the senator was on
another bus headed to Columbia. The unconventional roadside stop
caused some consternation in the state. Department of Public Safety
Department spokesman Sid Gaulden said someone from McCain's staff
called and urged that O'Donnell not be fired, but said that played
no role in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   SOMEBODY'S WATCHING
</P>
<P>
   What the Rev. Floyd Flake, an ex-Democratic congressman, said at
his Allen A.M.E. Church in Queens, N.Y., Sunday was: ``I don't do
endorsements from across the pulpit, because I never know who's out
there watching the types of laws that govern separation of church
and state. But I will say to you this morning, and you read it
well. This should be the next president of the United States.'' He
was referring to Al Gore, who was in the church. But Americans
United for Separation of Church and State went ahead and filed a
complaint with the IRS, charging Flake with knowingly violating tax
laws.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET PRIMARY COULD CRASH
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Democrats are struggling to save their plan to hold the
nation's first Internet presidential primary. The party faces
several hurdles, including a lawsuit alleging that voting by
computer would discriminate against minorities and the poor. It
also has yet to receive federal approval of its March 11 primary or
support from all three state universities, which have about 100,000
potential student voters with generally easy access to computers.
State Democrats also need approval from the Justice Department
because of past violations of the Voting Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   A DIFFERENT VOICE OF JOURNALISM
</P>
<P>
   There is at least one publication that is all but shouting its
hostility toward John McCain: World magazine, a little-known, North
Carolina-based newsweekly for evangelical Christians. In a scathing
article and sidebar, World, which claims a subscription-based
circulation of 109,000, attacks McCain and the media that it says
adore him. The cover article on McCain was written by Bob Jones IV,
scion of the family that founded the fundamentalist Christian Bob
Jones University. Its editor, Marvin Olasky, has served as an
informal adviser to George W. Bush's presidential campaign and,
according to the New York Times, was one of the inspirations for
Bush's credo of compassionate conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE, LIBERTY, AND THE PURSUIT OF COMPUTERS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, speaking at Morgan State University in Baltimore,
called for government and industry to work together to give all
households access to the Internet and to help teachers use
technology to improve instruction. He was vague about how he would
turn his ambitious technology agenda into reality, and his aides
said later that he would rely on relatively modest amounts of
federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   A TIP FROM TIPPER
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore journeyed into the heart of Bill Bradley territory _
New Jersey _ and collected almost $55,000 for her husband's
campaign. Speaking at a Princeton country club, she ``skimmed
over'' her husband's positions on health care and education, said
the Newark Star-Ledger, while touting his endorsement from the
National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League. Tipper
Gore suggested that the next president may be able to appoint three
to five Supreme Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   THE DOCTOR IS IN
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley told about 150 health care workers at Brooklyn
Hospital Center in New York that his health care proposals are
realistic and affordable. Bradley's aides tried to draw attention
to a new study by the UCLA Center for Health Policy Research, which
they said showed that Al Gore's health plan would neglect about
715,000 low-income adults in New York. Gore's plan would continue
Medicaid, which does not cover healthy childless adults; Bradley's
would provide subsidies for those people to get insurance.
</P>
<P>
   BIG LABOR PUSH IS ON
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO said it would spend more money than ever before to
help elect worker-friendly candidates to the White House and
Congress, and would devote more resources to mobilizing volunteers.
At the labor federation's winter meeting in New Orleans, president
John Sweeney said trade unions would focus on races in 71 swing
congressional districts and on electing Al Gore for president.
</P>
<P>
   NO STADIUM NAMING RIGHTS, EITHER
</P>
<P>
   Larry King apparently doesn't allow free advertising. Six huge
signs promoting the sponsor of the Republican presidential debate,
the South Carolina Business and Industry Political Education
Committee, had been set up as TV backdrops for the 1 1/2-hour
debate in Columbia on CNN's ``Larry King Live.'' But they were
removed and replaced with wordless signs showing images of the
American flag.
</P>
<P>
   ALL KINDS OF SURPRISES LURK IN FAMILY HISTORIES
</P>
<P>
   John McCain's ancestors owned as many as 52 slaves on their
plantation in Mississippi, campaign officials confirmed Tuesday.
``I did not know that,'' McCain said, after being shown
documentation by reporters for Salon, an online magazine. Salon
gathered documents from the Carroll County, Miss., area, including
slave schedules from 1860 that list ``W.A. McCain'' as the owner.
McCain declared the information ``fascinating,'' and a surprise
because he had always pursued his family history through the
military. He said he knew, for example, that William Alexander
McCain had fought in the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   BUT BRADLEY GOT THERE FIRST
</P>
<P>
   Splitting from President Clinton, Al Gore said he would not have
nominated Bradley Smith, a Republican who opposes the overhaul of
the campaign finance system, to the board of the Federal Election
Commission, and that he would urge the Senate to reject the
president's nomination. Clinton nominated Smith as a concession to
Republicans in order to advance his judicial nominees who have not
been confirmed. But Bill Bradley said last Saturday the
administration was making ``a major retreat on campaign finance
reform'' by naming Smith.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
