r a BC-ELDERLY-DATA-$ADV20-C     02-16 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-DATA-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With ELDERLY-DRIVERS. For release Sunday, Feb. 20.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TESTS FOR 'AT RISK' ELDERLY DRIVERS
</P>
<P>
   1. Walk along a 10-foot strip of masking tape while being timed.
(Measures mobility and balance.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Sit in a chair. Raise one arm all the way up. Lower it and
raise the other arm all the way up. (Measures mobility.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Sit in a chair with feet on the floor. Turn around and read a
cardboard clock held behind driver. (Measures upper body mobility.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Sit in a chair with loose-leaf notebook binder between feet.
Tap right foot on one side of binder and then on the other side 10
times while being timed. (Measures leg mobility.)
</P>
<P>
   5. A volunteer gives driver three easy words to repeat and
remember. Later in the test the driver will be asked to recall the
words. (Measures memory.)
</P>
<P>
   6. The driver is shown a wide strip of paper with various
geometric symbols such as a triangle and a square. The driver is
asked to identify the symbols without turning his or her head.
(Measures vision and scanning ability.)
</P>
<P>
   7. The driver is shown a sheet of paper. At the top is a
geometric figure. Beneath it are several incomplete figures. The
driver is asked to pick which of the incomplete figures would match
the top figure if the lines were filled in. This is repeated 10
times. (Measures visual perception and spatial relationships.)
</P>
<P>
   8. The driver is shown a computer screen with a group of
randomly placed dots with letters and numbers. The driver is asked
to tap them in order 1-A, 2-B, 3-C, etc. Then the driver is asked
to do the same thing on a computer screen where the dots are
displayed over a video of typical roadside scenery. (Measures
divided and selective attention.)
</P>
<P>
   9. The driver is asked to identify figures displayed with high
contrast and low contrast. (Measures vision, particularly night
vision.)
</P>
<P>
   10. The driver looks at a computer screen and is shown a
flashing picture of a car or truck in the middle and another
vehicle at some point on the periphery of the screen. The driver
must identify whether the vehicle in the middle was a car or truck
and where the other vehicle was on the periphery. (Measures useful
field of vision.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
