<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8906 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-ELDERLY-DRIVERS-$ADV2     02-16 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-DRIVERS-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TESTS OF ELDERLY DRIVERS' SKILLS MAY BE ON THE WAY
 &HT;    With ELDERLY-DATA. For release Sunday, Feb. 20.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SILVER SPRING, Md. _ Naomi Coale sits in a chair and taps her
foot. On the floor in front of her is a loose-leaf binder.
</P>
<P>
   She touches the floor on one side of the binder. Tap.
</P>
<P>
   She picks up her foot, crosses the binder, and touches the floor
again. Tap.
</P>
<P>
   Coale, an 81-year-old resident of Leisure World, a seniors
community north of Washington, D.C., is taking a test. It's a test
that might save her life, and yours.
</P>
<P>
   She's part of a $10,000 multi-year study to determine whether
there are tests that can determine which elderly drivers may be a
risk on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Age itself is not the issue,'' said Dr. Robert L. Raleigh, 74,
a physician who is chief of the Medical Advisory Board and director
of driver safety research for the Maryland Motor Vehicle
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the issue is, how does any individual change regarding
those capabilities that potentially impair their ability to drive
safely?'' Raleigh said. ``Impaired driving is a public health
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Since November 1998, more than 3,000 drivers age 50 and older
have taken the battery of 10 tests. The tests focus on visual,
perceptual and memory attributes that have a relation to driving.
</P>
<P>
   Because administering the full battery of tests would take too
long and be too costly for motor vehicle departments to do, Raleigh
is hoping his tests will identify one or two quick tests that might
help identify which drivers need more in-depth testing.
</P>
<P>
   Participation in the tests, which take about 15 minutes, is
voluntary. The results of each driver's test are confidential and
are not used to restrict any individual driver's license. However,
therapists and doctors who are experts in dealing with the elderly
review the results with the participants and may recommend
curtailing some driving or getting remedial help such as physical
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland is the only state conducting the study on behalf of the
Federal Highway Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the tests will be analyzed and then
cross-referenced against accident reports for the next several
years to determine whether any of the tests could be used as a
predictor for future accidents.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the foot-tapping test measures the time it takes to
move from a gas pedal to a brake pedal. Drivers who have difficulty
performing this function may have difficulty applying the brake.
</P>
<P>
   Another test involves a participant sitting forward in a chair
and then turning just his upper torso to look at a cardboard clock
held by a volunteer behind him. Drivers who cannot turn around far
enough to see vehicles behind them may be involved in more
accidents changing lanes than those who can turn around.
</P>
<P>
   Once it is determined which tests are helpful, Raleigh hopes
doctors will use them to advise their elderly patients about
possible remedies, such as exercises that improve mobility, or
possible driving restrictions, such as not driving at night or on
major roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Screening people for cancer and heart disease and getting them
to treatment may lengthen their time,'' Raleigh said. ``Screening
for fitness to drive is the same as screening for cancer and heart
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Raleigh expects doctors may notify motor vehicle
departments of patients who have problems. In December, the
American Medical Association passed a resolution requiring doctors
to report patients who refuse to restrict their driving or get help
for potential driving problems.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA decided that the public health responsibility to report
dangerous drivers outweighed the physician's oath of patient
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Whether motor vehicle departments decide to use the tests to
screen elderly drivers and restrict their licenses has not been
determined, Raleigh said. Using his tests might allow officials to
tailor restrictions to the needs of elderly drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal, literally, is how do we keep people on the road as
long as they're safe?'' Raleigh said. ``A lot of people think of
MVA as a place where you get your license taken away. We're asking,
'is there a remediation potential so that if they get treatment
they can come back and we still license them?' ``
</P>
<P>
   After completing her tests, Coale waits to talk to an
occupational therapist about the results. She's happy she
participated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very good,'' she said. ``I've limited my
extensive driving for a couple of years. Most of my driving is
around Leisure World and the shopping center.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
