<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8908 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-BOOK-POLK-INTERVIEW-H     02-16 1594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-POLK-INTERVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES K. POLK DESCENDANT TRACES NOTABLE FAMILY'S HISTORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (``Polk's Folly: An American Family History''; Doubleday, $29.95) 
 
By FRITZ LANHAM 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you add up the families that have accomplished notable things
in American public life over several generations, you don't get a
large number.
</P>
<P>
   The Adamses and Roosevelts and Rockefellers come to mind. Until
now, few would have put the Polks on the list. But the just
published ``Polk's Folly: An American Family History'' (Doubleday,
$29.95) makes a persuasive case that we should.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: The Polks can claim one president, James K., elected
in 1844. Leonidas LaFayette Polk, a leader in the late-19th-century
agrarian movement, might well have been the second if cancer had
not killed him in 1892.
</P>
<P>
   The family tree groans under the weight of soldiers and
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   There was Leonidas Polk, the Episcopal bishop who became a
skilled and respected Confederate general. His death in 1864, the
result of a well-placed Union cannon shot witnessed, ironically, by
a Polk from the Northern branch of the family, was an enormous loss
to the South's cause.
</P>
<P>
   Leonidas' nephew also was a Confederate general. Later,
officer-rank Polks fought with the American cavalry that chased
Pancho Villa unsuccessfully across northern Mexico and with Gen.
George Patton's Third Army during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Polks have been governors of Delaware and Missouri, the first
lady of Maryland and acting undersecretary of state for Woodrow
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   George Polk III, a pioneering broadcast reporter for CBS, was
murdered under mysterious circumstances in Greece in 1948. Today,
one of the most prestigious awards in journalism is given annually
in his name.
</P>
<P>
   And when Martin Luther King was arrested in Memphis, Tenn.,
shortly before his assassination, he hired Lucius Burch, a
respected local attorney and a Polk on the maternal side. Burch's
long support for desegregation in his hometown was especially
important because the Polks a hundred years before had been
slaveholders and plantation owners in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polk's Folly'' _ the title comes from the tract of Maryland
swamp purchased in 1687 by the first Polk to arrive on American
shores _ is the work of William R. Polk.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Fort Worth, Texas, Polk had a lengthy career as a
professor of Middle Eastern history at Harvard University, where he
earned his doctorate, and the University of Chicago before moving
to the south of France 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Courtly and polished, the 70-year-old author has more of the
Continent than of Cowtown in his manner. But his book began, he
explains, in Texas, with the family stories he heard as a child
from his aged grandmother. Born two years before the outbreak of
the Civil War, Mary Harding Polk was the granddaughter of a man
born before the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the remarkable thing was that with two memories I had the
whole history of the United States laid out for me,'' Polk
explains. ``And I think that's the reason I became a historian. I
had this very intimate view of American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Polk told these family stories to his children
and grandchildren. But his published books bore titles like ``The
Arab World Today'' and ``Neighbors and Strangers: The Fundamentals
of Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally I decided I would really do something I had never done
before and just bury myself in American history and learn enough to
write this book.''
</P>
<P>
   He delved into public records and the holdings at research
libraries and engaged in ``a tremendous amount of digging in
people's trunks in their attics.'' Before he started he knew
nothing of half the people he ended up writing about.
</P>
<P>
   What struck him most was the ``different America'' this project
opened up for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studying American history, you hear all about people doing
things in Philadelphia and Boston and New York. But the really
interesting things in the early part of the American Revolution
happened out on the frontier,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A year before the Declaration of Independence was drafted in
Philadelphia, nearly a hundred ``declarations of independence''
were drawn up by small groups out in the boondocks. In May 1775 in
North Carolina's Mecklenburg County, for example, the local
equivalent of the Colonial assembly drafted the ``Mecklenburg
Resolves'' and directed two of its members, Col. Thomas Polk and
Dr. Joseph Kenedy, ``to purchase 300 lb. of powder, 600 lb. of
lead, 1,000 flints, for the use of the militia of this county.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What interested me was not genealogy, not just the Polk
family, but the family encapsulated in American history, what they
showed us about the way people lived _ what they ate, how they
dressed, what they slept on, what they were afraid of,'' Polk says.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to tell the story of America through the lives of
one clan.
</P>
<P>
   ``One after another, in every generation, I was able to find
somebody who had been in some interesting activity,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Not every story involves war, politics and other affairs of
state (although most do involve male Polks _ the book devotes
relatively little space to the women of the family). Among the more
colorful offerings are those about the Polks in Texas in the rowdy
post-Civil War period.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there's the story about how Polk's grandfather,
James H. Polk, shot the sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Polk was in Laredo to buy cattle for the stockyard he and his
brother Rufus had established in Fort Worth. In a Laredo saloon, in
a foul mood because whoever was supposed to deliver the cattle
hadn't shown up, Polk made no effort to hide the fact that he was
carrying a large sum of money.
</P>
<P>
   When he went up to his room that night, he expected trouble and
took a spot in the corner instead of on the bed. Sure enough, a
short time later the door quietly opened, and a man holding a
pistol eased himself in. Polk fired. The sheriff dropped. ``Greedy
fellow'' was the only comment from Polk, who apparently suffered no
legal consequences for his deed.
</P>
<P>
   James H.'s contemporary, George Washington Polk, had a big role
in bringing the railroads to West Texas and was on hand to witness
some of the shenanigans of Judge Roy Bean, so-called ``Law West of
the Pecos.'' George Polk told the story of how the judge discovered
$44 and a pistol on the body of a dead man and declared the man
guilty of carrying a concealed weapon, ``fined'' him the $44 and
pocketed the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried first of all to find all these stories and to tell
them but then to be sure that I authenticated them and that I knew
that they'd actually, really happened,'' says William Polk.
</P>
<P>
   What does he think of the most famous Polk, the president?
</P>
<P>
   He laughs and says he was struck by Bill Bradley's comment that
Polk ``was the best president we ever had,'' a statement unlikely
to elicit general agreement among historians.
</P>
<P>
   President Polk had been a protege of Andrew Jackson, serving as
speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives and as governor of
Tennessee before winning the White House on the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   He was a workaholic at a time when the presidential staff
consisted of one aide and by convention the chief executive never
closed his office door. (``Gosh, that would have saved us such a
lot of trouble,'' the author quotes his Washington, D.C., friends
as saying, thinking of more recent history).
</P>
<P>
   Everyone from school choirs to frantic office seekers strolled
into the presidential office. Casual passers-by sometimes wandered
in during Cabinet meetings and took a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the major event of his four years was the
Mexican-American War, which resulted in U.S. acquisition of
California and the Southwest. That war was controversial then as
now, but Polk prosecuted it successfully, and when he left office
the country had nearly doubled in size.
</P>
<P>
   William R. gives James K. mixed marks, praising him, for
example, for his tolerance toward the persecuted Mormons. A
slaveholder himself, President Polk also tried to keep the issue of
slavery out of national politics and in this opposed the rising
tide of Southern nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   But the president isn't the author's favorite Polk.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite is his late brother, George Polk III, the CBS
reporter killed in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go into his story a great deal because I'm going to
write another book on him,'' he says. ``That's my next project.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Polk's Folly'' he discusses his brother's death briefly.
Stationed in Greece during the civil war between communist
insurgents and a corrupt, oppressive, right-wing government, Polk,
though no communist sympathizer, had alienated the government by
his reporting. He was murdered in Salonika on May 8, 1948,
becoming, in the words of journalist I.F. Stone, ``the first
casualty of the Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the official line was that the communists killed him,
those who have delved into the case over the years have pointed
fingers at the Greek government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm calling the book `The Good American,''' says William Polk,
who was very close to his brother and speaks of him movingly.
</P>
<P>
   William Polk declines to say who he thinks responsible for his
brother's death, but he has ``some pretty firm feelings about it.''
He hopes to get access to long withheld American government
documents that clear up the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty confident I'm going to get to the bottom of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
