<HEADER>
A8909 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-LETTERS-OFTHECENTURY-     02-16 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETTERS-OFTHECENTURY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WRITE STUFF NEVER LOSES ITS APPEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Letters of the Century: America 1900-1999'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Lisa Grunwald and Stephen J. Adler &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nonfiction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dial Press/Random House, $35 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, husband-and-wife journalists Lisa Grunwald
and Stephen J. Adler embarked on an inspired project: putting
together a book filled with other people's mail. What closet voyeur
would be able to resist?
</P>
<P>
   The resulting compilation, ``Letters of the Century,'' provides
an incredibly intimate glance into the soul of the 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Writing a personal letter, after all, tends to be a soul-baring
exercise. People put pen to paper to document their most profound
experiences or thoughts, to produce a hard copy of otherwise
intangible images and feelings. More casual and less self-conscious
than words written for publication, private letters resonate with
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the missives in ``Letters of the Century'' are personal.
There are letters written to newspaper editors (Attorney Clarence
Darrow to the ``Chicago Tribune'' and Unabomber Ted Kaczynski to
``The New York Times)'' and letters exchanged by heads of state
(Dwight Eisenhower to South Vietnamese President Ngo Dinh Diem).
There are letters passed between people who have never met, and a
couple of famous pseudoletters, such as Martin Luther King Jr.'s
exquisite ``Letter From Birmingham Jail,'' an essay never meant as
a private communication.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the senders and receivers have recognizable names: Elvis
Presley to Richard Nixon, Ayn Rand to Frank Lloyd Wright, Janis
Joplin to her parents, Monica to Bill. But at least as many of the
authors and their intended readers are regular folk: witnesses to
history and barometers of the times they lived in. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   In 1922, a desperate mother of two whose deliveries nearly
killed her writes to birth-control pioneer Margaret Sanger seeking
help: ``I am only 25 now and my two babies are one year and two
years old, and I would have had two more if a good kind doctor had
not helped me ... So I am slowly killing myself ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Cpl. H.W. Crayton sends a letter to the parents of Raymond and
Bedford Hoback after finding Raymond's Bible on Omaha Beach the day
after the 1944 D-Day invasion: ``... You have by now received a
letter from your son saying he is well. I sincerely hope so. I
imagine what has happened is that your son dropped the book without
any notice. Most everybody who landed on the beach D-Day lost
something ...'' In actuality, both Hoback boys had been killed in
action June 6.
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous viewer of the TV show ``Ellen'' in 1997 decides to
tell her mother she is gay after the show's lead character comes
out of the closet. ``I totally understand that this will probably
freak you out,'' she writes. ``I thought that writing you a letter
would be easier _ I've always been able to express myself better in
writing anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Letters by famous writers highlight this collection. Mark Twain
turns a complaint to Western Union into a hilariously deadpan rant.
Dorothy Parker's lengthy 1942 description of the Philadelphia
military enlistment office, written to friend Alexander Woolcott,
(she had accompanied her husband to enlist) paints war's reality in
painfully sharp detail.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many fascinating gems in ``Letters of the Century''
that you'll want to read aloud to just about anyone willing to
listen.
</P>
<P>
   Grunwald and Adler divide their chapters by decade, introducing
each with a laundry list of trivia (''1916: In Fort Worth, Texas, a
doctor advertises efficient cures for `blood poisoning, gonorrhea,
gleet piles, fistula, cancer, night emissions and lost
vitality'.''). They also provide a short introduction to each
letter, placing it in context; occasionally, the explanation is
more fascinating than the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Will the new century leave humanity with letters as fluent and
poetic as the last? As Grunwald and Adler note, the post office
reports that less than 2 percent of all mail sent today is
personal; the telephone has turned many of us into lazy
communicators.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some people have suggested that electronic
mail will revitalize the oft-bemoaned ``lost art of letter
writing.'' Disagree? I look forward to hearing from you _ in
writing, of course. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1728EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
