<HEADER>
A8912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCIENCE17-COX     02-16 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENTISTS TO COMPARE RESEARCH AT AAAS ANNUAL MEETING
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of America's largest and arguably most
influential scientific organization meet here Thursday to exchange
descriptions of their research and talk about public policy issues
important to science.
</P>
<P>
   From chocolate to land mines, from honeybees to gorillas, topics
that have attracted the interest of members of the American
Association for the Advancement of Science will be explored in more
than 1,000 research papers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the association's 152nd annual meeting, known
formally as the ``Annual Meeting and Scientific Innovation
Exposition,'' will include seminars and special lectures on topics
ranging from the relationship between science and religion to the
relationship between politics and the U.S. Census.
</P>
<P>
   A special session will give 80 teenaged scientists from
throughout the country a chance to describe their research. They
include a New Jersey youngster's demonstration of a deciphering
technique that he believes makes ``uncrackable'' computer codes
vulnerable and a Georgia student's search for a biological control
of the kudzu vine.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in the last four annual meetings of the
association, sessions will be devoted to scientific consideration
of chocolate. This year's deliberations will be devoted to the
question of whether it's good for you.
</P>
<P>
   Topical lectures will be devoted to topics such as whether
stress makes you sick and believing makes you well, the surgical
history of U.S. presidents, hostile exploitation of biotechnology
and many others.
</P>
<P>
   The AAAS, which likes to be called the ``Triple-A-S,'' was
founded in Philadelphia in 1848 and is among the oldest scientific
societies in America. With more than 143,000 members worldwide, it
is by far the largest.
</P>
<P>
   Details about this year's annual meeting and scientific
innovation exposition are available on the Internet at
http://www.aaas.org/meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
