<HEADER>
A8913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NASCAR-GORDON-NYTR &LR;      02-16 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-GORDON-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON FIGHTS HUMPTY DUMPTY LABEL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PAT ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ A lot of people are looking at Chevy's
Jeff Gordon a little bit like he's Humpty Dumpty.
</P>
<P>
   That's because once crew chief Ray Evernham was released to head
up Dodge's racing program last September, Gordon ``had a great
fall,'' and ``all the king's horses and all the king's men couldn't
put Gordon back together again.''
</P>
<P>
   So Jeff Gordon will have to do it by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Evernham, a brilliant chassis guy and
organizer who was always one step ahead of the curve, left, Gordon
won two straight races.
</P>
<P>
   But those were in cars left behind by Evernham, and in the final
five races of the year, for the most part, Gordon was a non-factor.
</P>
<P>
   He ran well at the Winston 500 in Talladega, Ala., and was
ging for the win right up to the end. Then, he got hung out
to dry and finished 12th, but again, that was in a car essentially
crafted by Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   Over the final five races, the best Gordon could do was a pair
of 10ths, and the leaders left him behind in the last four.
</P>
<P>
   That has a lot of his detractors smirking as he heads into 2000
and, in the minds of many, into the unknown. Not only is Evernham
gone, so is his pit crew, which deserted to Dale Jarrett. So is Ed
Guzzo, one of the top mechanics on Gordon's team, and so is Bill
Dees, Gordon's chief fabricator. They went with Evernham to Dodge.
</P>
<P>
   The Hendrick organization, with whom Gordon signed a lifetime
contract after Evernham left, has the resources to replace people.
The question is who replaces the leadership Evernham brought to the
table.
</P>
<P>
   By default, Gordon must step into the role. Now a part owner of
his team, Gordon becomes the key decision maker.
</P>
<P>
   He has made moves. Engineer Brian Whitesell, crew chief after
Evernham left, is now team manager and Robbie Loomis, who ran
Richard Petty's two-car operation last year, is the new crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Evernham loyalists are gone and the new
players are eager to prove, as is Gordon, that this was not a
one-man show.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways it's an advantage,'' Gordon said of the changes.
``You don't want people around second-guessing what's going on. You
don't want people saying `Ray didn't do it that way.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Evernham's imprint is still on this team. When
he left, Evernham said that if Gordon collapsed, then he hadn't
done his job very well, that this team should be able to carry on
without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian does a lot of things the way Ray did them,'' Gordon
said. ``And Robbie has his way of doing things. I think that's
good. You don't want to get stagnant. This sport is constantly
changing, and you always want new ideas, a fresh approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to this level, there's tremendous pressure to
stay there,'' Gordon said. ``Our expectations are high. We still
think we can be competitive. We all want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to win, we've done it,'' Gordon said. ``We know
what it's like to be on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some unknowns as far as working together, but I really
feel good about the things we did in the offseason, and I really
feel good about the cars we're building,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Something to consider: There has been a lot of complaining from
the Chevy teams at Daytona this week, who feel they are at a
disadvantage to the Fords.
</P>
<P>
   Only one Chevy team has been relatively quiet, Gordon's. They
think they can win the race.
</P>
<P>
   (Pat Zier writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. The Ledger is
a member of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1737EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
