<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8914 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-FACES-GAME-NYT &LR;      02-16 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FACES-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTRUCTING A REAL-LIFE POTATO HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By SHELLY FREIERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FACES: THE ULTIMATE COMPOSITE PICTURE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (InterQuest, $49.95; Windows 95 and higher, Mac OS 7.1 or
higher.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to never forget a face. It is another to
reproduce an image of that face, not only the deep-set eyes but the
Roman nose and square chin. But Faces: The Ultimate Composite
Picture offers users a chance to try.
</P>
<P>
   Its makers bill Faces as a game to build observational skills as
well as a crime-fighting tool. It relies on a smorgasbord of facial
components _ eyes, nose, lips, hair, beards, smile wrinkles and
even glasses _ to produce on a computer screen a composite
portrait, similar to those distributed by law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The manual for Faces says, ``Victims and witnesses can actively
participate in the fight against crime, completely revolutionizing
the way subjects are tracked down and identified.'' But the market
for Faces as a game may be limited.
</P>
<P>
   Young children, even would-be Rembrandts, might have difficulty
discerning the fine distinctions in component images, and most
teen-agers would probably be more excited about a role-playing or
an action game. And although fans of television shows like ``Cops''
could presumably create imaginary perpertrators just for fun, it
seems that the novelty of this software would quickly wear off.
Think about how long you might play with a real-life version of
Potato Head.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the interface is well designed and simple to learn. Users
choose a basic head shape. Facial components like noses, eyes and
hairstyles can be displayed on one side of the screen, and users
click on the images to construct a face. The facial features _
almost 4,000 of them _ are from photographs of real people.
</P>
<P>
   Except for their slightly different versions, the component
images have no context. At first glance, for example, 24 pairs of
eyebrows look more like birds flying in a strange formation than
like examples of facial hair with subtle distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   There are subcategories of features to refine a search, like
narrow or deep-set eyes, or noses that are either narrow or hooked
(shown from an angle where you can see the nostrils or not see
them). But there seem to be too few choices for elements like hair
and hats.
</P>
<P>
   Faces also has a section that lets users test their powers of
recall and observation by looking at a pre-drawn face and trying to
reproduce it. Even at a medium skill level, that can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   With practice, users can learn to study real people more
carefully, discern characteristics in an individual's eyes or mouth
and reproduce an image using the software. But it would take
considerable practice to become good enough to build faces
accurately and quickly: sorting dozens of eyes to select the exact
shape can be tedious.
</P>
<P>
   Once a user gets past throwing together random features,
building a portrait and clicking through different hairstyles to
make funny faces, or even bouncing the portrait's eyebrows up and
down like Groucho Marx's, Faces just isn't that much fun.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential of Faces as a crime-fighting tool, it may
not catch on with law enforcement agencies. The New York City
Police Department hires forensic artists to draw composite
portraits. Their skill is not only in drawing the facial features
of a suspect but in drawing out descriptive details from a witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The art of composite drawing is in the understanding and
retrieval of information from the witness,'' said Det. Stephen
Mancusi, who has been a forensic artist with the department for 16
years. It is not important, he said, whether you are recording the
information with a pencil or a computer program.
</P>
<P>
   The Faces software lets users share the files they make. The
manual emphasizes the potential for building a ``huge information
network'' of composite portraits and personal data. Each portrait a
user builds has a string of identifying numbers that can be sent by
phone or e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   There are also information sheets with places for a physical
description and a description of the ``incident in question,'' and
places to list aliases, occupation, address, port of entry, the
people the individual lives with, type of vehicle, clothing,
weapons and criminal partners.
</P>
<P>
   While law enforcement officials have a reason to collect data on
suspects, the specter of people compiling homemade databases raises
questions about privacy. Civil libertarians would shudder at the
idea of cadres of people passing around software-generated mug
shots of law-abiding people and information about them. You may
shudder, too. How much does your neighbor know about you, anyway?
And do you want him to tell his cousin Fred? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1741EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
