<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8915 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-QUAKE-GAME-NYT &LR;      02-16 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-QUAKE-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HEIGHTS, OR DEPTHS, OF BLOOD AND GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(EDS: The company id Software, mentioned in the next to last graf
and in the Game Notes at the end of the article, lower-cases
``id'') 
(lh) 
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Some of the most popular computer-based games today are
invitations to grab a joystick and enter exquisitely rendered,
full-color combat zones in which players assume the identities of
superhuman gladiators whose survival depends upon their being able
to turn opponents into canned ham _ without the can.
</P>
<P>
   The games _ generally described as first-person shooter games _
came under a great deal of scrutiny and criticism after news
reports that they were a favorite pastime of at least one of the
teen-agers who went on a murderous rampage last year at Columbine
High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, for the old days of computer games when everything was
black-and-white. No one ever charged the maker of Pong with
hastening the fall of civilization as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   Two new versions of popular games in this gory, heart-thumping
genre were recently released and are showing up on store shelves
side by side: Unreal Tournament and Quake III Arena. Both games are
sequels, but they bear little resemblance to their predecessors,
Unreal and Quake II.
</P>
<P>
   If the criticism that followed the rampage at Columbine affected
game manufacturers, you could not tell by Quake III and Unreal
Tournament. ``It blew over,'' John Carmack, a chief creator of the
Quake series (and its older brothers, Doom and Doom II), said in an
interview this week. ``It comes in cycles, when senators are waving
around their Doom boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Both games wear their amorality on their sleeves. The back story
for Unreal Tournament, which is explained in a stylish opening
video clip, is that in 2291 Earth's leaders begin sanctioning
bloody public exhibitions among brutal deep-space miners to vent
their violent tendencies. Some 50 years later these contests have
evolved into a multibillion-dollar professional league. Game
players are beckoned to compete in the league play ``to crush your
enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are a bit more mysterious in Quake III. Somehow a group
of characters who look like the members of Kiss on steroids show up
to fight monstrous demons in spooky yet spectacular settings.
</P>
<P>
   The play in both games is blazingly fast, thanks to very
powerful game engines. That translates into a lot of shooting and
getting shot at while running, ducking and hiding.
</P>
<P>
   The weaponry used to accomplish this mayhem is varied and coolly
efficient. The packaging for Quake III marvels over a futuristic
handgun ``perfect for close-range and splatter-proof surprise
attacks.'' In addition to single-shot handguns, both games offer
shoulder-held rocket launchers and high-energy plasma guns that
spew a kind of green lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Practically everything in these games goes boom thanks to finely
articulated sound designs that make everything from your own
footsteps as you run for your life to the grunts and groans of the
computer-generated slain and wounded sound bigger than life.
</P>
<P>
   And there are the taunts. Characters in Unreal Tournament speak
fluent macho, taunting faltering players as ``weak'' and dubbing
them with various unflattering locker-room names.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Quake III, Unreal Tournament's game characters are
rendered to look and act like people, not demons. When one of the
characters is killed, the game goes into overdrive to make the
killings as realistic as it can. Small-weapons fire usually drops
opponents where they stand, making them crumble to the ground with
a scream or final moan. Larger weapons, particularly if they are
fired at close range, cause bodies to explode into bloody mush,
sometimes sending heads and limbs ricocheting off walls to the
disquieting sounds of splats and bloody dribbles.
</P>
<P>
   Both games are rated Mature, for players 17 and older. While the
games' computer-generated violence among comic-book-style figures
can't approach the realistic blood and gore confronted by human
actors in popular films like ``Scream 3,'' it does push computer
animation to new heights _ or depths, depending on your perspective
_ in rendering the demise of game characters.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be a mistake to believe that the considerable
technology behind these games is all in the service of more blood
and gore. Both Quake III and Unreal Tournament are packed with
randomizing elements, so that no two scenes _ not even the death
scenes _ play exactly the same. The effect is to make the game's
action seem purely spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   In both games, player scores and status are kept in the borders
of the screen in heads-up displays. But Unreal Tournament adds
convincing detail by putting working LCD read-outs right on
weapons, telling the user how many rockets, for example, are left
in the trusty rocker launcher. Unreal Tournament, my pick for the
more engaging single-player action, also offers little touches like
supplying a marksman's glove whenever a player reaches for a
sniper's rifle.
</P>
<P>
   The games are not easy to play. For the novice, both Unreal
Tournament and Quake III have clever training levels for players.
These should be explored before players take on challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Both games possess exceptional artificial intelligence that can
convincingly animate opponents for single-player modes, but it is
Unreal Tournament's that really shines. In single-player mode,
Unreal Tournament can create the illusion that a player is playing
a team sport. Actually, the game directs the computer to animate
and control groups of virtual players, or bots; one group plays
with the human player and the other does its digital best to defeat
the player and his bots.
</P>
<P>
   Where Quake III truly succeeds is in its multiplayer modes,
where human players get to play other human players on the
Internet. The game's developer, id Software, in particular, seems
to have put most of its efforts into creating an exceptional online
gaming experience. Both games have streamlined the once difficult
and often confusing process of playing online. Quake III's approach
to online multiplayer gaming is quickly becoming an industry
standard among serious online gamers. It offers lots of
frighteningly fast action, richly detailed landscapes and interiors
with sophisticated visual effects like smog and cinematic lighting
without noticeable degradation in its translation to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; How to choose between the games? If characters in Quake III
Arena and Unreal Tournament met one night in a dark alley, I'd have
to put my money on the Unreal warriors. Both games have fighters
with big guns and polygon-rendered muscles, but the Unreal guys
talk more trash.
</P>
<P>
   GAME NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   Quake III Arena, developed by id Software and distributed by
Activision; CD-ROM for Windows 95, 98 and NT, Mac and Linux;
$49.95. Unreal Tournament, developed by Epic Games and distributed
by GT Interactive Software; Windows 95, 98, 2000 and NT, Mac and
Linux; $44.99. Both games are rated Mature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
