<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Feb. 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inclement weather will expand rapidly across the central Plains
and Mississippi Valley Thursday as a vigorous low-pressure system
moves east from the central Rockies. A broad flow of mild, moist
air from the Gulf of Mexico will glide over a cold air mass farther
north, resulting in a burgeoning area of snow from the east slopes
of the northern Rockies to the central Plains. The snow will become
heavier later Thursday across eastern Nebraska and Iowa. Farther
south where the cold air mass is eroded by the advancing mild air,
a mixture of sleet and freezing rain will glaze surfaces over
northern parts of Kansas and Missouri. The snow and sleet will
streak into the Great Lakes states and northern Ohio Valley
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and some strong thunderstorms will develop during the
midday and afternoon in the increasingly mild, moist air across the
southern parts of the Plains States and Mississippi Valley. Late
Thursday, a jet stream disturbance will streak east over these
regions, heightening the risk of scattered severe thunderstorms and
isolated tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Expansive high pressure will crest across the Northeastern
states bringing chilly conditions with ample sunshine. Clouds will
begin to increase over the interior late Thursday as the storm
system over the nation's mid-section moves east.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, snow will linger along many west-facing slopes from
northern California to central Colorado. Dry weather and ample
sunshine will develop over much of the Pacific Northwest and
northern Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tornado Season
</P>
<P>
   Tornado season first begins in late winter near the Gulf of
Mexico as strengthening sunlight increases evaporation rates,
providing increasing supplies of moisture for severe thunderstorms.
As spring arrives and Gulf moisture stakes a claim to a larger
area, tornado season begins in earnest from the central Plains and
the Ohio Valley to the southern Middle Atlantic states. By early
summer, tornado season arrives for the northern-tier states from
the Dakotas to the Great Lakes to New England as Gulf moisture
combines with strong solar heating and a weakened but still active
jet stream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8921 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-DIANNA-ROSE-900&AMP;ADD-N     02-16 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANNA-ROSE-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMERICAN SELLS BRITONS `THEIR' ROSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla.)  (js) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Elton John sang ``Goodbye England's Rose'' at Westminster
Abbey in 1997, who knew it would lead to ``Hello Garden Sales''?
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Masterson, who runs a little company called Collectible
Commemorative Gardens out of Tulsa, Okla., calls it ``one of life's
little miracles.'' Lt. Col. Kenneth Grapes, the director general of
the Royal National Rose Society in England, thinks it is ``the most
extraordinary coincidence you ever heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   And Cynthia Woodson in Tulsa, who introduced herself on the
telephone as ``assistant to the vice patron of the Royal National
Rose Society'' (the vice patron being her lifelong friend Bonnie
Belle), said: ``Guess what? I'm not selling real estate anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The players, with their collision of rolling Southern accents
and clipped British voices, are all counting on profits to roll in
from a new rose dedicated to Diana, princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first rose in her honor _ in fact, a Jackson &AMP;
Perkins rose and a dahlia from Spring Hill Nurseries are already
bearing her name, and earning contributions to the Diana, Princess
of Wales Memorial Fund _ but the bush named England's Rose is a
fine crossbreeding of American ambition and English taste. And
despite a scheme pandering to the world's unbelievably long
mourning period for Diana, this latest trinket is a glorious
flower. It had been under development for 10 years by the famed
English rosarian David Austin, who crossed a big yellow Graham
Thomas with a plush pink Heritage. All it wanted was a name.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Austin thinks it's the best he's ever bred,'' said
Grapes, an artillery man for 30 years before he turned to roses.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big, fat creamy white, with a blush of apricot and the
fragrance of myrrh.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw it, I wanted to eat it with a spoon,'' said
Masterson, who had a vision of such a rose in her bubble bath
shortly after Diana's death. ``I knew it was the one I was looking
for.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea came to her when she was in need of a new product to
market. She had not had a big hit since she designed the Winniest
Bear, a teddy bear to celebrate the famous football coach Bear
Bryant and his University of Alabama team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to combine something beautiful with business,'' said
Masterson, who calls herself a visionary. ``I started thinking of
that poor woman and her tragic life and those poor boys. I'd heard
the name England's Rose, so I called Cynthia, who's a gardener,
too, and said, `Have you ever seen an England's Rose in the
catalogs?' And she said, `No, I don't think so.' So I called the
trademark lawyers. Because I knew if there wasn't an England's Rose
there needed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   She trademarked the name but did not yet have a rose to attach
to it. And she did not see just one rose, but a dozen new roses,
bred by world-famous nurseries, all dedicated to the memory of
Diana and planted in a garden in her memory. She saw sales to fans
around the world, with part of the proceeds going to the garden,
and to the Diana, Princess of Wales Memorial Fund. But first
Masterson needed a royal connection. And finding the first rose
wouldn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I got on the Internet,'' she said. She found the Royal
National Rose Society, which was looking for money to expand its
garden.
</P>
<P>
   It took a couple of months before Grapes responded to
Masterson's e-mail messages, but she was not the type to get
discouraged. When she cooked up her Winniest Bear idea, she
recalled, ``I called for 45 days straight before I got Coach on the
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the bear is in the Paul W. Bryant Museum in Tuscaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   In England, Grapes began to admire the scope of Masterson's
plan, although, he admitted, ``I was slightly ashamed we hadn't
thought of it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   He started trawling the international waters for worthy roses,
from Austin in England to Sam McGreedy in New Zealand to Tantau in
Germany. The possibilities, the tie-ins, were all there: a memorial
garden at the society's languishing headquarters in St. Albans,
north of London, a ball on Diana's birthday, in July, to introduce
the new roses. The Queen Mother, the society's patron, seemed
receptive to the idea. So Grapes invited Masterson to England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to cross the ocean,'' Masterson said of her
first trip to Europe. ``But my sister kept saying, `You're dealing
with the Royal National Rose Society, you understand. You have to
go over there.''' When Masterson arrived at St. Albans, the members
of the rose society raised their glasses to her, and a venture was
born.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides remain in admiration of each other. Grapes, she
said, reminded her of a cross between David Niven and Colonel
Mustard in the board game Clue: ``very proper, with badges, very
witty.'' For his part, Grapes said he discovered a woman ``not at
all as one had envisaged, but really interesting, knowledgeable and
extremely professional.''
</P>
<P>
   In the joint venture, the Royal Society has already sold 2,000
of the 5,000 rose bushes available this year. Masterson has sold
another 400 in the United States. England's Rose sells for $35,
plus $10 for shipping, through www.englands-rose.com or by calling
(800) 863-1572. The Web site has a picture of Masterson (who looks
like Kathy Bates) and Grapes (who indeed looks like Colonel
Mustard). England's Rose looks as peachy and soft as Diana's
complexion, and there's music on the site, Ravel's ``Pavane for a
Dead Princess.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, Grapes says he is amazed that the rose can be made
available in the United States. When Masterson said she wanted to
sell the new roses here, he told her that the quarantine laws of
the U.S. Agriculture Department would stop her for some time.
</P>
<P>
   But she contacted the department ``and discovered that by
providing certain bits of paper, it's perfectly possible,'' he
said. And so England's Rose is available here (except in the states
of Washington and Oregon).
</P>
<P>
   Grapes has been negotiating with the Diana, Princess of Wales
Memorial Fund to put its imprimatur on England's Rose, in return
for which the society would make a substantial donation to the
fund, which supports the kinds of causes the princess made her
concern. The fund has to be careful about what it approves, because
it has been deluged by tacky proposals for everything from
``Princess Diana colonic irrigation kits to underwear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Masterson says she will not rest until her royal rose empire
includes spinoffs ``like chinas and other things.''
</P>
<P>
   And meanwhile, Masterson has been made a vice patron of the
society. ``There's another one that's Lord and Lady So-and-So,''
she said. ``But I'm the only American that has ever been a vice
patron.''
</P>
<P>
   And she and her husband, John, have begun enjoying some of the
perks befalling a vice patron of the Royal National Rose Society.
Last summer they were invited to take tea with the Queen. ``We
stood in the line that bowed,'' she said, ``and then we had tea and
crumpets in the back yard of Buckingham Palace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
