<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NC-BLACKS-BOOK-NYTR &LR;      02-16 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-BLACKS-BOOK-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH CAROLINA TOURISM BOOK PROMOTES BLACK HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By GREG RETSINAS   
 New York Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ In a bid to boost heritage tourism in North
Carolina and promote the state's African-American history, state
tourism officials released a 64-page book this week intended to
bolster both efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The book, entitled ``The Rich Heritage of African Americans in
North Carolina,'' is more of a tourism guide than a history, but it
has some of that as well. In an essay describing how African slaves
were left near Cape Fear in the 16th century by Sir Francis Drake,
state archives director Jeffrey Crow traces the growth of blacks in
the state, a progression marred by slavery and racial turmoil but
also accompanied by cultural traditions that endure today.
</P>
<P>
   A group of state officials worked for two years to compile the
book. Commerce Secretary Rick Carlisle said it was the first
state-sponsored document celebrating African-American heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The book includes a list of historic sites, famous black
leaders, festivals and events that celebrate black heritage and
prominent artists. It was produced at a cost of $115,000, most of
which came from corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read through every word of the galleys, what I
concluded was that the citizens of North Carolina have much to
offer visitors,'' said Dot Redford, a state historian.
</P>
<P>
   The book was unveiled Tuesday in Shaw University's Estey Hall, a
spot with historical significance. The university is the oldest
historically black institution in the South, having been chartered
in 1865 by Baptist missionary Henry Martin Tupper. It was renamed
10 years later for benefactor Elijah Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Estey Hall, built in 1873, was the nation's first dormitory to
house women on a coeducational campus and where the Student
Nonviolence Coordinating Committee organized in 1960 to advocate
for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The book mentions historic sites or people in connection with 47
different counties. For example, the book tells about David Walker,
a free black from Wilmington who fought for the abolition of
slavery in the 1820s. A festival every September now celebrates
Walker's life.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent people mentioned include James Shober, who was the
first black physician in North Carolina to have a medical degree;
James Benson Dudley, former president of what is now North Carolina
A&AMP;T University, and acclaimed Pender County artist Minnie Evans.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said they included every African-American site
that is already on the National Register of Historic Places as well
as people or places who have been recognized by state historical
markers.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of the book are being distributed to tourism
representatives and to state welcome centers. Officials said they
plan to make the book's text and photos available on the state's
tourism web site at www.visitnc.com or by calling 1-800-VISITNC.
</P>
<P>
   (Greg Retsinas is Raleigh Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1747EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CINEMA-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-16 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CINEMA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CONVERSATIONS IN WORLD CINEMA': WHY THEY BECAME FILM DIRECTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Terrifying'' is Jane Campion's description of working with
actors back when she was a fledgling director. ``I was like a
control freak. I thought, actors are going to have their own ideas!
Terrible. No way.'' It wasn't until her third and breakthrough
feature, ``The Piano,'' that she embraced the concept that actors
sometimes have ideas better than her own. Casual, witty and
exceptionally lucid about her creative development, Campion is the
first guest on a new monthly series, ``Conversations in World
Cinema,'' and she gets it off to a smashing start.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Sundance Channel and the Film Society of Lincoln
Center, ``Conversations in World Cinema'' only sounds as if it's
for film geeks. While most intelligent discussion shows about film
come with a heavy dose of pomposity, this one is modest and
surprisingly lively. (The premiere is Thursday night at 9.)
</P>
<P>
   The program begins with a brief overview of Campion's career,
narrated by the host, Richard Pena of the Film Society. Her first
film, ``Sweetie,'' now acknowledged as an influential gem, was
booed at the Cannes Film Festival. In an equally quick, but sleekly
produced and informative piece narrated by Campion, she talks about
her earliest influences when she was growing up in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Watching ``Swiss Family Robinson'' at 8, she saw a pile of logs
roll down a hill and thought they were going to come off the screen
and crush her; though she was almost hit over the head by the idea,
she still didn't think of becoming a filmmaker until she was in art
school after college. She saw ``Performance'' as an adolescent,
when it was the hippest of films, starring a young Mick Jagger. She
loved it and had no idea what it was about. That was the beginning
of what she calls a ``romance with mystery,'' not a bad description
of her own passionately evocative, enigmatic films.
</P>
<P>
   Though this series focuses on directors rather than actors, the
format has a passing resemblance to ``Inside the Actors Studio,''
with an interviewer and subject sitting onstage before a small
audience. The crucial difference is that ``Conversations in World
Cinema'' does not have that show's self-aggrandizing host, 
been deliciously skewered on ``Saturday Night Live.'' As an
interviewer, Pena knows how to ask a sharply defined question _
about the influence of Australian directors on Campion or her
method of working with cinematographers _ then get out of her way.
</P>
<P>
   Future guests include Atom Egoyan (interviewed by Wendy Keys of
the Film Society, also a regular host) and Kevin Smith. Next month
Pena talks to Mike Leigh. Asked why he was drawn to the story of
Gilbert and Sullivan, the subjects of his current film
``Topsy-Turvy,'' Leigh's answer reveals him to be a born iconoclast
and suggests that this series will continue to be refreshing. ``It
is so unfashionable, so politically incorrect to even admit that
you whistle it in the bath,'' he says of the music in their comic
operas. ``I thought it would be rather good to confront that. It is
fascinating, the way they did suffer hugely to produce this deeply,
deeply trivial stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   CONVERSATIONS IN WORLD CINEMA
</P>
<P>
   Jane Campion
</P>
<P>
   Sundance Channel, Thursday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Adam Pincus, Liz Manne and Graham Leggat, executive producers;
Scott Hopper, producer. Richard Pena, host.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
