<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8935 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-McCLAIN-COLUMN-HN     02-16 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-McCLAIN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Idolizing Landry was natural for a young fan
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
To a young boy growing up in Waco in the 1960s, Tom Landry was God.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know it's sacrilegious to refer to Landry or any man as
God, but to impressionable kids who loved to eat, drink and sleep
Dallas Cowboys football, he came closer than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Waco was and still is a Cowboys stronghold. For many of us, a
rite of passage was experiencing the thrill of a Cowboys victory
and the agony of their defeat. Tom Landry was the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Landry made an impact on our lives because he was a symbol of
our youth, a role model who transcended football and shaped many of
our beliefs. Landry stood for everything that was good.
</P>
<P>
   During games, Landry's calmness gave us confidence and made us
feel safe. Even if Vince Lombardi or George Allen was on the
opposing sideline, we knew Landry would outfox them and find a way
to lead the Cowboys to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Because Landry had been fighting a gallant and courageous battle
with leukemia, his death Saturday wasn't a surprise. Still, it's so
hard to believe that he will no longer be around.
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to the family of Buddy Holly, as far as I'm
concerned, Feb. 25, 1989, was the day the music died. When Landry
was fired that day, I surrendered my allegiance to the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   I became a Cowboys fan the moment they were awarded an NFL
expansion team. I've often thought how different the NFL would be
if Landry had accepted the first pro football job he was offered _
by Bud Adams, who owned the Houston Oilers of the fledgling
American Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine how different so many of our lives would have been
if Landry had not politely declined Adams' deal and later accepted
Clint Murchison's offer to become the first coach of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how bitter the defeat or how sweet the victory, Landry
was always the personification of class and dignity. He was easy to
spot because he wore a suit with his trademark hat. No matter what
kind of game the Cowboys played, old stone face never smiled or
frowned.
</P>
<P>
   I suffered through the early years of defeat, then celebrated
when they finally began to win and came tantalizingly close to
winning a championship. But they always fell short, and even though
my faith in the players waned, I always believed in Landry.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I saw Landry in person, I was too nervous to get
close to him. He came to Waco to speak at our church. On Sundays
during football season, I always sat in the back close to the exit
so I could leave a few minutes before noon and run to my
grandmother's house in time for the Cowboys' kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   But on this Sunday night in the offseason, I sat closer to the
front but not as close as I had hoped. With Landry in the pulpit,
it was kind of like sitting in the front row at school and being
called on to answer a question. I never sat in the front row at
school, and I guess that night I was afraid that Landry might
actually look at me.
</P>
<P>
   Because Landry was an icon, we were mesmerized by his words, and
transfixed by his stare. I listened intently to every word he said,
but they didn't hit home. Even though his sermon was captivating,
the entire time I watched him, I couldn't help but think about
certain plays and games and wonder what he had been thinking at
that time.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when I became a sportswriter at the Waco Tribune-Herald
and the Chronicle, I covered some Cowboys games. Even if I was
supposed to be in the opposing dressing room, I still went to
Landry's postgame session just to hear him speak.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, the Ice Bowl and Jim O'Brien still cause nightmares.
No matter how hard I try, I still hate Bart Starr, who is one of
the most likeable and well-respected players in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I go to Lambeau Field to cover a Packers game _ and
I've traveled to Green Bay many times through the years _ I can't
help but remember the Ice Bowl. When Starr sneaked for the winning
touchdown to ruin the Cowboys' season for the second consecutive
year, I thought the Packers were almost superhuman, robots created
in a lab by Lombardi, who, like Landry, was also larger than life.
</P>
<P>
   I've talked to many Packers who played in the Ice Bowl. To this
day, they are extremely humble because they know how fortunate they
were to win a game that is one of the greatest and most memorable
in sports history.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, I respect the late George Allen, and I believe he
should be in the Pro Football Hall of Fame, even though I hated
everything about him for so many years. Even though I like his son,
Raiders executive Bruce Allen, I still have this deep-rooted
resentment for Allen because he was able to do what others couldn't
_ torment Landry and the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Because Landry had been ill for so long, it's comforting to know
that he will not suffer any more. For a while, though, those of us
who admired him and appreciated what he accomplished on and off the
field will suffer without him.
</P>
<P>
   John McClain covers the NFL for the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
