<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      02-16 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHORT STORY REVIVAL MAY BE DEVELOPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The short story, a genre that has been more or less
remaindered by book publishing in recent years, seems to be having
a revival of sorts, and within the last couple of weeks it has been
very visibly celebrated. The New Yorker, the premiere showcase for
short fiction, observed its 75th anniversary on Monday with its
book awards entertainment at the public library, and two of its top
winners were short-story collections.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more interesting, if only for the very freshness of the
idea, was the third-anniversary gathering last week for the
magazine Zoetrope: All-Story, a quarterly founded by Francis Ford
Coppola to promote the short story. There is something curious and
fun about a moviemaker, rather than a publisher, being so
passionate about a literary form that he tries in some small way to
bring fresh juice to it and make it popular and profitable for the
writer the way it was in the '30s. And moviemaker-friendly also.
</P>
<P>
   The major brawn in short-story publishing is arguably that
applied by Bill Buford, the fiction editor of The New Yorker, who
buys up to 100 short stories a year and publishes about 60. Buford
said: ``Great short stories are few, but great novels are few. In a
good year, we publish eight or 10 great stories. They go straight
to the nerve of our readership and create an excitement that they
don't get from other forms. There's the patter, the word of
mouth.'' So not surprisingly the magazine's book award winner for
best fiction in 1999 was Annie Proulx's collection ``Close Range:
Wyoming Stories'' (Scribner) and for the best debut was
``Interpreter of Maladies'' (Mariner Books/Houghton Mifflin),
stories by Jhumpa Lahiri about Indian immigrants trying to adjust
to life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Besides The New Yorker, Harper's, The Atlantic and Esquire are
among major magazines that publish short stories, and, of course,
the bookish countryside is stippled with small literary reviews and
university publications largely devoted to short fiction.
</P>
<P>
   But none of these are quite like Coppola's Zoetrope: All-Story.
The magazine is not glossy but is printed on paper little better
than newsprint. Its color reproduction and illustration style, even
when the artist is being most modern or almost abstract, gives it a
1930s pulp magazine muscularity. (One sometimes expects to see
Flash Gordon burst from a page; indeed, its latest issue has Tarzan
on the cover, one of its eight stories a tale of Tarzan's and
Jane's first kiss.)
</P>
<P>
   How and why was this created? Coppola explained: ``The magazine
grew from the thought that in the old days many, many short-story
magazines were published. My great heroes were Hemingway and
Fitzgerald, who did short stories, and I wondered if possibly the
strong screenplays of the '40s were weaned on this type of short
fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   There is something strangely luxurious about the way the
magazine acquires short stories. Writers, of course, submit them,
sometimes at the rate of 50 to 100 a day, according to the editor
in chief, Adrienne Brodeur. (Payment ranges from $1,400 to $5,000
for a story.) But Coppola also commissions them, which is truly
singular for fiction. He gets an idea, sums it up in a paragraph
and sends it to Brodeur, who finds several possible writers. That's
the way it worked with the magazine's greatest success thus far.
Coppola read a review of ``The Rules: Time-Tested Secrets for
Capturing the Heart of Mr. Right'' (Warner Books, 1995) by Ellen
Fein and Sherrie Schneider and wrote his paragraph, and it landed
in the hands of a young writer named Melissa Bank.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote ``The Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing,'' in which
``the rules'' failed a young woman, for the magazine's
first-anniversary issue. But they certainly did not fail the
magazine or Bank. A collection of her short stories, published
under ``The Girls' Guide'' title, then was sold to Viking Penguin
for a $275,000 advance, a mighty sum for such a collection, and was
optioned to Disney. The book was on the New York Times best-seller
list for 14 weeks, now has 250,000 copies in print, and succeeded
in making Zoetrope: All-Story an important fiction magazine beyond
its 40,000 circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola is sensitive to suggestions that the magazine was
founded to supply stories for his moviemaking, a development office
in disguise. He does believe, he said, that the two most important
talents needed for film are writing and acting, and he added,
``Melissa illustrated that maybe a few dollars invested in the
cultivation of fiction writers _ without making a film _ is
worthwhile.'' His purchase of a story includes the first movie
option, but Coppola said: ``I wanted to be pure about it. I told
Adrienne to buy stories without thinking of movies. At best only
one or two of them might be suitable for films.'' So far, only a
few stories, including Bank's, have been optioned, all by Disney,
with whom Coppola did have a working arrangement but no longer
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds, maybe thousands, of writers out there only
occasionally producing something that could become a film or a
play, but this is a long-term thing,'' he said. ``I'd like to put
film back in the literary tradition and introduce writers to actors
and actors to writers like the old-fashion mixers where you
introduced boys to girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur said: ``There's no pressure on me to find movie stories.
Francis, in truth, if he just wanted a development office, it would
have been much less expensive to hire a development person to read
all the magazines and find stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoetrope: All-Story has a $200,000 annual budget, with most of
the cash coming from Coppola's winery, and has yet to operate in
the black. One successful movie from one story will pay for the
operation for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the idea that a major filmmaker, or anyone else for that
matter, is enthralled by short stories shouldn't be too surprising.
People have been fascinated by them as far back as the time of the
Bible, which, when one thinks of it, is a collection of collections
of short stories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8938 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     02-16 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Landry's image belied person
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
He was the man with the Dick Tracy hat and lantern jaw, and a
starched, straight-as-a-steel-rod image. A Dallas cartoonist once
drew a strip with six panels captioned, ``The Many Moods of Tom
Landry.'' In each panel, he wore the same unsmiling, pencil-lipped
expression.
</P>
<P>
   For 29 years, he was the only head coach the Dallas Cowboys had
ever known, and he was the first to be fired. When Landry lost his
battle with leukemia Saturday at twilight, surrounded by his
family, it was not his exit from the team he helped create that you
wanted to remember.
</P>
<P>
   His illness was diagnosed nine months ago, and no one tried to
pretend he had long to live. Yet he went through it pretty much as
he had gone through most things, with dignity and without false
hope or complaint. Landry was 75, and he spent roughly 50 of those
years engaged in football.
</P>
<P>
   He was the Man from Mission, an aptly named town in the Valley.
He went on to become a star fullback at the University of Texas,
and a solid defensive back with the New York Giants, where he began
his coaching career on the same staff as Vince Lombardi.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't actually give us America's Team; that kind of glitz
and puffery was beneath him. But he gave Cowboys fans the success
and the consistency that made it stick. Even those who rooted
against the Cowboys could not dislike honest Tom Landry. His teams
won 13 division titles and 270 games, including two Super Bowls
(out of five).
</P>
<P>
   His career was not without contradictions. Duane Thomas, then a
young back with a puzzling attitude, described him as a ``plastic
man.'' Don Meredith, the devil-may-care quarterback, once said that
if Landry were in a personality contest with Bud Grant, the
Minnesota coach, there would be no winner.
</P>
<P>
   And Jerry Jones, on his first day as the owner of the franchise,
ushered Landry out the door, suggesting the parade had passed him
by.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had gone three years without a winning record. In
his last season, 1988, they finished with three wins and 13 losses.
But Landry was far from disheartened. He felt confident he could
turn the team around, as he had done in the beginning, when they
didn't reach the .500 mark until 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Few remember _ why would anyone want to? _ that Dallas was the
only expansion team in NFL history to go into its first season
without the benefit of a college draft.
</P>
<P>
   In what might have been a whimsical mood, he once confided he
thought he had done his best coaching job with his first Cowboys
team. His most vivid memory of that virginal 1960 season was of the
only game the Cowboys didn't lose. They didn't win it either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember the score,'' he said, ``or whether they came
from behind or we did. I'm not sure if Eddie LeBaron or Don
Meredith was our quarterback. But the game was at Yankee Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   The pint-sized LeBaron played the whole game and completed four
TD passes, the last to Billy Howton to tie the score at 31 in the
darkening seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the way home,'' Landry said, ``we considered it a
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had lost their first 10 games and the tie kept them
from having a perfect record. A week later, they ended the season
by losing to the Detroit Lions.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they had given the rest of the league a 40-year head
start, the Cowboys lost only four games by more than 12 points. Out
of it came a trend that spread throughout the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have much to give us hope,'' Landry said. ``But it
forced us to comb the free-agent ranks and to take a good, hard
look at the all-black schools, something not all the teams had
done. We found the Jethro Pughs and the Rayfield Wrights and, in
time, that made us a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry's preference for the dedicated, clean-cut types, the
Roger Staubachs and Bob Lillys and Lee Roy Jordans, was well-known.
But he tolerated the rebels, up to a point, and won with them:
Meredith, Tony Dorsett, Pete Gent, Hollywood Henderson, to offer an
interesting cross section.
</P>
<P>
   Always, the enduring picture of Landry was that of an aloof,
mechanical kind of man, dry as a Santa Clara prune. For sure, he
was not a back-slapper, nor one who needed an audience. He rarely
chose to reveal himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Landry had a dry sense of humor. Once, asked by a
sportswriter what kind of field position he preferred, he replied,
``Frankly, I'm partial to my opponent's one-inch line.''
</P>
<P>
   When he relented during one Super Bowl trip and allowed the
wives to share a hotel room with their husbands, he explained that,
``Everyone enjoys a change now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall and taciturn, his face during a game revealed about as much
emotion as a lamp post. Somewhere along the line he became typed as
a conservative coach, but the record doesn't support that label. It
was Landry who revived the shotgun formation for Staubach in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   And it was Landry, as an assistant with the Giants in the late
1950s, who invented an alignment called the 4-3 defense. In the
opinion of some pro observers, that accomplishment put him right up
there with Eli Whitney and the cotton gin.
</P>
<P>
   Lombardi was the backfield coach under Jim Lee Howell and
Landry, still playing in the secondary, was a coach on the field.
Kyle Rote, who starred as a halfback and receiver, recalls walking
down the hall during training camp, peeking in the office doors,
and seeing Landry in one room running a film projector, and
Lombardi in another room, doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the hall, Howell, the head man, was reading a
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   No one knew then that there was a wonderful competition going
on, perhaps not even Lombardi and Landry. Both would become Hall of
Famers, and legendary figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' said Frank Gifford, the key back in Lombardi's
run-to-daylight philosophy, ``I learned more playing under Tom and
I don't mean that as a putdown of Vince. Landry taught. Lombardi
inspired.''
</P>
<P>
   In a game against the Redskins, Gifford, playing both ways,
intercepted a pass and was about to be tackled inside the
Washington 10-yard line. As he went down, he spotted Tom out of the
corner of his eye and lateraled to him. A startled Landry loped
over for the touchdown. On the sideline, he chewed out Gifford for
improvising.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one I admired more than Tom Landry,'' said
Gifford, who moved on to television and Monday Night Football. ``I
wrote him a letter a couple of years ago and tried to say that. I'm
not much for writing fan letters, but I did it this once. We create
images and we can't erase them. People would mistake his intensity,
his discipline, for coldness. But he was really very special. His
relationship with his wife, Alicia, and his kids, the closeness,
was marvelous to see. He was a great coach and an exemplary
person.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their corporate image under Landry, the history of the
Cowboys was anything but bland. They were for years a party team in
a fairly decent party town. Old-timers recalled fondly the days
when Meredith walked into the huddle singing a medley of his
favorite country songs. Then the Cowboys started winning, and
Meredith realized he was the only one still singing.
</P>
<P>
   Landry created the flex defense and the Cowboys introduced the
computer to pro football. He had his critics, early and late, but
he tolerated them.
</P>
<P>
   What Thomas Wade Landry couldn't tolerate was losing. He was
clearly bitter when Jones fired him, but at the same time he felt
sympathy for the task that faced the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot harder to start from scratch now,'' he said, ``than
it was in 1960.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was no longer his, and he made an interesting
discovery: ``I never realized how much pressure I was under, until
it wasn't there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   His place in pro football lore is permanent, and so is the image
of the man in the hat.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
