<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-ETIQUETTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOPHOLE MAKES LOWERED-FLAG TRIBUTE MORE COMMON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was a little kid in the early 1960s, I was so overly
versed in flag etiquette that I feared lightning bolts would strike
if the U.S. flag touched the ground or was otherwise mistreated.
Lowering a flag to half-staff was cause for alarm. The president
had ordered it. A national leader had fallen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, society is more tolerant of alterations to traditional flag
protocol. Once looked upon as a symbol of our government, the flag
now is being used more as a symbol of its people. As such, it is
lowered more frequently. It's put at half-staff not just for
high-ranking government officials but also for ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The sports world, for example, offers two recent illustrations:
The Dallas Cowboys lowered the flag at Texas Stadium in Irving
after legendary former coach Tom Landry died Saturday. Last week,
flags over Arrowhead Stadium in Missouri were lowered to half-staff
when Kansas City Chiefs star Derrick Thomas died unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, this could seem inappropriate. Federal law says
that in addition to certain holidays such as Memorial Day, the flag
should be lowered by order of the president upon the death of a
``principal figure'' in U.S. government, a foreign dignitary or a
governor. Some interpret that to mean that only the president
should issue the order to lower the flag.
</P>
<P>
   But the code also offers this loophole: ``In the event of the
death of other officials or foreign dignitaries, the flag is to be
displayed at half-staff according to recognized customs or
practices not inconsistent with law.''
</P>
<P>
   That clause, ``recognized customs or practices,'' means that
schools, cities, anyone can lower flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``That clause allows local communities to decide how they want
to grieve for significant deaths that affect the community,'' said
Marc Flake, spokesman for Tarrant County administration. Federal
law offers specific guidelines for how the president should respond
but leaves the door open for others to decide when to lower the
flag, Flake says.
</P>
<P>
   Texas law is more clear than national law in flag-lowering
decorum. By law, the governor can order it for any ``individual.''
</P>
<P>
   In North Texas, the U.S. flag flew at half-staff over Fort
Worth, Arlington and Tarrant County buildings after the shootings
at Wedgwood Baptist Church last September, not by order of the
president, but by order of city and county officials. The city of
Arlington lowered its flag after the Texas A&AMP;M bonfire tragedy, and
it has lowered its flags when Arlington police have been killed in
the line of duty. Fort Worth's city administration and Tarrant
County administrators ordered U.S. flags lowered on city and county
buildings after Fort Worth Police Chief Thomas Windham died Jan.
12.
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't bother me,'' says Douglas Kingston, a Veterans of
Foreign Wars officer in Fort Worth. ``It's honoring the
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1803EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
