<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-METAL-INTERIORS-NYT &LR;      02-16 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METAL-INTERIORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD WORK,   BEING A MAN   OF STEEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Americans consumed 130 million tons of steel last
year. Some were extremely fussy about it.
</P>
<P>
   The minimalist vogue has elected crude metal the interior
material of the moment. From the Tse boutique at 827 Madison Avenue
to Gianni Versace at No. 815 to the Giorgio Armani offices and
showroom at 114 Fifth Avenue, enough steel, aluminum and bronze
have gone in recently to make New York City the newest Rust Belt.
</P>
<P>
   Architects adore it, including Richard Gluckman, who designed
the two-story aluminum walls inside the Versace store; Peter
Marino, who created an aluminum conference table for Chanel's new
offices; and Philippe Starck, who is specifying stainless steel
medicine cabinets for Ian Schrager's new West Side residence.
</P>
<P>
   But as important as what you do with the stuff in this town is
who you get to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Hand, a metalworker and ex-sculptor with a studio on
Leonard Street in TriBeCa, is the cold-rolled-steel set's current
``It'' Boy.
</P>
<P>
   Superman, the Man of Steel, might have the trademark. Hand has
the clients. He has worked with every architect worth his or her
metal oxide, from Steven Holl to Tod Williams and Billy Tsien. His
last big job was 3,000 square feet of Cognac-colored steel for
Clarissa and Edgar Bronfman's East Side town house, designed by
Peter Rose. (His next big job: a rust-orange steel-arc staircase in
the style of Richard Serra for an apartment on the Upper East Side
of .)
</P>
<P>
   Though independent, Hand gets much of his work through the Clark
Construction Corp., one of the city's ``It'' general contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Design at the moment includes a lot of decorative metal
elements, on the contemporary end,'' said Chris Clark, the
president. ``I'm doing 15 major residences all over town right now,
and Tom will be involved in half of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Using a kid-glove touch on an unlikely material like steel has
made it newly popular as a warm, not cold, element in modern
design.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the hand finishing,'' Hand said recently at his
studio, a dirty ex-garage on a block closed to traffic because it
is clogged with loft-development crews. Hand has the hesitation of
an artist in answering questions; his speech is as soft as his work
is hard.
</P>
<P>
   Large metal pieces are sheared, bent or rolled to size by
subcontractors. Hand and his team weld, cure and polish them. ``All
those ceiling panels in the Bronfman residence _ they're cut by
laser, plotted in C.A.D. drawings, but the finishing was all done
by hand,'' Hand said.
</P>
<P>
   Steel is ``pickled,'' he explained, with an acid application to
remove the ``blue scale'' it arrives with, then chemically sprayed
and scrubbed by hand, as if it were being waxed, to achieve the
required color and patina. Rose, the architect, asked for a
black-brown for the Bronfmans' steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wash it down, then scrub it again, several times,'' Hand
said. ``In the process, you get a reflective quality and a
hand-rubbed quality. There's a subtle modulation in the surface
that makes it gentler than steel.''
</P>
<P>
   Hand worked as an apprentice, then taught at the Johnson Atelier
Technical Institute of Sculpture _ a school and foundry in
Mercerville, N.J., whose clients include George Segal, Joel Shapiro
and the Museum of Modern Art _ before establishing his New York
studio 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taught to be a craftsman,'' he said. ``It wasn't
something I learned by accident. We lived and slept metal. We lived
in little farmhouses _ we barely made money. I apprenticed to be a
metalworker, and that's common in Europe, but not common in
America. It's an Old World tradition I have no reservations
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any craftsman, Hand does not discuss his chemical formulas.
George Ranalli, an architect who worked with Hand on the Fashion
Center Building at 38th Street, said: ``All artisans, when they're
really good, have secret techniques. He has quite a few: formulas
or finishes for blackening steel, so it won't rust; sealing metals
with wax; the way he oxidizes copper. He just knows metal very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hand's other talent is working with architects. ``I never try to
impose any design sense on them,'' he said. ``Some metalworkers I
know, they try to be designers. That's not their place. I can draw
the distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   Success has created its stresses, especially on Hand's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best situation is when craftsmen are candid, and say,
`This is my schedule,' and we go along with it or not,'' said David
Piscuskas, at 1100 Architect, who worked with Hand on the Tse
boutique. ``Tom knew his steel, but frankly he was slow. The
clients want the architecture. And they want the architects to get
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Hand was quick to share the distress. ``You take on these big
jobs, and you can't handle it,'' he said, standing before a pushpin
board that held a working drawing for a metal desk destined for the
new SoHo offices of Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, the advertising agency. The
original metalworker had been removed from the project by the
architect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rough doing the custom work,'' he said. ``It's very
labor-intensive. You could bid a job at 150 hours and easily spend
300. Staying small, you can't always pump things out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Temerian, a metalworker and colleague who has worked in the
last year on the Nicole Farhi store and New York residences for
Calvin Klein and Robert Redford, agreed that, despite its sparks of
celebrity, the craft can involve a life as unforgiving as steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-end metalwork is a hard way to make a living,'' he said.
``The materials are expensive. You make a mistake, and you can just
throw it out. Everyone I know who does it wants to be a
carpenter.''
</P>
<P>
   Hand, who lives with his wife in Westchester County in an old
house that he calls his hobby, talked recently with Temerian about
giving up the big city and its big assignments, but the country is
a project he does not have time for right now.
</P>
<P>
   His cellular telephone rang. Then it rang again. Then it rang
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone seems to like steel this year,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
