<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8963 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-BIBLE-PURITY-CODE-NYT     02-16 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIBLE-PURITY-CODE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBLICAL PROHIBITIONS AND THE CALIFORNIA FAMILY CODE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A proponent of the California measure to limit the definition of
marriage claims that ``Proposition 22 is exactly 14 words long:
`Only marriage between a man and a woman is valid or recognized in
California.' That's it! No legal doubletalk, no hidden agenda. Just
common sense.''
 &HT;    And not entirely true.
 &HT;    Proposition 22 is much larger than 14 words. It embodies a
national moral argument _ frankly, a theological argument _ about
homosexuality. The not-so-hidden agenda is religion.
 &HT;    The theological case against homosexuality is, in the minds of
many, quite clear. In the beginning, God created ``Adam and Eve;
not Adam and Steve.'' God intended marriage for one man and one
woman.
 &HT;    The Hebrew scriptures teach, ``You shall not lie with a male as
with a woman; it is an abomination.''
 &HT;    And likewise the Christian New Testament: ``For this reason, God
gave them up to degrading passions. Their women exchanged natural
intercourse for unnatural, and in the same way also the men.''
 &HT;    Accordingly, homosexual persons were either condemned to death
(Lev 20:13) or consigned to Hell (Rom 1: 28-32). Since male-female
marriage is at the heart of God's plan for creation, homosexuality
is the ultimate violation of Judeo-Christian values.
 &HT;    Not surprisingly, many Proposition 22 supporters are members of
or have ties to religious right organizations. Many more are
conscientious church people who want to do the right thing for the
sake of their children and society. And they are seeking to follow
what they believe to be a ``common sense'' biblical mandate.
 &HT;    The problem is, however, this interpretation of the Bible lacks
common sense.
 &HT;    The Hebrew Bible prohibition against homosexuality occurs in a
portion of scripture referred to as ``the purity code.'' The book
of Leviticus sets out literally hundreds of laws and regulations
governing the life of ancient Israel.
 &HT;    Included are such commands as ``You shall rise before the aged,
and defer to the old,'' ``You shall not hate in your heart anyone
of your kin,'' ``A leper shall wear torn clothes and let the hair
of his head be disheveled,'' and ``You shall not touch the skin of
a dead pig.''
 &HT;    Few contemporary people, even strictly observant Jews, keep the
entirety of the purity code. Leviticus, and the supposed
prohibition against homosexuality, only makes sense in the context
of its history. It was intended to set up boundaries of religious
practice between the Israelites, God's people, and the pagan tribes
surrounding them.
 &HT;    Most Jewish believers interpret these commands spiritually and
not literally _ the full measure of God's Law being the Ten
Commandments. And they say nothing about homosexuality.
 &HT;    Even those who take the purity code literally only follow it
selectively. Leviticus 25 commands a practice known as the Jubilee.
``You shall hallow the fiftieth year and you shall proclaim liberty
throughout the land.'' During the jubilee year, prisoners and
slaves are to be freed; stolen property returned and debts
forgiven.
 &HT;    If biblical literalists are so insistent that society condemns
homosexuality as ``unbiblical,'' why are they not equally insistent
that the nation's jails be emptied or Third World debt be forgiven?
 &HT;    The use of these Hebrew Bible texts against homosexuality is a
relatively recent development _ almost no ancient Christian
authority invoked them.
 &HT;    Historical theologian John Boswell asserts, ``The assumption
that the creation of humankind through heterosexual union in
Genesis and subsequent emphasis on marriage throughout the Old
Testament demonstrates tacit rejection of gay sexuality is
insupportable in a modern context, and it does not seem to have
occurred to early Christians.''
 &HT;    The New Testament writings against homosexuality are equally
unclear and irrelevant. Actually, the word ``homosexual'' never
occurs in the Bible. Hebrew and Greek terms used to describe some
forms of homosexual activity simply do not condemn any modern
notion of ``same-sex marriage'' or monogamous homosexual
partnerships.
 &HT;    Although a controversial point, it appears the New Testament
condemns male prostitution and sexual violence (both homosexual and
heterosexual) but not gay and lesbian sexuality per se.
 &HT;    What is perfectly clear, however, is that the Bible does not
condemn gay and lesbian persons. All people are created in God's
image and deserve love, respect and freedom. All human beings are
equally flawed, shortsighted, and selfish. No one group has a
monopoly on sin.
 &HT;    As C.S. Lewis once pointedly remarked, ``Those who do not think
about their own sins make up for it by thinking incessantly about
the sins of others.''
 &HT;    So, where does this leave us? I'd like to counter the
Proposition 22 with 16 other words: ``Congress shall make no law
respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free
exercise thereof.''
 &HT;    Let's be people of uncommon good sense and keep theology out of
the California Family Code.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
