<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OLD-MASTER-DEBATE-ART     02-16 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-MASTER-DEBATE-ART-2TAKES-TRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD MASTER SOLD AT AUCTION RAISES DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CAROL VOGEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was such a classic tale of rags to riches that
Oprah Winfrey featured it. So did the ``Today'' show. A
500-year-old painting that had been lying face down in the attic of
a Massachusetts rectory, a work that a parishioner had described as
``huge, gold and gaudy,'' turned out to be worth $1 million.
Experts at Sotheby's auction house estimated that the painting,
believed to be by the Italian Renaissance artist Andrea del Sarto,
would sell for $1 million to $1.5 million. At an important sale of
old master paintings on Jan. 28, it went for $1.1 million, a record
price for the artist.
</P>
<P>
   But at that point the tale begins to unravel. Before the sale
Sotheby's failed to disclose that in early December the leading
expert on del Sarto, John Shearman, had written to experts in
Sotheby's old masters department to say that he believed the
painting was not wholly by the artist.
</P>
<P>
   In the scholarly world of old master paintings, debates about
authenticity are common and constitute a kind of blood sport.
Experts and art historians often agree to disagree. But opinions
pro and con are generally disclosed, either in a sale's catalog or,
if the discovery has come after the catalog has gone to the
printer, in a salesroom notice. That did not happen this time.
</P>
<P>
   The night before the auction, word leaked out to some of the
world's top dealers in old masters that Shearman, an art history
professor at Harvard University's School of Fine Arts and the
author of a definitive two-volume study of del Sarto, had written
to Sotheby's expressing doubts about the painting, ``Madonna and
Child,'' an oil on panel. Part of it was painted by del Sarto, but
a larger part was probably done by an assistant, Shearman
contended.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Shearman confirmed that he had seen the
painting and infrared photographs of it before the auction. The
same week he viewed the painting in early December, he told
Sotheby's about his findings, he said, but the house ignored his
concerns and made no note of them when its experts wrote the
catalog entry.
</P>
<P>
   An expert at Sotheby's said that Shearman's concerns were
omitted from the catalog because of a problem in communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called John Shearman to see if we could include the letter
in the catalog, but he didn't respond to our phone call,'' said
George Wachter, director of Sotheby's old masters painting
department worldwide. ``We never hid the letter. We showed it to
whoever asked to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shearman, however, said Wednesday: ``I'm very surprised. I
generally return phone calls, and I don't remember getting a
message from Wachter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's maintains that the work was painted entirely by del
Sarto.
</P>
<P>
   Such controversies over authenticity are fairly common in the
old masters world and this one did not seem to faze the buyers.
Although few people bid at the auction, the painting was sold to
three London dealers, among them Patrick Matthiesen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it baffling I wasn't shown the letter,'' said
Matthiesen, adding that he had nonetheless learned of its existence
just before the sale. ``I am waiting for Sotheby's to send it to
me. Shall we say they are being coy about it?''
</P>
<P>
   The painting depicts the Virgin Mary behind a stone ledge,
holding a book in her right hand and the Christ child in the left,
against a dark background. Shearman said that del Sarto (1486-1530)
painted the Christ child and an underdrawing visible in some areas.
The Virgin, however, was probably painted by one of the artist's
assistants, he said, explaining, ``It's rather hard and
simple-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   The process is murky. The canvas could have been started by the
master and then left lying around his studio, where an assistant
may have picked it up and worked on it. The background was not
finished by del Sarto or an assistant; experts believe it was
painted much later.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 24, four days before the auction, the ``Today'' show on
NBC featured the ``Madonna and Child'' and interviewed the Rev.
William Murray of All Saints Episcopal Church in West Newbury,
Mass. The church received the painting under a bequest from Clara
Winthrop, a parishioner who died in the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the show was Christopher T. Apostle, a senior vice
president in Sotheby's old master paintings department. When Ann
Curry, one of the show's anchors, asked Apostle if there was a
chance that the painting was not by the artist, he replied
emphatically: ``There's no question. The universal agreement seems
to be that the painting was made by him.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of ``Madonna and Child'' presented Sotheby's with
an irresistible marketing opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's catalog says that an All Saints Episcopal Church
history refers to the painting as ``a copy made about 1800 of the
original by Andrea del Sarto.'' It hung in the choir stall of the
church until about 20 years ago, when some parishioners who
disliked it had it moved to the rectory attic. From there it
somehow made its way to a closet where Father Murray hangs his
coat.
</P>
<P>
   When the church needed to raise money to repair its building, it
called in Sotheby's and Christie's to appraise the painting.
Anthony Crichton-Stuart, head of Christie's old master paintings
department, visited the church last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was aware of the existence of another version, which is in
the National Gallery of Canada in Ottawa and which the museum
believes is by del Sarto,'' Crichton-Stuart said. ``That makes
authenticating this painting more difficult because one would then
be dealing with the question of which version is correct. I thought
this was a most interesting painting, probably from del Sarto's
studio but with condition problems.'' He told the church it was
worth only about $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's experts were more upbeat. ``While all the old
documents said it was a copy, when I saw the painting I realized it
was high quality and from the 16th century,'' Apostle said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Sotheby's old master experts had brought in
scholars who examined the painting with infrared reflectography,
which reveals the drawing beneath a painting's surface. ``We showed
it to curators from the Metropolitan Museum, the National Gallery
in London and an Italian scholar,'' Wachter said. ``They all
thought the painting was by del Sarto.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Sarto was known for his skill as a draftsman. He would often
first make a detailed full-size drawing, blacken the back of it
with carbon and pin the drawing to a panel as if it were tracing
paper. He would then use a stylus to trace the design onto the
panel before painting it. Some of this drawing is visible through
the painting.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers in the old master field who were interested in buying
the painting said that when they asked Sotheby's experts if the
work had been X-rayed to see what was underneath the background,
they were told that there had been none and that an X-ray was not
necessary. (Infrared studies pick up primarily underdrawings made
of carbon; X-rays detect heavy pigments containing lead, used by
16th-century artists, and are considered the best tool for viewing
changes made by an artist.)
</P>
<P>
   Matthiesen, one of the three buyers, who studied under Shearman
at the Courtauld Institute in London, disagrees with the
professor's findings. ``I looked at the painting and came to my own
conclusions,'' he said. ``I feel we have to get the painting into
conservation before we know anything definitively.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was on the ``Today'' show, Apostle talked of the
painting's condition. ``It has great quality despite what you see _
the little specks on the surface,'' he said. ``It's in very good
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   But Matthiesen and several other dealers in old masters called
the condition appalling. White gesso, a plasterlike material used
as an undercoat by artists of the period, is visible, and there are
general signs of wear and of an earlier restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The painting couldn't have been shown in a worse possible
way,'' Matthiesen said. ``It has been cleaned on the figure, and
they were worried what might happen to the background so they left
it alone. They weren't prepared to take that risk.'' The
restoration was ``half-baked,'' he said. ``They couldn't have tried
to make it look worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Matthiesen said, he considered the purchase a good
gamble. ``One is compelled to take risks,'' he said. The three
dealers are having ``Madonna and Child'' restored in Europe, a
process that could take more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he thought Sotheby's acted as it did, Matthiesen
concluded: ``That's salesmanship. It's rather like going to a
secondhand car dealer who says the gloss on the body is perfect but
there's no engine inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
