<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-FREETOWN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sierra Leone horrors air tonight on CNN
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The boy, 12, was suspected of being a rebel, so armed soldiers
dragged him out onto the street to a pickup truck. He was stripped
naked, thrown into the back of the truck, and the soldiers stomped
on him with their heavy boots while he screamed piteously.
</P>
<P>
   Sorious Samura taped the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used the only weapon I had,'' Samura says. ``My camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Samura, a native of the West African country of Sierra Leone and
a cameraman for a United Nations agency, spent much of last year
videotaping the agony of his country, documenting scene after scene
of gut-wrenching atrocities committed by both sides in a brutal
civil war. His video, which is almost unwatchable at times,
receives its first full airing in the United States tonight on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The government's election slogan during the 1999 campaign had
been ``The future is in your hands,'' which inspired the rebel
forces to cut off the hands of anyone they suspected of being
pro-government. We see adults and children with bloody, unbandaged
stumps; soldiers pumping machine gun fire into a bound man lying on
the ground; public whippings; decaying corpses crawling with flies.
</P>
<P>
   What was it all about? Diamonds, says Samura, the only real
wealth in Sierra Leone. ``Ninety percent of the people in this
country had never seen a diamond, and there they were, having their
arms and legs chopped off.''
</P>
<P>
   Samura's original documentary is 27 minutes long. The hour
special starts out with CNN international anchor Jim Clancy
providing the context, the who's who and why. It's a difficult
story to follow in all its intricacies and could have been
explained better.
</P>
<P>
   Then Samura's documentary runs, without commercial interruption;
you just can't cut away to a funny dot.com commercial after seeing
a baby with one foot. Afterward, Clancy interviews Samura and other
key players in the Sierra Leone conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The BBC would not show Samura's documentary, shot at great peril
to his own life, because it was too graphic. It is as rough as
anything that's ever been shown on U.S. television, but because it
is inarguably important news, without even a whiff of the
sanctimonious hand-wringing that sometimes accompanies tragic news
stories, CNN made the correct, and gutsy, call to air it.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a gutsy call because the folks at CNN know this
special will barely register on Nielsen's radar. International news
stories that don't involve American lives tend not to attract
viewers; stories about Africa are among the worst.
</P>
<P>
   That is the sad truth. The people of Sierra Leone know a lot
about sad truth. The people who have the guts to watch tonight will
know a little more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cry Freetown.''
</P>
<P>
   10 tonight on CNN
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
