<HEADER>
A8969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NIETSCHE-BOOK-REVIEW-     02-16 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIETSCHE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHAT NIETZSCHE REALLY SAID': A TOP 30 LIST OF MYTHS ABOUT
NIETZSCHE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now many readers have at least an inkling of how much
misunderstanding has surrounded the ideas of the German philosopher
Friedrich Nietzsche (1844-1900), who has been blamed for everything
from killing God to advocating nihilism to inspiring Nazism with
his promotion of the Ubermensch and ``the will to power.''
</P>
<P>
   Such misunderstanding has greatly receded, for after all, as
Robert C. Solomon and Kathleen M. Higgins point out in ``What
Nietzsche Really Said'': ``Nietzsche has had enormous influence on
the 20th century, and he seems to be starting out as the premier
philosopher of the 21st.'' He ``is now the most often cited
philosopher in the Western tradition. His name gets dropped in
novels and movies, from Herman Hesse's `Steppenwolf' and Milan
Kundera's `The Unbearable Lightness of Being,' to `Blazing Saddles'
and `A Fish Called Wanda.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, further clarification of Nietzsche's ideas can never
hurt, and the authors do a useful, even amusing job of it in this
latest entry in Schocken's What They Really Said Series, which so
far has covered Freud, Jung and Darwin. Solomon and Higgins, both
professors of philosophy at the University of Texas at Austin,
employ a number of gimmicks, like lists of Nietzsche's virtues and
digests of his books, to summarize his ideas, yet they also manage
to convey the spirit of his elusive philosophy sensitively.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble, the authors suggest, is that Nietzsche's writing
contains no systematic account of what he thought. His books were
often disjointed, self-contradictory, obscurely aphoristic and
intentionally difficult. His life appears to have been unhappy,
full of pain and suffering and ending in madness in his final
decade. Then there was his sister, Elisabeth, a proto-Nazi married
to a notorious anti-Semite. Their fascist legacy became attached to
Nietzsche's name in the mind of posterity.
</P>
<P>
   To clear this overgrowth, Solomon and Higgins begin with a
section of 30 rumors about Nietzsche that they say should be
forgotten. These range from ``Nietzsche hated Jews'' (not only
didn't he, but he also eventually turned against Wagner because of
the composer's anti-Semitism) to ``Nietzsche had no sex life'' (the
authors give credit to a theory that he may have been gay) to
``Nietzsche sees the Ubermensch as an evolutionary goal'' (on the
contrary, he saw it more as the ideal aim of spiritual development
than as a biological objective).
</P>
<P>
   Following a chapter on Nietzsche's books in which the authors
stress, among other points, how Nietzsche's extreme irony can often
be misleading, they offer ``Nietzsche ad Hominem (Nietzsche's Top
10),'' in which they list both the philosopher's favorite and
unfavorite writers, some of whom, like Socrates, Wagner, Kant and
Schopenhauer, appear on both lists, as Nietzsche's best and worst.
</P>
<P>
   Such playfulness is not only witty and entertaining, it also
allows the authors to approach the same points from several
directions, shading in the varying nuances that Nietzsche brought
to his crucial ideas in different contexts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet interspersed with these faintly gimmicky sections are
chapters that try to reach deeper into Nietzsche's thinking and
stress the positive aspects of his most famous attacks. Two of
these take up his wars against Christianity and morality,
emphasizing that he tore them down only in the hope of replacing
them with something better.
</P>
<P>
   What was that to be? In answering this question, the authors
engage Nietzsche's most elusive ideas, his exhortation that
individuals strive to become more themselves (Be all that they can
be, in the words of the U.S. Army's advertising slogan), by
learning to love their fates (``Amor fati'') and embracing what he
called ``eternal recurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   This last, most difficult-to-define idea the authors see not as
``a theory about the basic structure of time, but a psychological
test'' in which you ask yourself how you feel about repeating your
life. They continue: ``Relishing one's life, with all of its pains
as well as its pleasures, is the affirmation of life. Resentment,
regret and remorse, by contrast, suggest an unwillingness to live
one's life again, exactly as it has been.''
</P>
<P>
   They conclude, ``Life is suffering, Nietzsche asserts (with
Schopenhauer), but the proper response to this is not resentment or
disengagement (as Schopenhauer proposed), but instead wholehearted
`Dionysian' acceptance.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Nietzsche's love of fate, the authors write, ``It is a
judicious outlook for a writer wracked with infirmity, wholly
ignored by the public, to dream of a generation of future readers,
`philosophers of the future,' who would appreciate him.''
</P>
<P>
   This book is simply further evidence that Nietzsche's dream has
come true. Solomon and Higgins not only appreciate him; they also
help us share their understanding.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WHAT NIETZSCHE REALLY SAID'
</P>
<P>
   By Robert C. Solomon and Kathleen M. Higgins
</P>
<P>
   263 pages. Schocken Books. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
