<HEADER>
A8977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TOBACCO-FARMERS17-COX     02-16 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-FARMERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. FARMERS JOIN $69 MILLION LAWSUIT AGAINST TOBACCO INDUSTRY
 &HT;    450&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By GINGER LIVINGSTON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A $69 million class-action lawsuit was filed
against the nation's top four cigarette makers Wednesday, claiming
they conspired to reduce producers' income by manipulating the
federal system that sets tobacco prices.
</P>
<P>
   The suit by 4,010 farmers and tobacco quota holders, including
1,700 from North Carolina, was filed against Philip Morris Inc.,
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp.,
Lorrillard Tobacco Co. and several of their subsidaries. British
American Tobacco Co. Ltd. was also named.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also names as co-conspirators the 14 attorney generals,
including North Carolina's Mike Easley, involved in the 1998
settlement of the states' health care lawsuits against the
cigarette industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``These farmers and growers have followed every rule and have
been the most loyal to the tobacco companies and are now being cut
out almost overnight,'' said the farmers' attorney, Alexander J.
Pires Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleges that the tobacco companies violated federal
antitrust laws by manipulating the federal quota system that allows
farmers to grow tobacco. It contends that the tobacco companies set
the quota amounts, even though the program is operated by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also alleges that the tobacco companies encouraged
farmers to oppose federal legislation that would have awarded the
farmers $28 billion in compensation to end the quota system, and
then reached a settlement with the states that provided the growers
with only $5.15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Lorillard officials said, ``It is always
unfortunate when customers are sued by their suppliers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies are not responsible for recent market changes
that have frustrated farmers, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we share many of the same frustrations, we do not
believe a frivolous lawsuit, organized and encouraged by a
Washington D.C. trial lawyer, can possibly play any constructive
role in addressing the many issues facing the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Pires settled a $1.2 billion civil rights class action against
the U.S. Department of Agriculture involving 19,000
African-American farmers. He predicted Wednesday that another
25,000 of the nation's 525,000 tobacco farmers would join the
lawsuit by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, currently presiding
over the federal antitrust lawsuit against Microsoft Corp., has
been assigned the case.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Farmers at the news conference said tobacco industry
representatives led them to believe tobacco purchases would remain
constant and perhaps increase if the legislation was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be part of this lawsuit. I was one of the
last to join,'' said farmer Sammy Tant of Rocky Mount, N.C. ``But
they already hung us out to dry and all but cut us out of the
formula for making cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   Harnett County, N.C., farmer Keith Parrish said joining the suit
was a difficult decision for most tobacco farmers.
</P>
<P>
   He said tobacco companies want to eliminate quotas so they can
directly contract with tobacco farmers instead of buying through
auction. That would be a system ``where you are a serf, an employee
of the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish acknowledged that tobacco company representatives never
explicitly said they would keep purchasing tobacco at mid-1990s
levels when persuading farmers to lobby against the compensation
program.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said the farmers were told, ``if you like what we did
last year (1996), you'll like what we do next.'' Since quota
amounts went up in 1996, Parrish said farmers assumed that would
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers had no reason to distrust tobacco industry
representatives, Tant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to the mail box and the mail's there every day you
expect it's going to be there every day,'' Tant said. ``They worked
with us for so long, were there for us and called us family for so
long that we started to believe we were family.''
</P>
<P>
   However, quotas for flue-cured tobacco, the type grown in North
Carolina, were reduced more than 18 percent this year, and farmers
predict it could be reduced another 20 to 30 percent in coming
years.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers attending Wednesday's press conference said their share
of the settlement would compensate them for less than 10 percent of
their losses.
</P>
<P>
   Tant farmed 173 acres of tobacco in 1997 and will farm 108 acres
this year. He said he has invested $200,000 to $300,000 in new
equipment and tobacco allotment purchases. The value of that
investment has dropped between 50 percent to 75 percent, he said.
The harvester he spent $70,000 on would only bring him $20,000
today. A single tobacco barn cost $15,000 in 1997, he said, and
``I'd have to hold a gun to someone to sell it for $4,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Livingston's e-mail address is gingerl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
