<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BERLIN-FILMFEST-2TAKE     02-16 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-FILMFEST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD :  EUROPEANS CELEBRATE THEIR FREEDOM TO DWELL IN
HOLLYWOOD'S SHADOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ For its 50th anniversary edition, the Berlin Film
Festival has moved its headquarters from the former West Berlin to
Potsdamer Platz, a new urban complex that symbolizes the
unification and rebirth of this long-divided city. Yet while the
festival now has a home fit for the 21st century, the Berlinale, as
it is widely known, is still struggling to find a new identity 10
years after the fall of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, things were often easier in the past. Veteran movie
directors from Eastern Europe can still be heard lamenting that
capitalism has proven to be a stricter censor than Communism. It
was always possible to find obtuse or allegorical ways of telling
the truth under Communism, they say, but there is no way of
circumventing the restrictions imposed by commercial budget and
distribution systems.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a parallel in the Berlinale. When this was a
divided and occupied city, the West Berlin festival had a clear
political mission, first as a showcase of democratic freedom, then
as a cultural bridge between East and West. Now, with Berlin
reunited and the Soviet bloc a thing of the past, the festival
seems to be adrift in the no man's land that divides the global
movie industry between the United States and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   This year's 10-day festival, which ends on Sunday, is therefore
a less than satisfying compromise. It is presenting a half-dozen
big-budget American movies, which have been released in the United
States and are merely using this festival as a springboard for
European distribution. But the Berlinale needs the glamour of
Hollywood stars: the world learns about it only because
photographers are willing to mob the likes of Leonardo DiCaprio
(here to promote ``The Beach'') or Gwyneth Paltrow (here for the
showing of ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'').
</P>
<P>
   This in turn reflects a reality beyond the festival's control:
the United States so dominates world cinema that it leaves little
room for anyone else. In most of Europe, including Germany,
American films account for 80 to 90 percent of ticket sales; only
in France, where government subsidies have kept the movie industry
alive, does the American share drop to around 70 percent. Thus if
few foreign-language movies reach the United States, few also find
markets elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In presenting scores of smaller movies from around the world,
the festival offers ample evidence that cinema is alive and well
outside the United States. Actors and directors from Spain to Japan
may wander around Berlin unnoticed, although even winning the
festival's awards, known as Bears, is no guarantee of wider
recognition. The talents and concerns of moviemakers working
outside the glare of Hollywood can nonetheless be seen here.
Perhaps surprisingly, politics are still an issue. A comedy from
Croatia called ``Marsal'' (known in English as ``Marshall Tito's
Spirit''), directed by Vinko Bresan, illustrates that country's
confused transition from Communism to capitalism by telling of an
apparition of Tito on a Croatian island. The mayor, having
privatized government properties and bought them on the cheap for
himself, now spots a new business opportunity: he invites veteran
Tito loyalists to contact the ghost and turns the island into a
Communist theme park.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the Balkans have proven adept at tackling their recent
tragedies with dark humor. ``Nebaska Udica'' (``Sky Hook''), which
was made by the Serbian director Ljubisa Samardzic during NATO's
bombing of Belgrade last April, tells of a group of beer-swilling
layabouts, including Kaja (Nebojsa Glogovac), whose 7-year-old son
has been struck mute by the bombing. Their main concern is to
rebuild their devastated basketball court, but the underlying theme
is their inability to influence the conflict disrupting their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Piao Ling Ma Ma'' (``Breaking the Silence''), directed by Sun
Zhou, also deals with contemporary events, this time in a China
hurriedly embracing the profits and perils of capitalism. This
serves as the background to a touching tale of a divorced mother,
played by the Chinese star Gong Li, as she struggles to have her
deaf 8-year-old son accepted in a regular school. Even with cuts
demanded by the Chinese authorities, the film captures the hardship
faced by many ordinary Chinese with the arrival of a market economy
and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, ``Russkij Bunt'' (``The Captain's Daughter''),
directed by Alexander Proshkin and adapted from two stories by
Pushkin, is a ``Dr. Zhivago''-like epic set in the 18th century. It
blends a love story with an account of the peasant uprising led by
an impostor posing as the czar, Yemelya Pugachev (Sergei
Machovecki). For all the film's snow, beards, swords and horses,
however, the director believes it to be topical. ``Our age, like
the times of Catherine II, is an age where morals have lost their
value, an age of swift career making and instantaneous downfalls,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A certain nostalgia also permeates Akira Ogata's first film,
``Boys' Choir,'' which is set in a Japan of the early 1970s where a
student movement with revolutionary dreams is facing defeat and
leaving an entire generation feeling pessimistic about the future.
The story focuses on two boys in a Christian boarding school where
a young pastor is trying to create his own version of the Vienna
Boys Choir. His past as a radical, however, catches up with him.
</P>
<P>
   Volker Schloendorff's new movie, ``The Legends of Rita,'' also
goes back to the radical movement of the 1970s, this time in West
Germany. When the movement collapses, Rita Vogt (Bibinana Beglau)
flees to East Germany, is given a new identity as a factory worker
and confronts the grimness of life under Communism. But when East
Germany finally implodes, she cannot escape responsibility for her
earlier terrorism in the West.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Still, most new movies from Europe show little interest in
politics, although several reflect the gradual blending of European
culture. Francois Ozon, an up-and-coming young French director, has
adapted an unstaged 1970 play by the German director Rainer Werner
Fassbinder, ``Water Drops on Burning Rocks,'' for the screen. Even
more of an international cocktail is ``Signs and Wonders,'' a new
film by the American director Jonathan Nossiter: it was financed by
a French company, made in English and set in Athens. It stars a
Swede (Stellan Skarsgard), a Briton (Charlotte Rampling), an
American (Deborah Kara Unger) and a Greek (Dimitris Katalifos).
</P>
<P>
   These films also offer human close-ups rather than social
statements. Ozon's movie, for instance, tells of a middle-aged man
who takes a young male lover only to find their menage a deux
disturbed by their former girlfriends. In ``Signs and Wonders'' a
man leaves his wife for a younger woman; when he decides to return
home, his wife has found happiness with another man, but his
pre-teen-age daughter proves to be a perverse ally.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolf Thome's ``Paradiso'' tells of a composer who celebrates
his 60th birthday with the seven most important lovers in his life.
Some critics described the film as a male fantasy; Thome said he
was being ironic.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the festival's Hollywood imports, which also include
``Three Kings,'' ``Magnolia,'' ``The Hurricane,'' ``Any Given
Sunday'' and ``Man on the Moon,'' there are other English-language
movies, not only small independent films from the United States but
also fare from the British Isles, including ``Saltwater,'' an
impressive directing debut by the young Irish playwright Conor
McPherson (``The Weir''), who also wrote the screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Branagh's latest Shakespeare, ``Love's Labour's Lost,''
though, seems closer to Hollywood in the 1950s than London in 1600.
Starring Alessandro Nivola as the king of Navarre and Alicia
Silverstone as the princess of France, with Branagh's Berowne
busily wooing Natascha McElhone's Rosaline, the film is peppered
with songs by Cole Porter, Irving Berlin and George Gershwin and
dance numbers inspired by Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers. In a nod
to Esther Williams, one scene even has the princess and her ladies
in waiting performing synchronized swimming. All of which goes to
prove that Shakespeare can survive anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1825EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
