<P>
   Mobile E-Mail and Web Access For Users of Palm V and Vx
</P>
<P>
   Hope is in the airwaves for Palm V and Vx owners. OmniSky Corp.
and AT&AMP;T have teamed up to provide a wireless modem and Internet
services for the users of the tiniest of the Palm organizers. The
combination package is undergoing a public beta trial by thousands
of Palm V owners, and OmniSky plans to release the final version in
the spring. Prices have not been set.
</P>
<P>
   There are wireless modems for earlier Palm handheld organizers,
and Palm VII owners have enjoyed wireless Web and e-mail functions
since last year. A regular corded modem is also available for the
Palm V.
</P>
<P>
   OmniSky's wireless Palm V modem, which weighs 4.6 ounces and is
about 5 inches long, can support a data speed of 19.2 kilobits per
second. Users will be able to send and receive e-mail and browse
the Web. Internet channels created by AvantGo can be browsed, and
OmniSky's service can also support the Palm Query Applications used
by the Palm VII for weather forecasts, airline schedules and stock
quotes.
</P>
<P>
   For $299, beta testers received the OmniSky Minstrel V wireless
modem unit and unlimited service until the end of March. Users
still wishing to participate can check OmniSky's Web site
(www.omnisky.com) or call (800) 860-5767. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   J.D. BIERSDORFER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Tantalizing Hope: Looking for Yeti
</P>
<P>
   In the past nine months, the SETI(at)home screen saver has
become a huge hit. The program has been loaded onto more than
1-and-a-half million home and office computers, where it is eagerly
crunching through recorded radio signals from space (distributed
via the Web) looking for signs of extraterrestrial life.
</P>
<P>
   So far not a single alien sitcom has come wafting through the
ether. The site, however, has proved that there is life on the
Internet: it has spawned a Web spoof, YETI(at)home.
</P>
<P>
   The YETI site (www.phobe.com/yeti) captures the look and feel of
the SETI site (www.setiathome.ssl.berkeley.edu), down to the
teasing come-on about the ``small but tantalizing possibility''
that the user will detect not alien life forms but ``the faint
footsteps of a hairy monster,'' otherwise known as Sasquatch,
Bigfoot or the Abominable Snowman.
</P>
<P>
   The YETI site says that anyone with a computer, a digital
camera, a window and a backyard can participate and that the
resulting images will be processed by millions of computers in
``the largest completely unscientific study of nonexistent
phenomenon to date.''
</P>
<P>
   YETI(at)home doesn't offer any software, but you get the sense
that even so, the site's author thinks the odds of finding a yeti
are better than the chances of finding E.T. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ HENRY FOUNTAIN &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
