<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ROOKIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIES REVVED UP FOR DAYTONA RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Tony Stewart established a standard for
NASCAR Winston Cup rookies last year. The 28-year-old driver of the
No. 20 Home Depot Pontiac compiled three victories, two pole
positions, 12 top five finishes, and 21 top 10s in winning
$3,190,149.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart finished fourth in the final Winston Cup point standings
to become only the third to make the top five. Even though he ran
away with Rookie of the Year honors, Stewart knows he would have
been hard-pressed to achieve those feats if he were in this year's
class of Winston Cup rookies, regarded by many veterans to be the
deepest and most talented crop in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rate 'em pretty high,'' said Stewart. ``They've got a good
batch of credentials and they're all here because they deserve to
be in Winston Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   To say NASCAR's eight-man rookie class is an eclectic group
would be an understatement. All of them will be gunning to qualify
for the 42d Daytona 500 when they line up Thursday in the Gatorade
Twin 125s, a pair of 125-mile qualifiers that will set the 43-car
field for Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty impressive class of rookies, that's for sure,''
said Jeff Gordon, a three-time Winston Cup champion who was the
1993 Rookie of the Year. ``I don't know how anybody is going to top
what Tony Stewart did last year. That was pretty amazing. But if
anybody could do it, it's this rookie class that we've got coming
up this year.''
</P>
<P>
   They will be led by reigning two-time Busch champion Dale
Earnhardt Jr., who will drive a Budweiser-sponsored Chevrolet for
his father, the seven-time Winston Cup champion. ``I'm so pumped up
for Daytona,'' said Earnhardt Jr. of his much-anticipated rookie
campaign. ``It's like waiting for a package to come in the mail.
You can't wait to open it and play with the toy inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr., 25, most likely will be challenged by Matt
Kenseth, 27, a familiar Busch rival who is considered to be the
Roush Racing protege of veteran Mark Martin; Scott Pruett, 39, a
former open-wheel driver from the CART who was the fastest rookie
(lap of 189.47 miles per hour) at Saturday's pole qualifications in
his Tide-sponsored Ford Taurus; and Dave Blaney, 37, a former USAC
and World of Outlaws sprint car champion who was the second-fastest
rookie (189.31) when qualified 10th in his Amoco-sponsored Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, most of the attention is on Dale Jr.,'' Gordon
said. ``But I'll tell you what, Matt Kenseth is a talented driver,
and he's got Roush behind him so I think he and Junior are going to
have some more battles out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the rookies will be distinguished by yellow stripes on
their rear bumpers, the elder Earnhardt believes it is a formality
in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they come into the sport, they're a lot more in tune _
and smarter _ to what's going on in Winston Cup racing with the
cars,'' Earnhardt said. ``So it's really not totally like being in
the dark when they hop in a Winston Cup race car. But I think the
rookie crop's been really good for the last couple of years, and
it's getting better, it seems, every year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Class of 2000 will be rounded out by former NASCAR Craftsman
Truck drivers Stacy Compton, 32, who will drive the No. 9 Kodiak
Ford Taurus for Mark Melling; Mike Bliss, 34, who will drive A.J.
Foyt's No. 14 Conseco Pontiac; and Jeff Fuller, 42, of Auburn,
Mass., a former Busch Rookie of the Year and NASCAR Featherlite
Modified champion who will pilot Eel River Racing's No. 27 Viagra
Pontiac that is owned by Boston businessman Jack Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '95, we came down here and we were a rookie (in the Busch
Series), people see the yellow stripe on the bumper, which is a big
giveaway to being a rookie,'' Fuller said. ``But sometimes you have
concerns about which rookies you can race and which ones you can't,
and a lot of that is due to the respect you get from other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they know you came up the hard way and paid your dues, then
they're more likely to cut you some slack and let you in line or
cut you a break. I think that, with the drivers in the Winston Cup
series, we're going to adapt just fine. I think this is going to be
a pretty competitive class, maybe the strongest class that NASCAR
has ever seen. Obviously, every one of us is looking forward to it
and we fully expect to be a contender for Rookie of the Year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
