<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DOGS-WESTMINSTER-BOS &LR;      02-16 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOGS-WESTMINSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGER SPANIEL LEADS DOGGIEDOM INTO THE NEW CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The century of the springer? At the country's most
prestigious dog show Tuesday night, at Madison Square Garden, the
first dog of the new millennium turned out to be a jaunty little
liver-and-white English springer spaniel named Samantha, or, as
she's officially named, Ch. (Champion) Salilyn 'N Erin's Shameless.
</P>
<P>
   If this top dog foretells our future, we are in for 100 years of
unfussy, handsome, good old American can-do style _ with a little
bit of sentimentality thrown in, too. This dog has just the kind of
background that the aficionados of the Westminster Kennel Club
love.
</P>
<P>
   After months and years of campaigning purebred dogs in shows
around the country, 2,500 champions of record, representing 156
breeds, land at this dog show, the second-oldest sporting event in
the country and the Super Bowl of canine conformation. The price of
getting here can run as high as $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Westminster is glitz, glamour, and drool. With black-tie events
(one of the hottest tickets being the Ken-L Ration dinner), awards
ceremonies, schmoozing, gossiping, and, of course, dog showing.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, individual breeds are judged. In the evening, they
compete to represent their group. Working, terrier, toy, and
non-sporting on Monday night. Sporting, hounds, herding, and best
in show, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That 2,500 turned into just seven hot dogs at about 10:30
Tuesday night. There was the standard poodle, a moving topiary of
white hair. A sleek Doberman pinscher. The superstar springer. A
lamb-like Bedlington terrier (who took a moment to relieve himself
at the entrance). The Shih Tzu with the blue hair doodad. The
almost comically dignified basset hound. And the foxy little
Pembroke Welsh corgi. All trotting out onto that trademark green
carpet.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, a titan of the dog show world and president of
Westminster, Chester Collier, focused on the dogs as they strutted
in front of him. Despite the buzz that the poodle, 1999's
top-ranked Ch. Lakecove That's My Boy, nicknamed Treson, would be a
shoo-in, and despite the crowd's enthusiasm for that sad-eyed
basset, Astro, it was Samantha, with her flowing skirt of perfectly
groomed hair, who swept the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted it,'' Collier said later, confusing this bitch, as
they say in these parts, with a dog, ``and he got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though this 5-year-old girl has quite a winning record, she
was not an expected winner. She really did prove herself Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Her handler, Kellie Fitzgerald, kept saying that she represents
her ancestors. Samantha's father, Robert, or Ch. Salilyns Condor,
took best in show in 1993. That was a memorable win, in part,
because one of his owners, a 92-year-old beloved grande dame of the
sport, Julia Gasow, surprised everyone by coming to the Garden at
the last moment despite the fact that her husband had recently
died. That night turned out to be her first best-in-show win at
Westminster.
</P>
<P>
   Gasow, who died last year, also co-owned Samantha. When this
spirited little springer took the top trophy, the crowd cheered and
co-owner Carl Blaine took a moment to look up past the Garden's
rafters, and say, ``This is for you, Julie.''
</P>
<P>
   Samantha, for her part, wagged her stub of a tail as she sat on
the purple winner's rug. Cameras clicked and reporters from around
the world shouted questions to Fitzgerald. Dave Frei, one of the
hosts of USA Channel's Westminster coverage, put his arm around
Fitzgerald just before the cameras rolled and whispered to her that
she should do ``Good Morning America'' with him the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha is scheduled for a busy press day, a lunch at Sardi's,
where she is supposed to get steak, and then retirement. Sort of.
All this fame will give way to romance. Her pups will be worth a
lot and she is due to come into season very soon. She is expected
to carry on a line that goes back more than 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night in Madison Square Garden, Blaine remembered the
evening when he and Gasow sipped gin and tonics after the win. She
had it absolutely right, he recalled. ``She said there's nothing
like it in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
