<P>
   RUSSIA-BANK (New York) _ Two leading figures in the Bank of New
York money laundering investigation told a federal judge Wednesday
that a scheme to move billions of dollars from Russia was
originated and controlled by politically connected Russian banks.
In detailed confessions in Manhattan federal court, Lucy Edwards, a
former Bank of New York vice president, and her husband Peter
Berlin described how between 1996 and last year more than $7
billion moved out of Russia illegally and into a network of front
company accounts at the Bank of New York, which were controlled by
Berlin. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KOHL (Berlin) _ The crisis of the conservative party
that has governed and stabilized Germany for most of the postwar
years deepened Wednesday with the abrupt resignation of its leader,
Wolfgang Schaeuble. The departure of Schaeuble, who was handpicked
by former Chancellor Helmut Kohl to be his successor as party
leader in 1998, leaves the opposition Christian Democratic Union
rudderless at a time of profound shifts in the political landscape
of German-speaking Europe. By Roger Cohen. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Grozny, Russia) _ Grozny is more than a
landscape of shattered buildings. It is also a city of broken
lives. The limited access Russian forces have granted to the
capital make it difficult to systemically chronicle the human
rights violations there. But accounts provided by residents during
a two-day period appeared credible and pointed to abuses by both
sides. Some of the most chilling allegations involve the Russian
troops who battled their way into the city. Anxious to avenge their
fallen comrades, some took out their frustrations on Grozny's
defenseless civilians. By Michael R. Gordon. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT24-27.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-POLL (Undated) _ Results of the latest N.Y. Times poll
on the national presidential campaign. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SC-POLITICAL-PROFILE (Greenville, S.C.) _ A look at the changing
nature of the economy and political power in South Carolina. When
the state's textile industry died, former Gov. Carroll Campbell, a
Republican, felt the answer could be found in modern manufacturing
and lured the biggest possible prize to the state: a BMW factory.
In it he began to sow the seeds of the dilution of his political
machine. By Jim Yardley and David Firestone. 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ As witness testimony in the
Diallo trial came to a swift conclusion Wednesday, both the defense
and the prosecution moved to let the jury consider charges below
second-degree murder. Should the judge agree, he could let the jury
consider manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide, lesser
charges that could mean little or no prison time for the accused
New York City officers should conviction result. By Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-IMMIG (New Orleans) _ The American labor movement, after
long regarding immigrants as a threat, adopted a sharp change in
policy Wednesday and called for amnesty for illegal immigrants and
an end to most sanctions against employers that hire such
immigrants. In decades past, many labor unions saw immigrant
workers as the enemy, often accusing them of pulling down wages and
breaking strikes. But the AFL-CIO's executive council adopted a
more sympathetic approach toward immigrants Wednesday, saying the
nation's immigration rules have too often enabled employers to
exploit undocumented workers. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
