<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Feb. 20,
2000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE Stories &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONG-ISLAND-FILMS (New York) _ For me _ a fanatical filmgoer
from an early age _ the real proof that Long Island was nowhere was
that I never saw it in the movies. It obviously wasn't important in
the way New York, London, Paris and Dodge City were. The lonely
exception to the silver screen's general embargo on images of Long
Island was that sequence in ``North by Northwest'' in which the
urbane Cary Grant was kidnapped outside the Plaza Hotel and taken
to a mansion on the North Shore, where he would barely survive an
attempt on his life. All this would change, though, in part thanks
to the rise of independent film, with its fondness for depicting
quirky people in ordinary settings (or, perhaps more to the point,
in cheap locations). By Terrence Rafferty. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-ART-DIRECTORS (Undated) _ A talk between two of the most
prominent figures in the New York art world, Philippe de
Montebello, the director of the Metropolitan Museum of Art and
Thomas Krens, the director of the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museun. By
Judith H. Dobrzynski. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEACH-FILM (Undated) _ In ``The Beach,'' Danny Boyle's film
adaptation of Alex Garland's popular novel, Leonardo DiCaprio is
Richard, a pleasure-seeking backpacker who finds himself alone and
itching for adventure in swinging Bangkok. Richard's vague search
for heaven on earth (with some requisite danger thrown in) leads
him to a secret commune on a remote coastal island that can be
reached only by swimming to its shores. At first, paradise appears
to be everything he has been looking for. Against a backdrop of
perfect sunsets and moonrises, its international brigade of
post-hippie sybarites (so preposterously well-tended that they
resemble the cast of ``Baywatch'' on a Club Med holiday) while away
their days in peppy beachside games of soccer and volleyball.
Utopia only begins to pall after a tragedy reveals Richard's fellow
exiles to be a bunch of selfish party animals willing to sacrifice
lives to keep their pristine enclave a secret. By Stephen Holden.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIFUNE-FILM (Copenhagen, Denmark) _ ``Mifune,'' is a touching
love story set on an isolated farm in southern Denmark. The film,
by the Danish diredtor, Soren Kragy-Jacobsen, 52, which won a
special jury prize at the 1999 Berlin film festival and is
Denmark's Academy Award nominee for best foreign language film this
year, opens in New York on Friday. By Alan Riding. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON-BALLET-SCHOOL (Washington) _ It was once a private
home, but now the four-floor white building at the intersection of
Wisconsin Avenue and Porter Street is filled with studios, offices
and dressing rooms. In a way it is still a home, but now to the
Washington School of Ballet, founded in 1944 by Mary Day and Lisa
Gardiner, and the Washington Ballet, founded by Day in 1976. In the
1980s, Choo San Goh, who was the resident choreographer,
transformed the company from a regional ballet troupe into an
internationally respected entity. Goh died in 1987, and after
several successors had come and gone, the company appointed its
present artistic director, Septime Webre, last June. By Kate
Mattingly. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JULIO-BOCCO-DANCE (New York) _ Julio Bocca, a dashing star of
American Ballet Theater, did not look himself as he rehearsed in a
mid-Manhattan studio early this month. With his toes turned in, his
back arched and his hands placed on his hips, not a trace of
Albrecht or Romeo could be discerned in his demeanor. While still
jet-lagged from a flight from Buenos Aires and worn from rehearsing
his own company, Ballet Argentina, for its recent performance at
the World Financial Center Winter Garden, he was trying to absorb a
choreographic style as different from Petipa as night from day. And
he had to learn it fast, because last Tuesday he was to make his
Broadway debut in the Tony Award-winning musical ``Fosse.'' By
Valerie Gladstone. (Moved). WTIH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SETLOCK-THEATER (New York) _ The play ``Fully Committed,'' is a
satirical look at a day in the life of a four-star restaurant
besieged by high-powered customers demanding tables. Written by
Becky Mode, a friend of its star Mark Setlock, and directed by
Nicholas Martin, opened to raves in September at the Vineyard
Theater and moved to a commercial run at the 180-seat Cherry Lane
in December. By Jesse McKinley. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARUSO-2000-MUSIC (Undated) _ Have you ever wondered what it
would be like to hear your favorite Caruso recordings freshened up:
say, with the great tenor's voice, exactly as it was captured by an
acoustic recording horn in the days before microphones, newly
cloaked in the lush timbres of a modern symphony orchestra recorded
in digital stereo? No, of course you haven't. Why would you? Why
would anyone? Yet someone not only did but also suspected that
other people might. Thus we have ``Caruso 2000,'' a production of
the Austrian Broadcasting Corp., released on CD by RCA Victor. By
Allan Kozinn. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIC-LYRICS (Undated) _ Composing lyrics in the classic
tradition of American song has always demanded a respect for, if
not slavish adherence to, laws: of form, function, poesy. That's
the fun of it. The challenge. The ideal. We live, however, in the
grip of a music culture that venerates rebelliousness. The
intricacies of lyric writing have thus been reduced to brute
effusion. Worse than a chore, adherence to craft is actually seen
as a sellout. By Barry Singer. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRAMMY-AWARDS (Undated) _ Yet another chapter in pop's latest
bout with adolescence unfolds this week at the 42nd annual Grammy
Awards. The nominee list, as undependable as ever in predicting
music's real history-makers, does crackle with one present
conflict, between the parent figures who run the event and the kids
now paying their allowances. Those kids get on adults' nerves with
their obvious commercial music, but these hit makers, sometimes
unwittingly, are pointing toward pop's future. A likely sweep by
the night's deserving front-runner, Carlos Santana, will reassure
those baby-boomer voters far too old to really understand the
chart-topping teenage nominees like Britney Spears, Christina
Aguilera and those ever-present, thrice-nominated Backstreet Boys.
By Ann Powers. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ED-LOGUE-ARCHITECT (New York) _ For many New Yorkers, Ed Logue's
name evokes an era when the quality of urban life was measured by
something more than skyrocketing real estate prices, the banishment
of homeless people from public sidewalks and the glitter of
confetti falling from the sky. The ideal of social equality also
figured in the equation. Logue, born in Philadelphia in 1921, was
among the last of the master planners to practice urban renewal on
an epic scale. By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CREWDSON-PHOTOGS (Lee, Mass.) _ Chaos may lie behind Gregory
Crewdson's work, but you would hardly know it from looking at his
pictures of suburbia, where an eerie calm always prevails. Since
1998, the 37-year-old photographer has been creating a series
titled ``Twilight,'' which now includes 20 meticulously detailed,
richly colored pictures, all taken in and around the outskirts of
Lee, ranging from domestic interiors to landscape views. The
photographs, featuring the local townspeople, are always shot at
dusk. Twelve of Crewdson's most recent ``Twilight'' photographs are
now on view at Luhring Augustine Gallery. By Elizabeth Hayt.
(Moved). WITH GRAPHIC. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-TALK-WALLS (Undated) _ Three years after they became the most
publicized, criticized, scrutinized gay couple in Hollywood, if not
the country, Ellen DeGeneres and Anne Heche have had enough. Not of
each other. Far from it. They have a new outlook and are eager to
declare, despite predictions that theirs was a relationship founded
on Hollywood-style eccentricity and star madness, that they are
still, as Ms. Heche put it, ``crazy happy'' together. As recently
as last July, when Ms. Heche and Ms. DeGeneres sat down for an
interview in their trailer on the set of ``If These Walls Could
Talk 2,'' the HBO film in which both women have had a prominent
hand, they were still anguished over the lack of enthusiasm their
pairing up had inspired. By Bill Carter. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Surfing the net: Pick a city, pick a
guide. By L.R. Shannon. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EVERGLADES (Undated) _ U.S. parks face pressure to ban
off-road vehicles. By John H. Cushamn Jr. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Tracing freedom's trail through
Philadelphia; Danish design center moves into a new home; A
Caribbean hotel joins an upscale crowd; Topkapi: you saw the movie,
now see the jewels. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Question and answers on travel. This
week: A day in Brussels; Pottery, coast to coast; Frankfurt Ballet.
By Joseph Siano. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Train or plane to Boston? By
Betsy Wade. (Moved).
</P>
