<SLUG> BC-BOOK-THEBRETHREN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS GRISHAM ABOUT TO DUMP THE LEGAL EAGLES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This month's publication of ``The Brethren'' (Doubleday,
$27.95), John Grisham's 10th legal-themed thriller in 10 years, may
someday be seen as a turning point in the megabestselling author's
career.
</P>
<P>
   It will not involve any slackening of typical Grisham book
sales. ``The Brethren'' was No. 1 on amazon.com two weeks before
hitting bookstore shelves. Doubleday ordered a 2.8 million-copy
first printing, almost three times as many copies as most
blockbusters get. No other writer _ not Stephen King or Tom Clancy
or Patricia Cornwell _ sells more hardcover books than John
Grisham.
</P>
<P>
   And Grisham isn't breaking ground with ``The Brethren,'' either.
Lawyers still are at the heart of this one, albeit three ex-judges
in a federal prison running mail scams on rich, middle-aged gay
men. Oh, Grisham is obviously pushing to include new plot twists,
and ``The Brethren'' finds its three blackmailers inadvertently
inserting their slimy schemes into the middle of a presidential
election masterminded by the CIA. But it's still a book Grisham
fans would recognize; nobody else crafts fiction in quite this way.
Critics who regularly pan Grisham will find the same reason
(well-written but with predictable plot lines) to fault him this
time out.
</P>
<P>
   Those critics would be wrong. More than ever in ``The
Brethren,'' Grisham demonstrates an exceptional ability to pull
together story lines that apparently have little relationship. His
narrative jumps around _ from the Florida minimum-security prison
where authorities allow the three incarcerated ``brethren'' to keep
kangaroo court for other inmates _ to all sorts of stops on the
campaign trail of Arizona U.S. Rep. Arthur Lake, picked by the CIA
as a figurehead candidate because he would support doubling the
U.S. defense budget if elected.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the book, it turns out that the one Lake vice
the CIA hadn't anticipated has put the next president squarely in
the power of the three cons. With the power to instigate terrorist
attacks halfway around the world or raise an instant $60 million
for Lake's campaign war chest, CIA Director Teddy Maynard suddenly
finds himself matching wits with three very greedy crooks who
consider their freedom more important than America's ability to
bomb enemies into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   OK _ it was obvious early on that the brethren and Lake would
cross paths _ but Grisham's tying-together at book's end is pretty
clever (bad guys win _ and lose), and ``The Brethren'' is certainly
a literary step up from recent bestselling potboilers by Nelson
DeMille and Dean Koontz.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Brethren'' may be significant for a reason other than
book sales. It could mark Grisham's last legal-themed book and his
final title for longtime publisher Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   The January/February edition of ``The Oxford American,'' a small
Mississippi-based literary magazine, contained the first of six
installments of ``A Painted House,'' a new Grisham yarn about a
family-run cotton farm in Arkansas and the menacing migrant worker
who arrives there in 1952. The surprises here are not that Grisham
would choose ``The Oxford American'' to run his serialized novel _
he owns the publication and serves as its publisher _ but that
Grisham would write something so radically different from his usual
style, and that he'd have its first chapter published at just about
the same time Doubleday released ``The Brethren.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports persist in the book industry that ``The Brethren''
concludes Grisham's current contract with Doubleday. He hasn't
spoken about it, and Doubleday spokeswoman Christina Brenner said,
``We can't give that (information) out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oxford American'' editor Mark Smirnoff, who is also Grisham's
private editor on books written for Doubleday, has said that ``John
owns `A Painted House,' '' and that he expects the six installments
eventually to be published in full book form, much like Stephen
King's ``The Green Mile,'' which originally appeared in six
mass-market paperbacks.
</P>
<P>
   All of this could leave Grisham in a powerful bargaining
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if his contract is through with Doubleday or
not,'' said Kenneth Kirkland, a publishing-industry analyst. ``But
if it is, and he was available for a new contract, bringing `A
Painted House' would mean Grisham's new publisher could practically
have an instant Grisham book to publish. Which publishers would bid
anything under those circumstances? The question is, which ones
wouldn't?''
</P>
<P>
   Grisham doesn't have to change publishers or genres. Doubleday
has long since allowed the author to choose his own publicity
appearances, and it has placed ``The Brethren'' literally anywhere
Grisham fans might care to shop. Tom Thumb grocery stores and Best
Buy appliance megastores have prominent displays of the book. It is
featured on almost every Internet bookstore site. Even Grisham's
Web site, www.jgrisham.com, offers tantalizing glimpses of the
newest title, with five free excerpts online even before the book
was published.
</P>
<P>
   But if Grisham is bored with churning out annual legal
thrillers, public response to ``A Painted House'' could indicate
whether his fans will embrace something new.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, it seems they will. Smirnoff said that the
``The Oxford American's'' usual run of 50,000 copies had increased
to 260,000 for January//February when the first ``Painted House''
installment ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks now as though that may not satisfy the demand,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Smirnoff is editing ``A Painted House's'' second chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, John Grisham can do whatever he wants,''
Kirkland concluded. ``It will be interesting to see how this turns
out.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
