<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9033 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-BAUER-HNS &LR;      02-16 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-BAUER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN SHOWCASES BAUER ENDORSEMENT IN BIBLE BELT  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Sen. John McCain struck back Wednesday at
Texas Gov. George Bush's bid to sow doubts about his anti-abortion
credentials, unveiling the endorsement of right-to-life advocate
Gary Bauer in a predominantly Baptist region known as ``the buckle
on the Bible belt.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign aides said they hoped that the endorsement by
Bauer four days before the Saturday South Carolina presidential
primary would help bolster McCain's support among the 20 percent of
South Carolina voters who identify themselves as members of the
religious right.
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby-Reuters polls released Wednesday showed Bush outpacing
McCain among ``born-again'' Christians, 50 percent to 34 percent,
in South Carolina. The same poll showed Bush leading McCain, 43
percent to 40 percent. The poll was conducted Monday and Tuesday
and has a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McCain called Bauer's endorsement ``one of the most wonderful
events of this entire political campaign'' because it would help
him reach a faction of the Republican party that has favored rival
GOP candidates for president.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said he was endorsing McCain ``without any hesitation''
despite their disagreement on exceptions to a ban on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bush favor a ban on abortion but allow for three
exceptions: to save the life of the mother or in cases of rape or
incest. Bauer and the GOP platform oppose any exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is ``the best shot we have to end the era of Bill and
Hillary and Al Gore,'' Bauer told a rally at Furman University
where his endorsement was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a former Reagan administration official who made his
anti-abortion stance a hallmark of his own campaign, said McCain
``by and large'' has an anti-abortion voting record. Bauer, who
calls the right to life an inalienable right protected in the
Declaration of Independence, said he hoped to persuade McCain to
support a more complete ban on abortion in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   McCain favors bringing the GOP platform into line with the
position that he and Bush share. Bush supports leaving the
hard-fought platform alone. Bush enjoys the support of the
Christian Coalition, led by Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys show that a minority of voters supports an absolute ban
on abortion. But the issue sharply divides competing wings of the
Republican party, fomenting a constant struggle.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been peppered with questions about his position
almost daily, including at a question-and-answer session with
voters in Newberry, S.C., en route to his endorsement by Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told several hundred people gathered in the opera house
on the town square that he personally believes exceptions are
warranted and that his view is the ``generally held view by the
majority of pro-life people.'' McCain said his disagreement with
any voters who support an all-out ban ought to be treated merely as
``an open and honest and respected disagreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Curtis Waters, 70, a Baptist minister in Greenville, S.C.,
said Bauer's endorsement could help McCain stem the loss of support
in northwest South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Waters said Bauer was ``a fine moral person'' well known to
voters across this predominantly Baptist region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his support will help McCain,'' Waters said. ``I think
it may make a turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Davis, McCain's campaign director, said Bauer's endorsement
was welcome because it ``will help reassure people that Sen. McCain
has a good record on right to life,'' adding: ``This will help cut
through all the misrepresentations.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the National Right to Life Committee have showered
South Carolina voters with campaign fliers urging the election of
Bush on the basis that he would support a tougher ban on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush brushed aside the Bauer endorsement of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   `Everybody's got a right to endorse who they want to endorse,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the announcement by California Secretary of State
Bill Jones _ the state's highest ranking elected Republican _ that
he was switching his support from Bush to McCain, Bush replied: `If
Bill wants to be on the winning team, he ought to stay here. If
he's interested in being on the team that's going to win the
Republican nomination, he made the wrong decision. I'm going to win
the Republican nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush downplayed reports of financial troubles in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   `I know we're on plan,'' he said. ``We've got a strategy in
place that's working. I like my chances'' in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported Wednesday that Bush's campaign
finance chiefs are concerned that Bush faces a potential money
shortfall in the wake of a $37 million spending spree through Dec.
31. The actual figure of what Bush has spent to date by now is
probably closer to $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman, acknowledged the campaign has
an unspecified number of fundraising events on tap for March and
April to replenish Bush's coffers. But she insisted those events
have been in the works for months and do not reflect any
last-minute desperation.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's next federally required campaign expenditure
report, to be filed Feb. 20, will report $20 million in the bank as
of Jan. 31, according to Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at
202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
