<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PINOCHET-HEALTH-570&AMP;A     02-16 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-HEALTH-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL REPORT REVEALS BRAIN DAMAGE IN PINOCHET, SPANISH PRESS
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See sidebar PINOCHET-AILMENTS) 
(js) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Two Spanish newspapers, citing copies of a secret
British medical report they had obtained on Gen. Augusto Pinochet,
reported Wednesday that he suffered brain damage from minor strokes
last year and is no longer mentally fit to stand trial in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   In similar articles, the newspapers El Mundo and ABC quoted from
a report signed by three British physicians on Jan. 6. They said
that the general was suffering from loss of short- and long-term
memory and that he was not fully able to grasp complex sentences
and questions. They also said he cannot express himself clearly and
suffers periods of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which the newspapers said was translated from
English into Spanish, noted that the damage to the blood vessels of
the brain appeared in the frontal and temporal lobes and was the
likely result of several recent minor strokes.
</P>
<P>
   If the report is authentic, then it alters little of what was
previously published about the health of the 84-year-old former
Chilean dictator. But the disclosure of the confidential documents
could further complicate the legal wrangling over Pinochet's
release and make his 16-month house-arrest in England even longer.
</P>
<P>
   After a ruling by the London High Court on Tuesday, Britain
reluctantly provided the medical report to the London embassies of
Belgium, France, Spain and Switzerland, which are seeking
Pinochet's extradition on charges of grave human rights violations
in Spain. The High Court said that the four countries were entitled
to see the medical report for the sake of ``transparency and
fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   But in its ruling, the High Court also said the four countries
could see the medical report only ``under conditions of strict
confidentiality.'' They were given until Feb. 22 to send their
reactions to London.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain Wednesday, angry government officials said they had
asked Spain to investigate who leaked the secret document. Lawyers
in Madrid said the publication of court documents was a violation
of Spanish law and could lead to charges of contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the Spanish reports Wednesday agree with a statement
released by Britain's home secretary, Jack Straw, who said in
January that the 84-year-old former Chilean dictator's health had
deteriorated and that he was not fit to stand trial. Therefore,
Straw said he was inclined to end the 16-month-long British house
arrest of the ailing general and let him return to Chile.
</P>
<P>
   In Madrid, where the Pinochet case has become intensely
politicized, it was the leak, more than the medical details, that
caused an uproar. Opposition leader Joaquin Almunia blamed the
Madrid government, which has long opposed having a Pinochet trial
in Spain. He said the government had been ``indecent'' in leaking
the document to two pro-government newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Baltasar Garzon, the Madrid judge who initiated the charges
against Pinochet and asked Britain for his arrest, said he had
received the doctors' report but had put it under seal and had not
leaked it. Various Spanish government spokesmen also denied that
the document came from them.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Garces, a Spanish lawyer representing the victims of the
Chilean dictatorship, said the leaking of the documents was one
more effort ``to keep the Pinochet case out of the courts, because
in court he keeps losing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The foreign ministers of both Britain and Spain have been trying
to solve the complex Pinochet question politically. Britain's
foreign minister has been quoted as saying he does not want
Pinochet to die in England.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's foreign minister has said he does not want to see
Pinochet tried in Spain. Also, the Madrid government is worried
that a prolonged fight could further disrupt relations with Chile,
where Spain has many business interests.
</P>
<P>
   Although the British medical report apparently provides lengthy
details about Pinochet's many physical ailments _ such as diabetes,
unsteadiness, pain in his knees, deafness and more _ lawyers said
only a person's mental fitness to stand trial counts.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC newspaper, in its Spanish translation of the report,
quoted the doctors as saying, ``In our opinion, Senator Pinochet is
presently not mentally fit to participate fully cognizant in a
trial.'' They said his memory problems and his difficulties in
processing information, apparently aggravated by minor strokes in
September and October, are not likely to improve.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors added, ``At the moment he shows no signs of clinical
depression.'' They said the trial could provoke stress that could
increase the damage to the blood vessels in the brain. But they
said they had been told in the past that Pinochet ``has shown
remarkable capacity to control stress. We are therefore unable to
give any useful opinion about the effects a trial may have on his
health.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
