<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9039 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-ENDORSEMENT-HN     02-16 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-ENDORSEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN PICKS UP BACKING OF BAUER 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ John McCain, who has largely kept religion
out of his Republican presidential campaign, was endorsed Wednesday
by former rival Gary Bauer, a leader in the Christian conservative
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement could prove significant Saturday in the tight
South Carolina primary between major candidates McCain and Texas
Gov. George W. Bush. Bauer dropped out of the race earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer announced his support for McCain at a rally at Furman
University in the heart of this state's conservative Christian
center.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Arizona senator was the ``best shot we have to end
the era of Bill and Hillary and Al Gore.``
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bush have been fighting for the votes of religious
and social conservatives, who could exert great influence over the
outcome of Saturday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who gained tremendous momentum with his upset victory
over Bush in the Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary, needs another
victory to keep his insurgent campaign alive, some observers
believe. And Bush, the early front-runner, will need to score a win
to revive his struggling campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In another potentially key development Wednesday, California
Secretary of State Bill Jones, the highest elected Republican in
that state, switched his allegiance from Bush and endorsed McCain.
California will hold its primary March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Los Angeles, Jones said he switched to McCain
because his message of campaign-finance reform would reach beyond
Republican stalwarts and help build the party. California, like
South Carolina, allows voters to choose in which primary they will
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message I hear from South Carolina from some of the GOP is
your vote doesn't count as an independent or crossover unless you
vote for Bush,'' Jones said. ``That isn't the message of
California.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bush oppose abortion rights, which Bauer made a key
target of his campaign. But unlike Bauer, McCain and Bush also
would allow abortions in cases or rape, incest or to protect the
life of the mother. And McCain has earned the wrath of other
anti-abortion groups because he favors federal funding of fetal
tissue research.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said that while both candidates opposed abortion rights,
``I weighed the relative merits of the men, and I'm convinced from
an honesty standpoint, trustworthiness standpoint, a values
standpoint that Sen. McCain is clearly the best choice.``
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, former head of the Family Research Council, said that he
believed McCain was guided by the ``central moral idea of
America,'' which he said was the protection of life principle
embodied in the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that John understands those words. I know that he
agrees with me that because of those words we must work to make
sure that every child is welcomed into the world and protected by
the law,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   He also praised McCain, who has made campaign-finance reform a
key issue of his presidential race, for wanting an ``American
political system that is not moneybags democracy, but a system
built on civility and decency and honor.``
</P>
<P>
   McCain told reporters he valued Bauer's endorsement as a means
to help him gain the support of religious conservatives. McCain is
not an overtly religious man and his only reference to religion in
the campaign has been to recount that he led prayers with his
cellmates in the North Vietnamese prisoner of war camp in which he
was held for nearly six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view Gary's support as a very important element in my effort
to broaden our base both within and without the Republican Party,''
McCain said. ``I view him as a trusted adviser, a person who will
provide lines of communication for me in parts of the party that my
lines of communication are not as strong as I would have liked them
to be.``
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the Bush campaign were at the rally and immediately
after Bauer's announcement distributed a written statement from
many of his former supporters, who was now backing the Texas
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot recall feeling more hurt or disappointed than I feel
today,'' state Sen. Mike Fair, Bauer's former South Carolina
campaign chairman, is quoted in the statement. Fair is now
supporting Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
