<P>
   TREASURY-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Last week, Secretary of
Treasury Lawrence Summers predicted that by 2013, the $3.6 trillion
in U.S. Treasury debt held by the public would be eliminated,
repurchased by funds from budget surpluses. The result, he said,
would be an even stronger economy and lower interest rates for all.
But in the meantime, the Treasury's plan to reduce its debt is
roiling the financial markets. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Display)
</P>
<P>
   TOYS-FAIR (New York) _ E-Specially My Barney comes with a cord
so the plush figure can be plugged into the nearest computer, where
information can be downloaded daily from a Web site and
``personalized'' for a particular child. V-Mail lets 5-year-olds
send and receive their own voicemail messages. And the Kick Start
Busy Crib Center features a chirping electronic lullaby that is
activated when a baby whacks a colored part of the toy with a foot.
At the five-day Toy Fair, it was abundantly clear that technology
has become an essential component in toys for the nation's
children. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 7:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
