<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-AILMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS REPORTS ON PINOCHET'S HEALTH LEAVE QUESTIONS UNANSWERED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With PINOCHET-HEALTH) 
(js) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spanish news reports citing a confidential report by British
doctors on the health of Gen. Augusto Pinochet said he suffers from
a number of ailments that make him mentally unfit to stand trial.
But the news accounts were based on excerpts of the full doctors'
report and leave unanswered many medical questions about what ails
the 84-year-old former Chilean dictator.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial question is how many times the British doctors
examined Pinochet before issuing their report. A report based on
repeated examinations is often more meaningful than one written
after one examination.
</P>
<P>
   Another important question is what are the 16 ailments Pinochet
is said to have. The news reports cited two medical problems:
memory loss and difficulties in comprehension from recent and
progressive cerebro-vascular damage, and nerve damage to his legs
as a complication of diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   But the news reports did not say whether Pinochet's brain damage
resulted from a stroke, Alzheimer's disease or some other
neurological condition.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes can damage blood vessels throughout the body, including
the brain, and increase the risk of strokes.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 11 drugs that Pinochet was said to be taking daily
were named in the news reports. They said he had been receiving
appropriate therapy for his ailments during his 16-month house
arrest in England.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of which drugs were prescribed and at what time could
be important in Pinochet's case because his condition deteriorated
seriously last September and October, the news reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Many drugs interact to cause mental confusion and difficulty in
communicating. The mental changes can mimic or aggravate the
symptoms of Alzheimer's and strokes, particularly in the elderly.
Mental problems can increase if the amount of drugs is not reduced.
The news reports did not say whether the British doctors' report
excluded drug reactions as a possible cause of Pinochet's mental
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   The front portion of Pinochet's brain has deteriorated, the news
reports said. In many elderly people, the brain shrinks in size,
but the shrinkage does not necessarily lead to mental changes. Many
elderly people have small brains yet are mentally alert. The news
reports did not say how many neurological examinations and brain
scans Pinochet had and over what period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPEAN-AUTO-MERGERS     02-16 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-AUTO-MERGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER SPECULATION ABOUNDS IN EUROPEAN AUTOMOBILE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Europe's automobile industry has gone into
overdrive _ at least when it comes to merger speculation.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive day, shares of PSA Peugeot Citroen
jumped Wednesday on rumors that it was in talks with
DaimlerChrysler AG Those rumors followed persistent speculation
about Daimler seeking to acquire the automobile business of Fiat
SPA.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, British and German newspapers speculated that
Volkswagen AG might take over Rover Cars, the ailing British
subsidiary of BMW AG.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts believe that more car mergers are inevitable,
because manufacturers are under pressure to keep prices down and
yet roll out new models faster than ever.
</P>
<P>
   That said, most of the merger predictions thus far have been
wrong. One reason is that the most desirable or at least needy car
companies are still controlled by their founding families _ the
Peugeots of France, the Agnellis of Italy and the Quandts of
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those families has rejected the idea of selling out.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Peugeot once again denied it is in merger talks,
following rumors on Tuesday that DaimlerChrysler had offered 35
shares of its own stock and 10 euros for every 10 shares of
Peugeot.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Martin Folz, Peugeot's president, said in Paris Wednesday
that the company wanted to remain independent and had the ability
to do so. ``We want neither a merger nor an acquisition,'' Folz
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger question is, why would DaimlerChrysler want to
pursue it?
</P>
<P>
   Each new rumor about a big Daimler acquisition has sent its
share price down.Daimler's stock has declined 13 percent this year,
while the DAX index of leading stocks has climbed about nine
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Daimler's decline reflects investor unhappiness about
possible takeovers of small-car makers like Fiat or Peugeot.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a capital markets point of view, we would rather see the
company say they are not going to do anything in small cars and
will return free cash flow to shareholders,'' said Christian
Breitsprecher, an analyst at Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's chairman, Juergen E. Schrempp, has left no
doubt that he badly wants to build up his small-car business _ the
one area that neither Mercedes Benz nor Chrysler have any real
strength.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts are overwhelmingly unhappy about a big push into
small cars. For one thing, the price competition in that segment is
brutal and the profit margins are much lower than for Mercedes
luxury cars or Chrysler's light trucks and sport-utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the margins available in the markets served by
Fiat and Peugeot are nowhere near comparable to those of
DaimlerChrysler,'' said Andrew Blair-Smith, an analyst in London at
Commerzbank.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, analysts worry that companies like Fiat or Peugeot
will require substantial new investment and management time.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally agree that Europe's smaller and weaker car
companies are under considerable pressure. Fiat lost money through
the first nine months of 1999, though it is now experiencing an
upswing and is believed to have turned a profit in the final
quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Peugeot fared better last year, with its automobile revenue
climbing 11.5 percent to 32.6 billion euros, or about $33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But with an annual output of 2.5 million vehicles, far behind
the 4 million produced both by Volkswagen and DaimlerChrysler,
Peugeot faces the problem of trying to spread out the development
costs for new models over fewer vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, investors in Peugeot have been more than happy
about the merger speculation. Peugeot's stock jumped by 6 percent
on Tuesday and a further 1 percent Wednesday to reach 218.2 euros
per share.
</P>
<P>
   Peugeot and Daimler held extensive talks last fall about
collaborating on a new ``platform,'' or underlying blueprint, for
Daimler's troubled line of Smart subcompact two-seater cars. Those
talks broke off, apparently because of reservations by Daimler's
top executives, but they did not put end to Daimler's interest in a
full-scale acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor racing through Paris on Tuesday was that members of
the founding Peugeot family, who own 25.1 percent of the stock and
control 37.4 percent of the voting rights, had become more
receptive to a deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
