<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON17-COX     02-16 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TALKS OF STEPS TO COUNTER RISING OIL PRICES
 &HT;    610&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With oil prices bounding to a nine-year high,
President Clinton Wednesday became the first president since Jimmy
Carter to formally caution the nation on the subject of rising oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   In his first news conference of the new year, Clinton called for
$725 million in emergency aid to help poor people pay their heating
bills.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of other ways to fight a supply crunch that is already
driving up prices ast the gas pump, such as dispatching his energy
secretary to press world oil producers for production hikes and
possibly drawing down the nation's strategic oil reserve.
</P>
<P>
   In a throwback to the oil shocks of the 1970s, Clinton discussed
high-efficiency vehicles and exotic alternatives to petroleum-based
fuels. He even hinted at the possibility of government subsidies
for large energy users that switch to petroleum alternatives, such
as natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Support for those ideas was all but abandoned by the government
two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters that he has ordered Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson to produce, within 60 days, a report on measures the
government might undertake to help businesses and households reduce
their reliance on petroleum-based fuels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to examine ... what are the institutional barriers for
businesses and
</P>
<P>
   individuals converting away from home heating oil to heating
sources that are more commonly used in other places,'' Clinton
said. ``What are the costs? Are there any federal actions that
might be undertaken, in concert with the states or with the private
sector, to help minimize those costs and facilitate a conversion?''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson is also girding for a diplomatic mission to key
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)
in the coming weeks, to caution them against further production
curbs that have helped spark a tripling of oil prices over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   With prices surging this week to $30 a barrel _ their highest
since U.S. forces drove Iraqi troops from the oil fields of Kuwait
in 1991 _ Clinton said Richardson would caution OPEC members that
further increases could squeeze global growth, eventually crimping
demand for fuel and forcing down prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the price stayed up for any period of time, it would make
non-OPEC members who could produce oil more likely to do it, which
would further drive the price down,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the OPEC members understand that,'' Clinton said in
his wide-ranging White House press conference, ``and I think that
there is an interest in stable prices at an acceptable level.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the remarks during an hour-long press conference
touching on subjects ranging from international affairs to the
presidential primary races.
</P>
<P>
   On other subjects, Clinton said that:
</P>
<P>
   _ He is considering adding a visit to Pakistan, where a military
junta recently overthrew the democratically elected government,
when he journeys to neighboring India late next month.
</P>
<P>
   _ He is open to compromise with congressional Republicans on the
question of strengthening gun controls.
</P>
<P>
   _ Asked about attacks on his character by Republican
presidential candidates, he responded, ``people are really smart,
you know, and ... it's pretty hard to convince them that they
should hold anyone responsible for someone else's mistake,
particularly a personal mistake. I mean, I can't imagine any voter
ever doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he could vouch for the integrity of Vice President
Al Gore, the Democratic front-runner, Clinton said, ``He was always
brutally honest with me.'' He added, ``in all my dealings with him,
he has been candid in the extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, consumers have been hit with the highest
gasoline costs in a decade in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast and Middle Atlantic states, bitterly cold
weather has converged with rising prices for home heating oil to
make life miserable for low-income families, many of whom have been
forced to choose between heat and food.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had ordered the immediate release of $125
million in emergency fuel assistance for low-income families on top
of the $175 million already paid out since January.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton announced that he would send Congress a
request over the next week or so for an additional $600 million in
emergency funding for fuel oil assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a reporter's question, Clinton said he was
considering opening the spigot on the strategic oil reserve,
millions of barrels of crude oil stored underground in Louisiana as
a national security hedge against supply disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would await a response to Richardson's mission
to OPEC before assessing further action, but added, ``I wouldn't
rule out using the petroleum reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
