<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-GAMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Goodwill takes first winter step
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ The Goodwill Games wasn't even a glimmer in
Ted Turner's eye the last time the world came here for a major,
multi-sport winter event.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly 20 years ago, Eric Heiden and the ``Miracle on Ice''
Olympic hockey players skated through this small Adirondacks
village giving Americans reason to cheer. Then the U.S. boycotted
the Moscow Olympics, the Soviet Union retaliated by staying home
from the Los Angeles Games, and Turner decided the world needed a
little Goodwill in the international sports arena.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the 1986 Goodwill Games in Moscow, Turner's
Atlanta-based company has staged four summer events to provide
original programming for the TBS network. After nearly a decade of
discussing a cold-weather format, TBS will show the inaugural
Winter Goodwill Games today through Sunday. About 450 elite
athletes from 22 countries will compete, by invitation only, in 11
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the time was right for us to venture into the
winter arena,'' said Mike Plant, president of the Goodwill Games.
``There was really only one multi-sport event, the Winter
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Goodwill Games no longer considers itself an
alternative to the Olympics, but rather a complementary sporting
venture. Some of the events aren't the same, other traditional
winter sports have been left out completely, and it offers the
bonus of prize money.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes in 10 sports will compete for a pot
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
