<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNATIONAL SOCCER NOTES
 &HT;    More troubles for Maradona
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sad images of Diego Maradona beginning a treatment program
for drug abuse in Cuba last month apparently are only a small part
of the problems for the fallen Argentine idol.
</P>
<P>
   His former Barcelona teammate, Julio Alberto, told a Spanish
newspaper this week that the 1986 World Cup hero ``will die unless
he leaves Havana.''
</P>
<P>
   Maradona, 39, fled to a rehab facility in Cuba after being
hospitalized over the New Year with heart troubles that his
handlers initially denied had anything to do with drugs. But
Alberto, who recently visited Maradona, said his familiar
surrounding cast of friends and family members isn't doing him any
good in what might be his final chance to end a long-time
addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't find a cure where he is,'' Alberto said in an
interview in Sport newspaper. ``Where he is at the moment, with all
those people and friends, he's living the same life as before.''
</P>
<P>
   A bloated Maradona, who recently died his hair bright orange,
has less than half his heart capacity working because of the damage
done by drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Africa: Violence mars upset
</P>
<P>
   Even if Cameroon had not taken the African Nations Cup in
controversial fashion over homestanding Nigeria on Sunday, a
disturbance probably would have happened anyway. Cameroon won 4-3
on penalty kicks after the two teams were tied 2-2 after extra
time, and mini-rioting broke out quickly, as it had after nearly
every Nigeria match. Police fired tear gas into mobs in and around
the Surulere Stadium in Lagos to regain control. A penalty-kick
goal by Nigeria's Victor Ikpeba was waved off despite a replay that
showed the ball had crossed the line, which set off the initial
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Euro 2000: Hooligan pact signed
</P>
<P>
   Dutch, Belgian and German authorities signed an agreement this
week that provides police escorts for some fans traveling to and
from this summer's European Championships. Authorities will get a
dry run to try out some of the new measures Wednesday when Germany
plays The Netherlands in a friendly in Amsterdam. The two countries
have some of the most severe hooligan problems in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Cup: Americans advance
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. advanced to the quarterfinals of the CONCACAF Gold Cup
even before its final Group B match against Peru on Wednesday,
thanks to a 1-1 draw Monday between Peru and Haiti. The Americans
will play either Colombia or Honduras on Saturday at the Orange
Bowl in Miami.... Mexico, winners of the last three Gold Cups, is
rolling in Group C, thanks to a 4-0 pounding of Trinidad and Tobago
and is set in the quarterfinals on Sunday in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Comeback in Madrid
</P>
<P>
   Frighteningly close to the relegation zone after the holidays,
Real Madrid has found new life and now is in third place in the
Primera Division, after a 1-0 win over Valladolid on Tuesday.
Madrid, which made a coaching change and has been racked with
internal strife, is just four points behind leaders Deportivo La
Coruna.... Madrid's bitter enemy Barcelona is on a slide and has
earned only one point out of its last four matches, including a 2-1
defeat to Real Betis on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   England: Four teams charged
</P>
<P>
   Four Premier League teams have been charged with misconduct by
the Football Association because of on-field melees over the
weekend. Leeds defender Ian Harte was cited for stepping on a prone
Chris Perry of Tottenham, while Dennis Wise of Chelsea and
Wimbledon's Kenny Cunningham started a 20-player brawl after their
match Saturday. The British House of Commons has condemned the
incidents.... Manchester United has signed an endorsement deal of
nearly $30 million with British cell-phone company Vodafone; it is
believed to be a world record for a soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland: Celtic ousts Barnes
</P>
<P>
   After a humiliating loss to first division Inverness Caledonian
Thistle in the Scottish Cup, Celtic canned first-year manager John
Barnes after only eight months on the job. The former England and
Liverpool star came under intense scrutiny from the start, and had
an unhappy locker room to boot. He will be replaced by director of
football operations Kenny Dalglish with the club in second place in
the Premier League, six points behind Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: River coach quits
</P>
<P>
   Less than two days before the start of the Clausura (closing)
season last weekend, River Plate coach Ramon Diaz resigned, citing
the club's refusal to sign more players. River, which won the
Apertura title in December, features 18-year-old phenom Javier
Saviola, but Diaz wanted to provide him with more help. River won
four Argentine titles and the South American Copa Libertadores
crown under Diaz. On Sunday, the club defeated Cordoba 2-1 with a
caretaker manager.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
