<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY TO PLAY WITH DOMINATES TOY FAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn., Mass.) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ E-Specially My Barney, expected in stores by August,
comes with a cord so the purple plush figure can be plugged into
the nearest computer, where information can be downloaded daily
from a Web site and ``personalized'' for a particular child.
</P>
<P>
   A toy called V-Mail lets 5-year-olds send and receive their own
voicemail messages (they get PIN numbers, too). Then there is the
Kick Start Busy Crib Center, featuring a chirping electronic
lullaby activated when a baby whacks a colored part of the toy with
a foot.
</P>
<P>
   These are just a few of the latest offerings from the nation's
toymakers, who converged in New York for the annual ritual known as
Toy Fair, which ends Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At the five-day fair, the epochal event in the toy-selling
business, it was abundantly clear that technology had become an
essential component in toys for the nation's children. That is true
for toys intended for children practically from the moment of their
birth _ often reconfiguring the kinds of inanimate objects once
considered playthings and supplanting adult involvement in
activities like learning the A B C's and singing an infant to
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The trend appears to be breathing new life into toys whose sales
might otherwise have trailed off. The president of the Fisher-Price
unit of Mattel, Neil Friedman, estimated that three years ago, less
than 10 percent of the division's toys relied on any form of
electronics. This year, he said, more than 60 percent use some kind
of technology to deliver what he calls ``all the things we want for
the child and what the child wants for fun and enjoyment.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Toy Manufacturers of America, Peter Eio,
said at a news conference that ``the most surprising new category
to reflect the influence of technology is in the infant and
preschool segment,'' noting that sales of such toys grew 7 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon has its critics, though, with child-development
experts expressing concern that many of the newer electronic toys
have effectively eliminated the need to interact with another
person, either a too-busy parent or another child, and may
short-circuit a child's social and intellectual development.
</P>
<P>
   But defenders of the products counter that high-technology toys
merely reflect the times, that there is an advantage in being
exposed to technology early and that interactive toys open up a
wealth of possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are very toy-centered, as opposed to
child-centered,'' noted Dr. Timothy J. Kasser, an assistant
professor of psychology at Knox College in Galesburg, Ill., who has
studied the relationship between people's values and their
psychological states. ``We just got this Barney book, and it's a
book where my child wouldn't need me at all to read it to him. He
can press the buttons, and all the words come out.''
</P>
<P>
   The array is impressive. Diva Starz is a set of dolls from
Mattel that ``not only interact with each other, they can interact
with the girls, too,'' according to the showroom sales pitch. The
Intelli-Table, developed by Microsoft and Fisher-Price, promises to
teach children who press its buttons about colors, letters, numbers
and musical concepts _ the last with animal sounds, like the baaing
of sheep, set to snippets of a Mozart sonata.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a self-directed, self-rewarding process,'' said Erik
Strommen, a developmental psychologist who is on the Microsoft
research staff. ``In our testing, we saw 9-month-olds play with it
for 15 or 20 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   A talking McDonald's Happy Meal Drive-Thru from Hasbro, which
also makes the talking Barney and the Busy Crib Center, features a
computerized voice that asks, ``May I take your order?'' Toots the
Train, from Mattel, responds by opening its eyes when a child says
``go'' and makes comments of its own, like ``Gee, it's dark in
here!'' when inside a tunnel. Zip the Robot, a computer game for
5-year-olds from Oregon Scientific, announces, directly enough,
``Hi, I'm Zip, your robot friend inside the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Many toys, including old standbys like Barbie, now come with a
computer tie-in, either to a Web site or a CD-ROM, if not to a
television show that in some cases can be downloaded directly into
the toy.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is often borrowed from other industries. The
V-Mail toy, made by Toy Biz, uses telemetry once found only in
medical instruments, a company spokesman said. Companies like
Microsoft and IS Robotics have formed partnerships with toymakers,
applying the knowledge that drives adult-oriented businesses to
products aimed at younger consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The critics say there is nothing fun or gamelike about many of
the toys. ``My concern about all of these toys, whether it's a
Furby or an edutainment game, is that they tend to squash
creativity,'' said Michael Rich, a Boston pediatrician who is a
member of an American Academy of Pediatrics committee that tracks
children's use of television, computers and other electronic
entertainment. The committee recently recommended that children
under 2 not watch television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tends to lead them to look for a right response, rather
than to encourage the kind of free play that used to happen in the
sandbox with water and sticks,'' Rich said. ``It forces people into
predetermined decision pathways.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Toy Manufacturers of America, which
sponsors Toy Fair, said children's play had always reflected
society, and thus the increase in technology in toys was a mirror
of the rest of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are not losing something, they are gaining
something,'' said the spokeswoman, Terri Bartlett. ``They respond
faster, and their senses are heightened, because in society,
everything is coming at them faster.'' She added: ``We're all into
doing more things. The times they are spending on various types of
toys is being shortened. It's like they are multitasking with their
toys.''
</P>
<P>
   Some toy-store owners see the boom in high-tech playthings
helping, not hurting, particularly as the technology becomes more
sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to not carry anything with electronics because it came
back for returns 70 percent of the time,'' said Cynthia Gerdes, who
owns a six-store chain called Creative Kidstuff in the Minneapolis
area. ``But something has really changed in the last 12 months. I
just saw a toy called the Babbler, a soft toy that babies can play
with. When they hit it, the pads light up and babble in Japanese,
French, English and Spanish. It's a wonderful cause-and-effect
toy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Gerdes said, technology seemed to drive the toys,
but she considers some newly developed toys to be more thoughtful.
``Finally, it's making sense,'' she said. ``Every year there has
been something out there that scares me. When I went to my first
vendor in 1982, he said to me, `Here's the section of shut-up toys.
That's the stuff that appeases kids, and they will leave you
alone.'''
</P>
<P>
   At Hasbro, the Barney toy with its computer connection was
developed so that parents could continually enhance Barney for
their children, said Lorrie Browning, a vice president of
marketing. ``We are giving Mom the tool to be the thrill-maker,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company believes that technology should support existing
patterns of play, Browning added. ``Parents believe that children
learn through play,'' she said, ``and as their experiences outside
the home become advanced, the experiences we provide at home with
toys need to keep pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, child-development experts say that a steady diet of
electronic toys can lead to boredom, isolation and worse. ``The
real essential element that seems to cause children's development
to unfurl is love and a feeling of warmth and relationship,'' said
Mary Pipher, a clinical psychologist who is the author of
``Reviving Ophelia'' and ``The Shelter of Each Other,'' studies of
contemporary family life.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``With all children, and especially teen-agers, it's all about
social development,'' she added. ``The kids who are the least
competent are the ones who are most likely to withdraw into
machines. They miss a real critical phase in terms of learning the
kinds of social skills we have to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Taylor, executive director of the Center for a New
American Dream, a Washington nonprofit group that promotes
``responsible consumption,'' said technology-based toys were
interfering with children's natural abilities, even as parents
believed they were providing their children with important learning
tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the love affair with technology and computer microchips,
we're actually dumbing-down our children's play,'' she said. ``We
are disconnecting children from the play opportunities that really
let them use the endless creativity that young children have.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers who worry about children's short attention spans may
have such toys to blame, the critics say. ``Many of the things you
learn in school are not easy, on-off or right-wrong answers,'' Rich
said. Electronic toys can instill a desire for instant
gratification and easy victory, and that can become an issue in the
classroom. ``It creates learned attention deficit because children
become used to the constant stimulation.''
</P>
<P>
   One expert said there was no substitute for parental
involvement, even if toys suggest otherwise. ``Parenting is a
time-based function,'' said Donald Shifrin, a Seattle pediatrician
who is also a member of Rich's committee. ``You are the door the
youngster will walk through on his way to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   So pervasive is technology's influence on the toy industry that
even bland board games have been swept up in the trend. Some have
been remade in electronic hand-held forms, and others have been
converted for online play.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the old-fashioned game of Life, invented 40 years
ago and updated by Hasbro for the present age. It is still in board
form, but now the squares are marked with requirements like ``Have
Web site designed _ pay $45,000.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
