<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECKFREE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CheckFree Net billing now on top
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Far less than 1 percent of the companies that send you
bills do so through the Internet. The other 99 percent print a
paper bill, stuff it in an envelope and pay someone to stick it in
your mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   Until late Tuesday, two companies were jostling to
electronically link companies and their customers, to take the
paper and some of the cost out of the billing and bill-paying
industry.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree's plan to buy rival TransPoint for more than $1
billion in stock would leave the Norcross, Ga., company alone on
top and poised to grab the largest chunk of that 99 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, investors treated CheckFree as that kind of leader
in an industry with serious potential. CheckFree shares hit a
52-week high of $125.62 1/2. They finished a manic day up about 47
percent, or $32, closing at $100.25.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 16 million shares traded hands, more than 13 times the
average daily volume over the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This move makes CheckFree the Microsoft of the bill payment
and processing industry, essentially. If you could invest in that,
you would, too,'' said Avivah Litan, who follows the industry for
GartnerGroup. ``This industry will take off. There are no
competitors to speak of, and CheckFree is going to dominate it.
There's no doubt now.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal, expected to close within six months, calls for
CheckFree to issue 17 million shares. Based on Tuesday's closing
price of $68.25, the deal was worth about $1.16 billion. Investors
added more than half a billion in paper value to those shares by
the close of the market Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree shares traded above $100 at the end of 1999. As
recently as Jan. 31, they were selling for less than $60.
</P>
<P>
   The three heads of the companies most involved in the deal,
CheckFree, Microsoft and First Data, said the acquisition would
speed the rate at which consumers and billers would start using the
service in substantial numbers. When the deal closes, TransPoint's
investors will own 23 percent of CheckFree.
</P>
<P>
   More than 350 billers, including phone companies, utilities and
banks, and 3 million consumers use CheckFree to deliver bills and
payments. But the technology has yet to take off, partly because
billers had to choose between CheckFree and TransPoint, each with
its own technology.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Kight, CheckFree's 43-year-old chairman and chief
executive, said the acquisition was motivated by billers, some of
whom did not like having to choose between or adopt two technology
platforms to reach customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the ones who changed our thinking in terms of not
always thinking competitively,'' Kight said.
</P>
<P>
   Kight said the acquisition should increase the speed at which
receiving and paying bills on the Internet becomes as functional
and widely used a tool as e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this merger is going to bring people's bills to them
electronically much faster than if we hadn't done it,'' Kight said.
``Everybody's been reading and hearing about e-commerce. Electronic
bill payment and presentment is really about `me commerce.' It
enables billers and consumers to get exactly what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree plans to be able to deliver at least four bills to the
average consumer through the Internet by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   GartnerGroup's Litan said CheckFree will have a bit of a grace
period in which to produce. She said the company will need to
double, to 6 million, the number of subscribers by next February.
</P>
<P>
   ``CheckFree is it for the time being,'' said Litan. ``They still
have to produce now. They still have to show some numbers. If they
don't generate adoption in the next year, I think the market will
hurt them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
