r s BC-BBN-BRAVES-COX     02-16 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plenty of concerns for Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Braves pitchers and catchers will
arrive at the spring training complex at Disney today _ with one
notable exception.
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Rocker will be absent, and the Braves are hoping
that they can focus on the other issues at hand. They have plenty
to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues at hand are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gauging Andres Galarraga's comeback bid from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Incorporating new left fielder Reggie Sanders, second baseman
Quilvio Veras and backup first baseman Wally Joyner into the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   _ Filling in the bullpen gaps, to work around Rocker's absence.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monitoring the health and well-being of Kerry Ligtenberg, Rudy
Seanez, Javy Lopez and, more recently, Eddie Perez, who had
offseason shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Settling on a fifth starter.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers and catchers begin their workouts Friday. The goal is
to be in throwing shape before spring-training games begin on March
2 with an exhibition against the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the team will report Tuesday, with full squad
workouts to begin Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg and Chipper Jones were among the early arrivals,
dropping by the complex on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the 1999 National League MVP, has been in his native
Florida working out, in preparation to try to put up another
MVP-caliber season.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg was cleared by Dr. James Andrews last week to aim for
being ready by Opening Day. He continues his progress toward
throwing at full strength, to complete his almost year-old
rehabilitation from Tommy John surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga will join the Braves pitchers and catchers on
Friday, four days earlier than when the rest of the position
players report. Galarraga, who weighs just five pounds more than
his usual playing weight, has been swinging a bat since December,
but he hasn't faced live pitching in almost 1 1/2 years. How he
will respond is one of the spring's most intriguing questions.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez was hard at work long before he rejoined the team today.
Lopez, who missed half of 1999 with a knee injury, added exercise
equipment at his home in Atlanta and a batting cage in his
backyard. He is expected to be at full strength by the start of the
season, but his progress will be monitored. Asfor Rocker, his
greatest hope is that baseball arbitrator Shyam Das decides to
reduce his penalty, which might allow Rocker to report to spring
training. But that decision, and what happens with his month-long
suspension, is not expected until early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
