<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBS-CAMPAIGN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELSEY GRAMMER RAISING AWARENESS OF IRRITABLE BOWEL SYNDROME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Psychiatrists can talk about anything _ especially radio
psychiatrists twice removed, like Dr. Frasier Crane.
</P>
<P>
   Although he doesn't talk specifically about constipation,
diarrhea, bloating and excessive flatulence, Emmy Award winner
Kelsey Grammer has launched a public-education initiative to raise
awareness of irritable bowel syndrome, also known as spastic colon.
</P>
<P>
   Grammer and his wife, Camille, are making radio and TV
public-service announcements in cooperation with the International
Foundation for Functional Gastrointestinal Disorders. They hope to
make it easier for people to discuss their symptoms with their
doctors, relatives and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear much about IBS because some of the symptoms
involved relate to subjects traditionally considered taboo by the
public and the press,'' he says. ``However, it's important that we
help people get over their embarrassment. We need to be able to
talk openly about any medical condition that causes so many people
to suffer in silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Camille Grammer has IBS, which was diagnosed about 3 1/2 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBS impacts my life in so many ways,'' she says. ``I am always
fearful that my IBS symptoms will return at any moment, so I always
have to know where the nearest bathroom is. I'm afraid that eating
will result in stomach pain. Traveling is difficult. And IBS often
makes even a simple night out with my husband, to enjoy a concert
or movie, seem impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   IBS is a medical disorder that is estimated to affect as many as
20 percent of all adults in the United States, with female
sufferers outnumbering males by about three to one. IBS is one of
the 10 most frequently diagnosed conditions, more common than
asthma or diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The disorder is characterized by multiple symptoms that include
chronic, recurrent abdominal pain and discomfort and irregular
bowel function, including diarrhea, constipation or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I can remember, I've always had stomach and bowel
problems and have never really known what to do about it. I have
been amazed to learn how so many women have been suffering in the
same way. I hope that my efforts to speak openly about my condition
will encourage others to do the same and get the help they need,''
Camille Grammer says.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
