<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENTS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home improvement retailers to look at industry changes
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the economy at full steam, home improvement
products are hot sellers. Yet retailers are working harder than
ever at courting the housing market.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Atlanta-based Home Depot has revolutionized the
business of two-by-fours and hardware with its sprawling
warehouses, the industry seems to be remodeling itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is at a crossroads right now. As good as this
business has been, companies are going in different directions,''
said Don Longo, editor of National Home Center News, a trade
publication. ``We're seeing dramatic change, and innovation is the
main buzzword in the industry right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the industry's creative thinkers will gather today in
Orlando, Fla., at the trade publication's inaugural Innovators 2000
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward convenience is sure to be a hot topic.
Retailers in general have been trying to make their stores easier
to shop, and home improvement is following suit, Longo noted.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's new Villager's Hardware chain, which debuted last
year in New Jersey, will be the focus of a planned discussion on
the small-store trend in the industry, Longo said.
</P>
<P>
   Home improvement retailing has shaped up as two extremes:
warehouses and smaller, old-fashioned hardware stores, said Mike
Largent, president of Stambaugh Hardware, a regional Ohio-based
chain.
</P>
<P>
   Taking clues from Gap and Old Navy, Largent revamped his
hardware stores with wide aisles, varnished wood and nostalgic
touches like a rolling ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Female do-it-yourselfers prefer a cozy environment, said
Largent, who'll lead a discussion on small-store formats.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its Villager's Hardware concept, Home Depot has
been trying to tone down the clutter and noise in some warehouses.
A new store in Alpharetta, Ga., for example, provides quiet,
intimate areas along the walls for home decor, kitchen and bathroom
design.
</P>
<P>
   Villager's Hardware and Home Depot representatives are notably
absent from the conference, because of scheduling conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Another topic made more pertinent by Home Depot is forest
certification and the sale of ``environmentally friendly''
products. Those issues are growing more complex because the
industry hasn't agreed on environmental guidelines. Home Depot is
pushing vendors to phase out products from so-called endangered
forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take a look at how you market these
environmentally safe products to consumers and how you can be
profitable at each level of the supply chain,'' said John
Caulfield, executive editor of National Home Center News.
``Consumers and business are all in favor of the environment, but
when push comes to shove, it's hard to market these goods.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference ends Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
