<HEADER>
A9088 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH-MONEY-COX     02-16 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MONEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush campaign has spent $50 million
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. _ The George W. Bush presidential
campaign, which raised money last year at record levels, is now
spending it at record levels and will soon pump up efforts to
collect more.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials said Wednesday that they have spent more than
$50 million since the campaign set up shop 11 months ago. That
surpasses the record $42.2 million Bob Dole spent to win the GOP
nomination in 1996 and approaches the $66 million that wealthy
publisher Steve Forbes spent in 1996 and this year before dropping
out of the GOP race last week.
</P>
<P>
   So far, all Bush has to show for all that spending are Iowa and
Delaware primary wins tainted by the absence of prime foe John
McCain, and a crushing, campaign-changing loss to him in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Top Bush aides said Wednesday that the campaign finance report
to be filed next week will show that the campaign had $20 million
on hand as of Jan. 31. Total money raised will be about $73
million.
</P>
<P>
   When it became apparent that Bush was no longer the prohibitive
favorite in New Hampshire, the Bush campaign pumped up spending,
though officials won't say by how much.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got Plan A and Plan B,'' said Don Evans, Bush's
national finance chairman. ``Guess what, we're on Plan B.''
</P>
<P>
   A Texan who has raised more than $100,00 for the Bush campaign
said Wednesday of the spending, ``It's shocking. It is shocking.''
He also said Bush campaign officials have been very tight-lipped
when asked about how things are going in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said he is not concerned because his campaign is
spending ``for the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides said the Arizona senator has spent about $26
million and had $10 million on hand as of Jan. 31. McCain,
campaigning Wednesday in Columbia, S.C., said Bush's spending is
``a remarkable expenditure, but we can overcome that.''
</P>
<P>
   His spokesman, Rick Davis, said the spending has minimized the
importance of Bush's record-breaking war chest. ``It's dwindling
down to being not a significant advantage,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, Saturday's South Carolina primary is the most
crucial contest on the political calendar. It is quickly followed
by contests in Michigan and Arizona next Tuesday. McCain wins in
all three states could severely damage Bush's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wins, however, would go a long way toward comforting
supporters _ including ``pioneers'' who each raised more than
$100,000 _ who are becoming concerned about Bush's ability to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to win South Carolina,'' said Bush spokeswoman
Karen Hughes. ``That's what we are going to do to stop that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he remains comfortable with his strategy, a nationwide
effort far different that McCain's targeted campaign. McCain has
concentrated only on South Carolina, Michigan and Arizona, as well
as New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a plan in place that's going to enable me to stay in
this race for the long run,'' Bush said. ``We have been fighting in
every primary state. We're on plan, and I think I've got a good
chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his spending total is high because it includes TV ad
buys in 14 states and Washington D.C. as he competes in all
primaries, while McCain picks and chooses. The return on investment
will come, Bush campaign officials believe, when he starts piling
up wins in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush TV ads began running in expensive California markets on
Tuesday. McCain also is running ads in California, which holds its
key primary on March 7 along with 11 other states.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan now includes going back into fund-raising mode in
March and April, assuming _ as Bush does _ that he will have the
nomination clinched by then. But campaign officials insist that has
always been the plan. They deny that the record spending levels
have forced them to add fund-raising efforts and events to the game
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a contingency budget we had outlined in the eventuality
that we lost New Hampshire in which we would beef up advertising
and voter advocacy in other states,'' Hughes said. ``That's exactly
what we're doing. We are on budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's long-range plan was aimed at clinching the nomination as
early as possible and then having enough money left to continue
campaigning through the Republican National Convention in August.
To that end, and as a result of the record fund-raising efforts,
Bush is not accepting federal matching funds for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, eventual nominee Dole took the matching money for the
primaries and ran out of cash shortly after he clinched the
nomination. His campaign shut down until the federal money began
flowing after the national convention for the general election
race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will take federal money for the general election but is
concerned that Vice President Al Gore, whom Bush believes will be
the Democratic nominee, will be able to use his office to campaign
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the Bush campaign has spent $3.1 million on TV ads
in South Carolina and believes McCain has spent $2.8 million.
Because he is taking federal matching money, McCain is subject to a
$1.5 million spending cap here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In return for taxpayers' money, candidates ought to conform to
the rules,'' Bush said. ``No candidate should be above the rules,
and Senator McCain needs to explain, if in fact he has busted the
spending cap in South Carolina, how on one hand you can be a
campaign funding reformer and on the other hand not live within the
spending caps.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's political director, John Weaver, said federal rules
allow spending of about $3 million on South Carolina, including
television and radio ad buys in neighboring states that are seen by
South Carolinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a dime under (federal spending caps) in New Hampshire,
and we will be a nickel under here,'' Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
