<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-REACT-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE FARMERS' GROUP QUIET AFTER A POLITICAL VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ A day after helping forge a major political
victory over President Robert Mugabe, the Commercial Farmers Union,
which represents this country's biggest planters, was not bragging
_ or even talking.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which represents 4,000 commercial growers, most of
them white, no doubt was relieved that voters here rejected a draft
constitution that would have given the government the right to
seize white-owned land without compensation. But the union also
realizes that the issue of land reform is not going away, so
boasting about the vote now could make the situation ahead even
more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are just sitting back now and waiting to see what
happens,'' said Ian Goggin, administrator of the Zimbabwe
Agricultural Commodity Exchange. ``No one wants to antagonize
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of the country's major players, Wednesday was a day for
taking stock of the political landscape, which was dramatically
reshaped this week when the proposed constitution championed by
Mugabe was voted down. For the 75-year-old former freedom fighter,
it was the biggest defeat of his political career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has been a rude awakening for them, and now they
are trying to strategize,'' said Morgan Tsvangirai, president of
the Movement for Democratic Change, a new party that is expected to
mount a formidable challenge to the ruling party's dominance of
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The new party and its ally, the National Constitutional
Assembly, led the campaign against the constitution, which, they
contended, would have strengthened Mugabe's power. Seizing on
popular discontent with Mugabe and the country's crumbling economy,
the organizations drew thousands of unhappy urban voters to the
polls and won almost 55 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the results were announced, the silence of the
farmers' union seemed particularly conspicuous. Just a week ago,
the union was running newspaper ads that pointed out flaws in the
proposed constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But now the farmers realize that the vote was not for them, but
against Mugabe, whose popularity has waned as the country's economy
has been worn down by surging inflation and steep unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to gloat,'' said Sam Moyo, who has studied
land reform for two decades and who heads the Harare-based Southern
Africa Regional Institute for Policy Studies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whites here number only about 70,000, but among the country's
12.5 million people, they remain an influential part of the
economy. Nowhere is that more true than in agriculture, which
whites dominate and which, according to the World Bank, supplies
about 40 percent of the country's exports.
</P>
<P>
   The complexion of the agriculture business is a legacy of the
country's white-minority rule that set aside much of the most
fertile territory for whites. An international program to help the
government acquire some of the land and use it to resettle landless
peasants on small plots has been in the planning stage for more
than a year. But it has been hindered in part by the Zimbabwean
treasury's shortage of money.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for Zimbabwe to pay to acquire the land, while
international donors would pay the far larger costs of building the
farms' infrastructure and training new owners.
</P>
<P>
   But further complicating the plan has been Mugabe's proposal
that the government simply take the land _ just as it was taken
from blacks decades ago _ without any compensation. His plan has
particularly unsettled foreign investors that the country so
desperately needs to keep the economy afloat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
