<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9090 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ZONOLITE-EPA-BOS &LR;      02-16 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZONOLITE-EPA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA TO HANDLE ZONOLITE INSULATION CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE APPEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Flooded with telephone calls from nervous homeowners,
the federal Environmental Protection Agency is advising people with
questions about Zonolite Attic Insulation to call its Boston
office.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA toll-free number is 1-888-372-7341, available weekdays
between 8 a.m. and 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported this week that Zonolite Attic Insulation, a
popular product made by W.R. Grace Co. from 1963 to 1984, contains
asbestos, but that Grace officials fought to keep warning labels
off its product.
</P>
<P>
   Zonolite is a loose-fill insulation that was made from
vermiculite, a mineral, and is gold-colored and shaped like small
pieces of bark. The vermiculite that Grace used in its Zonolite
came from a mine it owned in Libby, Mont. The mine also contained
asbestos, which was embedded in the vermiculite. Grace removed
some, but not all of the asbestos in the vermiculite it used in its
attic insulation, documents obtained by the Globe show. Vermiculite
from other mines is used to make products such as cat litter and
potting soil; those mines do not appear to be similarly
contaminated, according to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's acting regional administrator also said the agency was
putting new information about vermiculite insulation on its web
site (www.epa.gov/region01/qa.html). Some of the EPA's advice:
</P>
<P>
   --If you know or suspect you have vermiculite insulation, you
may want to test it to see how much asbestos is in it. The EPA
recommends that you hire an asbestos consultant to do this, rather
than collecting the sample yourself. Call EPA's toll-free number
for a list of licensed consultants.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you do decide to collect the sample yourself, wet down the
insulation and wear gloves and a cloth face mask, the EPA advises.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you do contact a laboratory directly, use a laboratory
certified by the National Voluntary Laboratory Accreditation
Program. Call the EPA's toll-free number for a list.
</P>
<P>
   -- If the samples show asbestos and it appears that the fibers
may be entering the air in your home, you may want to then have the
air in your house tested, again by a licensed consultant.
</P>
<P>
   -- The decision as to whether to remove the insulation is up to
you, the EPA says. If the insulation is sealed behind walls or in
an enclosed attic, it may be best to leave it alone. The EPA
cautions that removal may cost thousands of dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
