<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-IVESTER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ivester may leave Coke ahead of schedule
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Doug Daft may be moving up to the top spots at
Coca-Cola sooner than expected as M. Douglas Ivester moves out.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement could come as early as today when the board of
directors meets in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Ben Deutsch said Wednesday that the company
had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, 52, was supposed to retire as chairman and chief
executive officer at the April 19 shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been maintaining an extremely low profile since the
Dec. 6 announcement of the intended leadership change. Since that
time, important company announcements have been made by Daft in his
current role as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the board names Daft as CEO on Thursday, that simply
formalizes what is now reality,'' said John Sicher, editor and
publisher of Beverage Digest. ``Doug Daft is running the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Daft has been remaking the company from top to bottom in hopes
of regaining momentum lost following several setbacks, including
depressed earnings and a European health scare. The 56-year-old
Australia native has restructured Coca-Cola by decentralizing
operations. He has moved more executives and decision-making from
the Atlanta headquarters to the local markets around the world
where Coca-Cola beverages are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization prompted the decision to cut 6,000 jobs from
the company's global work force. Already, the company has cut about
1,500 jobs in North America, primarily in Atlanta. On Tuesday,
about 500 of those workers lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, Daft's moves have not generated much enthusiasm
on Wall Street. Since Ivester stunned investors and employees with
the announcement that he would retire prematurely, the stock has
dropped more than 21 percent. It closed at $53.75, down $1.93 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   If Daft ascends to the top spots earlier than expected, then
Jack Stahl is also likely to replace Daft as president and chief
operating officer sooner than originally planned. Stahl, 46, was
supposed to get those jobs at the April shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
