A9097 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-AUDIT-NAT     02-16 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-AUDIT-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        FEDERAL AUDIT TO PROBE BIG DIG, HIGHWAY SPENDING
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Feb. 16 - A team of federal auditors will conduct a
financial examination of the Big Dig and other road and bridge
projects in the state before any more federal dollars are spent,
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater told Massachusetts lawmakers
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the discrepancy of the cost of the project, they
want a full and open disclosure on all the projects that are going
to be put to them before any money is released,'' Rep. J. Joseph
Moakley, D-South Boston, told reporters after a meeting with the
secretary. ``They want to make sure that the financial plan is one
that will fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Slater also told the lawmakers that he would reject any finance
plan from Big Dig officials that steals funds slated for other
Massachusetts road and bridge projects.
</P>
<P>
   Big Dig managers are to release a finance plan by March 15 that
takes into account recent overruns of $1.4 billion, bringing the
project to a total of $12.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Coming one day after Congress grilled him to probe whether Big
Dig officials misled auditors and broke any laws by doing so, the
secretary's pledges eased Massachusett's legislators' fears that
the over-budget Big Dig would threaten other projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that this is what has to be done in this
situation in order for the state to avail themselves of the federal
money that's already there,'' Moakley said.
</P>
<P>
   Moakley said the chances for criminal penalties to be placed on
Big Dig managers were slim. ``The inspector general told me (from)
everything he saw, there was no criminal or illegal actions going
on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Slater reportedly told the lawmakers he would do all that he
could to make sure the Big Dig would be finished on time by 2005,
and that no additional federal dollars would be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to continuing to discuss this matter with not
only your congressional delegation but also (with) the people who
are working on it at the state and local level,'' Slater told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors from the federal highway administration, who will
investigate the project on-site in Boston beginning next week, will
probe whether Massachusetts highway officials have been forthcoming
with spending amounts for all federally-funded highway projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been disagreement as to whether the state has not
(paid) its fair share (for the Big Dig), but (also) in terms of
non-Big Dig road and bridge work, whether those submissions have
been accurate,'' said Rep. William Delahunt, D-Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   Slater's decision to send outside overseers to conduct the audit
demonstrated an apparent distrust of the regional federal highway
administration already charged with overseeing the project, the
lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local people will not be involved in the audit,'' Moakley
said. ``So he (Slater) feels they need some fresh air into that
whole situation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James McGovern, D-Worcester, was less reserved in
criticizing the federal highway authorities in Massachusetts, who
have said they were unaware of the $1.4 billion in shortfalls.
``Clearly they could have done a better job,'' McGovern said.
</P>
<P>
   As Slater reviews a series of recommendations in a 57-page audit
of the Big Dig from the department's inspector general, he is
expected to announce specific actions he will take in days to come.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers said Slater would likely approve of the
recommendations in that audit, such as a call for increased
scrutiny into oversight of the Central Artery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether or not he'll add any to those,'' said
John F. Tierney, D-Peabody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
