<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-ROOKIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookies are along for the ride
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daytona Beach, Fla. _ Tony Stewart knows all about being a
rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 rookie of the year in NASCAR's Winston Cup circuit said
the challenges facing this year's bumper crop of novices will begin
long before the drop of the green flag.
</P>
<P>
   Finding your way in and out of the race track and making
required meetings on time can't be taken for granted, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR holds those (rookie driver) meetings early on Friday
morning, and the hardest thing to do is to make yourself get up to
be there on time,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   But once the side issues are out of the way, the eight rookies
entered in the Daytona 500 _Dale Earnhardt Jr., Matt Kenseth, Dave
Blaney, Stacy Compton, Scott Pruett, Mike Bliss, Jeff Fuller and Ed
Berrier _ have a lot to learn, despite success in other racing.
Earnhardt Jr., who comes to Winston Cup after winning two NASCAR
Busch Grand National titles, said the Daytona 500 is a bigger
challenge than he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of downplayed the difficulty of qualifying for the
Daytona 500,'' Earnhardt Jr. said. ``There's a lot more at stake
than I thought, and practice gets kind of hairy sometimes.... There
are a whole lot more gut checks these two weeks than we'll see the
rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the rookies have to learn the drill in NASCAR's top
class, most of them have extensive experience in other divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be listed as rookies, but they're not really
rookies,'' said Bill Elliott, driver of the No. 94 Ford. ``Take
Scott Pruett. He's been in IROC cars and in open-wheeled cars that
are a lot more advanced than the stuff we've got.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, they've got their work cut out for them _ all of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who won three races and finished fourth in points in
winning the rookie title, said he rates the current rookie class
``pretty high.''
</P>
<P>
   His accomplishments ``could be overshadowed pretty quickly this
year,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fuller is the oldest rookie at 42 and has endured a
month-long barrage of questions and jokes about his sponsor,
Viagra. The former Modified racer from Auburn, Mass., has taken the
Viagra comments in stride, but he prefers to talk about his race
car and about being at Daytona as a driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everybody's dream to finally make it to this league,''
Fuller said. ``It took me 26 years to do it, but it's nice to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuller wrecked his primary car in a practice incident with Greg
Sacks but is soldiering on with a back-up. ``For the most part,
everything is going according to plans,'' he said. ``I hope this
all pays off.''
</P>
<P>
   Berrier was a late addition to the rookie field. He came up with
an 11th-hour plan to drive the No. 90 Ford that belongs to veteran
car-owner Junie Donlavey.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get an opportunity, you have to make the best of
it,'' Berrier said. ``I've been coming here for 20 years, and I've
always wondered what it feels like.''
</P>
<P>
   And how does it feel? ``It's as tough as it gets,'' he said.
``I'll feel a lot better if I can get through (today's 125-mile
qualifying race) and get into the 500.''
</P>
<P>
   The two drivers who have gotten the most pre-season attention
are Earnhardt Jr. and Kenseth, his closest Busch Series challenger.
They are in adjoining stalls in the Winston Cup garage this week.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth, like most other rookies, isn't overly concerned with
what the other rookies are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're here to try to eventually be competitive at
Winston Cup and be able to run like we have in the Busch,'' Kenseth
said. ``My main goal is to qualify for these races and try to
complete as many miles as we can, so we can learn and go back to
these tracks for the second time and be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. and many veteran drivers say the first race
probably won't be a true indicator of who's the top rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daytona isn't necessarily the best place to use as a measuring
stick,'' Earnhardt Jr. said. ``I think after about five or 10 races
you'll have a good idea of which team has jelled the quickest -_
and we're all pretty much good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
