<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9101 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-HOTSPORT-TIGER-CO     02-16 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOTSPORT-TIGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger effect: Attention dividend for Tour
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are they angry with Tiger Woods for dominating their tour? Was
there a pre-Buick Invitational meeting last week where the players
banded together over a bonfire of burning range balls and pledged
to beat him?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Other players on the PGA Tour are envious of Woods; a few of
them are even outwardly jealous. But the grousing among the ranks
can't amount to much, because they all benefit hugely from what the
24-year-old phenom has accomplished and will continue to do.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour's last TV contract was the richest by far in
history, and every round of every tournament is televised.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the ``Tiger Effect'' significantly affected
contract negotiations with the networks, and now it's even
stronger. Purses are bulging. Crowds are filling entrance roads
when Woods is in contention. Young people are jamming the fairways
in record numbers. Concession stands are overflowing. TV ratings
are up significantly when Woods plays. The 8.4 rating from San
Diego on Sunday was the highest for a regular PGA Tour event since
1987.
</P>
<P>
   When a Kirk Triplett starts to benefit from the Tiger Effect,
it's widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about Tiger,'' a smiling Triplett, who has yet to
win a tour event, said after a second-round 64 at the Buick. ``I
think it's great to see. I think it's great having all you (media)
guys here, all this interest. I love picking up USA Today and
(having golf) right there on the front page _ not the sports
page.... You turn on the TV and see David Duval doing commercials
for AT&AMP;T during prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fantastic. I mean, everybody thinks golf is a really
neat, great game, and they're excited about it. And a lot of it is
because of Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   It is only February, after all. Much of the nation is still
battling winter and remains two months from even thinking about
playing golf. But here was golf, and Woods, last week representing
the biggest story in sports, as he went for a seventh victory in a
row. The last time golf got so many people interested, Woods won
the Masters by 12 shots in 1997. Before that, Jack Nicklaus won the
1986 Masters at age 46.
</P>
<P>
   It will be like this all year. When Woods gets to the Masters,
April 6-9, he might have won a couple of more times, and the media
zoo will be seen in record proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in San Diego, Woods added about 10,000 fans per day.
The media assemblage grew from 100 to 300 after he won at Pebble
Beach and headed to Southern California. Usually, a half dozen
people are writing late in the day in the Buick Invitational press
room. This year, 10 times were.
</P>
<P>
   When Phil Mickelson managed to beat Woods on Sunday, he was
quick to point out the impact of The Streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Tiger has played the last six events, and prior to
that, he has generated a lot of interest for the game of golf,''
Mickelson said. ``Galleries were so large this week, they couldn't
accommodate it, parking-wise. And I'm a beneficiary of that.... I'm
making more money because Tiger is helping increase these purses.
He's creating more excitement in the game of golf, and all the
players are beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully for the other players, Woods doesn't play every week.
He's at the Nissan Open in Los Angeles beginning today at Riviera
Country Club and then will play next week at the Andersen
Consulting Match Play Championship in Carlsbad, Calif. But he will
skip two weeks and return for the Bay Hill Invitational and The
Players Championship before taking a week off before the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   But now every tournament wants Woods more than ever, and the
events that don't get him might start to resemble tennis
tournaments where Pete Sampras or Andre Agassi don't play. When
Woods failed to defend his title at the BellSouth Classic in 1999,
the tournament still sold out and raised record charity numbers,
but the TV ratings were off from the previous year. In fact, in the
10 tournaments last year with the biggest TV audiences, Woods was
in contention in all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have an incremental advantage of the extra eyes on
television, the extra tickets, which is what Tiger brings,'' PGA
Tour commissioner Tim Finchem said. ``But he has uplifted interest
in the entire sport, and that is paying dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   Such players asDuval, who returned to the tour this year with
the body-fat of a bicyclist, have sought their own edge. In this
country and with the world's other tours, players have been forced
to either improve or get out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it might be good for the game of golf,'' Spain's Jose
Maria Olazabal said. ``I think it's going to make us try harder and
work harder, to take our games to a higher level, so we can compete
against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
