<HEADER>
A9102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-IVORY-COAST17-COX     02-16 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVORY-COAST17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aid urged to nurture democracy in Ivory Coast
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Alassane Ouattara, the former prime minister of Ivory
Coast, places enormous faith in democracy. It can, he says, spur
economic growth, calm ethnic strife, reduce corruption and even
slow the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite all that, Ouattara is glad that a coup in December
forced his country's president out of office. Why? Because he
thinks the coup will help, rather than hinder, democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the wrong act for the right reason,'' Ouattara said.
With the ouster of President Henri Konan Bedie, whose government
Ouattara called corrupt and repressive, an obstacle to democracy
has been removed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bedie, who assumed office in 1993 upon the death of 33-year
President Felix Houphouet-Boigny, was re-elected in 1995 with a
startling 96 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ouattara plans to run for president in elections the new
government has promised to hold this year. The ousted president had
declared Ouattara ineligible to run because his father was born
outside Ivory Coast, but Ouattara said he and both of his parents
were born in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Ouattara said he had no involvement in the coup, and no advance
notice that it was afoot.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the United States last week to tell U.S. officials
and representatives of nongovernmental organizations that aid to
Ivory Coast needs to continue to ensure that the country's
transition to democracy is successful and quick.
</P>
<P>
   After the coup, which took place on Christmas Eve, the U.S.
government automatically cut off all aid to Ivory Coast. Ouattara
said that is understandable, but he hopes the United States will
use its influence with international lenders to allow Ivory Coast
to suspend payments on its debts for six months or so, until a new
government _ and a new economic plan _ can be put in place.
</P>
<P>
   Ouattara, a former deputy managing director of the International
Monetary Fund, came to Atlanta to make his case on CNN and to ask
the Carter Center to monitor the elections, which are scheduled to
be held no later than October.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Carter Center promised to make a favorable
recommendation to former President Jimmy Carter, Ouattara said.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the coup, Ivory Coast _ a West African country a little
more than twice the size of Georgia, with a population of 16
million people _ had been seen as an island of stability in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Ouattara said it can be that again. The divisions promoted by
the Bedie regime can be healed, he said, adding that the economy
can be revitalized and the per capita income, about $800, can be
doubled in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   If democracy takes hold.
</P>
<P>
   But judging from his visit to Atlanta, Ouattara's self-appointed
primary task of unifying the country may prove difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Divisions among his supporters emerged as different factions
here struggled for control of his agenda. At least one Atlanta
reporter was called repeatedly by different people claiming to
represent Ouattara, each of whom advised the reporter to pay no
attention to the others.
</P>
<P>
   The competition continued even as Ouattara arrived at Hartsfield
International Airport, where, said one person involved in
coordinating the visit, the former prime minister was met by
several limousines.
</P>
<P>
   On other matters, Ouattara said:
</P>
<P>
   _ AIDS poses a major threat to economic development in Ivory
Coast. One of every 10 Ivorians tests positive for HIV, he said.
But he said democracy would lead to reduced corruption _ and
international donations for health care would not be diverted, as
they have been in the past.
</P>
<P>
   _ The war in Congo poses a very serious threat to stability and
economic development of Africa. ``The country is important; it is
at the heart of Africa; it has, what, eight or nine bordering
countries,'' he said. ``It's a very rich country. It has 50 million
people _ 20 percent of the population of sub-Saharan Africa. So
it's very important for us to have a stable Congo leading to a
democratic and developed Congo.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The ethnic conflicts that have bedeviled many countries in
Africa can be overcome through ``participative democracy,'' he
said. ``If you look at how these ethnic conflicts erupted, in each
country it's been because there was an attempt by a group to
exclude the other. So it has to be an inclusive democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Despite the wars that seem to stymie economic development in
many parts of Africa, the continent has seen progress in the last
10 years, both politically and economically.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have more countries where elections are considered fairer
and more transparent than five or 10 years ago,'' he said. ``You
have multiparty systems in nearly all countries in Africa. Ten
years ago, you did not have that.
</P>
<P>
   ``And on the economic front, you had fairly good developments,
both in terms of growth (and) in terms of inflation reduction. ...
Privatization is no longer a dirty word in any country in Africa.
Ten years ago, when I was prime minister ... my gosh, in 1990, when
we were trying to privatize the electricity company, they would cut
electricity from my home for two days, the trade unions, so it was
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
