u i BC-IRELAND-PEACE-BOS &LR;      02-16 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEETING OF ULSTER LEADERS POINTS UP DIFFERENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British and Irish prime ministers brought the main
parties in Northern Ireland together Tuesday in an exercise that
served mainly to show how far apart they remain on the vexing
questions of disarming the Irish Republican Army and restoring
Belfast's power-sharing government.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart,
Bertie Ahern, emerged from several hours of meetings at 10 Downing
St., their glum faces offering clear evidence that no progress had
been made on the stalemate that led Blair's administration to
suspend the power-sharing government last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came less than 24 hours after the IRA responded to
the suspension by breaking off contact with an international
commission overseeing the disarming of Northern Ireland's
paramilitary groups. The IRA also withdrew its offer to eventually
put its weapons ``beyond use.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Ahern faced reporters after the talks, and Blair
sought to lower expectations for a quick solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today wasn't the day we were going to do anything other than
discuss what the parameters of the problem were and how to resolve
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern said he wanted to reestablish as soon as possible the
power-sharing government and the cross-border authorities that give
his government a direct role in the affairs of Northern Ireland.
But he offered no solution on how to accomplish that.
</P>
<P>
   Establishment of the short-lived government that includes
Catholic and Protestant parties was a key element of the 1998 Good
Friday Agreement that sought to end decades of sectarian strife in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   There was little evidence to suggest that the British and Irish
governments had repaired the rift between them over the
circumstances that led London to suspend the two-month old Belfast
regime. Dublin believed a last-minute offer by the IRA to discuss
when it would put its weapons ``beyond use'' was enough to avert
suspension, but London pulled the plug anyway, saying the IRA
pledge was too vague to prevent the Ulster Unionist Party from
walking out of the Northern Ireland assembly.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of any substantive progress, recrimination was
the order of the day. Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble blamed
Irish republicans for the impasse, saying they had refused to come
through with a gesture on weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The onus rests on them. They had an obligation and they failed
to deliver,'' said Trimble, who had vowed to resign as leader of
the power-sharing government if the British government did not
suspend it. The British suspended the Northern Ireland assembly and
cabinet rather than see it collapse, hoping it would be easier that
way to resume if the stalemate is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Martin McGuinness, Sinn Fein's chief negotiator, who lost his
post as education minister when the government was suspended, said
the power to revive the peace process lay mostly with the British
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Good Friday Agreement is lying in a waste paper bin. The
British government needs to get it out, put it back together again
and be serious about the process of conflict resolution in
Ireland,'' McGuinness said.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams said his party, which has close
links to the IRA, could do no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any notion that cajoling, coaxing, pressuring people like us
to get the IRA to do something, when the IRA moved so far only to
have it rejected, is just nonsense,'' said Adams. ``It wasn't us
that pulled down these institutions and it wasn't us that walked
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gloom, there was no suggestion the IRA, or their
loyalist enemies, were about to end the cease-fires that have
underpinned the peace process. But neither was there any indication
that either government had devised a route out of the impasse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
