<SLUG> BC-FUEL-AID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT RELEASES $125M IN FUNDS TO HELP FUEL POOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Tuesday ordered the release of
$125 million in emergency funds to help low- and middle-income
families pay for home heating oil, which has been exhorbitantly
expensive for New Englanders this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``These families have been especially hard hit,'' Clinton said
at a White House news conference. ``That is a serious concern,
because the winter months have been colder this year than in the
past few years.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of the funds depletes for the year the $300 million
allotted to provide not just heating aid, but also money to help
residents in warm-weather states deal with unusually hot summers.
The president said he would ask Congress to set aside another $600
million in supplemental assistance to deal with temperature-related
crises later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the new release of funds, Massachusetts will get
another $13.1 million for the Low Income Home Energy Assistance
Program, on top of the $13.6 million the state has already received
this winter. Maine is set to get another $6.3 million; New
Hampshire, $3 million; Rhode Island, $2.8 million; Vermont, $1.4
million; and Connecticut, $5.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic,'' said Robert Coard, president of Action for
Boston Community Development, a non-profit organization that
funnels the LIHEAP money to qualifying families in the metro area.
``A lot of folks have already exhausted their benefit levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization has been able to provide an average of $660 in
heating assistance to Boston area families this winter and now can
add another $300 to $400 to defray average heating bills of $1,400
to $1,500 for the season, Coard said.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging news conference, Clinton's first of the year,
the president handled questions from the death penalty to the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he does not support a federal moratorium on the
death penalty, although he lauded as ``courageous'' Illinois
Governor George Ryan's decision to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan suspended executions in Illinois until authorities
determine if capital punishment there is administered fairly.
Thirteen death-row inmates in Illinois have been exonerated in
Illinois since 1987 as a result of further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Governor Ryan did the right thing, and it was probably
a courageous thing to do because a majority of American people
support capital punishment, as do I,'' Clinton said. But he said
there are not grounds for a federal moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton drew ire from death penalty opponents in 1992, when he
was governor of Arkansas and in a competitive presidential primary
race in New Hampshire. Clinton interrupted his campaign to fly back
to Arkansas to sign a death warrant for Ricky Ray Rector, a
mentally retarded man.
</P>
<P>
   On questions about the presidential campaign, Clinton brushed
off the sniping among the candidates in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton chuckled when asked how he felt when Texas Governor
George W. Bush told Senator John McCain of Arizona that having his
honesty and integrity compared to Clinton's was ``about as low as
you can get'' in the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, they're playing to an electorate most of whom did
not vote for me,'' Clinton said, smiling. ``And secondly, I have a
lot of sympathy with Governor Bush and Senator McCain. I mean, it's
hard for them to figure out what to run on. They can't run against
the longest economic expansion in history, or the lowest crime rate
in 30 years, or the progress America has made in promoting peace
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a tough job and I have a lot of sympathy with them
and I don't want to complicate their problems by saying anything
more about it,'' the president quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended his vice president, Al Gore, whose honesty has
been agreessively questioned by his Democratic opponent, former
Senator Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great strengths he has had as a vice president is
that he was always brutally honest with me,'' Clinton said. ``And I
think the country is better for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
