<SLUG> BC-DRUG-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENTLY-MERGED GLAXO WELLCOME AND SMITHKLINE BEECHAM CITE '99
EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The two British drug makers that merged in January to
create Glaxo SmithKline PLC, the world's largest pharmaceutical
company, posted their 1999 earnings Wednesday and demonstrated what
analysts called the necessity for the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo Wellcome PLC, which acquired SmithKline Beecham PLC for
$76 billion in January, said earnings rose just 3.8 percent on a 6
percent increase in sales.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline, by contrast, reported a 13 percent rise in earnings
on a 10 percent increase in sales.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons that Glaxo bought SmithKline was that it
hoped a link with the rival would help increase growth and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo's chairman, Richard Sykes, tried to offer assurances that
his company's relatively weak results were simply a blip. ``Our
message for shareholders is hold your nerve,'' he said. ``This is
potentially a very strong company.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the companies announced their merger, shares of both drug
makers have fallen. Shares of SmithKline shares dropped 3 percent
Wednesday, to 674 pence, or $10.84. Shares of Glaxo fell 3.3
percent, to 1,459 pence, or $23.47.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have suggested that the merger was necessary to keep
growth rates competitive with rival drug makers, though they said
they did not expect a significant jump in their combined growth
rate as a result of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Leschly, chief executive of SmithKline, showed off his
company's results Wednesday, saying, ``We're very excited about the
way we are now entering into the proposed merger with Glaxo
Wellcome as a very strong company.''
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline's profits for the year were 1.94 billion pounds, or
$3.10 billion, on sales of 7.75 billion pounds, or $12.4 billion.
Glaxo's profits were 2.772 billion pounds, or $4.44 billion, on
sales of 8.5 billion pounds, or $13.6 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
