<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9111 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-KOREA17-COX     02-16 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Korean residents rally to fight man's deportation
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Members of the Korean Community Presbyterian Church
were surprised a few years ago when one of their deacons got into a
drunken scuffle and went to prison. The truly shocking news,
however, came when the church learned a few months ago that the
federal government plans to deport Dong Jin Park because of a 1996
immigration law roundly criticized as unduly harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Worry about the deacon's predicament became the flash point for
the first well-organized political effort among the roughly 50,000
Korean immigrants in Georgia. Groups as diverse as the Korean
Literary Club and the Korean Chamber of Commerce of Georgia rallied
to help the deacon. Pastors of about 100 Korean churches in metro
Atlanta told his story as a cautionary tale. Shoppers in Korean
supermarkets signed petitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had this kind of unified voice,'' said the Rev. In
Soo Jung of the Korean Community Presbyterian Church.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 2, after months of meetings, advocates for the deacon
mailed a petition with 2,709 signatures to Gov. Roy Barnes and the
Georgia Board of Pardons and Parole. They want the board to pardon
Park, an action that would prevent his deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers also mailed the petition to members of Congress. They
want Congress to revise the 1996 law that lowered from five years
to one the minimum prison sentence that triggers deportation
proceedings against someone convicted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Other incidents in the last 10 years generated attention in the
Korean community, but the legal trouble facing Park has unified
Korean immigrants here as has no cause in recent memory. A few
years ago, for example, Koreans closely followed the story of a
Korean woman who was shot and killed at a beauty shop. They also
paid attention when a Korean grocer sued the city of Atlanta on the
grounds that the city failed to protect his store from looters in
the aftermath of the verdict in California in the Rodney King
police-beating case.
</P>
<P>
   But Korean activists said the possibility that the government
will deport Park has brought together a once-fractured community.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that 70 percent to 80 percent of Korean immigrants
in metro Atlanta are, like Park, legal residents and not U.S.
citizens. Many fear that they, too, could be deported if they get
into trouble with the law, said Eugene Kim, Korean Literary Club
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   After Kim learned more about the 1996 immigration law, he wrote
a column about it for a Korean newspaper in metro Atlanta. Before
long, he was talking about the law during meetings of the literary
club. Other club members began writing columns, too.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Choi, a Korean who heads metro Atlanta's Asian American
Coalition, said the law that led to deportation proceedings against
Park has broken up families through deportations, just as the
Korean War separated families in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are experiencing the same situation in peacetime in
America,'' he said. ``The community feels like it's harsh, it's not
just.''
</P>
<P>
   Other immigrant groups, as well as organizations such as the
American Bar Association, have vigorously opposed the 1996 law.
Hundreds of immigrants across the country have been deported for
relatively minor crimes, and even the Immigration and
Naturalization Service says the law should be changed.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of immigrants from metro Atlanta have been deported for
crimes such as shoplifting a sandwich, a box of doughnuts and a $15
baby outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie McConnell, a spokeswoman for the board of pardons and
paroles, said the state has pardoned a handful of immigrants
convicted of relatively minor crimes so that they would not be
deported. In the case of someone like Park convicted of a serious
violent felony, she said, a pardon would be very rare.
</P>
<P>
   Park, 46, came to the United States in 1979 and lived in Cobb
County with his wife, Han. He owned a camera repair business in
Smyrna. He and his wife have three teen-age daughters _ all U.S.
citizens _ who have played cello, violin and viola in the Atlanta
Symphony Youth Orchestra. Two girls played in the closing
ceremonies of the 1996 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Park ``is pretty much an exemplary churchgoer _ just one
mistake,'' the Rev. Jung said.
</P>
<P>
   About 3:30 a.m. on Jan. 17, 1996, police arrested Park after a
fight in the parking lot of a DeKalb County tavern. They charged
him with public drunkenness at first but upgraded the charges days
later to a felony, aggravated assault, after the victim complained
that the fight left him with a permanent eye injury.
</P>
<P>
   A jury convicted Park of aggravated assault, and a judge ordered
him to serve three years in prison and another four on probation.
That would not have been enough to trigger deportation before
Congress changed the law in 1996, said Bonnie Youn, former
president of the Georgia Asian Pacific American Bar Association.
She said Park started a Bible study group in prison and poses no
danger to society. His prison term expired last month, but he
remains behind bars. He's in INS custody awaiting a deportation
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Park's wife took over her husband's camera-repair business after
his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really unfair. Our children were born in the United
States. We lived here 20 years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Youn said many Korean immigrants were shocked to find a
well-respected businessman and church deacon in such a legal jam.
``When people realized he was facing permanent deportation, they
realized, `Look. We've got to do something,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Church members pray for Park on Wednesday and Friday evenings at
their church building. The church is the largest Korean
congregation in metro Atlanta, and its decision to throw its weight
behind Park also galvanized leaders in the wider Korean community.
</P>
<P>
   Last Oct. 27, Choi went to Washington, D.C., to deliver letters
about Park to members of Georgia's congressional delegation as well
as House and Senate leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The main goal of the petition drive is to persuade Congress to
reconsider changes made by the 1996 law. Another goal is to
persuade Georgia officials to pardon Park. Regardless of the
outcome in Park's case, Korean leaders said, the effort on his
behalf has made the state's Korean community more cohesive and has
given them a taste of political activism that could come in handy
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Alerted to Park's plight by Korean immigrants in metro Atlanta,
Korean groups in Albany, Augusta, Columbus, Hinesville, Macon and
Savannah supported the effort. And leaders in metro Atlanta already
have begun to channel the new activism in the direction of another
Korean immigrant facing deportation _ 23-year-old Un Ho Kim of
Gwinnett County.
</P>
<P>
   His trouble began Oct. 7, 1995, when he and a group of buddies
hatched a plan while eating burgers at 3 a.m. in a Denny's
restaurant. They were talking about a movie in which one of the
characters robs a store. They decided it would be fun to imitate
that character.
</P>
<P>
   They went to a convenience store. One of them pulled out a BB
gun while others stole candy. They drove off and were promptly
pulled over and arrested by Gwinnett County police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said `You're going to do 10 years in prison.' I thought
they were just playing around,'' Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded guilty to robbery by intimidation, a felony, and was
sentenced to two years in prison and four years on probation. An
immigration judge recently ordered him deported, but his attorney
is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Kim has not visited Korea since he was 4 and knows no one there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even hardly speak Korean,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
