<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-DRUGS-265&AMP;ADD-N     02-16 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-DRUGS-265&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN FIRM RAISES STAKE IN JAPANESE DRUG MAKER VIA HOSTILE BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A large German pharmaceutical company secured a foothold
in the Japanese drug industry Wednesday through a successful and
unsolicited takeover effort _ something still highly unusual in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase by Boehringer Ingelheim, made through a tender
offer to shareholders, raised its stake in SS Pharmaceutical to
35.86 percent. The move reflected the deregulation that is
reshaping Japan's drug industry, which has increased the ability of
foreign drugmakers to set up shop here and made domestic companies
vulnerable to outside competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of other Japanese drug producers have risen recently on
speculation that they, too, may become part of the industry's
global consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   SS Pharmaceutical had little advance notice. The two companies
have had a long relationship. Boehringer had a seat on SS
Pharmaceutical's 16-member board and already owned 19.61 percent of
its shares, but the bigger stake now will give it greater influence
over decision-making and the ability to veto any major initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having gained a holding of more than 33.4 percent'' _ the
level at which a shareholder gains a limited veto in Japan _ ``the
long-term security of our investment is therefore assured,'' said
Christoph Hohbach, chairman of Boehringer's Japanese subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Boehringer's success was extraordinary partly because of its
novelty in a country where hostile takeovers are rare. It stands in
marked contrast to the failure earlier this week of a widely
watched hostile attempt to acquire Shoei, a real estate holding
company and electronics parts manufacturer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yoshiaki Murakami, a former civil servant who started his own
takeover investment fund, had sought to gain control of Shoei but
fell far short of his goal, collecting only a 6.52 percent stake in
a tender offer.
</P>
<P>
   But there were differences between the two bids, the most
significant being the mix of shareholders. Shoei is a member of the
Fuyo group, or keiretsu, an agglomeration of companies clustered
around Fuji Bank and its sister financial companies and bound by
cross-shareholding. The group, which owned a collective 60 percent
of Shoei, refused to sell its shares, despite a 14 percent premium
Murakami offered.
</P>
<P>
   SS Pharmaceutical, by contrast, is not formally part of a
keiretsu, and so economic considerations prevailed among its
shareholders. In this case, ``this was a matter of going to a broad
spectrum of shareholders and soliciting support,'' said Dean A.
Yoost, head of the financial services advisory practice at
PricewaterhouseCoopers in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals accounted for 37 percent of SS Pharmaceutical
ownership before the tender offer, and a spokeswoman said the vast
majority of shares bought by Boehringer had been sold by
individuals. Corporate shareholders accounted for 29 percent, and
institutional shareholders like pension fund managers and banks,
for 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Boehringer also offered a much heftier premium, 42 percent over
the closing price the day before it made its offer. It sent
shareholders letters explaining its offer and urged them to call a
toll-free number for more information. Boehringer said its adviser,
Jardine Fleming, received thousands of calls, particularly after it
ran ads in local papers appealing to SS Pharmaceutical
shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
