<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NATO-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AND RUSSIA TO RESUME RELATIONS AFTER BREAK OVER KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a sign of his desire to cultivate closer ties with
the West, Acting President Vladimir Putin agreed Wednesday to end
an 11-month estrangement between Russia and NATO and rebuild what
the Kremlin called an alliance aimed at ``a stable and indivisible
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The thaw was announced after a meeting between Putin and NATO's
secretary-general, George Robertson. Formally, at least, it closes
a cavernous divide that opened last March after NATO launched its
air war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But there were few illusions that the resumed partnership
signals any genuine meeting of minds, given the depth of Russian
bitterness over NATO's conduct of the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Wednesday's agreement was seen as one more strategic
move by Putin to shore up relations with the West, the one place
where he can find the money, technology and expertise for
rebuilding Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Putin sent the chairman of the Russian Security Council, Sergei
Ivanov, to Washington Wednesday to discuss arms proliferation and a
potential summit meeting with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Russia struck a deal after almost 18 months of talks
with private Western lenders to reschedule $31.8 billion in bad
debt.
</P>
<P>
   The deal instantly lifted Russia's credit rating and improved
the climate for foreign investment, one of Putin's stated goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to create, let's say, a favorable environment for his
`Russia project,' if you like,'' said Dmitry Trenin, an expert at
the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace in Moscow. Trenin
suggested that Wednesday's agreement was in part a response to
unusually warm comments on Tuesday by Clinton, who praised Putin as
a leader he could work with and offered only muted criticism of
Russia's conduct of the Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's spokesman, James P. Rubin, said the
United States welcomes the accord and that Putin has indicated that
``he regards the centrality of U.S.-Russian relations as larger
than differences on key issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Russia and NATO have never been especially
cordial. The western alliance has continued to expand toward the
Russian border, effectively ignoring Moscow's objections, and
Russia has complained that it has never gotten the consultative
role in NATO affairs that the alliance had seemed to promise.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship fell apart completely last March when the NATO
attack on Yugoslavia led Russia to expel alliance representatives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Kosovo war was a watershed that made it acceptable for
Russian politicians and citizens alike to express long-concealed
suspicions of the West. The estrangement has only deepened as NATO
has criticized Russia's conduct in Chechnya. Both sides agreed to
abide by a 1997 agreement governing relations between NATO and
Russia, and to hew to the U.N. charter _ an apparent sop to Moscow,
which has complained vociferously that NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia
violated U.N. principles.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials stressed that the accord did not signal any
change in military policy in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has courted support from the military.But Robertson said
Wednesday that the decision to resume relations with NATO was
clearly Putin's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he shared my view that the chilly period should come
to an end,'' he said on the Russian television network NTV. ``I
think we've moved from the permafrost onto slightly softer
ground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
