<SLUG> BC-BELL-FINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL FACES FINES OVER DELAYED CALLING-SERVICE CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp. is facing $100,000-a-day fines from New York
state regulators unless it moves by Friday to clear up widespread
computer problems that have delayed thousands of people trying to
switch their local calling service to rivals such as AT&AMP;T Corp. and
MCI WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of an AT&AMP;T-supported group, the Massachusetts Coalition
for Competitive Phone Service, pounced Tuesday on the k
problems, saying they give further proof Bay State regulators
should move slowly if at all in allowing Bell Atlantic into the $2
billion long-distance calling market here.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, which has already acquired nearly 1 million New
York long-distance customers, hopes to get into the Massachusetts
market by this fall by persuading state regulators it has promoted
strong competition for local service.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Telecommunications Act of 1996, the regional Bell
companies are required to show they have opened their local markets
to competition before they can enter the long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on New York's disastrous results, Massachusetts should
proceed cautiously when reviewing Bell Atlantic's claim that it has
opened the local calling market to true competition for
consumers,'' said Michelle Consalvo, executive director of the
Massachusetts coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of New Yorkers have reportedly faced delays in
getting their local service switched over to Bell rivals. MCI
WorldCom estimated that up to 70,000 orders to switch service from
Bell to MCI Local were lost or mishandled by Bell Atlantic, almost
1 in 3 orders for new service.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Public Service Commission late Friday ordered the
phone giant to clear up the problems or face $100,000-a-day fines,
saying Bell's ``performance problems, if unabated . . . could
undermine'' local competition.
</P>
<P>
   Bell spokesman Jack Hoey said ``we're taking this very
seriously. There has been a problem, and we fully expect to meet
the deadline of Friday to complete all the back orders.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Hoey stressed it was a ``start-up paperwork glitch''
that involves how promptly rival carriers get notification that
prospective customers have been switched over to them, not delays
in actually moving people to AT&AMP;T or MCI WorldCom. He also noted
that $100,000 fines are the normal threat for any utility failing
to comply with a PSC order.
</P>
<P>
   While stopping short of accusing AT&AMP;T of hypocrisy, Hoey noted
that AT&AMP;T has faced similarly severe problems in Texas that led it
to rebate long-distance bills for 100,000 customers in December and
delay signing up new customers for its phone-over-cable service
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a surprise or a shock if there weren't some
start-up problems,'' Hoey said. He added that Bell has successfully
moved 400,000 customers to other local carriers, and competitors
now have 1.5 million local lines in New York, compared to Bell's 12
million.
</P>
<P>
   But given that Bell uses many of the same order-processing
systems in Massachusetts and New York, Consalvo said, ``We can save
Massachusetts consumers lots of worry and millions of dollars in
service disruptions, lost dial tone and business costs if we learn
from New York's mistakes.'' He urged that regulators move slowly in
allowing Bell into the Bay State long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts regulators have had no comment on how soon they
will send a recommendation to the Federal Communications Commission
on whether Bell Atlantic should be allowed into the long-distance
market here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2000EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-460&AMP;AD     02-16 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEZBOLLAH VOWS TO CONTINUE ATTACKS AGAINST ISRAELIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NABIH CHIT, Lebanon _ The leader of the Hezbollah guerrilla
movement said Wednesday that the organization's forces in southern
Lebanon would continue to kill Israeli soldiers despite a pledge by
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel to make an unconditional
withdrawal of Israel's forces from the area by July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, the Shiite Muslim cleric who is
secretary-general of Hezbollah, the Party of God, told 3,000
supporters in this village 45 miles east of Beirut that Hezbollah
would press attacks that began in late January and have killed
seven Israeli soldiers and wounded many others in less than three
weeks. Israel responded last week by bombing three Lebanese power
plants, which cut electricity in this nation of 3.5 million by 50
percent and wounded 20 Lebanese civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Islamic resistance is committed to killing more of the
enemy's soldiers and militiamen,'' Nasrallah said, referring to the
Israeli troops and their allies in the South Lebanon Army, a mainly
Christian militia force, who jointly control a nine-mile ``security
zone'' in southern Lebanon. ``Let them do whatever they want,
whatever the price is and the sacrifices are, we will do whatever
is necessary to liberate our land.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak has warned of ``severe'' retaliation if attacks on Israeli
troops continue. But Nasrallah said Hezbollah wanted to be sure
that the Israeli withdrawal did not result in new conditions
restraining Hezbollah's military arm. ``If we stop, Israel will
impose new conditions on us, and we reject any kind of dictation
from them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reference to the possibility of ``new conditions'' for
Hezbollah appeared to involve the stalled Israeli-Syrian peace
talks, and the possibility that Israel, if the talks resume, could
exact conditions relating to Hezbollah's future role in southern
Lebanon from Syria, which effectively controls Lebanon through a
35,000-man military force deployed in Lebanon. Until now, Syria has
rejected diplomatic appeals to rein in Hezbollah, saying it does
not control the group.
</P>
<P>
   In a further taunt, Nasrallah refused to rule out the renewed
use of Russian-made Katyusha rockets, the powerful but notoriously
inaccurate weapon that has caused numerous casualties among
civilians in northern Israel during the 15-year occupation of the
security zone. In its recent offensive, Hezbollah has relied on the
more traditional tactics of guerrilla warfare, including infantry
attacks on Israeli fortifications with mortars and anti-tank
missiles, ambushes of Israeli patrols and roadside bombs. A U.N.
patrol in southern Lebanon last week discovered an arsenal of 48
Katyushas deployed in a gully, one of the largest concentrations of
the rockets the U.N. has seen.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Barak knows that the Katyushas are still in the equation,''
Nasrallah said. Referring to the large-scale evacuation of
settlements in northern Israel during the recent Hezbollah
offensive, and the retreat to underground shelters by many other
settlers, Nasrallah added: ``The Israeli settlers whom he ordered
into the shelters for three days rotted because they knew there was
a possibility the Katyushas could fall at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Katyushas become predictable, they lose their
importance as a weapon. It would be a mistake if our enemy finds
out when we are going to use the Katyushas and when we are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasrallah's appearance Wednesday was considered a surprise,
because he has long been considered Israel's number one target in
Lebanon and had been thought unlikely to risk an Israeli attack. By
showing up and making a fiery speech, he appeared intent on
pressing home the triumphant message that Hezbollah has been
putting out in recent weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
