u f BC-CIGARETTE-ADS-BOS &LR;      02-16 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGARETTE-ADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY'S ANTI-SMOKING ADS STIR CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At first glance, a chance to create a national campaign
for antismoking ads seemed like a dream assignment, one of the
largest pieces of business ever awarded to a New England ad agency.
But five months after Arnold Communications of Boston landed the
job, the agency is in the midst of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   This week, two of the first four TV ads developed by a team of
ad agencies led by Arnold were pulled off the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unusual to have a finished spot rejected,'' said
Skip Pile of Pile and Co., a Boston firm that advises clients
looking to hire agencies.
</P>
<P>
   One ad showed body bags piled up outside the headquarters of
Philip Morris Cos. Another ad showed a teenager with a lie detector
pursuing a tobacco executive in search of the truth.
</P>
<P>
   For Arnold, the challenge can be expressed this way: How do you
create ads that grab the attention of teenagers but still can get
by network censors? How do you make antismoking ads that don't
elicit howls of protest from the tobacco companies that are
indirectly paying for them?
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it would seem that ads demonize the tobacco
companies as liars and killers are not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what could be going through the minds of those ad
agencies,'' said Sue Parenio, an associate professor who teaches
advertising at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Body-bag and lie-detector ads seem ``almost engineered'' to make
tobacco companies mad and networks nervous, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can go over the edge. But to get the message out with
cleverness and wallop _ that's the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   At Arnold, executive vice president Pete Favat professed some
surprise that ads attacking tobacco companies would draw such fire.
For more than five years, he's helped create antismoking ads for
Massachusetts and, in his view, the the Massachusetts campaign as
well as statewide campaigns aired in Florida and California are
just as edgy as the ads that were just pulled off the air.
</P>
<P>
   In the Massachusetts ads, ``We questioned the morals and
conscience of the tobacco industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But as these same themes moved from statewide campaigns to the
national arena, it stirred up a higher level of controversy, Favat
speculated.
</P>
<P>
   The national antismoking campaign is the outgrowth of the 1998
legal settlement between most states and the tobacco industry. The
settlement created the American Legacy Foundation, part of whose
mandate was to hire ad agencies to devise a $1.5 billion marketing
campaign that would discourage smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Believing that it couldn't win the account on its own, Arnold
put together a coalition of agencies that included Crispin Porter &AMP;
Bogusky, a Miami ad agency that had much success with an edgy
antismoking campaign it created in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Arnold learned its coalition had beaten out
several other agencies to win the foundation's business.
</P>
<P>
   Because the ads are aimed at teenagers, a group that sometimes
prides itself on being immune to Madison Avenue appeals, the Arnold
coalition met repeatedly with teenage antismoking activists in
fashioning themes for the national campaign, Favat said.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas for the body-bag and lie-detector ads came out of
``brainstorming'' with teenagers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the foundation has said the true clients of the ad
campaign are teenagers. But if the definition of a client is the
one who pays the bills, then a case can be made that the clients of
this antismoking campaign are the tobacco companies, and they're
angry at having to subsidize their own bashings.
</P>
<P>
   According to the tobacco companies, ads that were pulled off the
air run afoul of the terms of their legal settlement with the
states. As they see it, antismoking ads that vilify tobacco
companies violate the spirit of an agreement under which they could
pay states as much as $246 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the ads were inconsistent with the purpose of the
foundation, which is to educate the public on tobacco-related
health issues,'' said Mary Carnovale, a spokesperson for Philip
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   As a recent Adweek story noted, the chief executive of Philip
Morris is a board member of the company that owns the Fox network,
and speculation abounds that tobacco companies have pressured the
major TV networks to refuse to run some of the antismoking ads,
something Carnovale declined to comment on.
</P>
<P>
   The ads certainly ``put the networks in an awkward position,''
said BU's Parenio, who noted that Philip Morris also owns such
brands as Miller Beer and Kraft Foods. Networks would be reluctant
to offend such a major advertiser, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Networks are not in the business of offending people; nor are
most companies that buy advertising, said Stephen A. Greyser, a
consumer marketing professor at Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   The one exception is advocacy groups, which sometimes
deliberately run offensive advertising in hopes of gaining
publicity for their cause, particularly when the advocacy group is
launching a new campaign, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold and the American Legacy Foundation denied that early ads
of its antismoking campaign were part of a publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   According to foundation spokesman William Furmanski, the
teenagers who shaped the ads were influenced greatly by the movie
``The Blair Witch Project.'' The teenagers wanted the antismoking
campaign to create an underground word-of-mouth buzz. Similar buzz
turned ``The Blair Witch Project'' into a sleeper hit movie, even
though it lacked a big marketing budget.
</P>
<P>
   The teenagers didn't want the splashy hoopla that accompanies
the launch of most big ad campaigns, he said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Don't do a big launch,' they told us. `Don't do ``Good
Morning, America.'' That's too adult,' '' Furmanski said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the foundation decided this week to pull the two
ads so it wouldn't get bogged down in controversy, hinting that the
same ads may return some day in a revised form.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is not to spend an enormous amount of time debating
two ads when there's a whole campaign to launch,'' said Furmanski,
who noted that the foundation expects to air about 40 ads this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ads don't vilify,'' he said. ``They talk about nicotine
and addiction. They talk about public health in ways kids
understand. We've got to reach these kids before they try their
first tobacco product.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
