<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON RELEASES $125 MILLION IN HEATING OIL FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton released $125 million in federal
aid Wednesday to help poor families in the Northeast pay for the
rising cost of home heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at his first official news conference of the year, said
the money, which would come out of the Low Income Home Energy
Assistance Program (LIHEAP), was all that is left this year in the
government fund that aids those who must rely on oil to heat their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These families have been especially hard hit because the
winter months have been colder this year than in the past few
years,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   But he promised to seek $600 million in emergency funds for the
program in a supplemental budget request that he will send later to
Congress to ensure that money will be available during the hot
summer months when air-conditioning will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have always pulled together to help their fellow
citizens in time of need,'' he noted. ``Now the families of the
Northeast need our help too, and we must act.''
</P>
<P>
   The government already has provided $200 million in LIHEAP
funding in an effort to offset the rising cost of heating oil. The
price of crude oil hit $30.25 earlier this week, the highest it has
been since the 1991 Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the money released Wednesday will go to the
hardest-hit states and that he will meet soon with governors and
members of Congress from those states.
</P>
<P>
   During the hour-long news conference, the president touched on a
wide range of issues, including the presidential campaign, First
Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's race for the U.S. Senate seat from
New York and his legislative priorities for his final year in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about the Republican presidential candidates
using comparisons with him as a campaign tool to disparage each
other, Clinton said jokingly, ``I have a lot of sympathy with
(Texas) Gov. (George W.) Bush and (Arizona) Sen. (John) McCain.''
The president asserted that the booming economy and lower crime
rates have left the Republicans struggling for campaign issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it's hard for them to figure out what to run on,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also was asked about his role in his wife's campaign for
the Senate. ``Well, I'm basically doing for her what she's always
done for me,'' he said. ``You know, I'm talking to her about
whatever she wants to talk about. I'm giving her my best ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to his legislative agenda, Clinton urged Congress to
devote more than half of the non-Social Security surplus to
Medicare, the government's health insurance program for the
elderly, and include a prescription drug program for seniors.``I
ask them to move quickly, and resist the temptation to spend large
portions of the surplus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called for tougher gun control measures, including
a mandatory 72-hour waiting period between the purchase and receipt
of a firearm. Congressional Republicans have argued that the
waiting period should be shorter, but the president has insisted
that 72 hours is needed to prevent people who should not be allowed
to buy guns from purchasing them on weekends when some records
cannot be checked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not sign a bill that promises the American people this
will make them safer, (if) it does not do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked about what he plans to do about a request by
the Arkansas Supreme Court for him to respond within 30 days to two
ethics complaints seeking to strip him of his law license because
of his conduct in the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   He can either fight the complaints, which could lead to his
disbarment, or voluntarily surrender his Arkansas law license.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who settled a sexual harassment lawsuit brought by
former Arkansas state worker Paula Jones without admitting
wrongdoing, refused to say what he would do about this latest legal
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He said he settled the Jones case because he thought that ``it
was wrong for the president to take an hour, much less a day, much
less weeks away from the job of the American people for anything
that could be a distraction.''However, he also hinted that he would
like to avoid a public fight over the matter. ``In all things that
have happened subsequently, I have left a lot of things unsaid that
might otherwise have been said, and I hope I can continue to do
that,'' he said.Addressing foreign policy issues, Clinton said he
would be willing to help mediate the decades-old dispute between
India and Pakistan over the contested province of Kashmir, as he
has done in Northern Ireland and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said India and Pakistan would have to be ``truly
committed'' to resolving the dispute. ``Unless we are asked by both
parties to help, we can't get involved,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 51 years, Pakistan and India have fought two wars
over Kashmir. More than 15,000 people have been killed and
thousands displaced by the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Clinton will travel to India and Bangladesh, but so
far he has no plans to visit Pakistan. Gen. Pervez Musharraf,
Pakistan's military ruler, urged Clinton earlier this month not to
bypass his country during his trip, saying a visit would go a long
way toward easing tensions with India.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he will base his decision on whether to visit
Pakistan _ a recent nuclear power _ on what will best serve U.S.
interests in trying to stop ``a nuclear arms race.'' On a domestic
issue, the president also discussed his recent decision to allow
the U.S. Navy to resume practice bombing on part of the Puerto
Rican island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy had used its range on the island for 58 years until a
Marine pilot accidentally dropped two bombs that killed a Puerto
Rican security guard and injured four other civilians working on
the range last April 19.
</P>
<P>
   After eight months of protests, Clinton agreed to stop live
bombing of the island and to use inert bombs instead during
training exercises for the next three years. But he said other
target practice should resume and that Vieques residents should
decide in a referendum whether the Navy should stay or leave.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico has agreed to let the limited training exercises
resume on the island as part of a deal that includes up to $90
million in aid if residents of Vieques vote sometime before
February 2002 on whether the Navy may once more use live
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have charged that the plan is unfair because it does not
allow for an immediate and permanent stop to the bombing exercises.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton said Wednesday that the plan was a ``perfectly
reasonable compromise'' under the circumstances and that his main
goal was to give the people of Vieques a chance to decide the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were just up to me, if I could sign an executive order
and let them have a sanctioned election, I would do it today,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2005EST &QL; 
