<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9124 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS &LR;      02-16 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON GIVES CELTICS SEASON-BEST PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ You didn't see it, did you? You've already
given up on the Celtics, and you didn't need the aggravation of
seeing them trashed by the Utah Jazz, especially on ``NYPD Blue''
night.
</P>
<P>
   That's understandable. Also regrettable. You missed what Johnny
Most would have called a ding-donger of a fourth period. You missed
a memorable comeback in a 101-99 victory. And you also missed a
delectable sideshow, almost undoubtedly as brilliant a 25-minute
outing as a Celtic point guard has ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Anderson was not just good on Tuesday night when, in 25
foul-plagued minutes, he shot 12 for 15, dished out 6 assists and
scored 19 points in a fourth quarter run (6 for 6 from the floor,
including a pair of 3-pointers) that began with a nervy pull-up
transition 3 at 7:36 and culminated with a pair of free throws with
9.9 seconds to play. He wasn't just great. He was positively
transcendent.
</P>
<P>
   And he's not about to ``Aw, gee, shucks'' it, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I'm capable of at this level,'' he said Tuesday at
the Celtics' workout. ``And the thing I'm proudest of is that
listening to John Thompson say on TV that `Great players come
through with the game on the line,' because that's what I did last
night. Anybody can do stuff in the first quarter or the second
quarter, or when you're up by 20 and everything is loosey-goosey.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing ``loosey-goosey'' about the Utah game. The
Jazz are battling for the Central Division title, and the Celtics
are battling for, among other things, respect.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting part was the 1999-2000 Kenny Anderson at his best.
``All year long, I've been shooting the ball well. I really have,''
he said. ``Even when I miss, I've been right there.''
</P>
<P>
   But this show was of the highest order. He sank the
aformentioned deep 3. He got a conventional 3-point play on a
stutter-step jumper that drew a foul from a frustrated John
Stockton. He hit an inside-out 3 from Paul Pierce. He swished a
baseline 13-foot moonshot right out of a 1967 Havlicek vs. Wilt
highlight reel. He canned a leaner. And he capped off his 12-field
goal night with a pumping, up-and-under banked drive learned long
ago on the New York City asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   Which was only half the story. He was a floor general in every
sense, abetting his individual offense with fourth-quarter feeds to
Tony Battie, Vitaly Potapenko, and Pierce, usually emanating from a
pick and roll, where he was happily doing unto the Jazz what they
normally do unto everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Among his other accomplishments were a veteran acceptance of NBA
reality. That is to say, he didn't allow some questionable early
foul trouble to ruin his evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my maturity showing,'' he said. ``Three or four years
ago, I'd have gotten on the refs or even gotten myself teched out
of the game. I just went back and cheered for my team, and when the
coach called on me, I was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Give the coach his own assist, too. When Anderson picked up his
fourth foul with 8:42 remaining in the third (53-45, Utah), it was
assumed that he'd be exiting, per Rick Pitino's policy. Dana Barros
was actually on his way to the scorer's table when Pitino heeded
Anderson's plea to remain in the game. Anderson gave the Celtics 7
points before leaving more than five minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the kind of night it was for the Celtics, who
survived an 18-0 Utah run in the second period (from 31-24, Boston,
to 42-31, Jazz), as well as a 14-point third-quarter deficit
(53-39).
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them at the half, `Inflate, don't deflate,''' Pitino
said. ``A young team has a tendency to deflate.''
</P>
<P>
   They're not all young. Anderson is 29. He's been around and
back, and situations don't faze him. For one Tuesday night he was
nothing less that the best player in basketball, and the Celtics
rode his brilliance to a superb victory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The news wasn't all good. Pierce, the team's best night-in,
night-out player, sustained some sort of right leg injury in the
area described by Celtics public relations chief Jeff Twiss as
``neither his knee nor his hamstring,'' and was taken for a
``precautionary'' MRI. He was caught in a monster sandwich between
sizable gentlemen named Olden Polynice (7 feet, 250 pounds) and
Potapenko (6-10, 285). His status is the proverbial day-to-day . .
. How good was the fourth-quarter action in Salt Lake City? ``I
walked off the floor feeling uplifted,'' said veteran official Dick
Bavetta. Pitino likewise conformed that the affair was a cut above
the modern NBA norm, with the teams exchanging the lead seven
straight times from 91-90 through 97-96, and with people on both
sides making tough shots. ``It was fun to see a battle like that
going on,'' Pitino said. ``It was fun for me to watch Stockton and
(Karl) Malone. The last time we played them we hung in for a while,
but we didn't have (Adrian) Griffin and Pierce.'' . . . Is Pitino
worried that this team might be a bit full of itself after such a
big road win? ``It's fortunate we have two days in-between games,''
he said. ``It would have been different if we were playing right
away. But these type of games (i.e. against weak teams) have been
very difficult for us.'' . . . The Celtics play the Warriors at the
Arena in Oakland Friday night . . . Pitino on the three-way trade
involving Philadelphia, Golden State, and Chicago: ``Larry Hughes
is a good young talent. I wish he weren't going to Golden State. Or
that he at least takes his time getting a physical. Toni Kukoc
makes Philly very tough.'' . . . Danny Fortson played 12 minutes
against the Jazz, hauling in five rebounds. ``(The trade with
Toronto) is behind us,'' Pitino said, ``but in all likelihood he
could be moved again. If we can get something good, we'll do it,
because I still don't think we can re-sign him.'' The trading
deadline is Feb. 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
