<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain gets conservative Bauer's nod
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Sen. John McCain's efforts to shore up
support among religious conservatives in South Carolina got a boost
Wednesday when he was endorsed by former rival Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a former adviser to President Reagan, appeared with
McCain at a Furman University rally in the most conservative region
of the state to offer his support ``with great pride and without
any hesitation.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also picked up endorsements from California Secretary of
State Bill Jones, a former Bush supporter, and former U.S. Sen. Dan
Evans of Washington. California's primary is March 7 and
Washington's is Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   At the Furman rally, Bauer said McCain wants ``not a money bags
democracy, but a system built on civility and decency and honor.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that McCain ``is the man most likely to end the
Clinton-Gore years.''
</P>
<P>
   Having the backing of a champion of the social conservative wing
of the Republican party may help McCain blunt the withering assault
on his conservative credentials by the campaign of Gov. George W.
Bush and its surrogates.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer had campaigned as a vocal opponent of abortion rights
until he left the race following the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Without using the word ``abortion'' on the college campus, he
said McCain would work to ensure that ``every child is welcomed
into the world and protected by the law.''
</P>
<P>
   In a session with reporters later in the day, Bauer provided a
comparison between McCain and Bush that was welcomed by the McCain
camp. ``Governor Bush is no different on the major issues,'' Bauer
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Hilton Head, Bush professed little concern that Bauer had
come out for McCain. ``People are free to endorse who they would
want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Furman rally, a Bush worker distributed a statement
from Bauer's former South Carolina chairman, who now is backing
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of Bauer's endorsement, many of us recognize that
George W. Bush is the true conservative and the real pro-life
candidate in this race,'' said state Sen. Mike Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Bush backers and interest groups have mounted telephone, mail
and television and radio advertising campaigns to undermine
McCain's standing among Christian conservatives, an important
segment of the South Carolina electorate.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism has ranged from his vote to allow scientists to
use fetal tissue in their quest for a cure for Parkinson's disease
to groundless charges that McCain fathered illegitimate children.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, a C-Span camera captured an exchange between Bush
and Fair in which Fair urged Bush to go after McCain's ``soft
spots'' to win over religious conservatives. Bush acknowledged he
would do so, but not on television.
</P>
<P>
   While polls show that the race in South Carolina is too close to
call, Bush has been running well ahead of McCain among socially
conservative voters. McCain conceded Wednesday that his `
</P>
</TEXT>
