<HEADLINE>
SOVEREIGN SUGGESTS PAYMENTS FOR FLEET, BANKBOS BRANCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hoping to ease federal regulators' concerns, Sovereign
Bancorp of Pennsylvania has submitted a new plan to the US Office
of Thrift Supervision that would allow it to spread out payments
for 280 Fleet and BankBoston branches over several months, rather
than make a single $1.4 billion payment.
</P>
<P>
   John Hamill, chairman and chief executive of Sovereign New
England, said he expects final approval within a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've submitted a plan to the regulators which is a good plan,
and we believe it will be approved,'' Hamill said.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Tuesday that although the bank, based in
Wyomissing, Pa., is well capitalized, regulators had questioned
whether a one-time payment for the branches would be too great a
burden at a time when financial reserves will be needed to convert
the branches.
</P>
<P>
   Under the revised plan, about 90 BankBoston branches in Rhode
Island and Connecticut would be purchased March 27. The second
purchase, on or about June 20, would involve about 95 Fleet
branches in Massachusetts. The last purchase, for 97 Fleet branches
in Massachusetts and New Hampshire, would be around July 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $1.8 billion or so has been raised and it is in the
bank,'' Hamill said. He added that the payments would coincide with
the bank's schedule for staggered conversions of the New England
branches to Sovereign branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sovereign has completed the financing,'' he said. ``The
staggered conversions we are talking about will be better for the
customer, because it will mean that each branch will be converted
in groupings of about the same size, as opposed to converting all
280 branches at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign, a $25 billion bank, currently has 300 branches in the
Mid-Atlantic region and total net income of about $180 million,
after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some analysts have wondered whether the deal might
be too large for Sovereign, which is technically a thrift. Others
say it should have no trouble expanding into New England.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jim Moynihan of Advest in Boston said the New England
entity's new management team ``brings an awful lot to the table'' _
particularly Hamill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sovereign was reaching when it came in to buy, but a good
management team adds strength,'' Moynihan said. ``There might be a
glitch or two, but I think by mid to late summer everything will be
in place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
