<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PEANUTS-AD-COLUMN-NYT     02-16 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEANUTS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: HELPING `PEANUTS' CHARACTERS SURVIVE THEIR CREATOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During the last 50 years, Charles M. Schulz built the
comic strip ``Peanuts'' into one of the most powerful and effective
brands in entertainment marketing. The adventures of characters
like Charlie Brown, Snoopy, Linus and Lucy spawned billions of
dollars worth of licensed merchandise from companies like Fossil,
Hallmark, Hasbro and Pez; inspired scores of advertising campaigns
for products like Ford automobiles, Dolly Madison snack cakes and
Metropolitan Life insurance; and generated hundreds of promotions
for fast food, soft drinks and other mass-market goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with the death of Schulz on Saturday, just as the final
original ``Peanuts'' strip appeared in newspapers, experts in the
field of corporate identity are divided over the future of the
brand. Some say they believe that ``Peanuts'' can remain salient
and relevant to new generations if the brand is tended as carefully
by the Schulz estate as it was supervised by him in life. They cite
as examples the Disney and Warner Brothers cartoon mainstays from
Mickey Mouse and Donald Duck to Bugs Bunny and Porky Pig.
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, say that the ``Peanuts'' gang, as Schulz
described his creations, must inevitably suffer the fate of
characters from comic strips like ``Li'l Abner'' and ``Pogo,''
which faded from popularity after their creators died and consumer
tastes changed.
</P>
<P>
   United Media, the division of E.W. Scripps Co. that oversees the
syndication and licensing of ``Peanuts'' and the characters, is
determined to keep its lucrative franchise fresh and thriving.
</P>
<P>
   Plans made for ``Peanuts'' before the death of Schulz ``will go
forward,'' Alexa Gardner, executive director at United Media in New
York, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The characters are global icons, beloved,'' she added.
``Newspapers in New York ran a silhouette of Charlie Brown and
Snoopy. How many images are instantly recognizable in silhouette?
Mickey Mouse, the Eiffel Tower and `Peanuts.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner acknowledged her familiarity with the vicissitudes of
American popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Capp was my favorite uncle; my child is named after him,''
she said, referring to the creator of ``Li'l Abner,'' whose
hillbilly characters were a national craze in the 1940s and 1950s.
But if Regis Philbin asked a question about Dogpatch, the Schmoos
or Kickapoo Joy Juice on ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'', he
would probably draw blank stares.
</P>
<P>
   To help ``Peanuts'' remain ``immortal,'' Gardner said, United
Media has ambitious campaigns that predate Schulz's death. They
include an extensive promotional campaign this year to commemorate
the strip's golden anniversary and the release of a Paramount Home
Video tape retelling ``The Pied Piper of Hamelin'' with Snoopy in
the lead role.
</P>
<P>
   ``The licensing program, with 600 licensees worldwide, will
continue,'' Gardner said. ``New art for merchandising and
advertising will be created by those artists authorized by Charles
Schulz to draw the `Peanuts' characters for those purposes'' _ he
delegated those tasks but always produced the strip himself _
``with new looks based on the themes established over the last 50
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 18,000 strips to draw from, 1,800 with a baseball
theme alone. And there's the animated library, shows and specials
like `A Charlie Brown Christmas,' which CBS and Nickelodeon will
continue to show.''
</P>
<P>
   Some corporate-identity experts applaud that strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brand can go on forever,'' said John Grace, executive
director at Interbrand Group in New York, part of Omnicom Group,
``because it touches a piece of the humanity in each of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think in 10 years people will be prone to personal
embarrassment?'' he asked, citing a recurring theme of the Schulz
oeuvre. ``Then the cartoon will be relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Johnson, chairman and chief executive at Enterprise IG in
New York, owned by the WPP Group, said: ```Peanuts' so successfully
captured a little bit of what the brand identity of this country
is. That's why it has resonated with so many people for so long.
And brands that are closely tended by their creators from the
beginning can remain fresh if you put the kind of resources into
the rejuvenation process that are needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts, however, say that whatever efforts are made by
United Media and the Schulz estate will not be sufficient to
counter the natural impulse of consumers to move on, particularly
in the fad- and trend-driven world of pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any other brand, `Peanuts' needs to be kept current,''
said Allen Adamson, managing director at Landor Associates in New
York, a division of Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the characters are not living and growing to talk about
what's important to people, there'll be a slow sunset for them like
retired movie stars,'' he added. ``And fewer and fewer advertisers
will tap into them.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Siegel, chairman and chief executive at Siegelgale in New
York, the corporate and brand consulting company formerly called
Siegel &AMP; Gale, said: `` `Peanuts' is an icon, but a static icon in
the future. I can't see it as a viable advertising expression
because advertising has to be topical and responsive to what's
happening in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were Met Life or somebody using the characters in ads,''
Siegel concluded, ``I would figure out a way to transition out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But executives at the Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., which has
used the ``Peanuts'' characters in advertising, blimps and
promotions since 1985, say they have no such intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing changes,'' said Kevin Foley, a spokesman for MetLife
in New York. ``Our contract runs through 2002, and while we don't
want to negotiate in your column, they remain as important to us as
they've always been.
</P>
<P>
   `` Schulz always took a personal interest in MetLife, and it's
fair to say he was very pleased with what it meant to us as a
company that people recognized us for his characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz was also a longtime MetLife policy holder, according to a
statement the company issued on Monday in which three current and
former chief executives mourned him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Schulz touched the lives of just about everybody on
this planet,'' said Denny Lynch, vice president for communications
at Wendy's International in Dublin, Ohio, which gave away Snoopy
toys in a children's meal promotion last year and will do so again
in late summer for the anniversary celebration. ``But his passing
will do nothing to change our plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The characters will live on, and some might say they will
increase in popularity now that the strip is no longer being
produced. Our anniversary toys will be numbered and have
collectible value. Maybe they'll be collector's items.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
