<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-GORE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore promises speedy storm relief to Georgians
 &HT;    By Christopher Quinn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMILLA, Ga. _ Vice President Al Gore walked through a
devastated neighborhood here Wednesday, promising tornado victims
that help was on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very impressed with the way this community has
pulled together,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary housing will arrive Monday, and the first federal
checks for disaster relief are expected by Wednesday, Gore said.
State officials estimate that property owners in Mitchell,
Colquitt, Grady and Tift counties suffered $20 million in insured
losses. The death toll was 18 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore appeared with several state politicians, including Gov. Roy
Barnes. After a helicopter tour, Gore said agricultural specialists
will come to South Georgia to examine the flattened chicken houses
and pecan groves and destroyed irrigation equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president visited the family of Tommy Lee Randell. Two
of Randell's daughters and his two sons lost their houses;
Randell's home was still inhabitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to do a little patching, but at least I've got
something to patch,'' Randell said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Jellets, a spokesman for the Georgia Emergency
Management Agency, said 258 homes were destroyed. An additional 88
homes were severely damaged and 103 houses suffered minor damage.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Emergency Management Agency teams walked through
hard-hit neighborhoods to register residents for relief. FEMA also
was scouting locations for temporary housing.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson Manufacturing Co., which makes mobile homes, was shut
down by the storm. FEMA assessor Mac Gardner said the building and
153 trailers were destroyed and 40 employees are out of work.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-mile-long footprint of the storm traveled mostly through
farmland, forest and pecan groves.
</P>
<P>
   Farm officials said the winds destroyed about 20 irrigation
systems and at least 14 chicken houses and flattened pecan groves.
</P>
<P>
   Animals also had a disaster relief team on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Animal Planet television channel sent a bright blue
tractor-trailer painted with pictures of two dogs, a tiger, eagle
and pig. The trailer goes from its headquarters in Denver to the
scene of disasters to rescue and treat animals.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanette Edelstein, the project manager, said the crew pulled
about 10 dogs out of the rubble Tuesday. They try to find the
animals' owners or take the pets to a local shelter. ''They get a
little forgotten,'' Edelstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The initial rush of help in the devastated areas has settled
into a steady movement of heavy machinery clearing acres of debris
and trees and victims picking through the litter that was their
homes. ''We'll be fine,'' said Danny Morrell, a farmer who lost
three massive irrigation systems due to the storm. ''We just have
to put the puzzle pieces back together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
