<SLUG> BC-NASA-FUNDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS ASSAIL NASA CHIEF FOR RELYING ON RUSSIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers considering NASA's first budget increase
in seven years attacked administrator Dan Goldin on Wednesday for
relying too heavily on the Russian government to complete the
international space station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fools for depending on them,'' fumed Rep. Dana
Rohrabacher, R-Calif., chairman of the House Space and Aeronautics
Subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Rohrabacher, along with other committee members, criticized the
Clinton administration for the ``grievous mistake'' of joining
forces with the financially unstable Russian government. He said
the partnership has cost taxpayers several billion dollars and
delayed the space station's construction by two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other recent problem in our space program has cost the
American people so dearly, both in money and lost opportunities,''
the chairman said during a 2 1/2-hour hearing on Goldin's 2001
budget request. ``Nothing has been so destructive as the naive
assumption that Russia's government would spend its limited
resources to help us build the international space station.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rohrabacher said, NASA should have dealt directly with
private Russian companies.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin, who is seeking a $435 million increase in fiscal year
2001 to the space program's current $13.6 billion budget, told the
panel that NASA's alliance with the Russian space agency has paid
off, both financially and in terms of the enormous boost in
knowledge gained from joint work aboard Russia's Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us not forget what we learned from the Russian
government,'' he said. ``It was monumental in opening our eyes up
to understand the rigors of long-term space flight. That occurred
not because of Russian companies. That occurred because of the
relationship at the top level with the Russian government. There
are a whole host of things that we did not know.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added that at least one Russian company the committee was
touting had tried to gouge NASA on space station hardware, offering
it at a much lower cost to a private U.S. company. It was the
Russian Aviation and Space Agency, he said, that stepped in to
force the company's prices down. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; When completed in 2005, the international space station will
provide research facilities for a permanent crew of seven. NASA
believes the space station, which involves 16 nations, is a crucial
first step in launching an eventual human mission to Mars and will
also aid medical and scientific research on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   House Science Committee Chairman Jim Sensenbrenner, R-Wisc.,
complained that RASA had repeatedly reneged on promises to produce
the space station's crew module. Originally slated for an April
1998 launch, the crew module, also known as the service module or
the Zvezda (Russian for ``star''), is critical if the Americans and
Russians want to meet a November target date for launching the
station's first resident crew.
</P>
<P>
   The module, which the Russians now plan to launch in early July,
also contains a life support apparatus, as well as the propulsion,
flight control and power generation needed before new U.S.
components can be added to the station.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner read a timeline for completing the service module,
pointing out that the Russians had missed every deadline since
March of 1996 and complaining that NASA had not followed through on
promises to launch an interim control module as a stop-gap measure.
</P>
<P>
   That module would take over maneuvering of the space station for
up to a year, keeping the outpost in orbit and buying time if the
Russians fail to launch the service module or if something goes
wrong with the service module once launched.
</P>
<P>
   The interim control module ``still sits on the ground, and now
you're telling us that NASA has made the wrong call every single
time,'' Sensenbrenner told Goldin.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldin said not all of the space station delays were
Russia's fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our own problems, along with the Russians,'' he said,
adding that he should have begun work on the interim module a few
years earlier than he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very serious mistake for which I accept
responsibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin also told lawmakers that despite their ribbing over last
year's loss of two spacecraft, the Mars Climate Orbiter and the
Mars Polar Lander, exploration of the red planet will remain a top
priority.
</P>
<P>
   The climate orbiter was lost in September as it approached Mars
because of navigational errors resulting from a mix-up between NASA
and its contractor Lockheed Martin in converting metric and English
measurements. The polar lander failed to send a signal from Mars
after its 11-month journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that we'll get over these problems,'' Goldin
said. ``We will be able land on Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said the loss of the probes was a ``tremendous blow,''
but he hopes to learn from what went wrong. A report on that is
expected next month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
