<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-POLITICS-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNING PARTY SEEKS TO PROSECUTE CANDIDATE FOR PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The bitter rivalry between Taiwan's president, Lee
Teng-hui, and a leading contender to succeed him took its nastiest
turn yet Wednesday as the governing Nationalist Party requested
prosecution of the candidate for embezzlement and forgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists filed their case with prosecutors against James
Soong, a former leading light of the party and ally of Lee,
charging that he diverted $12 million in party donations and
revenues to a personal account. Under Taiwanese law, the Taipei
prosecutor must now investigate and determine whether to bring a
criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   Soong mounted an independent run for president last year after
Lee supported Vice President Lien Chan as the party candidate in
the March 18 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts debated Wednesday night whether the new
charges, forcing an already harsh political dispute into the legal
arena, would harm Soong's candidacy or backfire on the
Nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Lu Ya-li, a political scientist at National Taiwan University,
said he doubted that the case would hurt the party. ``It looks like
they are using this as a campaign strategy, and Soong can say he is
being persecuted,'' Lu said.
</P>
<P>
   Soong, his former secretary and his sister-in-law are accused of
embezzlement and forgery to divert the funds during Soong's tenure
as party secretary-general from 1989 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Soong's attorneys repeated his firm denials of wrongdoing
Wednesday, saying that he put the money into a special account
under a direct mandate from Lee, for use in ``special missions''
that Soong has not described.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has previously denied approving the diversion.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's inquiry is expected to take months, a legal
expert said.
</P>
<P>
   Though it will not be complete by election day, the criminal
inquiry casts a shadow over the presidential campaign, and if the
prosecutors do proceed with charges, a guilty verdict could result
in prison sentences. The prosecution would be suspended if Soong
wins the presidency, the legal expert said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A decade ago Soong, a skilled politician with an unusual ability
to connect with the public, was a close friend and political ally
of Lee, helping him to consolidate his position as party chairman
and Taiwan's president.
</P>
<P>
   After 1994, as the elected governor of Taiwan province _ the
title was a relic of the Nationalists' former claim to be the
government of all of China _ Soong skillfully nurtured an image of
caring for the common people.
</P>
<P>
   But as his own popularity soared, he became more defiant and his
relations with Lee soured. In 1998, Lee led a drive to eviscerate
the governorship and Soong was elbowed to the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Soong began his independent campaign last year and was expelled
from the party. And until accusations of an illegal ``slush fund''
began to dog him late last year, he was a firm leader in the
opinion polls over Chan and the third contender, Chen Shui-bian of
the Democratic Progressive Party.
</P>
<P>
   The air of scandal has cost Soong some of his support, and the
three candidates now appear to be in a dead heat. But many
Taiwanese say they believe that the charges against Soong are
politically motivated, especially because the concealment of
political donations and secret doling out of funds to gain allies
have been common practices in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 10, the Control Yuan, a government watchdog, issued a
report finding that Soong had failed to properly report political
donations and certain family assets. It did not recommend a
criminal inquiry, although in Wednesday's filing the Nationalists
drew on some of its findings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
