<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-INTERNET-LONELY17-COX     02-16 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-LONELY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is Web severing lifelines?
 &HT;    By Richard Halicks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Has the Internet stolen your husband?
</P>
<P>
   Did you misplace your life somewhere between Yahoo and shop.com?
</P>
<P>
   Are your only friends people you've never actually seen?
</P>
<P>
   The Web world was vibrating Wednesday with talk of the latest
study: A Stanford University researcher concludes the Net is
increasingly isolating us from the people we love, that we're
working online at home without cutting hours at the office, and
that we're spending less time watching TV or shopping in stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you spend your time on the Internet, you don't hear a
human voice, and you never get a hug,'' declared Norman Nie, the
Stanford political scientist who headed the study of Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of Internet thinkers flamed Nie's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assertion that the Internet is socially isolating has not
held up to serious scrutiny,'' Donna Hoffman, co-director of the
eLab at Vanderbilt University, told The Washington Post. ``All of
the research I've seen points the other way _ not to mention the
anecdotal evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time people are actually spending on the Internet
is for e-mail, which is surely a form of communication,'' scoffed
Pat McKeown, head of the Management Information Systems Department
at the University of Georgia. ``It seems to me that you're actually
increasing socialization.''
</P>
<P>
   But others nodded their heads at Nie's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results aren't at all surprising,'' said Clifford Nass, an
associate communications professor at Stanford and author of ``The
Media Equation: How People Treat Computers, Televisions and New
Media Like Real People and Places.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heavy media users to tend to feel more isolated and lonely,''
Nass said. ``We don't know whether it's cause or effect. Do people
use media as a way of filling their loneliness; or does the use of
media cause loneliness? Probably a bit of both.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford report appears to support a landmark study by
Carnegie Mellon University, concluded in summer 1998, that stunned
researchers at the time: The two-year investigation found that
people who spend even a few hours on the Internet each week suffer
higher levels of depression and loneliness than they would if they
used the Net less frequently.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford study, based on a nationwide survey of 4,113
people, focused most closely on the 36 percent of respondents who
said they use the Web more than five hours a week. Of that group,
13 percent said they spend less time with family and friends
because they're occupied online; 25 percent said they work more at
home, without any decline in work at the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go home at 6:30 in the evening and spend the whole night
sending e-mail and wake up the next morning, I still haven't talked
to my wife or kids or friends,'' Nie said.
</P>
<P>
   People do interact on the Net. But much of the e-mail and
chat-room conversation occurs under aliases _ making it impersonal
and intrinsically false.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard for people to navigate the reality of what's
occurring online,'' said Jay Weinstein, a clinical and
neuropsychologist in Sandy Springs, Ga. ``Nothing is clearly real _
or real in the sense of how people would interact in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, you're not presenting yourself as you see
yourself. And on the other hand, people are responding to you based
on this false presentation. This reinforces the idea that if you
present yourself as you really are, you're not as acceptable,
perhaps,'' Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Guzdial, associate professor at Georgia Tech's College of
Computing, fights Internet isolation at home and at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's less isolating when I have my children on my lap
and we're doing Pokemon searches together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guzdial says the answer to problems caused by technology is _
yep _ more technology. At least in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Look for multiple-mouse computers, which enable more than one
person to work at the same time, Guzdial said. Also, check out
``collaborative browsing,'' in which Net users at different
locations can see how one another are navigating a Web page.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do some really collaborative, interesting things ...
that connect people, that improve on our day-to-day life, rather
than isolating us from our day-to-day life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
