<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9151 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-JUDGE17-COX     02-16 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-JUDGE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis' freedom puts him on leash
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Submitting weekly urine samples to Baltimore
authorities will become as common to the life of NFL football star
Ray Lewis as tackling a competitor on the field.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewis arrives at his Owings Mill, Md., home, where he is
expected today, the All-Pro player will be heavily monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Restrictions placed on Lewis when he was released from the
Fulton County Jail after posting $1.1 million bail Tuesday will be
enforced by officials at the Maryland Department of Public Safety's
Pretrial Detention Services.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland Public Safety Commissioner LaMont Flanagan said it's
the first time in his 10 years at the agency that it has been asked
to supervise a celebrity of Lewis' stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will require Mr. Lewis to give us access to his home,''
Flanagan said Wednesday afternoon. ``We'll be visiting him
periodically. This is not routine for us, monitoring a celebrity
like Mr. Lewis. It's the exception rather than the rule. But it's
incumbent upon us to make sure he (Lewis) follows this plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and two acquaintances _ Joseph Sweeting of Miami and
Reginald Oakley of Baltimore _ are charged in the stabbing deaths
of Jacinth Baker, 21, and Richard Lollar, 24, both of Decatur, Ga.
The two victims were killed Jan. 31 in a fight on an Atlanta street
corner the morning after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting, 34, and Oakley, 31, are in the Fulton County Jail
awaiting a bond hearing. Both surrendered this week.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been assigned to Fulton County Superior Court Judge
Alice D. Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   Restrictions on Lewis were outlined in a letter by Will Davis,
deputy director of FultonCounty's Pretrial Detention Services.
They are a 9 p.m. curfew; travel only to Georgia and in Maryland;
weekly drug and alcohol tests; weekly visits with pretrial
detention officials; and surrender of his passport.
</P>
<P>
   This means the 24-year-old athlete, regarded the Baltimore
Ravens' strongest player, also will not be allowed to play in
football games outside Maryland, Flanagan said, unless Fulton
County Superior Court Judge Doris Downs modifies the order.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is expected to hold a press conference today at 3 p.m. at
the Ravens complex in suburban Baltimore, said Jana Harris, one of
his attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Weekly urine samples submitted by Lewis to Flanagan's Baltimore
office will determine whether Lewis violates the drug and alcohol
rule, while impromptu phone calls and random visits to his house by
officials under Flanagan's division will determine whether he's
adhering to his curfew, Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must also fax us or call us everyday with his schedule,''
Flanagan said. ``If he does something that's not on the schedule,
that's fine as long as he sticks to the stipulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis will be interviewed by Flanagan's unit and assigned a case
manager as soon as he returns to Maryland, Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ravens officials are hoping some of the terms placed
on their middle linebacker will be relaxed by the time the NFL team
begins its pre-season play in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing planned out of town for the next several
months,'' said Kevin Byrne, vice president of public relations for
the team. ``The first out-of-town game we have scheduled is the
third weekend in August, but we have no idea who we'll be playing
against yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe something will change between now and the time we start
the season,'' Byrne said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
