<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9152 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-POLL-ART-895     02-16 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-POLL-ART-895(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL-METHOD-BOX)
</HEADLINE>
  
 SUPPORT FOR BUSH DECLINES SUBSTANTIALLY, POLL FINDS  (With(ART ADV: Two graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE with JANET ELDER   
 c. 2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Gov. George W. Bush of Texas finds himself in an unexpectedly
rancorous primary struggle, voters' impressions of him nationally
have diminished so substantially that now as many people dislike
him as like him, the latest New York Times/CBS News Poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   These findings are particularly striking given that for months
Bush towered over the Republican and Democratic fields in poll
after poll. But Bush's Republican challenger, Sen. John McCain, is
in a markedly better position after his impressive victory in the
New Hampshire primary on Feb. 1. In November, voters knew little
about the senator from Arizona; now, more people like him than do
not, by a margin of nearly 3 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Bush, Vice President Al Gore has enjoyed some
success in overcoming a decidedly negative image, and has benefited
from a huge proportion of Americans who credit President Clinton
for a flourishing economy.
</P>
<P>
   The most heartening news is not only for the vice president but
also for the Democratic Party. There were several signs in the
survey that Republicans might find it daunting to compete with
Democrats next November on both the presidential and congressional
levels.
</P>
<P>
   During the Republican debate in South Carolina on Tuesday night,
both Bush and McCain presented themselves as best prepared to steer
the country out of the Clinton era. But that may not be such a
prudent selling point, especially among Democrats and independents,
because the poll found that the president still draws remarkably
high marks for his job performance.
</P>
<P>
   Although only 43 percent of Americans say they like Clinton
personally, his job approval rating stands at 60 percent and his
stewardship of the economy draws a 73 percent approval.
</P>
<P>
   This is all encouraging for the vice president. When voters are
asked why they like Gore, the highest proportion _ 22 percent _ say
it is because of the Clinton administration's record, more than
double since last November. Another 17 percent say it is because of
Gore's experience as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The results are quite a turnabout from last year, when Gore was
struggling to contain the surge by his Democratic opponent Bill
Bradley, while also keeping a distance from the scandals at the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton remarked on the Democrats' good fortune at his news
conference in Washington on Wednesday. Asked why the two
Republicans condemned him in the debate, he said: ``I have a lot of
sympathy with Governor Bush and Senator McCain. It's hard for them
to figure out what to run on.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating Bush's challenge is that voters are now as likely
to hold a negative view of Bush as a positive one, a pronounced
shift from late last year, when he was far more popular. Bush has
suffered in part, the poll found, because voters do not identify
him with a particular set of policies and are not enamored of his
tax-cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   As McCain and Bush compete ferociously in the run-up to the
primary on Saturday in South Carolina, the Democratic contest
nationally seems to have evaporated in the eyes of many voters.
Bradley's losses to Gore in New Hampshire and Iowa have made him
less of a factor in the Democratic race; the vice president has
enlarged his already lopsided lead among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   About as many people have a favorable an image of Gore as
unfavorable. It is not an altogether enviable position, but it
represents a notable shift from last December, when a far higher
proportion viewed him negatively.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide telephone poll of 1,225 adults, including 979
registered voters, was conducted Saturday through Monday. The
entire sample has a margin of sampling error of plus or minus three
percentage points. Because of its broad national scope, this survey
is not a reliable measure of the state of the Republican contest in
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   If the general election were held today, the survey found, it
would be a dead heat, with Bush drawing 45 percent and Gore 44
percent. Last November, Bush was ahead of Gore, 50 percent to 41
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite McCain's surge in popularity, he would do no differently
against Gore than Bush would. He would receive 42 percent; Gore, 41
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of McCain's potency _ and success in courting
independents and Democrats _ he would beat Bradley, 45 percent to
31 percent. In November, Bradley led McCain, 47 percent to 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the primaries, Bush is still favored by more than half of the
Republican voters. But McCain has cut into Bush's once tremendous
lead. The poll shows that Bush is now the choice of 53 percent of
Republican primary voters, and McCain, 33 percent. In November,
Bush was the favorite of 68 percent, and McCain was the choice of
only 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many voters are only beginning to focus on the race and
said it was too early for them to know who they will vote for. Only
one-third of Bush's backers, and of McCain's, said they had decided
for certain.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Gore's national lead has grown.
Sixty-four percent of Democratic voters back Gore; 25 percent
support Bradley. In November, as Bradley was drawing national
notice as a threat to the vice president in New Hampshire, 56
percent favored Gore and 30 percent favored Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Another comforting sign for Gore is that voters no longer expect
a Republican victory in the presidential race. Now, they say, it is
a tossup.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Clinton's popularity is helping Democrats in the
same way it did when Washington was distracted by the impeachment
proceedings: The public likes the policies of the administration
despite the reservations about Clinton's personal qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``As vice president, he's had a part in the success of the
economy,'' said Kelly Rinaldo, an independent who was questioned
for the poll and explained in a follow-up interview on Wednesday
why she likes Gore. ``He's on the right track. And if he follows
through on Social Security and health care, he'd be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Rinaldo, 36, a homemaker from Patchogue Village, N.Y., added,
``When you're a vice president, you always play second fiddle, but
he has the upper hand because of this experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger for Bush is that the more that people get to know him
the more he seems to lose support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush seems to waffle more on the issues,'' said Mark Giloican,
27, a poll respondent who is a student in Savannah, Ga., and plans
to back McCain. ``All of the candidates tend to say what we want to
hear. But Bush seems to do it more. My opinion has changed recently
simply because I've heard more about him. He seems to have a little
more charisma than McCain, but that's not what matters to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings suggested that Bush's positions were a growing
vulnerability. Voters said they were more drawn to McCain's stand
on campaign reform than Bush's signature tax proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what any budget surplus should be used for, 56 percent of
Americans said it should go to Social Security; 17 percent to pay
down the debt; and only 13 percent to cut income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But respondents seemed more interested in campaign reform, which
has been McCain's major theme, although Bush announced a campaign
finance proposal of his own this week.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two percent of Americans said the campaign finance system
has so much wrong with it that it needs to be completely
overhauled. Another 44 percent said fundamental changes are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Bush's tax-cutting message still appeals to many
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Cassan, 78, a retired clothes presser who backs Bush, put
it this way: ``McCain has come out for campaign finance. But if it
was passed the Republicans wouldn't have a chance because the media
leans heavily Democratic. He's also more liberal than Bush. He
doesn't support as big a tax cut that Bush does, which the people
need and deserve.'' She added, ``He wants all the things I want,
such as tax cuts and smaller government.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Albert McCloud, 63, a retired shipworker
from Hampton, Va., said he would back Gore. ``It appears that Bill
Clinton is going to try to win the election for Al Gore, and it
appears that Al Gore is going to try to continue some of the
successful policies of the Clinton administration, like paying down
the debt, keeping the economy steady by working with the Federal
Reserve, and strengthening the education budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the presidential race, the poll found the Democrats are
better positioned for the November elections than the Republicans.
Sixty-one percent of voters said they had a positive view of the
Democratic Party; 31 percent have a negative view. By contrast, 49
percent have a positive view of the Republicans; 41 percent a
negative view.
</P>
<P>
   While national polls have little predictive value as to the
outcome of local House races, they do offer a sense of public
sentiment about the parties. In the poll, 33 percent of voters said
they planned to vote for the Republican candidate in their
district; 44 percent for the Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, Democrats are buoyed by the roaring
economy. In 1992, when Clinton triumphed over President George
Bush, only 23 percent of Americans said the economy was in good
shape. Now, 88 percent hold that view.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
