<HEADER>
A9154 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-VA-GUN-LIABILITY-(TRI     02-16 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VA-GUN-LIABILITY-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN CONTROL MEASURES LOSE STEAM IN STATEHOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ For all the political oratory and legislative
proposals prompted by the Columbine school shooting rampage, one of
the few fast-moving firearms bills in the nation's statehouses this
year is not a gun-control measure. It is a ban promoted by the
National Rifle Association against cities suing gun manufacturers
for liability in deadly sprees by citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of our top priorities,'' said Jim Baker, the NRA's
chief lobbyist, who estimated that the urban lawsuit ban, already
enacted into law last year in 15 states, would be fully approved by
15 to 20 more states this session.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to have two-thirds of the states done by the end of
this year,'' Baker said of the bill to protect gun manufacturers,
which the NRA is finding far easier to pursue on a state-by-state
basis than in the federal congressional arena.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between slow-moving gun control proposals and the
rapidly passing lawsuit ban was brought home first-hand here to a
House delegate, James H. Dillard II. No sooner were his three
post-Columbine proposals to ban guns and hunting on Virginia's
school grounds snuffed in committee than the House passed the city
lawsuit ban by a vote of 83-17 and sent it to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``School districts were begging for passage of my bills, but it
didn't matter,'' Dillard ruefully observed.
</P>
<P>
   The National League of Cities is opposed to the lawsuit ban as
an unfair pre-emption of local authority. But the league concedes
that the NRA has scored a strategic victory with its relatively
quiet statehouse blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``State legislatures tend to be more conservative, and the NRA
has very effectively pumped tons of money into this issue,'' said
Juan F. Otero, senior legislative counsel to the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA let the images of Columbine dissipate and then pushed
forward with this,'' said Otero, describing the lawsuit ban as a
``shameful endeavor'' that cities would eventually have to fight in
home-rule constitutional challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the lead of Chicago, New Orleans and other cities
with major gun-crime problems, various urban officials across the
nation have been discussing the possibility of innovative lawsuits
against gun manufacturers for the costly damages from shootings.
Their opponents argue that criminal use of guns is a product abuse,
not the manufacturer's fault. The lawsuit ban is moving more easily
in part because of state lawmakers' tradition of not easily
yielding dynamic prerogatives to localities, especially when they
are potentially revenue producing.
</P>
<P>
   Here on the statehouse level of politicking, Dillard, a
66-year-old schoolteacher and suburban Republican legislator who
has long been involved in Virginia's gun control debate, is not
surprised by the rejection of his school protection bills and the
rapid progress of the lawsuit ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banning guns from schools is a no-brainer, and I think my
bills would have easily passed if they had gotten beyond the
committee to the House floor,'' said the Fairfax lawmaker,
underlining the statehouse mix of committee power and rural
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Firearm legislation is in the hands of the House Militia and
Police Committee, where, Dillard notes, 18 of the 23 members have
earned ``A'' ratings in the NRA's influential legislative report
card.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no grand scheme here,'' said the committee chairman,
H. Morgan Griffith, a member of the Republican leadership that took
full control of Virginia's legislature this year for the first time
in more than a century. In the turnover, the committee was revamped
with rural gun rights advocates predominating over urban-suburban
gun control proponents. This is a change Dillard denounces as ``a
stacked deck,'' while Griffith said it mostly reflected the results
of the last election and the state's profile.
</P>
<P>
   In that election, a number of candidates in the northern suburbs
near Washington campaigned on the issue of gun control in the wake
of Columbine. ``They called for restrictions, and that didn't
happen,'' said Baker, the NRA lobbyist, emphasizing the voters'
rejection of a number of such candidates as the Democrats lost
control of the statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The current tenor of the House was suggested in its recent
endorsement of a proposed amendment to secure hunting and fishing
as a state right on a par with free speech. ``There was some fear
that with the animal rights movement and so forth we ought to state
it affirmatively in our constitution,'' Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   Dillard and Griffith agree that the gun issue has long played
out not so much on party lines as on the clashing interests of
rural and urban-suburban lawmakers. In fact, the main sponsor of
the ban on cities suing gun makers was Delegate C. Richard Cranwell
of Roanoke, the House Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of Griffith, a 41-year-old Salem lawyer who enjoys
bird watching, not hunting, the Columbine tragedy ``has put more
emotional energy into this issue.'' But he insists no workable gun
control bill has emerged. The basic problem, he said, is ``more
deep-seated in society'' and involves parental responsibility and
the waning of youth's respect for church and civic institutions.
``I know the answer is not passing new gun laws that don't have any
effect on people determined to commit mass murder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dillard, a deer hunter in his boyhood and a teacher and
principal for 30 years, concedes that, with the mass of ordnance
now routinely available across the nation, aberrant students cannot
be fully foiled from schemes of mass murder. ``But we needed to
send a clear message after Columbine that schools and guns don't
mix,'' he said. ``We proclaim drug-free school zones despite that
continuing problem, and this is the same idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, there is no outright ban on bringing weapons
onto school grounds. Current law provides for possible expulsion of
armed students, but no criminal prosecution unless the guns are
brandished dangerously.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Columbine may have haunted the national debate, state
legislative specialists find no major enactments looming on gun
controls, although ``smart gun'' proposals and other high-tech
alternatives to gun controls are drawing publicity. ``It's the
teeter-totter effect,'' said Kelly Anders, a policy analyst for the
National Conference of State Legislatures, referring to a general
standoff she finds in most statehouses on the issue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Virginia, gun control proponents are not encouraged by the
fact that one change being seriously studied by the militia
committee under the topic of gun controls would liberalize a
current law against weapons in drinking establishments to exclude
restaurants. ``You don't want to be subject to being robbed as you
come out of a family restaurant that people know you can't take a
gun into,'' Griffith explained.
</P>
<P>
   Last year 1,100 firearms bills of various sorts were submitted
to statehouse hoppers, Anders said. Of these, 150 were approved but
the vast majority of these involved noncontroversial administrative
changes affecting law enforcement agencies and other institutions,
not private gun owners. Despite the Columbine uproar, Anders said,
``This year may not be any different than years past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9155 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-MRSCLINTON-ART-8     02-16 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MRSCLINTON-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND MRS. CLINTON: UNUSUAL, POSSIBLY UNEASY, POLITICAL
RELATIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They talk about the same record and initiatives, and
assiduously avoid public discussion of certain shared memories from
their years in Washington. They court the same supporters and seek
money from the same contributors. Last Sunday morning, their
motorcades passed just miles from each other, as they campaigned
for votes in churches and restaurants in Brooklyn and Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the one thing that Vice President Al Gore and Hillary Rodham
Clinton don't talk much about these days is each other. And as Gore
and Mrs. Clinton find themselves forced into close political
quarters in New York in the last weeks before the state's
presidential primary, the relationship between these two Democrats,
both of whom who would like to ride President Clinton's legacy
while they distance themselves from his darker moments, has become
as a complicated work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tussle between two ambitious and not particularly close
public figures trying to stake out space on the same limited stage,
picking and choosing from pieces of the president's record as they
try, in their own ways, to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore speaks often and enthusiastically about President
Clinton, particularly when campaigning in New York, he tends to
discuss Mrs. Clinton only when he is asked, and then with reserve.
``I think she's going to win,'' Gore said last week when an upstate
television interviewer asked if Clinton's Senate campaign helped or
hurt Gore's own presidential effort. ``I think she's going to be a
great senator. I think that her campaign probably helps me. I
really don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   When another television interviewer asked Gore if he would
campaign at Mrs. Clinton's side in New York, he demurred: ``It's a
matter of scheduling. Not just me, but also her. I hope so, but
that's yet to be worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's schedule did not coincide with Mrs. Clinton's during two
days of campaigning in New York this week, though Wednesday night,
after questions were raised about the issue, Gore's aides announced
that an appearance with Mrs. Clinton that had been tentatively
scheduled in Albany, but then dropped to allow for debate
preparation, would take place.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Clinton spoke admiringly in an interview earlier
this month of what she called Gore's ``incredible strides'' as a
candidate after a difficult start, even saying she might borrow
some of the campaign phrases he used in introducing her husband
when they traveled the nation by bus after the 1992 Democratic
convention. Yet some of her senior aides have balked at allowing
her to campaign with Gore too often in the weeks ahead. They were
concerned that while it might aid Gore's presidential aspirations,
it would not help Clinton accomplish her immediate task, which is
to forge an identity separate from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I don't see any need for that,'' said one of
Mrs. Clinton's senior advisers. ``She still has to establish who
she is.''
</P>
<P>
   The wariness on both sides reflects a relationship that is
inherently, and perhaps inevitably, strained. If Gore and Mrs.
Clinton are both reminders of what voters, particularly in New
York, found admirable about President Clinton, they are also
symbols of some the more difficult moments in this White House,
whether it was the investigation into Mrs. Clinton's involvement
with Whitewater or Gore's zealous fund raising. Some Democrats
suggest that the sight of these two candidates together, too often,
can only invite reprises of some of these incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's presence at Mrs. Clinton's side may complicate her effort
to cut her association with the White House and to present herself
as a distinct New Yorker, if a recent one. Conversely, Mrs.
Clinton's presence may complicate Gore's effort in a general
election, should he become his party's nominee, to win the support
of New Yorkers, among them Orthodox Jews and some women. Those two
groups are deeply distrustful of Mrs. Clinton, both campaigns have
found. And if Gore won the New York primary, he most assuredly
would be going after voters who were firmly in the camp of
Clinton's likely Republican opponent, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, an
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also needs to be mindful that he is running in other states
outside New York. Television images of the vice president
campaigning with Mrs. Clinton in New York could be just what the
Republicans ordered in a dozen contested states this November.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, though, there is a relationship of mutual
dependency between these two Democrats. In different ways, and to
different degrees, each needs the other to ensure that they have a
career in politics after Bill Clinton leaves the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are both heirs to the same president and he's a president
who won New York state by huge margins, twice,'' said Phil
Friedman, a political strategist. ``For either of them to try to
deny their affiliation with the president _ or their affiliation or
affinity with each other _ would be a mistake.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is in Gore's immediate interest, his advisers have concluded,
to have Mrs. Clinton campaign with him in New York before the
primary. Whatever problems Mrs. Clinton might have with the general
electorate, polling by both sides suggests that she is
extraordinarily popular among kind of Democrats who vote in
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The tables seem likely to turn after March 7, assuming that Gore
wins the Democratic nomination. Advisers to both campaigns believe
that Mrs. Clinton will need a strong showing by Gore in New York to
help pull her across the finish line. In this view, Gore will need
to do for Mrs. Clinton what Lyndon B. Johnson did for another
newcomer to New York politics, Robert F. Kennedy, in 1964 when
Johnson's landslide victory lifted Kennedy to a narrow win as
senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the competition and relationship between Mrs.
Clinton and Gore is less prickly than it might have been. There is
a history of competition between them, said one administration
official. The two were known for squabbling over which one of them
would get to fill in for President Clinton at high-profile events.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when some Democrats thought that Mrs. Clinton
would come under pressure to campaign for Gore and against former
Sen. Bill Bradley, his Democratic opponent, at the risk of
alienating Bradley's supporters. However, Gore's advisers have
become increasingly confident of victory in New York, and thus have
been able to avoid inveighing on Mrs. Clinton in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   In this low-pressure environment, aides to both Gore and Mrs.
Clinton went to some lengths Wednesday night to say that the two
campaigns were prepared to cooperate in the months ahead for a
Democratic victory. To this end, they noted that both candidates
had picked the same building to locate their state headquarters, a
high-rise across from Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But not the same space. Gore's headquarters can be found on the
fifth floor. For Clinton, push eight.
</P>
</TEXT>
