<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW JONES FALLS; NASDAQ RISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks stood their ground Wednesday but
the rest of the market declined as investors awaited January
inflation figures and Alan Greenspan's assessment of the economy
with its implications for Federal Reserve monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of broad gains, the split between high-tech and
so-called old-economy stocks re-emerged. The Dow Jones industrial
average lost 156.68 points, or 1.46 percent, to 10,561.41, while
the tech-heavy Nasdaq composite index gained 6.88 points, to
4,427.65. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 14.38 points,
or 1.03 percent, to 1,387.67.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip Dow has lost 8.14 percent so far this year and is
9.91 percent below its Jan. 14 peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's clearly a notion that the Fed eventually will be
successful in slowing the economy, but it's a question of at what
cost,'' said Ned Riley Jr., chief investment strategist at State
Street Global Advisors. For companies sensitive to the business
cycle, he added, ``the market seems to be discounting almost
recession-like conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most prominent casualties was Wal-Mart, which slumped
5 1/4, to 52 3/4, as investors further digested company warnings
that recent sparkling results, announced Tuesday, would be hard to
beat. It did not help that Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch reported
disappointing holiday sales, sending that stock down 4 1/4, to 15
1/4, a two-year low.
</P>
<P>
   ``The retail stocks have totally rolled over,'' said Marion
Schultheis, a portfolio manager at J&AMP;W Seligman. Intimate Brands
slumped 3 7/16, to 31 1/16, and Limited 2 11/16, to 31 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot fell 3, to 56 3/4, seeming to also suffer from fears
of how high the Fed might have to push interest rates to cool off
an overheated economy. A report of surprisingly strong housing
starts Wednesday added to such concern.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks took a pounding, with American Express off 5
9/32, to 153 27/32, and Merrill Lynch, Goldman Sachs and J.P.
Morgan all losing more than 3.
</P>
<P>
   But technology largely withstood the decline, with
Hewlett-Packard the best-performing Dow stock, rising 3 15/16, to
129 1/16, as investors anticipated its earnings report after the
close. The stock subsequently climbed to 131 as investors appeared
to focus more on rising revenue than on slipping profits.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology was especially strong, spurred partly by Human
Genome Sciences, up 33 1/4, to 188, which patented a gene that
could help create drugs to treat AIDS. Amgen climbed 4 13/16, to 69
7/8; Hyseq 8 1/8 to 99; and Targeted Genetics 7 3/16, to 19 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Secondary technology stocks were a big factor in the rise of the
small-cap Russell 2000 to a record 547.76, ahead 1.39 percent for
the day and 8.52 percent for the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
