<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-THEBIGPICTURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MAN'S TAKE ON HOLLYWOOD IS SIMPLY NOT ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Big Picture: Who Killed Hollywood? &AMP; Other Essays'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By William Goldman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Essays/memoir &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Applause, $23.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a screenwriter, William Goldman is one of the best in the
business. Films such as ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid, All
the President's Men, The Princess Bride'' and ``Misery'' are just a
few of the gems on his screenwriting resume.
</P>
<P>
   As an essayist, William Goldman is, well, one of the best
screenwriters in the business. His new collection, ``The Big
Picture,'' an assortment of pieces published in ``Premiere, The
Daily News, New York'' and ``Los Angeles Magazine,'' is engaging
for film fans who might enjoy snickering at after-the-fact Oscar
predictions or studio chiefs' picks for several summers'
``sure-fire'' hits. But for anyone looking for a little historical
perspective on the business of making movies, ``The Big Picture''
has about as much depth as the collected works of Jim Mullen's Hot
Sheet from ``Entertainment Weekly.''
</P>
<P>
   On their own, these essays may have been amusing to read while
flipping through the pages of ``Premiere,'' but Goldman's
frequently updated list of the biggest stars in the world, his
blockbuster forecasts for summer and Christmas, his pleas for
tolerance for the increasingly annoying Academy Awards ceremony
each year, seem not only outdated and irrelevant, but also
naggingly short on insight.
</P>
<P>
   This is the guy who wrote things such as ``Marathon Man, The
Great Waldo Pepper'' and ``The Stepford Wives.'' We should expect a
little more depth than a bunch of off-the-record quotes from
unnamed studio executives. Worst of all, when sandwiched
back-to-back, the pieces aren't only uninteresting, they're
redundant, with Goldman recycling some of the same ideas and even
the same phrases to remake his points.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong, I enjoyed listening to studio honchos talk
about how ``The Last Action Hero'' (which is a less-than-stellar
item on the Goldman resume) was gonna stomp ``Jurassic Park,'' but
that smirk subsides after a few pages of nothing but more of the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's at his most interesting when he strays from the
formula of the annual offerings he's obviously been contracted to
write. His fond remembrance after the death of Andre the Giant was
nice, recounting stories about working with the professional
wrestler on ``The Princess Bride,'' but it barely fills three
pages. The rest of this 280-plus-page volume amounts to little more
than a glorified collection of lists.
</P>
<P>
   If I want to read lists, I'll hold out for the next collection
of ``Letterman'' Top 10s.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
