<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RUDD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDD THINKING TITLE WITH NEW TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Ricky Rudd's priorities have changed.
</P>
<P>
   The past six years were about survival. This year is about
winning.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd lost his sponsor and sold his 6-year-old race team after
last season, giving up his independence as one of the few remaining
owner-drivers in NASCAR Winston Cup racing. But in return, Rudd
gained an opportunity for his first points championship when he
joined Robert Yates Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just spent the past three or four years with a sponsor that
wasn't big enough to do the job right,'' Rudd, 43, said. ``I didn't
want to go down that road again. I finally had to ask myself what I
really wanted out of this. The answers were I knew my career was
winding down. I don't have 20 years left in the sport. I don't have
time to build a championship team for myself. I think it would take
probably longer than I've got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've set a three-year plan, and frankly, I don't know if that
could have been built in time if I had the support. I know we could
make vast improvements, but I don't know if we could actually
challenge for the championship. So then you've got Robert's team
sitting here that really all the key ingredients are here. The
chemistry just has to come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing Tide, the sponsor of his No. 10 team, to new Winston Cup
team owner Cal Wells might have been the best thing to happen to
Rudd. Instead of worrying about the bottom line, Rudd now is
focused on the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd had a chance to win Sunday's Bud Shootout before a last-lap
crash sent him sliding down the front straightaway on his roof,
and, having posted the second-fastest qualifying time, he will
start the Daytona 500 outside of teammate Dale Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can promise you one thing,'' said Tony Stewart, driver of
the No. 20 Home Depot Pontiac, ``Ricky Rudd hasn't forgotten how to
drive a race car. I'm sure they'll do real well this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year marked the first time since 1982 that Rudd failed to
win a race, but he has not lost his way to Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd's 20 victories in 661 Winston Cup starts won over Yates,
who hired Rudd to replace Kenny Irwin after Irwin's two winless
seasons in the No. 28 Ford. Now, Rudd has one of the best engine
programs in the business behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky Rudd wins races,'' Yates said. ``He's been a really good
competitor. If we give him good equipment, I don't see why we can't
be in the chase for wins and championships. If the car doesn't run
good, all fingers will be pointed at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yates is counting on becoming the next Rick Hendrick, who has
won four of the past five points championships with drivers Terry
Labonte and Jeff Gordon. Rudd wants to follow Jarrett, who last
season, at the age of 42, won his first championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tools, the people and everything is in place,'' said Rudd,
who finished a career-best second in the points in 1991 while
driving for Hendrick. ``Will it jell quick enough? There are no
guarantees in this business. But I can't think anything we're
lacking other than some time for it to come together.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
