A9159 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-SWORDANDSHIELD-T     02-16 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SWORDANDSHIELD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALPHABET SOUP MAKES A SHAMBLES OF AN IMPORTANT BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAT TRULY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Sword and the Shield: The Mitrokhin Archive and the Secret
History of the KGB' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Christopher Andrew and Vasili Mitrokhin &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Espionage history &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Basic Books &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $32.50 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sword and the Shield'' is an important book. It also is a
difficult book to read, and difficult to recommend (though, since
it has made some bestseller lists, sales indicate that no
recommendation is needed). The problem is in the way authors
Christopher Andrew and Vasili Mitrokhin included a confusing welter
of acronyms, thus making the reader's job a tough one.
</P>
<P>
   And that is a real shame. The book is taken from extensive, very
secret files of the Soviet intelligence-slash-security agencies
that evolved from the Cheka of Lenin's day through OGPU, NKVD and
MVD to the more recent KGB. Mitrokhin, a KGB officer, stealthily
stole these files over several years. They provide valuable insight
into the Soviet intelligence community, Soviet leaders, Western
intelligence shortcomings and successes, and the reasons for the
eventual collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   A constant thread is the inability of a succession of Soviet top
bosses, from Stalin through Gorbachev, to understand the West, and
thus to draw proper conclusions from the intelligence being
gathered by their agents. As the authors say of the early World War
II period, ``Stalin's understanding of British policy was so
distorted by conspiracy theory that no amount of good intelligence
was likely to enlighten him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev, in the mid-1980s, was ``the first postwar Soviet
leader who gained access to moderately accurate statistics on the
performance of the Soviet economy.'' What followed, when Gorbachev
finally learned the truth about his nation's no-growth economy, is
history.
</P>
<P>
   Other important insight is gained into the role of Pope John
Paul II in the downfall of communism and into the success the
Soviets had in penetrating U.S. defense industries during the Cold
War (much more so than in penetrating U.S. government), and the
ways in which Sen. Joe McCarthy inadvertently ``helped'' Soviet
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Valuable and comprehensive as it is, ``The Sword and the
Shield'' surely would profit from fewer code names (does the reader
really care that the NKVD's man in Marshal Tito's camp was
code-named VAZHDUH, or that British traitor Anthony Burgess was
called MADCHEN?). Putting all agents' code names, plus the names of
agencies and operations, in all-capital acronyms makes for hard
going. It is almost as though the authors wanted to write their
book in code.
</P>
<P>
   (Pat Truly is a retired ``Star-Telegram'' editorial writer.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0408 </DOCNO>
