<HEADLINE>
ARBITRATION HEARING PROBABLE AS RANGERS, STEVENS FAR APART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ With negotiations non-existent, the Rangers
are headed to an arbitration hearing with designated hitter Lee
Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an unexpected settlement, the two sides will convene in
front of a three-man arbitration panel at 8:30 a.m. tomorrow in
Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a word spoken between us,'' said Alan Nero,
Stevens' agent. ``At this point I don't think there will be any
negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who made $2.1 million last season, is asking for $4.7
million. The Rangers are offering $3.5 million. Rangers general
manager Doug Melvin said the difference is so significant that it's
difficult to come up with a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of the process,'' Melvin said. ``We'll just go
down there and present our case and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who played most of the season at first base because of
Rafael Palmeiro's knee injury, hit .282 last year with a
career-high 24 home runs and 81 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers usually avoid arbitration hearings because of the
hard feelings they can generate. Melvin has had one since he became
general manager in 1994, with catcher Ivan Rodriguez in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business,'' Nero said. ``Doug has to do what he thinks
is best for the club, and I have to do what's best for Lee Stevens.
There are no hard feelings; when it's over we'll go about our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Frank Casey will present the case for the Rangers while
Barry Meister, who works with Nero, will present Steven's case. The
panel must pick one of the two figures submitted. Melvin and
Stevens are both expected to be at the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   There were 158 players eligible for arbitration but most settled
without a hearing. There have been seven hearings so far with the
players winning four. There are five cases still to be heard,
including Stevens'. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
