<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-NUPTIAL-DERBY-TEX     02-16 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NUPTIAL-DERBY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE COME THE (POTENTIAL) BRIDES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday: 7 p.m., the Fox network &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The publicist nearly yells into her cell phone. ``I am not
supposed to talk to the press. I am only a publicist.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind her, strains of the Wedding March loudly start and stop,
start and stop. It's rehearsal day for the Fox network special
``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, a lot of women want to form a lifetime bond with a
multimillionaire they know nothing about. ``Thousands'' of women
applied to be on the special, which airs at 7 p.m. Tuesday on the
Fox network. Only 50 women were selected, creating a flurry of
prenuptial agreements that Fox's legal counsel required them all to
sign. The publicist, still yelling on a cell phone over wedding
music, will not discuss the terms of the prenuptials.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the wacky 21st-century version of arranged marriage.
</P>
<P>
   During a two-hour prime-time TV special, a rich man will select
one of the 50 women, then legally marry her on the air. The basis
for the marriage is wealth, looks, a male-controlled relationship
and a superficial knowledge of each other's lives. What could go
wrong?
</P>
<P>
   The brides-elect were selected using criteria set by the
potential groom, says the publicity person who publicizes shows
without using her name. The criteria are a closely kept secret at
Fox. The groom was selected from what the stealth-publicity person
said were 100 ``real-life'' multimillionaires who just hadn't been
able to find the right woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just really ready to make a commitment. He's fed up with
conventional methods of dating,'' the publicity person says.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional methods of dating work well for lots of folks.
What's the matter with this rich guy? The publicist won't say. She
says only that his identity is to remain a secret, even to the
contestants, at least until partway through the show.
</P>
<P>
   The publicist says the show will be run like a ``personality
pageant,'' which most of us know as beauty pageants. The women will
select their own wardrobes and apply their own makeup, so the groom
will have a better chance of learning something about them, the
publicist says.
</P>
<P>
   The groom will have a chance to ask the women questions and talk
to their friends and relatives. It's a little like ``The Dating
Game,'' only with more serious consequences. Gradually, through
elimination rounds, the field will be narrowed to five women, one
of whom he will pick as a supposedly lifetime mate.
</P>
<P>
   The women who will participate are not the same ones you may
have seen on TV promotions for the special, the publicist says.
Those supermodel-looking women on the promotions were models. Fox
didn't want to use the real potential brides in the ads because it
didn't want to influence the potential groom. After all, he might
have started choosing early during commercial breaks in ``The
X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   The groom will be required to sign a prenuptial agreement to
protect his bride from him, should he try to take her financial
assets, the publicity person says. Although, if a woman had
financial assets equal to his, why would she humiliate herself this
way? Why would she go off on her honeymoon feeling like a
refrigerator or something else he won on ``The Price Is Right?''
</P>
<P>
   The publicist says the women are saying it just sounds like a
``fun and crazy'' thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they scared?'' this reporter yells back to the publicist
through the static in the airwaves between Fort Worth and Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she says. ``I don't think it's really sunk in for them
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   All this is not as bad as it sounds, the Fox person says. The
groom will get to ask direct questions of the women. And he'll
still get to rely on ``love at first sight.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like an organized bar pickup, broadcast nationwide,
with commercials. But we shouldn't bother being too horrified by
all of this, a Fort Worth marriage counselor says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's indicative of anything in our culture but
media hype, with some women being victimized in the process,'' says
Douglas Weiss, of Heart to Heart Counseling Centers in Fort Worth.
``It doesn't reflect anything about the state of marriage. It only
shows there are 50 women desperate enough to believe that marrying
someone with money is better than marrying someone without.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' is planned as a
one-time-only event, thank goodness. OK, I'll watch, just to see if
any ideas about the gravity of their situation sinks in for these
women. Do they know the price of everything and the value of
nothing? Quietly, I'll be rooting for the selected bride to turn
him down. If not, I'll wait for the sequel, ``Who Wants to Divorce
a Multi-Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
