u a BC-OIL-STRATEGY-BOS &LR;      02-16 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-STRATEGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY CHIEF ADMITS US SURPRISED BY OIL-PRICE CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ US Energy Secretary Bill Richardson released funds
Tuesday to help low-income households pay fuel bills and called for
more homes to be heated with natural gas, steps he hopes will make
up for lost time after the Clinton administration was ``caught
napping'' as heating oil prices skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   The near tripling of heating oil prices in the Northeast this
month has made energy a hot political issue in New England, even
though prices had remained relatively low for a decade. The
governors of Massachusetts and New Hampshire, four members of
Congress, and nearly 300 observers came to Boston's Fanueil Hall
Tuesday for a summit meeting on how to prevent future oil-price
shocks.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson conceded that his agency had failed to predict the
oil-price hikes _ one of the steepest fuel price rises in the
United States since 1970. This slowed the government's response, he
said, as thousands of consumer complaints poured in, and energy
programs for low-income New England residents were overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   The root cause of the crisis is the rising cost of oil imported
from countries that belong to OPEC, said Richardson. He said he
would go to the Middle East next week to persuade major oil
exporters to increase the oil supply to the United States, thus
lowering the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the message. We were unprepared, but we have a
plan,'' said Richardson at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's promise to undertake ``energy diplomacy,'' coupled
with President Clinton's release of $125 million in low- income
energy assistance at an afternoon press conference, drew praise
from New England officials, including Sen. John Kerry (D-MA), who
had pushed for more energy aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're on the right track,'' said Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   However, consumer advocates such as Joseph P. Kennedy II,
president of Citizens Energy Corporation, wanted tougher actions,
including more regulation of the heating oil industry. He said oil
wholesalers should be required to keep a reserve oil supply to
prevent fuel shortages in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can blame OPEC. We can blame conspiracies . . . We can
blame whoever you want, but, at the end of the day, if you don't
have oil in the tanks in Massachusetts . . . when it gets cold, the
price is going to go up,'' declared Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Energy analysts warned that the heating oil fight may foreshadow
energy debates to come as world oil prices rise from their historic
lows of the 1990s. The combination of growing oil demand in a
booming world economy and a strengthened OPEC spells trouble for
the US, which imports half its oil.
</P>
<P>
   New England is uniquely sensitive to the price of heating oil,
which this week slid back to $1.56 a gallon from a high of more
than $2.
</P>
<P>
   Three quarters of all US heating oil is consumed on the eastern
seaboard from Maine to Virginia, while the rest of the nation heats
mainly with gas. Because of the colder New England weather and the
older, more drafty buildings, oil customers in New England may be
the most vulnerable to price hikes of all, because they use so much
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly three hours, Richardson got an earful on the damage
from the price increase that began during a mid-January cold snap,
forcing Massachusetts residents to pay at least $150 million extra
for heating oil. In addition to tales of poor and elderly people
struggling to make ends meet, 40 truckers attended the summit to
protest a rise in the price of diesel fuel, which is similar to
heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci said the oil crisis could have
been even worse, noting that New England had only a two weeks'
supply of oil left in the region on Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had had a blizzard followed by a cold snap, we would not
have had enough oil to keep all consumers warm,'' he said. ``This
margin of safety is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to ensure that what happened this winter in New
England never happens again,'' added New Hampshire Governor Jeanne
Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Energy Information Administration, which
provides energy forecasts at the Department of Energy, warned in
December that heating oil reserves were ``skating on thin ice''
because they were unusually low for the start of the heating
season.
</P>
<P>
   However, critics say the Clinton Administration made few
preparations to cope in the event of an unexpectedly cold winter.
As Northeastern politicians demanded action, the White House
considered, and then shelved, a proposal to release oil from the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve, intended for national emergencies, to
boost the supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of bold, decisive action from the White House, we have
heard a deafening silence in terms of serious actions which would
protect the people of the Northeast,'' said US Rep. Bernard Sanders
(I-Vt.), who wants a federal heating oil reserve to be set up in
New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, however, Richardson and Clinton unveiled a series of
steps intended to ease the crisis now, and to prevent a repeat in
the future:
</P>
<P>
   -- Clinton released the low-income heating assistance money,
including $13.1 million for Massachusetts and $19.2 million for the
rest of New England.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Department of Energy will report to Clinton in 60 days on
ways to reduce New England's reliance on heating oil, with a
special emphasis on improving access to natural gas supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If gas pipelines are needed, we are prepared to go to Congress
and work for them,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Transportation Department will relax regulations that
limit the number of oil deliveries trucks can make as part of a
three-year experiment.
</P>
<P>
   -- Richardson will meet with energy ministers in Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, Mexico and Norway to emphasize the need for more oil
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reminding our energy trading partners that our
relationship goes both ways,'' said Richardson. ``High oil prices
are bad for everyone . . . What we need is price stability.''
</P>
<P>
   But several speakers at Tuesday's summit told the audience that
the fundamental problem is this country's inability to reduce oil
imports. Despite three recessions since 1973 triggered by rising
imported oil prices, import levels have actually risen in recent
years, fueled in part by consumer demand for high-energy using
motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Oil industry officials at the summit called for an increase in
American oil production to reduce the imports. That would mean
allowing oil explorers into areas now closed for environmental
reasons or easing environmental regulations that have forced some
refineries to close down altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those refineries were still in operation, we wouldn't be
here today,'' said John Felmy, chief economist for the American
Petroleum Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Kerry countered that it would be better to increase
use of renewable energies, such as wind power and solar power,
while increasing energy conservation measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been on a remarkably indulgent and in some ways lucky
ride over the past few years,'' Kerry said. ``This in some ways is
a useful wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   Massood Samii, OPEC's former senior economist and now a business
professor at New Hampshire College, said Americans need a wake-up
call because oil-price increases aren't going away. He said
Richardson might well succeed in convincing OPEC to increase
supplies this summer, but, by fall, world economic growth will have
more than offset the gain, causing further price hikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This problem is going to be with us for some time,'' said
Samii, who worked for OPEC from 1979 to 1987.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
