u l BC-CHILDREN-TEXAS17-COX     02-16 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-TEXAS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Group blames Bush for making quality of life worse for Texas
children
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, who has dubbed himself the
``compassionate conservative'' on the presidential campaign trail,
has done little to improve the health and welfare of poor children
in his home state, said officials of the Texas Freedom Network.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush official disputed the charge by the group, which opposed
vouchers in public schools and social conservative candidates in
State Board of Education elections.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Texas Freedom Network, moving into new
political terrain, took aim at Bush, blaming him for the state's
slip in a national ranking as the best place to raise a child. In
1999, Texas ranked next to last _ 48th _ for the best place to
raise a child in the United States. That is down from 29th in 1995,
the year Bush took office. The ranking was done by the Children's
Rights Council in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``When children in the rest of the country have seen their lives
improve, Texas kids have become poorer, hungrier, more likely to
become parents, more likely to die of gun violence and less likely
to have health insurance,'' said Samantha Smoot, executive director
of the Texas Freedom Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``How dare he (Bush) speak of closing the gap of hope for
American's families when he's closed the door of hope for so many
Texas children?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan disputed the charge, citing Texas
schoolchildren's progress on achievement tests and the
Legislature's passage of a health insurance program aimed at
providing coverage for children of the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is a reformer with a record of closing the
opportunity gap by improving public schools so every child can
learn and succeed and moving families from welfare to work and
reaching out to faith-based groups to help those in need, and
lowering taxes for working families,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Texas Freedom Network has focused on halting
social conservatives' reach into Texas public schools. Smoot said
the nonpartisan group will reposition itself as a family-issues
organization, pursuing legislation to improve children's health and
welfare in the 2001 legislative session. The group was formed in
1994 by Cecile Richards, daughter of former Texas Democratic Gov.
Ann Richards.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rising test scores for minority and low-income students,
Smoot said conditions for poor children in Texas are worsening. She
cited statistics from the group's newly-released report which show:
</P>
<P>
   _ One in four Texas children lives in poverty; nationwide, one
in 5 children lives in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   _ About 1.4 million Texas children _ a higher number than any
other state _ are uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor George W. Bush seems remarkably unaware of how Texans
actually live,'' Smoot said. ``Bush sees a packed emergency room
and thinks that means that the one in four Texas children without
health insurance must be getting basic medical care.''
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said Bush worked with legislators in 1999 to pass the
Children's Health Insurance Program, aimed at insuring more
children of the working poor. ``By 2001, an additional 423,000
(children) will be insured,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
