<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9164 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-OIL-1STLD-WRI     02-16 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OIL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RELEASES $125 MILLION MORE FOR HOME-HEATING OIL
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: New England, Ill.)  (Eds: UPDATES throughout with more from news conference; note
byline change.)  
(See also OIL-PRICES) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT9-10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARC LACEY and DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton pledged even more money for
Northeasterners grappling with the soaring cost of home heating oil
Wednesday, even while he acknowledged that federal heating
assistance funds may not be adequate to help low-income families
endure the winter.
</P>
<P>
   In his first news conference of the year, Clinton touched on the
political campaigns of his wife and his vice president, and left
the door open to a visit to Pakistan next month. But he focused
much of his attention on the spike in heating oil prices, saying he
would order that the remaining $125 million in a Low Income Home
Energy Assistance Program be made immediately available _ on top of
$200 million already released _ and would seek from Congress $600
million in additional emergency funds for states hardest hit by the
cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last seven years, we've stood to help the victims of
earthquakes in California, of the farm crisis and a 500-year flood
in the Middle West,'' Clinton said. ``Now the families in the
Northeast need our help, too, and we must act.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the funding increases, Clinton also called on the
states to liberalize the income limits so that more families could
receive the federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stopped short of ordering any release of oil from the
government's Strategic Petroleum Reserve, even though a growing
chorus of officials in the Northeast have urged that the oil be put
on the market to depress prices. But the president said he had not
ruled out tapping into the emergency reserve later.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting with consumer groups and industry leaders in Boston
on Wednesday, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson admitted that the
federal government was caught by surprise by the rise in oil
prices. ``It is obvious that the federal government was not
prepared. We were caught napping,'' he said. ``We got complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton fielded 20 questions over the course of an hour,
insisting that he did not want to involve himself in either the
presidential race or his wife's run for senator from New York. But
he could not help himself.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how it felt to be used as a rhetorical punching bag by
Republican presidential candidates, Clinton said he wasn't
surprised that the Republicans were eager to attack him personally.
``They can't run against the longest economic expansion in history,
or the lowest crime rate in 30 years, or the lowest welfare roles
in 30 years,'' he said, ticking off his familiar litany of rosy
statistics and expressing ``sympathy'' for the position they find
themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy, Clinton held out the possibility that he
would extend a trip to India and Bangladesh next month to include a
stop in Pakistan _ a move that would put him at the center of one
of the tensest nuclear standoffs in the world today. Originally
Clinton had hoped to visit both India and Pakistan, but the
military coup in Islamabad led to the conclusion that he could not
appear to be giving legitimacy to military leaders who overthrew a
democratically elected government.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, the administration has been telling the
Pakistanis that if they want Clinton to visit _ a trip the Secret
Service has insisted ought to last only a few hours _ they must
announce a timetable for a return to democratic elections and some
steps toward curbing terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will make a decision about whether to go based on what I
think will best serve the long-term interests in nonproliferation
and trying to stop, particularly, a nuclear arms race,'' Clinton
said Wednesday. ``The very real danger that a conflict between
India and Pakistan not contained is one of the most significant
security threats to the interest of the United States in this new
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that the United States would step in to act as a
mediator in the long-running India-Pakistan dispute over Kashmir,
but only if both countries asked. ``Unless we are asked by both
parties to help, we can't get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also pressed Congress to move quickly on granting China
permanent trading status with the United States, under the deal
struck late last year to permit China into the World Trade
Organization. For the past two decades Congress has extended that
trading status year-by-year, and used the run-up to those votes to
highlight Chinese human rights violations, trade barriers to
American goods and military threats to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate has become an empty one: Each year Congress has
relented to overwhelming pressure from American businesses, which
say they would lose billions if the trade status was not extended.
Under the WTO rules, Congress would no longer have a choice: It
could not keep China on a year-by-year string, constantly
threatening to yank its trading privileges.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tried Wednesday, as he has in private meetings this week
with members of Congress, to make a broader case. ``This is a huge
national security issue,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trade agreement offers no increased access to the
American markets by China, but gives us dramatically increased
access to their markets. Moreover, it means we can get access to
their markets without having to transfer technology or agree to do
manufacturing in their country.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, American officials say they expect that, as a
practical matter, China will continue to get technology and more
American manufacturing presence.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that China's entry into the trade group would force
the country to accept the rule of law, and not only in commercial
disputes. ``They are far more likely to be constructive members of
the international community if they get into the WTO and they make
these changes than if they don't,'' he argued.
</P>
<P>
   On the domestic front, Clinton reiterated his call for
congressional action on gun control legislation this year and said
he saw no reason for the federal government to follow the state of
Illinois in calling a temporary halt to executions. Gov. George
Ryan of Illinois took that action after 13 inmates on death row
were exonerated over two decades.
</P>
<P>
   By providing more heating oil money, Clinton sought to dampen
the growing calls for more expansive action. Those pushing for a
release of some of the country's oil reserves include members of
both parties, including Hillary Rodham Clinton's rival in the New
York Senate race, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has been airing
television ads on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the president's announcement, Sen. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., criticized Clinton's action as not going far
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help the 1 million New Yorkers who benefit from this
program,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that dispensing more money from the oil fund ``will
not provide long-term relief for the price hikes that we are seeing
in heating oil bills and will soon see at the gas pump.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
