<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BONDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE ATTEMPTS TO EASE SEC BOND INQUIRY CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL REZENDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Cellucci administration downplayed the significance
Tuesday of a Securities and Exchange Commission inquiry into a
December bond prospectus that made no mention of a $1.4 billion
cost overrun for the Big Dig highway project, maintaining that
officials adequately disclosed information about state finances.
</P>
<P>
   But bond buyers and others familiar with the SEC say the probe
comes at a time when the agency is making a special effort to crack
down on state and local officials and underwriters who violate
disclosure requirements in the offering statements for sales of
municipal bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Maco, director of the SEC's Office of Municipal Securities,
declined to acknowledge the existence of the Massachusetts probe.
But he said the agency has taken action 95 times in the last six
years in municipal bond sales and that most of the cases involved
lapses in disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Commission has concentrated its resources in the municipal
market over the last six years emphasizing the disclosure
obligations of all parties involved in municipal security
offerings,'' Maco said.
</P>
<P>
   And SEC chairman Arthur Levitt, in a speech to municipal bond
officials last fall, said, ``The message to investors and the
municipal market should be clear _ our Enforcement Division is now
a permanent part of the municipal landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Administration and Finance Secrtary Andew S. Natsios
said said that while the SEC has jurisdiction over underwiters and
bond lawyers, ``they don't have any jurisdiction over state
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   But the agency has routinely moved against public officials in
cases where they did not fully disclose the financial condition of
their governments, including officials of Orange County,
California, which declared bankruptcy in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   That case prompted the SEC to increase its focus on disclosure
in the municipal bond market and led the the creation of its Office
of Municipal Securities. Since then, SEC officials have launched
disclosure inquiries in Washington, D.C., Syracuse, and Denver,
among other jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   Maco said the SEC has civil, not criminal, authority over
government officials and bond sellers, and typically issues a
``cease and desist'' order when it finds that public officials or
bond underwriters are untruthful in their offering statements or
fail to fully disclose financial information.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency has also refered criminal matters to the US
Department of Justice. And some SEC inquiries appear to have paved
the way for lawsuits filed by filed by private investors against
goverment entities and their bond underwriters who failed to fully
disclose their financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in 1997 brokerage houses that sold more than $3
billion in bonds to build Denver International Airport agreed to an
out-of-court financial settlement to a lawsuit brought by private
investors who claimed they were defrauded by officials who
allegedly failed to fully disclose information about revenue
projections and construction delays.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ladd, undersecretary of Administration and Finance, said
Tuesday that no lawsuits have been filed by investors in the wake
of a $200 million December municipal bond offering for the MBTA
that made no mention of Big Dig cost overruns in a description of
Massachusetts finances.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a prospectus, or offering statement, for a $500
million issue of general obligation municipal bonds this month
provides a detailed explanation of the projected $1.4 billion
overrun on the $12.2 billion Central Artery/Ted Williams Tunnel
Project.
</P>
<P>
   Although the SEC has neither confirmed nor denied that a
Massachusetts inquiry is underway, sources say the probe was
prompted after state officials including Massachusetts Turnpike
Authority Chairman James J. Kerasiotes said they had information
about a potential cost overrun as early as October.
</P>
<P>
   And while Cellucci administration officials are attempting to
discount the SEC probe, State Treasurer Shannon O'Brien said her
office has a different view.
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Brien spokesman Dwight Robson: ``The treasurer takes any
inquiry from the federal government seriously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
