<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MUGGER-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      02-16 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUGGER-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER EXONERATED IN SHOOTING OF YOUNG MUGGING SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY AND TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. -- Ten months after the fatal shooting of an
unarmed 14-year-old African-American suspect by a white police
officer enflamed racial tensions in Hartford, the outside
prosecutor's investigation that was demanded by members of the
minority community came down squarely on the side of the officer.
</P>
<P>
   Guiding the public through the nine tense minutes that led up to
the shooting through the eyes of Officer Robert Allan, New London
State's attorney Kevin Kane said he found that Allan's act was that
of a police officer with a reasonable fear that Aquan Salmon was
about to shoot him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A boy has been killed, a young boy, who was unarmed. It's a
tragedy for the community. It's a tragedy because it has focused on
what the community perceives as a rift between it and the police
department,'' Kane said. He added, though, that ``it's not
symptomatic of anything except the danger that police officers and
citizens can find themselves in.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 200-page report has not laid to rest lingering anger
about Salmon's killing, which some here see as an echo to the
police shooting of Amadou Diallo -- another unarmed black man --
that occured weeks earlier in New York City. As Public Safety
Commissioner Henry Lee spoke about the likely trajectory of the
bullet that pierced the front and back of Salmon's quilted parka,
George Cruz, one of the community leaders who had pressed Governor
John Rowland to appoint the probe, stood up from his chair and
walked out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything they said is `most likely, possibly,' '' said Cruz,
director of the San Juan recreation center in downtown Hartford.
``I don't like those words. Maybe this thing should go to trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Kane's presentation aimed to put members of the public into
Allan's shoes at 2:01 a.m. on April 13, 1999, when Allan responded
to a report of robberies by four young black men driving a white
Cadillac. Slides recreated the vacant lot where the Cadillac came
to a halt and its four occupants scattered. The p.a. system
replayed Allan's voice as he called, ``Bailing, bailing,'' to
report that they had scattered into the dark and, 16 seconds later,
when he reported that he had heard gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   Allan didn't actually hear gunshots, because none of the four
young men had guns. The first young man Allan saw in the lot was
carrying a cigarette lighter fashioned to look like a pistol, and
when Allan spun around at the sound he mistook for a shot, he saw
Aquan Salmon coming around a tree at an angle that obscured his
right side. According to Allan's testimony, Salmon did not respond
to his order to freeze, kept running and reached across his body
from his beltline. From a distance of 10 feet, Allan shot the boy
through the back, the bullet puncturing both lungs and his heart
and exiting through the front of his chest, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Kane said Allan was justified in shooting Salmon according to a
section in Connecticut's General Statutes, which allow officers to
use deadly force to defend themselves against deadly force.
</P>
<P>
   ``A police officer doesn't have to wait to see a gun pointed
toward him or her or pointed even at him or her before the police
officer decides to shoot, otherwise you wouldn't have too many
police officers around,'' Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   After Kane made his remarks, Hartford's mayor, Mike Peters, said
he hoped the report would be part of the city's long healing
process. ``Nobody wins in a situation like this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But many in Hartford long ago formed their own opinions about
that night, and the long wait for Kane's results has not made them
any more receptive. During the week after the shooting, marchers
carried a silver coffin to the site where he was shot, and black
and Latino organizers cast the event as symptomatic of tensions in
a mostly non-white city whose police force is mostly white.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the straw that broke the camel's back,'' Cruz said.
``We have to get more minorities, as opposed to people from the
suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who lobbied most actively for action against Allan said
the Kane report contained little to sway them, and looked beyond
this investigation toward possible civil rights charges. Among them
is city councilwoman Elizabeth Horton Sheff, who called Tuesday for
the police officer's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get a real surprise,'' said Wadell Muhammed, one of
number of community leaders who protested after the shooting. ``But
we would have expected that at least he be indicted. We think the
evidence represented today was enough to dictate an indictment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
