<HEADER>
A9169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BISHOP-FLADIOCESE17-C     02-16 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHOP-FLADIOCESE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New bishop `inspires hope' after scandal
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In a cramped confessional at St. Rita
Catholic Church, Bishop Anthony J. O'Connell gingerly lowers his
bulky frame into a chair, steadying his lower back with his right
hand on the way down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinched nerve,'' he says. ``Of course, I got it two days ago,
just before the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinched or not, a half-hour later, O'Connell is standing _
6-foot wooden shepherd's crook in hand, 2-foot white miter on head
_ in front of a packed sanctuary, dropping one-liners in his Irish
brogue to the delight of about 1,200 Sunday-morning worshipers.
</P>
<P>
   With the Wellington, Fla., congregation relaxed, O'Connell moves
to themes of forgiveness and redemption. His message is simple,
straightforward and, for a community trying to move past its
disappointment with the last bishop, resonant.
</P>
<P>
   A year after arriving from Nashville, Tenn., O'Connell, 61, has
tried to heal his diocese by concentrating on the future instead of
the past. He keeps himself so busy that he has spent little time
dwelling on Bishop Keith Symons' admission in 1998 that he had
sexual relations with several boys early in his career. O'Connell,
observers say, has tried to buoy the church on his shoulders and
propel it forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried not to live in the past,'' O'Connell said.
``There's no use to it. Still, I have tried to talk as openly about
reconciliation as I know how. In many cases, it's just listening to
someone. Overall, it has taken up very little focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite the fact that Symons led the diocese for eight
years and the two talk about once a month, O'Connell said he has
had fewer than five substantial conversations about his
predecessor's transgressions with either priests or parishioners.
(Symons has been leading spiritual retreats in Michigan since last
summer.)
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from Pope John Paul II, O'Connell has traveled
extensively to establish himself as a presence in both the church
and secular community. Though he lives next to his office, he drove
30,000 miles in the past 12 months, covering the five-county
diocese.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Sunday was a typical workday. O'Connell said Mass at
St. Rita, stayed another three hours for a party for a parish
priest celebrating 40 years in the clergy, and then drove to
Lantana to say Mass and celebrate the Vietnamese New Year at Holy
Spirit Catholic Church. He stayed until 9 at night, though a large
portion of the congregation doesn't speak English. Throughout the
day, he probably shook hands with 200 to 300 people. His face was
rarely without a smile.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell's stated goal is to show the 220,000 Catholics in his
diocese that if he can reach out, so must they. While many of the
wealthier churches could become isolated and insulated, O'Connell
insists it is the responsibility of the priests and parishioners to
help those in need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reaching out ... is of the essence,'' O'Connell says. ``To say
we don't need anybody else may be good for lots of things, but that
certainly isn't a church.'' And if the church gets down to the
business of being a church, healing and forgiveness will follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when Symons admitted to his past, it was quite a shock
to a lot of people,'' said Brian King, Symons' former secretary and
a seminarian set to be ordained this spring. ``But _ and I hate for
this to sound callous _ the church has to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When O'Connell came here, he was faced with a diocese that
wanted direction. People wanted someone to reassure them and tell
them everything was going to be all right. That's what (O'Connell)
has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauging the bishop's effectiveness or standing is tricky. The
church, like any organization, is a political institution. Still,
the positive seems to vastly outweigh the negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been like a breath of fresh air,'' said the Rev.
Alfredo Hernandez of St. Juliana Catholic Church in West Palm
Beach. ``He is a hopeful man, and he inspires hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind that hope is a faith in people and dislike for the
nitty-gritty of management. O'Connell has been praised as an
administrator who does not micromanage _ a frequent criticism of
his predecessor _ and as a man willing to walk his talk.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Juliana's 50th anniversary celebration in October,
Hernandez tells of watching O'Connell meet the congregation in the
churchyard. It was close to 90 degrees and humid, and O'Connell,
whose fair skin and beefy constitution are better suited for the
rolling hills of Ireland than the humid tropics of South Florida,
was sweating like a perforated water balloon. Still, he refused to
take off his vestments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew that people like to see their bishop looking like a
bishop,'' Hernandez said. ``He was out there in the heat with all
of his gear on, taking pictures, because he wanted to meet the
people where they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
