<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BIG-DIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS SAY `BIG DIG' COSTS DON'T HAVE TO MEAN TOLL HIKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The House is proposing its own plan to address the Big
Dig funding crisis without raising tolls on Massachusetts Turnpike
and harbor tunnel users next year.
</P>
<P>
   The House plan would pay for about half of the $1.4 billion
Central Artery cost overrun, enough to keep the project operating
through next year and give state officials more time to come up
with a long-term financial solution.
</P>
<P>
   Using driver's license fees, state borrowing of $600 million,
and a $200 cash contribution from turnpike reserves, the plan would
avoid the divisive toll hikes, House leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're attempting to do is discover the depth of this
problem and also areas of savings that the turnpike should be
required to identify,'' said Joseph C. Sullivan, House chairman of
the Joint Committee on Transportation. ``The need for an
accelerated toll may be eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Governor Paul Cellucci released his own blueprint
for bridging the Big Dig gap that relies on $1 billion in state
borrowing, with some of the loans extending 50 years. Cellucci also
called for raising turnpike and harbor tunnel tolls next January, a
year earlier than scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, a Braintree Democrat, said the House does not want to
saddle taxpayers with debt for a half century. He also said that
House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran ``has been very sensitive on the
issue of tolls. . . in terms of not having an adjustment until
2002. I think the House is inclined to keep that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, legislators from suburbs along the turnpike,
including House Majority Whip Barbara Gardner (D-Holliston), have
lobbied their House colleagues for relief from repeated toll
increases. Cellucci's plan would double tolls on the easternmost
extension of the turnpike to $1, and raise tunnel fees from $2 to
$3 for cars next January.
</P>
<P>
   The House plan would also give the Legislature more oversight on
spending for the project, expected to be completed in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The funding debate is likely to continue for weeks, leaving the
$12.2 billion project's financial crisis _ and the question of
whether there will be toll increases to cover it _ unresolved until
Cellucci and the Legislature can agree on a plan.
</P>
<P>
   The debate seems to be intensified by gubernatorial politics.
Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham has been aggressively laying
the groundwork to run for governor in 2002, and Finneran is seen as
a potential candidate too.
</P>
<P>
   A proposal could be voted on before the end of the month. The
Senate has yet to issue its own plan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the state has some $4 billion in surplus
cash, Cellucci has been reluctant to tap those reserves.
Administration sources said they quietly pitched the idea of using
reserve funds but were told that rank-and-file lawmakers would not
accept the plan because they would rather use the surplus for pet
projects in their districts.
</P>
<P>
   Both Finneran and Birmingham accuse the governor of protecting
the surplus to fund an income tax rate cut. Cellucci wants to scale
back the income tax to 5 percent, which would cost over $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor appears to be motivated not by best fiscal
practices but a by a single-minded devotion to an overly aggressive
tax cut,'' said Birmingham spokeswoman Alison Franklin. ``In that
regard, the 50-year bonds are Exhibit A.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran also said he is skeptical of another component in
Cellucci's plan, which would partially liquidate a controversial
Big Dig insurance policy and generate $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the last alternative we have, I won't rule it out. .
. but the misgivings have been serious and substantial,'' Finneran
said.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran said it is difficult to devise a solution to the
shortfall when no one is certain the Big Dig's $1.4 billion gap is
the limit of skyrocketing project costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people with some experience and some insight will
probably express a preference just to go slow, not rush into
anything,'' Finneran said. ``But unfortunately what we seem to be
seeing from some quarters is just a quick response to try to throw
the hot potato elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks were directed at Birmingham, who has threatened to
shut down state transportation funding until the governor presents
a more palatable solution to solve the Central Artery/Third Harbor
Tunnel financial problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not 2002 politics that is creeping up,'' Finneran
said of Birmingham, a possible gubernatorial rival in the next
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``That brings me back to the main point,'' Finneran added. ``I
don't want to just merely react, to score political points or act
like a demagogue. . . If they (the Senate) just want to turn off
the spigot, someone should explain that to the citizens, the
contractors, the unions, the laborers on that job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
