<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-R-WEB-ATTACK-ART-405&AMP;     02-16 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-WEB-ATTACK-ART-405&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFICIALS TELL OF GROWING THREATS TO COMPUTER SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A week after still-unidentified hackers paralyzed
several well-known commercial Internet companies, the country's
chief law enforcement and legal officers said Wednesday that
threats against computer networks have outstripped the government's
efforts to keep up with them.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before a Senate panel on Internet security, Attorney
General Janet Reno said last week's attacks on popular Web sites
illustrated the necessity of a coordinated law enforcement
strategy. ``How we deal with cyber-crime is one of the most
critical areas we face,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno proposed a five-year plan that would include tougher
penalties for hackers and standardized investigative technologies.
Such a step could lower the astronomical cost of security and
detection gear in an environment in which, she said, equipment is
obsolete almost as soon as its installed.
</P>
<P>
   Louis J. Freeh, the FBI director, told senators that the
investigation of last week's attacks was moving aggressively.
``There are fast-developing leads as we speak,'' Freeh said of the
search for those who barraged the computer systems of companies
like Yahoo, eBay and Amazon.com with meaningless data to clog the
paths of customers attempting to reach the sites.
</P>
<P>
   He said the investigation was being conducted in the United
States as well as in Germany and Canada. Scores of agents from FBI
offices in Atlanta, Boston, Los Angeles, San Francisco and Seattle
are at work on the attacks, known within law enforcement circles as
``distributed denial of service'' cases.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, law enforcement officials have said they are
interviewing several people, including some computer hackers,
although they did not yet have evidence clearly indicating who was
responsible for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the seriousness of the problem, Freeh cited the
growing number of such cases, to 1,154 last year from 547 such
cases in 1998. The cases range from minor attacks by teen-age
vandals and disgruntled employees to highly sophisticated
intrusions possibly directed by foreign intelligence services, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said that in 1998, 399 cases were closed, in contrast to
to 1999, when 912 cases closed. Almost none of the cases resulted
in prosecutions. The FBI closes a case when the agency decides
there is no basis for further investigation. The cases do not
include other major categories of cyber-crime, like Internet fraud
or child pornography.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Freeh acknowledged the difficulties
computer cases pose for law enforcement. ``In short, even though we
have markedly improved our capabilities to fight cyber intrusions,
the problem is growing even faster and thus we are falling further
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer crime is one of the most dynamic problems the FBI
faces today,'' Freeh said. ``Just think about how many computers
you have owned and how many different software packages you have
learned over the past several years, and you can only begin to
appreciate the scope of the problem we are dealing with in the
fast-changing era,'' Freeh said.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony by Reno and Freeh followed a White House meeting
convened Tuesday by President Clinton with technology experts and
Internet executives about how to improve the security of the
country's computer networks. Clinton adopted a reassuring tone,
saying the assaults were not an ``electronic Pearl Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry officials have said they want strong action
against computer criminals but fear that government intervention
and new criminal laws could unintentionally stifle the phenomenal
growth and creativity of the technology industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9174 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKA-ELDREDGE-BOS &LR;      02-16 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKA-ELDREDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDREDGE SETS PLAN TO MAKE 2002 WINTER GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Todd Eldredge, who's been out of Olympic-level figure skating
for two seasons, said Tuesday he's coming back next week _ and
aiming for the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mostly about the Olympics,'' said the 28-year-old from
Chatham, Mass., who'll make his reentry as a member of the US team
at the Four Continents championship in Osaka, Japan. ``I've never
skated the way I wanted to there. So that was really the motivating
factor.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1998 season, Eldredge went on what the International
Skating Union termed ``active rest.'' He did not defend his US
title last year and skated mostly pro-am events, exhibitions, and
tours. But he deliberately did not turn professional, which would
have closed the door on a third trip to Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I kept my eligibility, so I could keep my options
open,'' said Eldredge, who finished fourth in Nagano last time and
10th in Albertville in 1992. ``If the field looked like I could be
competitive, I wanted to be able to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   What Eldredge saw at last year's world championships in Helsinki
and last week's US championships, plus his own improvement,
convinced him he could be in the chase for 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt, yeah, I could be competitive if I want to be,'' said
Eldredge, who has won five world medals (including the 1996 gold)
and five US titles. ``There was no one moment when I made the
decision. Just kind of a feeling I've had over the last year that
my skating has started improving and my quadruple jump has gotten
better.''
</P>
<P>
   And the rest of his rivals haven't leaped beyond his reach.
Though Tim Goebel landed an unprecedented three quads at the US
championships, Michael Weiss retained the title without hitting
any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else is landing three quads,'' said Eldredge, who has
never landed one in competition. ``Most of the guys are doing the
same things they've been doing the last couple of years. I was
always competitive with them without the quad. Now that my quad is
1,000 times better, I can raise the bar for myself and be one of
the guys that can be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   By coming back now, Eldredge felt he could ease back into the
fast lane and have two full competitive seasons before the next
Games. ``It won't be like jumping in just before the Olympic year
and thinking, `Oh my God, I've forgotten what this is all about,'
'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eldredge said he'll skate a full competitive season next fall
and winter and will return to the US championships to try to snatch
back the title Weiss inherited from him two years ago. ``You'll see
me in Boston,'' he vowed. ``I'm looking forward to skating in the
FleetCenter and going for a sixth title.''
</P>
<P>
   The Four Continents event, which includes skaters from North
America, Asia, Africa, and Oceania, will be a decent gauge of where
Eldredge is and needs to be.
</P>
<P>
   Though entries are not yet final, the field could include four
of the top 10 from last year's world championships _ Canada's Elvis
Stojko, Japan's Takeshi Honda, China's Guo Zhengxin, and
Australia's Anthony Liu.
</P>
<P>
   Eldredge has fared well this season, winning the Canadian Open
and finishing second in the Japan Open and fourth in Skate Canada,
a Grand Prix event for Olympic-eligible skaters. Though he didn't
compete in the US championships, Eldredge asked to be added to the
American team, which will be without Goebel and Weiss, who'll be
preparing for next month's world event in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good opportunity for me to pick up where I left
off,'' said Eldredge. ``You always need a chance to keep your name
and your skating fresh in the judges' minds. If I want to be
considered in the mix for the medals in the next Olympics, I have
to be out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
