<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9176 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ROBERTOLENBUTLER-INTE     02-16 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERTOLENBUTLER-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT OLEN BUTLER AVOIDS FORMULA FOR SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight years after winning the Pulitizer Prize for ``A Good Scent
From a Strange Mountain,'' a dazzling collection of 15 short
stories, Robert Olen Butler is surprised when people recognize his
name and tell him they love his books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still feels a little unreal,'' says Butler, 55, who was in
Texas on a stopover that kicked off a national tour touting his
latest novel, ``Mr. Spaceman'' (Grove Press, $23). ``When I won the
prize, I was writing in absolute obscurity. My novel before that
sold 1,083 copies. Nobody seemed to care about my books.''
</P>
<P>
   Now critics rave over each new Butler title, and every
book-signing attracts devoted fans who want to tell the author how
much his work has meant to them. This doesn't mean Butler has
achieved sales superstardom. ``Mr. Spaceman'' and John Grisham's
``The Brethren'' were published within two weeks of each other.
``The Brethren'' is a fixture at No. 1 on Amazon.com's bestseller
list, while ``Mr. Spaceman'' bounces between No. 800 and No. 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Butler says, is the difference between
``entertainment'' and ``literary'' writers, and what each hopes to
achieve for readers. ``Think of it as the distinction between
Stephen King and Leo Tolstoy,'' he says. ``Entertainment writers
know the exact effect they want to have on their readers before
they even begin to write. They want to scare them, or want to hold
their attention with a story about lawyers. There is nothing wrong
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   For literary artists, as Butler calls them, ``writing is
exploration as well as expression.'' They often don't know where
they are headed when they begin their work. Butler's goal is to
touch the emotions of readers who open their imaginations to the
varied messages his eclectic topics provide.
</P>
<P>
   He is happy as long as he sells enough books to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   Butler doesn't deny that this philosophy makes him a minority
among authors. He wants every book to come at readers from a
different angle than the one before.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no challenge, and therefore no emotional and
intellectual reward, in writing the same book over and over,''
Butler says. ``Just before I won the Pulitzer Prize, I decided my
books probably weren't ever going to get much attention, and so I'd
just write to challenge and satisfy myself. Afterwards, I found
myself in the same frame of mind. That's why I've since written a
dense novel about human sexuality, (''They Whisper''); ``Tabloid
Dreams,'' a collection of stories based on extreme tabloid
headlines; and so forth. Because, after ``A Good Scent From a
Strange Mountain,'' I think everyone expected me to write
exclusively about Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been natural. All 15 stories in ``Strange
Mountain'' are based on Vietnamese people and folktales. It is a
culture and folklore Butler learned firsthand. In 1969, after
receiving an undergraduate degree in theater from Northwestern
University and a master's degree in playwriting from the University
of Iowa, he served in Vietnam. Butler's gift for language allowed
him to learn to speak fluent Vietnamese, and he served in military
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Butler returned to the States, burning to write about his
experiences, but he worked at other jobs (laborer in a steel mill,
taxi driver, high school teacher, journalist) before ``The Alleys
of Eden'' was published in 1981. That work, and some of his
subsequent poorly selling novels, focused on Vietnam. The Pulitzer
honoring ``Strange Mountain'' gave him a wider, if still cultlike
audience, and he has tried to engagingly confound it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Spaceman'' is a continuation of a short story in ``Tabloid
Dreams.'' In the earlier work, Butler wrote about a Southern woman
in love with an alien who was visiting Earth to learn about its
inhabitants. ``Mr. Spaceman'' finds the two wed as
out-of-this-worlder Desi is ordered by his far-off superiors to
reveal himself to humans on Jan. 1, 2000. The problem is, Desi has
learned enough about earthlings to realize that humans often
destroy anything or anyone that seems too, well, ``different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As I was writing, I had no idea what would happen to Desi in
the story,'' Butler says. ``But, given the propensities of the
human race, chances were that they would not be kind to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler believes most readers would get more from his books _
from any books _ if they read them in a less traditional way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ought to be a deep, primal connection between readers
and words on a page,'' Butler says. ``But people are taught in
school, in college, to be analytical from the first page. Teachers'
attitudes are that writers are like idiot savants who really want
to say abstract, philosophic things but are not quite able to. So
they present books as what they think the writer is saying. Well,
art does not come from the mind, from our analytical faculties. It
comes from where you dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The perfect meeting of writer and reader, Butler says, ``is a
process of deep communication, of companionship. That is what I ask
of readers. You don't understand a work of art, you `thrum' to it,
and it is more like a musical experience.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which can, Butler knows, make him sound like an
impractical ``artiste.'' But he's got his common sense side, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do realize publishing is a business,'' Butler says. ``Take
this current book tour. I'm going to 45 cities. Most authors, at
least those who've been published a lot, don't like to tour. They
find it demeaning. I'm always ready to do it, and I even told Grove
Press, my publisher for `Mr. Spaceman,' not to spend money on print
advertising. Instead, I asked them to use that money to send me to
more places.''
</P>
<P>
   When the tour concludes, Butler will go home to Louisiana and
write some more _ another novel (he's sorting through ideas), some
screenplays (''I've just come back from Hollywood pitching `Mr.
Spaceman,' though I'd have to write the screenplay myself''), and
he'll even teach at McNeese State in Lake Charles.
</P>
<P>
   And does he practice what he preaches in the classroom?
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I tell them (students) is to forget everything
they learned in the class,'' Butler says. ``I tell them that the
purpose of what we read, what we discussed, was to help them tune
their inner instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'll tell them not to read by thinking, but by dreaming.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
