<SLUG> BC-R-SC-REPUBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCE  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add art note)  
 BAUER ENDORSES McCAIN; CANDIDATES CONTINUE TO SPAR OVER CAMPAIGN(Eds: The material in the MCCAIN story, budgeted earlier, is now
folded into REPUBS; see also CAROLINA-PROFILE,
SC-POLITICAL-PROFILE.) 
(ART ADV: Photos of McCain _ NYT6, 7, 11 _ are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL with FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Sen. John McCain won the endorsement
Wednesday of Gary Bauer, a former presidential rival and prominent
social conservative who called him the ``best shot we have to end
the era of Bill and Hillary and Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer showed up at McCain's side at a midday rally here on the
campus of Furman University, in the northern quadrant of South
Carolina, where the state's large and influential bloc of voters
from the religious right is the strongest. The senator's senior
advisers said they hoped Bauer could bring new support from
Christian conservatives and help fend off charges by supporters of
Gov. George W. Bush that McCain is not reliable on social issues
such as abortion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain himself said Bauer could help him reach out to a part of
the Republican Party to which ``my lines of communication haven't
been as firm.'' Bauer immediately started offering a spirited
defense of McCain, providing an important counterweight to figures
like Pat Robertson who suggested this week that conservatives would
desert the party if McCain became the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Reminding the crowd at Furman University of McCain's
imprisonment as a prison of war in North Vietnam, Bauer said that
``when John was in that POW camp, he wasn't sitting around thinking
about the wealth of America or the power of America, he was
thinking about that moral idea of America, the reason that we are
who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who had made the crusade against abortion one of the
centerpieces of his own presidential campaign, said McCain agreed
with him that ``we must work to ensure that every child gets
welcomed into the world and protected by the law.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Bauer said he believed McCain and Bush had
the same position on abortion, which is less absolute than his own.
``At least on the surface there wasn't much difference'' he said of
the two men. ``But I've looked John in the eye. I've talked to him.
I've looked at his voting record. I believe it is by and large a
pro-life voting record.''
</P>
<P>
   With McCain and Bush running neck and neck, the senator has
gained solid support from independents. But most polls show him
running behind Bush with traditional Republicans and doing even
worse with the religious right. A South Carolina anti-abortion
group is running radio advertisements accusing McCain of voting
``to use tax dollars for experiments that use body parts from
aborted babies,'' a theme that is also being hit hard by the
National Right to Life Committee in direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Charleston sidestepped a question about
whether Bauer's endorsement of his rival would hurt him with
religious conservatives. ``I think I've got good chance to win
South Carolina,'' Bush said. ``I'm going to drive this campaign
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush took a more direct swipe at McCain and his commitment to
diluting the influence of money in politics, suggesting Wednesday
that McCain was ignoring federal spending limits for the Republican
primary in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides asserted that McCain had spent about $2.8 million
in advertising alone for South Carolina, and had thus undoubtedly
exceeded the limit of slightly more than $3 million for a full
array of expenditures. Bush himself declined to make charges or
cite numbers, but his comments left no doubt that he believed that
McCain had crossed the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``No candidate ought to be above the rules,'' Bush said at a
news conference in Hilton Head Wednesday morning. ``Senator McCain
needs to explain, if in fact he has busted the spending cap in
South Carolina, how on the one hand you can be a campaign funding
reformer and on the other hand, not live within spending caps.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides did not provide a specific figure for the Arizona
senator's spending but said that he would remain within the limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a dime under in New Hampshire,'' said John Weaver, the
political director for the McCain campaign. ``We'll be a nickel
under here.''
</P>
<P>
   The quarrel was about more than math. With striking consistency
over the last week and a half, Bush has worked to divert attention
from his own prodigious financial war chest and intense spending to
charges that McCain's fund raising violates some of his own
principles when it comes to campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush faces no spending limits, because he raised so much money
last year that he decided to forgo the federal matching funds that
are distributed on the condition that candidates stay within
certain caps. Bush's aides said Wednesday that the campaign had
spent about $3.1 million on advertising in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign provided a startling glimpse Wednesday into
the full extent of their spending, conceding that it had spent, by
the end of January, about $50 million of the $70 million it had
raised up to then, leaving the campaign with about $20 million in
reserve on the day before the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   That was a record-setting expenditure for this point in a
presidential race, and it topped by $8 million the amount that Bob
Dole had spent through July in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insisted that his campaign had nonetheless anticipated, and
was well equipped, to deal with this kind of scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on plan,'' Bush said at the news conference. ``We've got
a strategy. We've got a plan in place and we're executing the
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also engaged McCain in a new television commercial that
addresses campaign financing and began airing Wednesday in South
Carolina. The spot says that McCain's criticisms of Bush on this
issue have been gratuitous and unwarranted, and it casts Bush as
someone eager to usher in sensible reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer met secretly with McCain Tuesday in a Columbia hotel
before the final debate leading into the South Carolina primary.
Bauer flew back to Washington Tuesday night to consult with his
family. He then telephoned McCain at 7:30 a.m. Wednesday morning
with his decision and the campaign sent a chartered plane to bring
him back to South Carolina. Bauer was planning to stump for McCain
in South Carolina and then in Michigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2048EST &QL; 
