<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9180 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MOTHER-TO-KILLER-HNS &LR;      02-16 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHER-TO-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIEVING MOTHER WRITES TO KILLER: `I NO LONGER FEEL ALIVE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Colo.) 
 
By HARVEY RICE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONROE, Texas _ In anguished words addressed to her daughter's
killer, a mother told of no longer knowing love _ and no longer
believing in God _ because of the grief the man inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have taken every reason I had to live and I don't know
what it is like to love any more, because you have also taken that
away from me,'' Kim Brothers, the mother of 18-year-old Wanda May
Pitts, wrote in a letter to be sent to William Ray Mathews at the
Montgomery County Jail near Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can never forgive you and I can't tell you to ask God for
forgiveness, because with what you have done, I no longer think
there is a God, because if there was, he would never put men like
you on this earth to bring harm to special people like my baby,
Wanda!'' wrote Brothers, 35, of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In a videotaped confession, Mathews, 38, said recently that he
abducted Pitts from her job as a clerk at the Lodge Motel, now a
Howard Johnson, in nearby Shenandoah on Jan. 17, 1999. The attack
came after Mathews escaped for the fifth time from a Colorado
mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Conroe, a city of 43,500 people, is about 35 miles north of
downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Mathews was sentenced to 50 years in prison last week after
pleading guilty to robbery and aggravated assault in two unrelated
abduction attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, who said they could not bring murder charges
against Mathews because Pitts' body had not been found despite
numerous searches, agreed to never prosecute him for murder in
return for his confession and help in finding the body.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the guilty plea, Pitts' remains were found in a
brushy, wooded area just over the Montgomery County line in Walker
County.
</P>
<P>
   Given an opportunity to address Mathews in court, a distraught
Brothers was able to manage only a sentence or two.
</P>
<P>
   In a one-page, single-spaced letter, however, she wrote about
the pain she has felt because of her daughter's murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk around on this planet only as flesh and bones now
because my heart and soul are dead,'' Brothers wrote. ``You might
as well have taken me on 1-17-99 also, because I no longer feel
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know that you should have killed me on that
night and lay me next to the love of my life because I feel dead
anyway, again, no thanks to you William Ray Mathews!''
</P>
<P>
   The letter is signed, ``From a mother that walks this earth an
empty shell, Kim Brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ghigna, victim assistant coordinator at the Montgomery
County District Attorney's Office, said a copy of the letter will
be included in a file that will be sent to the Texas Department of
Criminal Justice Victim Services Office in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Ghigna said Pitts probably would have read the letter in court
had she been able. ``It's a very difficult thing to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter could be presented at any parole hearing after
Mathews becomes eligible in 25 years, Ghigna said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before he pleaded guilty last week, a jury concluded
that Mathews, whom judges in Illinois and Colorado have ruled not
guilty by reason of insanity in separate robbery cases, was
competent to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Mathews escaped from the Colorado State Mental Institution in
Pueblo a month before he killed Pitts.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted forcing Pitts into a pickup and taking her to a
motel in nearby Cleveland, where he strangled her early the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Mathews' last escape, the mental hospital adopted
a policy to notify the public of escapes, spokeswoman Eunice
Wolther said. The public did not hear of Mathews' escape in 1998
until last October, when Texas authorities tied him to Pitts'
slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Wolther also said maximum- and medium-security patients such as
Mathews can no longer go to the hospital's unlocked vocational
buildings. Mathews escaped during a class.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jonathan Olin, director of forensic psychiatry, said the
hospital has made other changes, including unspecified physical
improvements, to make it harder to escape.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
