<HEADER>
A9181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-FILE     02-16 2063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDs: This is File 1 of 2
</P>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the large amount of money that Steve Forbes spent on his
presidential campaign tax deductible?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. IRS spokesman Mark Green explained that amounts incurred
by an individual seeking public office aren't deductible as
business expenses. The same goes for re-election campaign expenses
for an officeholder. Forbes was reported to have spent a total of
some $66 million on his campaigns in 1996 and this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Also not deductible, by the way, are expenses for the support
of, or opposition to, any candidate for public office. This means
that contributions, gifts, or any other amount paid for
``participation or intervention'' in any political campaign on
behalf of any candidate for public office cannot be claimed as a
deduction. This includes donations to a political party, committee,
group or candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A news magazine recently reported that Sally Hemings was a
half-sister of Thomas Jefferson's wife. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: It has been reported often that Hemings was the illegitimate
half-sister of Jefferson's deceased wife, Martha, the offspring of
a relationship between John Wayles and Elizabeth ``Betty'' Hemings,
a slave. Wayles was the father of Martha Wayles, who married
Jefferson. When Wayles died, Sally Hemings became Jefferson's
property when he inherited the Wayles estate in 1774.
</P>
<P>
   Details about Sally Hemings can be found at libraries. Among the
resources: ``Black Women in America/An Historical Encyclopedia''
and ``Notable Black American Women.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: An author in Britain named Irving sued an Emory professor and
her publisher for calling him a ``holocaust revisionist.'' The
trial was covered extensively for some days, then disappeared from
the news. What's the status of that?
</P>
<P>
   A: The trial of historical writer David Irving's libel lawsuit
against Emory University professor Deborah Lipstadt ended its fifth
week on Feb. 10. It is expected to continue until late March.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has been presenting a series of witnesses to
challenge Irving's merits as an historian, and to attack his
honesty as a writer. Under English libel law, attorneys
representing Lipstadt and her publisher, Penguin Press, must prove
the truth of assertions contained in a book by Lipstadt that Irving
denied conventional accounts of the Holocaust and manipulated
historical facts to support his position.
</P>
<P>
   Lipstadt's book, ``Denying the Holocaust: The Growing Assault on
Truth and Memory,'' was published in Britain in 1994. Irving says
the book misrepresented his position, damaged his reputation, and
generated waves of hatred against him. Lipstadt's lawyers accuse
him of being a liar and a falsifier of history.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In what years were the Susan B. Anthony coins produced for
general circulation?
</P>
<P>
   A: 1979-81, plus an uncirculated coin set in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After a commercial airplane crashes, and the flight number is
reported so often that it becomes etched in people's minds, are the
airlines required to retire that number?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the Federal Aviation Administration and the Air
Transport Association, there's no regulation requiring airlines to
retire numbers falling into that category, such as TWA 800. But
Diana Cronan of the Washington-based ATA said it's typical for an
airline to stop using a recognizable flight number ``after any
high-profile accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What ever became of Lenny Skutnik, the man who jumped into
the icy waters of the Potomac River in an attempt to save
passengers in the early-'80s crash of an Air Florida flight? He was
singled out by President Reagan in a State of the Union address,
but I haven't heard anything about him since.
</P>
<P>
   A: At last report, Skutnik was still working at the same job he
had at the Congressional Budget Office in Washington when the crash
occurred on Jan. 13,1982.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Skutnik was on his way to his home in Lorton, Va.
As he neared the crash site, he saw a woman, later identified as a
flight attendant, in the river. She appeared to be losing her grip
on a rescue line. He jumped into the frigid water and dragged her
to safety.
</P>
<P>
   His act of heroism didn't go unnoticed. His biggest moment in
the spotlight came less than two weeks later, during Reagan's first
State of the Union address, when Reagan was discussing heroes. ``We
don't have to turn to our history books for heroes. They're all
around us,'' he said, recounting Skutnik's lifesaving deed. Skutnik
was in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last year with the Washington Post, Skutnik said
the crash rescue incident, and the mention by Reagan, didn't change
his life. ``I got caught up in the moment, but I knew it would
eventually be over,'' he said. ``At first ... I had no control over
it. But then I got back to work, back to normal, and things didn't
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that Delta Air Lines has restored an old DC-3 prop
plane that had been in its fleet years and years ago. Can the
public buy a ride on it?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. As Delta has explained previously, Ship 41, as it's
called, is being used only for major air shows and Delta-sponsored
events _ not for commercial or sightseeing flights.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Super Bowl Sunday next year is Jan. 28. When and how can fans
enter the lottery to try and get tickets?
</P>
<P>
   A: As you know, most Super Bowl tickets go to corporate sponsors
and other companies and individuals related to the business side of
the game. Another allotment is set aside for the competing teams. A
small percentage _ a National Football League spokesman wouldn't
specify exactly how many _ goes to the public through a random
drawing.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 Super Bowl will be played in Tampa. Anyone wanting to
get into the pool of potential applicants should send a certified
postcard with name, address and telephone number to: NFL Lottery,
280 Park Ave., New York, NY 10017. The deadline is June 1. Those
whose cards are chosen will be notified ``around the first of
November,'' the NFL spokesman said. Price information will be
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there an Internet site where I can look up Sen. John
McCain's voting record?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Web site of the non-partisan organization Project Vote
Smart _ www.vote-smart.org _ is a good place to start for voting
record information on any U.S. senator or House member.
</P>
<P>
   It displays a map of the United States. When you click on the
state you're interested in (Arizona, obviously, for McCain), you'll
find a wealth of data. Votes over a varying period on many issues _
such as affirmative action, gun issues, foreign aid, senior issues,
welfare and many more _ can be accessed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A TV commentator referred to the medal just awarded to Alfred
Rascon as the Congressional Medal of Honor. I thought it was just
the Medal of Honor. Who is right?
</P>
<P>
   A: You are. The proper name of the highest military decoration
that the United States grants to members of its armed forces is
simply the Medal of Honor. But the word ``Congressional''
frequently is added because the medal is presented by a high
official ``in the name of the Congress of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Rascon shielded men from grenade blasts in Vietnam 34 years ago,
but because of apparent administrative snafus, only now has he been
honored with the medal. It was approved by Defense Secretary
William Cohen in November and awarded to Rascon on Tuesday at the
White House by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to Howard Hughes' Spruce Goose? Some time
ago I read that it was bought and moved by barge from California to
Oregon. Is it on display now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not yet. The Hughes Flying Boat HK-1 is still in pieces, but
is expected to be reassembled in stages and put on display, along
with 40-50 other vintage aircraft, in early 2001. The Spruce Goose
will be the centerpiece of a museum under construction at the Capt.
Michael King Smith Evergreen Educational Institute in McMinnville,
Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Thompson, spokesman for the facility, said workers hope to
start putting the Spruce Goose in place in August or September. The
fuselage first will be placed in a 7-foot pit, after which the
wings, and then the tail, will be attached. Other aircraft will be
placed around the gigantic HK-1, while others will be suspended
from the museum's superstructure.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the museum can be found online at
http://sprucegoose.org.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in obtaining a copy of President Clinton's
2001 budget. How do I get one?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Budget of the United States Government, Fiscal Year 2001,
and related Office of Management and Budget documents can be
purchased at any Government Printing Office bookstore. One is in
Atlanta (999 Peachtree St. NE, Suite 120; telephone 404-347-1900).
The documents are priced separately: $38 for the budget; $72 for
the appendix; $54 for analytical perspectives; $28 for historical
tables; $3.75 for A Citizen's Guide to the Federal Budget, Fiscal
Year 2001; $3.25 for The Budget System and Concepts, Fiscal Year
2001; and $17 for the budget on CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to buy it, you may be able to view the
material at a public library, said Linda Schimmel of Congressional
Budget Office Publications. Budget documents also can be downloaded
from the Internet at www.gpo.gov/usbudget.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Don McLean's song ``American Pie'' has been in the news
recently because of a remake by Madonna. Beyond the generally
understood explanation that the lyrics are about the early days of
rock and roll, what do the words mean? For example, who are ``the
father, son and the holy ghost''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Numerous interpretations have been offered about the 1971
song's lyrics. Many Web sites exist that attempt to explain it. One
_ www.americanpie2000.com/americanpie/ _ lists this as its
interpretation of the line in Verse 6:
</P>
<P>
   ``And the three men I admire most The Father Son and Holy
Ghost'' refers to Buddy Holly, the Big Bopper (J.P. Richardson) and
Richie Valens.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Web site explains, McLean has never provided an
explanation of the meaning of ``American Pie,'' which has added to
the song's mystery.
</P>
<P>
   This interpretation suggests that the entire song is a tribute
to Holly and a commentary on how rock and roll music changed in the
years since his death in 1959. In that view, McLean is lamenting
the lack of ``danceable'' good-time party music in rock and roll
and, in part, is attributing that lack to the absence of Buddy
Holly, et. al.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative explanation, on a different Web site, says McLean
was a Catholic, and Verse 6 deals with religion and godless acts.
So if you accept that, the words refer to the traditional Trinity
of Christian theology.
</P>
<P>
   A search engine such as Yahoo can link you to several resources
for ``American Pie.'' That way, you can take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to visit cemeteries where famous people, such as
Buddy Holly and Richie Valens, are buried. Is there a book with
that sort of information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Several books with such information should be readily
available at libraries or bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Books in Print (1999-2000)'' lists these titles, for example:
``Who Lies Where: A Guide to Famous Graves'' by Michael Kerrigan
(Trafalgar Square Publishing Co.); ``Discovering Famous Graves'' by
Lynn F. Pearson (Shire Publications); ``Final Curtain _ Deaths of
Noted Movie and TV Personalities'' by Everett Grant Jarvis (Carol
Publishing Group); and ``Final Curtain: Eternal Resting Places of
Stars, Celebrities, Moguls, Misers, Misfits &AMP; Their Stories'' by
Margaret Burk and Gary Hudson (Seven Locks Press).
</P>
<P>
   Some information is very specific. For example, ``Final Curtain
_ Deaths of Noted Movie and TV Personalities'' shows that Valens is
buried at Missions Hills Cemetery in Mission Hills, Calif., Section
C, at Curb No. 247, three rows in. It doesn't list Holly's burial
place, but the Buddy Holly Center in Lubbock, Texas, confirmed that
he's buried in the City of Lubbock Cemetery. Holly was born in
Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
