<HEADLINE>
NEIMAN ON ART AND THE EYES OF A DOG
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The prolific artist  &UR; LeRoy Neiman &LR; , whose works depict such
treasured American themes as golf, football, racehorses and
interiors of bars, is the subject of a retrospective that begins
February 20 at the Franklin Bowles Gallery in San Francisco. ``He's
wined and dined with kings and presidents and sat with three
generations of cultural icons,'' says his press materials,
``including  &UR; Joe DiMaggio &LR; ,  &UR; Frank Sinatra &LR; ,  &UR; Mick Jagger &LR; ,
 &UR; Muhammad &LR; 
 &UR; Ali &LR; ,  &UR; Mark McGwire &LR;  and  &UR; John Lennon &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Neiman told us that he's a fan of abstract expressionists
 &UR; Willem de Kooning &LR;  and  &UR; Franz Klein &LR;  and that  &UR; Richard Diebenkorn &LR; 
is ``a hell of a painter. I think that guy out there,  &UR; Wayne &LR; 
 &UR; Thiebaud &LR; , is a giant. I've done some paintings on commissions of
the bridges in San Francisco, and I've always felt that it was his
territory. He gave me a different way to look at San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Does being a star of pop culture make it harder for him to be
taken seriously as an artist? ``People just paint,'' said Neiman,
whose work is largely commissioned. ``I paint anything. If someone
comes by and wants me to paint their dog, they put it on the table
and I paint it. I've painted sheepdogs, I've painted full-size
poodles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you something about painting a dog: It's not like
painting a horse. A thoroughbred has got markings, and the owner is
very particular about it. But if you paint a dog, it's like a
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to do a portrait of someone, it's life size,
more or less to scale. If you do a full figure, you would scale it
down to fit. But if somebody brings a dog in, it's very hard to
paint that dog in a different scale. That's my problem. ... One of
the great things about living in New York City is that people have
great dogs. ... You look at a dog. You can't do a dumb dog. Every
dog's eyes are intelligent and they're alert. You can do some
people and they're kind of docile. But you don't find a dumb dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Neiman said he'd be paid about $10,000 for a watercolor of a
dog.
</P>
<P>
   The artist is also being honored in San Francisco by the naming
after him of an after-school art program sponsored by the Good
Tidings Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASTRONAUT FINALLY GETS HIS DUE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Astronaut  &UR; John Young &LR; , who flew Gemini, Apollo and shuttle
missions and is the most traveled man in space, will be honored
with a plaque to be unveiled on February 23 at the California
Academy of Sciences in San Francisco. Young, who was born in San
Francisco, lives in Houston nowadays. The Westin St. Francis is
putting him up for a week.
</P>
<P>
   The honor for Young is the result of a campaign by space buff
 &UR; Ken Winans &LR; , who lives in Mill Valley and whose efforts included
successful lobbying of Mayor  &UR; Willie Brown &LR;  and the San Francisco
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ California Attorneys for Criminal Justice have named
 &UR; Clarence Darrow &LR;  Lawyer of the Century, reports California Lawyer.
Second place went to  &UR; Thurgood Marshall &LR; , followed by
 &UR; Michael Tigar &LR; ,  &UR; Charles Garry &LR; ,  &UR; William Kunstler &LR; ,  &UR; J. Tony &LR; 
 &UR; Serra &LR; ,  &UR; Gerry Spence &LR;  and  &UR; Stephen Bright &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ Re: Previous items this week: &UR; Harry Houdini &LR; 's heirs are
magicians; the price of an egg is $100,000; and Philadelphia is a
city. Everything else is fine.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Washington Post caught  &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR;  failing to leave
a tip at a diner in Albion, N.Y., but she said that her meal was on
the house and the owner had told her not to pay a cent. Etiquette
expert  &UR; Letitia Baldrige &LR;  said it was a faux pas. ``You always tip.
You guess what the bill was and you leave 15 to 20 percent ... but
frankly the first lady would give more.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Oakland Mayor  &UR; Jerry Brown &LR;  adamantly refused to allow a lei
to be looped around his neck the other day at Oakland Airport
festivities inaugurating Aloha Airlines' service from Oakland to
Honolulu. ``This is Oakland,'' he proclaimed. ``We should be
wearing oak trees.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've toured my whole life. I've broken every record, all over
the world. Me and the Grateful Dead. Every year, me and the
Grateful Dead would make the most money on the road. The road is a
way of life. You take your pictures, your pillow, you take the
songs. You find out where the best fish restaurant is. You find out
where the Versace store is.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Liza Minnelli in Interview magazine.
</P>
