u a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-FILE     02-16 1746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    EDITORS: THIS IS FILE 2 OF 2
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When airline flights are long and nonstop, such as 16 hours
between Atlanta and South Africa, how does it work with the cockpit
crew? Are there regulations about how long they can be at the
controls?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. International carriers are bound by the regulations of
their respective countries, according to the Montreal-based
International Civil Aviation Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the new South African Airways flights to and from
Atlanta, two sets of captains operate the aircraft on shifts, said
airline spokeswoman Ann Gillespie. She added that South African
Airways follows FAA guidelines, since the aircraft operate into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   FAA regulations specify that flight crews can fly for no more
than eight hours before they must be relieved, said agency
spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen. Usually, she said, a crew member flies
the aircraft for several hours, then rests in facilities that are
required to be available while someone else is at the controls.
After resting, the first person returns to duty. The eight hours is
``actual flying time,'' by the way, and doesn't include preflight
preparations, Bergen said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it still possible to purchase official programs from the
Atlanta Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, as long as supplies last. The Atlanta Super Bowl Host
Committee suggests checking an online source,
www.officialstuff.com, which as of Feb. 9 indicated programs were
available for $19.95 (shipping and handling included). A spokesman
at National Football League headquarters in New York said programs
also can be ordered by calling 1-877-NFL-SHOP (1-877-635-7467).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently reported how to convert temperatures from
Celsius to Fahrenheit. Is there a similar formula for determining
wind chill?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but it's complex. A simpler way is to check a chart that
has temperatures in Fahrenheit ranging from, say, 45 degrees above
zero to 45 below, relating them to wind velocity.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the formula is complicated is that the wind chill
equivalents don't simply double if, for instance, the actual
temperature is steady but the wind speed doubles. Say the air
temperature is 25 degrees F and the wind velocity is 10 mph; the
numerical table puts the wind chill equivalent temperature at 10.
If the temperature is the same (25) and the wind velocity is
doubled to 20 mph, the wind chill equivalent is 3 below zero. If
the temperature is 25 and the wind velocity is 30 mph, the wind
chill equivalent is 10 degrees below zero.
</P>
<P>
   A chart can be found in World Book Encyclopedia, available at
any library. Look under ``Wind chill.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: On a recent episode of the TV game show ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' the name of the Michelin mascot was identified as
Bibendum. We thought it was simply ``the Michelin tire man.'' What
is the origin of the name Bibendum, and how was it chosen as the
mascot?
</P>
<P>
   A: The genesis of the name Bibendum came in February 1893, at
the conference of the Society of Civil Engineers of Paris, when
Andre Michelin introduced the expression that was to become a
Michelin motto: ``The tire drinks obstacles.'' A year later, at the
Exposition Universelle et Coloniale at Lyon, France, Andre and his
brother, Edouard, noticed a pile of tires of varying sizes. Edouard
remarked to Andre that if the pile of tires had arms, it would look
like a man. Thus was the idea planted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1897, illustrator Marius Rossillon, who went by the pseudonym
O'Galop, showed the Michelin brothers several ideas for publicity.
One was a sketch showing a drinker raising his arm, with the motto,
``Nunc est bibendum'' (``It's time to drink''), after a verse from
Horace. The line reminded Andre of the phrase ``The tire drinks
obstacles.'' So he ordered a poster from O'Galop, who created one
the following year using a character composed of tires and
repeating the ``Nunc est bibendum'' motto.
</P>
<P>
   The association was complete when, several months later, a race
car driver spotted Andre Michelin and shouted, ``There's
Bibendum.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported recently on the selection process for candidates
for the TV program ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' Can you give
me similar information about getting on ``Wheel of Fortune''?
</P>
<P>
   A: A new system called the ``Wheelmobile,'' which will visit
several cities each month, is in the works. There's no schedule yet
for when and where it will be going, said a show spokeswoman. Her
advice: Watch local affiliates on which the program is broadcast,
and they will announce locations and schedules for the Wheelmobile.
</P>
<P>
   Once locations are established, people who want to be an
audience member or a contestant can go there and enter their names
and telephone numbers into a database. Names then will be chosen
randomly.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to make the system more equitable for people
nationwide, rather than having contestants and audience members
basically coming from the show's home base in Southern California,
the spokeswoman said. She added that nothing will happen soon,
because the show is scheduled to go on hiatus for a couple of
months.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has the recent spell of cold and ice in Georgia damaged the
Vidalia onion crop?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lovers of the sweet onions will be happy to hear that the
worst of the harsh weather bypassed the exclusive growing area. A
spokeswoman at Morris Farms in east-central Georgia said a few
onions may have suffered, but the majority of the crop is expected
to be fine. She said the onions should be in grocery stores in late
April, and will be available through June, or even longer if kept
in cold storage.
</P>
<P>
   Q: News reports indicate that oil found on a Russian freighter
originated from Iraq. How was that conclusion reached?
</P>
<P>
   A: The vessel carried a load of gas oil, a refined product often
used as diesel fuel. Samples were flown to the U.S. Customs Service
Laboratory in San Francisco, the routine procedure in cases of
suspected smuggling in the Persian Gulf. The sample's chemical
signature then was compared to those in a library of 3,000
reference samples collected worldwide. A positive match showed that
the tanker's cargo had originated as crude oil from an Iraqi well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We lost two pine and five maple trees as a result of ice
storms. They broke in two, so must be removed. Since none caused
damage to my home, my insurance company won't reimburse me. I have
a bid for $4,000 from a tree-removal company to remove the wood. Is
that deductible as a casualty loss on my income tax return?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some of it may be deductible, but several factors must be
taken into account, said IRS spokesman Mark Green.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's a ``$100 rule,'' that must be applied, meaning
you reduce the figure to $3,900. Then you must apply another rule,
which requires calculating 10 percent of your adjusted gross
income. If that is less than $3,900, the resulting dollar figure
becomes the deductible amount. As an example, 10 percent of an
adjusted gross income of $10,000 would be $1,000. Subtract that
from $3,900, and the actual deductible amount is $2,900. On the
other hand, if the adjustable gross income is $50,000, there can be
no deductible, because 10 percent ($5,000) is more than $3,900.
</P>
<P>
   Green said full information on this subject can be found on page
6 of IRS publication 547, Casualties, Disaster and Theft.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know the next Super Bowl will be in Tampa, but have the
dates and locations of others after that been announced?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The next two will be in New Orleans, on Jan. 27, 2002;
and in San Diego, on Jan. 26, 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that the Oscar statues are dipped in a 24-karat gold
solution. How much does it cost to produce them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Each statuette costs about $350 to fabricate, said John
Pavlik, communications director at the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 are made each year, he added, to ensure that there are
enough in case of ties, honorary or special achievement awards, or
other unforeseen circumstances. No one knows the exact number of
statuettes that will be presented until the envelopes are opened
March 26.
</P>
<P>
   Other factoids: Each statuette is made from the alloy britannium
and then is plated in copper, nickel silver, and finally 24-karat
gold. The original statuettes were solid bronze, and for a while
they were made of plaster. They stand 13 1/2 inches tall and weigh
8 1/2 pounds. To date, 2,328 have been presented. The official
name, by the way, isn't Oscar; it's the Academy Award of Merit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just got back from Florida, where I received the new $1
coins in change at two stores, Wal-Mart and Sam's Club. I was told
they had exclusive distribution of the coins for a limited period.
If true, how could the government favor one retailer over another?
</P>
<P>
   A: There was a practical reason. The U.S. Mint introduced the
new Golden Dollar in stages, one of which was an arrangement with
Wal-Mart and Sam's Clubs to put the dollar coins into their cash
drawers. Mint spokesman Michael White traced the initiative back to
the lack of acceptance of the earlier Susan B. Anthony dollar coin.
In 20 years, that coin ``never made it into the retail arena,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So this time around, with the new Golden Dollar, the Mint talked
with several retailers about ways to get them into cash drawers _
and consumers' pockets _ quickly. Wal-Mart and Sam's Clubs were the
first to agree with the Mint to begin using the coins, White said.
The Mint thought people would be more likely to get them quickly at
these huge retail outlets than at a bank, he added.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, the Golden Dollars were distributed in some boxes of
Cheerios. On Jan. 18, the Federal Reserve began receiving a supply.
On Jan. 27, the Federal Reserve began sending them to financial
institutions, and the Mint began offering the coins in rolls and
bags on its Web site. Wal-Marts and Sam's Clubs began distributing
them Jan. 30, with the promotion limited to February.
</P>
<P>
   March 1 is the target date for 200 million of the new coins to
be in general circulation.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
