<SLUG> BC-JULIO-BOCCA-DANCE-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, FIXING SLUGLINE)  
 BALLET'S MEN FEEL THE MACHO PULL OF `FOSSE'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Valerie Gladstone's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about the Brazilian choreographer Deborah Colker.  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Julio Bocca, a dashing star of American Ballet
Theater, did not look himself as he rehearsed in a mid-Manhattan
studio early this month. With his toes turned in, his back arched
and his hands placed on his hips, not a trace of Albrecht or Romeo
could be discerned in his demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   While still jet-lagged from a flight from Buenos Aires and worn
from rehearsing his own company, Ballet Argentina, for its recent
performance at the World Financial Center Winter Garden, he was
trying to absorb a choreographic style as different from Petipa as
night from day.
</P>
<P>
   And he had to learn it fast, because last Tuesday he was to make
his Broadway debut in the Tony Award-winning musical ``Fosse.'' A
compilation of 30 dance sequences, it features excerpts from
``Sweet Charity'' and ``Dancin''' by the quintessential Broadway
choreographer Bob Fosse.
</P>
<P>
   Bocca joins the show through April 2, when Keith Roberts _ a
former Ballet Theater principal who was bitten by the Broadway bug
when he danced the lead in Matthew Bourne's irreverent ``Swan
Lake'' _ comes in for the summer. ``Fosse,'' which opened in
January 1999, is now a plum for big-name male ballet dancers.
</P>
<P>
   From the sidelines, the show's dance captain, Bill Burns,
unobtrusively observed Bocca. He had scheduled five hours a day,
six days a week for two weeks to get Bocca up to par for his
several numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every step means something,'' said Burns, who, along with J.
Kathleen Watkins, coaches all 35 cast members. ``It's never just
dancing for dancing's sake. I tell them some of the images Bob had
in mind. Then I let them plan their attack.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first chord of ``Bojangles,'' from ``Dancin' ,'' Bocca
tilted his head to the side, rolled his shoulders and fell into a
slow, mellow soft shoe. But there was nothing of the ordinary
hoofer about him. ``Good and loose,'' Burns said approvingly. Bocca
smiled with some relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob felt that ballet dancers made his dances look classy,''
said Ann Reinking, the show's co-choreographer with Chet Walker.
``That's why we've had them in the show from the beginning. It
gives people who never go to the ballet a chance to see these
superb dancers. Plus, their star power doesn't hurt the box
office.'' In fact, ticket sales took off for Bocca's first week.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond Richardson, a former principal dancer with Ballet
Theater, led the pack and won a Tony nomination for best supporting
actor last year. Scott Jovovich, a former principal with the
Joffrey Ballet and the Pittsburgh Ballet, followed Richardson and
continues in the show, and Roberts briefly preceded Bocca and
returns when he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the coming months, Damian Woetzel, a New York City
Ballet principal, also plans to don bowler hat and gyrate. To him,
it means more than dancing. ``I can't wait to sing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Bocca was invited into the show last fall by Reinking, who
starred in many Fosse productions, he asked whether she would
rehearse him alone. ``I wanted to make sure,'' he said, ``that Ann
felt comfortable with me in Fosse's work.'' She agreed to teach him
``Percussion 4,'' also from ``Dancin','' an explosive solo danced
to drums and nicknamed ``Perk 4'' by the cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells the story of a man,'' said Reinking, ``going into a
studio and trying to figure out, as he watches himself in the
mirror, what he can do, what his next step should be. He's fighting
age. But as he warms up, he loses that grim feeling and starts to
have fun _ though soon his time runs out and he has to leave. In
four or five minutes you go through four or five hours in a life.
It's a tour de force.'' In a little over an hour, both Reinking and
Bocca felt he had a grip on it.
</P>
<P>
   Why do male ballet dancers so eagerly join ``Fosse''? ``There's
a bit of the grass-must-be-greener on the other side,'' said Burns.
``But they also like the ensemble work. I remember Desmond wanted
to be in every number. They love the energy. And the work doesn't
squelch personality; charisma is crucial for these parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps speaking for all of them, Jovovich said, ``It's nice to
get out from behind all those tutus.'' There's also not a little
machismo in their choice. ``Perk 4'' can ``trash the body, it's so
arduous,'' said Jovovich. ``Nothing compares to it. I think of it
as sporting event and approach it as a challenge. It's very
athletic but needs very good ballet technique. I love it and I hate
it. I never do `Perk 4' without trepidation. It's a very liberating
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts called the work ``manly'' and ``animalistic.'' He too
said he had to get pumped up to do it. In Richardson's opinion:
``Fosse loved to see the effort put into his dances. He wanted to
see the sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   At his rehearsal, Bocca was sweating, at least metaphorically.
``Right now,'' he said, ``I'm afraid if I do badly in the show, it
will reflect on my position at Ballet Theater. It's a new
beginning, but I'm scared.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not the only one. What if, once these dancers return to
their regular gigs, they can't get ``Fosse'' out of their blood?
Will Bocca confuse his winged creatures in the middle of ``Swan
Lake,'' swivel his hips, click his fingers and launch into ``Bye,
Bye Blackbird''? Could Roberts forget his gallant self in ``Romeo
and Juliet'' and slink around like the sexy dude in ``Cool Hand
Luke''? Will Woetzel break into song in Balanchine's ``Stars and
Stripes''? Oh, what has Fosse wrought?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
