A9198 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DIETITIAN17-COX     02-16 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIETITIAN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eating low-fat? Choose corn tortillas over flour
 &HT;    By Karen Collins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Are tortillas considered a grain product?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Anything made from plant grains such as wheat, corn,
rye, oats or barley is a grain product. Corn tortillas are
generally whole grain products and therefore a good source of fiber
and many nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Flour tortillas are most often made from refined flour, though
some are made from whole wheat flour, so look for these.
</P>
<P>
   Corn tortillas usually contain no more than 1 gram of fat, but
fat content of flour tortillas can range from 2 to 5 grams. If you
eat more than one tortilla, this small difference can add up, which
is a concern for weight control. In addition, the fat comes from
hydrogenated oils that contain trans fatty acids (not a
heart-healthy fat).
</P>
<P>
   The calories in tortillas also vary: Small ones may be about
equal to a slice of bread, but larger tortillas may contain the
calories of two slices of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much can people lower their blood cholesterol through
diet alone?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most studies have shown that a moderate reduction in
saturated fat (the cholesterol-raising fat found in meats and
high-fat dairy products) can lower total blood cholesterol about 8
percent (maybe 10 percent or more if the original diet was quite
high-fat).
</P>
<P>
   A more important indicator of heart disease risk is to look
specifically at LDL (''bad'') cholesterol. Studies show that
moderately low-fat diets can reduce LDL levels anywhere from 5
percent to 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A much more severe restriction of saturated fat that is part of
a total lifestyle program advocated by researcher Dean Ornish,
M.D., has reportedly reduced LDL cholesterol by about 37 percent.
Adding more fruits, vegetables, whole grains and beans for fiber
can sometimes enhance a diet's cholesterol-lowering ability.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have a genetic tendency to produce high blood
cholesterol, while others are very influenced by diet. But even in
people who require medication to bring blood cholesterol to normal
levels, a healthy diet is still important for the medication to
work properly.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do the fruit snacks that come in different shapes and strips
count toward the recommended number of fruit servings for children?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Although these snacks are labeled ``made with real
fruit'', they are not 100% fruit by any means. You can see this for
yourself by checking the ingredient list. These products are made
with fruit or juice concentrate, but have quite a bit of added
sugar, too. Although extra vitamin C is sometimes added, they are
generally low in other nutrients and don't offer the dietary fiber
that is found in fruit itself. For your child's lunchbox or
after-school snack, fresh fruits like apples, pears, oranges and
bananas are much more nutritious options. For added variety, pack
small boxes of raisins, plastic bags of dried fruit mixtures,
individual-serving packages of applesauce, or fresh kiwi cut in
half to eat by spooning it straight from the skin.
</P>
<P>
   These Ask a Dietitian questions were answered by Karen Collins,
M.S., R.D. of the American Institute for Cancer Research.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
