<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE URGES SENATE TO REJECT APPOINTMENT OF BRADLEY SMITH TO FEC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH N.C. _ Presidential hopeful Al Gore on Wednesday weighed
in on the man Republicans have chosen to join the Federal Election
Commission, saying the Senate should reject Bradley Smith because
of his opposition to campaign-finance regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I neither support this nomination nor agree with the views of
professor Bradley Smith,'' the vice president said in a statement
issued during a campaign stop in North Carolina. ``The last thing
we need is an FEC commissioner who publicly questions not only the
constitutionality of proposed reforms, but also the
constitutionality of current limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's statement came four days after his Democratic
presidential opponent, Bill Bradley, blasted Smith's nomination.
While Gore has endorsed more stringent campaign-finance laws, some
of his own fund-raising activities during the 1996 presidential
election have raised questions.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley called Clinton's Feb. 9 appointment of Smith to the FEC
``a major retreat on campaign-finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week President Clinton forwarded Smith's name to the Senate
as part of a deal with Republican leader Trent Lott of Mississippi.
The president and the senator made a deal that Clinton would not
block Smith's appointment in exchange for the Senate agreeing to
vote on several of Clinton's judicial nominations that have been
bottled up in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it, but I decided that I should not shut down the
whole appointments process and depart from the plain intent of the
law,'' Clinton said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But John Czwartacki, a Lott spokesman, said, ``There was no quid
pro quo. The two are not linked.''
</P>
<P>
   The FEC, a six-member panel that oversees campaign-finance
activity is, by law, split evenly between Democrats and
Republicans. The White House traditionally honors the opposing
party's selection.
</P>
<P>
   However, Smith's selection has been controversial since his name
was floated last year by Republicans. Clinton held the nomination
up for months in the hopes that Republicans would find a more
acceptable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ongoing public controversy over the GOP's choice,
Gore told reporters that he did not speak to Clinton about the
nominee until after the president had sent his name to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know the nomination was pending,'' Gore said. The
vice president explained that he is no longer regularly consulting
with the president about policy matters. ``I'm out of the road full
time now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore defended the arrangement between Clinton and Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a considered judgement because of the unfair position
adopted by Senator Lott,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, the vice president also called upon Republican
presidential candidates John McCain and George W. Bush to pressure
Senate Republicans to reject Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``If John McCain and George Bush support campaign-finance reform
_ as they profess _ they should have their Republican colleagues
withdraw professor Smith as their nominee,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Embarking on a two-day southern swing, Gore mixed official
duties with campaigning Wednesday as he took a helicopter tour of
Georgia communities that had been hard hit by tornadoes earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   While the Gore campaign must pay for the political trips, the
taxpayers picked up the tab for his tour of the tornado damage
because it was deemed official business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is a candidate for president but he still has his
constitutional duties as the vice president,'' said Gore spokesman
Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Quinn, a spokesman in the vice president's office in
Washington, could not provide an exact figure of exactly how much
the tornado portion of the trip cost taxpayers. She said it was a
``very small fraction of the trip.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
