<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9201 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-TV-MARRY-MILLIONAIRE-     02-16 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARRY-MILLIONAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORE ANOTHER HIT FOR BIZARRE TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mystery man sits in the shadows. The prospective brides
stand on a stage in wedding gowns, waiting for the proposal. And
every moment the suspense builds _ and so do the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   It took place Tuesday night, with a special on the Fox Network
called ``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?,'' the latest
offbeat real-life format to shake up a network television season
that is already one of the zaniest in memory.
</P>
<P>
   The entire landscape of network television was changed by the
success of ABC's game show ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and
Fox's Tuesday night show this week proved that variations on that
theme can reach similar ratings heights.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's two-hour special featured a parade of would-be brides
competing to be chosen by a multi-millionaire, and it culminated in
an on-the-air wedding presided over by a Nevada judge. Drawing
stunning ratings, it attracted more young viewers _ especially
female viewers _ than even the ABC's ``Millionaire'' show.
</P>
<P>
   The show's audience built strikingly through the night, as it
edged toward the actual wedding, growing from 10 million viewers in
its first half hour to 12.3 million in the second half hour to 18.9
million in the third half hour to a huge 22.8 million in the final
half hour.
</P>
<P>
   That final figure would have put the special among the top six
shows in all television, if it had been aired last week. The
ratings were even bigger among teen-age girls and young women. In
its final half hour, the show pulled in more than a third of all
women under the age of 35 watching television Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   One widespread reaction to the show's format was revulsion _ the
kind that apparently helps, not hurts ratings _ that women had
signed on to marry themselves off to an unknown man on a television
show.
</P>
<P>
   Women around the country discussed the show animatedly
Wednesday, some complaining that it reinforced stereotypes of women
desperate to be married, others clearly taken with the show's
fantasy element. The Fox website (Who Wants to Marry.com) was so
flooded with requests from women to be on the next edition of ``Who
Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire'' that it crashed Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took something like this to make the Miss America pageant
look good to me,'' Patricia Ireland, president of the National
Organization of Women said in an interview Wednesday night. ``At
least with the Miss America pageant you get scholarship money and
the guarantee of a year-long run. It perpetuates some very limited
stereotypes that men are success objects and women are sex
objects.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Darnell, the Fox executive who created the show,
defended the concept, saying that he planned to do another show
``the other way around,'' with a female millionaire choosing a
husband.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If you looked at these people at the end of the
show, you could tell it was less about the money, than it was about
the relationship. It'll either go on, or it won't. If they don't
get along, it won't work no matter how much money is involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The special, which aired during the February sweeps period,
became the latest example of network television reaching beyond
fictional drama and comedies for entertainment. Beyond the batch of
game shows, initiated by the success of ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' the networks have been lining up shows that reach
into real-life activities not usually meant to take place on
camera.
</P>
<P>
   CBS already has scheduled two shows for the summer that will
feature real people living together in enforced situations, one in
a house where every move they make will be on-camera, the other on
a desert island off Borneo. Both also involve big prize money for
the last surviving contestant.
</P>
<P>
   Darnell is known in television for creating such Fox specials as
``When Good Pets Go Bad'' and ``When Animals Attack.'' Last year
one of his programming ideas was a live show in which a 747 would
crash in the desert, an idea that top Fox executives made a point
of publicly disavowing.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Darnell was asked to create specials that avoided all
violence. His first idea was the marriage special. He acknowledged
that his concept had been to bring together the formats of the Miss
America pageant, ``The Dating Game'' and ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I thought it would be a little clever special,'' Darnell
said. ``The ratings and reactions to this are just stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   The show was promoted no more heavily than the average Fox
special. Probably because viewers starting to calling friends, the
audience built each half hour, receiving its biggest boost after
one hour, when ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' ended. For
the next hour, ``Who Wants to Marry a Millionaire?'' was the most
popular show on television.
</P>
<P>
   Darnell said more than a thousand women signed up for Tuesday's
show, a number that was pared down, through interviews, to the 50
contestants in the pageant, which was taped in Las Vegas last week.
The format included parades in evening gowns and beach wear, and
extensive interview segments where the women described their
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The multi-millionaire, shown only in shadow, then pared the
group down to 10, with the help of a panel made up of his friends
and family. The 10 semifinalists went through further interview
sessions to bring the number down to five finalists. The
contestants then appeared in wedding gowns. The multi-millionaire
made his choice, kneeling to propose. The wedding, officiated by a
Nevada judge, followed.
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives said the contestants had all undergone
appropriate health tests. They said that a ``standard pre-nuptual
agreement'' was signed, but they would not be specific about its
contents. From the show, the winner received _ in addition to the
husband _ a two-week vacation (the honeymoon), an Isuzu Trooper
automobile and a $35,000 diamond ring.
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives said the couple went off to the Caribbean, but
they would not disclose where. The details of their relationship
will be up to them, Darnell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding is they are taking it very slow, trying to
find out what their relationship will really be,'' Darnell said.
</P>
<P>
   The bride turned out to be Darva Conger, a 34-year-old emergency
room nurse from Santa Monica, Calif., who had also served in the
Gulf War. The lucky _ and rich _ man was Rick Rockwell, 42,
described on the show as a real estate developer and motivational
speaker who came to California after college to be a stand-up
comic. Darnell said Fox had throughly researched his financial
status, and he does, in fact, have assets worth many millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's entertainment division said Wednesday that it is not yet
ready to announce a second edition of the special. But Darnell said
that given the success of this one, more can be expected. Fox will
repeat an edited, one-hour version of this special next Tuesday
night at 8, for all those who missed it the first time. And, as
Darnell said, sometime in the future it will be done the other way
around.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he believed there was such willingness on the part of
both single women and a single millionaire to take part in a
produced, taped and edited blessed event, Darnell said, ``Obviously
it's hard to meet people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
