<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VULCAN-SPORTING-NEWS-     02-16 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VULCAN-SPORTING-NEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VULCAN VENTURES TO PURCHASE THE SPORTING NEWS FROM TIMES MIRROR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul G. Allen, who co-founded Microsoft with Bill Gates,
announced Wednesday that his company, Vulcan Ventures Inc., is
buying The Sporting News, the country's oldest sporting magazine,
from the Times Mirror Co.
</P>
<P>
   Executives involved in the talks said that Vulcan agreed to pay
more than $100 million for the magazine and its other properties,
which include a sports-licensing venture, a line of annual preview
magazines, a book-publishing arm and the Web site affiliated with
the magazine, www.thesportingnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   While it is Allen's first magazine purchase, it is part of a
strategy to develop relationships with consumers on the Internet
through magazine sites, and a Vulcan executive added that the
company was exploring other magazine options.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the 114-year-old weekly magazine also marks the
first time that an owner of sports teams has bought a news
organization devoted to covering sports, sometimes with a critical
eye. Allen owns The Seattle Seahawks, a professional football team,
and The Portland Trail Blazers, a professional basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   The sale comes six months after The Times Mirror Co. announced
that it was paring certain assets to concentrate on its newspaper
business, which has been the core of the corporate strategy put
forth by its chairman and chief executive, Mark H. Willes. Times
Mirror publishes seven newspapers, including The Los Angeles Times,
Newsday and The Baltimore Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Efrem Zimbalist 3rd, the chief financial officer and chairman of
Times Mirror Magazines _ which publishes enthusiast magazines like
Ski, Yachting and Outdoor Life _ said that he had chosen Allen's
company in part based on its connection to the broadcast world.
Vulcan Ventures also owns Charter Communications, a cable company
based in St. Louis. The company will rank as the fourth-largest
cable operator in the country after it completes pending purchases
of other cable concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sporting News was the only title we had that deals with
spectator sports, not participatory sports,'' Zimbalist said.
``Consumers' primary relationship with spectator sports is through
television and sometimes, radio, so if you have a relationship with
television, it gives the publication a leg up.''
</P>
<P>
   Of The Sporting News' competitors, Sports Illustrated provides
content for CNN-SI, a program service of CNN, and ESPN magazine is
visibly linked to the ESPN network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hoped that the magazine would wind up with someone with a
strong cable presence,'' Zimbalist said. ``We felt it would never
be No. 1 or No. 2 without that advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Vulcan is also an investor in dozens of Internet,
telecommunications and media companies, including Oxygen Media and
Drugstore.com. In a statement, William D. Savoy, the president of
Vulcan, said that the purchase fit in with Allen's strategy of
developing a multimedia company that connects consumers through the
Internet, broadcast and cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of strong national brands to Internet audiences
cannot be underestimated,'' he said. ``As we further develop the
comprehensive channel and portal offerings for our cable customers,
we will look for precisely these types of branded, established
vertical content offerings.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   James Nuckols, the president and chief executive of The Sporting
News, said that the fact that Allen owns sports teams would not
affect the magazine's coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an identical issue to Sports Illustrated being in the
Time Warner empire,'' Nuckols said, referring to a recent incident
in which the Time Inc. magazine Sports Illustrated ran a damaging
interview with John Rocker, a pitcher with the Atlanta Braves, a
team owned owned by Time Warner. ``The John Rocker issue was pretty
good evidence that it doesn't affect how they cover sports. We will
operate the same way. And Paul Allen runs his companies in a very,
very decentralized way.''
</P>
<P>
   The sports magazine market has shifted dramatically in the last
two years. The Sporting News and other smaller, sports magazines,
such as EMAP Petersen's Sport, have had to react to the success of
ESPN magazine, which is published by the magazine division of the
Walt Disney Co. Since 1998, when ESPN magazine was founded, its
biweekly circulation has soared to 850,000. Founded in 1886, The
Sporting News was long a bible for baseball fans, later shifting
its focus to include other professional and collegiate sports.
Despite a 1997 redesign that cost Times Mirror about $6 million and
editorial and publishing efforts to increase circulation, The
Sporting News loses about $2 million a year, said executives at
companies who had considered buying the magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
