<SLUG> BC-ELANCE-BACKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE GETS $12 MILLION IN FINANCING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELance.com, a World Wide Web site that has added an auction
twist to the buying and selling of professional services online,
said Wednesday that it had received $12 million in financing from
the venture capital firm of Kleiner, Perkins, Caufield &AMP; Byers.
</P>
<P>
   John Doerr and Joe Lacob, general partners at Kleiner, joined
the board of eLance.com, which is based in Sunnyvale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The site permits companies or individuals seeking a range of
services as varied as language translation, business and technical
consulting, manuscript typing and Web site design, to post requests
for bids from free-lancers. It also lists offers of fixed-price
services from freelancers.
</P>
<P>
   The site, which started operations in September, has been free,
but that will soon change. Srini R. Anumolu, the cofounder and
president, said eLance.com planned to begin taking 5 percent of the
transaction fee, probably starting March 1.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
