A9207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-BRADLEY-270&AMP;ADD-NY     02-16 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRADLEY-270&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY SAYS CLINTON AND GORE NEGLECTED UPSTATE NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH with KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Turning his attention to upstate New York, Bill
Bradley said Wednesday that the federal government had not invested
enough money in the region's depressed economy and criticized Vice
President Al Gore for not spending enough time here.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing small crowds in Buffalo and Rochester, Bradley said
one reason that upstate cities had not benefited from the recent
economic boom nearly as much as other regions was that the Clinton
administration had not spent enough on economic development
projects here. While the national employment rate increased by
almost 19 percent in the 1990s, Bradley said, the employment rate
in western New York grew by only 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we can do in being a good steward of the
good economy is to recognize that not every place in America is
booming,'' Bradley told about 200 students and administrators at
Erie Community College in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said several times that Gore had neglected upstate New
York. ``Al Gore says he's been to California 60 times since he
became vice president,'' he said. ``My question to him is, how many
times has he been to western New York?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore last visited upstate New York on Monday, when he delivered
a speech in Rochester on education.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Bradley, Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for the Gore
campaign, said, ``Al Gore has been fighting with the administration
to expand prosperity all across the country while Bill Bradley was
out on the speaking circuit making money for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley last visited upstate New York in October, when he made
stops in Albany and Syracuse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wednesday, Bradley also lamented the rising cost of heating oil,
a pressing issue throughout New York and particularly upstate.
</P>
<P>
   As he has done before, Bradley called on the Clinton
administration to release oil from the nation's Strategic Petroleum
Reserve to drive down the cost of home heating oil. The
administration has refused to release oil from the reserves, saying
it should be saved for emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Wednesday that he would provide
low-income families in the Northeast with $125 million to help with
the rising cost of home heating oil, on top of $200 million
provided earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley praised the administration for granting the heating
subsidies, but at the same time, his campaign said ``the real
intended beneficiary was Al Gore.'' According to a press release
from the Bradley campaign, New Hampshire received $5.4 million in
heating subsidies last month, on the eve of that state's primary,
while New York received only $2.6 million. The press release
suggested that a $34 million subsidy that New York received this
month was timed to arrive near the state primary, March 7, so that
Gore would win more votes here.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway scoffed at Bradley's suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The release was intended to help low-income people stay
warmer,'' he said. ```I was in New Hampshire, and it was cold.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley spoke Wednesday night in New York City at the
Lesbian and Gay Community Services Center, Gore on Wednesday
received the endorsement of the Empire State Pride Agenda, one of
the state's largest gay and lesbian groups. On Friday, Gore
received the backing of the Human Rights Campaign, the nation's
largest gay and lesbian group.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Soref, co-chairman of the New York group, acknowledged that
Gore and Bradley had similar positions on gay issues but said his
group chose Gore because ``the Clinton/Gore administration has
brought unprecedented changes'' for gays. In thanking the group,
Gore noted that he was ``the first vice president to speak at a
gay-rights event.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would appoint a commission to study ``how domestic
partners should be recognized.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2110EST &QL; 
