<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SC-POLITICAL-PROFILE-     02-16 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-POLITICAL-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 VOTERS SKEPTICAL OF MOTIVE OF McCAIN IN PULLING ADS 
 (See also CAROLINA-PROFILE, SC-REPUBS) 
(rk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SULLIVAN'S ISLAND, S.C. - Huntington Smith, restaurateur and
political independent, thinks highly of Sen. John McCain, but not
as highly as he did a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with McCain because I thought he was running a
clean campaign,'' he said, standing in the parking lot of Sully's,
the seafood place he owns in this affluent beach town near
Charleston. ``But I've been disappointed he's been running some
negative ads in South Carolina. It's disappointing that he has to
resort to that to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he had heard about McCain's vow to withdraw his
attack ads _ in which he portrayed Gov. George W. Bush as
untrustworthy and likened him to President Clinton _ but it did not
diminish his feeling of having been let down by the senator. ``Has
he pulled them?'' he asked. ``I don't know if he's honestly pulled
them or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies a problem for McCain, at least insofar as his
appeal to a random assortment of voters here is concerned. In
interviews Wednesday up and down the tiny business district of this
resort community, South Carolinians who plan to vote in the
Republican primary on Saturday declined to give the senator any
credit for having taken off the air his spots attacking Bush. They
tended to view the withdrawal as a ploy, as an indication, perhaps,
that the senator is less the outsider than he claims to be.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those interviewed identified themselves as McCain
supporters. ``He says, `I will not lie to you'; I believe him,''
said Ann Matthews, a retired day care worker. But many also
expressed a kind of I-should-have-known-better disillusionment with
the nasty tone of the campaign, and the role that McCain had played
in fostering it.
</P>
<P>
   Like others who stopped to talk, Jackie Donohoe of North
Charleston said the harsh tone of the televised debate Tuesday
night in Columbia had reinforced her feeling that McCain had not
seriously abandoned the negativity that was obscuring other issues
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went right back and started doing it again,'' Donohoe said,
referring to McCain's argument with Bush during the debate over who
was to blame for the attack ads. ``All he had to do was say, `I'm
not answering that question.'''
</P>
<P>
   Strategists for McCain have said they hoped that pulling the
attack ads would highlight the contrasting campaign styles of their
candidate and Bush. But if the views of voters here are any
indication, the tactic may have been a little too transparent to
have the desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   The reactions of viewers and voters here suggest to some
political analysts that McCain's effort to position himself as a
kind of anti-politician was harmed by his venturing into attack
advertising; some polls taken over the last several days showed his
negative ratings rising.
</P>
<P>
   William V. Moore, a political scientist at the College of
Charleston, said it was the nature of McCain's attack that may
cause him trouble. Suggesting in a spot that Bush's character was
comparable to Clinton's was perceived by the Bush campaign as being
over the line.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, people on the streets of Sullivan's Island, waved
away the significance of McCain's repudiation of his own
commercials. Some said the damage had been done, and expressing
regret did not erase the television images. Others had a hard time
recalling anything but the shouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've gotten from the whole thing is the bickering back and
forth,'' said Gay Slough, one of the proprietors of the Gibson
Cafe. ``They're both like schoolchildren; I don't know who to vote
for.''
</P>
<P>
   At the cafe bar, Kirk Heidenreich, who has a custom furniture
business in nearby Mount Pleasant, was nursing a beer and a gripe
about the corrosive impact of negative political commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the ads help them any,'' Heidenreich said.
``They get enough coverage on the news _ it's not as if they need
any more. They're wasting all this money, if you ask me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Vavreck, an assistant professor of government at Dartmouth
College who studies political advertising, said that in view of the
ways in which the content of the television spots are endlessly
recycled by the news media, voters should not be blamed for being
so skeptical about McCain's motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the message of the ad is going to remain in the
discourse,'' Vavreck said, ``so it doesn't surprise me that people
haven't cut him any slack: The message is still out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some supporters like Smith, the restaurateur, are
willing to give him the benefit of the doubt. ``It's just being a
politician,'' he said with a shrug. ``It's not enough for me to
turn my back on him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
