<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NBA OFFERS MOOD SWINGS EACH NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He never went to college, but Kevin Garnett has a
head on his shoulders, way up there.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett has figured out the loop-the-loop logistics of the
National Basketball Association: There is always another game. Good
grief, is there always another game.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett and the Minnesota Timberwolves were visiting the Knicks
Wednesday night after both teams had flown in from other cities
Tuesday night. Minnesota had merely lost, but the Knicks had been
downright ghastly in Toronto, which would be alarming if mood
swings were not the norm for the league.
</P>
<P>
   There was always the possibility that the Knicks would light up
the Garden and that the Timberwolves would be energized by the rare
visit to New York. But in the new, new NBA, you really don't know
who is going to emerge from the runway just before the anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these last few games show that when you relax and when
you don't come out with that focus or edge, you get beat up pretty
bad,'' Garnett said after his team lost to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA's crazy like that,'' the young sage from a Chicago
high school added. ``You have one night when you're great and one
night when you're terrible. The best thing is that tomorrow is
another day.''
</P>
<P>
   The inconsistency in the league _ we are not talking here about
losing; we are talking about apathy _ is yet another symptom the
NBA is floundering right now. And people are noticing.
</P>
<P>
   The television rating for the All-Star Game last Sunday was the
lowest since the game went on the networks, down 35 percent from
the last one, two years ago, when a certain Michael Jordan still
roamed the land. People are avoiding pro hoops on Sunday afternoon
to see if Tiger Woods can take another golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, it was a distinct pleasure to push the clicker
and get away from Patrick Ewing's bemused scowl in search of George
W. Bush's characteristic smirk.
</P>
<P>
   The eminently clickable Knicks seem unable to put a few strong
games together, and their coach, Jeff Van Gundy, does not want to
blame road games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can lose the fight on the road, but when you have no
fight, that's a problem,'' Van Gundy said Wednesday night, not
knowing whether his players would bring any defense with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different guys take a possession off,'' Van Gundy said of his
starting team. ``There is not a priority to set a tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy said he constantly asks himself ``a litany of
questions'' about his own coaching, at least as much as he
re-evaluates his players. He was forced to take stock of his team
again Wednesday as the Philadelphia 76ers seemed to improve
themselves by trading for Toni Kukoc. If the Knicks have many more
walkabouts on the road, they could be in jeopardy for losing the
home-court advantage even in the first round of the playoffs. And
the road is not where these people excel.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Knicks had enough talent, Van Gundy screwed up his
face and remained silent long enough to make the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't separate talent from commitment,'' he said.
``Hustling is part of talent. It's all part of the same package.''
</P>
<P>
   He criticized his players for not being physical enough, despite
their reputation for aggression, most of which went north with
Charles Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are going in unimpeded,'' Van Gundy said, adding that his
players ``sort of got out of the way'' on layups Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He did not blame the league's crackdown on physicality since
some of the nasty Knick-Miami playoff series in recent years. He
just let it be known that nobody _ nobody _ in the starting lineup
was coming out and playing hard every game.
</P>
<P>
   The players seem mildly embarrassed but not to the point of
losing their cool or throwing themselves around on the floor after
the ball. This is certainly the personality of this team. Much of
the character left with Doc Rivers, Derek Harper, Buck Williams and
Oakley in what is now essentially ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the Knicks who give off the stale aroma of a
tired act. The new ownership of the Dallas Mavericks set a new low
by renting the definitive tired old act, Dennis Rodman, for the
rest of the season. Although he can still rebound, Rodman sets a
dreadful example to all concerned. He pulled his
sitting-on-the-court act Tuesday night, and was tossed out of the
game, all wearily predictable. It's not Rodman's fault but rather
the fault of the new owner, Joe Cuban, who hasn't been around long
enough to be embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   But hang in there. The playoffs are in two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
