<SLUG> BC-MICH-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN PLAYS SECOND-HAND ROLE AS GOP PRIMARY NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. _ Michigan may be the first big state that
the Republican presidential candidates are competing for _ with
more delegates at stake in its primary next Tuesday than in New
Hampshire and South Carolina combined _ but it is a second-hand
campaign that they are giving it.
</P>
<P>
   There are no advertisements with glimpses of the state flag, as
in South Carolina. No local debates have been turned into national
dramas. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of
Arizona have each spent one day here since the New Hampshire
primary Feb. 1, and neither is due back until after South Carolina
votes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't expect to shake the hand of a candidate any time soon,''
The Detroit News warned a bit sourly on its front page Tuesday
under a headline that said, ``S. Carolina Steals Show from Mich.''
</P>
<P>
   With surrogate speakers, advertising and dueling if comically
mismatched state organizations, the candidates are previewing in
Michigan the kind of campaign much of the country will get as the
Republicans turn their increasingly divided attention to the 16
states, including California, New York and Ohio, that will hold
primaries or caucuses March 7.
</P>
<P>
   This is not quite what Michigan expected when it moved up its
primary by a month to elbow into the limelight. But few people are
complaining because the primary used to be a ``nonentity,'' said
Bill Ballenger, the editor of Inside Michigan Politics. ``The
candidates were never here very much before this year, compared to
how often they've been here this time, which still isn't very
much.'' he said, adding, ``This is the biggest state east of the
Mississippi, particularly if you include all of the Great Lakes
water.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates have not forgotten Michigan, which will send 58
delegates to the party's convention this summer. The Republicans
held a debate here on Jan. 10. Bush's wife, Laura, visited for two
days earlier this week, and his father, former President George
Bush, is scheduled to begin a two-day swing Thursday, his second
trip. McCain is sending in a brace of senators this week, Mike
DeWine of Ohio and Chuck Hagel of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush is also exporting his feeling of victimization to
Michigan. He is running an advertisement here protesting a McCain
commercial that compared the governor to Bill Clinton, even though
the commercial ran only in South Carolina. And outside
organizations are coming to Bush's aid here as elsewhere. ``If you
want a strong pro-life candidate, don't vote for John McCain,''
declares an anti-abortion group's advertisement broadcast on
Christian radio in this conservative stronghold in western
Michigan. ``Vote for George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is also broadcasting advertisements here that were seen
elsewhere, recounting his biography and declaring him prepared to
be president.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are holding a separate, closed caucus in Michigan
next month. But anyone who is registered can vote in the Republican
primary, and McCain has surged in public opinion polls on the
support of Democrats and independents. In New Hampshire and South
Carolina, McCain made a kind of judo move, using the weight of
Bush's establishment support against him. In Michigan, the
establishment is pre-emptively blaming itself to protect Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At the bustling Bush headquarters in East Lansing, Del Chenault,
the 31-year-old executive director of the Michigan campaign, said,
``This has nothing to do with a referendum on George W. Bush.''
Instead, he said, Democrats are trying to embarrass the governor,
John Engler, a Republican who has put his political machine behind
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no, no, no,'' said Ed Sarpolus, of Epic/MRA, a Lansing
polling firm. ``This is scapegoat time. This is point-the-finger
time, we-don't-want-to-take-any-blame time. I've heard all of this
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarpolus said that voters who said they would cross over for
McCain want to support him, not to punish another candidate, and
that Michigan had a history of backing insurgents, including former
Gov. George C. Wallace of Alabama, the Rev. Jesse Jackson and
Patrick J. Buchanan, the conservative commentator.
</P>
<P>
   Sarpolus noted that McCain had climbed in the polls despite
barely organizing in Michigan. This suggests that it is his
performance elsewhere that has buoyed him in this state, and that
if he loses in South Carolina his support may fade.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain headquarters here has a slapped-together feel, which
its denizens cite as a virtue. ``It's message over money,'' said
Mike Hudome, a media consultant who previously helped re-elect
Engler.
</P>
<P>
   The television receives two channels, and the nine telephones
are on separate lines, so that a meeting of the state campaign
leaders on Monday night was repeatedly interrupted as they dashed
to different rooms to answer the phones. The group planned McCain's
clockwise route through the state Sunday and Monday and discussed
where Senator DeWine should appear to draw news media attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the cameras in Toledo,'' said Hudome, referring to the
stations in the Ohio border city that broadcast into Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Peter DeMarco, the communications director, newly imported from
Washington, looked puzzled. ``Behind you, on the map _ where's
Toledo?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Voters seem pleased at the chance for a say in the nomination.
``If we waited another month there might be only one guy that's got
a shot at it,'' said Greg Blake, a 47-year-old diemaker who plans
to vote for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some wished they had seen more of the candidates. ``I was
a little surprised _ I wasn't hurt by it _ that McCain didn't make
a show in western Michigan when he was in Michigan,'' said a
67-year-old businessman here who spoke on condition that his name
not be published.
</P>
<P>
   The surrogates have generated some excitement, however. Bush's
visit to Battle Creek was the top story Tuesday on the local
television station. ``Melissa, it looks like the whole family is
getting involved in the campaign now,'' an anchor remarked to
Melissa Dunbar, the correspondent covering the visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are,'' she replied. ``It's really neat to see. It's nice
to have all the attention on Michigan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT &LR;      02-16 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS BRING AN AIR OF IRREVERENCE TO PRADA'S TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Argentina, Germany, New Zealand, Italy, Australia, Calif.,
Wash.) )(Eds: See also AMERICAS-CUP-ITALY) (DW) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ With mischief in his eye, and the trace
of a grin shadowed in his thick red beard, Doug Peterson looks like
a man enjoying the calm within the eye of a storm.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, the creator of the small tempest surrounding the
impending start of the 30th America's Cup match, most certainly is.
``I love this stuff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The five-of-nine-race finals between Team New Zealand and
Italy's Prada Challenge begin here Saturday. While there may be no
United States challenger for the cup this time, there is a strong
American presence in Prada's camp. Peterson, the gifted 54-year-old
naval architect who leads Prada's design team with the Argentine
German Frers, means to deliver his third straight cup-winning boat,
and thus is the most visible American. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His efforts are being matched by a fellow native Southern
Californian, the head coach Rod Davis _ who has transformed the
Prada afterguard of the helmsman Francesco de Angelis and the
tactician Torben Grael, former fleet-racing specialists, into
dangerous boat-versus-boat match racers _ and by the assistant
coach, Steve Erickson. Erickson is a 1984 Olympic sailing gold
medalist who has drilled the concept of working together into
Prada's 16-man crew.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, Peterson has been the newsmaker. On the front
page of Wednesday's New Zealand Herald, a photograph of the Team
New Zealand boat was splashed alongside this large, rather
indelicate caption: ``Is it a dog?''
</P>
<P>
   The picture referred to an article in which Peterson offered his
candid opinion of the boat the Kiwis have decided to sail in the
coming match. Under race rules, on Monday each team was obliged to
unveil its vessel; and no further changes to rigs, keels and other
equipment will be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   At the unveiling, Peterson stopped short of dropping to all
fours and barking at NZL 60, New Zealand's boat. He pulled no
punches in assessing the boat, which he believes employs too much
wetted surface _ it's too wide, he thinks, among other related
faults _ combined with a corresponding lack of sail area to nudge
it along.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't a fan of the placement of the wings in the ballast bulb
at the bottom of the keel: Team New Zealand's are placed in the
center of the bulb, Prada's are set in the more conventional
location on the bulb's trailing aft edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally,'' he said, ``I think they have a bit of a problem.
Particularly in winds below 12 knots. Maybe all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Peterson's summation, Clay Oliver, a member of Team
New Zealand's design team, would only say, ``Well, Doug always
seems to have all the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson has had many answers to the mysteries of boat speed
since arriving onto the international scene in 1973 with his
breakthrough one-tonner Ganbare. But it's in the America's Cup
arena where the self-taught designer has truly shined.
</P>
<P>
   As a main force behind the successful American defense in 1992,
and the dominating Kiwi challenge in 1995, Peterson has been on the
winning side in every campaign since the International America's
Cup Class boats replaced the 12-Meters. Now, he is going for a cup
triple. ``I guess I've just been able to stay a step ahead of the
field,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is only one of the American pieces of the Prada
puzzle. Like Peterson, the 45-year-old Davis is a veteran of the
cup wars. He is in his eighth campaign, having represented
syndicates from the United States, Australia, and New Zealand, in
roles ranging from sail trimmer to skipper, over a cup career that
has spanned 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of his marriage to his New Zealand-born wife, Liz,
Davis holds dual citizenship and won an Olympic silver medal
sailing under the Kiwi flag in 1992. His brother-in-law, Tom
Schnakenberg, is a stalwart of the Team New Zealand design and
sailing team. But family connections only go so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like he's sending me an e-mail every time they make a
change,'' Davis said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Erickson, 38, has also played the cup game as both a coach and a
competitor. A native of Seattle, he won a world championship with
Paul Cayard in the Star class nearly a decade before they joined
forces in a winning Whitbread round-the-world race campaign in
1998. But when Erickson received a call from his longtime friend de
Angelis to join Prada, the timing was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   As for Peterson's blunt appraisal of the competition, and the
differences in their two boats, Davis shrugged and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Team New Zealand is onto a different page of
refinement,'' he said. ``Whether it's a page backward or forward,
we'll wait and see.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICAS-CUP-ITALY-NY     02-16 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-ITALY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S CUP CHALLENGER, LUNA ROSSA, CAPTURES ITALIANS FANCY 
</HEADLINE>
 - (Eds: See also Americas-Cup; Also being filed in `i' category.) 
(DW) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The night that the Prada sailboat Luna Rossa wound up
qualifying for the America's Cup finals _ the first Italian boat to
do so since 1992 _ the coach of the AC Milan soccer team blacked
out the players' training camp television sets, afraid that they
would blow their next match by staying up all night to watch the
chic gray-and-red Prada sails edge ahead of America One in the
deciding race.
</P>
<P>
   In Naples, members of the Circolo Italia yacht club that spawned
the Prada skipper, Francesco De Angelis, voluntarily pledged not to
watch. Sailors are superstitious, and none more so than
Neopolitans. They were afraid of jinxing Italy's greatest source of
pride in almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
   They could be the only Italians averting their eyes on Saturday
when Prada's Luna Rossa, which means Red Moon, begins its first
race in the best-five-of-nine-race series against New Zealand's
Black Magic. Italians are fanatical about soccer and passionately
follow Formula One racing. But they have now become enamored of a
far more complicated and elitist sport.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3 million Italians watched the Louis Vuitton Cup
finals, which determined the challenger to Team New Zealand in the
America's Cup match, live earlier this month, even though the
10-hour time difference meant that races were broadcast beginning
at 2 a.m. Millions more are expected to tune in to watch Italy face
New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Even Italians whose knowledge of boating is limited to ferry
rides to Sardinia have become overnight experts on spinnakers and
bowlines, debating technique and wind factors in elevators, cafes
and business meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is national pride, sweetened by the satisfaction of
watching Italy beat American efficiency and technology. Even if
Italy ultimately loses to New Zealand, that victory will remain.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Italians are mostly known for being creative, for making
things that are good-looking,'' said Domenico Minchilli, an
architect who watched the qualifying races. ``This is a case where
Italian fashion was able to put together the financing and
technical effort to win one of the most competitive international
sporting events, and that is a different image.''
</P>
<P>
   Minchilli confessed he could not watch the last two races, when
Prada first rallied and then won the ninth and deciding race
against America One. ``The anxiety level was too high.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying for the America's Cup, an event that has never been
done by a European sailboat, certainly provided the Milan fashion
house Prada with untold millions in free advertising as well as a
burst of souvenir sales. Prada's chief executive, Patrizio
Bertelli, the husband of the designer Miuccia Prada, is an amateur
sailor who sponsored and financed Luna Rossa to the tune of an
estimated $50 million. Bertelli rejected other commercial sponsors,
insisting that only the Prada logo appear on Luna Rossa's sails.
</P>
<P>
   The morning after Luna Rossa won, fans mobbed the Prada store in
Rome, eager to bask in victory and buy luxury mementos.
</P>
<P>
   Sailing is an elitist pastime here, and so is fashion.
Predictably, Italian newspapers have been avidly chronicling how
Italian celebrities, fashion designers and starlets have been
following the races, focusing in particular on Gianni Agnelli, 78,
the retired chairman of Fiat, who is a yacht-racing enthusiast and
who spoke almost daily by telephone to the crew of Luna Rossa.
</P>
<P>
   Crew members, moreover, have become overnight celebrities, with
newspapers and television shows pouring over their sailing
credentials and also their personalities, girlfriends and favorite
hobbies. Public fascination is particularly acute in the case of De
Angelis, 40, who though Neopolitan by birth, is so reserved and
taciturn, Italian newspapers refer to him as the ``the
Englishman,'' and even ``the German.''
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to find a humanizing tidbit, the news magazine
Panorama, hunted down De Angelis' mother, Linda, who confided that
her son loses his legendary cool when confronted with ``struffoli''
a sugary, deep-fried Neopolitan pastry.
</P>
<P>
   Italy has experienced yacht racing mania before. In 1992, Il
Moro de Venezia, or the Moor of Venice, a sailboat financed by the
industrialist Raul Gardini, became the first European sailboat in
decades to qualify for the America's Cup and challenge,
unsuccessfully, the U.S. defender. That morale triumph was
blemished a few months later, when Gardini, the head of
Feruzzi-Montedison, an agro-chemical giant, committed suicide while
under investigation in a vast financial scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Italians have also not forgotten Azzurra, which in 1983, became
the first Italian sailboat to ever seek to qualify for the
America's Cup, reaching the challenger semifinals. Italians were so
swept up in that milestone that parents throughout the country
named baby girls Azzurra, a feminization of the color blue,
azzurro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italians root for their teams in ways that other nations can't
match,'' said Paolo Massarini, secretary general of the Costa
Smeralda yacht club, under whose flag Azzurra raced. ``I don't know
if parents will name their daughters Luna, but given their current
enthusiasm, it's very likely.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
