<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9219 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      02-16 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ISN'T RUNNING FOR OFFICE, BUT HE HAS A LOT TO SAY ABOUT THE
RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His name is not on the ballot, he reminded the
audience. He is just another voter, he said. But President Clinton
could not resist weighing in Wednesday on the first political
campaign season in decades that did not directly involve him.
</P>
<P>
   The president declared himself a supportive spouse, but not a
senior adviser, for Hillary Rodham Clinton in her bid for a Senate
seat in New York. And he said he was not concerned that his wife
was trailing in the polls against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's doing remarkably well, given the unusual nature
of the campaign and the formidable obstacles out there,'' Clinton
said at his first, formal news conference of 2000. ``And I think
now the people will begin to listen and debate, and I think she's
doing real well.''
</P>
<P>
   His role?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically doing for her what she's always done for me,''
he said. ``I'm talking to her about whatever she wants to talk
about. I'm giving her my best ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was reluctant, initially, to weigh in on the
presidential contest. ``I'm not running for office and, by and
large, I think I shouldn't comment,'' he said. ``There may be a few
exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the journalists questioning Clinton, fresh from the
campaign trail, eagerly sought out those exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this will be one of the exceptions that you'll be
willing to make,'' said Claire Shipman of NBC News, offering a
question on former Sen. Bill Bradley's attacks on the veracity of
Vice President Al Gore in the Democratic presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton bit, defending the vice president for having been
``brutally honest'' over the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was an unpopular thing to go into Kosovo, he wanted to
do it,'' Clinton said, offering other examples of Gore's candid
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was unpopular to go into Bosnia, he wanted to do it,''
Clinton said. ``When it was unpopular to stand up for freedom in
Haiti, he wanted to do it. When only 15 percent of the people
thought we ought to help Mexico, but I knew it could hurt our
economy, he was right there. And I could go on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton stopped short of criticizing Bradley for doubting
Gore's truthfulness, saying the vehement back-and-forth between the
two candidates was typical campaign heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a tough race where people fought with each
other, where they didn't have different interpretations of each
other's record and each other's positions,'' Clinton said. ``And
then once you disagree with someone's position or someone's record,
then the person will say, `I just think you're mischaracterizing
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said later that he thought Americans were too smart to
blame a candidate _ Gore _ for personal mistakes made by someone
else _ Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the implication that anybody would be held responsible
for somebody else's mistake or misconduct is just _ it's a real
insult to the American people,'' the president said. ``And they're
not going to do that. That's not in their interest, and it's not in
their nature. They're too smart and too good for that''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Clinton came across as magnanimous toward the two
Republicans seeking to replace him. He said all four major
presidential candidates _ Republicans John McCain and George W.
Bush included _ were ``people of accomplishment, people who have
certain convictions, people who have, I think, pretty clear
philosophies and records.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, brushing off a question about how often his name
has been disparaged on the campaign trail, still showed his
partisan ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of sympathy with Governor Bush and Senator
McCain,'' he said, barely able to suppress a smile. ``I mean, it's
hard for them to figure out what to run on. They can't run against
the longest economic expansion in history or the lowest crime rate
in 30 years or the lowest welfare rolls in 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``They've got a tough job, and I have a lot of
sympathy with them. And I don't want to complicate their problems
by saying any more about them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
