<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHES-POVERTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIANS ASK FOR RENEWED ATTACK ON POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned that poverty persists in America despite a prolonged
period of national prosperity, a broad group of Christian leaders
gathered in Washington Wednesday to call for an effort by churches,
businesses, labor and government to help poor people.
</P>
<P>
   The group's statement, a ``Covenant to Overcome Poverty,'' urges
religious organizations to make working on behalf of the poor a
priority. It also asks people to evaluate political policies and
candidates ``by how they impact people who are poor.''
</P>
<P>
   The document was signed by officials of evangelical and mainline
Protestant organizations, including the National Association of
Evangelicals and the National Council of Churches, as well as by
ministers of African-American churches and representatives of
several Roman Catholic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put poor people on the national agenda _ they're
not there now,'' said the Rev. Jim Wallis, a leader in Call to
Renewal, a five-year-old coalition of religious organizations that
wrote the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The statement noted that one in every five American children is
growing up in poverty but that the proportion is higher _ one in
every three _ among children of racial minorities. Wallis said the
religious leaders believed that a ``moral constituency'' was needed
to focus attention on finding ways to alleviate poverty, especially
for children's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious constituency is the churches, given how clear the
Bible is'' about an obligation to help the poor, said Wallis, who
is also editor of Sojourners, a religious magazine based in
Washington. ``When you have rising inequality and record prosperity
at the same time, it's a biblical issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement said, ``Just as some of our religious forebears
decided no longer to accept slavery or segregation, we decide to no
longer accept poverty and its disproportionate impact on people of
color.'' The document called for making alleviation of poverty ``a
bipartisan cause,'' and was issued by the signers on the steps of
the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview afterward, the Rev. Wes
Granberg-Michaelson, general secretary of the Reformed Church in
America and chairman of Call to Renewal, said that while the
various participating Christian groups might disagree on ``specific
policy positions,'' they were united in their belief that a shared
national effort on behalf of the poor was needed. He said they
agreed that poverty could be relieved neither by the churches alone
nor exclusively by government programs.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was issued after three days of Washington
meetings, involving some 500 people from religious organizations
around the country, that were organized by Call to Renewal to
discuss how local groups were trying to help the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been laying the groundwork all across the country'' with
such local efforts, Wallis said. ``And now we're building a
network'' to link the groups.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped that working against poverty would emerge as a
leading moral issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what might be happening,'' he said, ``is, you reach a
new millennium and find some leftover questions that did not get
resolved and then become the primary moral issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
