</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9236 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES     02-16 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Competition Heats Up in Fierce Race for Online Sports Supremacy 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Hey, sports fans, don't let the February doldrums get you down. You
know, this is the month after the NFL season ends, before baseball
spring training starts in earnest, before the NCAA tournament,
while the meaningless NBA and NHL seasons drag on until the real
season _ the playoffs _ start in the spring.
<P>
   But there is real competition happening right now in the sports
world.
</P>
<P>
   It's on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The battle was trench warfare even before yesterday, when
cybermogul Paul Allen bought the venerable Sporting News. Under
Times Mirror's stewardship, www.sportingnews.com was the
11th-ranked sports site, according to Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   The big three sports media companies, and their backers, are
Disney's ESPN.com, CBS' SportsLine.com and Time Warner's CNNSI.com
(a joint venture of CNN and Sports Illustrated). Other big players
are the leagues themselves, with NFL.com and NBA.com also ranking
in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   The top sports site, with almost twice the Web traffic of its
closest competitor, is AOL's Sports Channel, but that draws most of
its content from SportsLine.com.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on strong, though, is FoxSports.com, a newly revamped
offering from Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. that cracked the top 10
last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the game for one reason, and that's to win,'' said
Danny Greenberg, vice president of FoxSports.com, serving up
appropriately cliched sports metaphors. ``We were late to the game
on the Web, but we still view it as the first inning.''
</P>
<P>
   FoxSports started as a section of TVGuide.com, but now it's
getting its act together. It is taking some novel approaches that
should help it continue to gain ground on the leaders, including:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Regional sites. &LR;  Fox's cable operations include a television
network broadcasting sports in 22 regions, including the Bay Area.
Greenberg says the company has so far created 18 corresponding Web
sites, using local on-air personalities to help build the Web
presence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; _Stats.  &LR; Last month, News Corp. bought Stats Inc., the official
statistician for Major League Baseball and a company that supplies
stats for more than 80 percent of the fantasy games on the
Internet, Greenberg says. That's important, as FoxSports.com plans
to add to its fantasy offerings, among the most popular features of
any sports Web site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; _High school sports.  &LR; Fox started ranking top prep athletes last
fall and found popularity ``more incredible than I ever would have
thought,'' Greenberg says. ``On a daily basis, it outdraws the NBA
and NFL.'' With regional correspondents, Fox plans to do even more
in this arena.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; _Alternate technologies. &LR;  Fox has deals with TimeWarner's
RoadRunner service to bring proprietary services to households with
high-speed cable connections to the Internet, and it's also
investigating mobile and handheld electronics devices. In these
areas, Greenberg says, the vast reach of News Corp. will help
provide leverage and access.
</P>
<P>
   For all its advantages, though, it has some challenges ahead as
well. ESPN is probably the best-known brand in sports media today.
SportsLine.com is an agile, Internet-only company that has an early
mover edge.
</P>
<P>
   And CNNSI, well _ magazine readers know Sports Illustrated's
solution to the February sports doldrums. It's called the Swimsuit
Issue _ and that's one type of content that's proven effective on
the Internet.  &QL; 
BASEBALL DOT COM:  &QL; 
I took my 4-month-old son, Harry, to a luncheon last week on
Treasure Island, where our hosts, Fox Sports Net, the cable network
that televises Giants and A's games, tried to get the local media
excited about the forthcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Giants manager Dusty Baker and his A's counterpart, Art Howe,
predicted wonderful things for their teams in the season ahead, but
Harry didn't care about any of that. This new generation is
interested in only one thing: the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   So Harry liked hearing what Sandy Alderson, once the A's general
manager and now Major League Baseball's executive vice president of
baseball operations, had to say.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson explained how a few weeks ago, Major League Baseball
persuaded all of its teams to turn their Web operations over to the
league office. It's a striking deal because it departs from the
league's television practice, in which some teams, such as like
 &LR; the New York Yankees and Atlanta Braves, are able to stay on top
because of the money they make from their local television rights,
and small-market teams suffer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  On the Internet, though, the teams will cede their Web sites
_ which sell tickets and merchandise and provide stats, news and
even radio broadcasts _ to the league, and the league will make
sure content is uniform and revenues are shared.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Net, they saw the big picture,'' Alderson said.
``One-thirtieth of what could be created (by an aggregate
operation) is greater than what any one can create.''
</P>
<P>
   I looked at Harry to see if he was satisfied with this response.
He was asleep in his stroller.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RED HERRING, GREENBACKS: &QL; 
Is the Web eclipsing magazines? Look at the unusual case of the
Ziff-Davis investment in San Francisco's Red Herring
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff, a leading tech mag publisher, had a 10 percent stake in
the Herring, known for its magazine that focuses on high finance in
the tech world.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Herring has been on the hustings, trying
to raise beaucoup bucks to grow its online business.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ziff-Davis was undergoing a breakup. The
magazine unit was sold off, and the online component, ZDNet, will
become the company.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the Herring found a new soul mate. ZDNet not only
inherited Ziff-Davis' investment in the Herring, but it also
participated last week in the Herring's $28 million round of
funding. While Ziff-Davis publishing leaders Eric Hippeau and Tom
McGrade step off the Herring's board of directors, ZDNet Executive
Vice President Barry Briggs and Vice President Dan Farber take
their places.
</P>
<P>
   ``ZDNet raised their hand because they think we have a
tremendous dot-com opportunity,'' said Red Herring CEO Chris Alden.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SELLING THESTREET.COM: &QL; 
TheStreet.com hadn't even implemented its new strategy of making
its Web site free when word leaked out yesterday that the company
has retained investment bank Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co. to ``explore
the wide variety of strategic partnerships,'' in the words of
TheStreet CEO Thomas Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   What that usually means is: The bank is shopping the company
around.
</P>
<P>
   Who would buy it? Speculation turns first to the New York Times
Co. and News Corp., both of which have invested in TheStreet. The
Times even runs a joint Web newsroom with the upstart Web site.
Yahoo and E-Trade have also been mentioned as potential suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps TheStreet's rival MarketWatch.com, based in San
Francisco, might snap up the firm?
</P>
<P>
   No comment, says MarketWatch CEO Larry Kramer. But Kramer adds,
``It is sure great to be validated as No.1.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer praises TheStreet for its strong reporting, writing and
analysis, but says, ``They made one bad bet,'' charging for
information. ``That was not a little mistake,'' Kramer says.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer says his site garners more than 150 million page views
per month, while TheStreet reports fewer than 25 million. ``The
question becomes, if they change their model, how long is it going
to take them to get to our size?'' Kramer asks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOLAN'S UPSIDE: &QL; 
Ousted Mercury News tech gossip queen Chris Nolan's column-in-exile
will start appearing on Upside Today, the online adjunct of San
Francisco biz-tech mag Upside. Her high-tech dish will continue
appearing in the New York Post once a week, as it has for the past
couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Merc has posted a job listing on the Craig's List
Web site for someone who can write ``the juicy
heard-at-the-water-cooler tidbits and the seen-at-the-society-event
news that reflects the money and power of Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, the paper had someone like that, but it reassigned her to
Redwood City _ and now she's writing for the New York Post and
Upside.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the job listing should note: Candidates not eligible for
``friends and family'' stock deals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DOT-COM-A-RAMA: &QL; 
Tech author Po Bronson will deliver a keynote address at
Dot-com-a-Rama, an ``information fair'' staged by radio station
Alice  &LR;  &LR; 97.3 FM from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. March 4 at the San Francisco
Gift Center, 888 Brannan St. The event is free and will feature
everything from live music to panel discussions on how to get your
startup financed or promote your music on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
