<HEADER>
A9237 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NEXTCARD-NEXTCARD_SFC     02-16 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEXTCARD-NEXTCARD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXTCARD NEARS APPROVAL ON KEY PATENT 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Internet credit card issuer NextCard is expected to announce today
a patent development that the company hopes is a first step toward
gaining the exclusive right to take card applications over the Web.
<P>
   NextCard, the largest credit card company that operates only
over the Internet, said it got a notice last month from the U.S.
Patent and Trademark Office protecting certain aspects of its
online credit card application and pricing system. The office
issues such notices before it actually awards patents.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics say NextCard's likely patent only gives them narrow
protections and will almost certainly not give them a monopoly on
online credit applications.
</P>
<P>
   The government notice covered one of a series of patent
applications San Francisco's NextCard has filed connected to
selling credit cards over the Internet. Company officials said
their aim is to gain the sole right to take applications online, in
effect crippling rivals on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say we want to have the whole online application process
covered is a true statement,'' said NextCard Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Jeremy Lent.
</P>
<P>
   If NextCard's claims are successful, the result would be ``one
company dominating the channel that would be the future of the
industry,'' Lent said. Still, he admitted, it's far from certain
that NextCard's remaining patent requests will be granted.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said NextCard's larger claim is weak since patents
are only granted for inventions that aren't obvious. Competitors
could argue that using the Internet to process credit card
applications is a readily apparent use of Web technology.
</P>
<P>
   NextCard ``would have difficulty with the broad concept (of
taking applications over the Internet.) They would have to show
that it would not be obvious,'' said Neil Smith, a San Francisco
intellectual property attorney with the firm Limbach &AMP; Limbach.
</P>
<P>
   The company's patent applications are based on an emerging area
of the law extending protections that traditionally covered
inventions to business methods. Internet companies have been
particularly aggressive in using patents to cover their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Online bookseller Amazon.com, for example, won a patent last
year covering its one-click service that allows customers to store
shipping and billing data so that the information doesn't have to
be re-entered every time they make a purchase. It is suing
Barnesandnoble.com to prevent it from offering the same service.
</P>
<P>
   The NextCard patent application covered by the government notice
concerns the company's custom-tailored method for setting credit
card interest rates. Applicants who agree to transfer balances from
other card issuers are instantly offered lower rates than those
offered people who don't transfer balances.
</P>
<P>
   The practice is central to NextCard's strategy, since the
company makes more money from customers who transfer balances than
from those who start at zero. As a result, NextCard is able to
offer the best interest rates to its potentially most profitable
customers.
</P>
<P>
   NextCard had approximately 220,000 credit card accounts at the
end of 1999, up 64 percent from the year before. Providian
Financial, a leading rival, said this week that it also has 220,000
online credit card accounts, under its own name or the Aria brand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
