<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9239 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HEARST-HEARST_SFCHRON     02-16 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-HEARST_ </SLUG>
 SF CHRON  
 Reilly Seeks Revenue-Sharing Deal to Help Buy Examiner  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Clint Reilly asked Hearst Corp. officials last week to consider a
revenue-sharing deal if he purchases the San Francisco Examiner,
his lawyer said yesterday.
<P>
   Joseph Alioto, attorney for former mayoral candidate Clint
Reilly, said he and Reilly met for four hours in New York on Friday
with Hearst chief legal officer James Asher before Reilly expressed
interest in buying the afternoon Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   More details surfaced yesterday surrounding Reilly's surprise,
11th-hour expression of interest in buying the Examiner. Hearst,
based in New York, is trying to sell the afternoon paper to meet
antitrust concerns following its offer to buy The San Francisco
Chronicle in August for roughly $660 million.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly has sued Hearst to stop it from buying The Chronicle and
closing the Examiner. The two papers maintain separate editorial
staffs but share equally printing expenses and advertising revenues
under a joint operating agreement scheduled to expire in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said Reilly's meeting with Asher covered ``all the topics
we're interested in,'' including an agreement with some aspects of
the current JOA agreement to make the Examiner more attractive and
possibly a revision of the current 50-50 profit split to reflect
the difference in circulation between the two papers.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst had no comment on Alioto's statements.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle's daily circulation is 456,742 and the Examiner's
is 107,129. The two papers produce a combined Sunday edition.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto also suggested his client is working alone in seeking to
purchase the Examiner and is not, as some have speculated, part of
a consortium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always done everything on his own, without any help,''
Alioto said. ``There's no difference here.''
</P>
<P>
   Alioto declined to discuss Reilly's offer. Reilly is out of town
for two weeks. Hearst has not said when it will make a decision on
the Examiner's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Fang, owner of the San Francisco Independent and the other
rumored bidder, did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   But Oakland Tribune Publisher Scott McKibben, who said his boss
Dean Singleton still has no interest in purchasing the Examiner,
said Fang would have a good chance of making the Examiner
profitable _ especially if Hearst threw in some profit-sharing
arrangement to get the new owner started.
</P>
<P>
   McKibben suggested Fang could switch the Examiner to a morning
newspaper, combine its circulation with the Independent's and offer
advertisers a way to reach every household in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new owner, McKibben said the Examiner would need to cut
its editorial staff to about 125 people (from about 225 now), and
add about 175 sales, production, printing and delivery people.
</P>
<P>
   David Cole, a newspaper industry consultant in San Francisco,
said other than Reilly and Fang, the only other potential bidders
are probably real estate developers with an eye on the Examiner's
Fifth Street offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no buzz about any private or public newspaper chain
being interested,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle staff writer David Lazarus contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
