<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9240 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GOODHOME-GOODHOME_SFC     02-16 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODHOME-GOODHOME </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 GoodHome Spruces Up With FurnitureFind.com  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
For the second time in five months, online furniture seller
GoodHome.com is gobbling up a rival.
<P>
   The San Rafael company will announce today that it is merging
with FurnitureFind.com, a Michigan e-tailer of sofas, lamps, beds
and other home goods, in a deal worth about $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   The combined 230-employee firm will operate under the GoodHome
name and the headquarters will stay in San Rafael. FurnitureFind
will remain a stand-alone site _ at least for the foreseeable
forseeable  &LR; future.
</P>
<P>
   GoodHome, a privately held venture backed by publishing giant
Hearst and toymaker Mattel, launched in September. But in a
pre-emptive strike to eliminate some competition in the burgeoning
online furniture market, it merged with Virginia's nHabit.com
before either site was up and running.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly part of our strategy'' to merge with similar
companies, said GoodHome chief executive Doug Mack. ``Our sense is
that you have to move fast. And in this case, we saw an attractive
company, with deep manufacturing relationships, which would take
several years to develop on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   With the nHabit merger, GoodHome obtained Roger Horchow _ now
the company's chairman _ known for masterminding the merchandise
for the upscale Horchow Collection (now a unit of the Neiman Marcus
Group).
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be a good match,'' said Jeff Quinn, analyst at
Gomez Advisors, a Massachusetts Internet research firm. ``GoodHome
has positioned itself as providing advice on decorating and
grouping products to help people design rooms. FurnitureFind has a
great relationships with manufacturers and an abundance of
products. They've opened up the best of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   For the fledgling GoodHome, FurnitureFind also adds needed
experience. The 4-year-old company, which grew out of an online
brochure for a 48-year-old family business, is practically ancient
in the cyberselling arena.
</P>
<P>
   While the move may help GoodHome grab a bigger piece of the
estimated $954 million online furnishings market this year, Quinn
Gomez  &LR; said GoodHome still faces intense competition.
</P>
<P>
   Living.com of Austin, Texas, has announced a $145 million deal
to promote its products on e-tailing behemoth Amazon.com, and
Furniture.com of Framingham, Mass., recently filed documents with
the Securities and Exchange Commission to offer its shares to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   That's the same public that has yet to embrace the industry
wholeheartedly, despite Gomez's projection that online furnishings
sales will reach $13.6 billion by 2004, compared with to  &LR; about
$423 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Point-and-click furniture purveyors are doing well, ``but no one
is hitting it out of the park,'' Quinn said. ``That has a lot to do
with people getting more comfortable spending large amounts of
money online. They'll spend $20 on a book or a CD, but they're not
as comfortable with furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
