A9243 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-JARRETT-TEX     02-16 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINSTON CUP TEAMS SEARCHING FOR SPEED TO CATCH DALE JARRETT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ With almost alarming ease, Dale Jarrett
has won everything worthy of a checkered flag during Speed Weeks at
the Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Pole. Bud Shootout Qualifier. Bud Shootout. In every
instance it was Jarrett, all day long. Today, however, Jarrett
could deliver the biggest psychological blow seen here in a decade
during the first Gatorade Twin 125-mile qualifying race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win ... and try to keep Earnhardt from winning 11 in
a row,'' said Jarrett, referring to Dale Earnhardt's record-setting
10-race winning streak in the Twin 125s. ``I think every one of us,
as much as we enjoy Earnhardt, we're all out to end that streak.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's two 50-lap sprints around the high-banked, 2.5-mile
trioval will fill positions 3-30 in what will be a 43-car field for
the NASCAR Winston Cup season-opening Daytona 500 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett and Earnhardt _ otherwise billed as ``The Dale and Dale
Show'' _ inexorably have been linked at Daytona. Jarrett's Daytona
500 victories in 1993 and 1996 came at the expense of runner-up
Earnhardt, who did not win his first Daytona 500 until 1998. After
six days of tweaking the aerodynamically challenged 2000 Chevrolet
Monte Carlo, Earnhardt admittedly is not the favorite today, in an
all-star field of 28 that also includes Bill Elliott, Mark Martin,
Rusty Wallace, Jeff Gordon, Bobby Labonte and Terry Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   All chasing Jarrett, perhaps all day long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about the IROC race, is that Jarrett won't be
driving that damned \RNo.\S 88 car,'' said Earnhardt, the reigning
champion of the International Race of Champions series that begins
here tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jarrett has locks on the \RCup\S show right now,'' said
Earnhardt, who has won a record 33 races in all types of stock cars
at Daytona, but who will start ninth in today's Twin 125. ``We'll
see if we can stink that up on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from dismissing today's exercise, Jarrett said he is
``pretty close'' to sorting out his new car for race day. And so,
he insisted, are seven-time series champion Earnhardt and the usual
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to give up, no matter what we do,'' said
Jarrett, driver of the No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit
Taurus. ``It would certainly be a boost if we could go out there
\Rand dominate\S, especially in the race we have. Not to take away
from the group in the second race, but there's a lot of cars I see
in the first one that I know if I can beat them on Sunday, that
we'll have a good chance of winning the Daytona 500. So, it's an
important race for us. We need to see what our car's going to do
around these fast race cars, and what we can do in the draft, and
what our car will do for 50 laps on tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a fast race car. But handling's going to be the key
here, and we're struggling a little bit with the handling.''
</P>
<P>
   Based upon his pole-winning speed of 191.091 mph and his runaway
dash in the Bud Shootout, that looms as an ominous warning for
anyone attempting to stink up Jarrett's show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody comes here excited to start a new season,'' said
Jarrett, who is beginning his sixth year of driving for car owner
Robert Yates and fifth of working with crew chief Todd Parrott.
``You have to have that kind of killer instinct when you come here
because everybody is here with their very best equipment. If you're
struggling, it's hard to find \Rthe answer\S throughout the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all championship teams, Jarrett and Parrott have reloaded
in a bid to repeat the consistency that carried them to their first
championship. Specifically, Yates added five members of three-time
Cup champion Jeff Gordon's ``Rainbow Warriors'' pit crew, and their
precision work in both of Sunday's races keyed what turned out to
be runaway victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Daytona, obviously, Dale's got to drive a smart race and
try to stay out of trouble,'' said Parrott, who like Jarrett is a
second-generation NASCAR star. ``And the pit crew's got to try to
keep him up front. We didn't start out last year very good. We
started out upside down on our roof, but bounced back pretty good
from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett scored his only Did Not Finish in the 1999 Daytona 500,
when he was eliminated in a grinding 12-car wreck. Thirty-three
races later, however, that result was little more than a crumpled
footnote to a feel-good championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you win a championship, that carries over a lot of
confidence,'' said Jarrett, 43. ``I think we wanted to make sure we
didn't have any letdowns. We want to make sure we continue to work
hard. It's a hard pace to keep up, but the guys that want to win do
it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
