r e BC-FILM-PITCH-BLACK-REVI     02-16 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PITCH-BLACK-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PITCH BLACK' IS A BIT DIM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Down-on-their-luck space humans crash-land on a desert planet
populated by strange, dangerous things.
</P>
<P>
   You've seen it before. ``Pitch Black'' doesn't do it
particularly worse or better than the median ``Alien''-attrition
norm.
</P>
<P>
   Radha Mitchell (``High Art'') is the pilot, Fry, who loses most
of the ship and its sleeping passengers in the accident. She feels
guilty for the rest of the movie, especially about almost
jettisoning the pod containing the few survivors in order to save
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Except for bounty hunter Johns (Cole Hauser) and his violent
captive Riddick (Vin Diesel), the castaways are essentially defined
by their expendability. Keith David's Imam and a few kids are
presented as devout Muslims _ for no compelling reason other than
they make good vehicles for questioning God's mercy in a horror
film.
</P>
<P>
   An abandoned mining station is found where there's an old ship
that may be used for rescue. They also find nasty things with
wings, tentacles and very active teeth lurking underground. But the
creatures aren't too urgent of a threat, since they're allergic to
light, and the planet fortunately revolves around three suns (an
astronomical phenomenon that's never explained).
</P>
<P>
   Things get edgy when Riddick escapes his bonds. But that's
nothing compared to what happens when the Saharan spaceball enters
an unanticipated total eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   You never get a good, complete look at any of the monsters, but
to compensate for that there seem to be many of them. Director
David Twohy, who co-wrote ``The Fugitive,'' overexposes the
blistering daytime footage and shoots the night stuff, well, dark.
In this way, the movie is rudimentarily cinematic.
</P>
<P>
   Acting doesn't count so much as the illusion of endurance in a
project like this. Whatever allotted time they have before being
violently yanked off the screen, the actors endure. Fry and the
not-thoroughly-evil Riddick have redemption issues and a certain
animal attraction to contend with as well, so Mitchell and Diesel
get a little extra work.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it's scary and some of it isn't. There is gore, but
you've seen worse.
</P>
<P>
   You won't waste your time watching ``Pitch Black.'' But there
are better things to do. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Pitch Black'' (R; violence, language, drug use,
children in jeopardy). &QL; 
The stars: Vin Diesel, Radha Mitchell, Cole Hauser, Keith David. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by David Twohy. Written by Twohy and
Jim and Ken Whaet. Produced by Tom Engelman. Released by USA
Films. &QL; 
Running time: 1 hour, 47 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
