<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9253 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-NOT-ONE-LESS-REV     02-16 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NOT-ONE-LESS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOT ONE LESS' EMBRACES HUMAN SPIRIT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A sweet and winning tale of an innocent girl's fierce
determination, ``Not One Less'' finds Chinese director Zhang Yimou
embracing the very same themes he did eight years ago in ``The
Story of Qiu Ju.'' Only here, Yimou has cast the film entirely with
non-professionals, with all participants roughly playing the same
roles they have in life. The gambit suits the story's simplicity,
giving ``Not One Less'' a freshness that is as absorbing as it is
appealing. This is a very special movie.
</P>
<P>
   The film tells the story of 13-year-old Wei Minzhi (Wei Minzhi;
the characters in the film have the same names as the actors), who
comes to work as a substitute teacher at a remote mountain primary
school. The school's teacher, Gao, has to leave for a month to care
for his ailing mother. Even though Wei Minzhi is just a bit older
than many of her students, she is left in charge because no one
else is willing to go to such a remote destination.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher Gao admonishes Wei Minzhi to keep the remaining students
in class. He wants to return and find ``not one less'' than the
current enrollment number. This is easier said than done. For one
the thing, the crumbling school's only resource is chalk _ and the
teacher has only enough for one stick a day. More significant, many
of the school's students come from poor families who are heavily in
debt. These children are often sent to find work in the city in
order to help their families meet their obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Wei Minzhi herself doesn't appear up to the task of
teaching. Her authority is less than commanding and she seems
largely content to write the lesson on the board and then guard the
door so none of the students can escape. When the children ask her
to do something, she replies, ``There's nothing I can do.'' She
feels that overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   However, when one of her students, the likable troublemaker
Zhang Huike, is forced to go to the city to find work, we find out
just how stubborn Wei Minzhi can be. It's in this discovery that
the film achieves a moving power that is made all the more poetic
by the simple, naturalistic way Yimou has shot the movie.
</P>
<P>
   In its mood and themes, ``Not One Less'' bears a striking
resemblance to Yimou's 1992 film, ``The Story of Qui Ju,'' which
starred Gong Li as a determined innocent who travels to the city to
seek justice for her husband. Both movies are full of sincere
emotions, unfeeling bureaucrats and heart-rending humanity. The
only false note in ``Not One Less'' comes in its ending, which is a
tad too upbeat. But then, Yimou clearly wants to believe his
country's cycle of rural poverty can be broken and you can't
begrudge him his hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Yimou leavens the drama with plenty of sweet humor, particularly
in the first hour when Wei Minzhi settles into her situation and
rather inadvertently becomes a good teacher. The decision to cast
the film by finding people to play characters like themselves leads
to several interesting performances, particularly from the young
students. Every scene in the classroom rings true. And when the
action shifts to the city, Yimou ups the ante by shooting scenes on
the sly, apparently without the participants knowing they're being
filmed.
</P>
<P>
   As for Wei Minzhi, she's a tremendous discovery, a highly
affecting young woman who provides Yimou with a poignant heroine
fully capable of conveying the stirring humanity that runs through
his work. ``Not One Less'' continues that masterful vision. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Not One Less'' (G). &QL; 
The stars: Wei Minzhi, Zhang Huike. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Zhang Yimou. Screenplay by Shi
Xiansheng. Released by Sony Pictures Classics. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 46 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0472 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9254 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-NINE-YARDS-REVIE     02-16 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NINE-YARDS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIS, PEET CARRY IT `THE WHOLE NINE YARDS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sympathetic mobster comedy trend reaches a thematic
peak/moral nadir with ``The Whole Nine Yards,'' a film in which the
best people are the most ruthless killers and those who like and
abet them.
</P>
<P>
   The outlandish angle is a step beyond that of last year's
``Analyze This,'' a film this one otherwise wishes to emulate in
every way. ``Nine Yards'' isn't as funny, but after a slow start it
develops into its own kind of farcical good time. And its extreme
nature actually adds to the laughs _ what you're expected to buy
into here is often so dark, the only honest response to it is in
gasping chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all of this presumes that your sense of humor is not
connected to your conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Some very good comic performances, especially from the actors
you least expect to be that way, add to the film's overall ambience
of can-you-believe-it? hilarity. Bruce Willis, for example, has
been playing action heroes or bland leading men for so long that
he's made us forget what great timing and amusing attitude he
regularly exhibited on TV's ``Moonlighting.'' It's back here in
every insinuating line-reading, only this time with an
appropriately sardonic, life-and-death charge instead of mere,
leering suggestiveness. Willis hasn't looked like he's had this
much fun since ``Pulp Fiction'' _ which says more than it's
probably healthy to contemplate about what turns his acting juices
on.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's sneaky Amanda Peet, a young actress on the WB's
``Jack and Jill'' romantic angst series, who starts out in a glibly
pretty throwaway part, but is really ``Nine Yards''' comedy stealth
bomb, a time-released booby trap of escalating character
contradictions. When she and Willis start sparking _ they're each
infatuated with the other's professional killing skills _ they give
the whole ``Prizzi's Honor'' premise a new and ticklesome,
screwball spin.
</P>
<P>
   Willis' Jimmy ``The Tulip'' Tudeski is a Chicago hit man turned
informant who, eschewing the witness protection program, sets up an
easily traceable, seemingly suicidal new life in a Montreal suburb.
His neighbor is an unhappy American dentist, Nicholas ``Oz''
Oseransky (``Friends''' Matthew Perry), who's married to a French
Canadian shrew (Rosanna Arquette with a wandering accent and
abjectly lost comic judgment).
</P>
<P>
   Oz quickly recognizes The Tulip for who he is, but Jimmy insists
on becoming pals with the jumpy dentist. Plot contrivances get Oz
in up past his neck with a vengeful mob boss (Kevin Pollak), a
gigantic underworld enforcer (``The Green Mile's'' Michael Clarke
Duncan) and Jimmy's endangered wife (``Species''' Natasha
Henstridge). Just about everybody Oz encounters is double-crossing
someone else, and they all want somebody or other _ oftentimes him
_ dead.
</P>
<P>
   Laugh riot, huh? Amazingly, it often is, thanks in great part to
director Jonathan Lynn's patient setup of good slow-fused gags
(Mitchell Kapner is credited with the script) and a tonal control
of the potentially offensive material that's nothing short of
astonishing. And while Perry isn't the funniest person in the film
_ he essentially adds pratfalls and mortal fear to your basic
Chandler Bing _ he never fails to provide the antic energy that
keeps the convoluted story skipping along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Whole Nine Yards'' is easily Lynn's best movie since ``My
Cousin Vinny,'' and, like that one, it triumphs on a combination of
careful craftsmanship, deft casting and well-sprung surprises. And
as he did with the earlier film's cliched, fish-out-of-water
dynamics, Lynn once again finds a way to breathe freshness into a
concept that's quite overused in this age of ``Sopranos'' worship.
</P>
<P>
   So, enjoy. And see you afterward in line at the confessional. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``The Whole Nine Yards'' (R; violence, nudity, sex,
language). &QL; 
The stars: Matthew Perry, Bruce Willis, Michael Clarke Duncan,
Natasha Henstridge, Amanda Peet, Rosanna Arquette. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Jonathan Lynn. Written by Mitchell
Kapner. Produced by David Willis and Allan Kaufman. Released by
Warner Bros. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 45 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9255 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-HANGING-UP-REVIE     02-16 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HANGING-UP-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HANGING UP' RINGS IN A SHRILL SORT OF WAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The unsurprising news that families can drive you nuts is
unnecessarily emphasized by the shrill clan depicted in ``Hanging
Up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mozells _ three adult sisters and their rascally, dying dad
_ are supposed to be the lovable-despite-their-foibles types that
fans of comic tearjerkers love to laugh and cry with. But this
bunch rarely gets far enough beyond the foibles stage to make you
want to spend time with them, let alone share their life issues.
Which, annoyingly, doesn't prevent them in the least from
bombarding you with information about the slightest variation in
every single, trite feeling that darts through their irritated
nervous systems.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of telephones in this film. They're used to frustrate more
than facilitate communication, to keep unpleasantness at a distance
and to torture the central protagonist, Meg Ryan as middle sister
Eve. And they are, of course, indications that this is an Ephron
sisters production (Delia, whose novel the film is based upon,
co-scripted with Nora), serving the same
ain't-it-hard-to-make-real-connections-in-this-modern-world
function as computers in ``You've Got Mail'' and talk radio in
``Sleepless in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nora Ephron declined to direct this one, which is very
loosely based on her own crazy-making father's relationship with
his grown girls. That task fell to Diane Keaton, who plays eldest
daughter Georgia and has made one interesting film about an
interesting family, ``Unstrung Heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   That record stands at one.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is the overachieving egomaniac, a superstar journalist
with her own self-named glamour magazine. The baby, Maddy (Lisa
Kudrow), is a flake who's just recently found minor success as a
soap opera actress after innumerable false career starts.
</P>
<P>
   And Eve is the martyr, although she'll tell you she's the
responsible nurturer who's holding the family together. She has a
young son and a nice but often away-on-business husband (Adam
Arkin) and runs a high-end party-planning business. As if that
didn't keep her hopping, when ex-screenwriter father Lou (Walter
Matthau) takes a turn toward catastrophic illness and delirium, he
and the other girls just naturally assume that it's Eve's job to
attend to him ... which, for the most part, means taking his
dreaded calls.
</P>
<P>
   It's all pretty innocuous stuff, made obnoxious by how much
dramatic weight and off-the-mark comic observation is put on it.
</P>
<P>
   There are repeated flashbacks to earlier incidents involving
trash-talking, sometimes mean-drunk, more often mildly misbehaving
pops, all part of Eve's effort to figure out why she loves the old
problem (though the film seems to think otherwise, we're left
presuming she's just a wimp). When any configuration of sisters is
on screen, it's usually for a shouting match or, if they're not in
the mood for recrimination, one of those bonding movie food fights
that no woman who cares the least about her clothes would ever
enjoy. At one point, an Iranian surrogate mom figure (Ann
Bortolotti) is brought in to provide much-needed aphorisms,
moral-supporting hugs and make an Ayatollah joke.
</P>
<P>
   The Mozells' real mother, played by Cloris Leachman in one
flashback scene, just up and abandoned her family when the girls
were little. She says that was because she just wasn't cut out to
do the parenting thing (it took her three tries to realize this?),
and we're of course supposed to despise her blithe lack of
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   But more than a few viewers, I suspect, will be sympathetic to
the old gal. At least she has enough sensitivity to politely lie
about what really drove her away from this wearying,
overdramatizing brood. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``Hanging Up'' (PG-13; language, sex). &QL; 
The stars: Meg Ryan, Diane Keaton, Lisa Kudrow, Walter Matthau,
Adam Arkin. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Diane Keaton. Written by Delia and
Nora Ephron, based on Delia's novel. Produced by Laurence Mark and
Nora Ephron. Released by Columbia Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 32 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
