<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9256 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-BOILER-ROOM-REVI     02-16 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOILER-ROOM-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOILER ROOM' ECHOES `WALL STREET,' `GLENGARRY GLEN ROSS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Boiler Room,'' a high-energy look at a group of Generation-X
stock swindlers, is a modestly entertaining film that's mostly
derivative of other, better movies like ``Wall Street'' and
``Glengarry Glen Ross.'' But at least first-time writer-director
Ben Younger is smart enough to acknowledge those sources, while
simultaneously bidding to become part of the greed canon.
</P>
<P>
   A good night's entertainment for ``Boiler Room's'' young men is
to sit around a sparsely appointed mansion (who needs furniture
when you're always at the office?) and watch ``Wall Street'' on
video, seeing who can do the best Michael Douglas impersonation.
The company's chief recruiter, Ben Affleck, (effectively echoing
Alec Baldwin's role in ``Glengarry Glen Ross'') has seemingly
memorized David Mamet's ``Glengarry'' script. His spiel is filled
with Mamet lingo. (``ABC,'' he instructs, as in ``always be
closing.'')
</P>
<P>
   The film's boiler room is a bomb-shelter-like chamber located
far away from Wall Street in the boonies of Long Island. There,
scores of 20-something men with self-esteem issues ply their trade,
manically calling prospective people they've never met and trying
to interest them in ``hot'' stocks. The offerings they're peddling
are worthless, but that hardly matters. These guys appeal to our
society's greed and desire to make a fast buck. Nobody wants to
watch the parade pass them by.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the film's watchful young protagonist, Seth (Giovanni
Ribisi), doesn't. That would mean he'd have to find a real job. And
after making some fast money running a casino out of his apartment,
Seth is looking for bigger stakes and larger scores. He's also
looking for the cloak of respectability because what he wants most
is the respect and love of his father (Ron Rifkin), a judge who has
never been generous with his approval. (With a son like Seth, it's
hard to blame him.)
</P>
<P>
   Seth signs up with the bogus brokerage firm J.T. Marlin, where
he's promised that he'll make his first million within three years.
This is where ``Boiler Room'' works best, right in the
testosterone-fueled trenches, with Seth and his associates
energetically working the phones in search of the latest ``whale''
(a customer with plenty of cash).
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Younger, who says he was once recruited as a
boiler room trainee, stages these scenes with plenty of energy and
a keen eye for detail. Unfortunately, his storytelling skills don't
extend to the movie's interpersonal dramas. Here, ``Boiler Room''
lapses into tired theatrics, its father-son soap opera a pale
imitation of Charlie Sheen's situation in ``Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Ribisi shows considerable intelligence and craft, as long as the
story stays focused on the money. A subplot involving a romance
with the beautiful office secretary (Nia Long) is unnecessary,
apart from the hope it will give to short, nebbishy twerps in the
audience. Supporting cast standouts include Affleck in the showy
role and Vin Diesel, Ribisi's ``Saving Private Ryan'' co-star, as a
boiler room star who doesn't want to consider the moral
implications of his profession.
</P>
<P>
   Given the movie's conventional last act (and its aping of ``Wall
Street''), moral comeuppance isn't so much possible as it is
required. Yet you get the feeling Younger really likes these guys
and hopes that someday, somewhere, amoral men will sit around and
watch his movie, quoting its best lines. Best guess: They'll stick
to his source material. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``Boiler Room'' (R; language). &QL; 
The stars: Giovanni Ribisi, Vin Diesel, Nia Long, Nicky Katt, Scott
Caan, Ron Rifkin, Ben Affleck. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Ben Younger. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 59 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
