</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNING STREET TALKS FAIL TO PATCH UP NORTHERN IRELAND RIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subbing throughout for additional quotes by Adams, Blair and
others; new 2nd graf provides better background and context; story
grows by about 200 words)  
 (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Demands by the Sinn Fein president, Gerry Adams, that
Britain restore the suspended Northern Ireland government were met
with counterdemands Wednesday from other participants in a crisis
session at 10 Downing St. that the Irish Republican Army first
return to disarmament talks.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour meeting of Roman Catholic and Protestant
politicians with Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish
counterpart, Bertie Ahern, adjourned still deeply divided over the
weapons issue, which has repeatedly halted progress in putting the
elements of the April 1998 peace agreement into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Adams, whose party is the political wing of the IRA,
said: ``We have no room at all to do anything in this situation.
The only breakthrough which can start to make politics work is a
return to the institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, however, that he had not persuaded Britain to
move on reviving those governmental institutions. ``There appears
to me anyway to be no sign that the British government is prepared
to do that,'' he said grimly outside the British prime minister's
official residence.
</P>
<P>
   Under fire for the IRA's refusal to make any move on weapons,
Adams testily complained that his party was being unfairly used as
a scapegoat. ``I don't think we can play a useful role on the arms
issue when all we are met with is rejections and rebuttals,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also ruled out participating in a formal review of the
stalled peace negotiations, saying the British had acted illegally
in shutting down the Belfast administration last Friday. ``There
cannot be a review based on unilateral suspension,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, with Ahern by his side, said, ``Today wasn't the day we
were going to do anything but discuss the parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Blair's insistence that the time had come
for a start to IRA disarmament gained valuable support from remarks
made in Dublin by Ahern.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that it was unacceptable for republicans to continue to
take part in the Northern Ireland government while the IRA
stockpiles remained intact, Ahern told members of the Irish
parliament: ``Whether people like it or not, it is not compatible,
beyond a short transitional period, to have that democratic mandate
with armed backing. I cannot agree to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The republican movement, largely Catholic, favors closer links
with Ireland and is unaccustomed to being lectured to by an Irish
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern said the Irish and British governments could put the peace
settlement back on track rapidly with cooperation, but, he added,
``I can't put it back if only one part goes back on the track _ it
has to be all the parts.''
</P>
<P>
   His words may go some way toward closing a rift that had
developed between Britain and Ireland, the two sponsors of the
Ulster peace talks, over the British action suspending the
government in Belfast. Britain took the action, it said, because
the IRA had failed to begin disarming even after members of Sinn
Fein had been admitted to their ministerial positions in the
Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening while speaking to the Irish Parliament, Mr.
Ahern had been surprised by an announcement by the IRA that it was
ending its contact with weapons mediators and withdrawing from
negotiating fresh proposals it had made to consider disarming for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy leader of the moderate Catholic Social Democratic and
Labor Party, Seamus Mallon, who like Ahern had been opposed to the
suspension, joined in the criticism of the IRA on Wednesday for
pulling out of the consultations with the disarmament commission.
He said he found it incredible that the clandestine organization
had made its announcement at a time when Ahern was before his own
legislators in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only have they made a studied insult to Bertie Ahern, but
to the entire political process in Ireland as a whole and to the
Irish people,'' he said. The IRA, he said, was ``prepared to use
and abuse anybody in their own interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRA action was a dismaying development for supporters of the
peace plan who had been holding meetings throughout recent days
hoping that the new IRA arms initiative would be a basis for
restoring the home rule government. The IRA had offered late Friday
to consider putting its arms ``beyond use'' and suggested that it
would consider a timetable that would see full disarmament by the
May date fixed in the peace agreement. Then on Tuesday it took
those words off the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's meeting was scheduled to find a way to keep the
staggering peace process on its feet, and the consensus that
emerged was that the vexing issue of paramilitary disarmament had
to be confronted before any progress could be made on restarting
the mothballed Northern Ireland government. ``There is this issue
we have to resolve,'' Blair said at a news conference after the
session. ``We are going to knuckle down and get it resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams presented another proposal in which the government would
have to be restored before the issue of disarmament could be taken
up, but he had no takers outside his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at Downing Street, his chief rival, the Ulster Unionist
leader David Trimble, said, ``The onus is fairly and squarely on
the republican movement to put forward proposals as to how this is
going to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
