<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-AUTO-MERGERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER SPECULATION ABOUNDS IN EUROPEAN AUTOMOBILE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (UPDATES figures in 10th graf) 
 (rk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Europe's automobile industry has gone into
overdrive _ at least when it comes to merger speculation.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive day, shares of PSA Peugeot Citroen
jumped Wednesday on rumors that it was in talks with
DaimlerChrysler AG Those rumors followed persistent speculation
about Daimler seeking to acquire the automobile business of Fiat
SPA.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, British and German newspapers speculated that
Volkswagen AG might take over Rover Cars, the ailing British
subsidiary of BMW AG.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts believe that more car mergers are inevitable,
because manufacturers are under pressure to keep prices down and
yet roll out new models faster than ever.
</P>
<P>
   That said, most of the merger predictions thus far have been
wrong. One reason is that the most desirable or at least needy car
companies are still controlled by their founding families _ the
Peugeots of France, the Agnellis of Italy and the Quandts of
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those families has rejected the idea of selling out.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Peugeot once again denied it is in merger talks,
following rumors on Tuesday that DaimlerChrysler had offered 35
shares of its own stock and 10 euros for every 10 shares of
Peugeot.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Martin Folz, Peugeot's president, said in Paris Wednesday
that the company wanted to remain independent and had the ability
to do so. ``We want neither a merger nor an acquisition,'' Folz
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger question is, why would DaimlerChrysler want to
pursue it?
</P>
<P>
   Each new rumor about a big Daimler acquisition has sent its
share price down. Daimler's stock has declined 17 percent this
year, while the DAX index of leading German stocks has climbed
about 7.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Daimler's decline reflects investor unhappiness about
possible takeovers of small-car makers like Fiat or Peugeot.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a capital markets point of view, we would rather see the
company say they are not going to do anything in small cars and
will return free cash flow to shareholders,'' said Christian
Breitsprecher, an analyst at Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's chairman, Juergen E. Schrempp, has left no
doubt that he badly wants to build up his small-car business _ the
one area that neither Mercedes Benz nor Chrysler have any real
strength.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts are overwhelmingly unhappy about a big push into
small cars. For one thing, the price competition in that segment is
brutal and the profit margins are much lower than for Mercedes
luxury cars or Chrysler's light trucks and sport-utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the margins available in the markets served by
Fiat and Peugeot are nowhere near comparable to those of
DaimlerChrysler,'' said Andrew Blair-Smith, an analyst in London at
Commerzbank.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, analysts worry that companies like Fiat or Peugeot
will require substantial new investment and management time.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally agree that Europe's smaller and weaker car
companies are under considerable pressure. Fiat lost money through
the first nine months of 1999, though it is now experiencing an
upswing and is believed to have turned a profit in the final
quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Peugeot fared better last year, with its automobile revenue
climbing 11.5 percent to 32.6 billion euros, or about $33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But with an annual output of 2.5 million vehicles, far behind
the 4 million produced both by Volkswagen and DaimlerChrysler,
Peugeot faces the problem of trying to spread out the development
costs for new models over fewer vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, investors in Peugeot have been more than happy
about the merger speculation. Peugeot's stock jumped by 6 percent
on Tuesday and a further 1 percent Wednesday to reach 218.2 euros
per share, or $215.32.
</P>
<P>
   Peugeot and Daimler held extensive talks last fall about
collaborating on a new ``platform,'' or underlying blueprint, for
Daimler's troubled line of Smart subcompact two-seater cars. Those
talks broke off, apparently because of reservations by Daimler's
top executives, but they did not put end to Daimler's interest in a
full-scale acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor racing through Paris on Tuesday was that members of
the founding Peugeot family, who own 25.1 percent of the stock and
control 37.4 percent of the voting rights, had become more
receptive to a deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-ASBESTOS-SAFETY-SPI &LR;      02-16 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASBESTOS-SAFETY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL SAFETY AGENCY OPENS NATIONWIDE PROBE OF ASBESTOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH and ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After more than a decade of inaction, the Consumer
Product Safety Commission will open a nationwide investigation of
asbestos in consumer products, including attic insulation, the
agency announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The agency declined to say what other types of products it would
test.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's new initiative marks the first time since 1987
that it has checked products to see if they contain the
cancer-causing fibers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was announced two days after the Post-Intelligencer
revealed that products containing asbestos are still being sold,
and few regulations exist to protect consumers against unknowingly
being exposed.
</P>
<P>
   The P-I reported Monday that Environmental Protection Agency
investigators have begun testing products for asbestos, and that
their preliminary tests have found asbestos in some products.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's testing continued Wednesday as an agency investigator
crawled through rafters to take samples of old vermiculite
insulation in the house of a man with asbestos-related disease.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after dawn in Manchester, across Puget Sound from
Seattle, Robert Parks held a ladder as EPA investigator Keven
McDermott climbed through a 2-foot-square opening into his attic.
</P>
<P>
   Decked out from head to toe in protective coveralls, surgical
gloves on her hands, her face fully covered with a respirator,
McDermott slithered from rafter to rafter, picking her perches with
care to avoid falling through Parks' ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The beam of her flashlight swept over a scattering of empty red
and black paper bags, labeled ``Zonolite Attic Insulation.''
</P>
<P>
   The bags also carried the label ``100 percent vermiculite,''
below two smiling cartoon characters captioned ``Just pour ... and
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks, 73, squinted up to the green ceiling, trying to figure
how far the EPA investigator had progressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1970, I dumped 130 bags of that Zonolite up there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``About eight years ago, the doctor says I have asbestosis in
the one lung I have left.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks, who retired after 37 years as a mechanic for The Boeing
Co., said, ``I never could figure out where I was ever exposed to
asbestos. It must have come from up there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a bit of it up here,'' McDermott said, her voice
muffled by the filters which were supposed to protect her. She
filled clean plastic bags with the fluffy, expanded vermiculite
from several places around the darkened attic.
</P>
<P>
   She placed the samples and her gear in a large yellow ``asbestos
hazard'' bag and climbed back down the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Parks eyed the bag warily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read about the Zonolite in the paper and thought maybe
that's what happened here,'' he said, tapping his chest.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott shrugged out of the safety clothing, saying that the
EPA demands it when their staff deals with any potential
carcinogen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean that Zonolite is that dangerous,'' she
explained. ``It just means that we have to be careful until we know
exactly what's in the material and the testing we'll do over the
next few weeks will tell us that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zonolite in Parks' attic came from a company called
Vermiculite Northwest, which ran vermiculite expansion plants years
ago in Spokane and Portland. That company, along with producers of
millions of other bags of Zonolite insulation, used vermiculite
mined from 1963 to 1990 by W.R. Grace and Co. in Libby, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   EPA investigators have been in Libby since November, after the
Post-Intelligencer reported that hundreds of vermiculite miners and
their family members have died or are dying from asbestos-caused
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Peronard, EPA's coordinator of the Libby investigation, is
concerned about the potential health effects from asbestos
contamination in the vermiculite insulatin and other products which
used vermiculite.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Zonolite is all over the country, in millions of homes,
from what we're being told,'' Peronard said. ``If it's dangerous,
we need to know it. If it's not, that information is valuable also.
There's a lot of information needed on what's in this vermiculite,
and we need to start collecting it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that information is being gathered about a mile from
Parks' home, at an EPA regional laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   There, Jed Januch, a member of McDermott's investigative
response team, has his hand buried deep in a sealed,
plastic-fronted chamber. He carefully spades potting soil from a
bag into small flower pots, and dumps the vermiculite-speckled soil
from one pot to another, emulating how a gardener might work with
the material.
</P>
<P>
   At the back of the chamber, two pumps suck the air into filter
cartridges. Sophisticated analysis of the filter will tell the
investigators whether harmful levels of asbestos are contaminating
the vermiculite.
</P>
<P>
   The elaborate process will continue for days as different brands
are examined. The results will be evaluated by Dr. Mike Watson,
EPA's regional toxicologist in Seattle, and his counterparts in
other EPA offices.
</P>
<P>
   Watson acknowledges the difficulty of linking the asbestos
levels to a risk assessment. He warns that it's a complex process
that will take time.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of research on workers with long-term exposures to
asbestos, such as shipyard employees and miners, have shown that
asbestos can cause fatal diseases, including asbestosis, lung
cancer and a rare form of cancer called mesothelioma.
</P>
<P>
   The potential exposure and health risks to consumers have been
less well documented. However as early as 1972, investigators at
the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH)
reported that a one-time acute dose of asbestos may be as harmful
as the cumulative effect of lower doses over many years.
</P>
<P>
   A 1991 EPA report stated that a person installing insulation in
a home receives an eight-hour exposure, on average.
</P>
<P>
   The CPSC would not release more specific details of its new
investigation Wednesday, except to say it would include other
product categories in addition to attic insulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any (specific) information right now that people
are being exposed to asbestos fibers from household products,''
said CPSC spokesman Ken Giles. ``But we're going to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the commission finds consumer products that pose a health
hazard, it has the regulatory power to take action.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we find exposures that present a health risk, we do have
the power to require cancer hazard warning labels,'' Giles said.
The agency can also ban products, or issue recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Giles would not comment on what the agency would do if it finds
products that contain dangerous levels of asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to speculate,'' he said. ``It's premature to say
what other regulatory actions we might take.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
