<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SELIG-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS WIN BIG ONE ON ASSIST FROM SELIG
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The season hasn't even started, and the Detroit Tigers have
already registered a victory. They scored one over Commissioner Bud
Selig, and the surprising aspect of it was he let them have it. Not
a good start to the season for the commissioner. Baseball's
impartial arbitrator may be the next to hand him a loss, that one
on the John Rocker grievance.
</P>
<P>
   If the arbitrator, Shyam Das, should overturn or even reduce
Selig's 73-day suspension of Rocker for his ugly comments about all
sorts of groups, the commissioner would have the excuse that he was
unable to do anything about it. But in the Tigers' case, Selig has
been a willing accomplice. He has allowed the Tigers to blatantly
flout his directive on interviewing minority candidates for certain
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Selig failed to discipline the Tigers, but he has
also praised them for taking what some skeptics might see as a
cosmetic step designed to get them off the hook with the man whose
powers were recently enhanced so that he could fine a team $2
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard they were going to be fined,'' said one club
executive, who was clearly disappointed to learn that the Tigers
hadn't been fined. ``Some people assumed that one of the reasons
this new power was given was that he'd be able to fine clubs more
if they didn't address the inequality in hiring.''
</P>
<P>
   About six months before the Tigers hired Phil Garner as their
manager, the commissioner clearly set out his position on
interviewing minority candidates. That's right, interviewing, not
hiring. Baseball is a game that is played slowly and makes
advancement at glacial speed. Last April Selig sent a directive to
all clubs outlining the steps they were to take if they had
vacancies in any of five positions of decision-making authority,
including manager and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a club has an opening in any of these positions, the club
owner must notify me personally,'' he said in a letter to owners.
``In addition, your list of candidates must be provided to me. I
expect the list to include minority candidates whom you and your
staff have identified. I will provide assistance to you if you
cannot identify candidates on your own.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig also told the owners he would discipline clubs that did
not ``aggressively pursue equal opportunities and initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Tigers decided last October to make a managerial
change, they did not (1) notify Selig of the vacancy, (2) provide
him with a list of their candidates, (3) identify any minority
candidates or (4) seek assistance in identifying candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Then, heaping insult upon insult, the club president, John
McHale Jr., when asked about the Tigers' failure to follow the
directive, said, ``There isn't a legal obligation to adhere to any
directives from the commissioner's office.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers got away with it because they established a community
advisory board dedicated, in the words of a news release from the
commissioner's office, ``to Equal Employment Opportunities, their
Diverse Business Partners Program and their community relations
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig, in the release, called the Tigers' plan ``a very
progressive and sensitive series of programs.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised the club for recognizing the problem and addressing
it, adding, ``That, I believe, is more important than taking
disciplinary action.''
</P>
<P>
   On the telephone Wednesday, Selig said he expects the Tigers'
program to be beneficial to baseball and to the Detroit community.
``This is not just a glitzy thing,'' he said. ``They have many
announcements to come. They're going to be meaningful. The
economics of it will be good in terms of what they're spending and
what they're going to be doing. As much as I would have fined them,
they're going to spend a lot more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig talked about minority suppliers and minority banks, but
his directive talked about positions whose holders control budgets
and have the authority to make decisions in baseball operations.
The Tigers, like most teams, still have a white manager, a white
general manager, a white assistant general manager and a white
scouting director, positions specified in the directive. If members
of minority groups aren't interviewed, they can't be hired. That
was the message behind Selig's letter.
</P>
<P>
   The club executive who lamented Selig's failure to fine the
Tigers raised the postulation that the Tigers' behavior was worse
for baseball than Rocker's remarks. Rocker's comments, he reasoned,
were the act of an individual; the failure to interview and hire
members of minorities is institutional.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a hint here of a double standard at work, consider
some other issues that baseball officials have ignored. While
Rocker has been suspended for 73 days and fined $20,000, his
employer in Atlanta, Ted Turner, has made a career out of making
outrageous statements about ethnic groups and remains
undisciplined. Marge Schott should have been so widely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves also continue to encourage their fans to perform the
tomahawk chop that American Indians find offensive. The Cleveland
Indians offend the same group with their name and their Chief Wahoo
emblem. For many years they defended their use of both by
explaining that they were honoring a former player who was an
Indian. Recently, the Indians admitted that well, maybe that wasn't
quite the real story.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball doesn't necessarily have to conform suddenly to the
strictest practice of political correctness, but its officials and
teams might want to try their hand at consistency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
