u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      02-16 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: GERMAN APOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   President Johannes Rau of Germany addressed Israel's parliament,
asking forgiveness _ in German _ for ``what the Germans did''
during the Holocaust. It was the first time the German language had
been heard from the podium, causing some members to boycott the
session. Avraham Burg, the speaker, said, ``I deliberated greatly
but finally I decided that today the parliament will hear this
language because the language is not the main point, but rather the
speaker and his words.''
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: HOLOCAUST AID
</P>
<P>
   Belatedly, legislators say, Israel is joining the effort to help
heirs of Holocaust victims trace Israeli properties and bank
accounts. Colette Avital, head of a commission on assets of
Holocaust victims in British-ruled Palestine, said Israelis
``haven't managed to do here what we managed to do in other
countries, like Switzerland.'' The panel will investigate assets in
Israel owned by European Jews who did not emigrate and were killed
by the Nazis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: PULLOUT COSTS
</P>
<P>
   It will cost about $250 million to pull out of Lebanon this year
and build new defenses, Finance Minister Avraham Shochat said,
quoting army estimates. The government could finance a pullout
without exceeding its budget or receiving extra outside aid, he
said. But he cited figures of $17 billion as the amount of military
aid Israel would need to cover costs of a Golan Heights withdrawal
in the event of peace with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: 14TH CHARGED IN HIJACK
</P>
<P>
   A 14th man has been charged with hijacking the Afghan airliner
that spent last week at Stansted airport with more than 150 people
aboard. At the same time, another passenger from the plane formally
applied for political asylum, bringing the number to 75.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: FOSTER CHILD ABUSE
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a damning report exposing the systematic abuse of
650 foster children in group homes in Wales in the 1970s and '80s,
the government began a nationwide search for 28 former child-care
workers said to be involved in the abuse. All 28 still pose a risk
to children, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: AUSTRIA ENVOY REMOVED
</P>
<P>
   The government removed its ambassador to Austria, Juan Carlos
Kreckler, after a newspaper published a cable he wrote last year
characterizing Joerg Haider of the Freedom Party as a misunderstood
democrat ``who is not a neo-Nazi nor an extremist.'' Kreckler was
recalled after Haider's party helped form a governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ECOLOGICAL ACCIDENT
</P>
<P>
   A cruise ship ran aground off Quintana Roo, near Cozumel Island,
causing an oil spill and forcing 1,400 passengers and crew members
to return to Miami by air. Authorities were holding the ship,
registered in Liberia, pending a report on ecological damage. The
navy said the spill posed no risks to Caribbean coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: ANTI-CORRUPTION BILL
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a sweeping anti-corruption bill that President
Olusegun Obasanjo introduced seven months ago. The Senate version,
which provides for an independent counsel to investigate government
corruption and weakens the government's powers over an
anti-corruption commission, was passed by the House of
Representatives in December. It must now be signed by Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   NORTH KOREA: KIM'S BIRTHDAY
</P>
<P>
   North Korea marked the 58th birthday of its supreme leader, Kim
Jong Il, with gala celebrations, including sports events and
fireworks. Kim took over in 1994 after the death of his father, Kim
Il Sung, at 82. As part of the festivities, North Korean soldiers
pledged to defend the country's leader with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG: NORTH KOREA CONSULATE
</P>
<P>
   North Korea opened a consulate as part of growing efforts to
improve its ties to the outside world. Permission to open the
mission was received after China, one of North Korea's few allies,
regained Hong Kong in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: MAHATHIR HEARING
</P>
<P>
   A Malaysian court will hold a hearing Thursday on whether to
summon Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad for a confrontation with his
former deputy, Anwar Ibrahim, who is on trial for sexual
misconduct. Anwar's lawyers have called Mahathir as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: ATROCITIES
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan, said in Jakarta that
there would be no need to convene an international court for
atrocities committed in East Timor if the Indonesian government
brings those responsible to trial.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHARIF TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   A prosecution witness testified in the trial of Nawaz Sharif,
the deposed prime minister, that the nation's chief aviation
official told him that Sharif had forbidden a plane carrying the
army chief he had just fired to land in Pakistan. Prosecutors say
the flight had too little fuel to make it to another country. The
court ruled to admit the logbook showing how much fuel was left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
