<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-RUSSIA-DEBT-NYT (moved on Saturday, Feb. 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Feb. 12,
about an agreement to restructure some of Russia's debt to foreign
banks and investors referred incorrectly to the price of oil, a
major Russian export. The figure of $30 a barrel is not
unprecedented; oil rose to that price before the Persian Gulf war
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-PAASCHE-NYT (moved on Saturday, Feb. 12)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Maria Paasche sent by the New York Times News
Service on Saturday, Feb. 12, misspelled the surname of the former
German chancellor who praised her father, Gen. Kurt von
Hammerstein, for his part in a plot to kill Hitler. The chancellor
was Heinrich Bruning, not Brening.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ZAGAT-EXPANSION-NYT (moved on Sunday, Feb. 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Feb. 13,
about the sale of an equity stake in the Zagat Survey to a group of
outside investors misstated the affiliation of one investor, Nathan
Myhrvold. He is on leave from Microsoft, where he was chief
technology officer. He was not a founder of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-BROADWAY-TICKETS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Feb. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Feb. 15,
about the winning design for a new TKTS booth in Times Square
misstated the value of discount theater tickets sold annually at
the booth. It is $60 million, not $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, the article misspelled the name of
the engineering firm associated with Thomas Phifer, an architect
whose design won second prize. The firm is Ove Arup, not Ove Aup.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MUSEUMS-AND-MONEY-NYT (moved on Sunday, Feb. 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Feb. 13,
about a conference in Chicago examining the relationship between
arts and society in light of the outcry over the ``Sensation'' show
at the Brooklyn Museum reversed the initials of a University of
Chicago art professor whose program organized the conference. He is
W.J.T. Mitchell, not W.T.J.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ARMS-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Thursday, Feb. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Feb. 10,
about the Roundabout Theater Co.'s production of ``Arms and the
Man'' misidentified the role played by Kevin Kline in 1985 at
Circle in the Square. It was Bluntschli, not Sergius.
</P>
</TEXT>
