<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9279 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BANK-1STLD-WRI     02-16 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: entered Wednesday.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Appearing calm and rested, and smiling occasionally at one
another and their lawyers, Edwards and Berlin described the origins
and purpose of the money laundering operation during a court
appearance that lasted slightly more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a small, well-groomed woman who spoke with a soft
Russian accent, said she was first approached in late 1995 by
representatives of DKB, a Russian bank whose full name is
Depozitarno-Kliringovy Bank, who were interested in using the Bank
of New York's offices and technology to illegally move funds out of
Russia. During the following years, the 41 year-old Edwards said,
those activities came to include money laundering and the other
schemes to which she pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Russian banking during the 1990s has been a notoriously
freewheeling affair, with allegations of extensive involvement in
the banks by organized criminals. Edwards noted in her testimony
that DKB's Moscow employees told her in 1998 that they were afraid
to leave the bank's headquarters because ``customers with machine
guns were waiting for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The ransom money referred to in court Wednesday relates to a
1998 request by the Russian government for the FBI's help in a
kidnapping case. The ransom, it turned out, moved through a Benex
account at the Bank of New York on its way to Russian organized
crime figures, prompting the bureau to open its own inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bank of New York earned relatively small profits
from its business in Russia, its aggressive pursuit of clients
there held out the promise of potentially lucrative future deals.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin, 45, testified that Benex, Becs and Lowland all had
accounts at the Bank of New York that he had opened on behalf of
his overseers in Moscow. He said that the companies were staffed by
DKB employees and that Edwards helped install Bank of New York
computer software in the Forest Hills, Queens, office of a Benex
affiliate to allow funds to be moved electronically.
</P>
<P>
   The couple said that DKB representatives told them in fall 1998
that they had acquired control of another bank, Commercial Flamingo
Bank, and wanted a new company created to move funds from that bank
through the Bank of New York. Berlin opened Lowland in Jersey City,
N.J., for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   According to a series of confidential financial audits, a Moscow
bank controlled by Alexander Smolensky, SBS-Agro, owned sizable
stakes in both Sobinbank and Flamingo Bank.
</P>
<P>
   One of the audits, conducted in 1997 by the accounting firm
Arthur Andersen &AMP; Co., with the cooperation of SBS-Agro's
management, found that the purpose of SBS-Agro's investment in
Flamingo Bank was ``the possible purchase of its business in the
future.'' It could not be determined whether SBS-Agro ever acted on
that goal. A 1998 audit of SBS-Agro by Arthur Andersen notes that
the bank's 20 percent stake in Sobinbank amounted to ``control or
significant influence'' over Sobinbank's activities.
</P>
<P>
   SBS-Agro, which largely collapsed during the Russian economic
crisis in 1998, was part of a financial and oil empire controlled
by Smolensky; Boris Berezovsky, a prominent Russian financier with
long ties to former President Boris Yeltsin; and Roman Abramovich.
The three financiers did not respond to repeated interview requests
over the last few weeks. Neither SBS-Agro nor any of the three
financiers were mentioned by Edwards or her husband, or in the
court documents filed by federal investigators Wednesday. There is
no evidence of any involvement by them in the Bank of New York
activities.
</P>
<P>
   For their cooperation with their handlers in Moscow, Edwards and
Berlin received $1.8 million, which represented a percentage of the
funds moved through the Benex network. ``We were paid substantial
commissions for doing very little work,'' Edwards noted.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and Berlin said they directed that those funds be
deposited in off-shore bank accounts so they could avoid paying
taxes on the money in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said she had assisted ``hundreds'' of Russians to secure
bogus visas for travel to the United States and that most of them
worked in the Russian banking industry.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that after the couple moved to London in 1996,
they paid a Bank of New York employee, Svetlana Kudryavtsev, $500 a
month to make sure the Benex accounts were operating properly.
Kudryavtsev, a lower-level employee at the bank, is the individual
cited in the court charges for taking bribes. Kudryavtsev was
indicted last month for allegedly lying to federal investigators
about whether she or her husband had received money or loans from
Edwards. Her lawyer could not be reached for comment Wednesday, but
on Monday he described the charges as unwarranted. The indictment
alleges that Kudryavtsev received about $30,000 from Edwards and
Berlin between 1995 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and Berlin face a maximum of 10 years in prison for the
charges against them when they appear at a sentencing hearing on
May 3, but it is likely that their cooperation with authorities
will lessen the severity of any punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucy Edwards and Peter Berlin have come voluntarily to New
York from their home in London to accept responsibility for their
part in the illegal transfer of funds through the Bank of New
York,'' T. Barry Kingham, the couple's attorney, said Wednesday in
Manhattan. ``They have cooperated fully with the investigation
being conducted by the FBI and the U.S. Attorney's Office and they
will continue to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple has surrendered about $1 million to authorities, some
of which was maintained in Swiss bank accounts, and they will be
released from federal custody pending their posting of a $500,000
bail bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's pleas starkly demonstrate the serious dangers of
unlicensed and unregulated entities operating within the American
banking system as cover for money laundering and other criminal
activities,'' said Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan,
in a prepared statement Wednesday. ``Evading and disregarding
American laws in this manner significantly undermines the integrity
of United States and foreign banking systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Schiliro, assistant director in charge of the FBI's New
York office, said that the investigation ``has followed a long,
winding road throughout the United States and abroad'' and that his
agency is ``determined to continue following the complicated trail
of money and banking transactions until all those who have
committed crimes are identified and charged.''
</P>
</TEXT>
