<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GORE MIXES ROLES
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Georgia on Thursday, Al Gore took a vice
presidential detour to view tornado-ravaged Camilla. His campaign
paid for his trip to Georgia, but taxpayers paid to take him from
Macon to Albany and then for a helicopter to Camilla. Laura Quinn,
a vice presidential spokeswoman, said Gore did not want to go so
near the destruction ``and not have the administration give it its
full attention.''
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A DEFECTION FROM BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Bill Jones of California, the state's
highest-ranking Republican, switched his endorsement from Gov.
George W. Bush to Sen. John McCain on Wednesday, becoming the first
prominent Californian to defect from Bush. Jones, the sole
statewide survivor of a 1998 Republican electoral debacle, said
McCain was ``a candidate that not only crosses party lines but cuts
to the very core of why people want to be involved in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   POLLS IN WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state, polls show growing support for John McCain,
especially among independents. An Elway Poll of registered voters
last weekend found that 26 percent supported Bush and 16 percent
McCain, up from 6 percent in November. Twenty percent supported
Gore and 12 percent former Sen. Bill Bradley. An Evans/McDonough
poll for the state Democratic Party showed Bush with a 53 percent
to 32 percent lead over McCain among Republicans. But among all
voters, 23 percent backed or leaned toward McCain and 21 percent
toward Bush. A Mason-Dixon Poll of likely voters found McCain ahead
of Gore but that Bush and Gore were neck and neck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW LEADER FOR CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of internal squabbling over plans for the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles this summer, Mayor Richard J.
Riordan installed a trusted aide Wednesday as the new head of the
local host committee to oversee final fund-raising and organization
for the event. Deputy Mayor Noelia Rodriguez, who has been
Riordan's chief spokeswoman, will be the new chief executive of
L.A. Convention 2000, replacing Lucy McCoy, who resigned.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
