<HEADLINE>
DALLAS TO REMEMBER LANDRY IN MEMORIAL SERVICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to correct story. Use this version) 
 
By JIM HENDERSON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When he was fired in 1989 after 29 years as coach of
the Dallas Cowboys, Tom Landry anticipated that once the spotlight
was turned off, he would recede into the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will forget me quick,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not very quick, it turned out. This week Dallas has been
preparing an elaborate eulogy for the man many considered
responsible for bringing more to the city than football
championships.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that Landry died last Saturday without realizing
the unique place he occupied in the psyche of Dallas, which spent
decades trying to live down the assassination of President Kennedy
and the image of J.R. Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Since his death, former Cowboys, pundits and old friends have
credited Landry with doing more than any other person to give
Dallas back its self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Being a winning coach was only a part of that process.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a recognized class about him, a style,'' said Tex
Schramm, the team's general manger who hired Landry in 1960. ``He
had character and was honest to the extreme. He was a great man you
would want to look up to. It's like they used to say during the
war: If you're going to charge up the mountain, this is the guy you
want leading you.''
</P>
<P>
   He not only took a rag-tag expansion franchise and turned it
into ``America's Team,'' one of the most recognizable and
marketable organizations in professional sports, he did it without
allowing the job to dominate his life.
</P>
<P>
   Before he accepted the job he warned Schramm that he might not
be suited to the task because football was not his highest
priority. Faith and family ranked higher.
</P>
<P>
   To the crowds and television cameras on game day, he presented a
stern persona, as humorless as artificial turf and as stoic as a
goal post.
</P>
<P>
   Someone once asked fullback Walt Garrison if Landry ever smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Garrison said. ``But, I've only been here nine
years.''
</P>
<P>
   But behind the frozen expression, those who worked with him and
played for him saw another Landry. Carlton Stowers, who covered the
Cowboys for the Dallas Morning News for many years, recalled an
occasion when, to celebrate Landry's birthday, the players hired a
dancer to surprise him at his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was singing and tap dancing,'' Stowers said, ``and he got
up and sang and tap danced along with her.''
</P>
<P>
   When a group of sportswriters covering training camp grew
beards, Landry watched grimly, arms folded, as they approached him
after practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everytime I see you guys, I feel like I should call
security,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was one of the most public figures in Dallas, he
guarded his privacy and practiced his faith without fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those closest to him did not know that for more than 20
years he had participated in a prison ministry run by former
Cleveland Brown Pro Bowler Bill Glass. Landry frequently visited
prisons with Glass and other sports figures to minister to inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Glass said he was not surprised this week to see the outpouring
of emotion that followed Landry's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way you could have overvalued him as a human
being,'' he said. ``He was the greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   There were immediate calls from sports columnists and
politicians to rename Texas Stadium for him. The Dallas Stars and
Mavericks began their games with a moment of silence in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   F-16s flew overhead and Pro Football Hall of Famers sat in
mourning Wednesday as Landry was buried in a private ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The guest list of about 400 friends and family members included
former Cowboys Tony Dorsett, Roger Staubach, Harvey Martin, Dan
Reeves and former New York Giants teammate Frank Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   More memorials and tributes are planned for Thursday. At noon
CST, family and friends will hold a private memorial service at
Highland Park United Methodist Church, where Landry was a member
for 43 years.
</P>
<P>
   At 4 p.m., a public memorial will be held in the Morton Meyerson
Symphony Center and, while television cables were being installed
Wednesday for a live telecast, police were grappling with concerns
over security, traffic and crowd control.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame members such as Bob Lilly, Sam Huff, Schramm and
Staubach will speak, as will NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Children's Chorus and the Dallas Baptist University
Chorale will perform, and Dyess Air Force Base in Abilene will
provide a color guard. Tommy Loy, whose trumpet solo of the
national anthem opened many Cowboy games, also will play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to keep this a memorial service rather than an
event,'' said David Fisher, interim director of administration for
the symphony center. ``It's a somber event.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
