<HEADLINE>
2 BIRDS, 1 STONE: GIULIANI FAULTS CLINTON ON OIL RESERVES IN
UPSTATE VISIT
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-OIL, OIL-PRICES) 
(nk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ In a campaign sweep of Plattsburgh and Syracuse
meant to quell criticism that he is spending too little time in
upstate New York, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on Wednesday repeated his
criticism of the Clinton administration for refusing to free up
part of the nation's Strategic Petroleum Reserve to counterbalance
the soaring cost of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made his first stop at midafternoon in Plattsburgh,
close to the Canadian border, saying he had chosen the frigid city
because it had experienced ``the biggest impact in the state'' from
a sharp spike in oil prices caused by cuts in OPEC oil production
and the winter cold snaps in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   In Syracuse, where Giuliani appeared at a news conference with
the city's Republican loyalists, he said the increases in oil
prices had provided ``an illustration of what I can do if elected
to the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can fight very hard for New Yorkers,'' he said. ``I am
willing to take on the president.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for the spigot on the Strategic Petroleum Reserve to
be opened to counter OPEC's yearlong cut in oil production.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving upstate, Giuliani said that his criticisms had
prompted President Clinton to hold a news conference Wednesday to
announce a fresh federal allocation of $120 million in emergency
cash subsidies to help poor people pay for heating oil. New York is
to get $36.6 million of the subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   In questions from reporters here, Giuliani was asked repeatedly
why he had not appeared more frequently in Syracuse and other
upstate cities. It is a question much on the minds of some Syracuse
residents since the mayor's rival for U.S. Senate, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, has visited this city three times since July, most
recently attracting 500 people at fund-raising event and speech a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   As he has in the past, Giuliani responded by saying that his
duties as New York mayor prevented frequent campaign trips outside
the city. He told a television reporter here that he would ``come
up here more as the campaign progresses,'' but acknowledged to
another that he would ``not be able to travel around the state as
much'' as Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Syracuse residents who gathered shortly before 6 p.m.
at a tavern in this city's historic downtown Armory Square
district, Giuliani's appearance provoked a mixture of enthusiasm
and relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody here has not been affected in January by the price of
oil,'' said Nicholas J. Pirro, the Onondaga County executive and a
Republican, who said his constituents considered Giuliani to be ``a
guy who knows how to get things done, and does it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Adam Beasley, a Syracuse University student who awaited
Giuliani's arrival with several members of the university's
Republican student organization, said Clinton had ``pulled a lot of
votes'' here with her visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People upstate are more ideologically attuned to Rudy,'' he
said, ``but he better not take them for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
