<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-NUKE-PREPARE-ART-N     02-16 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NUKE-PREPARE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN CONFUSED ON A DAY THE SIRENS DIDN'T GO OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHANAN, N.Y. _ Mitchell M. Vanderveer was running on a
treadmill at a health club here Wednesday morning when he heard
that the Indian Point 2 nuclear power plant had apparently released
a small amount of radiation Tuesday night. Suddenly, his heart rate
spiked.
</P>
<P>
   Where were the sirens? Why wasn't he notified? What, exactly,
was going on?
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am, huffing and puffing, and I'm wondering what I'm
breathing in,'' said Vanderveer, 46, a groundskeeper at an estate
in Croton-on-Hudson. ``They use that siren system, which is
certainly annoying, when they don't need it. And when they do need
it, they don't use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanderveer was hardly the only person living, working or passing
through this Hudson River town Wednesday who was rattled and a bit
confused about what happened at Indian Point. Adding to the sense
of confusion, Consolidated Edison said early Wednesday evening that
it was unclear whether any radiation had even escaped the plant.
</P>
<P>
   But for many people here, what seemed most important Wednesday
was not the scientific data, or engineering jargon, or calls for
calm from public officials that invariably accompany any anomalous
event at a nuclear power plant. Instead, they questioned whether
emergency officials had handled matters properly, or had
underplayed the situation. And they reminded themselves that a
26-year-old institution that people around here often take for
granted, in a wishful-thinking kind of way, can still malfunction
or at least produce unwanted events.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly did not help that news helicopters were over the
area in pitch darkness early Wednesday morning, rousing many people
from bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there was a convict who escaped; I didn't know what
was going on,'' said a shaken George Roppoccio, 44, a self-employed
handyman who has lived all his life in this corner of Westchester
County. ``I don't think anything like this ever occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time, in fact, that Con Edison had issued an
alert _ the second of four levels of nuclear emergency _ since the
Indian Point 2 plant opened in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour or so of being notified by Con Edison on Tuesday
night, Andrew J. Spano, the Westchester County executive, opened an
emergency operations center in White Plains. Spano also directed
the county's Health Department to conduct independent radiation
tests within a 2.5-mile radius of the plant, said Adele Dowling, a
spokeswoman for the county's Indian Point emergency response team.
</P>
<P>
   Those tests showed nothing abnormal, Dowling said.
</P>
<P>
   By the small hours of Wednesday morning, when Con Edison was
reporting that the situation was stabilized, Spano and the county
executives of Rockland, Putnam and Orange counties decided that it
would not be necessary to sound the 153 sirens within a 10-mile
radius of Indian Point. To date, the sirens have only blared during
drills, Dowling said.
</P>
<P>
   Spano was so confident, in fact, that he decided to go ahead, as
planned, with a business trip to Los Angeles on Wednesday morning
to get advice _ ironically enough _ from officials operating a new
emergency services center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was assured that there was no public threat,'' said Susan
Tolchin, a spokeswoman for Spano.
</P>
<P>
   To disseminate information, emergency officials opened a media
center at Westchester County Airport on Tuesday night and
established what Con Edison called a ``rumor control'' phone
number. By early Wednesday evening, more than 450 people had
called.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some people said that the very term ``rumor control''
did not exactly inspire confidence in what officials were saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird,'' said Ann Makelainen of the use of ``rumor
control'' to calm fears. ``I'd rather be notified than have to
listen to the news. I'd rather be safe than sorry,'' said
Makelainen, a receptionist at the National Maritime Historical
Society in Peekskill, which is within view of the Indian Point
plant, less than a quarter-mile away.
</P>
<P>
   For years, many people here have been ambivalent about their
relationship with Con Edison and Indian Point. While grateful for
the taxes the plant pumps into the local economy, many people also
say that they do not feel that Con Edison has not done enough to
inform the public, especially considering the plant's spotty record
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   At Johnny Rit's, a sports bar near the entrance to the plant,
the owner, Johnny Ritornato, and the manager, Johnny Ritornato Jr.,
had different interpretations. The younger Ritornato said that he
could not trust Con Edison. But the elder Ritornato, who has owned
the bar for 35 years and counts many Indian Point workers among his
regulars, said he did not mind not being notified about what had
happened.
</P>
<P>
   As he watched the crush of journalists in the area Wednesday
afternoon, he said: ``Most everyone who works at Indian Point, they
are all pretty intelligent guys. I think they know what they are
doing. They all have degrees, some have master's, some have
doctorates, some have worked on submarines; they're a solid
bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of Ritornato's customers, George Ondek, was more
skeptical, more nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' Ondek said, in between sips of a soda. ``I
was surprised they didn't notify us. Why were all the government
agencies notified and not the general public? After Three Mile
Island and Chernobyl, of course you worry about these things.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
