<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9286 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CAROLINA-PROFILE-1STL     02-16 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAROLINA-PROFILE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS IN SOUTH CAROLINA NO LONGER PREDICTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS: spelling of ``Lindsey'' in 9th graf; DELETES ``Once
reactionary and isolated'' from 12th graf) 
 (See also SC-REPUBS, SC-POLITICAL-PROFILE) 
(rk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY and DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Not quite a decade ago, Gov. Carroll Campbell
Jr. of South Carolina bought an airplane ticket to Germany and
brought home a BMW. Not a car, but a factory. For Campbell, who had
a talent for luring foreign industry, the arrival of BMW meant
thousands of new jobs and international cachet for a state once
dismissed as a redneck backwater.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent days, Campbell, who stepped down in 1995 after two
terms, has felt the burden of his own success. For two decades, he
has delivered his state's primary for every Republican presidential
front-runner. Just as New Hampshire has made a habit of deflating
front-runners, South Carolina has propped them back up. The state
became known as the fire wall, the place where upstarts and
insurgents, notably Pat Buchanan, inevitably flamed out.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell is again trolling for support for yet another wounded
front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, for the Republican
primary on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the state he is encountering, a place he dominated and
helped revive, is no longer the same. His political machine is
still intact, but there is a new generation of voters, many of them
new to South Carolina, drawn by industries like BMW. They are
conservative, but they are not predictable, or necessarily
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have a weakened fire wall,'' said Campbell, who is
now a lobbyist in Washington. ``We used to be a state where four or
five people ran everything. Now, it's open and it's challenging,
and I think that is good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate beneficiary of this evolving political culture is
Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who is trying to stoke South
Carolina's populist streak and build an improbable coalition of
Republicans, independents and alienated Democrats. A decade ago,
political observers say, McCain could never have pulled this off,
and even now, his chances of victory on Saturday depend on an
unprecedented turnout of natives and newcomers outside the old
Republican mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome, the competitiveness of the race has
underscored how the changing national economy is changing politics
everywhere, even in once-isolated places like South Carolina. It
was evidence in New Hampshire, where a new pool of voters created
by that state's technology boom helped McCain trounce Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But there are new pools of voters here, whether transplants from
the Midwest and the Northeast working along the I-85 corridor, or
the thousands of retirees, many of them ex-military, who continue
to repopulate the coastline. There also are younger native
Republicans, raised in the state's suburbs, who are less inclined
to walk lock step with establishment leaders.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's candidacy has sparked an open rebellion by two
Republican congressmen, Lindsey Graham and Mark Sanford, who have
embraced his populist message and have escorted him around the
state, partly in hopes of burnishing their own chances at higher
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``That granular political structure, built up around county
courthouses, is all gone now,'' said Blease Graham, a professor of
state history at the University of South Carolina. ``Things are so
much more fluid now. People are mobile, and the old loyalties are
dying.''
</P>
<P>
   What is changing South Carolina more than anything is
prosperity. The dispute over flying the Confederate battle flag
atop the state Capitol is a reminder that the state's past is far
from buried. But the present and future are in plain view: The
booming manufacturing zone along I-85 in the north and the retirees
flocking to the coastal low country, particularly near Hilton Head,
where the accents are often from Chicago and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Not more than 40 years ago, South Carolina suffered endemic
poverty, masked by the aristocratic sheen of Charleston. Now, the
state is a national leader in attracting manufacturing, including
$42 billion in capital investment during the 1990s, a boom that
created 207,000 jobs. South Carolina now has 500 foreign companies
that employ nearly 85,000 people. Of the state's 3.9 million
residents, nearly 144,000, mostly from the Midwest and the
Northeast, have moved in since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people think we're a bunch of corn pones with pickup trucks
and trailers, they're wrong,'' said Vic Sherlock, a recent
transplant from suburban Washington who is now an officer in the
Greenville County Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This state is going through dramatic, dramatic growth,''
Sherlock said. ``There is the old guard and the new guard. There is
a very hard-core conservative base. It seems like the new people
coming in are predominantly Republican but perhaps not as
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Along I-85, growth is everywhere. In Greenville, the downtown
streets are lined with restaurants like Bistro Europa or with bars
where conversations are often conducted in German. Local residents
have nicknamed the interstate ``the autobahn'' not only because of
the high rate of speed but because of the German companies that are
alongside.
</P>
<P>
   In Spartanburg, a city northeast of Greenville, the county
Republican Party is run by a New Jersey transplant, Rick Beltram.
Newspapers from New Delhi, India, are available in the new
Spartanburg public library. The old mill villages of white frame
houses that were built for textile workers are still standing, but
most of the mills have closed. A new downtown hotel is planned with
a nine-hole golf course, and Republicans hold fund-raisers at the
BMW museum beside the factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told somebody the other day that this place is beginning to
look like New Jersey,'' said Gary Towery, who left Spartanburg more
than 40 years ago and returned in 1996, perhaps overstating the
comparison a bit. ``I look around, and I am mesmerized by the
difference in the people. You don't hear the accents as
predominantly as you did before.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Few politicians in South Carolina have better gauged the
changing moods of the state than Campbell. He built the state's
Republican Party in the 1970s and 1980s, capitalizing on white
resentment of the civil rights era and the growing sense of
alienation from Washington. He and allies like Sen. Strom Thurmond
and Lee Atwater, a Republican strategist, bridged the state's two
rival regions, assembling a coalition of Charleston Republicans
with upstate religious conservatives, many of whom were moving into
the middle class and to the right economically. There were 29
Republicans out of 124 state legislators in 1987; by 1994, the
party had a majority and had elected a House speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a party builder, more of a partisan by nature than his
predecessors,'' said Warren Tompkins, Campbell's chief of staff,
who is now the chief strategist in South Carolina for the Bush
campaign. ``He was able to utilize the growing discontentment with
Washington, and the new economic climate, to add people to the
Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   But prosperity has brought a growing independence among voters,
as the freshness and rigidity of the earlier conversion to
Republicanism had begun to fade. Voters began identifying
themselves as independents, splitting their tickets, and black
voters became better organized. The turning point came in 1998,
when Campbell's hand-picked successor, Republican Gov. David
Beasley, lost his re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans not only lost the governor's office to Jim Hodges,
but their majority in the Legislature was cut, and they failed to
dislodge Sen. Ernest Hollings, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some of the pains that you suffer from when you
achieve majority status,'' Tompkins said. ``You're not as tightly
knit as you were when there were only 29 Republicans. Back then, we
never had to worry about voters wandering off the reservation.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Bush-McCain race is the prism through which change is
being measured. Whit Ayres, a prominent Republican pollster in
Atlanta who once worked in Campbell's administration, said the
influence of newcomers is significant but should not be overstated.
The number of people voting in the Republican primary has grown
from 149,000 in 1992 to 274,000 in 1996, and Ayres noted that many
of the new residents have joined the establishment embodied by
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're talking about the plant manager for BMW in
Spartanburg, that person is very much a part of the traditional
business establishment,'' Ayres said. ``But if we're talking about
the guy on the factory floor, I think he may be for McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Buchanan had hoped to shatter the Campbell
coalition by dividing the Bubbas from the Blue Bloods with his
blunt appeal for trade barriers. But he badly miscalculated. The
factory workers who collected paychecks from foreign corporations
such as BMW, Michelin and Hitachi concluded that tariffs were not
in their best interest.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is taking a different tack, preaching free trade like
Bush, but hammering away at the Washington establishment even as
Bush tries to wed him to it. The great unknown is whether the same
wave of independents who poured forth for McCain in New Hampshire _
largely under the radar of polls _ will appear in South Carolina.
He is counting on military retirees along the coast, just as Bush
has worked the Bible Belt in the upstate.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Brafman, 72, a Republican and chairman of the Beaufort
County Council, said McCain's appeal is one of personality. He said
demographic changes in his area skews handicapping. He suspects,
for example, that many of the new residents are Democrats, maybe 25
percent. ``They are very quiet,'' Brafman said, but they do vote in
national elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever experienced anything like this where
nobody knows what will happen,'' said Brafman, who supports Bush.
``It's different upstate, where Bush has the edge. ... It's hard to
gauge how Republican are going to vote, because ideology has
nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanford, whose congressional district encompasses much of the
state's northern coast, said the notion of voters following orders
from above could get someone ``clubbed to death with a 7-iron'' at
the retirement communities on Hilton Head.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this whole notion after New Hampshire that the
Southerners in South Carolina would throw out what the Yankees had
done,'' he said. ``But in many neighborhoods in my district, there
are more Yankees than Southerners. That whole notion just isn't
true. The uncle of that voter up north is probably retired here on
Hilton Head Island.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of Campbell? He stood at the back of a Bush rally last
week, talking with reporters. He spoke a bit testily of Graham and
Sanford; he said Graham, who became famous for his role in last
year's impeachment proceedings, is trying out for a U.S. Senate
run, a notion Graham doesn't exactly deny. ``You're gonna have
cliques,'' Campbell said of the split.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has taken a leave from his lobbying job to help Bush.
He believes Bush will win. His numbers are rising in the polls, and
South Carolina residents love the Bush family. Asked whether
politicking was harder today, he laughed. ''Probably,'' he said.
``Because we had a lot of success then, and it doesn't come as easy
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
