<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MONEY-HNS &LR;      02-16 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMP HAS SPENT $50 MILLION ON CAMPAIGN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILTON HEAD, S.C. _ George W. Bush's aides confirmed Wednesday
he has spent $50 million of the record $70 million he raised last
year in what has become a battle to win the GOP presidential
nomination that once seemed his for the asking.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it is expensive to run a 50-state campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a plan in place that will enable me to stay in this
race for the long run,'' Bush said. ``We have been in fighting in
every primary state. We are on plan, and I think I've got a good
chance of winning.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said a report to be filed with the
Federal Election Commission next week will show Bush had $20
million cash on hand Jan. 31 out of a total of more than $70
million raised.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's defeat to John McCain in the Feb. 1 New Hampshire
primary prompted Bush to step up spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to spend more money because we lost New
Hampshire, and we're up against a big publicity bonanza that we
anticipated would happen should we lose New Hampshire,'' Hughes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spending through Jan. 31, before the first primary vote
was cast, was a record of more than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole spent $42 million through July 1996 in securing the GOP
presidential nomination in the entire primary season. President
Clinton spent $38 million for the Democratic nomination that year.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's original budget had set a goal of spending about $40
million to secure the nomination and then another $38 million to
campaign against the Democratic nominee through July's Republican
National Convention when the GOP nominee will receive $60 million
in federal funds for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was plan A. Now we're on plan B,'' said one senior Bush
aide, and Hughes said Bush was now operating on a ``contingency
plan'' that was written last fall. Hughes said the campaign had
always anticipated needing to hold planned fund-raising events in
March and April.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush's spending through January included major
purchases of television advertising time in 14 states and the
District of Columbia. Those states include Michigan and California,
which hold their primaries Feb. 22 and March 7, respectively, after
this Saturday's pivotal Republican primary in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign also has spent heavily on direct mail and on
setting up campaign offices in numerous states, Hughes said.
Another aide said Bush held 452 political and fund-raising events
in 1999 around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Don Evans, Bush's national finance chairman, said Bush's
spending is not terribly out of line for what the campaign had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we increased our spending as a result of New Hampshire?
Yes, we have,'' Evans said. ``We raised money in 1999 to be
competitive in the spring, and we're competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign had anticipated a potential financial war of
attrition with millionaire Steve Forbes, who dropped out of the
race after disappointing showings in Iowa, New Hampshire and
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bush's new spending plan risks that he will spend
everything to win the nomination in a fight with McCain and be left
with little money to finance his campaign through July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to spend more money trying to secure the
Republican nomination, but we think we will be amply funded to be
able to compete in the period between the nomination and the
convention,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing of Bush's money woes, McCain said: ``I hope that
there's a category in the Guinness Book of Records for how much
money he has spent. It's pretty remarkable. I believe that it's
ample testimony that we're winning the battle of ideas and not the
battle of bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole's 1996 campaign was severely hampered when he couldn't
afford to respond to Clinton's attacks between the time Dole
secured the nomination and he received federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crisis spending that they didn't anticipate having to
spend this percentage of their money this early,'' said University
of Texas political science professor Bruce Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said Bush's financial future could be determined by the
South Carolina outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't win Saturday, they're going to have big
fund-raising problems,'' Buchanan said. ``If he wins, he heals up
dramatically and quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he is not worried about how much money he might need
if he wins the nomination over McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to see. I haven't projected beyond Saturday,'' Bush
said. ``My intense focus is on turning out the vote here in South
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also raised questions about whether McCain has violated
federal spendng caps for campaigning in South Carolina. Bush is
not subject to spending limits because he decided not to accept
federal matching funds. McCain did agree to take matching funds and
to abide by spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   The two camps disagree on what that limit is. Bush says McCain
was limited to $1.5 million. McCain said he interprets the
convoluted law to mean the limit is $3 million, and he has spent
``a nickel under'' that amount, his political director said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In exchange for taxpayer money, candidates should conform to
the rules,'' Bush said. ``Senator McCain should explain if in fact
he has busted the spending cap in South Carolina how on the one
hand you can be a campaign funding reformer and on the other hand
not live within the spending caps.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, launched a new television commercial in South
Carolina, Michigan, North Dakota and Virginia accusing McCain of
continuing to use negative campaigning against Bush despite
promising not to. The commercial also says McCain, whose candidacy
is based on campaign-finance reform, voted ``to use your taxes to
pay for political campaigns. That's not real reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who also has a campaign-finance reform plan, has said his
plans to use tax money to run a presidential campaign is different
from the legislation McCain voted for that would have financed
congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
