<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NARCOTICS-SCHEME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR AND 2 PHARMACISTS CHARGED IN PRESCRIPTION DRUG CONSPIRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Va., W.Va.)  (bl) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors charged a Manhattan doctor and
two pharmacists Wednesday with taking part in a conspiracy to
illegally distribute prescription narcotics. The prosecutors said
the three men were charged after a federal agency shut down a
network that they said transported drugs from New York City to
Virginia and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White released a statement Wednesday
accusing the men of being part of ``an alleged scheme to divert
huge quantities of the prescription drug Dilaudid into the illicit
narcotics market.''
</P>
<P>
   Dilaudid, a painkiller whose generic name is hydromorphone
hydrochloride, is derived from opium and is an extremely potent
narcotic. It is highly addictive and typically prescribed in small
amounts under strict control. Federal agents said that the street
price for illegal Dilaudid in Virginia was $25 to $60 per tablet.
In New York City, the wholesale price for the painkiller is $3 to
$5 per tablet, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extremely high profit margin is an attractive motive for
this type of association to continue,'' said Lewis Rice Jr., the
special agent in charge of the Drug Enforcement Administration
office in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors said in their statement that Dr. Ronald A.
Jones, 47, wrote ``thousands of Dilaudid prescriptions without any
medical justification for at least that past two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, an internal medicine specialist with offices on Central
Park West and on 57th Street, was arrested Wednesday. Federal
agents also arrested two pharmacists, Gordon Brodwin, 65, and
Ismael Sosa, 53. Prosecutors said the prescriptions were filled at
the Brodwin-Sosa Pharmacy, at 1344 First Ave. at 72nd Street.
Lawyers for the three men could not be reached Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the Brodwin-Sosa Pharmacy bought more Dilaudid
from its distributor than any other pharmacy in New York state over
the last two years. In 1999, prosecutors said, the pharmacy bought
1,268,500 tablets of the drug, six times greater than the purchase
by the second-largest buyer. They said that 75 percent of that was
dispensed under prescriptions rom Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In January, drug enforcement agents and New York City police
officers arrested 36 people in New York City, Virginia and West
Virginia. Prosecutors said the arrests focused on a drug operation
based in the South Bronx. They have charged 18 people with
involvement in the operation, which prosecutors say sold narcotics
including Dilaudid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
