<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Feb. 16, 2000 -- CIR-PIANO-TUNING --
Mordecai Shehori, a concert pianist in New York, uses software to
tune his instrument. He often changes tunings slightly, according
to the composer being played. ``When the octaves are stretched very
little, it creates purer sonorities and leaner sound, which fits
better Scarlatti, Mozart and Haydn,'' he says. ``When the octaves
are stretched more, it creates a more robust, gritty sound that
fits better to Schumann, Brahms or Liszt.'' (Andrea Mohin/The New
York Times) LITE
