<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KUKOC-TRADED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUKOC GOES TO 76ERS IN 3-TEAM TRADE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Philadelphia 76ers were stuck in the middle of the Eastern
Conference. Like Toronto, Milwaukee, Charlotte and Detroit, they
fit somewhere between a playoff-bound team and a championship
pretender. Wednesday, the 76ers upgraded their status and caused
concern throughout the conference.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-team swap, Chicago shipped Toni Kukoc to
Philadelphia, which traded Larry Hughes and Billy Owens to Golden
State and Bruce Bowen to Chicago. To complete the deal, the
Warriors sent John Starks and their No. 1 pick in the 2000 draft to
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to improve before the Feb. 24 trading deadline
could be mounting for teams like the Knicks, Miami and Indiana. ``I
think Philadelphia did well for themselves,'' Knicks Coach Jeff Van
Gundy said. ``They got a very good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc, the only player left from Chicago's dynasty, will team
with Allen Iverson to form one of the conference's most potent
offensive duos. For the Bulls, General Manager Jerry Krause freed
more salary-cap room to pursue free agents this summer. Kukoc, 31,
was in the final year of his contract and there was little chance
Chicago would re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors accomplished two goals: getting rid of Starks, who
will be a free agent, and acquiring Hughes, an exciting young
player who must stay at Golden State for at least three years under
the rules of the current collective bargaining agreement between
players and owners.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers got what they wanted _ a multi-skilled 6-foot-11-inch
and 235-pound veteran who can shoot over small forwards and go
around power forwards with his quickness.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc's ball-handling and passing skills can take some of the
offensive load off Iverson, while not threatening his playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, 21, often complained to 76ers Coach Larry Brown about
his minutes. His slashing, uptempo game is so similar to Iverson's,
Brown and the organization eventually deemed him expendable.
Securing a veteran in return was a major coup for the 76ers. They
had also explored a deal with Miami for Jamal Mashburn until the
trade fell through last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams that win in this league _ the Indiana Pacers, the
New York Knicks, the Miami Heat, the Utah Jazz, the Los Angeles
Lakers and the Portland Trail Blazers _ those teams are not winning
with all young players,'' said Billy King, Philadelphia's general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Though back spasms sidelined him early in the season, Kukoc has
already had 10 games in which he has scored at least 20 points this
season and two games in which he has scored at least 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors were also happy with the deal. Along with Antawn
Jamison, taken fourth in the first round last year, Golden State
has two of the first eight players chosen in the 1999 draft.
Hughes, the No. 8 pick, played in all 50 games and was the
fourth-leading scorer for the 76ers this season. He gets his wish
of becoming an instant franchise player, although it will be on a
very bad team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are excited to get what we think is one of the top young
shooting guards in the NBA,'' Golden State Coach and General
Manager Garry St. Jean said.
</P>
<P>
   The draft pick sent to Chicago by the Warriors is a
lottery-protected selection from Washington. If the Wizards get the
first, second or third pick in the 2000 draft, the Bulls cannot
exercise it until the following season. The best the Bulls could do
this season is secure the No. 4 pick.
</P>
<P>
   Starks, whose contract expires at the end of the season, goes to
a city in which he was often booed during his career. Having heard
rumors that he may have been headed to Miami to again play for
Coach Pat Riley, Starks was shaken by the deal. Starks said he
would not comment on the trade until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for the guy,'' said a former Knick teammate,
Chris Childs. ``His family just moved and now he's got to do it all
over again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
