of course, dog painting collectors. (Ruth Fremson/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Feb. 16, 2000 -- DOG-PICTURES-1 -- Dog art
was a cause for delight among auctioneers this week. Dorothy
Palmer, an art dealer and designer from Manhattan, examines a
plaster pug in a Tiffany case at the William Doyle Galleries.
``Some of these things that would only go for $100 or $200 in one
of our regular sales are bringing $400 or $500,'' says Alan Fausel,
the senior vice president in charge of European and American
painting at Doyle. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Feb. 16, 2000 -- METAL-INTERIORS-2 -- Thomas
Hand, a metalworker and ex-sculptor with a studio on Leonard Street
in TriBeCa, is the cold-rolled-steel set's current ``It'' Boy.
``It's all the hand finishing,'' he says. Steel is ``pickled,''
Hand explains, with an acid application to remove the ``blue
scale'' it arrives with, then chemically sprayed and scrubbed by
hand, as if it were being waxed, to achieve the required color and
patina. (Philip Greenberg/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Feb. 16, 2000 -- METAL-INTERIORS-1 -- Thomas
Hand, left, constructing a steel chair designed by Russell Groves,
who used Hand's metalwork at Armani's Fifth Avenue offices. Hand, a
metalworker and ex-sculptor with a studio on Leonard Street in
TriBeCa, is the cold-rolled-steel set's current ``It'' Boy. (Philip
Greenberg/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Feb. 16, 2000 -- CIR-PIANO-TUNING --
Mordecai Shehori, a concert pianist in New York, uses software to
tune his instrument. He often changes tunings slightly, according
to the composer being played. ``When the octaves are stretched very
little, it creates purer sonorities and leaner sound, which fits
better Scarlatti, Mozart and Haydn,'' he says. ``When the octaves
are stretched more, it creates a more robust, gritty sound that
fits better to Schumann, Brahms or Liszt.'' (Andrea Mohin/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
