</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THESTREET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL SITES ARE SAID TO SEEK MERGER
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TheStreet.com, whose fledgling stock soared and then dipped
sharply in the last six months, is in preliminary merger talks with
Marketwatch.com, a leading rival in the hotly contested business of
delivering financial news online, a person close to the discussions
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com announced Wednesday that it has hired the
investment banking firm of Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co. to help the
company find a buyer or a partner. Its executives would not expand
on the one-paragraph announcement, which said that it had hired the
investment firm ``to explore the wide variety of strategic
partnerships and other transactions in order to help grow the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the announcement made no mention of Marketwatch or any
other possible partner, speculation on Wall Street immediately
focused on companies like America Online, the News Corp. and The
New York Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com's attitude-laden news and analysis is already
available on several sites owned by America Online. News Corp. has
a 1.6 percent equity stake in TheStreet.com, while the Times Co.
has a 6.2 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The competition among financial Web sites has sometimes been
direct and at other times glancing, analysts say. Some sites, like
fool.com, are aimed largely at small investors, and others, like
TheStreet.com, seek a more sophisticated audience, a combination of
professionals and well-informed private investors.
</P>
<P>
   But in that competition for audience, TheStreet.com, which has
been a subscription-based site for almost its entire existence, has
been passed by other general news sites. According to the Web
measurement firm Media Matrix, TheStreet.com had 908,000 different
visitors in December, compared with 1.2 million for cnnfn.com and
3.2 million for Marketwatch, which leads the group.
</P>
<P>
   People close to both TheStreet.com and marketwatch.com draw
sharp journalistic and business distinctions between the two sites.
Journalistically, TheStreet.com has prided itself on deep, quick
reporting and sharp analysis. The skeptical, knowing tone and sharp
opinions of the leading columnists, James C. Cramer and Herb
Greenberg, has won the site a cadre of loyal followers on Wall
Street _ and another cadre of investors and professionals who
loathe them.
</P>
<P>
   On the business side, TheStreet.com, like The Wall Street
Journal, chose to use a subscription model for its business,
ensuring two revenue streams _ advertising and subscription _ but
also depressing its audience size. While some of its information
was available for free, those wishing to read Greenberg's column,
for instance, had to subscribe.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, TheStreet.com announced it was amending this
strategy and providing most of its news for free, while developing
premium sister sites like Realmoney.com and TheStreetPros.com that
would offer rich analysis and would charge. RealMonday.com would
offer the commentaries of Cramer, who is also a hedge fund manager
and a co-founder of the Web site, to subscribers who would pay $20
a month, or $200 annually.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Marketwatch.com has focused on plain-vanilla
breaking news and strategies and partnership relationships that
would increase the audience for its free offerings. CBS has a 38
percent stake in the company, as does Data Broadcasting Co., which
was its original backer. A part of CBS's investment, however, is in
in-kind advertising, and the site's Web address is frequently
mentioned on such CBS programs as The Evening News with Dan Rather.
</P>
<P>
   Marketwatch's audience increased sharply in each of the last two
months, after deals with Yahoo and America Online brought thousands
of new users to its site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is fairly simple _ it's about getting users'' and selling
the audience to advertisers, said Lawrence Marcus, an analyst with
Deutsche Bank BT Alex. Brown. ``The beauty of being No. 1 is you
get a disproportionate share of the opportunity'' for deals that
can expand a site's reach.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus' firm was an underwriter for Marketwatch.com's public
offering of its shares last year.
</P>
<P>
   A comparison of the fourth-quarter earnings reports from the two
companies showed that Marketwatch.com, which has a market
capitalization of $588.8 million, had net revenues of $10 million.
TheStreet.com, with a market capitalization of $412.3 million, had
net revenues of $5.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   As an analysis by fool.com _ a competitor of both sites _
recently pointed out, ``TheStreet is running a more expensive
operation than Marketwatch.com to produce just half the revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kramer, the president and chief executive of Marketwatch,
would not comment on any possible negotiations Wednesday, and
Thomas J. Clarke, the chief executive of TheStreet.com, did not
return a message left with TheStreet.com's public relations
spokesman. The spokesman for News Corp. also did not return calls
seeking comment on whether his company would have an interest in a
partnership with TheStreet.com, whose leading commentators appear
frequently on the Fox News Channel's programs. A spokeswoman for
the Times Co. said it never commented on potential investments.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of TheStreet.com closed at $16 13/16 Wednesday, up 13/16.
SHare of Marketwatch closed at $42.50, down $1.
</P>
</TEXT>
