<SLUG> BC-HP-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEWLETT-PACKARD EARNINGS EXCEED ESTIMATES IN QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Hewlett-Packard Co. reported first-quarter
earnings Wednesday that exceeded Wall Street estimates by a couple
of pennies, excluding costs associated with the spinoff of its
test- and measurement-equipment maker, Agilent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue growth, at 14 percent, was particularly strong, compared
with the year earlier, when its revenue grew by just 1 percent.
Last quarter, Carleton S. Fiorina, who joined Hewlett-Packard in
July as president and chief executive, set a goal for the year of
12 percent to 15 percent growth in revenue and earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent, which operates a test and measurement equipment
business, will report its financial results separately for the
first time on Thursday. Hewlett-Packard sold 72 million Agilent
shares at $30 each in November, representing a 15 percent stake.
Hewlett-Packard plans to distribute the remaining shares to its
shareholders this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard reported its results after the close of the
market, but a strong quarter had been anticipated. Hewlett-Packard
shares closed at $129.375, up $4.0625, on the New York Stock
Exchange. In after-hours trading, Hewlett-Packard traded as high as
$132.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Jan. 31, net income from continuing
operations dropped to $794 million, or 77 cents a diluted share,
down 10 percent from $882 million, or 85 cents a share, in the
corresponding period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Year-earlier earnings that included Agilent was $960 million, or
92 cents a share. Revenue grew to $11.67 billion from $10.24
billion in the first quarter of fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding expenses related to the Agilent spinoff and the
incremental effect of stock appreciation rights resulting from a 46
percent rise in the company's stock price during the quarter,
Hewlett-Packard had earnings of 80 cents a share. Analysts had
expected the company to earn 78 cents, according to First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making clear and measurable progress in our enterprise
business,'' Fiorina said in a conference call with analysts. ``We
are winning more deals against tough competitors. The renewal and
reinvention of Hewlett-Packard is under way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard said its imaging and printing segment _ which
includes laser and inkjet printing and imaging devices like digital
cameras and scanners, and corresponding supplies and services _
grew 13 percent year over year. The computing systems segment _
which includes workstations, desktops, laptops, Unix servers,
storage and software _ grew 15 percent from a year earlier.
Services grew by 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They managed to show some growth in Unix, and had pretty good
PC and printer growth,'' said Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P.
Morgan. Fiorina ``couldn't expect the honeymoon to last forever,
and she knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   If she hadn't delivered the goods this quarter, the honeymoon
would have come to an abrupt end, and she prevented that,'' he
said. ``I think she's leaning on a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard still trails Sun Microsystems Inc. in the market
for Unix servers, which are commonly used to run Web sites and in
corporate applications. But Fiorina says the company is winning
more sales against Sun than in the past, and is moving into a
strong competitive position with the release later this year of the
IA 64 chip, or Itanium, jointly developed by Hewlett-Packard and
the Intel Corp. This chip will be used first in servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the low end, our data suggest we are growing as fast if not
faster than Sun,'' Fiorina said. ``We believe that based on order
growth we're seeing in these last two quarters. At the high end, we
think our total number of shipments continues to outpace Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Milunovich, an analyst with Merrill Lynch, said;
``Although still clearly trailing Sun, ``H.P. ought to be able to
at least grow in line with the market. They've got a decent product
line. With printers being 65 percent of profits, that really buys
them time to rebuild the Unix product line.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's revenue growth of 14 percent, he added,
``shows that Carly is having an impact on the company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
