<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSCHOOL-KERREY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR BOB KERREY TO HEAD NEW SCHOOL UNIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sen. Bob Kerrey, the war hero who failed in his bid
for the White House in 1992, is leaving the Senate _ and Nebraska _
to become president of the New School University in Manhattan, best
known for its offbeat catalog of continuing education classes for
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, a 56-year-old Democrat, said his decision to leave the
Senate came after the school approached him and expressed
enthusiasm about his ideas for education. He announced in January
that he would not seek a third term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be addressing what I consider one of the most difficult
problems in higher education,'' the senator said in an interview
from Omaha, ``in that it is becoming less and less accessible to
the middle class because of the costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, chairman of the Federal Web-Based Education Commission,
said he wanted to pursue the idea that using the Web could help run
a school more efficiently and lower the costs. And he said higher
education needed to play a more active role in finding solutions to
the problems in primary and secondary education.
</P>
<P>
   The New School University, founded in 1919 as the New School of
Social Research, gradually rose in stature in the 1930s and 1940s
when it served as a haven for social scientists fleeing persecution
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The university has 7,000 students seeking degrees and a
full-time faculty of 162, but it is better known for its 20,000
students in continuing education and its staff of 1,175 part-time
instructors. Its courses run the gamut from English literature to
astronomy to photography to more off-beat topics ranging from
basket weaving to a course entitled ``Gym Culture and the Modern
Amazon.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey said he hoped he would be able to teach one class
himself, in how to draft a law. He also said the fact that his
longtime girlfriend, Sara Paley, a screenwriter, lives in New York
was a ``happy coincidence'' in making his decision.
</P>
<P>
   He will be the school's seventh president. Its sixth, Jonathan
F. Fanton, was appointed in 1984 but left the $250,000 post with
its official Greenwich Village residence in September to become
president of the MacArthur Foundation in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The university said that it was attracted to Kerrey both for his
high public profile and his extensive work in education. ``We view
ourselves as a place of independence,'' said Philip Scaturro, the
school's chancellor, ``a place where free inquiry and discussion is
valued, and we believe those same values are important to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, a Vietnam veteran who lost his leg there and won a Medal
of Honor, was governor of Nebraska and operates a chain of
restaurants and health clubs in his home state. He has a reputation
as something of a maverick, but also as an important player on
Capitol Hill. His decision not to return to what was a safe seat
came as a blow to the Democratic Party, which would like to reverse
the Republican's 55 to 45 margin of control in the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
