u w BC-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      02-16 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES HOPE OF REVIVING IRISH PEACE PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite the breakdown in the Irish peace process,
President Clinton spoke optimistically Wednesday of reviving the
deal aimed at ending decades of violence and restoring self-rule to
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in a rough spot,'' Clinton said of the peace plan
mediated by his administration, as he called the decision this week
by the Irish Republican Army to pull out of disarmament talks an
``unfortunate development.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his first White House news conference of the year,
Clinton insisted ``there's still a good chance'' that the peace
process will succeed and pledged to do all he can to help get
things back on track.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish peace accord is considered one of the most significant
foreign policy accomplishments of Clinton's presidency. But the
IRA's withdrawal from talks Tuesday, a move that was made in
retaliation for Britain's suspension last week of the power-sharing
Northern Ireland government, is a serious setback that could
jeopardize the continuation of the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA's action worries some Irish observers who fear that the
militant group may be inclined to break its 3-year-old cease-fire
and resume a war of terror aimed at rooting out the British
presence in Northern Ireland. But Clinton said he has seen ``no
indication at all'' that the IRA intends to resort to violence
again, which he suggested is cause in itself to be hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means they still think that, no matter what the rhetoric
is, that all the parties really believe they ought to find a way to
work this out,'' the president added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton addressed the Irish peace process during an hourlong
news conference at which he also tackled topics ranging from the
Republican presidential campaign to gun control and the
India-Pakistan dispute over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will travel to India next month, but is not scheduled to
visit Pakistan. However, he left open the possibility of a stop in
Pakistan and offered to mediate the dispute over Kashmir if both
sides ask the United States to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is willing to play a key role in resolving the
decades-old dispute over the mountain territory that has sparked
several wars in the region, Clinton said, ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   He called South Asia a ``hugely important area of the world''
that's threatened by a potential nuclear arms race between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``A conflict between India and Pakistan, if not contained, is
one of the most significant security threats to the interest of the
United States in this new century, and, I might say, a tragic
situation,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton spent considerable time addressing foreign
policy issues, he used his appearance before reporters in the East
Room to tout his record on the domestic front and to announce the
release of $125 million from the federal Low Income Home Energy
Assistance Program to help poor families in the Northeast and
Midwest hit by the rising cost of home-heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   He also highlighted a study by the Department of Housing and
Urban Development suggesting that residents of public housing are
more than twice as likely to be victims of gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than a million children and 360,000 seniors live in
public housing in the United States. They deserve to be as safe as
the rest of us,'' Clinton declared, as he again urged Congress to
pass tougher, ``common sense'' gun-control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The president also reminded Americans that the nation is now in
the midst of the longest-running economic recovery in history. He
said there is still ``important work to be done'' in his remaining
year to help ensure that it continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must stay on the path of fiscal discipline that got us to
this point,'' he said, calling for most of the projected budget
surpluses over the next 13 years to be used to pay off the nation's
$3.7 trillion public debt. He added that debt reduction would help
ensure the preservation of the Social Security and Medicare
programs, and enable the government to provide a prescription-drug
benefit for elderly Americans who can no longer afford the high
cost of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   As he fielded questions, Clinton seemed to enjoy those that
dealt with the Republican presidential campaign between Gov. George
W. Bush and Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Laughing, Clinton said he has a ``lot of sympathy '' for Bush
and McCain who have made him the target of much of their rhetoric
because, ``It's hard for them to figure out what to run on,'' given
the state of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a tough job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he feels about being ridiculed by the GOP candidates
for his personal conduct while in office, the president added,
laughing, ``Well, if I were running, I'd do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said he likes to think that he is ``casting a little
sunshine'' over the 2000 campaign by ``being nice and generous''
for the most part in his assessment of each candidate's
qualifications for the job he now holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You basically have got four people (including Democrats Al
Gore and Bill Bradley) running for president now who are people of
accomplishment, people who have certain convictions. This is not a
bad thing for America, this choice they've got.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
