<SLUG> BC-OBIT-COHN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTOR E. COHN, JOURNALIST, DIES AT 80 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Victor Edward Cohn, a prize-winning science reporter, editor and
columnist for The Washington Post and, earlier, The Minneapolis
Tribune, died on Monday at his home in Washington. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was lung cancer, The Post reported.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn was the author of several books, including ``News and
Numbers: A Guide to Reporting Statistical Claims and Controversies
in Health and Other Fields'' (Iowa State University Press, 1988).
It is a standard reference book.
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement from The Post in 1993, Cohn was associated
with the American Statistical Association, Georgetown University
and the Harvard University School of Public Health. He was a
founder of the Council for the Advancement of Science Writing.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn was the first writer to twice win the American Association
for the Advancement of Science-George Westinghouse Prize for
Distinguished Science Reporting, in 1951 and 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn was a native of Minneapolis and a 1941 graduate of the
University of Minnesota. Before joining The Post as science editor
in 1968, he was a science reporter for The Tribune for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a son, Jeffrey P., of Takoma Park, Md.; two
daughters, Deborah Runkle of Kensington, Md., and Phyllis Beetsch
of Minneapolis, and six grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
