<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-DIALLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METRO MATTERS: SOME RELIEF FOR KILLERS OF DIALLO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DIALLO-TRIAL, DIALLO-CHARGES) 
(js) 
 By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The relief was palpable in Justice Joseph C.
Teresi's courtroom here Wednesday, when he said that the defense
and the prosecution had agreed that the jury should consider less
serious charges than murder in the trial of four police officers
accused in the killing of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   The taut features of Kenneth Boss, one of the officers, relaxed
_ almost imperceptibly, but not quite. Defense lawyers and about
two dozen police officers up from New York City wearing their
``Free the Bronx Four'' buttons all but hugged each other. Even the
four couldn't suppress small smiles as they left the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The reason isn't complicated. Jurors would be able to consider
charges that include manslaughter and criminally negligent
homicide, which carries a penalty as light as probation. The
original charge of murder carries a punishment of up to life in
prison _ 15 years at least. Any of the four can still be convicted
of the higher counts, but even some of their harshest critics say
that the prosecution has hardly made a case for murder.
</P>
<P>
   So there was plenty of elation on the defense side when Teresi
announced that he would consider charging the jury with the lower
counts _ the ``lesser includeds.'' But there was no surprise. In
fact, it was expected, just as the judge, who has reserved his
decision, is expected to accept the recommendation for broadening
the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The day the case began, over three weeks ago, even before the
jury had been selected, lawyers and reporters were already talking
about adding charges. That's because from the beginning of this
sad, politicized case over a year ago, many lawyers have said that
Robert T. Johnson, the district attorney of the Bronx, overcharged
_ that he accused the four officers of the high counts of
intentional murder and murder ``with depraved indifference to human
life'' knowing that convictions on those counts were unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   He denies that. He has complained that because the officers
would not appear before the grand jury, he did not know their
explanation. And his chief assistant, Barry L. Kluger, said
Wednesday, ``Of course we do not believe it was an overcharge,''
adding that requesting lesser includeds is ``not unusual.'' ``No
special significance should be given to that.''
</P>
<P>
   But little about the shooting of the unarmed African immigrant
by four white police officers has been without political
significance. The death of Diallo outraged millions of New Yorkers,
and legitimately so. An innocent man was killed, his body riddled
with 19 of 41 bullets fired at him because, the four defendants
say, they mistook his wallet for a gun. His death incensed people
all over the city, especially in the Bronx, most especially
African-Americans, already infuriated by aggressive police tactics.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to view the charges of intentional murder and
murder with depraved indifference through an apolitical lens. If
the jury convicts on lower counts, or acquits any of the officers,
Johnson can say at least he tried. Imagine the outcry if this
district attorney, who is, after all, an elected official,
originally charged them with manslaughter. Nor is overcharging
unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always overcharge,'' Gerald Lefcourt, a criminal lawyer,
said of district attorneys. ``You throw a lot against the wall and
hope something will stick.'' The hope is that by starting out too
high, the jury will come back with more than acquittal, similar to
a union leader insisting on unreasonably high salary increases at
the outset of a labor negotiation, then compromising.
</P>
<P>
   But there are consequences to this strategy. ``You totally raise
expectations,'' Lefcourt said. ``Look at that family. They're
totally going along with intentional murder. You'll have people
saying he threw the case.'' There was never a strong case for
intentional or depraved murder, he went on. ``You'd have to have
people on duty running around killing people.''
</P>
<P>
   Law textbooks describe depraved-indifference murder as the
equivalent of driving down Main Street, doing 60 miles an hour at 3
in the afternoon; intentional murder would be waiting for a
pedestrian to walk into the street and then stepping on the
accelerator. How does a prosecutor without one reliable witness
prove that four officers who say they saw a gun in a man's hand
committed depraved or intentional murder?
</P>
<P>
   He can't. Johnson will never admit it, and we will not know for
sure until the verdict comes in. But the betting here is that he
never stood a good chance of getting the four officers convicted of
murdering Diallo. And being a good lawyer, he knew it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
