<HEADLINE>
MINING SUIT MAY HURT LAND DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Down in the fertile green farmlands of Virginia, a fight over
vermiculite mining has spawned a nasty court case that some say
could halt efforts throughout the country to preserve ancient
forests, farmlands and pristine streams.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia case pits a land trust that husbands historic
farmlands and a major mining company that donated property to the
trust against a competing company that wants to mine vermiculite
from those lands.
</P>
<P>
   The case is being closely monitored by major environmental
groups such as the Nature Conservancy, which could eventually find
itself out of business if the courts side with the company that
seeks to mine the vermiculite. The Nature Conservancy is dedicated
to preserving lands for plants and animals by the use of
conservation easements that prohibit development.
</P>
<P>
   The group and other land-trust organizations were dealt a blow
by a ruling earlier in the case by the U.S. Court of Appeals Fourth
Circuit, which held that a non-profit organization that accepts a
land donation with commercial restrictions could be sued for
anti-trust violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservation easements and land donations are important
land-use tools that serve to protect hundreds of acres of
historically sensitive and environmentally sensitive resources
across the country,'' the Nature Conservancy and the Land Trust
Alliance wrote in a friend-of-the-court brief. ``The Fourth
Circuit's ruling that the receipt of donated land may be subject to
an anti-trust challenge directly threatens the continued viability
of conservation easements and land trusts.''
</P>
<P>
   The opponents in the Virginia case meet in U.S. District Court
in Charlottesville Thursday, where a federal judge will hear
motions in the case. Trial is scheduled for April 24.
</P>
<P>
   The same judge earlier dismissed the land trust from the suit,
but the organization was subsequently reinstated as a party by the
Fourth Circuit decision.
</P>
<P>
   The case has placed W.R. Grace &AMP; Co., a multibillion-dollar
corporation long the target of criticism by environmentalists and
public health experts, in the novel position of defending a
donation that would actually preserve lands from mining or other
development.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing Grace is Virginia Vermiculite Ltd., a mining company
owned by Robert Sansom, a former Environmental Protection Agency
official.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sansom's resume, he was a Fulbright Scholar, a
Rhodes Scholar and a White House Fellow. He worked for Henry
Kissinger at the National Security Council as well as serving as
assistant administrator for the EPA in the Nixon Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The legal squabble has roots stretching back to 1992, when Grace
donated about 1,400 acres to a land trust known as Historic Green
Springs Inc. The trust was established to protect the Green Springs
National Historic Landmark District and its surroundings in Louisa
County, Va., from development.
</P>
<P>
   The oval-shaped district encompasses about 14,000 acres, and
contains more 250 historic buildings on farmlands that date from
the American Revolution to about the mid-1880s.
</P>
<P>
   But the lands have a significance that goes beyond the historic:
they contain an enormous quantity of vermiculite.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other known vermiculite deposit ...in this country
or worldwide that has anywhere near the potential for the
production of vermiculite as the Green Springs area of Louisa
County,'' reported a 1972 Grace interal memo.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Libby, Mont., where vermiculite formerly mined by Grace
is contaminated by asbestos, the ore is found in commercial
quantities near Dillon and Hamilton, Mont., and in Virginia and
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Vermiculite is a unique, fireproof mineral that expands tenfold
when heated. It is used in insulation, fire safety, energy
conservation, construction, food processing and horticulture. It
also has promising future applications in water and soil
detoxification, nuclear waste cleanup and the containment of
industrial spills.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, Grace produced 57 percent of all vermiculite
sold in the United States. Virginia Vermiculite, the only other
major U.S. producer of the mineral, produced 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the remaining vermiculate sold in the country is
imported from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Grace had been under pressure from conservationists and the
Interior Department not to mine at Louisa.
</P>
<P>
   But when Grace donated the 1,400 acres in Louisa County to the
land trust, it didn't sit very well with Virginia Vermiculite.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Grace had offered its holdings in the county to
Virginia Vermiculate, and that company submitted an offer that
Grace found unacceptable. Rather than making a counteroffer, Grace
instead donated the land to the Green Springs trust in exchange for
a hefty tax deduction from the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   The donation came with a restrictive convenant that prohibited
vermiculite mining.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Virginia Vermiculite sued Grace and the land trust,
alleging it had been injured by the donation, which the company
claimed resulted in the supression of 40 percent of the vermiculite
supply in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That, Virginia Vermiculite contended, was a violation of the
Sherman Antitrust Act because it helped give Grace monopoly power
in the vermiculite market in the United States. Keeping the 1,400
acres from ever being mined by anyone depreciated the value of
Virginia Vermiculite's business and caused it to suffer increased
costs and lost profits, the company contended.
</P>
<P>
   Sansom says he filed the anti-trust suit ``for the public''
because the vermiculite reserves donated by Grace should ``be
available to the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   The land trust is represented by Seattle attorney Charles
Montange, a solo practioner with a broad background in enviromental
law.
</P>
<P>
   To Montange, the case has ramifications far beyond vermiculite
mining. If Virginia Vermiculite prevails in federal court, it could
well mean the end of land donations that protect property from
development, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would render any donation for state forest land illegal,''
Montange said. ``Any donation to the Nature Conservancy for
historic preservation, salmon preservation, old growth forest
preservation, would be subject to the Sherman Antitrust act.''
</P>
<P>
   If that argument is carried to its logical extreme, it means
that if vermiculite were found on the grounds of Thomas Jefferson's
Monticello, ``We'd have to tear it down, otherwise we'd be
restricting (commerce),'' Montange said. ``It's an amazingly
aggressive argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Sansom disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any reverberations for any easement
programs or anything else,'' he says. ``This is a unique case and I
don't think it has any broader consequences because it's in a
(historic) landmark.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals, runs counter
to previous decisions made by several other federal appellate
courts around the country, Montange and Grace contend in court
papers.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Judge James Michael, who originally dismissed the land
trust from the suit, had agreed, saying ``like the participants in
the temperance movement and anti-abortion movement, (the land
trust) is not engaged in commercial activities and should not be
exposed to antitrust liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis O'Donnell, an attorney who earlier drafted arguments on
behalf of the land trust, said he wasn't surprised by the Fourth
Circuit's ruling. Many of the judges hew to the politically
conservative side, and aren't afraid to put that into practice, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   David Izakowitz, an attorney representing Virginia Vermiculite,
says it's important to keep the case - and the intended mining - in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talk about this mining and what it does to a
historic district,'' Izakowitz said. ``But the mining, when it's
done, is in relatively small areas, a couple of acres at time. And
it can't be seen, because of the land berms.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Virginia Vermiculite would reclaim the land at the
end of mining, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be returned to green pastures that can be farmed,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
