<SLUG> BC-FORTUNE-STOCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCHANGE TO OFFER DERIVATIVES LINKED TO THE FORTUNE 500 LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Move over Dow Jones and Standard &AMP; Poor's, here comes
the Fortune 500 stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after Dow Jones &AMP; Co. agreed to allow investors to
trade derivatives based on the Dow Jones industrials, Fortune
magazine says it is going to allow the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
to begin offering futures and options linked to a new Fortune 500
index, which the magazine will create.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, which is owned by Time Warner Inc., said Wednesday
that it would also license the exchange to trade derivatives based
on a newly developed Fortune E-50 index, which would track the
performance of companies tied to the Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Fortune Inc. said the move was an attempt to
leverage a well-known brand name and capitalize on the growing
popularity of stock indexes by coming up with two measures derived
from the magazine's annual ranking.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine hopes the new indices _ which will move up and down
as a stock measure, just like the Dow Jones average _ will become
major benchmarks of stock performance in the broader market as well
as the increasingly popular technology sector. And for its part,
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange hopes to increase volume and
attract investors looking to do one-stop shopping in two more stock
index derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   Investors can currently trade futures and options on the Dow
Jones industrial average index at the Chicago Board of Trade and
the Chicago Board Options Exchange. The Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, which pioneered stock index futures when it introduced
widespread trading in the S.&AMP; P. 500 index in 1982, tried and
failed to win the Dow contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the Chicago Mercantile Exchange has begun
offering a popular contract called the e-mini, a bite-sized S&AMP;P 500
contract that is meant to appeal to smaller investors. The larger
S&AMP; P 500 contracts remain the most sought after, though, with over
27 million contracts traded in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The American Stock Exchange has also introduced new stock index
contracts in recent years that track the Dow and S&AMP; P. They are
known as Diamonds and Spiders. The Nasdaq stock market, owned by
the National Association of Securities Dealers, also licenses
indices tied to its index at several derivatives exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   In creating a stock index, Fortune magazine, which introduced
its annual Fortune 500 list in 1955, joins other large financial
institutions and publishers that have created market measures.
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, the big Wall
Street brokerage houses, have indices that track commodity prices
and technology stocks. Standard &AMP; Poor's, a unit of McGraw-Hill,
offers an array of stock indices.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1997, however, the Dow Jones industrial average was simply
a measurement of 30 big U.S. companies, chosen by the editors of
The Wall Street Journal, which is owned by Dow Jones. The major
futures exchanges were unable to offer products tied to the
average.
</P>
<P>
   The editors of Fortune will determine the components and metrics
that will be used in calculating the index. The company said those
details would be released in the March 6 edition of Fortune, which
is due on newsstands next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
