<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-SANCTIONS-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IMPOSES SANCTIONS ON OIL VENTURE IN SUDAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States imposed sanctions Wednesday on a
multinational oil venture in Sudan, a project that critics say has
helped the government there finance a religious war against
southern rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department's sanctions prohibit U.S. companies and
citizens from doing business with the Greater Nile Petroleum
Operating Co., a joint venture between Sudapet, Sudan's national
oil company, and Chinese, Malaysian and Canadian partners. The
sanctions ban trade and financial transactions with the joint
venture and freeze any assets it has placed in U.S. banks.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions do not cover the foreign parent companies that
backed the oil venture. Some members of Congress and human rights
groups had urged the Clinton administration to punish Talisman
Energy, China National Petroleum Corp. and Petronas, the leading
oil companies in Canada, China and Malaysia, respectively, for
their involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan's Islamist government has used oil revenue to fuel its war
against rebels in the mainly Christian and animist southern part of
the country, Western religious and human rights groups have argued.
The civil war has gone on for 17 years and killed millions of
people.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the United States has banned all trade, loans and
aid to Sudan, accusing the Khartoum regime of allowing slavery,
supporting terrorism and seeking to overthrow neighboring
governments. Wednesday's sanctions were an extension of the earlier
action, coming after the Treasury Department determined that the
oil project was essentially part of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a strong finding that the Sudapet project is part of
the country,'' a senior Treasury official said. ``Once we did that,
applying sanctions was more or less automatic.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The United States imposed sanctions just two days after Canada
made the opposite decision, electing to spare Talisman and Sudan
itself from punishment. Talisman, which has a 25 percent stake in
the Sudapet project, is one of the few large Western companies
willing to invest in Sudan, and has come under pressure to sever
links.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department's sanctions are not expected to impact
Talisman directly. Company officials told reporters Wednesday that
they had separated the finances and operations of the Sudanese
joint venture from those of the parent company. Still, Talisman
shares fell 2.30 Canadian dollars, or 5.6 percent, to 38.80
Canadian dollars in Toronto trading.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the sanctions are unlikely to affect China National
Petroleum, known as CNPC. The state-owned company is planning to
list shares on the New York Stock Exchange this spring, an offering
underwritten by Goldman Sachs Group. CNPC is selling shares in a
new subsidiary called PetroChina that consists exclusively of the
company's domestic assets.
</P>
<P>
   Some human rights groups and members of Congress have urged the
Clinton administration to take stronger action against the three
foreign companies that backed the Sudan venture. Rep. Frank Wolf,
R-Va., has argued that the administration should block the planned
U.S. listing of the CNPC subsidiary because of its ties to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything they do to punish those companies, I support,'' Wolf
said of the Clinton administration. ``But I would like to see it
broader. This is one of the major moral issues in the world
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior Treasury official said the Trading With the Enemy
Act, under which sanctions against Sudan were imposed, does not
allow the administration to punish third-country companies, only
U.S. citizens and U. S. companies.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
