<HEADER>
A9460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SC-TRIALS-740(2TA     02-16 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SC-TRIALS-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFEDERATE FLAG CASTS SHADOW ON OLYMPIC TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., W.Va., Va., N.J., Md.)   (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The presence of the Confederate battle flag above South
Carolina's state Capitol is a hot-button political issue that has
reverberated beyond Saturday's state Republican primary and into
the world of Olympic distance running.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women's marathon trials will take place in Columbia on
Feb. 26, where the flag flies over the capitol even though many
consider it a symbol of slavery, segregation and the Ku Klux Klan.
USA Track and Field, the sport's national governing body, has
issued a statement in support of the removal of the flag from the
South Carolina Statehouse, although it has not called for
postponing the race or for moving it to another location.
</P>
<P>
   The track federation has also offered to assist marathoners who
wish to support an economic boycott of the state, which has been
called for by the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People. Runners who wish to avoid patronizing hotels will
be housed by local families in Columbia, the federation said in a
letter sent to the approximately 200 qualifiers for the marathon
trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would minimize the economic impact of your visit to South
Carolina,'' said the letter, which was signed by Craig Masback, the
chief executive officer of USA Track and Field and by Patricia
Rico, the federation's president.
</P>
<P>
   Some college sports programs are also joining the fight against
the flag. Last week, Swarthmore College announced that it was
canceling spring-training trips to South Carolina for its tennis,
lacrosse, softball, golf and track and field teams, joining other
Philadelphia-area schools such as Haverford College, Bryn Mawr and
Temple, which have also voided trips for tennis and lacrosse teams
in support of the NAACP-sanctioned economic boycott.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA has also been asked by a coaching group that the South
Regional of the men's college basketball tournament be removed from
Greenville in 2002 if the confederate flag continues to fly above
the Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Conference, which includes such schools as Furman
and the Citadel, has called for a removal of the battle flag and
has indicated that it will consider moving its 2001 postseason
basketball tournament from Greenville, S.C., and the 2002 and 2003
tournaments from Charleston if the issue is not resolved by the
current session of the South Carolina Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have confidence things will be resolved; that's what we're
hearing through the grapevine, said Alfred White, commissioner of
the Southern Conference. He noted that South Carolina Gov. Jim
Hodges had won support from several black legislators for moving
the Confederate battle flag from the Statehouse to a monument of a
Confederate general on the Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued this week by USA Track and Field said that,
``For many Americans, the Confederate flag is a symbol of
subjugation and segregation. We urge the South Carolina Legislature
to remove the Confederate flag from its Statehouse as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Masback said that it would be impractical to
move a 26.2-mile race at the last minute, as well as unfair to
athletes who have been preparing for months for the Columbia
course. He said the federation decided to take a public stance on
the flag issue after being encouraged to do so by some of its
officers and athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Pilgrim, the general counsel for the federation, also said
the track group was bound by contractual obligations to keep the
race in Columbia. Mike Moran, a spokesman for the U.S. Olympic
Committee, said the USOC was bound by its constitution not to make
political statements unless athletes were being deprived of the
right to compete.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 trials were held in the South Carolina capital, which
won the 2000 Olympic marathon trials two years ago after a
competitive bidding process. The state NAACP began calling for an
economic boycott last July. Considering that time frame, along with
the fact that race organizers have also called for a removal of the
Confederate flag, NAACP leaders said they did not oppose the
holding of next week's marathon trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are glad that the Carolina Marathon Association has taken a
stand on the issue,'' said Lonnie Randolph, president of the
Columbia branch of the NAACP. ``They are not violating sanctions
per se. But I did meet with race officials and expressed to them
the hope that they will support our efforts in the future and not
return until the matter is resolved.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Katrina Price-Crosby of South Pasadena, Calif., an
African-American who will compete in the Olympic trials at 5,000
and 10,000 meters in July in Sacramento, said she canceled a race
appearance in South Carolina last December. She added that she has
also canceled plans to attend the marathon trials to cheer on her
friends. She has asked them to support the economic boycott by
bringing some of their own food and by not renting cars while in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Price-Crosby and Steve Holman, an African-American who is
America's top miler, said they have begun exploring the idea of
manufacturing red, white and blue ribbons that could be worn as
lapel pins by the marathoners as a sign of silent, individual
protest during next Saturday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd wear one in a heartbeat,'' said Kristy Johnston of
Shepherdstown, W.Va., who has the second-fastest qualifying time.
She said she had considered wearing a confederate flag pin with a
line through it on her ball cap, but was afraid ``I could get shot
by some redneck.'' She said she planned some sort of flag protest
during the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm in a position to express my opinion,'' Johnston
said. ``It seems like majority of people in South Carolina don't
want the flag there. It's amazing a small group of people have kept
the flag flying. It's unbelievable to me it's still up.''
</P>
<P>
   Alisa Harvey of Manassas, Va., who might be the only
African-American in the women's marathon trials, said that she
would consider wearing a ribbon. But she added, ``We need to run a
race and deal with this afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Holman, who lives in Arlington, Va., has vociferously called for
the women marathoners to make some sort of statement about the flag
during the Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say to anyone with a microphone that if the Olympics
are about bringing people across the world together, why does South
Carolina continue to support a flag that stands for keeping people
apart?'' he wrote in a column on the online version of Runners
World magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Holman said: ``If they were flying a swastika,
would Jewish athletes sit on their hands? I think it's pretty
unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lauck, the husband of Anne Marie Lauck, who finished 10th in
the marathon at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics and is a top contender in
2000, said that his wife would have no comment on the flag issue.
``It's a shame it has drawn the attention it has,'' said Lauck, of
Hampton, N.J. ``Sport is supposed to be something where you put
aside politics. We're upset that's what is getting all the press
attention, not the fact that this is athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwyn Coogan, who finished fourth at the 1996 Olympic trials,
said that she thought it was ``a shame that people feel the need to
fly the flag,'' and that she felt conflicted about competing in the
2000 trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great if I could say, `I disapprove of that flag,
it represents terrible things to many people, therefore I'm not
going to run in the race,''' said Coogan, who lives in Frederick,
Md. ``Not running would be the ultimate way of saying you agree
with the NAACP tourism boycott. In a sense, I'm very much violating
their boycott. But this event happens every four years. I've been
planning to do it for four years. I need to run this race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
