<HEADLINE>
LEHTINEN FACES SURGERY
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Stars winger Jere Lehtinen decided to clear up the
uncertainty surrounding his slow-to-heal ankle with surgery.
Lehtinen, who has played only 16 of the Stars' 57 games, is
scheduled to have surgery on his right ankle today at Baylor
Medical Center. He's expected to miss six weeks, which would put
him back March 30 and give him two weeks, or five games, to get
ready before the playoffs. ``For whatever reason, even doing
nothing on it, it didn't heal,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``The good news is we know when we have a player.'' Lehtinen
fractured the ankle Oct. 16 and underwent surgery. He tried to
return Nov. 28, going on the Stars' road trip, but never played,
returning to Dallas after two games with soreness in the ankle. He
returned to the ice on New Year's Eve and played in eight games
before being taken out of the lineup to rest the ankle. After rest
didn't work, Lehtinen went to an ankle specialist Tuesday in New
York. He decided to have surgery when the exam revealed the
fracture hasn't healed. ``No,'' Stars trainer Dave Surprenant said
when asked if Lehtinen's comeback had led to further injury. ``It's
just not strong enough to handle what he had to do.'' HATCHER
UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   It seems like every injured NHL player is listed as day to day
whether he's sidelined by a broken nail or a broken leg. Stars
defenseman Derian Hatcher said he's ``officially day to day'' with
the lacerated calf suffered Dec. 17. He can't say for sure he'll be
in the lineup tomorrow against Phoenix. He did say it's a
possibility. A lot, he says, will depend on how his calf responds
today after three consecutive hard practices. He skated for 60
minutes yesterday. Hatcher said he realizes that whenever he
returns his calf muscle isn't going to be 100 percent. ``It's
something I talked to Hitch and \Rassistant coach Doug\S Wilson
about. My first game back, I won't play 30 minutes,'' said Hatcher,
who figures 15 to 20 is more realistic. ``When you get used to
playing, you need some minutes to get you going.'' NIEUWENDYK
UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock said Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk is recovering
well from the separated right shoulder suffered Jan. 19. He was
originally expected to miss eight weeks. ``Nieuwendyk is on
schedule,'' Hitchcock said. ``Nieuwendyk is really on schedule.
He's had a good week of rehab.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
