</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MISSILE-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FORCED DASH TO A MISSILE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Feb. 17:
</P>
<P>
   Perfecting and building a limited national missile defense would
give America added security against future threats from North
Korea, Iran and Iraq. But a weapons system this complex must go
through long and rigorous testing before engineers can be sure it
will reliably shield American cities from enemy missile attack.
Until that standard has been met, a decision to begin construction
of the proposed $27 billion missile system would be premature, and
not worth the risk of imperiling nuclear arms control treaties with
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, the Clinton administration still hopes to make a
decision on construction this summer, a timetable it set early last
year in response to intense Republican pressure. That schedule is
unrealistic. The last two tests of the prototype missile
interceptor revealed significant problems. Only one more test
remains, in May, before the Pentagon is supposed to decide whether
the system is technologically ready. Even if that test fully
succeeds, it will not provide enough information to go ahead.
Several successful tests, including some against dummy warheads
equipped with sophisticated decoys, are needed to determine whether
the system is dependable.
</P>
<P>
   This week a report by the Defense Department's director of
testing and evaluation, Philip E. Coyle III, complained that
Clinton's ``artificial'' timetable ignored major technical problems
and put the Pentagon under unnecessary pressure to reach an early
and possibly flawed decision. Similar calls for a more informed
decision-making process come from Sens. Chuck Hagel and Gordon
Smith, both Republican supporters of missile defense, and from
Henry Kissinger, the former secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   The White House should heed their advice. North Korea's recent
advances in missile technology call for some urgency. But the right
course is to allow another 6 to 12 months of testing to make sure
the system is effective. Too often weapons systems have been pushed
into production without adequate testing and incorporating mistakes
that must later be fixed at enormous expense.
</P>
<P>
   Other considerations also argue for delay. America's security
would not be enhanced if building a national missile defense led to
the unraveling of major arms control treaties with Moscow, as it
now threatens to do. Such consequences could be avoided if
Washington persuades Russia to modify the 1972 Antiballistic
Missile Treaty to permit limited defensive systems. There is a
reasonable chance that Russia would reconsider its objections after
its presidential elections next month. Even if there is a
negotiating breakthrough this spring, it will take time to win
legislative approval in both countries. By putting off his decision
on construction, Clinton would leave more time for this to take
place.
</P>
<P>
   If no agreement is reached on the ABM treaty, a decision to
begin construction this summer would require Washington to give
formal notice in November that it is withdrawing from the treaty. A
decision of that magnitude requires far more consideration and
national debate than it is likely to receive in the final weeks of
the Clinton presidency. We find it hard to believe that Clinton,
who has worked to reduce nuclear arsenals, would want to dismantle
a central arms control treaty in his last days in office. He should
move now to delay the entire missile defense timetable until a more
careful decision can be made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
