<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-WOLVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERSTUDIES GIVE SPARK AS KNICKS STOP WOLVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Knicks' starters had been chastised the
night before, and even benched, but it wasn't players like Allan
Houston, Patrick Ewing and Latrell Sprewell felt compelled to
respond against the Minnesota Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   It was the group of Knicks reserves Minnesota coach Flip
Saunders referred to as waste two weeks ago, when he smirked at the
Knicks' effort to send John Wallace, Kurt Thomas and Chris Childs
to the Timberwolves for Terrell Brandon, who led the team.
</P>
<P>
   Waste not, want not? Maybe Saunders had better measure his words
next time because it was players like Thomas, Wallace and Childs
who were more than a supporting cast in a tight fourth quarter and
helped give the Knicks a 93-89 victory at Madison Square Garden
Wednesday night. The victory also restored the self-esteem the
Knicks lost in their dismal display Tuesday night in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks usually fade in the second of a back-to-back games.
But they were faced with an equally worn Timberwolves team, which
arrived in town at 4 a.m. Wednesday after losing to Denver in
overtime Tuesday night. And yet, neither team wanted to give in.
After Thomas, Childs and Wallace helped put the Knicks in position
to win, Ewing, Sprewell and Larry Johnson finished it off.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson rebounded a miss by Houston with 22 seconds left, a play
that led to Sprewell hitting two free throws with 18.5 seconds on
the clock to give the Knicks a 91-87 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the tension was severed. At least that was the thought.
Houston put the drama right back into the game when he continued
his bad habit of missing clutch free throws. He missed two free
throws with 13.1 seconds left and gave the Wolves a chance to tie
the score or win the game. But Sam Mitchell forced a wild runner
over Johnson with 5 seconds on the clock. The rebound was fielded
by Houston, who was instantly fouled. This time, Houston, with 3.9
seconds on the clock, made both.
</P>
<P>
   In a narrow escape, Sprewell led the Knicks with 19 points,
while Thomas added 16 and Childs and Wallace combined for 11. The
Wolves were led by Kevin Garnett's 23 points. The Knicks ended the
game shooting 46.5 percent and allowed the Wolves to do the same.
The difference was in the turnovers: the Wolves had 20, while the
Knicks ended with 15.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks led by six points with 4 minutes 57 seconds left but
celebrated too soon and allowed the Wolves to take an 86-85 lead on
a jumper from Garnett. After a jumper from Sprewell, the Knicks had
a chance at some breathing room. But when Sprewell fed Houston on a
fast break, Houston blew the layup with three minutes left. The
Wolves had a chance to tie the score with 42.8 seconds left.
Houston then gave them a chance to win it in a dramatic finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were one night removed from a forgettable effort in
Toronto that ended so badly coach Jeff Van Gundy benched his
starters in the fourth quarter and ripped into them later. He
chastised their effort throughout the game and expressed disgust at
their commitment but was especially upset by their uninspired
defense at the start.
</P>
<P>
   It had become a trend. In 11 of the Knicks' previous 12 games,
the starters had allowed opponents to score 24 or more points in
the first quarter. Often, Houston and Sprewell have been the stars
giving up the most.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, that habit went unbroken as Houston allowed
Malik Sealy to sneak backdoor for two quick layups as the
Timberwolves took a 10-4 lead. Houston's defense was sloppy
throughout the first half, but his other half, Sprewell, became an
early riser. He scored a quick eight points in the first quarter
while the big men were collapsing on Garnett and cutting off the
Timberwolves' All-Star threat.
</P>
<P>
   With that combination, the Knicks took an impressive nine-point
lead midway through the second quarter only to come undone at the
close of the quarter beneath a 19-5 run by the Wolves. The Knicks,
down by 48-43 at the half, looked as stunned as they did in Toronto
when the Raptors crushed their spirits at the end of the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks opened the third in a daze, falling behind by 54-43
when Joe Smith blew by Ewing for a dunk in transition. There were
boos echoing before the Knicks were jarred into showing some
passion.
</P>
<P>
   In a snappy 7-0 run, Ewing made up for his sluggishness by
racing up the floor and fielding a fullcourt pass by Ward for a
dunk with 9:03 left in the third quarter. A possession later, Ewing
completed a three-point play to bring the Knicks within 54-51 with
8:20 left.
</P>
<P>
   But after Sprewell was poked in the eye by Sam Mitchell, and the
Knicks failed on three straight possessions, the Wolves built a
60-51 lead. The Knicks needed their third star to appear. Where was
Houston? He ended an almost invisible by scoring six points in a
two-minute spurt to pull the Knicks within one point.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks tied the score when Houston missed a runner and the
frumpy Thomas, not the most agile player on the floor, leaped for a
put-back dunk with 1.7 seconds on the clock. Two teams exhausted
from playing the night before were reaching down for energy and
were even, 66-66, to start the fourth quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
