<HEADER>
A9478 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-LANDRY-REEVESCOLU     02-16 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LANDRY-REEVES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN NOW, PEOPLE TOUCHED BY RIPPLES OF LANDRY'S LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This will be a difficult day. Saying goodbye to an old friend is
like that, and when that old friend is Tom Landry, that makes it
doubly tough.
</P>
<P>
   He has been like a rock in our lives, as solid and dependable as
a mountain, someone we thought would always be there. And yet, most
of us realized that he probably always had a higher calling.
</P>
<P>
   That call has finally come.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we will gather at the church, or at the Myerrson, or sit
alone in front of our television sets to pay our last respects to
someone who was such a central figure in our lives for such a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   But saying goodbye doesn't mean we have to forget. In fact, it
is imperative that we remember what Landry stood for, what he
believed in, the way he lived his life.
</P>
<P>
   That, more than any building we can name, any monument we can
erect, would be the perfect way to honor his life.
</P>
<P>
   Like a stone tossed into the middle of a pond, Tom Landry
touched so many others, sending ripples through countless lives,
leaving them changed for the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ripple Effect,'' in fact, is the title of the Rev. Tom
Wilbanks' sermon this Sunday at the First Presbyterian Church of
Mesquite. So many great stories and anecdotes of Landry taking the
time to reach out and touch someone's life have emerged over the
past week. That's the wonderful legacy he leaves us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Landry is the stone cast into the pond, sending out waves
that become wider and wider until they lap upon the shore,'' Rev.
Wilbanks said yesterday. ``He reminds me of the apostle Paul
saying, `Stand firm and be steady. Keep busy in the work of the
Lord.'
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's what Tom Landry stood for. He left people with
better faith and hope than before they met him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like so many others, Rev. Wilbanks' life was gently touched by
Landry, leaving an indelible memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was when our daughter Margie was involved in athletics in
school, and she was in the Fellowship of Christian Athletes,'' Rev.
Wilbanks said. ``The night before a big Cowboys playoff game, there
was a large meeting of FCA youth, and Tom Landry was there to talk
to those young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget that. He said in a newspaper article the
next day that even though it was the night before that big game, he
felt it was important for him to be there because it was an
opportunity to make a positive difference in the lives of young
people. That made such a powerful impression on me and on my
daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   It was so typical of Landry, who had a different set of
priorities than most coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't relate to success on the football team,'' Rev.
Wilbanks said. ``Yes, that playoff game the next day was important,
but he was there the night before the game anyway. It just
typifies, it seems to me, what his approach was.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as we share our feelings, our emotions and our personal
anecdotes about Landry, there are still those who are turned off by
all the ``hyperbole.'' An e-mailer scolded me the other day for
having the gall to mention Landry and Abraham Lincoln in the same
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   No apologies here. True, one man led a country in the most
crucial era in history, and the other simply led a football team.
We all understand the difference. But they shared common traits of
dedication, perseverance, honesty, integrity, character and an
unshakeable belief and faith in God. Both had a tremendous drive to
do the right thing, even when it wasn't necessarily the popular
thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, the writer suggested, would be insulted and embarrassed
by all the slobbering being done on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Insulted, I don't think so; embarrassed, almost certainly. What
he did for others was not to gain public acclaim. He simply
genuinely cared about his fellow man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all possessed of great opportunities, great
possibilities,'' Rev. Wilbanks said. ``A few can go into high
places and change the direction of entire nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We too are part of creating those good and constructive
ripples that make for a better society.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Tom Landry spent most of his life trying to tell us.
He did it, not through words, but through positive, powerful
actions.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't a stone tossed into a pond.
</P>
<P>
   He was a boulder. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
