<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' DEFECTIONS COULD RISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys might now be paying for having the
NFL's ninth-best defense last season, as a second defensive starter
begins to look to greener pastures through unrestricted free
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, middle linebacker Randall Godfrey signed a five-year,
$25-million contract, including a $5-million signing bonus, with
the Tennessee Titans, who lost to the St. Louis Rams in Super Bowl
XXXIV last month.
</P>
<P>
   Now Cowboys defensive end Kavika Pittman is beginning to shop
himself on the open market. He will visit Denver today, followed by
Atlanta over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey, who led the team in tackles last season, will receive
more than a 1,100 percent raise to live in Nashville, Tenn., and
play for the reigning AFC champion Titans. Last season, Godfrey
played for $429,000, which was the Cowboys' qualifying offer to him
as a restricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the right decision,'' Godfrey said of his defection to
Tennessee. ``I was prepared for this since I've seen so many
linebackers _ Robert Jones, Darrin Smith, Fred Strickland _ leave
Dallas over the years. I think that helped me prepare myself for
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the free-agency game is played, the fast decision is
usually the best decision because each NFL team has only so much
room under its $62.172-million salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman, like Godfrey, is a four-year veteran who has been a
starter for the past two seasons. Defensive coaches praise Pittman
for his work ethic and his ability to do the little things that
don't always show up on the stat sheet.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys want to hold the line on losing defensive starters
when it comes to defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman and free safety
George Teague, both unrestricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cowboys are expected to begin setting up visits
soon by unrestricted free-agent cornerbacks of other teams.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
