<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES GO ONLINE TO GIVE JOB APPLICANTS QUICKER ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Job applicants hate it when they submit resumes and never hear
back. So along comes an Internet product designed to give quick
yeas or nays in response to applications.
</P>
<P>
   My knee-jerk reaction? Yuck. A rejection untouched by human
hands.
</P>
<P>
   After further thought, my knee didn't jerk far. Any kind of
response _ even a cyber-sent ``We have nothing for you at this
time'' _ is better than no response.
</P>
<P>
   Some background: Internet job-posting sites draw hundreds of
thousands of resumes. It's so easy to apply online that companies
are utterly overwhelmed by volume. They have neither the time nor
the manpower to wade through or respond to all applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Many online job hunters are frustrated. They say they post their
resumes in vain. And there are tales (perhaps apocryphal) of
workers fired when their current employers discovered their
job-hunting evidence online.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I looked at one of the new applicant-screening tools
from Development Dimensions International. The product is
customized and sold to big corporate clients for use on their own
company Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The product allows an applicant to go to a company's Web page,
fill out questionnaires about personal values and qualifications,
learn about the company and submit applications confidentially. The
company-tailored software quickly evaluates submissions and either
rejects candidates or encourages them to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Cosentino, a DDI vice president, admits that a
computerized response ``is not as good as a personal interview.''
But, he said, ``If there are 1,000 people who appear to be
qualified, and this can reduce them to the top 10 candidates
through the Web screening, then the company can focus its interview
time on the best available people.''
</P>
<P>
   I had doubts. What if a great candidate is rejected by a
computer programmed to search for a buzzword he or she doesn't
enter? What if the applicant submits lies? And where does all this
leave the vital face-to-face part of hiring?
</P>
<P>
   I called a DDI corporate client, John Jordan, director of
organization and management development at Bestfoods, who said the
company tried to consider all those questions. It believes it has
safeguards and follow-ups in its new system, which it bought to
help find good candidates worldwide and apply basic hiring
standards in the 62 countries where it operates.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods, Johnson &AMP; Johnson, Bank of America, Pfizer and Owens
Corning are among corporate clients using DDI's Web-Screen to
separate the job candidate wheat from chaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's increasing our speed to hire from weeks to days,'' Jordan
said. ``It's helping us find more good candidates in places where
we could never afford to recruit.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Bestfoods Web site, I worked through the initial pages of
screening material for its fast-track management applicants. It
urged me to go on to the next step, but my high school Spanish is
/{muy/} rusty and I'm not qualified for the bilingual jobs they're
offering.
</P>
<P>
   I'll leave it to a real applicant to let me know what you think
of your online screening. Better yet, tell me if you get the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2331EST &QL; 
