u k BC-EDIT-RETIRE-NYT &LR;      02-16 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WORKING AFTER RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Feb. 17:
</P>
<P>
   A proposal in Congress to repeal limits on what Social Security
recipients can earn after retirement is a reasonable move that will
allow people between the ages of 65 and 70 to work without losing
all or part of their Social Security benefits. The idea is popular
with older Americans, and President Clinton endorsed it a year ago.
While piecemeal changes to the Social Security system are rarely a
good idea, this particular proposal is acceptable because it will
have no significant effect on the solvency of the trust fund, and
it can help the elderly who need to supplement their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement earnings limit was created in the 1930s to
encourage older workers to retire and open up jobs for younger
people. Over the years, the limit has been adjusted to allow
retirees to earn more without being penalized. But it remains
cumbersome to administer, confusing to the public and a modest
disincentive to work.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, people between the ages of 65 and 70 lose $1 of their
benefits for every $3 they earn above $17,000 a year. That limit
will be raised to $30,000 in 2002 under present law and would be
eliminated entirely under the bill sponsored by Rep. Sam Johnson,
R-Texas. Roughly 800,000 Social Security recipients have some of
their benefits reduced. The earnings test does not apply to anyone
over 70, nor does it apply to unearned income such as dividends or
private pensions.
</P>
<P>
   After they reach the age of 70, those whose benefits were
reduced can eventually get all the money back in the form of higher
benefits in future years, provided they live long enough. But the
delayed payback is confusing, and many people need their full
benefits immediately upon retirement. Critics also argue that the
earnings limit is unfair to the working elderly since those who
supplement their Social Security checks with income from
investments and pensions are not subject to benefit reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Repealing the earnings test for those 65 and older will raise
Social Security expenditures by about $22.7 billion over the next
10 years. But over time, those costs will be fully offset by
savings since workers will no longer get higher benefits when they
reach 70.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation wisely does not repeal the earnings
test for those who choose to retire early, at age 62. Such a change
might encourage more people to draw Social Security benefits early
at a permanently reduced level. Since that reduction is generally
passed on to widows, ending the earnings test at 62 might lead to
increased poverty among elderly women in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000216.0533 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9483 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-NURSE-LOWPAY-KAN &LR;      02-16 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSE-LOWPAY-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Low wages contribute to poor quality of Missouri nursing homes
care  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Low wages are driving down the quality of
care at Missouri nursing homes, prompting state officials to
declare an emergency and to seek more funding.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing homes do not pay well enough in a tight labor market to
attract good workers. That has caused the number of facilities
cited for substandard care to triple in the past year, according to
the new director of the state Division of Aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at a critical point in trying to serve and protect the
elderly,'' said Richard Dunn, who on Monday became the division's
new director.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not take immediate steps to change the direction we
are heading in, hundreds, if not thousands of older Missourians'
health and well-being may be in jeopardy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn and Gary Stangler, director of the Missouri Department of
Social Services, were in Kansas City on Wednesday to draw attention
to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mel Carnahan is asking the Missouri General Assembly for 30
new Division of Aging positions to oversee nursing home operations
and for $11 million in additional state and federal Medicaid funds.
</P>
<P>
   The money would be used to increase the reimbursement rate
nursing homes receive for low-income patients. The increase would
have to be spent on higher wages or training for nursing home
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't keep good staff, they can't get good staff,''
Stangler said in a meeting with the editorial board of The Kansas
City Star. ``Flipping burgers is more attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   One nursing home company with a payroll of 900 positions issued
about 2,000 W-2 tax forms last month because of high employee
turnover, Stangler said.
</P>
<P>
   The labor situation is tied to the current booming economy. But
pressure on nursing homes and state budgets is projected to worsen
as the senior population grows.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, several nursing home chains have filed for
bankruptcy and the federal government is cracking down with fines
on facilities that violate standards of care. But Stangler said
fines only make it more difficult for struggling nursing homes to
improve.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, according to the Department of Social Services:
</P>
<P>
   95 percent of nursing homes receive full annual inspections from
the state and 62 percent are inspected more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   The number of nursing homes cited for failing to meet state
standards has nearly doubled, to 211, in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The number cited for failing to meet federal Medicare and
Medicaid standards has nearly tripled, to 90, in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The number of facilities deemed in immediate jeopardy of losing
funding nearly quadrupled, to 73, in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have coined the term ``roller coaster homes'' for
nursing facilities that are cited for problems, improve briefly and
then slide back below minimum standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next governor is going to have to face this and face it
directly,'' Stangler said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, in his last year of office, recently appointed a task
force to look at staff training and compensation in nursing homes
and make recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 57,000 senior Missourians receive some form of
state-assisted nursing home and at-home care. The nursing home
population has remained stable, at about 42,000 for the last five
years, as more people receive less costly at-home care. But that
has meant that the people who have to be in nursing homes tend to
be sicker and require more costly care.
</P>
<P>
   The labor shortage has strained the supply of qualified at-home
caregivers, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid, the federal-state health insurance program for the
poor, pays the bills for two-thirds of Missouri's nursing home
residents. The average daily cost is about $95. Sixty percent of
Medicaid is federal money and 40 percent is from the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 new staff positions requested for the Division of Aging
would join 158 current employees. The additional $11 million sought
for Medicaid patient reimbursement would be a 4 percent increase,
Stangler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-00 2335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
