<HEADLINE>
BLOCK HOPES TO REOPEN ITS TAX-FILING WEB SITE THIS WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ H&AMP;R Block Inc. said Wednesday that it
expected to reopen its new tax-filing Web site for home computer
users this weekend, after its latest software problem is fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Block said the latest glitch, which erroneously caused some
customer tax information to be shared with other filers, affected
``fewer than 10'' online users out of more than 300,000 who have
tried the service since it was launched Jan. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Block has fixed the problem and determined that all the returns
filed through the Web site so far have been filed accurately, said
Linda McDougall, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The company is now running further tests to make sure the
original problem is out of the system. It hopes to reopen the site
either at the end of business Friday or early Saturday for weekend
filers, McDougall said.
</P>
<P>
   The problems did not affect any traditional tax service
operations at Block's 9,000 tax offices, where 2 million taxpayers
are expected this week, or any online trading and mortgage service
operations also offered through the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Block also closed its online preparation and filing site to home
computer users Feb. 1-3 when more people than expected logged on
and caused the system to slow almost to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   Block originally estimated that 650,000 people would use the new
service between its opening and this year's April 17 filing
deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
