<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-MOVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AEROFLEX TO MOVE ITS STOCK LISTING FROM NYSE TO NASDAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Aeroflex Inc., a maker of communications equipment,
will announce on Thursday that it is moving its stock listing from
the New York Stock Exchange to Nasdaq, becoming the first company
to make that move.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gorin, the company's president, confirmed on Wednesday
night that the announcement would be made. ``We are a small-cap,
high-technology company that feels that our interests are best
served by being on the Nasdaq market, with many of our peers,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Zarb, the chairman of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, the Nasdaq parent organization, scheduled a
news conference on Thursday to make what the NASD called ``a major
announcement'' regarding a new listing.
</P>
<P>
   While many companies have moved from Nasdaq to the Big Board, a
New York Stock Exchange rule made it all but impossible to move the
other way. But that rule, No. 500, was changed last July, making it
possible for companies to move if their boards determined that was
wise.
</P>
<P>
   Gorin said that ``our treatment on the New York Stock Exchange
has been superb'' and said the specialist who handled the stock had
done a good job. But he said that he thought the company would be
best served by listing on the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   Aeroflex, based in Plainview, N.Y., has been listed on the Big
Board since 1983. It has a market capitalization of $720 million.
Its share price has tripled in the last two weeks, after the
company reported strong earnings for the final quarter of 1999 and
said it expected its sales and earnings to grow during the first
half of this year. On Wednesday, its shares rose $4.625, to $39.25.
</P>
<P>
   While Aeroflex is a small company that has rarely traded more
than 200,000 shares a day until the big run-up of the last two
weeks, when volume has topped a million shares a day, the Nasdaq
market apparently considers it a coup to persuade any NYSE company
to move. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
