<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-16 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-INTERNET-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      02-16 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSHING AND PULLING FOR AN URBANE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Darien Dash has piled on the gold chains and partied
with Puffy, then put on his three-piece suit for a Rose Garden
briefing with President Clinton on the perils of Internet
illiteracy in black and Hispanic communities.
</P>
<P>
   He has huddled with the secretary of commerce, William Daley,
and communications czars like AT&AMP;T's Michael Armstrong to discuss
``the digital divide'' _ the one where 41 million white Americans
but just 5 million blacks have access to the Internet. Then he has
headed home to Hackensack, N.J., to help bankroll a hip-hop anthem
(``No Pigeons,'' which sold 700,000 copies last year).
</P>
<P>
   He has accepted the post of ``technology chair'' for School
District 5, in Harlem, along with the directive to put a computer
on every desk. The appointment came 10 years after he returned home
from school, a kid himself, to find his father, a methadone addict,
dead of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   At 28, he heads the first-ever publicly traded, black-owned
Internet company, and he's also the happily married head of a
frenetic household that contains three children under the age of 7.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the hats, some of them virtual and some the real
thing, worn by Dash, who is to black American entrepreneurs on the
World Wide Web what Martha Stewart is to the lifestyle scene:
ubiquitous.
</P>
<P>
   He's an Internet missionary worth millions. Last time he peeked,
his salary was $250,000, and his net worth reached an amount that
leaves him at a loss for the Dale Carnegie eloquence that usually
comes so naturally. ``Um, ah, a lot, about $110 or $115 million,''
he guesses, nearly strangling himself with the earpiece cord for
his car phone, which he wears even when not in his car.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Dash can filter in some Ebonics, the better to keep in
tune with his juvenile audience and rapper acquaintances (he made _
and spent _ $100,000 during his sophomore year of college when he
and a cousin, Damon Dash, teamed up as managers and snagged
inaugural record deals for the rappers Jay-Z and Original Flavor).
But the lawyer-speak that came with his political science degree
from the University of Southern California has been handy in
navigating the boardrooms of mainstream clients like Reader's
Digest, Visa, and Otis Elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Still, according to Dash, whose hipper clients include Queen
Latifah, the heart of his business is delivering something the next
generation of blacks and Hispanics won't successfully negotiate the
21st century without: Internet access and customized content for
minority households, 71 percent of which are Internet-less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thing is, get connected, get plugged in, or get shut
out,'' says the slogan-conscious Dash.
</P>
<P>
   This is how Dash, whose mind moves as fast as his name suggests,
describes the straws that stirred the drink for entrepreneurial
youth, himself included, on the street: ``In the '70s, the game was
pimps and prostitution and hustling, in the '80s the game was
crack, in the '90s the game was sports and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in 2000, the game is technology. That's the new hustle.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we define it,'' he adds, indicating two dozen workers
communing with their computers in a 28th-floor suite just off Wall
Street. Of the 50 or so technicians he employs here and at his New
Jersey office, just two are over 35, and one of those is his
mother, Linda.
</P>
<P>
   ``She watches my back,'' he says. ``And she signs my paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   Last February, in step with Black History Month, his
six-year-old company, DME Interactive Holdings, became the first
publicly traded black-owned Internet entity in a reverse merger
that left Dash with 66 percent of the company's stock. On Monday,
again with a nod to Black History Month, Dash announced a
partnership with America Online, which has taken a minority stake
in DME to start Places of Color, an online service for urban
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL was the vehicle that first put 20 million Americans
online, and we're like the urban version of AOL,'' says Dash.
``We're going after a $700 billion market that's 75 percent
unpenetrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Dash is convinced that his Internet inroads may help his
customers avoid some wrong roads. He says that if he hadn't had a
stepfather _ the Casablanca Records executive Cecil Holmes, who
taught him the value ``of hard work and walking the straight and
narrow'' _ he probably would have been sucked in by the same fast
track that ruined his parents' marriage and eventually killed his
father, Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the space of two weeks when I was 18, my father died, and I
was one of the first ones to find him; my dog died; my stepfather's
house in Paramus burned down; my mother and stepfather separated;
and my girlfriend, the woman who later became my wife, left me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was either going to turn to ice,'' he said, ``or have faith
and make something of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   First came USC, then a Madison Avenue marketing job. He sold a
digitally compressed 30-channel music service, took note of the
company's reluctance to install cable boxes in poor and minority
urban homes, and determined to start a business without those
prejudices. So far, so good. Now, his addiction to technology is
his only problem, and to solve it, he intends to retire at 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, how much money do you need, how many hamburgers can
you eat, how many cars can you drive?'' he asks. ``People say
`you'll never be able to leave this.' I say never say never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
