<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-BLACK-RACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK BROTHER-SISTER DUO PURSUING OLYMPICS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)  (rk) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost any time he's skiing _ on any slope anywhere _ the
Alaskan downhiller Andre Horton seldom sees another black person on
the mountain. If he does, that other skier is probably the only
other African- American besides himself out there that day. Despite
years of ski racing, the realization still gives Horton pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, that guy must be lonely,'' Horton said in a recent
telephone interview. ``I see him, and I think he must be the only
one there. But then, sometimes I'm the only one there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than letting the numbers bother him, however, Horton
turns reality around. ``It's the position I've been given,'' he
said about his ski-racing career. ``It's a strong position to be
in, because I know I can have a big impact on others.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old Horton, and his 17-year-old sister, Suki, are
primed to become the first African-Americans on the U.S. Ski and
Snowboard Team. But for both athletes, who grew up near ski slopes
in Anchorage and are the children of two schoolteachers _ Elsena,
an expert downhill skier who is white, and Garry, who is black _
the dream is still at least a season away.
</P>
<P>
   Both Andre and Suki are being nudged in that direction with
financial and moral support from the National Brotherhood of
Skiers. With a membership of 14,000, the brotherhood is the largest
skier organization in the country for African-Americans. As for how
many black skiers there are in the United States, no one knows. But
the number is apt to be a fraction of the country's estimated 15
million skiers.
</P>
<P>
   Schone Malliet, the Hortons' ski coach and a member of the
brotherhood, has a theory about that. ``While the number of skier
visits is flat over all in the industry,'' Malliet said, ``the
number of African-Americans probably is increasing because the
discretionary income of blacks is increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the brotherhood's intention to prepare a skier for
world-class competition, the Hortons are attending the
brotherhood's racefest this week. Billed as the Pontiac-GMC Annual
Meeting Challenge Cup 2000, the event at Copper Mountain, Colo.,
brings members together for 11 days of racing and slopeside
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   For Suki Horton, an appearance there is no small task. Last Dec.
10, she injured a knee while skiing at Jackson Hole, Wyo. Surgery
and a rehabilitation schedule means that she will not be able to
ski again this season. But she's showing up at Copper anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It was a blow to the young Suki, who at 15, was the first black
to make the skiing and snowboarding development team, the precursor
to the full ski team. It was a milestone that gave her as good a
chance as anyone to become the first black Olympic skier from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   And so why is it that no African- Americans have made the ski
team? ``TV really influences us,'' Suki said. ``Yet kids in the
city never even see skiing. Beyond that, not many blacks are living
in resort areas because they don't want to be that one black skiing
down the mountain. But it has to start somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting a black American on the U.S. Ski Team may be on the
horizon. But how soon it comes about is another question. Skier
rankings are important, but so far, neither of the Hortons have
enough points to make the grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked with the National Brotherhood, and we're trying
to move that along,'' Tom Kelly, spokesman for the skiing and
snowboarding group in Park City, Utah, said recently. ``A number of
skiers have come close. Andre and Suki are particularly notable,
and we hope that will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre is racing with a western regional team this year. Last
month, he was first and second in two downhill races at the Doug
Smith Memorial in Big Mountain, Mont. He figures that if he can be
among the top five in at least three events this season in the
Super Series, part of the North American circuit, he can qualify
for the U.S. Development Team next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I make the national team, hopefully it will be with a low
profile,'' he said. ``It wouldn't be like being a Tiger Woods with
all the national attention. But I would like to be a role model.
I'm up for the task, even though I know it won't be easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
